<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BCS SYSTEM AN IMPROVEMENT BUT BUGS REMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first season of college football's Bowl Championship Series
will conclude Sunday with the naming of teams to the Jan. 4 Fiesta
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes to plan between now and then, the new BCS system
will have killed no one. Let us offer preliminary congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Not that deaths were expected, but anytime this many of college
football's thinkers agree on a single thing, public safety cannot
be assumed.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there will be emotional casualties, particularly if
the three top unbeaten teams, Tennessee, UCLA and Kansas State,
stay that way after this weekend's final games. Only two of them
will make the Fiesta Bowl, leaving the third to wail pitifully
about injustice and mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, despite all the machinations involving polls,
newspapers, computers, quartiles and eye of newt that make up the
BCS rating system, the decision on the two best teams, and more
precisely who the two best teams aren't, still comes down to
somebody's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: If form prevails this weekend and UCLA and
Tennessee are selected, who is to say that Kansas State wouldn't
beat either or both?
</P>
<P>
   That annoying question is an annual fixture of the sport, and
the BCS set out to answer it. But unless there's an upset this
weekend, the BCS will whiff on its first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS employs a better methodology than its dubious ancestors,
the Bowl Alliance and the Bowl Coalition. And it is certainly an
improvement over the system of less than 10 years ago, when the
bowl selection process made 18th-century piracy look like a picnic
with the Muppets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old system was absolutely the wrong thing for colleges to
be engaged in,'' said Tom Hansen, Pac-10 commissioner and an
architect of the new apparatus. ``It was a cutthroat and
essentially dishonest practice. You couldn't believe anybody about
anything. Now, we still have to compete to sign (bowl) contracts,
but there's no more of this backstabbing and trying to outsell each
other in bowl tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change that made the BCS the best system so far was
the decision of the Pac-10 and Big Ten to surrender their
exclusive, lucrative contract with the Rose Bowl in order to make
the game and their conferences part of the new show.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10 ``realized at some point that the coalition and
alliance weren't working in the best interests of the game without
us,'' Hansen said. ``It wasn't clean, regardless of how beneficial
our Rose Bowl arrangement was to the two conferences. The Big Ten
especially felt roundly criticized and said it was hurting the
schools in recruiting. Other schools would say if you go to a Big
Ten school, you can only play in the Rose Bowl and not the national
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Pac-10 caved. Still, a few days shy of conclusion, Hansen
is pleased with the BCS's first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worked for the better,'' he said. ``The system
responds to games played and has movement, rather than locking
teams into position (under the old poll system). Strength of
schedule has become a major factor, as we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   All true. Unfortunately, the BCS simply doesn't go far enough.
Besides being mis-named _ it is not a series, nor is it a true
championship because the final-game berths are invitations unearned
via playoffs _ the system settles for just two teams and one game.
</P>
<P>
   The various rankings and strength of schedule formulas do
eliminate the chance for travesty, such as in 1984 when BYU was
selected as national poll champion ahead of Washington. But without
a playoff format that includes the top four or eight teams, it's
still guesswork, as it has always been, but no longer is in any
other sport (except for the NFL, where referees are helpless to
distinguish between the words ``heads'' and ``tails'').
</P>
<P>
   Hansen is convinced the BCS isn't likely to accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worked rather well,'' he said. ``I don't think it
could have happened better or differently if we had changed
anything. If you look at the problems as well as the potential in a
(multi-team) tournament, the answer is no, not with the bowls the
way they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, you'll always get an argument wherever you draw the
selection line, whether it's No. 3 or No. 64'' as with the men's
basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Except that few will care who's No. 65.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a season in which the BCS must choose two from a
half-dozen teams with one loss. The computer-generated
hairsplitting will produce little more satisfaction than the old
method of relying on geography-challenged sportswriters and
time-challenged coaches who turn over their poll ballots to kids in
the office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, relying on computers for a champion bodes ill. Once
Bill Gates gets back from the Big House and sees that computers are
the foundation of college football, he will purchase the NCAA and
play the entire season on his Macintosh in about a day and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Scoff if you will, but his virtual championship will be no
better or worse than the virtual championship the BCS offers.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
