<HEADLINE>
LAVIN'S RECRUITS ON SCREAM TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Meet Steve Lavin, yeller and screamer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real fiery guy,'' Bruins guard Rico Hines said. ``When
he wants you to play hard, you knows it's time. He starts foaming
at the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, and his hair gets messed up,'' forward Travis Reed said.
``The slickness comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin is far from a raging lunatic and can't match his mentor,
Purdue's Gene Keady, on the emotion meter. But having recruited 12
of the 14 Bruins himself, he's more emphatic this season when
making his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, it wasn't really his team, it was more like Jim
Harrick's team and he was the stepdad,'' Reed said, referring to
Harrick recruits Toby Bailey, J.R. Henderson and Kris Johnson.
``Now, we're all his players, and that's why he yells at us more.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kentucky game is any indication, they thrive on tough
love. Lavin was enraged after a 70-54 loss to Maryland and
challenged their manhood, and they responded with their best game
yet, a 66-62 loss to Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can deal with the yelling,'' Hines said. ``Last year, the
three seniors didn't really respond well to yelling. They were
older, and they thought, `Hey, coach is only eight years older than
we are.' We respond better.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis update: Injured guard Baron Davis may be cleared to play
today. Or he may be told to wait another week. Or he may not be
told anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be this week, it could be next week,'' Lavin said.
``We're encouraged and hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   When he does return, Davis will be on a restricted-minutes
program: 15-20 minutes per game for a few weeks, then 25-30 minutes
for a few weeks, then full clearance.
</P>
<P>
   Can't look back: Freshman forward JaRon Rush is shooting 29.2
percent from the field _ in part because of poor shot selection, in
part because of back spasms that have nagged him for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The spasms often strike when Rush is on the bench, so he rides
an exercise bike to stay loose. He's on a back-strengthening
program, but the flights to and from Puerto Rico were painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bothering me, but I had to play through it,'' he said.
``I'm going to rehab it (this week), and I think I'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine time for Farnham: Walk-on forward Sean Farnham got a rare
opportunity against Kentucky _ the chance to play with the outcome
in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach Lavin told me I was going in, I turned the
intensity to overload,'' he said. ``I was going to knock somebody
down. From where I've been to where I am, it was nice to
contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Farnham had one rebound and one turnover in six minutes and
energized the Bruins' bench with his hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team was as excited about his one rebound as I ever seen a
team excited about one rebound,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
