<HEADER>
A8170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     12-02 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CHICAGO _ Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen, Dennis Rodman and the
usual inhabitants of the United Center at this time of year remain
absent because of the hardheadedness on both sides of the NBA
fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the house where championships are rolled off the assembly
line like the latest-model cars was filled Tuesday with the names
of schools that carry pedigrees of success and individuals who
carry promise for another season of thrills.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, Duke and Kansas, the blue bloods of the sport, are on
hand for a made-for-ESPN event called the Great Eight, as is UConn,
still an outsider to the Final Four but for the moment ranked No. 1
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   By the time another unpredictable season takes its twists and
turns and lands on the doorstep of March Madness, the cast of
characters assembled here will make up many of the All-Everything
teams.
</P>
<P>
   There was UConn's Richard Hamilton, cooler than the other side
of the pillow, dribbling twice, giving a head fake right, then
cutting left on a stutter-step drive down the lane that produced a
slick bucket on a finger roll.
</P>
<P>
   There was Hamilton's teammate, the barrel-chested Khalid
El-Amin, taking Washington's Donald Watts down along the baseline,
doing a 180-degree spin and sticking a defiant jumper in his eye.
</P>
<P>
   There was Wayne Turner, the point guard who steered No. 8
Kentucky's drive to the NCAA title last season, getting the
Wildcats back on the early prowl with drives and dishes and Heshimu
Evans controlling the inside in a 63-45 thumping of seventh-ranked
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   There were Kenny Gregory and Eric Chenowith trying to step up
into the roles formerly filled by Paul Pierce and Raef LaFrentz as
the Jayhawks embark on another season that will likely be as
unchanging as the Kansas topography.
</P>
<P>
   We know that between now and the time the championship nets are
cut down next March in St. Petersburg, Fla., that so many of the
games will be entertaining. But the question is whether the quality
of those games _ and the health of the sport itself _ will be good.
</P>
<P>
   The game is changing fast. Maybe too fast. What used to be a
trickle of players leaving school early to pursue the big dreams
and big bucks of the NBA has turned into a torrent. Antawn Jamison
and Vince Carter, the pair of pillars who took North Carolina to
last year's Final Four, were among a group of eight early entrants
who crashed the top 10 picks in the NBA draft. One of them, Larry
Hughes of Saint Louis, leaped for the cash as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   There is the ongoing controversy with summer leagues that
recruit _ and in some cases pay for _ players coming out of high
schools. There continue to be recruiting violations at colleges
across the country, and in the past couple of years, point-shaving
scandals have been uncovered at Northwestern and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at a lot of the kids who have left North Carolina and
Kentucky,'' said Utah coach Rick Majerus, whose team lost to
Kentucky in last season's national-title game and will face Rhode
Island tonight. ``One of the questions that goes through my mind is
whether it makes more sense to try to recruit kids who are maybe a
notch below the elite level but will stay for four years and allow
you to build a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Mike Krzyzewski has won two NCAA titles in the '90s but
has watched the landscape change dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is in good shape and bad shape at the same time,''
Krzyzewski said. ``It's in good shape on the court, because it is
still played with intensity and at a very high level. But the game
suffers off the court because a lot of it hasn't kept up with all
the changes that have taken place. You could say that the house
still looks very nice, but maybe we have termites.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the changes, the early exodus to the pros is the most
visible and is the one that most readily affects the caliber of
play.
</P>
<P>
   Washington stepped off a 4,300-mile flight from Hawaii, where it
played in a tournament, and was knocked for a hula loop in a 69-48
loss to UConn. But in a game that had 41 turnovers and a combined
shooting percentage of .408, not everything could be attributed to
beach legs. Of the 24 players who got into the game, only three
were seniors. And they totaled just 19 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's Hamilton is a junior, and El-Amin is a sophomore. But
there is no time for patience or building these days, because by
next year they both will likely be gone to the NBA. Which brings a
sense of urgency to the current No. 1 team.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, even amid the color and excitement, a sense of
despair over where the game is headed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
