<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 1 UCONN BURIES WASHINGTON IN SECOND HALF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ So many of the principals were the same. So much about
the games was different.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch of the grinder in Greensboro was interesting only
for about 25 minutes Tuesday night in the tepid atmosphere of the
United Center. Then top-ranked Connecticut stifled Washington with
a 29-9 finishing run and handed the UW its first basketball loss of
the season, 69-48, in the Great Eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not every day you get the chance to play the No. 1
team,'' said UW guard Donald Watts. ``It's not every day you get
the chance to play in the United Center. It just didn't work out
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the sequel to Connecticut's pulsating, buzzer-beating
75-74 victory over Washington last March in the East Regional
semifinals. That one was won by Richard Hamilton's fallaway
13-footer; this was decided just after the first TV timeout in the
second half, when _ pick one _ (a) fatigue, (b) Washington's lack
of toughness, or (c) Connecticut's horde of athletes took over.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation of choice in the UW locker room was the middle
one; nobody from Washington, least of all coach Bob Bender, wanted
to lean on the most convenient excuse, which was the UW's three
weekend games in Hawaii and the 4,500-mile Sunday-night trip here
through Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it had much of an effect,'' UW center Todd
MacCulloch said in referring to fatigue. ``We won the (Big Island)
tournament, and everybody was feeling good. It was just a couple of
flights, that's all it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an excuse for the way we played tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington was all right defensively, save for allowing 17
Connecticut offensive rebounds that helped UConn to a 48-28 edge on
the boards. UConn made more turnovers, 22-19. It was half-court
offense that was an adventure for the West Coast Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch led Washington with 13 points, hard-earned against
UConn's physical inside defense and quick weak-side help.
MacCulloch had six baskets and nobody else for the UW had more than
three, as neither Watts nor Deon Luton (a combined 6-for-19 from
the field) produced enough offensive support to keep Washington in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, we had nothing easy,'' Bender said. ``But I
credit Connecticut for that. They're deeper than they were a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very difficult to play against. They can attack the
defensive glass, and we were so worried about getting back, I don't
know if we had any offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington had two horrendous stretches in the game. The UW
recovered from the first, but the second will stick with the
Huskies a while.
</P>
<P>
   In a first-half stretch of 9:43 between Washington baskets,
Connecticut built a 20-7 lead while the UW was going 0-for-11 with
six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington crept back within 35-27 at halftime, exactly the
eight-point margin UW had to make up at the break in last spring's
NCAA tourney game. And when Washington nosed to within 40-39 on
MacCulloch's free throw with 15:59 left, it appeared a possibility
this one was also headed for the wire.
</P>
<P>
   That was an illusion. Washington blew two possessions to take
the lead, the start of a nightmarish eight turnovers in 12 trips
that quickly shoved UConn's lead to double digits.
</P>
<P>
   We'll never know whether it was fatigue, but suddenly Washington
couldn't repel UConn's acquisitive hands or keep Connecticut off
the glass. Bender also lamented quick UW offense in a game in which
the experimental 45-second shot clock could have worked to
Washington's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's got to happen is, we've got to be tougher,'' Bender
said. ``I don't know if that's a simple thing to accomplish or a
difficult thing. But at least we can identify it.''
</P>
<P>
   Most shocking was that Connecticut's winning run coincided
perfectly with the departure of point guard Khalid El-Amin with
foul trouble. He exited with UConn ahead 40-39 when he drew his
fourth foul, and when he returned with 2:15 left, his team was up
by 22.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who feel El-Amin often hurts UConn by looking to
shoot too readily before passing, and that school of thought was
rewarded on this night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a guy of his ability go off the floor should be to our
advantage,'' Bender said. ``They turned it around and used it to
their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington did a reasonable job on player-of-the-year candidate
Richard Hamilton, limiting him to 17 points on 7-of-21 shooting.
But Hamilton, unlike MacCulloch, had all sorts of help.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good player, but we guard players like that in the
Pac-10 everywhere,'' said Luton, who had primary responsibility on
Hamilton. ``I think I did pretty well. He did pretty well on me,
too, because I didn't make my shots, but I take the blame for that.
All my looks were wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts, recalling that season-ending game in Greensboro, felt a
distinct difference this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great basketball game,'' he said, thinking back.
``Everybody just put it down, everybody gave 100 percent. Somebody
had to lose but you walked out with your head high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we didn't fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
