<SLUG> BC-BKC-GREAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT, KENTUCKY ROLL IN GREAT 8 
</HEADLINE>
 8-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For three weeks, they feasted on cupcakes: Quinnipiac,
a team playing its first game in Division 1, plus Richmond,
Hartford, and Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the ``preseason'' for the University of
Connecticut. Tuesday night, in what coach Jim Calhoun said was the
start of a four-game, week-and-a-half stretch that would more
clearly define his team, UConn began chewing on tougher fare, a Top
20 team that could test the Huskies, perhaps even beat them.
</P>
<P>
   But for the UConn faithful who made the journey here for Tuesday
night's Great Eight game at the United Center, the Huskies of
Washington proved to be nothing more than an annoyance for one
half.
</P>
<P>
   Using its speed, its defense, and its depth, UConn _ newly atop
the rankings in both men's and women's basketball _ made Washington
look like an ordinary opponent (instead of the 15th-ranked team
that it was) by rolling to a 69-48 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the second game of the doubleheader, eighth-ranked Kentucky
(6-1) opened a big early lead over No. 7 Kansas (4-1) and never
looked back as it rolled to a 63-45 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead for UConn in the next 10 days are games with Michigan
State, Massachusetts, and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played a game that made it difficult for us to do easy
things,'' said Washington coach Bob Bender, who brought his team
nearly 5,000 miles after winning the Big Island tournament in
Hawaii, only to see it lose for the first time in five games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   For a little more than a half, both sets of Huskies made it
difficult on themselves with sloppiness that belied their talent.
</P>
<P>
   In taking a 35-27 halftime lead, UConn committed 15 turnovers.
Calhoun chewed out his players _ mainly center Jake Voskhul _ as he
looked for solutions. Part of the problem, said Calhoun, were the
basketballs. Seems they were slippery, hard to hold, hard to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Something clearly was wrong when Calhoun looked up five minutes
into the second half and saw that his team's double-digit lead had
shrunk to 1 _ 40-39.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to his concern were the four fouls on sophomore point
guard Khalid El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Huskies might have been in trouble, might have
started to question what they were doing. Not this team. Calhoun
not only can go nine deep in his rotation but also can go four deep
at point guard without losing a lot.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was forward Kevin Freeman who proved the catalyst,
along with All-America forward Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   During a timeout after Washington closed to 40-39, Freeman (12
points) outlined the strategy he wanted his teammates to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hell with scoring,'' Freeman said in the huddle. ``Let's
not let them score.''
</P>
<P>
   And for the next seven minutes, that's just about what happened.
UConn, which is preparing for a Saturday meeting with No. 9
Michigan State in Storrs, Conn., simply overwhelmed Washington with
a 20-2 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their quickness, their ability to put the ball on the floor
put us back on our heels,'' said Bender. ``They tightened the
screws on us. We didn't have an easy way to score.''
</P>
<P>
   While UConn continued to struggle offensively, the Huskies were
downright scary defensively _ double-teaming, flicking away at
loose balls, and crashing the boards with an effort that emphasized
how deep and talented they truly are.
</P>
<P>
   As for the pressure of being No. 1, the Huskies shrugged it off
the way they have all five opponents this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being No. 1 is a fun kind of pressure,'' said Hamilton, who
had a quiet evening of 17 points. ``You dream about being No. 1,
and if you don't want to, you don't belong in college basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said it is too early to get excited about the ``We're
No. 1'' issue _ he says he still hasn't finished eating his
Thanksgiving turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see where we are after we play Michigan State, UMass,
and Pittsburgh,'' he said. ``Then if we're No. 1, that will be a
good start to the season. But that's all it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nightcap, Kentucky's Massachusetts combination _ Boston's
Wayne Turner and Worcester's Mike Bradley _ was instrumental in the
victory. Turner, a 6-foot-2-inch guard, scored a team-high 14
points, while Bradley, the 6-10 former Boston College recruit,
contributed 7 points and 6 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
