<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHOP-KANSAS-STATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS STATE'S MICHAEL BISHOP A WINNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one time Michael Bishop left a college football field as a
loser helps explain why and how he has won the other 46 times.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Kansas State lost at Nebraska, 56-26. It was
Bishop's fourth game with the Wildcats. After the game, he made it
clear that he felt his teammates had quit after the Huskers built a
41-6 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation I had never been in before, and I was just
trying to react the way I felt I needed to react,'' Bishop said.
``After that game, I felt it was time for me to step up. I started
speaking up in meetings, and people started listening to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might have sounded like I was being hard on the team, but I
was speaking the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kansas State, Bishop is the truth. The senior quarterback
has been the Wildcats' playmaker in this 11-0 season that continues
with Saturday's Big 12 Conference championship game in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's ``say what you feel'' attitude makes Kansas State coach
Bill Snyder uncomfortable. That's one of the reasons Snyder placed
Bishop off-limits to the media for much of this season. But Snyder
also knows that Bishop's comments after last season's Nebraska game
displayed Bishop's will to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael is an extremely competitive guy,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `I never lost,' and he said, `I never want to lose
again while I'm at K-State,''' Wildcats receiver Darnell McDonald
said of Bishop's comments a year ago. ``Everyone took that to
heart. We thought about it, and from then on, we've gotten better
and better.''
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons at Blinn College, Bishop led the Buccaneers to
consecutive 12-0 records and national junior college championships.
Last season, Kansas State was 11-1, including a Fiesta Bowl victory
over Syracuse in which Bishop had 390 yards total offense and
accounted for five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   That's a 46-1 record as a starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised he's had this much success,'' said Central
Missouri State coach Willie Fritz, who coached Bishop at Blinn. ``I
didn't have any doubts that he could start \Rat Kansas State\S, but
to say he's going to wind up being in the running for the Heisman
Trophy and quarterbacking a team with a chance at the national
championship ... that's a stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop is from Willis. He was recruited out of high school by
Tennessee and Baylor. However, a change in NCAA eligibility rules
left Bishop half a credit short of core courses to be eligible as a
freshman. He enrolled at Blinn.
</P>
<P>
   After two national titles in junior college, Bishop was ready
for Division I-A. But several schools wanted him to change
positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the schools that recruited me wanted to move me to
defensive back or wide receiver,'' Bishop said. ``Coach Snyder
didn't want to play me anywhere but quarterback. I felt like \Rthe
other schools\S didn't think I could play quarterback at the
major-college level. All I needed was a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those schools was Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were reasons why we didn't recruit him, but it serves no
purpose to go into those publicly,'' Aggies coach R.C. Slocum said.
``But the statement that we tried to make a receiver out of him, I
would question the accuracy of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum, though, has no doubt about Bishop's abilities as a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as dangerous as any quarterback I've seen play,'' Slocum
said. ``He's got the best combination of run and pass. He can run
like a running back, he can avoid the pass rush and he's got an
absolute rocket arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching film, and he threw a corner route way down
field, and he made it look like a 10-yard sideline throw. He is a
phenomenal player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's junior season was one of transition. Snyder considered
redshirting him last season to allow him to learn the team's
offense. However, Bishop showed too much athletic ability. Snyder
made him the quarterback and trimmed back the playbook to allow
Bishop to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you I honestly knew how quickly he would mature
into our system,'' Snyder said. ``He's been in our program for just
14 months, I think he's made great progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop blossomed a year ago during 16 days of practice in
preparing for the Fiesta Bowl. He studied film for hours and
brainstormed with Snyder and offensive coordinator Ron Hudson. The
result was a dazzling performance and the foundation for this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Bishop completed 43 percent of his passes,
producing 13 touchdowns and eight interceptions. This season, he's
completing 53 percent and has 21 touchdowns against just three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has made a commitment to being a student of the
game,'' Hudson said. ``And he does things I can't coach.
Athletically, he's far and away the best I've worked with.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bishop gained his revenge against Nebraska. He led the
Wildcats to a 40-30 victory over the Cornhuskers on Nov. 14. Bishop
threw for two touchdowns and ran for two as he totaled 446 yards
total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``In junior college I never had the opportunity to feel what it
was like to be on the losing end,'' Bishop said. ``Here, I had lost
to Nebraska once before. I had the opportunity to go back and play
against them and come out on top this time. That motivated me. I
wanted to go out and have another shot at them. It was a great
feeling to win that game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
