</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PALMEIRO-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO RETURNS TO RANGERS FOR FIVE YEARS, $45 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers re-signed their first baseman
yesterday, five years after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro, who left the team as a free agent in November
1993, signed a five-year contract worth $45 million yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers owner Tom Hicks, president Tom Schieffer and general
manager Doug Melvin introduced Palmeiro as their first baseman last
night from The Ballpark in Arlington's fourth-floor offices.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro replaces Will Clark, the first baseman who replaced him
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who hit .296 with a career-high 43 home runs and 121
runs batted in during 162 games this past season with Baltimore,
supplants Clark after an 11th-hour flurry he initiated.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted at home last night, Clark did not want to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro will receive $8 million annually and another $1 million
deferred per season. That represents a bargain compared to the
six-year, $80 million contract first baseman Mo Vaughn received
recently from the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought this would become a reality,'' Palmeiro said.
``It was always a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin arrived at The Ballpark yesterday morning with ``no plans
or idea this would happen.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Palmeiro _ urged by former Rangers left-hander Kenny
Rogers _ telephoned Melvin, despite the Orioles' offer of a
five-year contract worth $50 million Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's emotions, though, tugged at him and made the
left-handed power hitter realize his desire to return to the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I want to be,'' Palmeiro said. ``This is where I
want to finish my career, and I want to win here. I think this is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer and Melvin reached Hicks, who was returning from New
York on his private airplane. A five-minute conversation put the
wheels in motion, Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a unanimous recommendation that Rafael would be a very
positive influence on our team,'' Schieffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who resides in Colleyville, might have given up some
money to return, but he added that ``it really didn't make a
difference _ whether it's $45 \Rmillion\S, $50 \Rmillion\S, $55
million _ when you're talking about that kind of money. You have to
weigh other things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' deal included twice as much deferred money, and
Palmeiro had investigated differences in Texas' and Maryland's tax
structures that decrease the apparent $5 million difference in
total value of the two offers.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin weighed the Rangers' most likely option _ re-signing
Clark to a one-year contract, perhaps with an option for the 2000
season _ should the organization bypass Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin planned to meet today with Jeff Moorad, who represents
Clark, to discuss his possible return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult to talk to Will,'' Melvin said. ``It's not
the way I wanted to do it. I had to call him and tell him that I
couldn't even meet with his agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, though, judged Palmeiro a better fit for the Rangers for
these reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Power: Palmeiro, a left-handed power hitter, makes him ideal for
The Ballpark. Palmeiro hit .292 with 182 home runs and 553 RBI the
past five seasons. Clark hit .308, but his left-handed swing
produced only 77 home runs and 397 RBI the past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that The Ballpark was built for Rafael,'' Melvin
said. ``I think it is. You look at his stroke, his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Durability: Palmeiro appeared in 736 games the past five
seasons. The oft-injured Clark, who turns 35 before Opening Day,
appeared in 609.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important,'' Melvin said. ``That's stability. That's
having someone you know will be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Hicks: ``Will probably had one more year left in him. He's
had injury issues in the past. Rafael will play for five years.
Will Clark will not, in our opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense: Palmeiro received his second consecutive Gold Glove
Award for defensive excellence this past season. Opponents often
took advantage of Clark's inferior arm strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense will improve dramatically,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro also made his first request of manager Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to hit third,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere you want,'' Oates responded, ``except fourth.'' Juan
Gonzalez, the American League most valuable player, bats cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not view Palmeiro as the missing link between
their organization and catching the World Series champion New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't be the final piece,'' Oates said. ``He's just one of
the pieces. We all have to do our job.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin's will continue today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very good nucleus for a club,'' Melvin said, ``but
we still need pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
