<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     12-02 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD IDEA GETS OLDER BY THE MINUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS _ The trouble with next month's fight between
George Foreman and Larry Holmes is not that they're a couple of
middle-age men. It's that they're the (begin ital)wrong(end ital)
middle-age men.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton vs. Kenneth Starr, you might fork over $39.95 to
watch on pay-per-view television. Jay Leno vs. David Letterman, you
might pay $500 for a ringside seat. Or, how about Gray Davis vs.
Dan Lungren in a rematch between the ropes?
</P>
<P>
   Foreman vs. Holmes, that's a harder sell, even in a day when
boxing fans have learned to expect the bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   But sell the fight, scheduled for Jan. 23 at the Houston
Astrodome, is what the two long-ago heavyweight champions tried to
do Tuesday afternoon at Planet Hollywood, mugging and posing
through the fourth of six stops on a nationwide promotional tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both men are going to have their ears intact,'' said Roger
Levitt, the bow-tied Englishman who is promoting the bout, as if to
say that not even Foreman-Holmes can compare with the 1997 Mike
Tyson-Evander Holyfield Bite of the Century for sheer buffoonery.
``Both men are going to be fighting for honor and pride, and to
celebrate George's birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, strange as it may seem, George's birthday is the
promotional hook for this fight, in which no championship and
little in the way of reputation will be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Foreman, who began his boxing comeback in 1987 after a decade
out of the ring, will turn 50 on Jan. 10. Thus the fight in his
native Houston is billed as The Birthday Bash.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly The Rumble in the Jungle, the title of his 1974
fight, and rope-a-dope loss, to Muhammad Ali in Zaire, but at least
The Birthday Bash is a marketing first.
</P>
<P>
   As for Holmes, who has come out of retirement twice, he turned
49 on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   At the mere suggestion that a pair of grandfathers whose ages
will total 99 won't do their spry best to put on a good show for
the TV and arena audiences, Foreman launched into a rollicking, if
sometimes nonsensical, speech on the powers of the paunch. Somehow,
he drew a connection between his derring-do on the canvas and the
career challenges facing downsized workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here to tell my (middle-age) brothers, when they're
looking at your birth certificates and getting ready to fire you,
don't wait for them to fire you _ quit!'' roared Foreman, who has
been hit in the head a lot.
</P>
<P>
   It is _ and will be _ quite a show, all right.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether a pair of guys at this late stage of
their careers have the will to put on more than a 10-round show and
make it a credible fight.
</P>
<P>
   Levitt is paying Foreman $10million and Holmes $4million. The
checks will be in their pockets before they climb into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   And, the financial guarantees aside, neither man has anything to
prove or much of a boxing future to secure. Neither expects to
parlay a victory in Houston into a shot at a championship. Each, in
fact, hinted Tuesday that the fight could be his last.
</P>
<P>
   Which, in fact, makes this promotion, trumpeted as the summit of
geezer boxing, less appealing than each man's recent bouts against
much younger fighters. In those, at least, the greener opponents
were trying to make names for themselves by knocking off legends;
there was an edge, a hint of danger, to those weird spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   In !ital!this!off! weird spectacle, a skeptic might expect
Foreman and Holmes to enter the ring not so much as bitter rivals
than as dancing bears, throwing their hooks and uppercuts for
theatrical instead of concussive effect. And where boxing is
concerned, it pays to be a skeptic.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it just conceivable they'll go through the motions for the
entertainment of nostalgia buffs but when push comes to shove comes
to clinch, will they protect each other from serious harm?
</P>
<P>
   Foreman said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give me my integrity or don't give me anything,'' he told
a cynical reporter. ``No amount of money will take my integrity
away from me.'' In boxing, integrity means being willing to batter
and bloody even the most respected foe.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes agreed _ while acknowledging the complexity of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to hurt George Foreman. I don't want to kill him.
I hope he feels the same about me,'' Holmes said. ``But I'll do
whatever I have to do to win the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   If either man could work up a violent dislike for the other, it
might be Holmes, who was often less popular than his opponents even
during his 1978-85 reign as heavyweight champ and now finds himself
fighting another sentimental favorite in Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Foreman has ducked me,'' Holmes contended when asked
why the two have never fought.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Holmes admitted it's not hatred but the $4million
that's making him fight for the first time in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' he said, ``is to make some money and not
get hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that kind of talk won't pry $39.95 out of too many people.
</P>
<P>
   How much for Rupert Murdoch vs. Michael Eisner? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
