<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSPITAL-RATINGS-LADN     12-02 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-RATINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY RATES HOSPITALS FOR SERVICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 1st graf refers to Wednesday.) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ San Fernando Valley area health centers rate well
at treating heart problems and orthopedic disorders, but shine a
little less brightly when fighting cancer, according to a private
survey of Los Angeles hospitals to be released today.
</P>
<P>
   The study by HCIA Inc., a Baltimore-based health care data firm,
analyzed government statistics on patient outcomes in cardiology,
oncology and orthopedics at 72 hospitals in the greater-Los Angeles
area. The results were used to rank the hospitals in the targeted
cases and overall.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the UCLA Medical Center and Cedars-Sinai
Medical Center each received top honors. The two facilities are
consistently ranked among the nation's top-five hospitals in the
public and private sectors, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Burbank's Providence Saint Joseph Medical Center was ranked No.
4 in total quality, while Glendale Memorial was No. 14, second best
in the Valley area. In cardiology, Saint Joseph was No. 5, top in
its local area, while Glendale Adventist took the No. 8 spot. The
two also were the local area's best in orthopedics _ at No. 8 and
No. 16. And in oncology, Saint Joseph was rated fourth-best in
greater Los Angeles, while Valley Presbyterian in Van Nuys came in
at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   HCIA said the study should help consumers choose a hospital
tailored to their medical need, much the way would-be students
might pick a business school.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of information is not generally available to the
public ... (but) it's important that consumers have this,'' said
Tod Featherling, president of the online health publication
Ahn.com, which co-sponsored the study.
</P>
<P>
   While Featherling and HCIA officials say the rankings are based
on objective, third-party data, primarily from the federal
government's Medicare program, others say any rating system is open
to bias in the way the numbers are interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   HCIA used data ``not designed for this purpose, so one could
question their validity,'' said Jim Lott, a spokesman for the
Healthcare Association of Southern California, the region's main
hospital trade group. Lott said, however, that HCIA is respected in
the industry for the numbers-crunching services the company
provides health-care organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Kara Welter, a spokeswoman for the Tarzana and Encino hospitals,
which scored below the mean in several categories, said the HCIA
report does not tell the full story. ``We all agree it's good
data,'' she said, ``but there's about five of these reports out
there, and this is only one.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen how HCIA's report or similar reports will
affect area hospitals. Most people choose a hospital because it is
covered by health plan or because their doctor has admitting
privileges at the hospital. HCIA's study might, however, be
extensively used by employers considering which health plans to
choose for their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Overall in the study, 11 San Fernando Valley-area hospitals were
ranked in the top half of greater-Los Angeles hospitals in
orthopedics, while five were in the bottom half. In oncology, nine
made it to the top half, while eight were below average. And for
total quality, 12 area hospitals were in the top half, while seven
were below the average.
</P>
<P>
   Complete results of the study are available on the Web site,
ahn.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8194 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     12-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WILL DO JUST FINE, EVEN WITHOUT HIS UNITNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ As fate would have it, there really was Life
After Randy Johnson for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, some of us wondered about that. The notion of waiting
for His Unitness to make up his hairy mind had been ominous from
the start.
</P>
<P>
   Jilted by Johnson, the Rangers figured to turn to Plan B.
Whatever that was.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't Plan B,'' general manager Doug Melvin could say
with a smile on his moustache last night. ``Plan B can change
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   You bet your Will Clark souvenir jersey it can.
</P>
<P>
   In signing Rafael Palmeiro yesterday, the Rangers not only made
themselves a better baseball team, but turned down the figurative
heat in the club's Ballpark offices.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the news from Arizona, the natives were restless.
In due time, maybe the owner himself would have become restless.
</P>
<P>
   It was Melvin's task this off-season to improve the lot of the
reigning American League West champions. Everything seemed to stem
from signing Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson, bedazzled by Jerry Colangelo, enlisted in Operation
Desert Mirage instead.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Randy, can I buy a couple of those Diamondbacks World
Series tickets? (Giggle, giggle).
</P>
<P>
   If Diamondbacks owner Colangelo truly did convince Johnson that
his outfield of Bernard Gilkey, Dante Powell and Andy Fox is going
to turn the worst-hitting lineup in the National League (.246 last
year) into a pennant contender, maybe Melvin never did really have
a chance to get him.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe my original column for this morning _ the one where I
planned to wag an accusing finger at Melvin for letting down his
new owner _ would have been out of line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really set a mandate for Doug to pursue Randy,'' owner Tom
Hicks said last night. ``And I give him credit for doing as great a
job as he could possibly have done. It just wasn't meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hold that thought. Hold it close, because I have never figured
Hicks as a ``wasn't meant to be'' kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   He seems more of a ``just get it done'' guy. And until
yesterday, frankly, Melvin wasn't getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us were imagining what the Rangers' new marketing slogan
for next season would be _ ``Rangers '99: Please Hit It to the
Shortstop''? Or maybe ``The Thrill is Back ... and so is Todd
Zeile''?
</P>
<P>
   Surely, that would have silenced those higher-ticket-price
complainers.
</P>
<P>
   As Melvin said, ``You sit there and you wait and wait and wait
for the pitchers to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He sat, he waited, he got rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   But in a stunning turn of developments, the sun did come up at
The Ballpark in Arlington yesterday morning. The fact that the
day's events started with a phone call from ex-Rangers pitcher
Kenny Rogers is too laden with Freudian implications and cosmic
intervention to allow possible explanation here.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny gave Rafael the piece of advice he should have delivered
five long years ago. ``He just said, `If you want to make it
possible in Texas, you can make it possible,''' Palmeiro related.
</P>
<P>
   Just say yes, in other words. And in a dizzying turn of events,
there suddenly appeared a familiar face at the podium last night,
saying, ``It's good to be home.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the night to debate who misled whom in those
negotiations-turned-ugly five years ago. It was not the night to
weigh the pluses and minuses of a trade that, for all of its
undertones, did help produce the only two postseason teams in
Rangers franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Palmeiro is an acknowledged star who should still
be producing at an All-Star level in the final year of his new
contract. In the five years since he left for Baltimore, he has
eclipsed Clark in nearly every offensive and defensive category _
especially in games played.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks himself was quick to note that this was not a move born of
post-Johnson anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying he wouldn't have done both Randy and Rafael, if
the opportunity presented itself,'' Hicks said.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner was confident that, yes, there would be Life After
Randy Johnson. Melvin would see to it.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Plan B. There really was one, after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 0119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8195 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     12-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS WILL DO JUST FINE, EVEN WITHOUT HIS UNITNESS
</HEADLINE>
