r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TCU-NORTH-TEXAS-T     12-02 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-NORTH-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU STARTS QUICKLY, RUNS OVER UNT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ North Texas' plan coming into last night's game
against TCU was just to keep it close in the first minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We flunked the test,'' UNT coach Vic Trilli said.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs (6-2) had a 21-1 lead with 15:01 remaining on
the way to beating the Eagles (0-3), 122-69, at Daniel-Meyer
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs reached 50 points with almost five minutes
remaining in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   They eclipsed 100 when guard Ryan Carroll nailed a 3-pointer
with 8:15 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' Carroll said. ``We hadn't gotten 100 all
season. We should be averaging that.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the most points TCU had scored since getting 126 last
season against Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Games like this had come easy and often last season; the Horned
Frogs scored at least 100 points on 14 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to TCU basketball,'' coach Billy Tubbs said. ``It was our
kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU had six players finish in double figures, led by Marquise
Gainous with 26 points and 12 rebounds. Lee Nailon finished with 25
points, 11 rebounds and a career-high seven assists.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles forward Dexter Tennell said UNT's plan had been to double
Nailon and take chances with Gainous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nailon went out and just destroyed us,'' Tennell said. ``He
killed us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles tried to shut down the inside, and the Frogs
responded by shooting 55 percent on 3-pointers. UNT shot 25 percent
from behind the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   TCU also forced 32 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, outside, in transition, TCU dominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of fun wasn't it?'' Nailon said. ``We finally
found someone to run with us.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Frogs had been playing teams trying to slow it
down and keep the tempo at a crawl.
</P>
<P>
   UNT tried to run with TCU, but simply lacked the fire power.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mangrum led the Eagles with 17 points while Tennell and
Deginald Erskin both added 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran on us, and we got down, and we didn't respond,''
Mangrum said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the biggest margin of defeat for UNT since a
Tubbs-coached Oklahoma team defeated UNT, 147-94, on Dec. 29 1989.
It was also the most points given up by UNT since a 124-107 loss to
Texas on Dec. 6, 1991.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs said guard Derale Wilson had surgery on his left ankle
yesterday, and that surgery had gone well. He'll likely miss eight
weeks. ... UNT guard Chris Davis also missed last night's game.
He's having X-rays done today and likely will miss the next three
games. Davis, from Dallas Kimball, is averaging 8.0 points and 3.0
rebounds per game while playing an average of 21 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
