<HEADER>
A8200 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     12-02 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TRADE FOR HUNDLEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It breaks down tidily to the Dodgers trading the
best hitting catcher in Mike Piazza for possibly the best
switch-batting power hitter in the game.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Tuesday's trade of offensively challenged
catcher Charles Johnson to the Mets for catcher Todd Hundley could
ultimately mean.
</P>
<P>
   If Hundley's surgically repaired right elbow is fully healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt all along we needed to balance our lineup,'' Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said. ``We needed a left-handed,
power-hitting, middle-of-the-lineup run-producer, and that's
exactly what Todd Hundley brings to the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also picked up minor-league pitcher Arnold Gooch, a
22-year-old right-hander who spent last season at the Double-A
level, while the Mets got once-promising center fielder Roger
Cedeno. The Mets then traded Johnson, a Gold Glove catcher, to the
Baltimore Orioles for reliever Armando Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   However, Malone isn't done with offseason deals. Hundley joins
offseason acquisitions Devon White, Alan Mills and Mel Rojas, and
Malone said he wants to add depth to the bench and a quality
left-hander to the bullpen. Still, his primary target remains
free-agent pitcher Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be aggressive and active in the pursuit of Kevin
Brown,'' Malone said. ``We're going to do our best to add Kevin
Brown to this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, it should be noted, was traded to the Dodgers last
summer as part of the Piazza deal with the Florida Marlins. Hundley
becomes the third Dodgers catcher in six months, a turnaround that
mirrors the managing carousel during the same time frame. The
Dodgers had predominantly three catchers _ Johnny Roseboro, Steve
Yeager and Mike Scioscia _ during their first 33 years in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said discussions involving Hundley began prior to the
World Series, and he tried to include the 29-year-old in an
expanded trade when the Dodgers acquired the right-handed Rojas
from the Mets for Bobby Bonilla last month.
</P>
<P>
   But the acquisition of Hundley is, at least partially, a risk
for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The health of Hundley's elbow remains a question, especially how
it will respond to, and withstand, a season's worth of pounding and
throwing behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My elbow is back to 100 percent,'' Hundley said. ``I think
taking most of the year off last year is helping me now. I have
been throwing, and it keeps getting stronger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who hit 71 homers and drove in 198 runs in 1996 and
'97, is still on the mend from his reconstructive surgery. It
forced him to miss most of the 1998 season, and when he did rejoin
the Mets he played almost exclusively in the outfield, hitting .161
with three homers and 12 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley caught a handful of games with the Mets last season and
threw out two of three baserunners. He said he had an MRI on Monday
that revealed no lingering damage. Malone said he and Dodgers team
doctors spoke with Mets team physician Dr. David Altchek about
Hundley's elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``They assured me that Todd was healthy, that this had healed
quicker than they anticipated and it healed stronger than Todd
anticipated,'' Malone said. ``Dr. Altchek had nothing but glowing
comments about Todd, his work habits, his flexibility. He says
that's a key to players rehabbing, their muscle structure and their
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very comfortable with all the medical reports on Todd
and we think he's 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he wasn't certain whether
Hundley would bat cleanup or fifth, but did say he wanted Hundley
to protect Gary Sheffield in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives our lineup a lot more flexibility, and I know how
good he is handling pitchers,'' Johnson said. ``I like Todd hitting
behind Sheffield. The main thing that Todd brings to the lineup is
he's explosive, but they're going to have to pitch to some guys in
front of him, and that's really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeway Series shakeup: Although it wasn't the biggest news of
the day, the Dodgers will play two exhibition games against the
World Series champion New York Yankees before the regular season
opens April 5 against Arizona. The Dodgers, who have played the
Angels in the Freeway Series since 1961, will play Anaheim on
Friday, April 3, then play two against the Yankees at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 0130EST &QL; 
