<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NEWORLEANS-ARIZST     12-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NEW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLAPSE IN 2ND HALF DEFLATES ASU, EVANS 
</HEADLINE>
 ORLEANS-ARIZSTATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona State Coach Rob Evans kept saying that the recent trip
to Hawaii was no vacation, but Tuesday night, it looked as if a
vacation is just what the Sun Devils need.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a rebuilding New Orleans squad playing its sixth straight
road game and fourth game in five days, ASU wilted in the second
half and lost to the Privateers, 53-47, at Wells Fargo Arena. The
point total was the Sun Devils' lowest since Jan. 30, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (2-4) led by 12 shortly after halftime but squandered that.
Then they went up by seven with 7:21 remaining and managed one
basket the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Evans knew his first season at ASU would be a challenge, but he
was nearly crestfallen afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely the most disappointing loss I've ever been
associated with in 30 years as a coach,'' he said, ``from the
standpoint of the effort and the execution we didn't bring to the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   After leading, 27-19, at the break, ASU made 7 of 26 shots in
the second half. New Orleans (2-4) shot 13 for 24 after going 8 for
27 in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really played well in practice,'' Evans said. ``And then to
see that not flow over to the court is what makes it
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing but bad news for Evans. Freshman Chris Bryant,
a guard from Washington High School, has left the team for personal
reasons. And junior forward Okeme Oziwo, who came back from a
near-fatal car crash in August 1997, suffered a sprained ankle and
knee in practice and was out for this game and likely the next two.
</P>
<P>
   Oziwo's injury, combined with the result, heaped more misfortune
on ASU and junior guard Eddie House. He has withstood player
dismissals, a point-shaving scandal and the forced resignation of
Coach Bill Frieder to name but a few problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like bad luck like this always keeps happening to
Arizona State,'' said House, who came in scoring 21.4 points a game
but made 4 of 11 shots and had only nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ASU did, in fact, get a mini-vacation of sorts. The Sun Devils
have a mandatory day off, and House will get the wires removed from
the jaw he broke during practice Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only good thing I can see out of this,'' he said.
``Everything else is kind of bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who had said the team improved in its three games in
Hawaii, didn't see much good, either. The Sun Devils took bad
shots, he said, or missed too many layups, especially down the
stretch. And the defense, which Evans harps on more than anything,
was non-existent in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   It got so bad that Evans was forced to play a zone, and he
regards zones with the same fondness that kids do spinach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played this much zone defense in my life,'' Evans
said. ``And we're having to play zone defense because we're not
guarding anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU shot 29.5 percent against New Orleans and had a season-high
19 turnovers. Freshman forward Chad Prewitt, from Greenway High
School, scored 12 points. He became the first starter other than
House and Bobby Lazor to reach double figures, and he drew praise
from Evans for his effort. So did freshman Kenny Crandall and
junior Jason Patton.
</P>
<P>
   Lazor had 12 points and 14 rebounds, but made 3 of 12 shots. He
did not elicit praise from Evans, who cited a leadership gap among
the players. Evans said his best leaders are Mike Batiste, who is
expected to be eligible Dec. 19, and Awvee Story, who transferred
from Illinois and is ineligible. The lack of floor leadership,
Evans said, ``is killing us right now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
