<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 03:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8267 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-     12-02 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP-RANKED CONNECTICUT UNIMPRESSIVE, BUT UNDEFEATED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Life at the top of college basketball's heap is sweet
only if it comes at the end of sports' best weekend, the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're No. 1 any other time of the year, all you get is
added pressure, increased expectations and lots of inky clippings.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Connecticut men's basketball team ascended to
No. 1 this week for the second time in school history. And most of
the attention generated was because the school's women's team also
is atop the polls. (That's happened twice in Division I poll-dom;
UConn both times.)
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's wildly popular women's team has won its national
championship (1995). The men have yet to be emancipated.
</P>
<P>
   In its first outing atop the polls, the Huskies played like ...
an NIT first-round loser. Here at the Great Eight Basketball
Classic last night, UConn beat No. 16 Washington, 69-48, only
because the West Coast Huskies played worse than the East Coast
Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always coming at us, and now, especially at No. 1,
everybody will be coming for us,'' Huskies husky point guard Khalid
El-Amin said. ``We showed how much character and talent this team
has. It really doesn't mean anything as a long as we keep playing
the best basketball we can.''
</P>
<P>
   That was hardly the case last night. The Huskies committed 22
turnovers. The highlights: They held Washington to 34.5 percent
shooting and blew the game open while El-Amin was on the bench with
foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Connecticut is a deep team,'' said Washington coach Bob
Bender, who was wearing a shirt that was awfully close to burnt
orange, the color of the school (Texas) where he nearly became the
coach last April. ``Having El-Amin on the bench should be an
advantage for us; they turned it into their advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The traveling road show that college basketball stages each
November and December conspired to reduce this to a rec-league
game. Washington was playing after completing a 9,963-mile road
trip (Seattle-Hawaii-Chicago). Good for frequent fliers, but not
for basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   Washington played as though jet-lagged; after taking an early
6-2 lead, the Huskies missed their next 12 shots and committed six
turnovers over their next 19 possessions. Even though their
opponent was inept, Connecticut didn't play much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rushed things on offense and played like we were nervous,''
UConn coach Jim Calhoun said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a mania about Huskies Hoops. It's the No. 1 _ and only
sport _ in the state; nine papers regularly staff the team's games.
And while Calhoun has built a consistent top 10 program, this
season has created more excitement. In October, UConn fans began
inquiring about Final Four travel packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Final Four is somewhere Connecticut has never visited. The
Huskies have come close this decade, losing three regional finals
to Duke, UCLA and North Carolina, all members of the sports'
aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   With five starters returning from last season's 32-5 team, UConn
was lumped with Duke and Stanford as this season's national
championship contenders. Based on NCAA Tournament history, one will
be lucky to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   For the Huskies and Calhoun, their fast-talking, gum-chewing,
beat cop of a coach, a less than stellar performance in December
can be stored away for March viewing. The valuable lesson? Win when
you don't play your best and when you're manpower is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can learn from a game like this,'' Calhoun said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
