<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-PASS-RUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS UNDER RUSH ORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Left tackle Willie Roaf is regarded by Cowboys
coaches as the New Orleans Saints' best offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Roaf will represent the stiffest challenge for
Cowboys defensive ends Kavika Pittman and Greg Ellis, who know that
pressure on Saints quarterback Kerry Collins will take the pressure
off the depleted Cowboys secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg and Kavika have got to mix up how they try to rush the
passer,'' defensive line coach Jim Bates said. ``They'll have to
know when to use speed, when to use power. And we'll have to win
some games on some stunts. If you keep coming at \RRoaf\S with the
same technique, he'll stop you because he's a good enough athlete.
We've got to try to keep him off balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Roaf may be the power gear in the Saints' offensive line, but he
has certainly had his problems this season. Roaf has been called
for holding four times (the league leaders have seven), and has
been flagged for three false-start penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Both totals lead the Saints. Roaf and company have allowed 46
sacks, fourth-most in the league, including 15 in the last four
games. After the Saints allowed six sacks in a 30-10 loss Sunday to
the Miami Dolphins, the team was chewed on by coach Mike Ditka, who
called his team a bunch of ``cowards.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was as bad as we've played,'' Roaf told the New Orleans
media. ``He \RDitka\S told us there were a lot of cowards on this
team, and we've got to play better or a lot of changes are going to
be made. I would like to think that people will come out with a
sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the Cowboys will have to raise their game, as well.
Pittman, who started the season with five sacks in the first seven
games, has just one sack in the last five. Ellis has 2.5 sacks,
none in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Cowboys are ranked 19th in the NFL with 31 sacks.
They have just six sacks in the last three games, including none
from nose tackle Chad Hennings, and one from defensive tackle Leon
Lett.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of pressure has allowed opposing quarterbacks to stand
tall in the pocket (or run around, as Arizona's Jake Plummer did)
to throw for 984 yards and nine touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you create a big pass rush it helps your coverage,''
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``I think \RCowboys pressure\S has
come in spurts for us. We've not done as consistently as we like,
but at the same time, there have been times when we've got around
the \Rquarterback\S quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last month of the season, the Cowboys need to do more
than quite a bit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
