r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-PERJURY-SFCHR     12-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-PERJURY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL BICKERS OVER PERJURY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In another prolonged display of partisan
infighting, the House Judiciary Committee grappled Tuesday with
whether perjury constitutes an impeachable offense and voted to
expand its inquiry into possible campaign finance violations by
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-hour hearing moved at an often tedious pace, reflecting
none of the urgency that could be expected from an impeachment
inquiry that Republicans say they want to wrap up by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, positions on both sides seemed to harden, and rhetoric
intensified. ``Here we are moving closer and closer to
impeachment,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``Why? Because
there is is one small segment on the far right who have lost all
objectivity and are determined to impeach the president at all
costs. Their hatred of the president exceeds their caring about
this country and its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer appealed to Rep. Bob Livingston, who will replace House
Speaker Newt Gingrich in January, to ``put an end to the hearings.
. . . Mr. Livingston, this test may be the most important you'll
ever face as speaker. Lead us out of the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the committee chairman, rejected
suggestions that Clinton should be held to a lower standard than
ordinary Americans who perjured themselves. ``It is particularly
disturbing, and indeed shameful, that many who generally claim to
represent the weak now argue that the powerful should be allowed a
pass when they break the rules,'' he said. ``There is nothing just
or fair in a double standard.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, too, weighed in with some of its strongest
criticisms of the committee to date. ``What it really is is a
partisan process designed to damage the president and go after and
investigate the president on any subject that they see fit,'' said
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``My guess is that the
committee has been hijacked by the extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee officially expanded its investigation beyond
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's charges that there is
``substantial and credible evidence'' that Clinton had committed
impeachable offenses in attempting to keep secret his affair with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The panel voted along party lines, 20 to 15, to issue subpoenas
to obtain memos prepared by Charles LaBella, the former head of the
Justice Department's campaign finance task force, and by FBI
Director Louis Freeh. It also voted to subpoena materials that
Starr has gathered on former Democratic fund-raiser John Huang.
</P>
<P>
   In this partisan atmosphere, even moderate Democrats are shying
away from considering voting for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Rep. Ellen Tauscher, a moderate Democrat from
Northern California, was one of only 31 Democrats to vote for the
Republican resolution authorizing the current impeachment inquiry.
But Tuesday, Tauscher blasted the hearings as partisan and said she
will not vote to impeach Clinton, regardless of the panel's
eventual recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard a single new factoid,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tauscher said Clinton's behavior was ``indefensible and
inappropriate,'' but she expressed disappointment that the
committee has not defined what constitutes an impeachable offense.
``That's what I expected them to do; that's why I voted for the
hearings in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee heard from 11 witnesses, including Elliot
Richardson, the attorney general for Richard Nixon who resigned
rather than fire Archibald Cox, the special prosecutor
investigating Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no comparison between the aggregate of the things for
which this committee voted articles of impeachment in 1974 and the
conduct of a president in a sexual relationship with a White House
intern,'' said Richardson, now 78.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the committee called two witnesses who had been
convicted of lying about sex in a civil lawsuit in an attempt to
rebut Democratic arguments that Clinton's offenses were so minor
that no prosecutor would ever move to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because a president is not a king, he or she must abide by the
same laws as the rest of us,'' Barbara Battalino told the
committee. Battalino is a former Veterans Affairs hospital
psychologist who is serving a six-month home detention sentence
after pleading guilty in a case in which she lied about a sexual
relationship with a patient.
</P>
<P>
   Another witness was Pam Parsons of Atlanta, a former University
of South Carolina women's basketball coach who pleaded guilty to a
federal perjury charge in the mid-1980s for giving false testimony
in a civil case about a sexual relationship she had with one of her
players.
</P>
<P>
   At times some of the exchanges seemed to be more appropriate for
late-night comedy routines than the weighty matter of impeaching a
president for possibly the second time in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., one of the president's strongest
critics on the panel, asked Parsons, ``Am I correct that the
subject of your perjury was consensual sex?''
</P>
<P>
   When Parsons answered ``no,'' McCollum seemed taken aback, and
said, ``No? What was the subject of the perjury, then? Please
clarify that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's really kind of funny,'' said Parsons. ``There is a
gay bar, called Puss 'N Boots, in Salt Lake City, Utah. It wasn't
easy to say I'd been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Another witness, retired federal Judge Leon Higginbotham,
testified he could not see the relevance of the women's testimony.
``The president is the most indispensable person in America,'' he
said. ``I don't see how you can equate the president of the United
States with a basketball coach from the University of South
Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde ended the contentious session just before 7 p.m., telling
his colleagues that the panel will not meet again until next week,
when it may well vote on articles on impeachment. But he gave no
hint how the panel will deal with any new material it gathers on
Clinton's fund-raising practices. ``I think next week will be a big
week in our lives,'' Hyde said, as he gaveled the session to a
close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
