A8439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EARHART-BONES03-COX     12-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARHART-BONES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Records suggest remains of Earhart found in 1940
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Newly discovered records of bones found in 1940 on a
remote island in the South Pacific indicate that the remains might
have been those of aviator Amelia Earhart, according to a report to
be presented Friday at the annual meeting of the American
Anthropological Association in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Two forensic scientists who have studied those records say they
appear to describe bones that would belong to a white woman of
about the same height and weight as Earhart, who disappeared July
2, 1937, while on an attempt to fly around the world. If the
scientists can find the bones, possibly stored at the Fiji Medical
School, they hope to conduct a DNA analysis to see if their theory
is correct.
</P>
<P>
   Since radio contact was lost with Earhart's plane, theories have
abounded about what happened to her and the navigator. The
consensus is that they crashed into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The International Group for Historic Aircraft Recovery, led by
Richard E. Gillespie, has been trying for years to solve the
mystery. In the past decade, the group has focused on the island of
Nikumaroro, which at the time of Earhart's disappearance was an
uninhabited British colony called Gardner Island. In 1991,
Gillespie found shoe fragments on the island that he said were
similar in size and appearance to those worn by Earhart on the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   But the Amelia Earhart Birthplace Museum, headquartered in
Atchison, Kan., maintained there is no evidence Earhart's plane
landed or crashed near or on Gardner Island, and it expressed
skepticism at any evidence suggesting otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unlikely it went down near Gardner,'' said Louise
Foudray, the museum's director. ``We don't think it went that
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The bones were discovered in September 1940 on Nikumaroro. In
1997, a TIGHAR investigator stumbled across the long-forgotten
report of the findings. The report by British officials, found on
nearby Tarawa Atoll, suggested they ``possibly (are) those of
Amelia Earhart.''
</P>
<P>
   The records consisted of radio communications and apparently
were kept secret after the remains were found because World War II
had started and the Japanese were threatening the South Pacific,
Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   The British Foreign Office in England had additional records on
the discovery, descriptions by a primary care physician on the
island of Fiji who examined the bones. Dr. D. W. Hoodless'
observations were sent to Gillespie, then to two forensics experts,
Drs. Karen Burns of the University of North Carolina and Richard
Jantz of the University of Tennessee. Both concluded the
descriptions suggest the remains were those of a white woman,
between 5-foot-5 and 5-foot-9.
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Hoodless' handwritten notes contain observations and
measurements of bones. Both Burns and Jantz concluded that Hoodless
made mistakes both in naming skeletal parts and in measuring them.
His measurements, which he used to conclude the skeleton was that
of a male, could not have been that of a man, the scientists
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Burns and Jantz used a sophisticated computer model now widely
used by forensic anthropologists and police to identify skeletal
remains. ``My results are different from those of Dr. Hoodless
because the methods for analyzing human skeletal material are far
superior today than they were in 1940,'' Burns said. Jantz said:
``There's a very strong circumstantial case these are the remains
of Amelia Earhart. At the least, you would say these remains are
consistent with what we would expect Amelia Earhart's remains to be
like.''
</P>
<P>
   TIGHAR, a nonprofit organization, plans to go to Fiji either
next spring or in 2000 to hunt for a box containing the bones
described by the British. If the remains are found, Burns hopes to
draw DNA samples that can be compared to relatives of Earhart's.
</P>
<P>
   Burns is involved in another high-profile identification case.
She is part of a team trying to use DNA to determine whether bones
found in the Pulaski monument in Savannah are indeed those of Gen.
Casimir Pulaski, a Revolutionary War hero killed in the Battle of
Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
