u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-LOTTO-FELON03-COX     12-02 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-LOTTO-FELON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia lottery winner a felon
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The winner of the state's biggest Lotto jackpot _ a
prize estimated at $31 million if paid out over time _ is on parole
and has a lengthy criminal history in Georgia and at least three
other states, according to criminal justice records.
</P>
<P>
   Two-and-a-half months after his numbers were drawn, Kenny Dukes
appeared Monday at a news conference and picked up a check for
$10.65 million _ his winnings after taxes were taken and about half
of what he would have received had he taken it in 30 annual
installments.
</P>
<P>
   He was vague about his past, describing himself as a ``simple''
man who recently retired from his job as a superintendent at a
Savannah pre-cast concrete company. Now that he is rich, he said,
he wants to build Habitat for Humanity houses and start a
construction business.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes stood with his family and told reporters that he had a
``good relationship with the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no law preventing lottery jackpots going to felons.
</P>
<P>
   According to state records, Dukes, who also had called himself
David Lee McKenzie over the years, has been in Georgia prisons
three times and in a South Carolina prison once since the late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   He is on parole until July 2001 for burglarizing his mother's
trailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least we know there will never be an excuse for him not
paying his parole supervision fee,'' said Chuck Topetzes, director
of parole for Georgia. The $10 monthly fee goes into a fund from
which victims can claim restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Topetzes said while Dukes had a ``checkered past,'' he has done
well on parole.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes' telephone number is not listed and he could not be
reached for comment Tuesday. But his attorney said Dukes had hoped
that his past would not become public. ``You can't do much about
it,'' said Brunswick attorney Jim Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop said Dukes told him of his past, and that he had tried to
make things right with his family and `` 'right with my God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Dukes' mother said her son's past is irrelevant. ``He's paid his
debt to society, and he's risen from a carpenter to a plant
superintendent in two years,'' Marlene Dukes said.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes was released from a Savannah halfway house May 29, 1997,
after serving more than two years for burglarizing his mother's
Glynn County mobile home and taking $1,400 in jewelry before
grabbing $80 in coins she kept under the front seat of her truck.
</P>
<P>
   State records show that two weeks before he was to leave the
Savannah Transitional Center, Dukes was put on restriction because
he came back to the halfway house from an approved outing with a
lottery ticket, which was against the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Marlene Dukes said she and her son had long ago settled their
differences. ``I don't think that's anybody's concern but mine.
That's in the past. It's over and done with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes is also on parole for burglarizing the home of a man who
had just fired Dukes' then-wife _ the same night he robbed his
mother's home.
</P>
<P>
   Records show he has been charged in Florida, South Carolina and
Nevada with a range of felonies, including aggravated assault,
theft, robbery, drunken driving, fraud, domestic violence, simple
battery, trespassing and obstruction of a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Gavalas, spokeswoman for the Georgia Lottery, said
officials did not know of Dukes' past. ``Anybody over the age of 18
can purchase a lottery ticket. And we certainly have no way of
knowing any player's background,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as we're concerned, the purchase of the ticket, the
validation of the ticket, was all legal,'' Gavalas said. ``There's
no reason for us to check the background of any player.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sept. 19, folks in the little town of Darien, Ga. have
wondered who bought a winning QuikPik ticket at the nearby Mobile
Express station in McIntosh County. Dukes, who was living in
Savannah when he bought the ticket, told only his lawyer and his
parents that he was a sudden multimillionaire because, he said, he
needed the time to make sure he had ``all the i's dotted and all
the t's crossed,'' Bishop said at the Monday news conference.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, while still anonymous, he shopped at a coastal
Georgia Walmart, then drove to Atlanta for a car-and-truck shopping
spree with his brother and three sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Dukes explained to reporters Monday that he was
``quite comfortable with my lifestyle before and I wasn't in a
hurry to become rich.'' He said he needed time to get used to the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   According state Board of Pardons and Paroles records, Dukes
faced charges in 1976 in Georgia for burglary and in Florida for
trespassing. He was again charged with trespassing in Florida in
January 1977 and had a drunken driving charge in Georgia in July
before being sent to prison that year for the burglary. He was
sentenced to a year in prison and three years probation; he was
paroled after two months.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina sentenced Dukes to four years in prison in late
1979 for theft by taking, robbery and disorderly conduct. He served
less than four months.
</P>
<P>
   His next trouble in Georgia, according to records, was in 1985
when he was charged with obstructing a police officer, aggravated
assault and theft. He pleaded guilty to the aggravated assault
charge, stemming from an incident at a night club. He walked in
without paying the $3 cover charge and got into a tussle with
bouncers. As he fled in his car, he drove in circles in the yards
of at least two homes and rammed two police cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Dukes admitted to police, he broke into several vending
machines at a Brunswick Holiday Inn. Police found him at the hotel
registration desk, drinking a beer, and they found $84 in coins on
the front seat of his Cutlass.
</P>
<P>
   He faced a judge one time for both the 1985 and 1987 charges and
was sentenced to his second term in the Georgia prison system, a
total of five years. He served about 2 1/2 years and was paroled
Jan. 1, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But before he went to court in 1987, Dukes faced several charges
in Florida, including robbery, theft, and burglary. Nevada charged
Dukes with fraud in 1991, and in 1994 Dukes again was charged in
Florida with simple battery and domestic violence. There were no
details in his Georgia file on the outcome of the Nevada and
Florida charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Jingle Davis contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
