<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pigs' music determined a legal noise
 &HT;    By Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ The music two pig farmers say they play for their
swine's health and enjoyment fell within allowable levels of Martin
County's new noise ordinance last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thankful the truth is in black and white,'' pig
farmer Paul Thompson said of the sheriff's report, released
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and his neighbors, Thomas and Faith Anne Rossano, were
sued this year by The Florida Club, which claims the country and
contemporary music blaring from speakers aimed toward its golf
course is so loud it disturbs the community's way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about music. It's about pigs, and it's about
smell,'' said Thompson, who has raised pigs at his home for more
than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the golf community said the sheriff's noise tests
will not affect the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not suing for any violation of the county code at all.
We're suing under the law of nuisance,'' attorney Louis Lozeau
said. ``The law says you cannot unreasonably annoy or harass your
neighbor, and playing music so loud it can be heard a half-mile
away is an unreasonable annoyance.''
</P>
<P>
   Lozeau and attorney Tom Warner, a Republican state
representative, persuaded Circuit Judge Larry Schack last month to
order Rossano to lower the music he plays to his pigs until the
case is decided at trial in January.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Rose Marie Richard said Schack didn't consider the
county's noise ordinance when ruling against the Rossanos because
Martin deputies did not yet have equipment to measure sound levels.
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's officer from St. Lucie County, which has used noise
meters for several years, took the readings for Martin deputies
Nov. 9 after golf community residents complained of loud music from
both pig farms.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said she may ask Schack to rescind his order based on
the sheriff's findings.
</P>
<P>
   But Lozeau and Warner filed court documents Tuesday asking the
judge to enter a similar order requiring Thompson to lower the
music at his farm. A hearing date has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said Florida's Right to Farm Act protects him from
nuisance suits, because he farmed on his property nearly 30 years
before The Florida Club was developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I be a nuisance if I'm not violating the law?''
Thompson asked. ``I think I should be entitled to the freedom that
the law allows everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Moore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
