</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-TELEPHONE-CHARGES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charges to change on Texas phone bills
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State regulators have approved a new surcharge
that will begin appearing on all telephone bills next month, but
officials said it will replace several charges that customers
already pay and should not result in a higher total bill.
</P>
<P>
   All telephone companies _ local, long-distance and wireless,
including pagers _ must pay the new fee, about eight tenths of 1
percent of each monthly bill. They are not required to pass on the
new surcharge to customers but are expected to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Utility Commission, voting 2-0, acted Tuesday under
mandates from federal and state laws to spell out and spread out
subsidies built into the telephone system as it moves from monopoly
to competition so that all customers pay them, not just local
service customers.
</P>
<P>
   The new surcharge, expected to bring in about $87 million a year
for the Universal Service Fund, will appear as a separate item on
monthly bills and replace charges that have been collected for
years to subsidize telephone service for low-income customers,
those with speech or hearing problems and the rural customers of
small local phone companies. The fund provides the money for the
subsidized services.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite two years of work, the new surcharge will not
incorporate a much larger, additional subsidy that keeps rates low
for local service in rural areas served by larger local phone
companies, particularly Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. and GTE
Southwest Inc. On that issue, the commission will ask for guidance
from the Legislature, which will convene Jan. 12 for a five-month
session.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had hoped to collect an additional 4 percent or
so on monthly bills for the fund to subsidize telephone service in
rural areas, where costs are higher because there are fewer
customers distributed over a larger area than in cities and
suburbs. The additional surcharge would have brought in an
estimated $359 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the 4 percent increase, the commission had planned to
slice the access charge on long-distance calls _ about 12 cents a
minute _ by about 3 cents. Long-distance providers pay local phone
companies access charges to complete their calls.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the commissioners wanted the savings passed on to all
local customers, not just those who make frequent long-distance
phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission has no authority to require the long-distance
companies to pass on to their customers any reduction in access
charges.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, MCI WorldCom and Sprint, the three long-distance companies
with more than 90 percent of the Texas market, said they would pass
on the savings to customers. But MCI declined to detail how it
would spread out the savings among customers, saying the
competitive market would best determine that.
</P>
<P>
   So PUC Chairman Pat Wood and Commissioner Judy Walsh, rather
than add a significant surcharge to all telephone bills with no
assurance of reductions elsewhere, said they would ask the
Legislature to resolve the issue either by giving them sufficient
authority to ensure the savings are passed on to customers or by
making it clear that lawmakers are willing to take their chances
with the market.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said she saw ``customers caught in a vise here and no one
seems to care about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Kitty Fox-Hessler, vice president of regulatory
affairs for AT&AMP;T in the Southwest, said the company was committed
to passing onto customers any cuts in access charges but that it
``disagrees that such a heavy regulatory hand is needed in this
very competitive market.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Maddox, a spokesman for Southwestern Bell, said the company
had no immediate reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Hight writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
