<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN03-CO     12-02 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A black 'leader' abandons his own
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Maybe it's the holiday season of
thanksgiving, good cheer and the prospect of a new year. Whatever
the reasons, after the fall elections, I tend to adopt a hopeful
attitude that the winning candidates, even if they weren't my
choice, will serve all citizens equally well.
</P>
<P>
   That posture has certainly been my response to the election of
Jeb Bush as governor. But before we move forward, political
analysts insist on looking back, especially at the campaign issues
related to race.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, The Orlando Sentinel published a study of how
blacks in Florida's seven largest urban counties voted in the
gubernatorial election. Reviewing precincts where at least 75
percent of the registered voters are black, the paper reported that
while Mr. Bush campaigned heavily in black neighborhoods, he
received only 7.52 percent of those votes. That wasn't much of an
increase over the 5.77 percent he got in 1994, when he said that,
if elected, he would do ``probably nothing'' for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Bush's supporters say the numbers don't tell the whole story
because they don't include the thousands of blacks who live in
predominantly white neighborhoods. There is some validity in that
argument. In fact, I wonder whether a study of voting patterns
based on income would be more instructive in uniting our democracy
than one based on race.
</P>
<P>
   Still, understanding why Mr. Bush lost the black urban vote
should concern all of us. Since a governor cannot know first-hand
every constituency, he must rely on key supporters who do. In
seeking advice about inner-city residents, however, I hope the
governor-elect looks beyond Rep. Willie Logan, D-Opa-locka, who
campaigned for the Republican candidate after Democrats ousted him
in January as the House's first black leader.
</P>
<P>
   In this post-election debate as to why Mr. Bush lost the inner
cities, Rep. Logan's explanation rings with the kind of prejudice
that would bring howls of criticism were he white. ``Bush would
have been more attractive to African-Americans who are more
informed and more willing to make decisions based on information
rather than emotional attachment,'' Rep. Logan told The Associated
Press. ``That means African-Americans who don't live in the urban
core area.''
</P>
<P>
   With that statement, he dismisses every voter still living in
the ghetto, the older neighborhoods to which almost every black
citizen can trace his roots. Integration of residential areas is so
new that the reasons many blacks remain in predominantly black
neighborhoods are too complex to be explained as a lack of
education or a propensity to be ruled by emotion rather than
intelligence. Nor can one generalize that a suburban address
automatically makes one more capable of logical reasoning. Thus,
Rep. Logan insults every black Floridian by suggesting such to be
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Most disturbing, his mentality reflects a bias which, if widely
adopted, could instruct that only blacks who live among whites are
worthy of dignity and respect. That line of thought indicts blacks
in the ghetto as incapable of making rational decisions because
they haven't gotten themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the same kind of simple-minded, race-based classism
separates poor, inner-city kids from those who live in middle-class
suburban neighborhoods. Many black children from ``the core area''
often generalize that all suburbanite black kids consider
themselves superior. The schism grows wider because far too many
middle-class kids assume themselves to be inherently better than
all poor blacks simply because of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   At that point of mutual rejection, communication breaks down
between the two groups, which desperately need each other's support
to eliminate the race-based obstacles that continue to be a part of
our lives. The strength of the black community derives from an
acknowledgment of our common identity. When we impose divisive
stereotypes on each other, we all lose.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
