<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 09:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-COX     12-02 2256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    By Colin Bessonette
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Arianna Huffington's background? I thought she was
just the wife of an aspiring politician, but I see her on TV talk
shows all the time.
</P>
<P>
   A: Huffington, 47, was born in Greece and moved to England when
she was 16. She graduated from Cambridge University with a degree
in economics. She's now a nationally syndicated columnist and
author of a number of books, including ``The Woman Behind the
Legend,'' a biography of Maria Callas; ``Picasso: Creator and
Destroyer,'' which became an international best-seller and the
basis of the film ``Surviving Picasso''; ``The Female Woman'';
``After Reason''; ``Greetings From the Lincoln Bedroom,'' a book of
political satire; and ``The Fourth Instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been described as having huge political ambitions. Her
ex-husband, Michael Huffington, was a Republican congressman from
California who spent $30 million of his own oil fortune in losing a
1994 Senate race to incumbent Democrat Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Huffington had bought a $4.3 million home in Montecito, near
Santa Barbara, in 1988. He joined Arianna there only on weekends in
1988, 1989, and 1990, remaining in Houston during the week to run
his family's oil business. But he officially switched his residency
to California in 1991, and entered politics. The Huffingtons
divorced in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you settle this question once and for all: How do you
pronounce the name of Brett Favre of the Green Bay Packers? We have
had endless discussions about it.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're not the only one who isn't sure, judging by how many
times the quarterback's name is mangled on the air. For the record,
it's pronounced ``Fahv,'' not ``FAV-re'' or, as some even say,
``FAR-ve.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was former Sen. Bob Dole's injury in World War II? What
were his awards?
</P>
<P>
   A: As an Army second lieutenant, Dole was leading an assault on
a last-ditch German machine gun nest in the Po Valley of Italy on
April 14, 1945, when he was struck by an exploding shell that
destroyed his right shoulder, fractured vertebrae in his neck and
spine, and riddled his body with metal slivers. It happened just
three days before V-E Day.
</P>
<P>
   He was told that he might never walk again, but over the course
of three years in Army hospitals, and several major operations, he
began standing and cautiously moving about. His right arm and hand
were beyond recuperation, but his left hand had some residual
feeling and he gradually mastered its use.
</P>
<P>
   He was awarded two Purple Hearts and a bronze star with two
clusters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend of mine will be 100 years old soon. How can I
contact Willard Scott of the ``Today'' show, so he can mention this
milestone birthday?
</P>
<P>
   A: Send a letter several weeks in advance with the person's
name, date the person will be 100, and a photo, to: Willard Scott,
c/o NBC News ``Today,'' 30 Rockefeller Plaza, Room 304, New York,
NY 10112. Or, if time is running short, you could fax the
information to Allison Gollust, publicist for ``Today,'' at
212-664-4426. It isn't always possible for every candidate to be
mentioned on the air, NBC reminds viewers, especially when the
information is provided on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is caffeine, and how is something decaffeinated?
</P>
<P>
   A: Grab a cup of java as you wade through this short
dissertation. Caffeine is considered a mild stimulant. It affects
the central nervous system. In high doses, it can cause rapid
heartbeat, insomnia and anxiety. The substance is quickly absorbed,
reaching the body cells in 15 to 45 minutes, depending on the
person.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine occurs naturally in coffee, tea and cocoa. Moderate
doses of caffeine, up to three cups of coffee a day, are generally
considered safe for most people. A drug-like dose, in something
like Vivarin or NoDoz, is 100 milligrams. The stimulant also is
used in pain relievers like Anacin (32 milligrams) and Excedrin (65
milligrams). A 5-ounce cup of brewed coffee contains between 110
and 150 milligrams; a cup of instant coffee has 64 to 124
milligrams; a cup of brewed tea has between 20 and 90 milligrams; a
12-ounce glass of cola has about 60 milligrams; and a glass of
chocolate milk has about 7 milligrams.
</P>
<P>
   For a coffee to be ``decaffeinated,'' it must have 97 percent of
its caffeine removed. In one method, unroasted beans are softened
by steam and washed by a solvent that removes the caffeine.
Decaffeination agents include carbon dioxide; ethyl acetate, a
substance that occurs naturally in many fruits; methylene chloride,
a solvent; fats and oils; and water. The process starts with
softening the green, unroasted beans in the agents, after which
they're ``agitated'' to draw the caffeine away. Then the beans are
heated and blown with steam, followed by roasting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently cleaned out a safe deposit box and there was a $10
bill, ripped but not completely. It was dated 1934, series A. I
went to the bank and included it in some payments and the teller
gave it back thinking it was worth more than face value. Is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: As it was 64 years ago, the answer is still 10 bucks ``unless
it was in mint condition,'' said Larry Jackson, an authority on
rare coins and money. If it were in perfect condition, a dealer or
collector might pay $20. Jackson said large quantities of similar
bills from that era, in various conditions, constantly are emerging
from storage. ``It would have been worth more if the person had
invested it rather than put it in a safe deposit box,'' Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you tell me how to contact Attorney General Janet Reno to
express my anger at her for not requesting an independent counsel
to investigate Vice President Al Gore and his campaign finance
problems?
</P>
<P>
   A: Address a letter to Reno and send it to: U.S. Justice
Department, 950 Pennsylvania Ave NW, Washington, DC 20530-0001.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When soldiers are referred to as GIs, what does that mean and
what is the origin?
</P>
<P>
   A: One of the popular explanations is that it refers to the term
Government Issue or General Issue, abbreviated GI, that was common
in mid-1930s. Before that, heavy Army garbage cans were known as GI
cans, referring to the material they were made of: galvanized iron.
On June 17, 1942, in a comic strip for the Army weekly Yank, David
Bregar used the term ``GI Joe'' to mean enlisted men. The phrase
later was shortened to GI. The use of ``GI'' to mean soldiers, and
pertaining to the Army only, gained notoriety after the death of
war correspondent Ernie Pyle in 1945, according to the book
``Speaking Freely: A Guided Tour of American English from Plymouth
Rock to Silicon Valley.'' But after Pyle was killed by Japanese
gunfire, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower said, ``Every GI in Europe, and
that means all of us, has lost one of his best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I think there was a famous statesman who had the poem used in
the movie ``Four Weddings and a Funeral'' read at his wake. Could
you repeat it, or at least print the poet's name? And who was the
statesman?
</P>
<P>
   A: The poem was written by English-born writer Wystan Hugh
Auden. He was born in 1907 and immigrated to the United States in
1939. Actor John Hannah read Auden's ``Funeral Blues'' in the
movie:
</P>
<P>
   Stop all the clocks, cut off the telephone,/ Prevent the dog
from barking with a juicy bone,/ Silence the pianos and with
muffled drum/ Bring out the coffin, let the mourners come./ Let
aeroplanes circle moaning overhead/ Scribbling on the sky the
message He Is Dead./ Put crepe bows round the white necks of public
doves,/ Let the traffic policemen wear black cotton gloves./ He was
my North, my South, my East and West./ My working week and my
Sunday rest,/
</P>
<P>
   My noon, my midnight, my talk, my song;/ I thought that love
would last forever; I was wrong./ The stars are not wanted now: Put
out every one;/ Pack up the moon and dismantle the sun;/ Pour away
the ocean and sweep up the wood;/ For nothing now can ever come to
any good.
</P>
<P>
   As for the poem being read at a statesman's wake, Nicholas
Jenkins, a Stanford English professor and co-chair of the W.H.
Auden Society, said you may be referring to the lead editorial of
the London Times printed shortly after Princess Diana's death. The
Auden piece was quoted and described as a ``fitting note'' for a
period of great national mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My husband and I have a little wager on this question. In the
last 30 years, how many high school basketball players have skipped
college and gone straight to the pros?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since 1968, the National Basketball Association has counted
on its rosters eight players who entered the league straight from
high school. This does not include the three high school players
taken during the June 1998 draft, though they will be added if they
make the cut with their teams, said NBA spokesman Evan Silverman.
In June, Al Harrington of Elizabeth, N.J., who was heavily
recruited by Georgia Tech, was taken in the NBA's first round by
the Indiana Pacers. Harrington was the No. 25 pick overall. In the
second round, high school players Rashard Lewis (Seattle
Supersonics, No. 32 overall) and Korleone Young (Detroit Pistons,
No. 40 overall) also were drafted.
</P>
<P>
   As for the eight players who preceded them, the NBA lists the
following: Reggie Harding with Detroit and Indiana (ABA); Moses
Malone with Utah (ABA) and San Antonio; Bill Willoughby with
Atlanta and New Jersey; Darryl Dawkins with Philadelphia and
Detroit; Kevin Garnett with Minnesota; Kobe Bryant with the Los
Angeles Lakers; Jermaine O'Neal with Portland; and Tracy McGrady
with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Several players in the 1940s and 1950s did not play college ball
and went straight to pro teams. But that's considered a separate
time from the modern era of basketball, Silverman said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the net income of residents on the island of Guam?
What is their currency? Is it the American dollar or do they have
their own money?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the 1997 Central Intelligence Agency World
Factbook, estimated per capita income for 1996 in Guam was $19,000.
The island's currency is the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the buyout of Netscape by America Online, who will
provide libraries, schools and universities with Internet service?
</P>
<P>
   A: Netscape is a World Wide Web browser and does not provide
connectivity to the Internet. That is done by Internet service
providers such as America Online or Atlanta-based MindSpring.
Browsers such as Netscape allow users to access the Web, but the
user must already be connected to the Internet. MindSpring, which
has more than 600,000 customers nationwide, will continue to
provide connection service to libraries, schools and universities
at a reduced price, said company spokesman Ed Hansen. Free Internet
connection for educational institutions is provided through a
federal grant program, Hansen said. That will not change, either.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is on the board of directors for America Online?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 10-member board of directors consists of: Stephen M.
Case, chairman of the board and chief executive officer of America
Online; Daniel F. Akerson, chairman and CEO of Nextel
Communications Inc.; Frank J. Caufield, general partner of Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers; Robert J. Frankenberg, president and CEO
of Encanto Networks Inc.; Alexander M. Haig Jr., former White House
chief of staff and now chairman and president of Worldwide
Associates Inc.; William N. Melton, president and CEO of
CyberCashcq Inc.; Thomas Middelhoff, chairman and CEO of
Bertelsmann AG; Robert W. Pittman, presint and chief operating
officer of America Online; Colin L. Powell, former chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff and now chairman of America's Promise: The
Alliance for Youth; and Franklin D. Raines, former White House
budget director and now chairman and CEO-designate of Fannie Mae.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I admire and respect Susan McDougal and would like to write
her. Could you provide a mailing address?
</P>
<P>
   A: You can send McDougal mail via her attorney, Mark Geragos, at
201 N. Figueroa Blvd., Suite 500, Los Angeles, Calif., 90012.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever happened to the young boy whose father abducted him
and tried to keep him alive on lettuce and water?
</P>
<P>
   A: The child you refer to is 22-month-old David Fink, whose
parents are members of a religious cult. His parents believed he
was ``the Christ Child'' and fed him only lettuce and watermelon in
an attempt to keep him pure, authorities said. David currently is
in foster care in Utah, said FBI Special Agent George Dougherty.
David's parents, Christopher and Kyndra, were arrested and charged
with kidnapping and aggravated assaulted. The latter charge is the
result of injuries a nurse's aide sustained when she tried to stop
the couple from taking David from a Salt Lake City hospital. The
child had been admitted for malnourishment by Kyndra Fink's family.
At the time, David weighed 16 pounds the size of an average
6-month-old. For more than two weeks, the couple eluded authorities
before they were captured in a remote part of Montana. The parents
await trial and are free on bond, Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Bessonette writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
