<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADLICE-SIDE03-COX     12-02 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADLICE-SIDE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doing battle against lice
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If your kids come home with head lice, don't expect a quick
solution. Here are a few pointers I can offer from experience:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the lice-killing shampoo. While common over-the-counter
pediculicides are only 70 percent to 80 percent effective at
killing the eggs, that's the only way to start. Most contain
pyrethrum, a naturally occurring pesticide derived from
chrysanthemum flowers. Lindane, the prescription pesticide used for
pubic lice, is considered somewhat toxic and should be used only as
a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a metal comb. Those plastic combs that come with
lice-killing shampoo are practically useless at trapping nits. Give
it to your daughter so she can disinfest Barbie's hair while you
work on hers with a sturdy metal comb, which costs about $5.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get a few small plastic hair clips and a fine-tooth plastic
comb with a long handle. You can and will learn to part and repart
the kids' hair like a stylist cutting a shag.
</P>
<P>
   _ Every night: Get the children sitting in position with water,
toys and treats. Comb their hair out with a regular comb. Check the
scalp thoroughly for live and dead lice, pick them out and put them
in a cup of water. Next, nits. Take a small ( 1/2-inch to 1-inch)
bunch of hair, and scrape the nit-removal comb through it, making
sure the shafts of hair push against the top of the comb. Check the
hair carefully and pick out nits the comb misses; deposit in the
cup of water. Repeat with the next bunch of hair.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change kids' sheets and pillowcases every night for the first
week. Then change their pillowcases every night until the nits are
history. Good luck: You'll need it.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the National Pediculosis Association
at 1-800-446-4672 or visit the nonprofit agency's Web site:
http://www.headlice.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
