<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 09:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEADLICE03-COX     12-02 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEADLICE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Head lice: It takes patience to rid your home of persistent pest
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Come to school right away. Your child has head lice.
</P>
<P>
   What's the big deal, you wonder? It's a simple matter of giving
them a shampoo treatment and running a load or two of laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Hah. Getting rid of head lice takes more time and energy than
Brownie troop, soccer meets and choir practice combined. These
microscopic pests can and will turn your household upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Our ordeal started when our eldest daughter failed a routine
head check, along with her entire second-grade clique, a few weeks
ago. All three girls had to stay home until their flowing hair was
free not only of live lice but also of nits.
</P>
<P>
   Nits? Those itty-bitty white egg sacks that attach to a strand
of hair and wait seven days to hatch. At first glance they appear
to be a piece of fluff or a speck of dandruff, but smaller. Though
they look innocuous, don't be taken in. They're your lethal enemy.
</P>
<P>
   And they're particularly hard to spot in the kind of fine, fair
hair that our three daughters have. Oldest daughter has luxuriant
tresses down to the small of her back. Middle daughter would look
like a Botticelli angel if we could ever comb out her rat's nest.
Baby daughter has pillows of blond fluff. We're the head lice
poster family.
</P>
<P>
   But, we thought foolishly, all we had to do was follow the
instructions on our $17.99 over-the-counter lice kit, and we'd be
done with it. So we washed the whole family's hair with
foul-smelling lice shampoo. We combed it all out with dinky plastic
rakes to trap nits. We changed all the sheets, sprayed the
mattresses, laundered the car seat covers and tied all the
nit-infested blankies and stuffed animals in plastic bags for two
weeks to suffocate the hateful bloodsuckers as soon as they
hatched.
</P>
<P>
   End of problem? Not on your life.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, we got simultaneous calls from the school and the
day care center. The cooties were back.
</P>
<P>
   My first despairing thought: ``Why can't I pay someone else to
do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, somewhere, there must be some sort of lice removal
service. The name for this business is obvious: the Nitpickers.
</P>
<P>
   Just hire a squadron of Type A personalities _ intent little
people armed with steel combs, magnifying glasses, tweezers and
endless reserves of obsessive patience. They could pick to their
hearts' content.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps someone could open a head lice camp, where you could
drop off the children every day for a week until the problem is
eradicated. The staff could combine fun, instructive activity with
thorough head cleansing. Puzzles in the morning, pediculicide in
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   True, the kids couldn't engage in contact sports or even a
friendly game of telephone. But, well, they could play checkers.
Wearing shower caps. Filled with mineral oil.
</P>
<P>
   I could daydream 1,000 solutions, but here's the miserable
truth: The only way to rid your poor kids of lice is to pick the
nits out one by one. A metal lice comb works much better than a
plastic comb.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing works as well as a thumbnail pressed against the pad
of a forefinger. Strand by strand. Nit by nit. Pick, pick, pick.
</P>
<P>
   You must launch a full-scale offensive and change their bedding
every night until you no longer find nits. We've washed and dried
their ``Lion King'' sheets so many times, and with such religious
fervor, that we're due a visitation from Mufasa.
</P>
<P>
   You must cut unruly hair, no matter how lovely. Middle child
traded in her angelic curls for a smart bob, and nitpicking got a
whole lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   And you must access your inner chimpanzee. I can barely look at
my kids' pretty hair these days without wanting to squat nearby and
paw through it. Because every time I think we've got this thing
licked, I find more nits.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after a month, middle daughter appeared to be nit-free.
A few days ago, we got a call from the day care center.
</P>
<P>
   They're baaaack.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
