</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH BRIEFS: Vaccine against AIDS virus being tested on
thousands
 &HT;    (Eds: A compilation of health stories that moved in the past
week.)
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 30 experimental HIV vaccines are being developed, but only
one, AIDSVAX, has entered Phase III, in which thousands of people
are being tested. In Phase I, a few dozen people are tested; in
Phase II, hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other HIV vaccine, based on the canarypox virus, is
expected to enter Phase III testing within the next year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much believe that for the vaccine effort to succeed,
we're going to need a lot of vaccine concepts tested
systematically, in both primates and in people,'' said Sam Avrett,
executive director of the AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition, based in
Washington. ``The question we should be asking is, `Why are there
not more products?'''
</P>
<P>
   These Internet sites have regularly updated information about
HIV vaccine research and trials:
</P>
<P>
   _ AIDS Vaccine Advocacy Coalition: http://www.avac.org
</P>
<P>
   _ International AIDS Vaccine Initiative: http://www.iavi.org
</P>
<P>
   _ National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases,
Division of AIDS:
http://www.niaid.nih.gov/daids/vaccine/default.htm
</P>
<P>
   _ Vaccine Advocates: http://www.vactup.org
</P>
<P>
   Numbers of children using tobacco higher than expected
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Puffing on a cigarette as he leaned against a
downtown drug store, 17-year-old Rick Short offered a terse
explanation for his unhealthy habit, which he began when he was 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got to have something in my mouth,'' he said simply.
</P>
<P>
   A study released by the Texas Department of Health found that 43
percent of high school students and nearly a third of middle
schoolers _ including about a fourth of all sixth-graders _ chewed
tobacco or smoked it through a cigarette, cigar, or pipe on at
least one day in the previous month. Researchers describe such
teens as ``current'' users.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen percent of high school students and four percent of
middle schoolers said they smoked or chewed tobacco on 20 of the
past 30 days, which classified them as ``frequent'' users.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials said the numbers were higher than they
expected. They also were surprised by the relatively high number of
teens _ 8 percent of students in both high school and middle school
_ who said they smoked pipes at least once in the past month. The
survey is believed to be the first in the country to ask
specifically about pipe use.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking campaign is all in the family
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Twelve-year-old Kevin Hickman has been after his
mom for months to quit smoking, ever since he learned in his
classes about the dangers of tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Karen Hall, has promised she'll try to kick her
25-year-old habit. But if she doesn't, she'll soon have looming
reminders of her son's wish: 10-foot-high billboards of a poster
Kevin designed for a local anti-smoking campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The poster shows a teen-age girl visiting the grave site of her
mother and crying, ``Mom, I miss you.'' Behind the girl, a talking
cigarette sneers, ``Do you want to die, too?''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin submitted the winning poster among 114 entries from
second- through sixth-graders, where teachers were approached by
the Miami Valley Health Improvement Council for a child's drawing
to be featured in a monthlong billboard campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about quitting for a long time, but now I
should at least try,'' said Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The billboards will go up in late December at six locations in
Montgomery, Clark and Miami counties, including a site near the
Nutter Center. The advertising tab will be picked up by a $25,000
grant from the Physicians Charitable Foundation of the Miami
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer group brands items as risky for kids
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some teething rings could be dangerous to a baby's
health, and other toys on the market pose choking hazards for young
children, according to the U.S. Public Interest Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual survey of dangerous toys, the nonprofit consumer
group cited 20 examples of items it thinks should be discontinued
or carry more prominent warnings.
</P>
<P>
   The teething rings appear on the group's trouble list because
they contain ``pthalates,'' substances that PIRG says can cause
liver and kidney problems and reproductive abnormalities. Specific
teethers named include the Baby Looney Tunes Cooling Ring by
Gerber, the Cool Ring Teether by First Years, the Funny Face
Teether Rattle and Disney Babies Mickey Collection by Playskool and
the Sof'Sport Teether and the Sports Fan Water Teether, both by
Safety First.
</P>
<P>
   The Toy Manufacturers of America, which represents more than 300
toy producers and importers, disputed the claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at the research and the allegations. The toys are
safe. Period,'' said Terri Bartlett, TMA's communications director.
</P>
<P>
   TMA also accused PIRG and other ``self-appointed watchdog
individuals and groups'' of alarming consumers when no real danger
exists.
</P>
<P>
   The PIRG report on the Web:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.uspirg.org/consumer/products/toy/98/index.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Early detection of diabetes urged
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Screening and treating adults earlier for Type 2
diabetes would reduce its most severe complications and result in a
better quality of life, but not a longer life, a study by the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention found.
</P>
<P>
   A computer analysis published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association found that detecting diabetes earlier in its
onset would reduce the likelihood of kidney failure during a
patient's lifetime by 26 percent, blindness by 35 percent and foot
or leg amputation by 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Using what is known as ``opportunistic'' screening _ adding a
diabetes blood test onto an already scheduled doctor's visit _ on
average found diabetes 5.5 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   However, such a strategy also ends up costing more in health
care dollars, not less, said Dr. Michael Engelgau, CDC medical
epidemiologist. Screening and treating those age 25 and older now
for diabetes instead of waiting until age 45 _ the current
guideline _ would cost about $4,500 more over a person's lifetime,
Engelgau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some cost reductions from the decrease or delaying
complications, but in the end, it's not a net savings,'' Engelgau
said. ``You actually spend a little bit more on the screening, and
the treatment begins earlier. But you're getting a better value for
your money. It's an improved quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
