<HEADER>
A8463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-ROADS03-COX     12-02 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-ROADS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio cities to receive road improvements, thanks to growth
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The new millennium will mean a massive
reconstruction of area highways fueled largely by growth in the
Dayton-Cincinnati area, ambitious plans unveiled earlier this week
by state highway officials show.
</P>
<P>
   The four largest new major Dayton area highway projects to begin
in the year 2000 will cost at least $204 million when the dust
settles and the orange barrels return to hibernation, Ohio
Department of Transportation director Jerry Wray said.
</P>
<P>
   The spending promises to speed commuters, cut down on accidents
and reduce traffic snarls throughout the Miami Valley's most
rapidly growing communities.
</P>
<P>
   The projects _ boosted courtesy of this summer's landmark $216
billion federal highway bill _ include the long-awaited
reconstruction of the Interstate-70/I-75 interchange, widening I-75
to six lanes from Piqua to Troy, building a new interchange on U.S.
35 at North Fairfield Road and widening I-71 from the Ohio 48
intersection in Warren County south of Lebanon to I-275 in Hamilton
County.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest of the large-scale projects is the rebuilding
of the I-70/I-75 interchange, pegged to cost at least $107 million
when construction finishes sometime between 2007 and 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intersection is congested, over-capacity and not able to
accommodate the thousands of trucks which use it every day,'' Wray
said.
</P>
<P>
   The project calls for eventually widening ramps to two lanes and
rerouting merging traffic so it won't mix with exiting traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The project is divided into three independent phases, the first
costing $30 million for a new interchange at Brentwood and Wyse
roads. The Little York Road interchange will close, Wray said.
</P>
<P>
   The second phase costing $38 million will replace Little York
and Brown School roads and County Road 25A bridges with four ramps
to improve traffic merges. Sometime after 2003, west- and
east-bound ramps will be upgraded, Wray said.
</P>
<P>
   Further north on I-75 beginning in 2002, ODOT will spend $29
million to widen the highway to six lanes from Piqua to Troy. It is
now four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area has been rapidly developing and has become
increasingly congested,'' Wray said. The project moved up sharply
among the state's priorities in the last year, said ODOT
spokeswoman Rhonda Higgins.
</P>
<P>
   In Beavercreek on U.S. 35 at North Fairfield Road, ODOT will
spend $20 million to build an interchange with ramps to replace an
intersection just east on I-675. Again, Wray said, new development
has severely strained existing road capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area has had tremendous residential and commercial
expansion resulting in a high level of traffic congestion,'' he
said. The project will also extend Ohio 835 to North Fairfield
Road.
</P>
<P>
   South of Lebanon on I-71, ODOT plans to spend $44 million
widening the four-lane highway to six lanes from Ohio 48 to the
I-275 loop around Cincinnati. The first phase from I-275 to Western
Row Road could begin as early as late next year. ``That area is
extremely congested _ complete gridlock,'' said ODOT spokeswoman
Kim Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   Another major announcement Tuesday will speed funding to expand
U.S. 35 to a four-lane road from Xenia to the Ohio River through
Jamestown, Washington Courthouse and Chillicothe. Patterson said
the leg of the project from Bickett Road to a mile west of
Jamestown could open by year's end. The next section to a mile west
of the Fayette County line could open by the fall of 2000, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Dave Hobson, R-Springfield, applauded the move. ``''I
am truly pleased to see ODOT's commitment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bennish writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
