<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Dec. 2, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-BRIDGE (Laredo, Texas) _ A badly needed fourth span over
the Rio Grande is being built, promising a more efficient flow of
goods between Mexico and the United States. The $101 million
project also will bring new commerce to this booming trading port.
By DAVID HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   CHEVRON (San Francisco) _ It may seem like the world's oil and
gas companies are merging left and right. But don't expect Chevron
Corp. to follow suit immediately, if at all, the company and
analysts said. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FLEMISH-ART (New York) _ Large museums like the Metropolitan
Museum contain within them holdings that could form independent
museums of their own. The richness of the Met's collection in one
crucial area of Western art is made vividly clear in ``From Van
Eyck to Bruegel: Early Netherlandish Painting in the Metropolitan
Museum of Art.'' By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-BOOKS (Houston) _ The deluge of new design books this
season reflects some wide-ranging interests. No matter what style
you favor, whether you are interested in history or decorating
advice, there's probably a book about it. To review the best of the
new books, we have divided them into five categories: decorating
insight, styles, small spaces, design history and cultural history.
By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS (Houston) _ Holiday cookbooks range from the
basic to the exotic and there's a book for everyone this season _
for those who can barely boil water as well as those who can
prepare a meal fit for a king. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-MAIL-ORDER (Houston) _ It wouldn't be the holidays
without some specialty foods and mail-order products that have
become traditions. By ANN CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-CHEF (Albany, N.Y.) _ The United States Personal Chef
Association helps cooking-minded men and women set up their own
businesses making meals for busy families who desire to dine at
home but don't have the time to prepare dinner. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN (Undated) _ There are many similarities between the
history of wine in Australia and that of wine in California. Both
industries didn't really get under way until the mid-1800s. And
both prove to be innovative. By MICHAEL LONSFORD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-FRANCHISES (San Francisco) _ The annual Forbes magazine
rankings of sports franchises always cause a twitter among our
nation's fattest cats, because while you and I think that sports is
about athletic achievement, they know better. If they didn't know
better, they'd be sitting next to you at the diner asking you if
you're going to finish that sausage. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS (Jerusalem) _ Despite the passionate talk
from both Jews and Arabs about the sacredness of their land, this
is an era when land is not sacred soil, but a political commodity
to be exploited. Until now, the Israelis have had that privilege.
But Palestinians have generated their own forms of urban sprawl,
paying little attention to how unplanned growth might consume the
very soil that they profess to adore. By ELAINE RUTH FLETCHER.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIC-VEHICLES (San Francisco) _ Two California
transportation analysts say electric vehicles aren't ready for
prime time and may never be because the batteries that run them
aren't very effecient. A better choice to reduce pollution:
Clean-burning gasoline engines. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
