<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BYTES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH BYTES: IF HOLIDAY SEASON MEANS BUYING NEW PC, THERE'S A LOT
TO DIGEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    (ital)Welcome back my friends to the show that never ends
 &HT;    We're so glad you could attend
 &HT;    Come inside! Come inside! (endital)
 &HT;    _ Emerson, Lake &AMP; Palmer 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indeed, it never ends.
</P>
<P>
   Computing power gets more powerful, and does so at an increasing
rate. Prices drop just as quickly. Today's technology will be
obsolete tomorrow _ and you can almost take the words ``today'' and
``tomorrow'' literally.
</P>
<P>
   So what's a Christmas-season PC shopper to do? If you're aching
to put a computer under the tree this year, how do you guarantee
that it won't be a doorstop by next Christmas _ or even this
Easter?
</P>
<P>
   First, develop the proper attitude. Realize that, no matter what
you do today, there will always be something better to buy
tomorrow. It's a fact of life about the personal computer industry.
Make peace with it rather than agonize over it.
</P>
<P>
   Second, shop smart. If you buy old technology today, it's not
going to be fresh when you set it up, much less when you try to
load the latest and greatest programs on it a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   While you don't have to spend the astronomical sums you once did
for a modern PC, buying the cheapest you can find is only going to
leave you frustrated sooner rather than later. On the other hand,
depending on how you use a personal computer, you don't have to
overspend to get a machine that will provide you several years of
service.
</P>
<P>
   As it has matured, the computer market has developed into three
main branches.
</P>
<P>
   Budget buyers are looking for a low-cost computer that will do
most of what they want, ranging from managing family finances to
doing work at home to playing games. The sub-$1,000 category of
computers _ which really includes systems up to about $1,200 _ has
been one of the hottest in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The second branch are buyers who want to do work at home,
operate a home office or want a computer for education. They may be
doing some desktop publishing, working on graphical presentation or
may need to set up a home office. They need a PC that's a bit more
powerful or sophisticated and thus a bit more expensive _ in the
$1,200-$2,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there's the high-end user, usually a computing
enthusiast and/or a hard-core gamer. Typically, these folks use
fancy graphics applications, play state-of-the-art games and may be
willing to pay whatever it takes for faster-than-normal Internet
access. Their systems start at about $1,800 _ and the sky's the
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Budget buyers
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ryan, an editor with Family PC magazine, said budget
systems may be all that most home computer users need. You can
spend the minimum and still get plenty of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice is to spend the minimum amount required to get a
computer that runs the software you want to run today,'' Ryan said
via e-mail. ``With the exception of 3-D games, which appeal to a
small segment of the computer-buying public, I haven't seen a
compelling application that requires more processing power than you
get in a $700 system.''
</P>
<P>
   The systems that a year ago sold for close to $2,000 or more now
cost less than $1,000. Power comes cheap nowadays.
</P>
<P>
   Processor _ Shop for a system with at least a 300-megahertz
processor, which can be easily found in budget systems today. Most
300-Mhz chips in low-cost systems are going to be either Intel's
Celeron, the Advanced Micro Devices K6-2 or a Cyrix MII.
</P>
<P>
   There are two chips to avoid. The original 300-Mhz Celeron
lacked an onboard cache _ a kind of buffer that speeds up the
movement of data into and out of the chip. The latest 300-Mhz
Celeron that comes with a cache is called the 300A.
</P>
<P>
   Also, stay away from Cyrix's MediaGX chip, which robs at least 2
megabytes of system memory for use with graphics. That means if you
buy a computer with 32 MB of memory, only 30 MB is available to run
programs. Many of the super-cheap PCs that sell for as little as
$399 use this chip.
</P>
<P>
   Memory _ Remember that the more random access memory your
computer has, the faster and smoother it will run. Thirty-two MB is
the minimum, but RAM is so inexpensive these days that
computer-makers are loading up their low-end products with 48, 64
and even 96 MB of memory.
</P>
<P>
   However, memory prices are forecast to recover in 1999, so it's
smart to get as much memory as you can afford now. It may not be
this cheap again.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drives _ As with memory, hard drives are very inexpensive.
That makes it easy to recommend a minimum 4-gigabyte hard drive for
budget systems _ most have this size, or larger.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROM drive _ Most budget PCs do not come with DVD-ROM, the
new, higher-capacity compact disk format for data and movies. That
makes your choice here easy. Look for a standard CD-ROM drive with
a maximum speed of 24X _ meaning it's 24 times faster than the
original CD-ROM drives.
</P>
<P>
   Modem _ Again, your choice is easy here. All computers sold
today come with a fast 56K fax modem.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these, unfortunately, are a low-cost type known as a
winmodem. With a traditional modem, the commands used to control
the device are stored on chips on the modem. But with a winmodem,
these instructions are stored as a file on the computer's hard
drive. When the PC launches the Windows operating system, the
instructions are loaded into the modem.
</P>
<P>
   Winmodems are notoriously flaky. Reading the comp.dcom.modems
news group on Usenet on the Internet, you can find dozens of cries
for help from owners of these modems. If you can find a budget PC
that does not have a winmodem, and its specifications are
acceptable, buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is, however, that because the ``guts'' of a
winmodem are software-based, they can be upgraded just by applying
a software patch. If you own a winmodem that has difficulty making
or maintaining a connection to other computers, frequently check
the manufacturer's Web site for new updates.
</P>
<P>
   Video _ Look for a budget system that has at least 2 MB of video
memory. Most low-cost computers have at least that much, but if you
can find one with 4 MB, consider that a plus. The more video memory
on a graphics card, the more colors your PC can display at higher
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   You should also insist on a video card that can handle 3-D
graphics for games. It should be compatible with Microsoft's
DirectX graphics system.
</P>
<P>
   Audio _ Nearly all PCs sold today come with 16-bit, wavetable
sound (for realistic music) and a set of adequate speakers.
However, a growing trend is positional audio, which creates a 3-D
effect. Some games that support positional audio, for example, can
make sounds that seem to come from behind you. It's a neat feature
to have if you want to play games, and merely an option to consider
if you don't.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor _ Most budget systems don't come with a monitor, so the
category name ``sub-$1,000'' is often a misnomer. But as with PCs
themselves, the cost of monitors _ particularly smaller ones _ has
been dropping.
</P>
<P>
   You should look for at least a 15-inch monitor that has a
maximum dot pitch of .28mm. The dot pitch refers to how close the
screen's pixels _ the tiny dots that make up an image _ are to each
other. The smaller the number, the better.
</P>
<P>
   You should be able to find a decent 15-inch monitor in the $200
price range.
</P>
<P>
   Slots and ports _ Nearly all PCs today come with Universal
Serial Bus ports, along with the traditional serial and parallel
ports. But you'll want to pay close attention to how many internal
expansion slots a budget PC includes.
</P>
<P>
   Expansion slots are used to add features to a computer. For
example, if you decide you want to buy a scanner, and you want it
to scan images quickly, you'd probably want to consider adding an
SCSI card to your computer. You'd do this by plugging the card into
one of these slots.
</P>
<P>
   There are two primary kinds of slots _ ISA and PCI. The former
is an older design, while PCI is newer and works better with the
Windows Plug &AMP; Play feature. By this time next year, ISA slots will
be a rarity _ they will be gone from most PCs sold starting in 2000
_ but for now you'll want one in your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Thus look for a budget computer with at least one ISA and one
PCI slot. Some budget systems have a shared slot _ you can install
an ISA or a PCI card, but not both _ and you should avoid these.
</P>
<P>
   Basic home/business
</P>
<P>
   Kristina Blachere, an assistant editor with Computers.com _ part
of the CNet family of technology-related Web sites _ advises home
PC buyers to think carefully about how they would use a PC. And
research is very important.
</P>
<P>
   ``When choosing which brand of PC to buy, doing research is
important,'' Blachere said via e-mail. ``Read reviews. When you're
evaluating a potential system, find out what kind of components are
going into it. You'll have to look around to find good analyses of
these products, it's worth it not to get stuck with substandard
components.''
</P>
<P>
   The single most common application used on home computers
continues to be word processing, and this hasn't changed since
people first started bringing these machines into their dens.
</P>
<P>
   Many people use their PCs either to run a home business, or to
bring work home. These kinds of machines need to be a bit more
powerful than budget systems, because work done at home often
involves graphics. These machines also get used for home education,
and multimedia-based children's software also benefits from a more
powerful system.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   U,F,9 - BC-COMPUTER-BYTES-2NDTAK, -  &QL; 
 &UR; BC-COMPUTER-BYTES-2NDTAKE-HNS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &LR;  &QL; 
COMPUTER-BYTES-2NDTAKE &QL; 
UNDATED: powerful system.
</P>
<P>
   Processor _ Consider at least a 300-350 Mhz or faster Pentium II
or Celeron processor. The K6-2 and the Cyrix MII remain
alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Memory _ Sixty-four MB of memory is the minimum in this
category, largely because many home-business users tend to run
three or more applications at a time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not uncommon for a home worker to be using a word
processor, a spreadsheet, e-mail and a Web browser at the same
time. More memory makes this less painful.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drive _ Look for a system with 4 GB to 6 GB of hard drive
space. And again, the more the better, particularly if you do work
with graphics files, which can be large.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia software also tends to take up quite a bit of space
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Modem _ A 56K fax modem remains the standard here, although
business users may want to consider a modem that will handle voice
and comes with voice-mail software.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuters may want to consider ISDN or some other form of
higher-bandwidth connection, but that remains a luxury for now.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROM _ As with the budget line, a 24X drive is the minimum.
DVD really doesn't come into play in this category yet _ there just
isn't the software out there to justify including it.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, this will change, particularly as more reference
works and databases are available on DVD. But for now, you can pass
without worry.
</P>
<P>
   Video _ For educational software and home business use, a
minimum of 4 MB of video memory is a must, particularly since a
larger monitor (see the next category) also is a good idea. With
the kinds of recommended processors in this category, you also
begin to see video cards that use Accelerated Graphics Port
connections. These are faster than PCI-based cards, and they tend
to have more memory as well.
</P>
<P>
   Audio _ The specifications here are about the same as for a
budget system, though positional audio becomes more important if
you use educational or multimedia software.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor _ A 15-inch monitor also is the minimum here, but a
17-inch model is highly desirable, particularly if you do tend to
work with more than one program open at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Slots and ports _ Expandability becomes more important for those
who use their computers for work. Look for systems with at least
two ISA and two PCI slots.
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiast/gamer
</P>
<P>
   John Romero _ co-author of the hits Doom and Quake and
co-founder of Ion Storm, a Dallas-based game company _ doesn't
believe gamers should compromise at all when it comes to high-end
PCs. Asked via e-mail for his recommended minimum specifications,
Romero came up with the following:
</P>
<P>
   (ital) ``OK, a hard-core gamer is going to want this stuff:
</P>
<P>
   Intel Pentium II MMX 450Mhz w/512K L2 cache
</P>
<P>
   ViewSonic 21 P815 USB Hub Monitor
</P>
<P>
   Creative Labs RIVA TNT 3D accelerator
</P>
<P>
   256Mb RAM
</P>
<P>
   9.1Gb Ultra-wide SCSI Hard drive, 7.5ms seek, 1mb buffer
</P>
<P>
   Adaptec 2940 Ultra-wide SCSI adapter
</P>
<P>
   Creative AWE64 value
</P>
<P>
   Logitech USB First Mouse+ wheel mouse
</P>
<P>
   Plextor Ultraplex 40max CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Mad Catz Panther XL joystick
</P>
<P>
   Databurst ISDN external modem
</P>
<P>
   BSG Intensor chair or an Altec Lansing USB speaker system
</P>
<P>
   With some extra cash, I would get a Roland SoundCanvas SC-88 Pro
and an MPU-401 card.'' (endital)
</P>
<P>
   Romero estimated this would set you back about $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most gamers don't have that kind of cash lying
around. So Romero was shown the following specs, of which he
approved:
</P>
<P>
   Processor _ Insist on a 400 or 450 Mhz Pentium II chip. Although
AMD just introduced a 400 Mhz version of its K6-2, not all games
support its 3-D-graphics enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   Memory _ Sixty-four megabytes would be considered the absolute
minimum. Most gamers aren't multitasking when they play games, so
64 will do just fine in most cases. But more is always better, RAM
is cheap and ... well, you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Hard drive _ Games take up a huge amount of space. It's not
uncommon for a graphically intense title to grab up to 400 MB or
more off a hard drive. That's nearly half a gigabyte, and dedicated
gamers who buy many titles are going to quickly find themselves
constrained.
</P>
<P>
   That's why 6 GB to 8 GB should be the minimum. Romero mentioned
an SCSI-based hard drive, and while these are faster, they also are
very expensive. Drives that use the Ultra-DMA or EIDE standard are
just fine and are much cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   Modem _ Romero also mentioned an ISDN modem, and gamers who play
multiplayer titles over the Internet _ or enthusiasts who can't
stand to wait for Web pages to load _ should consider ISDN if it's
available in your area.
</P>
<P>
   It won't come cheaply, though. ISDN modems generally are twice
as costly as traditional modems, and ISDN service from the phone
company is pricey, too. Southwestern Bell charges $56 a month, not
including installation fees. And most Internet service providers
also charge more for an ISDN account.
</P>
<P>
   But since cable modems are not available in most areas (Time
Warner Cable won't bring them to Houston until next spring) and
Digital Subscriber Line (DSL) service from the phone company is
even further off, ISDN remains a bandwidth junkie's best friend for
now.
</P>
<P>
   CD-ROM _ The gamer/enthusiast category is the only one in which
a DVD drive makes sense. There are already a handful of adventure
games available on DVD _ including the excellent Tex Murphy:
Overseer _ and more are on the way. However, be aware that many
DVD-ROM drives, while they are compatible with traditional CD-ROM
disks, aren't as fast as CD-only drives. That's changing as DVD
technology improves, but it will be a while before DVD-ROM drives
catch up. If you feel you need blinding CD-ROM speed, it might be
worth skipping DVD for now. A true enthusiast doesn't mind cracking
a PC's case to install something better.
</P>
<P>
   Video _ For gamers, a video card that supports either Silicon
Graphics' OpenGL standard, or 3Dfx's proprietary Glide technology,
is a must. The hottest games use these display schemes, as well as
Microsoft's DirectX.
</P>
<P>
   Additional video memory is important for games as well. Advanced
video cards can use extra memory to aid in rapidly generating
incredible effects, so look for cards with at least 8 MB of video
RAM.
</P>
<P>
   Audio _ Positional audio is a must for gamers. There are two
standards _ one from Aureal, A3D, and the other from Creative Labs,
Environmental Audio. More games currently support A3D, but Creative
Labs is gaining, largely on the basis of its popular SoundBlaster
line of cards.
</P>
<P>
   Game-players also will want a set of speakers with a subwoofer,
a large bass speaker that usually is placed on the floor. Or, for
the ultimate in audio immersion, consider Romero's suggestion for
the BSG Intensor, a chair with speakers built into the base and
back.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor _ Because gamers want their experiences to be immersive,
a bigger monitor puts you in the middle of the action. A 17-inch
monitor is the minimum. But with the cost of 19-inch monitors now
where 17-inch models were last year, they are worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   Slots and ports _ Gamers may want to add a special 3-D-only card
to their current graphics card, such as one that uses 3Dfx
Interactive's Voodoo or Voodoo2 chips. And enthusiasts may want to
add an SCSI card, or a video-capture card. For those reasons,
you'll want two ISA and three free PCI slots.
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in home video editing, consider a PC that
has a IEEE 1394 connector _ also known as FireWire or ILink,
depending on the PC maker _ which can be used to connect consumer
electronics devices, including some video cameras. &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-27-98 1428EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
