<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-IBM-SFCHRON &LR;      12-02 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-IBM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESURGENT IBM THRIVES BY MEETING TECHNOLOGY NEEDS FOR 
U.S. BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By David Einstein   
 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a great ``Seinfeld'' scene in which George, after
fretting that he has become impotent, rediscovers his manhood and
shouts for all the world to hear, ``I'm back, baby!''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty well describes IBM these days.
</P>
<P>
   Given up for dead by many people just five years ago, Big Blue
has enjoyed under Lou Gerstner one of the great turnarounds in the
annals of U.S. business. With record sales and profits in 1997 and
a stock price that's shot through the roof, the Armonk, N.Y.,
company has regained its title as king of the computing world.
</P>
<P>
   Look anywhere in the industry and you'll find IBM's footprints.
Eight out of 10 mainframe computers sold carry the company's logo,
and an IBM AS/400, the most popular commercial business computer in
the world, is delivered to a new customer every 12 minutes of every
working day.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is among the leading makers of personal computers. It's one
of the top manufacturers of hard disk drives, which it develops and
produces in San Jose. And it makes microprocessors both for itself
and other computer-makers.
</P>
<P>
   It also is one of the top software companies in the world:
Nearly three-fourths of all the corporate data in the world is
managed by IBM's software, on IBM computers.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, IBM is among the leading makers of
supercomputers _ its Deep Blue system routed world chess champion
Garry Kasparov without breaking a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, the company routinely leads the United States in
patents, which come out of eight research laboratories including
the Almaden Research Lab in San Jose. IBM scientists recently have
developed a hard disk drive capable of holding 25 gigabytes of
information, and have found a way to replace aluminum in computer
chips with copper, which conducts electricity 40 percent better.
</P>
<P>
   What has really enabled IBM to prosper, however, is its ability
to help businesses develop, implement and maintain computer systems
for the Internet age, including networks, intranets and electronic
commerce Web sites. IBM goes in and provides the equipment _ both
its own and other companies' _ and then services the system. Such
services now account for 25 percent of IBM's sales
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of detail and deliverables they can get into are
astounding,'' said analyst Daniel Kunstler of J.P. Morgan. ``A lot
of companies can talk about creating a seamless global network, but
this is complicated stuff, and they can deliver it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by its ``Solutions for a small planet'' TV ads, IBM
has projected itself as the company others turn to for their
technology needs. It has been far more successful in promoting that
image than has Hewlett-Packard, its nearest competitor.
</P>
<P>
   OK: ``IBM has the largest service organization on the planet.
HP's not even close,'' said James Poyner, a respected analyst with
CIBC Oppenheimer. ``IBM has focused on pulling its various entities
together to provide a total bundle, and HP is just now pondering
these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, by acquiring Tandem and Digital Equipment, also signaled
its desire to be like IBM, but has a lot of catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   The heady confidence in Armonk these days contrasts sharply with
five years ago, when IBM, an icon of American business since the
1920s, was on the ropes after losing money for three straight years
_ including $8.1 billion in 1993 alone.
</P>
<P>
   IBM found itself caught in a shift away from mainframe computers
to client-server systems that could be run with smaller,
less-expensive computers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, IBM's PC business was in turmoil. After
pioneering PCs in the early 1980s, the company had watched
helplessly as a horde of IBM clones overwhelmed the market.
</P>
<P>
   IBM also was having trouble in the PC software business, where
its OS/2 operating system was in the process of being overwhelmed
by Microsoft Windows.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, it was clear that the company was on the ropes, despite
restructurings that had cut the workforce from 400,000 to 300,000.
In April of that year, the board sent chief executive John Akers
packing, replacing him with Gerstner, who had been CEO of RJR
Nabisco, the big food conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Gerstner started out with two strikes against him. He was the
first outsider ever to head up IBM, and he knew exactly zip about
technology.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, however, both of those apparent drawbacks
actually helped. Gerstner wasn't burdened by the traditional
blue-suit mentality that had paralyzed the company. And he cared
much more about selling products than what went inside them.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his grand vision for IBM, Gerstner said he didn't
have any. What he wanted to do was play to the company's strengths,
using its vast resources and global presence to forge a
product-services company second to none.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve that goal, Gerstner lopped off another 35,000 jobs
and began to cut back on research spending. At the same time, he
made it plain that pure research would take second place to
research that led directly to products.
</P>
<P>
   He also retooled the PC division, reducing a confusing product
line to a manageable number of models and doing a better job of
managing the retail channel.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gerstner, despite being a technological
neophyte, recognized early on that IBM could use the Internet as a
vehicle for its global business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to focus on a strategy that unifies all parts of
IBM, and it's about using technology centered around the Web to
help customers transform their businesses and compete more
effectively,'' said John Thompson, a 27-year IBM veteran who heads
up its North American operations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, IBM returned to the black with a profit of $3 billion.
The earnings grew to $4.2 billion in 1995, $5.4 billion in 1997 and
$6.1 billion last year. Revenues also rose steadily, going from
$62.7 billion in 1993 to $78.5 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has continued on its roll this year. For the third quarter,
net income totaled $1.5 billion, and revenues were $20.1 billion.
Mainframe sales still shone and the PC business was good enough to
lift IBM to the No.3 spot in the U.S. market, behind Dell and
Compaq. Disk drive sales were strong.
</P>
<P>
   So were sales of Lotus Notes, the corporate groupware that IBM
got when it acquired software pioneer Lotus for $3.5 billion in
1995. At the time, critics said IBM paid too much, but last summer,
Lotus sold 3.4 million licenses for Notes, compared to 3.2 million
for Microsoft's Exchange, the only major competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it's hard to find anyone critical of IBM these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit to Gerstner and his management team
for taking what had been a giant mismanaged company not nimble
enough to respond to a rapidly changing industry, and turning it
into a focused company aggressively attacking every segment of the
industry,'' said Collins &AMP; Co. analyst Bruce Raabe.
</P>
<P>
   About the only knock on IBM is its heady stock price, which has
gone from $106 a share in June to a record $170 on Friday.
Oppenheimer's Poyner downgraded the stock to a ``hold'' because he
doesn't expect the price to go much above $160.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-29-98 2038EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8662 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY01-COX     12-02 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
COLUMN: A UPS delivers cheap insurance against power surges 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Either computers are getting more delicate or my readers live
especially highly charged lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year or so, the number of reports I've received from
readers about electrical damage to computers _ mostly through
lightning strikes to the home, but often just from voltage surges
or unknown causes _ has greatly increased. Honestly, a week seldom
goes by without learning of some newly fried computer.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, owning a good voltage surge protector was
almost considered overkill. But nowadays, the really prudent
computer user uses a device called a UPS _ uninterruptable power
supply _ to protect a computer.
</P>
<P>
   By now you may know what a UPS is, but both a joy and handicap
of this column is to be sentenced to teach first grade year after
year. The notion is to treat fairly complex technical problems
without forcing you to learn a word of technobabble. The handicap
of all that is the necessity to just hit the high points of a topic
and to explain things that many of you already know.
</P>
<P>
   So let's start by making sure you know just what a UPS is. Think
of it as a big battery, equipped with circuitry that turns the DC
power into the AC current that your computer needs. Add to that
bundle the ability of the gadget to sense when the regular AC goes
out and to quickly (we're talking milliseconds here, less time than
it takes you to blink) switch from house current to power from the
UPS.
</P>
<P>
   If that's all a UPS did (and it is about all that very early
units were capable of doing), then a UPS would still be a terrific
device. You'd never lose any data when the lights went out.
Instead, you'd have time to save the information you were working
on and to shut down the computer normally. A UPS was never intended
to be a long-term source of power for home computer users. If the
unit furnishes even 10 minutes of backup power, that's plenty of
time to shut down your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays there have been two big improvements in the kind of UPS
a home user is likely to buy. For one, these units now include
protection from the kind of power problems that are a lot less
dramatic _ and a lot more likely _ than a blackout. I'll give you a
few ``for instances,'' but there are so many types of power
glitches you'll either have to do research on your own or just take
my word _ there are a lot of unseen gremlins crawling around the
power grid. One type of problem, maybe the most common, is a
voltage sag. That's caused when a device that uses a lot of current
when it starts up _ think of a refrigerator compressor, for
instance _ pulls the voltage level down. Air conditioners do the
same thing. In an extreme case, the lights will lower, but often
you never even see these potentially harmful sags.
</P>
<P>
   But you probably have seen the results of a sag. A big one can
literally freeze your screen and _ over time _ reduce the life span
of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the opposite end of the spectrum, there's the spike.
That's a big jolt of electricity that suddenly zaps down the line.
One cause could be a lightning strike so far away that you never
hear the thunder from it. But your computer can feel it and be
destroyed or damaged.
</P>
<P>
   So the first big improvement is the built-in filtering you'll
find in almost any UPS you find at the computer store. The second
big improvement is the one that makes it possible for me to
recommend that you buy a UPS. Prices have dropped dramatically.
Even three or four years ago, you would pay $400 or so for a good
UPS. While that was probably still a sensible thing to do, the high
price tag made a UPS difficult to recommend.
</P>
<P>
   But nowadays, you can find a decent UPS for $100 and _ even for
a really fine unit _ you'll pay $200 or less.
</P>
<P>
   It's some of the best money you'll spend on computing. And,
unlike that fancy PC of yours, your UPS won't go out of date. You
may eventually have to replace the battery, or even buy a new unit,
but it's the cheapest insurance available for computing today.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted appreciates hearing from you but cannot respond to
all e-mail. Personal home page:
http://www.mindspring.com/(tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
