<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Comparison Shopping For an ISP  
 By David Einstein   
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Question: &LR;  I need a new Internet service provider. I want
unlimited monthly use. There seem to be hundreds of choices
available. Do you have any suggestions on how to find a good ISP?
And are there any comparisons I could look at?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You're right, there are hundreds of ISPs to choose
from in California _ and more than 5,000 throughout the country.
Finding one that suits your needs won't be difficult, though,
because most ISPs offer unlimited service for a monthly fee of
about $20. (Some go as low as $8 a month if you prepay for a year.)
For information about ISPs with local access numbers for your area,
go to either www.boardwatch.com or www.isps.com. Both Web sites
have extensive lists of ISPs and the services they offer.
</P>
<P>
   As for comparisons, rating ISPs is a little tough because there
are so many of them. You might check out an article by my
colleague, Jon Swartz, in the October 27 special Telecommunications
Section in which he spotlighted some of the top performers. You can
find the article at sfgate.com, The Chronicle's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing an ISP, the most important considerations should
be reliability, service and technical support. Above all, you
shouldn't have to suffer busy signals or other connection problems.
</P>
<P>
   Grammatically Correct
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Packard Bell PC which came with Microsoft Works.
Although it has a spell checker, we badly need a grammar checker
for my teenage daughter. Is there a patch or add-on I can download
without upgrading to Word?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not that I know of. However, you can get Word, complete with
grammar checker, as part of Microsoft's Works Suite 99. This
under-$100 package is one of the best bargains around. Besides
Word, it includes Works version 4.5, the Encarta Encyclopedia 99,
Money 99, a mapping program and a greeting card program.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want my advice, forget the software and get your
daughter a good English grammar workbook. That way, she might learn
how to use the language so she wouldn't have to depend on a
computer. An electronic grammar checker can clean up her work and
possibly even improve her grades, but in the long run, she won't
know any more about English than she does now.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for spell checkers, which have given us a
generation of kids who don't know how to spell and don't care
because they can always ask the computer to bail them out.
</P>
<P>
   Little Black Book
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there some way to print out the address book in the
Netscape e-mail program? It would be handy to have a copy while
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   A: You can't send the address book information directly to the
printer, but with the latest upgrade of Netscape Communicator,
version 4.5, you can save it and print it out using another program
like Word.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how: With your address book open, select the name of the
directory _ such as Personal Address Book _ that you want to save.
Then choose Export from the File menu. Give the file a name and
save it. You can choose a format that's compatible with Netscape
Communicator or one that works with a word processor or
spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   No More Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Q: A few months ago, you provided information on how to disable
cookies when using Netscape Navigator or Internet Explorer. Is
there also a way to do it in the newest 4.0 version of America
Online?
</P>
<P>
   A: There is indeed. But before I get to that, let's define
cookies for readers who aren't familiar with them. A cookie is a
tiny file sent to your browser by a Web site. It's used to store
information about you for use when you return to the site. A cookie
could be a sign-on password, an account number or, more often,
information about your shopping preferences. By default, your
browser accepts cookies and doesn't alert you when one is sent.
</P>
<P>
   To change the way AOL 4.0 deals with cookies, choose Preferences
from the My AOL menu, click on WWW, and then click the Security
tab. Now select the very last option on the screen, titled Custom
(for expert users). Didn't know you were an expert, did you?
Finally, click on Settings. This brings up the Security Settings
box. Scroll down till you come to the part about cookies. You'll
see three options: Always accept cookies, Prompt before accepting
cookies, and Disable all cookie use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of columns ago, I described a way to create a shortcut
on the Windows desktop using Windows Explorer. A reader responded
with an even easier way. Right-click the Start button and choose
Open. Locate the program, folder or document you want, then drag it
to the desktop with the right mouse button. Finally, choose the
option labeled Create Shortcut(s) Here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Got a question about computing? E-mail it to computers(at
sign)sfgate.com
</P>
