<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Metallica scores with cover songs
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An album such as ``Garage Inc.,'' in which reigning hard rock
act Metallica pays tribute to the bands that influenced its early
career, could easily be a throwaway. Like those rarity-laden boxed
sets that show up just in time for Christmas, this two-CD package
of ``cover'' songs _ the sort of tunes Metallica played before it
had written many of its own _ is geared to the true fan's collector
mentality. But it's much more than a novelty, it's actually a
Metallica tradition: the latest installment in a series that
includes 1987's ``Garage Days Re-revisited'' album plus various
B-sides to vinyl and CD releases. (Disc 1 is newly recorded; Disc 2
features material from 1984 to '96).
</P>
<P>
   As expected, there's an abundance of death-tripping intensity
and ghoulish shenanigans (such as Budgie's ``Crash Course in Brain
Surgery'' and Danzig's pathological ``Last Caress'') as well as
homages to eternal underground faves Motorhead, the Misfits and
Mercyful Fate (bands whose names all, curiously, start with the
letter M). It's all delivered, as it should be, with a gleaming
ferocity and bit of a smirk, as if the songs were really the source
for good-natured horseplay. Yet there are all kinds of surprises.
Bob Seger's ``Turn the Page'' and Blue Oyster Cult's ``Astronomy''
provide glimpses of introspection and ``Tuesday's Gone,'' a
signature for Lynyrd Skynyrd, comes complete with a harmonica solo
by John Popper, the frontman for hippie jam faves Blues Traveler.
Stranger meetings could be imagined, but not anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garage Inc.''
</P>
<P>
   Metallica. Elektra. 27 tracks (two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A crash course in heavy metal fandom.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
