<HEADER>
A8692 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUTLER-ADVENT-NEW-YEA     12-02 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUTLER-ADVENT-NEW-YEAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CHRISTIANS, ADVENT PUTS NEW YEAR ON SOLID FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Hope you're having a Happy New Year.
 &HT;    No, it's not January. And Christmas is still weeks away. It is
Advent -- the beginning of the Christian year.
 &HT;    Many religions begin a new year at some time other than the
calendar new year of January 1. Although Christians have used that
calendar for centuries, it was not originally theirs -- it was a
secular calendar. Early Christians marked time differently than the
surrounding culture. Their year, the church year, began four weeks
before Christmas with Advent.
 &HT;    Most of us anticipate a new year with hope that the coming
twelve months will bring joy and prosperity. Yet, no matter our
hopes, what is to come remains unknown to us -- events will unfold
according to circumstances largely outside our control.
 &HT;    The Christian year also starts with expectation of what is to
come. Unlike the beginning of the secular year, however, Advent
proclaims what is coming can be known -- the coming of the Lord.
 &HT;    When I was a teenager attending a non-liturgical church, we
ignored Advent. Sometimes, my mother -- following an old family
tradition -- would buy an Advent calendar. After a few days, we
children would usually forget to open the windows until Christmas
eve. Advent -- the word itself means ``coming'' -- came and went in
the midst of holiday stress.
 &HT;    At that time, ``the coming of the Lord'' scared me. My church
taught that God's coming would be a time of judgment accompanied by
fire and destruction -- the end of the world. Although the pastor
believed the Lord would return soon (and seemed to think this a
good thing), I fervently prayed God would wait. I was sure I wanted
to avoid the end of the world. The coming of the Lord was not
something I anticipated with joy.
 &HT;    When I later joined the Episcopal church I was shocked -- and
dismayed -- to discover that the Christian year began with ``the
coming of the Lord.'' In spite of such wariness, Advent became my
favorite church season. It felt pleasingly counter-cultural to
celebrate a new year in the last weeks of everyone else's old one.
 &HT;    I came to appreciate the regularity of the church year in
contrast to the unpredictability of the secular year. More than
anything else, however, I learned to hope for the coming of the
Lord.
 &HT;    The Lord's advent should not inspire dread and fear. Rather,
when the church proclaims God's coming it proclaims hope and love.
Advent is about God's presence -- a God who comes into our lives as
as we face the vicissitudes of that other calendar.
 &HT;    When the strains of ``O come, O come, Emmanuel'' sound, we are
reminded that Emmanuel means ``God with us.'' Not God against us.
Not God judging us. God with us.
 &HT;    The Christian year -- indeed the Christian message -- centers on
the belief that God became enfleshed and dwelt with human beings.
God is not a distant, cold entity. Rather, God has joined us on our
journey; God has been with us and is with us.
 &HT;    Advent teaches that God came, does come, and will come. But it
also reminds that God comes in unpredictable ways.
 &HT;    At the time Jesus -- whom Christians believe the enfleshment of
God -- was born, those awaiting God thought God would come to judge
the earth, punish the wicked and establish a kingdom of justice.
Instead of this flashy entrance, God chose to be born as a child --
love and justice suckling its mother's breast.
 &HT;    God comes, yes. But God comes where least expected and often
unnoticed. This is not a God of glory, but, as Martin Luther, the
founder of Protestantism said, as a ``God hidden'' in humanity.
 &HT;    Beginning last January, I could have never predicted the changes
a single year brought in my life. But Advent prepared me by
reminding that -- in the midst of unpredictability -- the Lord will
come. Over the last year, I have seen God come many times -- as my
infant daughter grew and took her first steps, as my husband and I
learned to parent her, as my family cried when my father died, as
my sister and I held my mother's hands in the hospital after her
heart attack.
 &HT;    In these things and a thousand others, God came as companion and
comforter, teacher and mentor, guide and fellow-pilgrim along the
way. God came hidden in human suffering; swaddled in human joy.
 &HT;    Advent is not simply a time to prepare for Christmas -- a kind
of religious warm-up to the big event. Rather, Advent grounds the
new year on a solid foundation: whatever comes, God comes.
 &HT;    Not a bad way to begin.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
