<HEADLINE>
FIRST BOSTON POLISHES ITS IMAGE 
 HELP FOR SPEEDERS 
WEB ADDRESS FOR SALE 
DR. LAURA AU NATUREL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston's technology banking team _ led by
the uber-banker Frank Quattrone, who moved from Deutsche Bank in
July _ is turning the luxurious Phoenician resort in Arizona into a
playland for clients at its annual conference starting Monday. And
for the first time, reporters are invited to this most exclusive of
parties, which will include four-wheeling in the Sonoran desert and
a dinner show starring the comedian Dana Carvey.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden new openness? Credit Suisse First Boston could be
trying to improve its image.
</P>
<P>
   The company ranks seventh in advising on technology mergers and
acquisitions in the five months since Quattrone was promised
millions in exchange for bringing in more technology business.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse First Boston has been involved in six transactions
worth $2.14 billion, according to Securities Data Co.
</P>
<P>
   That pales in comparison with activity for Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, where Quattrone got his start, which advised on 16 deals
valued at $23.8 billion, and Bear Stearns Co., which advised on
five deals for $14.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse was absent last week from one of the technology
sector's highest-profile deals _ the acquisition of Netscape
Communications Corp. by America Online.
</P>
<P>
   And when Ascend Communications bought Stratus Computer Inc.
earlier this year, it was Salomon Smith Barney representing Ascend,
not the longtime relationship bankers in Quattrone's group.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Credit Suisse have to say?
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the company said it was indeed trying to
market itself to a wider audience. ``Frank Quattrone recognizes the
value of cultivating good media,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURA M. HOLSON &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Get a Speeding Ticket, Head for the Internet
</P>
<P>
   What do you get when you cross an Internet marketing guy with a
lawyer? In one case, www.speedingticket.net, a new Web service for
people nabbed for speeding and other traffic violations while away
from home territory.
</P>
<P>
   The intent of the site _ not to be confused with
www.speedingticket.com, which sells a book on how to beat a
speeding ticket _ is to match traffic violators with local lawyers
who can represent them in court in the counties where they got
their tickets. And with the holiday travel season soon to be in
full swing, the prospects are pretty good that there will be plenty
of tickets doled out to people just passing through town. Already,
the site is getting 11,000 hits a day on some weekends.
</P>
<P>
   John White, an Internet entrepreneur in Charlotte, N.C., said he
came up with the idea after a friend who is a lawyer told him how
much effort he had been putting into trying to get the names of
traffic violators from out of town in the hopes of getting their
business. Eventually, White says, he plans to offer an online
traffic school and listings of bail bondsmen nationwide. Pretty
soon, traffic violators will not even have to leave their homes to
get themselves out of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   White charges lawyers $99 each to list their firms on
speedingticket.net, and so far he has 1,500 of the nation's 3,100
counties covered. His goal is to list three or four lawyers in each
county, so people can shop around.
</P>
<P>
   For the ticketed, the service is free _ but the legal services
are not. Depending on the area of the country and the complexity of
the case, a traffic violator can typically hire a lawyer in a
speeding case for $100 to $300. White says his biggest customers so
far have been truck drivers and traveling salespeople, who cannot
afford to see their insurance premiums go up.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   More Fancy Prices for a Domain Name
</P>
<P>
   And you thought the days of Internet squatting were over? Kevin
Sinclair, who lives in a Silicon Valley suburb, is the lucky owner
of www.computer.com, presumably one the most valuable domain names
on the World Wide Web. And now he wants to sell it for at least
$500,000. So far the highest bidder has offered $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   His associate representing him in the sale, Gary Kremen, insists
that Sinclair is not a speculator but that he planned to start an
online computer store when he acquired the name in 1994. He quickly
realized he did not have a shot in such a competitive market, even
with the right address. So he left the working world to stay home
with his children.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinclair, who also has the phone number 1-800-COMPUTER, is
willing to accept cash, he would prefer stock in an Internet
start-up. And Kremen may be just the right guy to help him make a
deal: Kremen was involved in the negotiations between Digital
Equipment Corp. and Jack Marshall, who until earlier this year
owned the address www.altavista.com. Digital, which owns the Alta
Vista search engine, paid Marshall $3 million to give the name up,
reportedly the largest amount ever paid for a domain name.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   12 Nude Pictures Start a Copyright Extravaganza
</P>
<P>
   As copyright battles go, this one just does not seem to have an
end in sight. Just a few weeks after a federal judge ruled that the
Internet Entertainment Group could display 12 nude photos of Laura
Schlessinger, the radio talk show celebrity whose program offers
advice to both the lovesick and the just plain sick, on its Web
site, the company finds itself caught up in a nasty fight to
prevent other Web sites from doing the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   The company, based in Seattle, has sent a cease-and-desist
warning to more than 50 Web site owners to get them to stop
publishing the photos, which the company bought from Bill Ballance,
Schlessinger's lover 20 years ago. And last week, it filed a
lawsuit against one of them, the After Hours Production Co. of
Houston, calling the whole lot Internet pirates.
</P>
<P>
   It all started earlier this fall when Schlessinger, known to her
fans as Laura, sued Internet Entertainment in an ill-fated attempt
to prevent it from displaying the photos. On Nov. 2, a federal
judge in Los Angeles ruled in favor of the company, saying that as
the legal copyright holder, it had the right to publish the photos,
which were apparently taken while Schlessinger and Ballance were
married to other people. Since then, more than 100,000 people have
viewed the photos online.
</P>
<P>
   With this latest action, the saga of the dirty dozen is, once
again, about to test the limits of the nation's copyright laws as
they apply to the Internet. Internet Entertainment Group contends
that the other Web site owners could be fined as much as $100,000
and handed jail terms of as long as five years.
</P>
<P>
   As for Schlessinger, it's irrelevant to her how many Web sites
pick up the photos at this point or who wins the court battles.
``What difference does it make?'' said Keven Bellows, vice
president and general manager of ``The Laura Schlessinger Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The cow is already out of the barn,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-29-98 1633EST &QL;
</P>
