<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHTOOLS01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Grolier encyclopedia serves its purpose well 
By Jack Warner  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 1999 Grolier multimedia encyclopedia has its share
of problems, but on the whole it is a very useful reference work.
</P>
<P>
   The interface, while easy enough to use, also allows the user to
easily miss some features. I've grown used to encyclopedias that
use little icons to show you when a photo, video or sound is
available. Grolier's doesn't do that _ ancillary stuff is included
in a pull-down menu.
</P>
<P>
   However, a quick look at the little manual or a glance at the
help screens will prevent this kind of problem.
</P>
<P>
   A two-disc encyclopedia, it can behave very strangely if you
don't change discs just the way it tells you to, and my text
windows had an unfortunate tendency to come up in a nearly
unreadable script font.
</P>
<P>
   My usual checks revealed no insurmountable problems.
</P>
<P>
   The article on flamenco is exceedingly brief, and online
articles yield little more.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reference to the Three Guardsmen _ Deputy U.S.
Marshals Bill Tilghman, Heck Thomas and Chris Madsen _ or to Bill
Doolin, their greatest nemesis. There is, curously, a paragraph on
Cat Thompson, a three-time All-America basketball player for
Montana State in the 1930s. Grolier is big on sports.
</P>
<P>
   The article on bullfighting is quite adequate to the
encyclopedia's purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Music is a mixed bag. Composers do not seem to be awarded aural
samples according to their stature; Mozart is represented only by a
smidgen of Eiene Kleine Nachtmusik, execrably presented via
synthesizer. The presentation of the music is also random; an
excerpt from the first movement of Beethoven's 5th symphony is
played by orchestra, while excerpts from the 6th are done,
inaccurately, on a synthesizer.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine why publishers continue to let this happen. How
much more can it cost to acquire a snippet of orchestral music than
the same snippet butchered on a synthesizer? Presumably it requires
more space to store _ but I believe students would benefit more
from a few bars of Beethoven's 6th played the way he wrote it on
the instruments he intended than they would from a biography of Cat
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   Articles on the major composers, however, are quite generous,
and there are brief synopses of the plots of major operas.
</P>
<P>
   The panoramic scenes are plentiful, and reasonably well
realized. The list of videos includes most of the old standbys.
</P>
<P>
   Articles are well written and appear to contain more than enough
material to satisfy the needs of high school students. Authors are
cited for major articles.
</P>
<P>
   The two-disc encyclopedia itself sells for about $50; the
version I looked at came as the Grolier Multimedia Reference Suite,
with three other disks; the Wall Street Journal Almanac, a Hammond
atlas, Bartlett's Familiar Quotations, and, for some reason, a
thin, hardbound grammar text.
</P>
<P>
   The Bartlett's is in an ``Expanded Multimedia Edition,'' a
bizarre thing in which pictures and even musical excerpts are
strewn among the quotations, but have absolutely nothing to do with
them.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, that's multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
