<SLUG> BC-CPT-MAC-REPORT01-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
OS 8.5 fixes problems with system 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You've heard that it's faster. You've heard it has a
much more powerful search engine. But did you know OS 8.5 will
automatically check your hard disk for problems and fix any ones if
found?
</P>
<P>
   This is just one of the many small but important improvements
Apple Computer has added to the latest version of the software,
called the operating system, or OS. Some have likened the purpose
of an OS to a computer's central nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the Mac's OS was getting a little unstable. But with
each incremental improvement during the past two years, the OS has
gotten stronger and stronger. OS 8.5 is the strongest enhancement
yet.
</P>
<P>
   I've written about the big improvements, including the powerful
new find system and speed enhancements. Now I'm going to address
some of the smaller yet important improvements and additions in OS
8.5.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more significant of those is an automatic problem
detection system. Whenever you start up your Mac, the OS now checks
your hard drive for any damage to files or directories and, if it
finds problems, it tries to repair it. Such preventive maintenance
can prevent small problems from becoming big ones that might bring
down your Mac.
</P>
<P>
   In OS 8.5, Apple Computer has added a popular feature pioneered
by Netscape Navigator. You can add favorite files, folders and Web
sites to a handy list and quickly jump to them.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Apple Menu is a folder titled Favorites. Add items to
this folder by holding down the Apple command key and clicking the
mouse. Up will pop a menu of commands, which includes an Add to
Favorites item. Highlight and release this command to add stuff to
the favorites folder.
</P>
<P>
   OS 8.5 makes it easy to see what application is currently
running and switch among various applications. It does this through
a new feature called Application Switcher.
</P>
<P>
   The name of any active application is now displayed in the upper
right-hand corner of the menu bar with OS 8.5. Drag and drop that
name onto the desktop, and it turns into a little panel. Listed in
the panel are icons representing any running applications.
</P>
<P>
   To switch among applications, you click on its icon in the
panel. You can also cycle through running applications by pressing
the Command and Tab keys.
</P>
<P>
   As with everything with OS 8.5, Application Switcher is easy to
customize.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, OS 8.5 only works on PowerPC-based Macs. Those of
you with earlier models are out of luck. OS 8.5 retails for $99.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-30-98 1024EST &QL;
</P>
