<HEADLINE>
US MOVES TO PROTECT INTERNET COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By AARON ZITNER   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, invoking a future in which
Internet commerce helps everyone from American holiday shoppers to
impoverished Third World farmers, unveiled new steps Monday to
encourage more people to buy and sell products on line.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting a report from his staff on Internet shopping, the
president called for stronger fraud and privacy protections to make
people more comfortable with electronic commerce, or e-commerce.
But those protections should come from industry, not from new laws,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who surf the Web still don't shop there,'' Clinton
said. ``They worry they won't get what they thought they were
paying for; they'll have nowhere to go if they get cheated.''
</P>
<P>
   He said these fears should be addressed ``not with burdensome
regulations that might stifle growth and innovation, but with
incentives for on-line companies to offer customers the protections
they need.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's address, to staff and business executives near the
White House, was part cheerleading session for the Internet and
part goodbye party for Ira Magaziner, a longtime Clinton friend and
adviser who supervised the Internet report.
</P>
<P>
   Magaziner, a longtime businessman and political activist in
Rhode Island and Massachusetts, will return to New England this
month (December) after six years as a senior adviser to the
president. Magaziner was a key adviser on Clinton's 1994 health
plan, which died amid a massive fight in Congress. After that
bruising defeat, Clinton asked him to work in a different policy
area, and in 1995 Magaziner began helping to formulate
administration policy on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, Magaziner's inter-agency group calls for the
government to create new incentives for companies to invest in
high-speed networks so that material can be downloaded from the
Internet more quickly. Clinton said Monday he had instructed
several agencies to work on that issue with the independent Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, FCC Chairman William Kennard said his agency
would try to create more competition among telephone, cable, and
other companies in offering high-speed Internet connections to
consumers. But he offered no specifics. ``This creates a new sense
of urgency for those of is in government,'' he said of the
Magaziner report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also called on the FTC to continue its efforts to
enforce fraud and consumer protection laws on the Internet.
Magaziner said the federal government would urge other countries to
sign treaties that extend similar protections to consumers who
cross national borders when they buy goods over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should get what they pay for on line,'' Clinton said.
``It should be easy to get redress if they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also instructed the State Department to find ways to
spur e-commerce in developing countries. As a model, Vice President
Al Gore cited a Peruvian town that had quintupled its income by
using the Internet to sell its vegetables in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A central issue in e-commerce involves consumer privacy: what
information businesses should be able to collect from consumers,
and what they may do with that information. Magaziner said the
Clinton administration backed an industry self-policing plan in
which companies that adhere to standard practices can display a
special ``seal of approval'' on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Several private groups are offering these seals, including the
Council of Better Business Bureaus and an organization called
TRUSTe. In order to display a seal, companies must offer consumers
a clear statement of what information is being collected about
them, how it is being used, and what they can do to correct errors
and control the spread of the information.
</P>
<P>
   Magaziner predicted that by March, companies responsible for 70
percent of e-commerce will adopt a privacy seal. He said trade
groups in Japan and Australia had agreed to adopt a similar system
so that the same seals can be used worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The administration approach has drawn several critics. At the
Center for Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit civil liberties
group, Deirdre Mulligan said the administration had failed to
follow through on an earlier promise to assess whether
self-regulation was truly protecting consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear right now whether self-regulation is working...
and the administration should say what it will do if it doesn't
work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cato Institute, a libertarian think tank, Solveig
Singleton said the government may have already used too heavy a
hand in protecting privacy. She questioned whether companies had
adopted privacy seals in the best interest of consumers, or because
the government had threatened to pass its own burdensome rules if
they did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is all kinds of experimentation going on about when
consumers care about confidentiality and when they do not, and
about how you have a relationship on line,'' she said, adding that
government privacy rules could stifle that experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   The event Monday provided a rousing send-off for Magaziner. In
his speech, Clinton thanked him for his work and called him ``my
friend of 30 years now.'' In the audience were Magaziner's wife,
Suzanne, and their three children.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his White House service, Magaziner said: ``I feel
good about it, particularly the last couple of years. It's nice to
succeed at something, though I'm still proud of what we've done''
in health care policy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-30-98 1956EST &QL;
</P>
