<HEADER>
A8775 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGERBREAD-SIDE-AZR &LR;      12-02 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGERBREAD-SIDE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS IS AS FUN TO DECORATE AS IT IS TO EAT  
 (ADV: WITH GINGERBREAD. INCLUDES RECIPE AND TIPS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - So you think maybe, just maybe, despite Kathleen
Ingley's dire warnings, that you want to decorate a gingerbread
house.
</P>
<P>
   Never fear. Meet Cathy Wochner of Phoenix. On Sunday (note: dec.
6) she will have three generations around her dining room table,
making gingerbread houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun is building memories,'' Wochner says. ``They look back
every year and say, `Wow, this is what we did last year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her three sons grew up making and nibbling on their mother's
baked architecture around the holidays. Now, they bring their
families, girlfriends, and Wochner's 2{-year-old granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   After years of experimentation, Wochner developed a gingerbread
house plan that bakes in one jellyroll pan. It makes a small house
approximately 6 inches square, perfect for individual decorating.
Since you can bake the house and let it stand for up to a week
before covering it with cute candy, you have time (theoretically!)
to make one for each child in the family.
</P>
<P>
   And, let's face it, big kids love to decorate gingerbread
houses, too.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Wochner had a business making gingerbread houses,
and sold 1,000 videos on the subject. She since has moved on to
other things and says no to the calls she still gets from people
who want her to bake gingerbread houses for them. She has gone back
to the tradition of making them just for family.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, kits and cast-iron plaques and all other sorts of
short-cuts to making candy condos have evolved. And Wochner
approves of them all. If you can't bake, go ahead and buy the
undecorated houses, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those work!'' she said. ``Buy five and spend an evening around
the table. It's absolutely fabulous. I encourage people to bring
what they want to nibble on. Of course, the house doesn't smell as
good; that's a drawback. But that's OK. It's a '90s kind of
thing.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gingerbread House &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From Cathy Wochner) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon allspice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup brown sugar, packed
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup light molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup oil plus 1/4 cup for greasing pan
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal icing: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cream of tartar
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 cup water
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
In a medium bowl, thoroughly blend dry ingredients. Add the
molasses, beaten egg, and half-cup of oil. Blend thoroughly. Chill
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Oil a 12- by 18-inch jellyroll pan
(no other size) with the additional quarter-cup of oil. Roll dough
very evenly, making absolutely sure the extra oil is absorbed into
the dough. Fill pan completely with dough and roll smooth. Before
going into the oven, the dough must be oily and smooth _ this is
the secret to a beautiful gingerbread house. Bake 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While still hot, quickly lay pattern pieces on dough and cut out
shapes. Lift out carefully and cool on racks until gingerbread is
hard and cool. If necessary to harden, pieces can be put back in
the oven on cooling rack for 5 to 10 minutes longer.
</P>
<P>
   For icing: beat egg whites and cream of tartar until very stiff.
Gradually add powdered sugar, also adding a little water to make
the proper consistency. Keep covered with damp cloth at all times.
</P>
<P>
   Makes one gingerbread house. &QL; 
GINGERBREAD HOUSE TIPS &QL; 
 &QL; 
- You will need a base for the house, such as a 14-inch round of
cardboard. &QL; 
- To glue the house together with royal icing, you also will need a
large pastry bag with plastic coupling and two tips, including a
small one for writing and making icicles, and a large one for major
``cement.'' All are sold as cake-decorating supplies. &QL; 
- Humidity will soften the dough, so don't try to make gingerbread
houses when it rains. &QL; 
- Don't double the recipe to make more than one house. Bake each
batch separately. &QL; 
- To decorate your house, remember small candies will look best on
a small house. Cereals make good construction materials, such as
shredded wheat for thatched roofs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Source: Cathy Wochner &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
