<HEADER>
A8778 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGERBREAD-AZR &LR;      12-02 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGERBREAD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISION OF GINGERBREAD BECOMES CONSTRUCTION NIGHTMARE  
 (ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS. WITH
GINGERBREAD-SIDE) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The holiday lights are twinkling, the stores are
filled with the strains of ``Rudolph, the Red-Nosed Reindeer,'' and
you can't help feeling the nostalgic urge to make a gingerbread
house. Take my advice: Lie down until the feeling passes.
</P>
<P>
   My own moment of weakness came last December, when I was getting
down the boxes of Christmas trappings and decorations. There,
making me feel guilty once again, was the never-opened box with a
kit to make a gingerbread house.
</P>
<P>
   My children were in their teens, and I'd never made them a
gingerbread house. If I didn't act now, they'd have one more
complaint to bring up in future therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The box held almost everything I'd need: a stone mold for the
walls, roof and chimney; a cloth tube for squirting frosting; and a
booklet with the directions and recipe.
</P>
<P>
   My trip to the supermarket was an omen.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching the booklet, I steered my cart through the
holiday-crowded story. I'm not the cook in our household, so I was
tracking down ingredients I hadn't bought in years. If ever.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger, of course. Molasses. Multicolored sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   But I scoured the shelves without finding cream of tartar. From
watching my mother cook when I was a kid, I had a dim recollection
of a white powder that had something to do with thickening. I was
tempted to skip it altogether. But just then a clerk happened by,
so I asked him where to find it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cream of tartar?'' he asked doubtfully. ``Like tartar sauce?
Wouldn't that be over by the fish?''
</P>
<P>
   I gave up and went through the checkout line, humming Christmas
carols to myself. But when I got home, my mood darkened: I'd lost
the crucial booklet with all the directions.
</P>
<P>
   Even after a trip back to the store, retracing my steps with the
vigilance of Sherlock Holmes, I couldn't find the book. However, I
did find a clerk who knew cream of tartar.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, I dug through yellowed and aging cookbooks without
spotting a gingerbread recipe that seemed likely to produce a house
that would stay upright. Then I recalled a cute flier of holiday
tips and recipes that my husband threw away. I fished it out of the
trash.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo.
</P>
<P>
   The actual baking went surprisingly well. I had no idea whether
to grease the mold, but figured a light oiling wouldn't hurt. I
baked a separate sheet of cut-out dough to stop the family from
nibbling on the house. I shouldn't have worried. The dough cooked
up like a rock.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect for construction, I thought. I started mixing up the
frosting to use as mortar. Now, I don't actually have a mixer, but
I figured a fork would do just as well for ``mix at high speed for
3-4 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   I carefully drizzled frosting along all the edges and lined the
pieces up. The house imploded.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the best technique was one side at a time. I balanced
two walls together, positioned the other two, added a piece of
roof. It all fell down.
</P>
<P>
   Variations of this scenario continued for the next half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I finally decided, no one was going to eat this gingerbread
house, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It was time for glue. The Goop glue had an uncanny resemblance
to the frosting as I squeezed it along the gingerbread. And it had
an uncanny resemblance to frosting as the entire house fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe that was the wrong kind of glue.
</P>
<P>
   So I whipped out the Duco cement. Two walls and a chimney seemed
to be holding. I gently attached the other walls and squeezed the
building together. The chimney broke. The roof slid off. My hands
were coated with dried glue.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so this was really a craft project.
</P>
<P>
   So I got the fabric paste. I slathered it on the walls and roof.
I tried to reconstruct the chimney.
</P>
<P>
   The doorbell rang. The house fell down.
</P>
<P>
   ``What on earth are you doing?'' asked my friend Barbara,
coughing a bit from the glue fumes.
</P>
<P>
   But she saved the house.
</P>
<P>
   She started with toothpicks, gently driving them in like nails
in the thicker parts and breaking off the ends. Then she called for
straight pins, carefully joining the thinner spots. The colored
pinheads looked like little candies.
</P>
<P>
   I retreated while my daughter Rachel did the final decorating. I
did hear her call out, ``This frosting tube should have had a
closed end.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess that's why there was icing on the floor, the counter,
the table, the refrigerator, the cat dish.
</P>
<P>
   When we were out at a restaurant that night, my husband leaned
over and whispered, ``What's that white stuff in your hair?''
</P>
<P>
   And he couldn't understand why it was February before I was
willing to take the gingerbread house off display on the mantel.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson No. 1: A gingerbread house doesn't need a cook but a
carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson No. 2: Those ready-made gingerbread houses at the
supermarket are a steal. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
