<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8781 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS03-COX     12-02 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESENDING CORRECTED VERSION. USE THIS
 &HT;    More of same from still rockin' Stones
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault, Doug Hamilton, Steve Dollar and Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the question is whether this live album is necessary, then
the answer _ one being volunteered by many critics _ is a
resounding ``No.'' It's the umpteenth live recording from the
Stones, whose music is also available on some 50 other releases.
But if the question is, does ``No Security'' satisfyingly document
the band's just-ended tour, the answer is an equally resounding
``Yes.'' It captures the ability of fiftysomething Mick Jagger &AMP;
Co. to still raise a sonic ruckus and delight fans with strong
versions of ``Sister Morphine,'' ``Gimme Shelter,'' ``The Last
Time'' and other tunes from a deep catalog. As the just-announced
plans for an arena tour starting in January indicate, the Stones
won't go away. So let 'em roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Security''
</P>
<P>
   Rolling Stones. Virgin. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's redundant, but it rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Mini audio reviews
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FOLK
</P>
<P>
   ``Holiday Songs and Lullabies''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Colvin. Columbia. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The Grammy-winning singer of ``Sunny Came Home'' wishes you
not-so-happy holidays with this somber, slow-moving collection.
Colvin's morose delivery on the already melancholy seasonal
standards ``Christmas Time Is Here'' and ``Silent Night'' may make
you want to throw yourself on the yule log. And while the
interspersed lullabies, including ``All the Pretty Li'l Horses''
are obviously close to the singer's heart _ she became a mother for
the first time last year _ they won't soothe an infant so much as
depress one. The perfect background music for a holiday party at
Dr. Jack Kevorkian's place.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Visions of Jazz: The First Century''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Blue Note. 38 tracks (two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Collections of yesteryear with a survey of great artists through
the decades: from Sidney Bechet and Art Hodes' ``Memphis Blues'' to
Cassandra Wilson singing Son House's ``Death Letter.'' Like the
book, it's extensive in what it covers and highly selective in who
it covers, but consistently serves as an easy introduction to an
often complicated music. And, whether it's Sonny Rollins, Joe
Lovano or Lester Young blowing their horns, the emphasis is on
tunefulness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  BLUES / JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. V2 . 27 tracks. 2 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   It's been so unfair. For 40 years we have only been able to
experience the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater on stage. The
incredible blues (Hugh Masekela's ``Babjula Bonke''), gospel (``I
Been 'Buked''), and jazz (Charlie Parker's ``A Night in Tunisia'')
used to score the dancers' interpretations of slavery, the
pageantry of black churchgoing, and sinning have never been
available on one recording. So for many who have seen an Ailey
show, not being able to relive it audibly has been comparable to
being moved by a sermon on Sunday and not having a Bible to refer
to for reminders during the week. But now, finally, the soul of not
only Ailey, but some of the powerful experiences that make one
American, is captured in this cohesive and representative box set.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
