<HEADLINE>
MERGER ANNOUNCEMENT TAKES GAS STATION OWNERS BY SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL BOWEN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's a long way from the Mobil Corp.
boardroom to Dennis Heiser's Mobil station on Loop 820 in North
Richland Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Heiser has run the dealership for 23 years and has long enjoyed
a companionable relationship with the owner of the Exxon across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after Exxon and Mobil's megamerger, the Exxon station on
the opposite corner will be a brother business to Heiser's Mobil
station. What that means for dealers and consumers remains in
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all at a kind of a loss,'' Heiser said Tuesday.
``Usually, they tell us about something before it hits the papers.
But this came as a slap in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies said that they will retain both brands at the
retail level. But regulators and consumers will be watching for
signs that the loss of competition hurts consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think many times it's better for the consumer to have more
brands and more competitors,'' said Lynton Allred, executive vice
president of the Austin-based Texas Petroleum Marketers and
Convenience Store Association. ``I think it might hurt consumers in
the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined company will control almost 20 percent of the Texas
retail gasoline market. Exxon is the dominant player in the state,
with about 14 percent of the retail gasoline market, compared with
Mobil's 5 percent, according to Trilby Lundberg, a California-based
consumer research company.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil has recently shifted its retail presence in the state. In
October, it entered a venture with San Antonio-based Tetco to
operate its 145 Metroplex stations. Mobil retained a 49 percent
stake in local stores. In return, Tetco's 173 stores across the
state will sell Mobil products exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon has a stronger retail presence with hundreds of
company-owned outlets in Texas, which account for 30 percent of its
sales in the state. The remaining 70 percent of the sales are
handled by independent operators and convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   The question for Allred and his association members is the same
for consumers: Will any of the company's estimated annual savings
of $2.15 billion to $3 billion mean lower gasoline prices?
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have said supply and demand play the key role in
dictating prices. And they noted that any corporate savings may
flow to the bottom line, boosting profits and perhaps stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   But as Allred says, ``If you can cut that much in operational
costs, someone is going to benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
