<HEADLINE>
CLEANER GAS ENGINES MAY BE BETTER THAN ELECTRIC VEHICLES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Randy Rentschler's first car was a tan 1970
Oldsmobile Cutlass with a four on the floor, dual carbs and a white
vinyl top. It was awful looking, but a pleasure to drive. He
totaled the thing a month after buying it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Rentschler is a financial analyst for the Metropolitan
Transportation Commission in Alameda, Calif. At 38, he drives a
1988 Ford Ranger truck and a 1990 Ford Aerostar Van, while his wife
tools around in a Dodge Neon.
</P>
<P>
   Rentschler still loves cars, but it's more of a platonic thing
with him now. He reads about them, thinks about them and writes
about them. His home in Alameda is cluttered with Auto Week and
Road and Track magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, he's been pondering the future of motoring. With the
help of a fellow Transportation Commission worker, Marjorie
Blackwell, he pulled together everything pertinent about electric
cars and hybrids _ cars powered both by electricity and gas engines
_ in an edition of ``Transactions,'' the commission's newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, Rentschler and Blackwell contend, is that
electric vehicles, or EVs, aren't ready for prime time and may
never be. The battery is the reason. Thomas Edison couldn't get it
right a century ago and Detroit can't get it right today. Designers
still haven't solved the problems of range and recharge time.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can plug the pollution-free cars into your household
current, but you'll be lucky to drive 100 miles before you need a
recharge, which could take up to six hours. More likely are the
combo vehicles, which rely on electric engines at lower speeds, gas
engines at higher ones _ and, best of all, recharge themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Rentschler said that state governments can push for EVs all they
like and the cars still won't catch on because they don't make
sense economically, particularly with gas so cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are small, compact cars, which are a shrinking segment
of the market. But say you could get a mid-sized one. What you're
buying probably is pretty good around town. Take it down I-5 and
get it up to 70 miles an hour, however, and you'd be pushing the
technology,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds bad. But only if you take the short view, Rentschler
said. Because the Law of Unintended Consequences is playing a
behind-the-scenes role here, he explained, and everything could
work out fine environmentally.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect of the challenge posed to conventional vehicles
by EVs, Rentschler said, has been to push the automotive companies
to make cleaner combustion engines.
</P>
<P>
   Gas isn't burned perfectly _ and that's why there is pollution
in the form of hydrocarbon residues, he said. In the bad old days,
if you put a piston under a microscope, it would resemble a
mountain range. Each of those countless pits in the metal could be
the birthplace of junk that mucks up the air, the skylines and our
lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, the automakers _ fearing costly replacement
technology even as it experiments, under prodding, with alternative
power sources _ is making pistons so smooth there's no place for
the gas and its waste products to hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought electric cars were the answer, but they're just the
bridesmaid again, though their net effect has been positive,''
Rentschler said. ``The industry got excited, like hornets get
excited, and put money into research. The outcome has been an
internal combustion engine that's incredibly competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
