</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS JOBS COULD BE LOST AS OIL GIANTS JOIN FORCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
and ANDREW BACKOVER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If the merger of oil giants Exxon and Mobil
is approved, North Texas will be home to the world's biggest
corporation. But the region might have to accept some job cuts
along with the distinction.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mobil Corp. employs 2,300 at a production research
center in Farmers Branch and at a Dallas data center.
</P>
<P>
   But Exxon Corp., which is based in Irving's Las Colinas area,
also has a production research center. It's in Houston, the site of
Exxon's U.S. production headquarters and the designated home of the
merged company's world production and chemical operations.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives declined to speculate about where job cuts
are likely. In a joint statement issued Tuesday, Exxon and Mobil
said they expect to trim about 9,000 of their 123,000 worldwide
employees within three years. Analysts said many of those cuts are
likely to come from the office ranks, where administrative duties
would be duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts will come on top of about 30,000 job reductions at the
two companies in recent years, as fluctuating petroleum prices have
put the spotlight on cost-cutting. Crude oil prices have slipped 35
percent since January and more than 50 percent since January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon has trimmed its U.S. payroll from more than 40,000
employees in 1991 to less than 30,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a general downsizing in the industry, and this
merger might accelerate that somewhat,'' said Ray Perryman, a Waco
economist and Southern Methodist University business professor.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could cost several thousand Texas jobs, he said. But
he and others said the state's economy should withstand those
losses, in contrast with the '80s, when an oil price collapse
sparked a near-depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil used to be 25 percent of the state's gross product, and
now maybe it's 10 or 12 percent,'' Perryman said. ``We have a much
more diverse economy, and most industries do better with low oil
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   As crude oil prices have plunged this year, Texas has seen
employment in petroleum drilling and production fall 3,700, to
156,600 in October. In contrast, the state gained 8,200 of those
jobs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil both retain sizable payrolls in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil employs 6,500 people in Texas, including 900 at its
refinery in Beaumont, said Don Turk, a spokesman at Mobil's
Fairfax, Va., headquarters. Mobil has more employees here than in
any other state, Turk said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon employs 350 in Irving, 4,000 at its huge Baytown refinery
and another 8,500 at its U.S. production headquarters in Houston.
The company, which has other operations in Texas, was unable to
provide an estimate of statewide employment.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies also have significant production in Texas. Exxon
is the state's No. 2 crude oil producer and Mobil is No. 5,
according to Texas Railroad Commission figures.
</P>
<P>
   Oil production has traditionally driven an army of oilfield
service and equipment suppliers. One supplier said Tuesday that he
was worried that the Exxon-Mobil deal, and expected mergers to
come, will mean fewer customers for his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary concern is that in the process of mergers and
acquisitions in the oil sector, there will be reduced capital
spending for equipment and services,'' said Dan Lowrance, president
of SPM Flow Control in White Settlement. ``I'm hearing it from
everybody. There's a real concern out there.''
</P>
<P>
   SPM sells flow control and plunger pumps to well-service
companies that serve oil producers.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts speculated that Exxon and Mobil might
have to sell refineries in Texas, Louisiana and California, where
the future partners both have refineries. The two Texas refineries
are state-of-the-art facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The deal might also prompt the sale of some gasoline stations to
satisfy antitrust concerns. Mobil has an estimated 12 percent of
the U.S. gasoline market; Exxon has about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   John Parry, an industry analyst for John S. Herold Inc. in
Connecticut, noted, for example, that both companies have a strong
retail presence in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they had to dump half of it, it's not an issue,''
Parry said. ``We're talking about a $200 billion company.''
Divestitures shouldn't total more than several billion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
