<HEADER>
A8801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-HN     12-02 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLEMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN SPRAWL: THE OTHER CONFLICT IN THE MIDDLE EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE RUTH FLETCHER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Tucked into a handsome grove of trees on the West
Bank, in a pastoral landscape of rolling hills, the stone-hewn
World War I-era train station of Sebastiya is a wistful remnant of
an era when railroads crisscrossed a remote and undeveloped region
called Palestine and continued on to Damascus, Beirut, Cairo and
Amman.
</P>
<P>
   It was to Sebastiya that a group of Jewish settlers came in
1974, following the Yom Kippur War, to squat and demand government
permission to settle the northern West Bank. They chose Sebastiya
not only because it had been the capital of the ancient Kingdom of
Israel, but also because of its strategic value as a point at the
crossroads of routes leading from the Mediterranean coast inland to
the Samarian Hills, and from the Galilee to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The settlers campaign of the 1970s led to the creation of dozens
of settlements in the region, transforming Sebastiya into a
modern-day symbol of the Jewish movement to settle the Biblical
``Greater Land of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for the last two decades, the train station and groves of
trees have remained untouched, preserved as a park and historical
site.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was to this quiet site that another, younger
generation of settlers returned last week _ in a symbolic protest
against the Wye Plantation accord between Israel and the
Palestinians. Lugging heavy, hand-hewn rocks, the settlers began to
``renovate'' the old stone structure, saying that they wanted to
realize a long-term plan to turn it into a museum.
</P>
<P>
   There is a tremendous irony in the settlers' struggle to gain
control over this isolated train station and turn it into a museum.
It is an irony that would be lost on many politicians, but which
environmentalists might appreciate _ as well as any Jew, Christian
or Muslim who has drawn inspiration from images of the Biblical
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   While the Jewish settlement drive that began in places like
Sebastiya was founded on the principle of ``redeeming'' the ancient
and historic land of the Bible, today it is contributing to the
destruction of the very resource that the settlers claim to
cherish.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement experience was suckled on the archetypal images
of the Biblical and medieval contours of the land itself _ on the
images of ancient olive groves and shepherds' hills, and small
groves of trees drinking water from a tiny, underground spring, set
in the broader expanse of a barren, rocky field. And it is just
those features which are fast disappearing under the weight of Arab
and Jewish development _ both in pre-1967 Israel and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In this tiny region, Israel's annual population growth of 2.4
percent is the fastest in the developed world; the Arab population
of the West Bank and Gaza is growing even faster, about 3 percent
annually. By 2020, the combined area of Israel and the Palestinian
Authority will boast a population of about 12 million _ with
average population densities roughly equal to those of Los Angeles
or the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the fact that some 70 percent of Israel is virtually
uninhabitable desert, the Negev, and you wind up with some of the
highest population densities in the world in Israel's central and
northern districts. The edges of the Israeli urban megalopolis _
extending from Lebanon almost to Gaza _ are creeping steadily
inland and are today only miles away from the borders of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers have argued that Israel's small size makes it
imperative for the Jewish state to gain control of as much West
Bank land as possible as an environmental ``escape valve'' for the
crowded coastline. Yet such a view not only ignores the growth
needs of the Palestinians, it misrepresents the true development
pattern of the settlements themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The West Bank's 144 settlements average only about 1,200
residents each. Most settlements, built of one- and two-story
garden homes capped with red-tiled roofs, are the Middle Eastern
equivalent of American-style suburban or exurban growth. As such,
they represent a development pattern that guzzles the land, rather
than ``redeeming'' it, and is wholly unsustainable in a region
where land is scarce and populations are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   The settlements are too small and dispersed to be hooked to any
public transportation grid, so transportation to and from them is
largely by automobile. In the lingo of urban planners, the
settlements are massive ``trip generators'' _ since most work,
educational and shopping needs cannot be met within these small,
isolated enclaves.
</P>
<P>
   Left to grow on their own, these settlements would generate
increasing levels of traffic and pollution, and ever-increasing
demands for new roads on the West Bank's landscape of ancient olive
groves, shepherds' hills and valleys of lush but tiny,
stone-bordered fields.
</P>
<P>
   Stand on the edge of many Jewish settlements in the West Bank
highlands at night and you can see the process under way; the
lights of central Israel are increasingly close as the carpet of
continuous urban development creeps up from the Israeli coast into
the West Bank foothills. From another direction, you can see the
expanding halo of West Bank Palestinian cities such as Ramallah,
Bethlehem and Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the passionate talk from both Jews and Arabs about the
sacredness of the land, this is still an era when land is
essentially not sacred soil, but a political commodity to be
exploited, sometimes ruthlessly. Until now, Israelis have had that
dubious privilege. But Palestinians have generated their own forms
of sprawl, paying little attention to how unfettered and unplanned
growth might consume the very soil that they profess to adore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Project out the region's growth rates by only a few decades and
don't be surprised if the ancient Biblical landscape disappears
almost entirely, giving way to more and more suburbs, superstores
and shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   There will be the Middle East franchises of carpet outlets and
burger joints, some built on ``liberated'' Palestinian lands by
entrepreneurs like those who created the new Jericho Casino _ whose
squat, square profile surrounded by parking lots already looks like
a giant shopping mall rising out of the desert.
</P>
<P>
   And there will be more and more roads _ roads built to link
isolated Jewish outposts and roads built as highways to bypass
other crowded local roads, roads that are tied up in enormous
traffic jams of both Israelis and Palestinians at rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than building a museum to settlement at Sebastiya's train
station, the settlers would do well to redirect their boundless
energies, money and political clout into the rebuilding of the rail
station itself. And then they should insist that all future
development be in the form of compact, pedestrian-scale cities with
strict controls on surrounding green spaces, linked to a larger
regional development grid by an ultramodern rail system.
</P>
<P>
   As they stand today, the settlements are not only an obstacle to
the effort to draw a political ``boundary'' between Israel and the
Palestinians, they are part of the bloodletting of the land itself.
The sooner permanent political boundaries are fixed, the sooner
Israelis and Palestinians will begin to assess the limits of their
resources and think about conservation, rather than endless
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the old train station in the grove of trees called
Sebastiya is indeed destined to become a museum piece _ an
anachronistic remnant of life in the Holy Land before most of it
was buried under asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Elaine Ruth Fletcher is the Jerusalem-based correspondent for
the San Francisco Examiner.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
