<HEADLINE>
EXXON COMPLEX IN IRVING, TEXAS, CAN ABSORB MORE WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MILES MOFFEIT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It's almost as if a megamerger were in the
blueprints four years ago when Exxon built its headquarters
complex, which dominates the horizon west of Las Colinas' pink
granite towers.
</P>
<P>
   The 360,000-square-foot complex can accommodate hundreds of
additional workers who could be shifted as a result of the
Exxon-Mobil merger, according to real estate observers and local
chamber officials.
</P>
<P>
   And if they can't be squeezed into the main office, which
already houses about 300 employees, the company also has 30 acres
on which it can build nearby.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Exxon and Mobil officials said they would base their
new company's headquarters at the north Irving site, but they
declined to specify what the future holds for staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Economic development officials are betting on a sizable boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, with any merger, the headquarters end up with more
employees,'' said James Spriggs, president of the Greater
Irving-Las Colinas Chamber of Commerce. ``They have a very large
facility, with ample room to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Spriggs described the Irving site as a natural and said chamber
officials will be working closely with the oil giant to help
relocated workers find homes near the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes a lot of sense for them to be in Irving, since
Mobil has its largest refinery in Beaumont and it's close to
Exxon's major refinery,'' Spriggs said. ``We're kind of a unique
centerpiece of the world right here by D/FW Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon built its 3-story headquarters, appraised at about $40
million, after relocating from New York in the early '90s. The
sprawling facility hugs the skyline along Las Colinas Boulevard
about a mile west of the tower-packed Urban Center.
</P>
<P>
   The complex has been viewed as an office prototype by many
corporations shunning bustling urban centers for wooded suburban
settings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Exxon added 30 acres to the complex, triggering
speculation that it might relocate another division to the site,
but Exxon officials termed it a ``buffer zone,'' saying no moves
were under way.
</P>
<P>
   A small portion of the complex extends into Las Colinas' utility
district, but district officials say Exxon has not disclosed any
plans for an expansion.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
