<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEMISH-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MET'S EXHIBIT OF FLEMISH PAINTINGS IS ART IN ITSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Large, comprehensive museums like the Metropolitan
Museum contain within them holdings that could form independent
museums of their own. The richness of the Met's collection in one
crucial area of Western art is made vividly clear in ``From Van
Eyck to Bruegel: Early Netherlandish Painting in the Metropolitan
Museum of Art.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawn almost exclusively from the Met's own holdings of 15th-
and 16th-century Flemish painting, the exhibition, which continues
through Jan. 3, traces the medium's development from the invention
of oil painting, most likely by Jan van Eyck circa 1420, to its
thorough secularization under the hands of Pieter Bruegel the Elder
nearly 150 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The Met possesses the largest and most comprehensive collection
of such painting in the Western Hemisphere. Indeed, you would have
to go to Berlin or Madrid to see its better under one roof. But
until now you couldn't see all the Met's early Flemish paintings in
one place.
</P>
<P>
   For various reasons, its Flemish painting was hung in three
different areas of the Fifth Avenue building; other works were
installed at the Cloisters, the Met's re-creation of a medieval
monastery high above the Hudson River in Washington Heights.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, all the Met's major Flemish paintings,
joined by lesser works kept in storage, have been brought together.
(A few choice works, panels from the same altar piece that had been
separated, for instance, have been borrowed from other
institutions.) This is the opportunity of a lifetime for lovers of
Early Netherlandish art to see so much of the astonishing painting
that captures the way the world looks, as if by magic.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which includes more than 140 works, proceeds
chronologically and thematically. Sections on portraiture, studio
workshop practice, the influence of Italian painting and a
show-within-a-show of paintings by Gerard David (1455-1523)
punctuate its flow.
</P>
<P>
   The inclusion of paintings usually kept in storage pays off in
the section devoted to the busy Flemish workshops, where a wall of
small, devotional pictures treating Mary breast-feeding Christ
reveals in one sweep the variations possible within a strictly
codified theme.
</P>
<P>
   The show opens with a bang. Its first gallery, devoted to
religious painting, contains two of the Met's greatest paintings
from any time and place, van Eyck's Crucifixion and Last Judgment
diptych, and Robert Campin's Annunciation triptych, both dating
from circa 1430.
</P>
<P>
   Van Eyck's Crucifixion still astonishes with its microscopic
observation. The tall, narrow panel, only 22 by 8 inches, is packed
with activity organized vertically into three zones. The viewer
looks at the scene from a position that makes him look up toward
the crucifixion itself and down at the group of mourners in the
foreground. The painting is suffused with spiritual feeling. In no
other religious art are we so aware of the spiritual made flesh as
in Flemish painting.
</P>
<P>
   The bodily sacrifice of God's son that van Eyck and his
contemporaries believed saved mankind from eternal damnation
dominates the scene. The three crosses bearing Christ and the two
thieves rising above the crowd are outlined against the sky, but
our attention is riveted not by Christ's anguish but by that of the
suffering of his mother and his disciples in the foreground,
separated from the foot of the cross by a densely packed band of
individualized Roman soldiers and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Mary, wrapped in her blue robe as in a protective cocoon, and
Mary Magdalen, her long red hair flowing freely over her green
robe, her hands joined together in prayer, are, between them, the
very emblems of grief.
</P>
<P>
   Campin's Annunciation is the earliest that survives that shows
the moment when Mary is impregnated by the holy spirit in a
domestic setting, and it is painted with an eye-cleansing clarity.
Looking at these early oil paintings, you can understand why
Italian artists flipped when they first saw them, adopting the new
technique as fast as they could learn how to use it.
</P>
<P>
   This triptych, a high-priced and much-discussed object when
purchased by the Met in 1956, has offered generations of art
historians the opportunity to weigh in on the nature of symbolism
in Flemish art, and it is easy to see that each object in this
bourgeois interior, the just-extinguished candle, the open book,
the majolica vase holding a lily, the white towel hanging from the
rack, was carefully chosen by the artist _ whatever his intention.
</P>
<P>
   The show contains several other annunciations, none quite as
brilliant as this, although one, by Hans Memling, in which the
Virgin is held up by two angels, is particularly charming. Its
theme, the idea that spirit is made flesh in the body of Christ, is
one that is particularly resonant in Flemish art, so spiritual and
so worldly at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is demanding on the eye, and repeated visits are
necessary to do it justice. In a show in which religious painting
dominates, the two galleries devoted to portraiture are sure to be
popular, even though many of them were cut down from larger
compositions, often of a religious nature. The verisimilitude of
Flemish portraiture has never been surpassed, and the sitters'
wrinkles, warts and beard stubble are all lovingly detailed.
</P>
<P>
   Although even the most religious of Flemish painting abounds
with details of physical reality, a whole new world is suggested in
Bruegel's ``The Harvesters'' (1565), the masterpiece that closes
the show. One of six compositions on the theme of the seasons, this
famous painting shows peasants lunching on a brief break from
harvesting wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Absorbed in their food and in their work, they nevertheless
inhabit a world that is complete in itself. In the distance, the
landscape extends through green fields and a village and another
golden field of grain to a harbor where the hazy atmosphere
suggests the globe's curvature and a distant world to be explored.
God is present here only by implication, and if you choose not to
see him, you don't have to.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
