<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-CHEF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE CHEFS MAKE EATING AT HOME MORE CONVENIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSONVILLE, N.Y. _ Barbara Ford missed cooking. She had worked
at a restaurant in the Berkshire Mountains for almost 10 years.
Devoted customers were her source of personal satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   But she had to give up the restaurant job four years ago when
she had her second child and the family moved to Johnsonville, N.Y.
A culinary career was on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Then Ford learned about the United States Personal Chef
Association, an Albuquerque, N.M.-based organization that helps
cooking-minded men and women set up their own businesses making
meals for busy families who desire to dine at home but don't have
the time to prepare dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who earlier this year named her chef service Dinner's
Done, now has a half-dozen regular clients. She develops a one- or
two-week menu plan for each, based on their nutritional needs and
individual preferences, buys the necessary groceries and makes all
of the meals during a daylong cooking marathon in the customer's
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is more fun than being a restaurant cook. I love to
cook,'' Ford said. ``This is a challenge to get it done and hope
people enjoy it. You set your own pace and each client is
different, so you're cooking different foods off a menu you put
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford charges between $200 and $250 for a week's worth of
dinners, including the cost of the groceries. She also provides
instructions for each meal, letting the family know when it should
be removed from the freezer and how much reheating time is
required.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the service,'' said LeeLee Nielsen, an owner of Grafton
Mountain Modular Homes in nearby Valley Falls who has been using
Dinner's Done for the past six months. ``The main reason I did it
was for convenience and so everybody was home for supper instead of
going out in six different places.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put the meal in and put the timer on and when you get home
at six it's ready for you. All you have to do is make a salad.
Plus, she accommodates you. My kids don't like onions, so Barbara
omits onions. The only way we can tell she has been here making
dinners is that the kitchen is spotless, cleaner than we left it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner's Done gives Ford almost complete control over her
schedule, allowing her to be home when her two boys get home from
school. Her biggest hurdle has been expanding the client base. But
most of her customers learn about her business by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Sanchez is dealing with the same problem. The Delmar,
N.Y.-based personal chef named his business The Secret Ingredient
when he joined the USPCA in June, and he has found that
self-promotion is considerably more difficult than making two
week's worth of tasty dinners in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get the word out,'' said Sanchez, who has set up
a Website for his business (www.thesecret-ingredient.com). ``The
business is growing steadily, just not as quickly as I would
prefer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, 34, has what seems to be the ideal resume. He went
through the hotel and restaurant school at Rochester Institute of
Technology and attended the prestigious Culinary Institute of
America in Hyde Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   With his food and business acumen, Sanchez developed a
good-paying career as a district manager for a company that manages
corporate dining rooms. But he found that too much of his time was
spent on paperwork and too little of it in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sanchez discovered the USPCA, which charges a minimum
annual membership of $49 for a variety of services (start-up
information, training manual, regulatory guidelines, how to obtain
the proper income tax status, recipe library, etc.), and he decided
to go into business for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing well but I'm not making the same kind of money as I
was,'' he said. ``The thing is, I love being a chef and I didn't
always love being a district manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been this personally satisfied doing anything for a
living ever. That outweighs everything. It was my primary goal.
It's allowed things to grow in my marriage and my relationship with
my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez charges $275 for a standard two-week service for two
people, and his introductory offer includes a $50 saving.
</P>
<P>
   David MacKay, executive director of the USPCA, founded the
service in 1991. About 11 years ago, MacKay said he ``created a
concept'' to get his wife, Susan, out of the hectic restaurant
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Hey, if the yuppies are paying to have maids come
in to their house, they'll pay to have personal chefs come in,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay started the association with five members. Today, there
are conventions, training sessions, correspondence courses,
certification and a bimonthly magazine. At the present growth rate
there will be more than 5,000 personal chef services in the United
States in five years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez said personal chefs make financial sense for families
who either don't have the time or the disposition to cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people find out that my charge for a typical, two-week
service for two people ends up being quite economical compared to
eating out for two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
