A8811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKREVIEW-ANCHORS03-     12-02 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKREVIEW-ANCHORS03-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MacNeil and Lehrer publish two books simultaneously
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MacNeil and Lehrer are together again, this time on bookshelves
rather than on television. For almost 15 years, Robert MacNeil and
Jim Lehrer co-anchored PBS's hourlong evening newscast. MacNeil
left in 1996, primarily to write, and Lehrer soldiers on alone.
These two genteel journalists have published new novels
simultaneously, and while neither is going to prompt Updike or Roth
to check his heels to see who's nipping there, both are brisk,
engaging reads.
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil sets ``Breaking News'' close to the milieu he's most
familiar with: a network newscast. But whereas PBS's ``NewsHour''
is somewhat immune to ratings pressure, MacNeil's fictional
newscast is on a commercial network, an amalgam of NBC, CBS and
ABC, the better to deal in conflicts and current issues.
</P>
<P>
   And his hero, aging anchor Grant Munro, is a composite of Tom
Brokaw, Dan Rather and Peter Jennings. Munro is a hold-out for
old-fashioned news standards, battling day to day on a win-some,
lose-some basis against ratings-obsessed producers and
bottom-line-obsessed corporate chieftains. Munro is smart enough to
see where his business is going (toward the predatory Ann Murrow, a
younger Diane Sawyer-Barbara Walters-Connie Chung knock-off), and
vain enough to wonder whether a facelift will solve all his
problems.
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil's best creation is Hollygo Lightly, the ``first
electronic black drag queen gossip columnist,'' whose Internet site
dishes deliciously on the TV news business. If you can't imagine an
unholy cross between Matt Drudge and the Lady Chablis from
``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' MacNeil can, and
Hollygo makes ``Breaking News'' feel delightfully in the know.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer's ``Purple Dots'' is a lightweight espionage thriller;
but lightweight in the same positive sense as William F. Buckley's
Blackford Oakes books. The title refers to secret marks on license
plates used by CIA agents, and has nothing to do with the main
plot, about dealings and double-dealings over the confirmation of a
nominee to head the CIA.
</P>
<P>
   Lehrer's hero is Charles Henderson, a retired spook who runs a
bed-and-breakfast inn in West Virginia and who digs out his old
secret decoder ring to help his friend, the nominee. There's never
any sense that the fate of the free world depends on what happens,
but Lehrer makes us like Hamilton enough that we care whether or
not he succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking News. By Robert MacNeil. Doubleday. $24.95. 371 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Purple Dots. By Jim Lehrer. Random House. $23.95. 262 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Brisk prose from two old news pros.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer covers television for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
