<SLUG> BC-BORDER-BRIDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRIDGE PROMISES LESS GRIDLOCK FOR BORDER COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Locals call it the ``fourth bridge.''
Construction bidders call it the Laredo Northwest International
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what it is called, the $101 million span promises to
relieve some of the gridlock created by the booming cross-border
commerce that has turned this Texas city into a major commercial
port.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nation's fastest growing cities, Laredo has become a
gateway for truck traffic hauling goods north and south _ a result
of the vast common market created by Canada, Mexico and the United
States under the North American Free Trade Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Construction on the bridge that spans the Rio Grande began
earlier this year. It is expected to open in March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It will be used for commercial truck traffic only, setting aside
the two oldest bridges connecting downtown Laredo to downtown Nuevo
Laredo, Mexico, for passenger traffic.
</P>
<P>
   And a connecting road will have areas for up to 300 trucks to
queue while waiting border checks, helping avoid the long lines
that form every afternoon on Interstate 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a lot better,'' said Laredo Transportation
Association President Tom Wade. ``It means no more trucks (backing
up) on Interstate 35, just local delivery. It will be a big break
for the Laredo driving public.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of a new bridge probably will speed up northbound
freight to U.S. and Canadian destinations. But it might not make
southbound freight arrive earlier in Mexico because of red-tape
that snarls traffic at the checkpoint south of Nuevo Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of improvement is needed there, too, to speed up the
trucks, to be as fast as the new bridge,'' said Alejandro Pardo,
sales manager of Dicex International Inc., a Monterrey,
Mexico-based customs broker.
</P>
<P>
   The new bridge will be positioned between two older downtown
bridges and the relatively new Solidarity Bridge that was dedicated
in 1991. The Solidarity Bridge is about 20 miles upriver from
downtown Laredo and was spearheaded by the industrial state of
Nuevo Leon.
</P>
<P>
   But the Solidarity Bridge failed to reduce the high truck demand
for one of the older bridges because connecting roads to the main
highways in Texas and Mexico have not been completed. Construction
began recently on a 20-mile toll road from the Solidarity to I-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth bridge is the one we've really wanted all along,''
said Florencio Pena III, the city manager of Laredo, a city of
188,000 people. ``It will take care of our urban problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico will pay up to $30 million for the new bridge. The U.S.
share will be paid by the Texas Department of Transportation, the
city of Laredo and bridge revenues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
