A8824 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARTFORD-PATRIOTS-ART     12-02 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTFORD-PATRIOTS-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PATRIOTS GIVE HARTFORD A LIFT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ It is Worcester on a very good day _ a cluster
of glass-and-chrome towers ringed by sturdy suburbs and red-brick
neighborhoods where hope has taken tenacious root.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's capital is no Boston. Next to New York, it's a
hamlet. It's the milepost in between, and suddenly, it no longer
seems to care.
</P>
<P>
   Hartford has heard your gray-flannel jokes about its
buttoned-down obsession with actuarial tables and its too-earnest
interest in the difference between term and whole life insurance
policies.
</P>
<P>
   And these days _ these Patriots-are-coming giddy days _ Hartford
finally has the self-assurance to chuckle right along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have a chance to redefine ourselves,'' Republican
Governor John Rowland said, announcing the tentative deal to
redirect New England's professional football franchise from Route 1
in Foxborough to the nexus of Interstates 84 and 91 here.
</P>
<P>
   The TV cameras caught predictable euphoria of beer-guzzling fans
in the downtown sports barrooms. But in the dark-paneled
boardrooms, the linen-cloth dining rooms, and the just-folks living
rooms where this city really lives and breathes, the reaction was
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' this city seems to be saying to itself, nodding
confidently. ``Finally, Hartford is ready for this.''
</P>
<P>
   It's got shock-jock Howard Stern on the radio, over-caffeinated
anchors on its morning TV broadcasts, a stately City Hall worthy of
a Hollywood back lot, and enough buses on Main Street to make
Greyhound proud.
</P>
<P>
   It's got its own symphony orchestra, a stubby skyline, a
struggling ballet company, a world-class art museum,
over-in-a-flash rush hours, and a public school system desperately
in need of rescue.
</P>
<P>
   New England's sixth-largest city (after Boston, Worcester,
Providence, Springfield, and Bridgeport, Conn.) is an
18-square-mile postage stamp that sits in one of the wealthiest
regions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always looked out windows like this and knew that this
is really a small town,'' said Lewis B. Rome, a former state
senator and gubernatorial candidate and now a downtown mover and
shaker, from his office overlooking the proposed downtown stadium
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're so dramatically located between Boston and New York,
that we should be one of the most successful little towns in the
country. We're sleepy, yes. But we're sophisticated, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that combination that attracts people like Chuck DeLeo, 63,
a Framingham, Mass. native who has no intention of moving away from
a place where the state's governor was once asked to surrender his
seat at a restaurant because it belonged to a regular with dibs on
it for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford isn't as complicated as Boston, but it still has that
cosmopolitan flair,'' said DeLeo, a retired teacher and coach who
moved to Hartford 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small enough city that you know almost everybody. In a
big city like Boston you can be lonely. It's hard being lonely in
Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Smith, 64, likes those rhythms, too.
</P>
<P>
   A genial retiree with a pencil-thin mustache and just a trace of
the silky accent of his native North Carolina, Smith headed north
after World War II in search of jobs, stopping briefly in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford was more my speed,'' Smith said over an
egg-and-homefries breakfast at Mo's Midtown, a tiny West End diner.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, Smith's Hartford wore overalls, not pin-striped
suits. It was a place where you could get a factory job. And if you
didn't like it, you could choose another.
</P>
<P>
   Smith worked at the old Hartford Sugar Co. on Windsor Street as
a supply clerk before leaving for a similar job at the Royal
Typewriter Co. The Cold War was in its deepest frost and
Connecticut, maker of Revolutionary War cannons and Civil War
gunpowder, was humming along again on Pentagon dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was booming in those days,'' said Smith, who
ultimately decided to go into business for himself, running a
service station and later a package store, and raised six children
who all went to Hartford's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't having the problems with the schools then that
they're having now,'' Smith said, noting Hartford Public High
School's recent threatened loss of its accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's children include a bank supervisor, a fitness
instructor, a school librarian, and a state employee. ``I lost one
to the streets,'' he said of a son serving a prison term in
Enfield. ``He wound up with a drug problem, but he's doing fine now
and I'm proud of the progress he's making.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith is proud of his city, too. He's a church deacon and a
member of the men's choir who sings Hartford's praises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hartford is one of the best cities in the country,''
he said. ``The streets are pretty safe. All big cities have
problems and we have our share, but I think drug use is on the
decline.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith holds no illusions that an NFL franchise can remake the
city. ``For the people in the neighborhoods, their box seat is
going to be where it is right now: in front of the TV set. We have
some of the richest people in the state and some of the poorest
people in the state.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
