A8826 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGER-INDEPENDENTS-T     12-02 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-INDEPENDENTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENTS TO PICK UP PIECES BIG OIL LEAVES BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Exxon-Mobil deal is all about Big Oil,
and that makes it a big deal in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But Little Oil is standing by to pick up the leftovers, and
that, too, is a big deal in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the huge, integrated multinationals such as Exxon
and Mobil have been doing a long, slow retreat from Texas and the
U.S. midcontinent over the past two decades in favor of new plays
in the former Soviet Union, China and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   They have been replaced, at least in some fields, by small
independents. And those independents lucky enough to have some
spare cash may find some opportunities from the leavings of Exxon
and Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon and Mobil aren't merging because they can get synergies
in the Permian Basin of Texas,'' said Jon Brumley, a veteran Fort
Worth-based independent oilman. ``They're after new opportunities
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will create opportunities for those who are looking for
assets in Texas,'' added Brumley, whose Encore Acquisition
Partners, formed this year, is looking for such properties.
</P>
<P>
   In retreating, Big Oil has sharply cut its share of Texas
production.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, according to Texas Railroad Commission figures, about 1
billion barrels of oil were produced in Texas. Of that, Exxon
accounted for 223.6 million barrels and Mobil, 48.6 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996, Texas' production had dropped to 495.5 million barrels.
Exxon's share was only 29.2 million barrels, while Mobil produced
18.9 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think how big this merger would have been under the numbers of
20 years ago,'' said David Garlick of the Texas Independent Royalty
Owners Association, the trade group of Texas' independent energy
operators.
</P>
<P>
   Low crude oil and natural gas prices have accelerated the trend
of property sales in Texas in 1998, with big auctions held in
Houston, Midland and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   But those low crude prices have cut into the cash flow of energy
producers, which in turn reduces the ability of independents who
can't afford to be patient to take advantage of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   John Pinkerton, chairman of Fort Worth-based Range Resources,
said the opportunities Big Oil leaves behind ``may not mean much to
operators who can't generate profits and favorable cash flow when
oil is selling effectively for $10 a barrel and natural gas prices
have dropped below $2 per thousand cubic feet.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pinkerton and Brumley both said that low oil and gas prices
are here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger tells me that prices are going to stay low for a
while, as best anyone can tell,'' Brumley said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Elyea of Wichita Falls, president of the North Texas Oil &AMP;
Gas Association, noted that so-called ``stripper wells,'' those
producing 15 barrels of oil or less per day, are likely to be
capped during the next year because they are no longer profitable.
Once capped, he said, those wells are unlikely to be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. domestic oil production stood at 8.6 million barrels per
day in 1986, and now is 6.2 million barrels,'' Elyea said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another big problem is that the industry has lost a lot of
talent,'' Elyea added. ``There are thousands of engineers,
geologists and other well-trained people who have simply drifted
away from the energy industry. We'll never get them back.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
