<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8828 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGER-LEADERS-TEX     12-02 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-LEADERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LEADERS WILL MOLD EXXON MOBIL'S CULTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN+ c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On paper, they seem so similar. In the flesh, they seem very
different.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Raymond and Lucio Noto, the chief executives of Exxon and
Mobil, respectively, joined their companies in the early 1960s
within a year of each other.
</P>
<P>
   They spent time working abroad and then, after displaying
financial skills, climbed through the ranks at home.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 30 years after joining their organizations, each was
named chairman and chief executive _ again, within 12 months of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with both at age 60 and with the oil industry in the throes
of extensive consolidation, the paths of Raymond and Noto have
converged, with the agreement to combine their companies in the
biggest merger in history.
</P>
<P>
   As with most mergers, there are concerns over how the two
corporate cultures will mesh. And the two executives will set the
tone.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, a native of South Dakota, has been described as a
bookish, stern headmaster who disdains publicity and has built a
company known for its financial discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Noto, a Brooklyn native, is more talkative and seems to enjoy
bantering with reporters. His company is considered more
freewheeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their behavior is going to be the example for every Exxon and
Mobil employee in the world,'' said Allen Mesch, director of the
Maguire Oil &AMP; Gas Institute at Southern Methodist University in
Dallas. ``They may not go on long vacations together, but they
better demonstrate more than professional etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're essentially engaged. And engagements can break up over
some pretty small things.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the prospect of their combination prompted The Wall
Street Journal to say this week that it would be like mixing oil
and water. And the mergers-and-acquisitions landscape is littered
with corporate-suite casualties. Some huge deals were even scrapped
because top executives clashed over how to share power.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, BankAmerica President David Coulter resigned amid
reports of conflicts with Hugh McColl, whose NationsBank led the
merger of the financial insitutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a great majority of cases, the No. 2 guy leaves within a
year,'' said Chuck Becker, associate professor of finance at Texas
Christian University in Fort Worth. ``Sometimes people never find a
way to march to the same drummer. And that can extend down through
all the ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Noto said that won't be an issue at Exxon Mobil because the
leadership is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work for Lee,'' Noto said Tuesday at a news
conference in New York. ``I've spent 36 years with Mobil, and
believe it or not, for 32 of those years I actually worked for
people, as opposed to shareholders. And I think I can adapt myself
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   They have agreed to share power in a way that seems
proportionate to the deal, which calls for Exxon shareholders to
retain a 70 percent stake in the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond will be chairman, CEO and president. Noto will be vice
chairman of a 19-member board that will include six Mobil
directors.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond and Noto have both been lauded for their willingness to
slash costs and boost performance. In the '90s, they have both cut
thousands of jobs and jettisoned poor-performing properties.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, who holds a doctorate in chemical engineering from the
University of Minnesota, pushed for stock buybacks when many other
oil companies were investing in risky projects that later failed.
</P>
<P>
   He has been praised for producing the best returns in the energy
business, and he has steadily reduced Exxon's costs, pushing
profits and stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond made clear yesterday that the combined company will
impose the same tough financial discipline on the new operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exxon has set the pace'' for return on capital, Raymond said,
and the company will have ``a relentless commitment to being the
most efficient competitor in each business segment.''
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks yesterday, Raymond was usually short and to the
point, with little flourish. Noto, by contrast, came across as more
conversational.
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked for more details about plans to reduce the
work force and sell properties, Raymond said it was premature to
speculate on specifics, adding that legal advisers had told him not
to make any comments until Exxon met with regulators.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston reporter followed up by asking why Exxon was not
offering its own proposal to the Federal Trade Commission, rather
than waiting on the government reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be candid about it,'' Raymond said, ``I'm not interested in
your views on how we should deal with the FTC.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, Raymond was asked about his profit
projections and, after challenging the reporter's assumption about
a company chart, he took another dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very confident about predicting oil prices,'' Raymond
said, ``which is why I like to come to these meetings. So you can
tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Noto, who has a master's in business administration from Cornell
University, lightened the mood when he was asked about working with
Raymond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lee and I have a good equation, notwithstanding all
the stuff that's been written about us,'' Noto said. ``We'll do a
bear act if you'll give us a moment.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
