<SLUG> BC-TEST-TEX </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   This is a test from the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1316EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8831 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARTFORD-PATRIOTS-2ND     12-02 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTFORD-PATRIOTS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 HARTFORD, Conn.: ... in the state.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``They say their first game will be in the fall of 2001. They're
giving us plenty of time,'' he said, breaking into a sly smile. ``I
should be able to save up money for a ticket by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes people have to remind Ellen Nurse that the city of
Hartford issues her paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus system stinks. The police department is terrible. The
school system stinks,'' said Nurse, 51, her hand gestures sending
cigarette smoke in wild patterns over a soup-and-sandwich lunch at
a downtown tavern.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse also makes it clear that Hartford is like her family. If
you're a member, you can criticize it. If you're not, it's best
that you keep your opinions to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Hartford has its own unique personality,'' said Nurse,
an information services city employee. ``This is a Yankee city.
People say it takes a long time to fit into a clique here. When you
walk down the streets in Hartford, people may say hi to you, or
they may not. They've got to check you out first.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurse has been parading the streets of this city all her life.
She's one of the city's seven constables and, because she owns no
car, serves her official papers by riding the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the city's not but 18 square miles,'' she explained.
</P>
<P>
   And she knows every block. Nurse knew Hartford before the
downtown department stores abandoned Main Street for the tony
shopping malls of the city's swankier suburbs. She recalls a jumble
of downtown movie theaters whose prerequisite for entry was
attendance that week at Sunday school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of fun and we looked out after each other in
those days,'' said Nurse. ``And we got a good education, too. Now,
we have some good teachers, but we've got far too many who don't
give a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurse said Hartford needs to move beyond a hurtful political
mentality in which the city is balkanized by race or by the
ethnicities of its neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem here is that we still too often talk North End
versus South End, black and white and Hispanic,'' she said. ``We
need to put that in our past. I tell people there's nothing wrong
with this city that we can't fix. ... The thing that kills Hartford
is that nobody lives downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, said Nurse, is something that the Patriots won't
affect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are going to benefit are the people on the
outskirts of Hartford,'' said Nurse. ``People in my neighborhood
are not going to have access to tickets. You cannot come out and
enjoy a game if you don't have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Nurse's no-nonsense criticism of her hometown softens when she's
asked how she would describe the place to a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford? This is a good city. Actually, a small New England
village is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   If all of the cliched adjectives about this city _ staid,
conservative, dull, pedestrian _ were accurate, Mike Peters could
never say this: ``How ya doin'. I'm the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters, or Mayor Mike, as he is universally known, is not your
father's chief executive. A former career firefighter whose own
family mocked him when he announced in 1993 that he was running for
mayor, Peters was reelected to a third term last year with 90
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A five-hour tour of his town last week, in which hizzoner drove
a reporter through neighborhood after neighborhood and held court
over beer and sausages, was equal parts civic promotion, hometown
history lesson, and Vegas lounge act.
</P>
<P>
   Judging Hartford by its shiny central-city office buildings
would be like judging Boston by the Hancock tower. And Peters, a
Marlboro-smoking, Budweiser-drinking man, doesn't want anyone to
take that one-dimensional measure of his city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come for a ride,'' Peters said, throwing his blue Buick into
drive, ``and I'll show you a city on the move.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters never went to college, says he couldn't run for high
office because he did inhale, and laces his language with
profanities that roll off his tongue like prepositions.
</P>
<P>
   But in rapid-fire delivery, the man gets his message across. The
city's crime rate is down 35 percent in the past five years. The
vacancy rate in offices downtown _ once at 27 percent _ now hovers
around 10 percent. The streets are clean. The parks are groomed.
Graffiti doesn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   As he drives (``If I had a driver, then two of us would know
where I was''), cops, bus drivers, house painters, and teenagers
shout to him as if he were a folk hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel better about this city than they did before,'' he
said, cruising through the Blue Hill sections of North Hartford.
``We've lowered taxes four years in a row. We've got people moving
back to the city. We've done more studies than any other city and
now we're just saying, `(Expletive) it. Let's just do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even his critics don't deny that Peters is in love with his
hometown. He lives six blocks from where he grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father worked for the state, and when he died, he left me a
pair of pants,'' he said. ``But they didn't fit and the wallet was
missing.''
</P>
<P>
   The city is tearing down Dickensian housing projects, working to
redevelop dilapidated housing and boarded-up three-deckers, and
reclaiming its waterfront on the Connecticut River.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to meet the guy who decided to build this highway right
next to the river so I can punch him right in the head,'' Peters
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been out there every day for the past five years, telling
people that Hartford is a great city with a lot of promise,'' he
said. ``Finally, it's paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, census figures showed that Hartford was the
nation's fastest-diminishing city, but officials think they have
stanched the decline. The population, at 139,739 in 1990, is
projected to be 131,640 by 2000 and 145,580 by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   As Puerto Ricans and West Indians retrace the steps of their
Irish, Italian, and Eastern European immigrant predecessors,
Hartford appears perfectly at ease with its municipal station in
life. If the sidewalks roll up at 5 p.m., so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a transplant from New York, and there's no hustle and
bustle here like there is there,'' said Stafford Chisholm, 34, an
insurance account executive. ``When I used to visit my old friends
in New York, they used to tease me about going back to the `woods'
in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as I get older, I appreciate that more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas D. Ritter, retiring this year after serving the longest
tenure as speaker of the Connecticut Legislature, said the Patriots
deal is more important to him for what it symbolizes than for the
Sunday afternoon excitement it may mean.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a real problem here,'' he said. ``The end of the Cold
War really hit us hard. We were having trouble maintaining our
young people. What I care more about is the people of Hartford
feeling that the city is on the way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our 6- and 7-year-olds are excited as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Those intangibles are not unimportant for a city finally
emerging from the recession, the worst economic storm since the
Depression, which raged with particular fury here.
</P>
<P>
   So last Monday night, as Drew Bledsoe, fractured finger and all,
led the Patriots to a last-minute come-from-behind victory over
Miami, beer-soaked fans packed a sports bar in famously sleepy
downtown Hartford. And they cheered as if they'd won the Super
Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
