<HEADER>
A8835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-02 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK STATE IS STARVING SCHOOLS TO BUILD PRISONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vincent Schiraldi has long believed that America has sacrificed
public education for prisons. But even he, the executive director
of the Justice Policy Institute, a Washington, think tank, was not
prepared for the newest evidence.
</P>
<P>
   His institute and the Correctional Association of New York has
reeleased a study that finds that over the last decade, New York
State has made nearly a dollar-for-dollar tradeoff in the building
of prisons and the starving of public universities. Since 1988,
state funding for colleges has plummeted by $615 million. Spending
for prisons has gone up by $761 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dollar-for-dollar aspect really brings this whole debate
into a new light,'' Schiraldi said of the study, funded by the
Rockefeller Foundation and released Tuesday (12/1). ``The debate
used to be locking them up vs. not locking them up. These new data
bring into question, particularly for blue-collar, working-class
families, why the resources that could go to public colleges _
resources that could either provide for lower tuitions or higher
enrollments _ are instead going to lock people up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now open up the debate to whether the skyrocketing
costs of college are due to some significant degree to paying for
prisons instead.''
</P>
<P>
   In percentages, college spending declined over the last decade
in New York State by 29 percent as prison spending shot up 76
percent. In 1988, New York spent twice as much on universities than
on prisons. By 1996, annual spending for incarceration, $1.6
billion, surpassed the $1.3 billion in the budget for colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The study is more proof that at the same moment that affirmative
action for educated African-Americans and Latinos is under
withering attack, this society is throwing poorly educated people
of color into the waste bin. The explosion of prisons has not been
fueled by the need to lock up violent marauders. Last year,
two-thirds of new prisoners were nonviolent offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies, including a major one last year by the Rand
Corp., have said clearly that drug treatment is a far more
effective deterrent to drug abuse and crime than mandatory minimum
sentences. Up to now, few politicians have listened. In New York,
harsh mandatory sentences have pushed the cost of keeping
nonviolent drug offenders locked up to $680 million a year, a
haunting contrast to the $615 million drop since 1988 in college
spending.
</P>
<P>
   Even though white people make up about 75 percent of New York
State's population and consume about that percentage of all illegal
drugs, only 5 percent of New Yorkers doing time for drug offenses
are white. Even though African-Americans and Latinos are about 25
percent of the state's population, they are 95 percent of the
prisoners locked up for drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Worse is that the number of African-Americans and Latinos behind
bars in upstate New York prisons now surpasses the number in the
upstate SUNY system. There are 34,809 African-Americans in upstate
jails, compared with 27,925 in upstate SUNY schools. There are
22,421 Latino prisoners compared with 17,845 SUNY students. In
contrast, there are 274,504 white students in SUNY colleges and
only 10,715 in upstate prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had one in three white men between the ages of 20-29 who
have a criminal record, the president would declare a state of
emergency,'' Schiraldi said. ``I don't want to be inflammatory, but
the only reason this level of incarceration is permitted in our
country is because it is African-Americans and Latinos. If people
are serious in this country about racial equity, prisons have to be
at the crux of any discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, should be the cost of college. The total cost for
someone who goes away to a SUNY school has risen steeply since
1988, from $6,303 to $11,478. The annual cost has risen from around
20 percent of the national median family income for Latinos and 24
percent of the family income for African-Americans to 42 percent
for both groups.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty of rising costs has hit them much harder than white
families. White families have seen the costs rise from 13.5 percent
of their income to 25 percent. Even so, Schiraldi hopes that white
families might come around to seeing that their pocket is also
being picked by the prison boom. Everyone should question a system
where it costs $30,000 a year to keep one person in prison, money
that could send nearly three students away to SUNY or nearly nine
students who live at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the politicians' pandering to people's worst
emotions about crime and fear-mongering has won the day,''
Schiraldi said. ``Because times are good now, some people are
trying to figure out how to make college more affordable, and
that's good. But unless something changes, when times go bad again,
universities will feel the blows. The prisons will continue to
flourish.''
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
