<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BO     12-02 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABERCROMBIE'S: APPALLING TO MOMS, APPEALING TO TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Where's the absolutely hottest spot to buy clothes for high
school these days?
</P>
<P>
   A. The Gap.
</P>
<P>
   B. J. Crew.
</P>
<P>
   C. Banana Republic.
</P>
<P>
   D. Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't guess Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, you must be an
out-of-touch adult or a clueless freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Every junior and senior knows Abercrombie is the place to shop.
And hang out after school. ``It's trendy,'' says Florina Gordon,
16, a junior at Boston Latin School. ``I come every week.''
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The music is cutting-edge and so loud that it
drives out most adults. The clothes are cool though not
cutting-edge. And the catalog is sexy _ so racy in fact that some
parents in Brookline, Mass. are now considering protesting weekly
in front of local stores. ``The message is `Sex is cool,'''
complains Dori Stern, a parent and teacher who protested in front
of the Atrium Mall on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt Abercrombie's image among high schoolers that
college students like Kelly Fernandes of Northeastern University
are flocking to the store as well. ``I'm applying for a job here
because I want the discount,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, unlike at the Gap, there are no young kids spilling
over from adjacent stores like Gap Kids and Baby Gap _ destroying
all sense of coolness. ``My little brother is still into the Gap.
It's his favorite store,'' sighs Karen McCarthy, 18, a senior at
South Boston High School, of her 14-year-old sibling. ``I think
Abercrombie is more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Just where did this Abercrombie craze come from? It's weird. A
lot of the styles are so classically casual, they probably predate
your grandfather: rustic plaid cotton shirts; simple baseball caps;
corduroy coats; sweaters with horizontal stripes; and reversible
gym shirts (yellow on one side, blue on the other, for example).
</P>
<P>
   And ironically, this is a company that's known to old-timers for
selling fishing rods and guns, of all things. Abercrombie was
founded in 1892 as a sporting goods and expedition-equipment store.
Over the years, it's dressed people like Ernest Hemingway and
Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   But that's really all ancient history now. The modern-day
Abercrombie put itself on the map six years ago when it hired chief
executive Michael Jeffries. Jeffries's strategy was simple: Target
college kids by promoting the American college experience.
</P>
<P>
   Following the path of designers like Calvin Klein and Donna
Karan, Abercrombie's ads are filled with sexy, edgy images of
muscular young men with chests bared, arms bulging, and boxer
shorts showing. As in Tommy Hilfiger's and Ralph Lauren's ads,
Abercrombie's models are athletic and privileged-looking, often
pictured outdoors on ski lifts or boating, camping, skinny-dipping,
and playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie hired well-known fashion photographer Bruce Weber to
shoot its campaign. And the results are a marketer's dream: Girls
are now hanging Abercrombie shopping bags on their walls.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie's network of stores, which has grown from 40
nationwide in 1992 to 177, routinely hires staffers from local
college campuses. Dressed head to toe in merchandise, these clerks
are virtually indistinguishable from shoppers _ a good selling
point for impressionable teens.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Abercrombie made what was probably its most
remarkable move: It created a ``magalogue,'' or magazine/catalog,
called the A&AMP;F Quarterly. Unlike most catalogs, this one is
actually entertaining. Written in part by college students, the
Christmas issue includes (in addition to pages of clothing spreads)
a holiday film guide with an A list (``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Enemy
of the State'') and an F list (``Star Trek: Insurrection'' and ``I
Still Know What You Did Last Summer'').
</P>
<P>
   There's also a profile of author Bret Easton Ellis
(``Glamorama'' and ``American Psycho''); a book list; a CD list;
lists of recommended outdoors equipment, snow resorts, trendy
technology (like the flat TV), and volunteer opportunities. There
are also New Year's resolutions: Get up before noon, call Mom, read
a book with no pictures, promise not to make anyone MADD, and get
off the couch.
</P>
<P>
   Punchy and clever, the book, from a marketing standpoint, makes
Abercrombie stand way out from the pack. ``To be able to look at a
magalogue and have it tell you what to pack for school, where you
should go to be in the know. ... It's state of the art,'' says Tom
Julian, a trend analyst for New York ad agency Fallon McElligott.
``The fact that it's written (in part) by college students means
it's definitely the audience talking to the audience.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Abercrombie says it has a paid circulation of 200,000
for the quarterly, the retailer, based in Reynoldsburg, Ohio, has
learned that trying to be too cool can backfire sometimes. Consider
these controversial elements of the latest issue: party game
descriptions like Strip Yahtzee, Dirty Scrabble, and Naked Twister
(``Right hand red was never this much fun'') and recipes for
post-party pick-me-ups like Irish coffee (``Add a good slug of
Irish whiskey ... to freshly brewed, strong black coffee.'').
</P>
<P>
   There is a picture of a naked young man in bed with four
adolescent girls. All of them have their mouths open, as if they
were caught in the act, and two of the girls are holding a pair of
men's boxer shorts. There's also a shot of a young couple lying on
the grass. The young man is naked, with his bottom exposed. The
girl has on a skimpy dress. And a third photo _ albeit out of focus
_ shows three couples sleeping in the same bed. At least one of the
young men is naked.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very calculated marketing,'' says Frances Avrin, a and
lawyer who attended Saturday's protest. ``Whatever they can do to
sell, they're going to do it. ... I feel it crosses the line.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Abercrombie has enraged parents. In
July _ shortly after it was spun off from the Limited Inc. to
become an independent company _ Abercrombie recalled its
Back-to-School '98 issue. Mothers Against Drunk Driving was
protesting a two-page article called ``Drinking 101,'' which
included drinking games and recipes for mixed drinks like ``brain
hemorrhages'' that the quarterly suggested students substitute for
the standard beer binge.
</P>
<P>
   In postcards sent to its magalogue readers, the company said
that ``under no circumstances does Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch support
underage or binge drinking. Although it was not meant in a serious
vein, we made a mistake in describing a `drinking game' that could
be interpreted as encouraging binge drinking.''
</P>
<P>
   All the parental protesting in the world may not hurt
Abercrombie's popularity with high school kids, but the retailer
may still shoot itself in the foot. This summer, Abercrombie opened
its first test store designed exclusively for 7- to 14-year-olds,
called ``abercrombie.'' To date, there are 11 such stores in the
United States (including one in Fanueil Hall), and in February, the
company will decide whether to expand.
</P>
<P>
   While little kids may love dressing like their older siblings,
it's unlikely the feeling will be mutual. For students like
McCarthy, the idea is a turnoff. ``It wouldn't have that preppy
look anymore,'' she says. While McCarthy concedes that little kids
would probably look cute in the gear, she wants no part of
Abercrombie if it becomes a middle-school trend. She says, ``I'd
look around for something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
