u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-02 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS FROM MANY LANDS TO SEEK COMMON GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 2,000 years, Christians have struggled to fulfill Jesus's
prayer that all people be united in one church.
</P>
<P>
   From the very beginning, Christianity has been marked _ many
would say marred _ by divisions and feuds.
</P>
<P>
   Schisms, from the break between Orthodox Christianity and the
Roman Catholic Church to the Protestant Reformation, have been the
hallmark of relations among Christians for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, in a historic conclave in Amsterdam, Christian
leaders banded together to try to chart a new course for
Christianity _ one emphasizing the qualities that unite, rather
than separate, followers of the world's largest religion.
</P>
<P>
   So was born the World Council of Churches, an ambitious
ecumenical organization that will celebrate its 50th anniversary,
beginning Thursday (12/3), with a general assembly expected to draw
thousands of Christians to Harare, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   There is much to cheer about for an organization created in the
aftermath of World War II amid a strong desire to find ways to heal
the wounds of war.
</P>
<P>
   With 500 million Christians represented through 332 churches,
denominations and fellowships in 120 countries, the World Council
of Churches has helped foment better relations and better
understanding on every continent.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Massachusetts, the ability of different Christian
denominations to work together on social, religious, economic, and
other issues is largely due to the seeds planted by the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be the only place where concerns about the life of the
Christian church can be addressed in a broad and very diverse
arena,'' said the Rev. Richard Signore, rector of St. Peter's
Episcopal Church in Buzzards Bay, who will attend the meeting in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   One tangible byproduct of the ecumenical movement spurred by the
World Council of Churches is the level of cooperation among
Christian churches in the delivery of humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time in the early part of this century, according to
the Rev. Diane C. Kessler, executive director of the Massachusetts
Council of Churches, when Christian missionary groups would compete
over who would provide relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (World Council of Churches) didn't exist, we would have
to invent it,'' said Kessler, who has been chosen editor of the
English version of the final general assembly report.
</P>
<P>
   But the World Council of Churches faces several significant
problems that strike at the core of its foundation. One prominent
missing member is the Roman Catholic Church, home to 1 billion
Catholics around the world. The church is not likely to formally
join the council anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   The council also faces the prospect of losing its single biggest
member _ the 80 million-member Russian Orthodox Church.
</P>
<P>
   The church is sending just three representatives and is
contending with an uprising among conservatives who denounce the
world council for its discussions of feminist theology and
homosexual clergy. Conservative leaders say associating with the
council would besmirch the Russian Orthodox Church's image.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox leaders also are smarting over efforts by some
evangelical Christian groups to rush into the former Soviet
republics after the collapse of communism to win converts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, accusations that the council is tilting to the left
have been leveled by conservative and evangelical Christians in
other denominations, particularly in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative movements within several North American Protestant
mainline denominations, for example, are sending a delegation to
Zimbabwe to challenge what they say is the council's drift away
from biblical authority.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from concerns about the council's direction on gays and
women, conservatives are alarmed that some within the council want
to expand dialogue to include non-Christian religions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that the council could be signing its own
death warrant because of its current direction,'' said Janice Shaw
Crouse, director of the Ecumenical Coalition on Women and Society,
a conservative Christian group. ``The council is moving in a
direction contrary to Scripture.''
</P>
<P>
   The open and vocal disagreements among Christians promise to
make for lively discussions in Harare.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of being seen as a reason to abandon the ecumenical
movement, Kessler, of the Massachusetts Council of Churches, said
the disputes underscore the importance of the council's work _ no
matter how difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marker moment in the life of the church,'' she said.
``We still have a lot of work ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   (AT)5Religion Notes
</P>
<P>
   (AT)7 _ Bishop Donald Trautman, the conservative leader of the
Roman Catholic Diocese of Erie, Pa., has drawn the proverbial line
in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   He recently informed politicians who endorse abortion rights
that they are no longer welcome to speak at church-owned
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Governor Tom Ridge, a Catholic who supports
abortion rights even though he personally opposes abortion, said he
has no problem adhering to Trautman's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Trautman's controversial decision follows the National
Conference of Catholic Bishops' adoption of a new, stricter policy
statement on abortion and the role of public officials.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference eight days ago, Trautman defended his
position by quoting from the Bishops' policy statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Catholics who are privileged to serve in public leadership
positions have an obligation to place their faith at the heart of
their public service, particularly on issues regarding the sanctity
and dignity of human life,'' the statement reads.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge told reporters, ``I intend on honoring my bishop's
instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The leader of the United Church of Christ has reaffirmed the
denomination's support for gay rights in a pastoral letter to all
congregations in the 1.4 million-member church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign against homosexuals by many conservative
politicians and religious leaders this summer convinced me that
another Christian voice needed to be heard,'' said the Rev. Paul H.
Sherry in a letter that he asked be read from the pulpits of the
more than 6,000 UCC churches.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry's letter also was prompted by the murder of Matthew
Shepard, the gay college student who was fatally beaten in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be it slavery, women's rights, or human rights, every age
demands that Christians look at Scripture with `new eyes,''' Sherry
wrote. ``All this has helped us discover that our church's concern
for the rights and dignity of gay, lesbian and bisexual people is
not a break from our past, or a departure from Scripture, but is
informed by our moments of greatest fidelity to the prophetic voice
of the Bible and the gospel's embrace of those who, with Christ,
have been despised.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
