u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-02 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE'S PRIMARY ADVANTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coordinated effort by California and eight other Western
states (a.k.a. the Thundering Herd) to move their presidential
primaries closer to New Hampshire's February-of-2000 kickoff may be
one of those carefully plotted political maneuvers that goes ``Pow!
Right in the kisser!'' to the plotters.
</P>
<P>
   The megastate and its followers, tired of hearing how much
influence tiny New Hampshire has on the selection process, want to
elbow their way toward the front of the field. Fine, in theory.
</P>
<P>
   The Westerners want candidates talking about ``their'' issues _
mining, grazing rights on federal property, harvesting (looting?)
timber from public lands, agribusiness poaching of diminishing
water supplies, etc.
</P>
<P>
   But the resulting jam at the start of the delegate-selecting
race _ ``frontloading'' in consultant lingo _ may have quite the
opposite effect of what the Western states intended. It's possible
to construct a theory that makes New Hampshire's snowy verdict even
more important to the wannabes than previously. How come? We start
with the money.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seriously thinks this Congress will substantially alter
the present system of collecting and spending money to win federal
office. Sure, it's corrupt, inefficient, a scandal, a mine field,
blah-blah. But it also favors incumbents of both parties, so
nothing will change in D.C. until, state by state, enough states
enact their own sorts of reforms that can culminate in a federal
law requiring free or low-cost broadcast time for major-party
candidates. But that's another column.
</P>
<P>
   To run a serious national campaign for president, the consensus
of experts is that you need a large sum _ say, $22 million, the
vast bulk of it in hand by next New Year's Eve. So for each day of
1999, Mr. I-wanna-be-president must raise $60,000, give or take, in
order to be at the front of the trough.
</P>
<P>
   There are only a handful of men _ no women visible at this
juncture, sad to report _ with any reasonable shot at raising that
kind of money. They are: Vice President Al Gore, the prohibitive
favorite on the Democratic side, and on the Republican side,
Governor George W. Bush of Texas, who sits atop a gusher of oil and
other kinds of Texas money, Lamar Alexander, and Steve Forbes. The
latter two have been advertising on New Hampshire television since
last August, believe it or not.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a lot of breaks for Republican hopefuls like
former vice president Dan Quayle, the best-known of the second
tier, or California's Governor Pete Wilson, Representative John
Kasich of Ohio, Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri, or even the
widely praised Senator John McCain of Arizona to crack the
60-grand-per-day club. Not even his close friends think Senator Bob
Smith, the GOP homeboy of the Granite State, could come close.
</P>
<P>
   Either party could win or lose the whole kit and caboodle next
time _ House, Senate, White House. Turnout will be way up,
increasing the Democrats' chances of making solid gains. That makes
it more likely that the House minority leader, Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, will not run for president, leaving the
who'll-challenge-Gore chores to the likes of Senators Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, John Kerry of Massachusetts, Paul Wellstone of Minnesota,
and former senator Bill Bradley of New Jersey. Not exactly
Murderer's Row in the money-raising department, unless you count in
the two-thirds of a billion pile accrued by Kerry's spouse, the
redoubtable Teresa Heinz.
</P>
<P>
   Just how does this discussion of filthy lucre affect the primary
calendar? With California and the Thundering Herd crowding forward
from the rear to the front of the schedule, it shortens the time in
which a candidate can build name recognition, organize some
semblance of a grass-roots effort on the ground, and raise enough
money to be competitive in the disgracefully expensive world of
television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``free media'' _ newspaper and broadcast coverage
_ concentrate on the horse race, the candidates' inevitable gaffes
and screwups, the confetti tossed in the air by those who wish you
ill. Rare is the outsider _ wrestler-turned-Governor-elect Jesse
Ventura is one _ who can sneak under the media's radar screen to
score points with actual voters.
</P>
<P>
   Without a top-three finish in Iowa's jury-rigged caucuses, a
candidate is extremely unlikely to do much in New Hampshire a week
later. But do well in New Hampshire and your mug is on the cover of
Time and Newsweek, the cable networks go bananas making you a
household name, and with the calendar scrunched toward the weeks
just after New Hampshire, the single biggest bang you can get is to
come out of the Granite State as the man who is hot-hot-hot!
</P>
<P>
   With the lights going out on the Republican congressional
leadership's broken-down impeachment effort and the media hounds
dousing their Monica cigars for the nuts and bolts of presidential
positioning, the road to the White House has to go through New
Hampshire, the Panama Canal of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will probably secure the support of Governor Jeanne
Shaheen, she of the 70 percent approval rating. New Hampshire is
friendly territory. Even his wife is popular there; Tipper is
regarded as Hillary without the barbed wire.
</P>
<P>
   (A GOP note: last Friday on CNN's ``Inside Politics'' I
incorrectly said Representative John Sununu supports Forbes. Sununu
is uncommitted.)
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
