<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERS TOO OFTEN IN HARM'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was a loyal alumna of Wheaton College, where she had been an
English major in the all-female Class of '36.
</P>
<P>
   She was a walker in her Arlington Heights neighborhood, where
the hills can present a challenge to calves decades younger than
her own.
</P>
<P>
   She was a lady-who-lunched, at whatever new restaurant her group
of longtime friends had discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever image one summons to mind at news that an old woman has
been beaten and scalded, nearly to death, in her own home, it is a
fair bet that Jane Sheard does not fit the stereotype. At 85, she
is elderly only by the calendar's measure; by all others she is _
or was _ more vital than many half her age.
</P>
<P>
   She was neither frail in body nor feeble in spirit when she fell
victim to a category of violence that too often occurs out of
public view. It was only the severity of Mrs. Sheard's injuries _
several broken ribs, a fractured skull, a broken wrist, multiple
broken fingers, and second degree burns over 15 percent of her body
_ that forced us to pause and take notice.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after Thanksgiving, authorities allege, 85-year-old
Jane Sheard was battered within an inch of her life by her own
daughter. While her mother is clinging to life in the intensive
care unit at the Leahy Clinic, Nancy Reida, 54, is undergoing
court-ordered psychiatric tests.
</P>
<P>
   One can only hope that Mrs. Sheard's daughter is crazy.
</P>
<P>
   How much easier to believe that a woman would have to be insane
to pour boiling water over her already vanquished mother than to
accept that such acts of brutality are tragically commonplace in
the lives of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The latest statistics compiled by the state's Executive Office
of Elder Affairs offer no such solace, however, indicating as they
do just how frequently older people are victimized by their
caregivers, often their own children. In fiscal 1998, there were
6,010 reports of elder abuse in Massachusetts, a substantial
increase over the year before. Indeed, such violence has increased
every year since fiscal 1984, when the state began tracking abuse
of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those numbers have faces for Marian Ryan, an assistant
district attorney who has been prosecuting elder abuse cases for 20
years. She estimates that 25 such cases land on her desk every
month. The numbers go up during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   The crimes, she says, do not occur just in some tenements or
housing projects. She has 12 cases. The offenders, she says, are
not just cruel home health aides. There is, for instance, the son
who broke his elderly mother's arm in the middle of the day in the
center of what Ryan describes as ``a very nice town.'' Imagine what
was happening to her in private.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what people think. More often than not, it's an adult
child who has moved back to the parents' home. It's often a nice
home; it's the financial security that lures them back. He or she
usually has problems of his own, drugs or alcohol maybe. Sometimes
a parent is frail and needs constant care; maybe she has
Alzheimer's. The frustration builds. It's inexcusable, but at least
it's more understandable than what happened to Mrs. Sheard.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what happened to Mrs. Sheard is a matter for the courts
to decide, but what may yet end in death might well have begun as
an argument about the family china. Every plate in the house was
smashed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sheard had been due to try out a new restaurant with her
lunch bunch last Friday but canceled because her son was visiting
from western Massachusetts. Her pals called later to tease her
about what a fine meal she had missed and became alarmed when her
telephone went unanswered. Concerned, they stopped by Tanager
Street, a tidy neighborhood of one- and two-family houses built
into the side of a hill in Arlington, a Boston suburb. When they
got no response to their knock, they called again. After several
rings, Mrs. Sheard picked up the receiver. ``I'm bleeding,'' she
whispered, before dropping the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters had only to follow the bloody handprints on the
wall to locate Mrs. Sheard at the top of the staircase where she
had dragged herself to reach the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   In District Court this week, Nancy Reida looked vacant when she
was committed for a 20-day psychiatric evaluation. The baggy blue
sweatshirt she wore proclaimed that ``Nothing is impossible if you
don't have to do it yourself,'' a message as enigmatic as the crime
for which Jane Sheard's daughter stands accused.
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
