<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE BELIEVER HEDGES HIS BET ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even Joe McNay, the truest believer among Boston's Internet
investors, thinks all this has gotten nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 18 months, no one in this town has bet more of his
money on those incredible rising Internet stocks than McNay,
chairman of Essex Investment Management. The biggest positions in
his portfolio read like a who's who among the pricest stocks in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Essex, with roughly $5 billion under management, was the largest
institutional owner of Amazon.com at the end of the September
quarter, and it was the firm's biggest single holding. Yahoo, CMG
Information Services, and America Online were three of his next
five largest holdings, according to the Carson Group, a New York
consulting firm. He was the second-largest institutional owner of
eBay and had top 10 positions in such Internet favorites as
(AT)Home, Lycos, Excite, and Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But now, McNay is stepping back. In the past two weeks, as the
stocks have risen fast, McNay has cut his Internet positions
roughly in half. McNay reduced the Internet exposure in his
institutional accounts to 10 percent and to 15 percent in his more
aggressive hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it had become a short-term mania,'' McNay said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After posting sharp gains for several weeks, Internet stocks
tanked on Monday, with the American Stock Exchange Internet index
falling 7 percent. Yahoo plunged nearly 25 points, or 12 percent;
Amazon.com fell 24 5/8, or 8 percent; and Onsale Inc. was down more
than 36, or 37 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks recovered some of their gains Tuesday, but McNay
doesn't think the correction is over. He won't name names, but says
he has started selling short _ betting the prices will continue to
fall _ some of the lesser Net companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that have moved from 20 to 90 in a week that we feel
weren't worth 20,'' he says. Hello Onsale?
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake: McNay is not walking away from the Internet.
Just the opposite, in fact. He calls it ``the biggest revolution
that has occurred in my lifetime in terms of the impact it will
have on us in little ways and big ways.''
</P>
<P>
   This is McNay's kind of market. He is maybe Boston's most
prominent momentum investor, who looks for the big concept and then
rides it up. He did that with oil service stocks in the late 1970s,
cellular telephones and waste management in the late '80s. He was
an early and big player in biotechnology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe is one of the best conceptual momentum investors of his
time,'' says James Pallotta, who worked in McNay's shop until 1993
and now runs a $1.3 billion hedge fund in Boston for Tudor
Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum investing doesn't come without volatility. Over the
last year through Sept. 30, McNay's growth-equity portfolios, which
contain the lion's share of the assets, were up 6.96 &UR;  &LR; percent,
ranking them in the top 10 percent of all institutional midcap
growth managers tracked by Pensions &AMP; Investments. But those same
growth portfolios ranked among the bottom 20 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Returns for two of McNay's hedge funds show just how hot the
Internet stocks have been for him this year. His Essex High Tech
fund, with about $40 million in assets, was up a stunning 86
percent through Nov. 30 and his Permal Media and Communications
fund, with $38 million in assets, was up 43 percent through Nov.
15. Both funds are available only to clients outside the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Internet stocks, McNay continues to like companies
that have ``the true franchise positions.'' He mentions America
Online, Yahoo, Amazon.com, Lycos, eBay. He also continues to like
CMG as an incubator of evolving Internet technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some of the biggest smart money in the United States
invested behind them,'' McNay says.
</P>
<P>
   But until the prices come down, McNay is unlikely to be a buyer.
By the end of the third quarter, after all, his holdings taken
together carried a price-earnings ratio of 40, nearly 50 percent
higher than the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, Carson says.
</P>
<P>
   What's he done with all that money he has pulled out of the
Internet companies? ``For a little while cash doesn't feel bad,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas O'Neill, chief investment officer for Fleet Investment
Advisors, has himself a nice little side gig: running three hedge
funds.
</P>
<P>
   At a tough time to find money in the suddenly suspect hedge fund
business, O'Neill raised $100 million for the three funds,
including an undisclosed sum from his daytime employer, Fleet
Financial Group, according to a bank spokesman. The funds are
geared to institutions and wealthy individuals, and will pursue
traditional long and short trading in both US and foreign
securities.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill will presumably charge the industry standard fees of 1
percent of assets and 20 percent of profits _ not bad for a kid who
grew up in South Boston and went to Harvard on a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
