<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8855 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKER-MYTH-2TAKES-BO     12-02 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-MYTH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYTH OF YOUNG COMPUTER HACKERS LOSES A BIT 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sean Trifero awoke one morning in May &UR;  &LR; as federal agents stormed
into his bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested in his boxer shorts, Trifero was charged with
``computer abuse.'' Last month, the 21-year-old from Middletown,
R.I., pleaded guilty in US District Court in Boston to charges he
shut down or illegally accessed five university and commercial
computer systems _ intrusions the Justice Department says caused
damages of about $67,500. He faces sentencing in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case graphically shows the harm that hackers can cause,''
says Donald K. Stern, the US attorney for Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But exactly how much harm is that? The federal judge overseeing
the case has questioned whether the damages caused by Trifero were
really as high as the government figures.
</P>
<P>
   The charges also fell far short of earlier suspicions, described
by the FBI in November 1997, which had painted Trifero as a menace
to society. The agency, which began investigating Trifero earlier
that year, reported he boasted of attacking White House computers,
shutting down MCI Worldcom Inc. telephone switching equipment, and
discussed intrusions by another hacker into a NASA facility.
</P>
<P>
   Trifero's attorney, Edward St. Onge of Providence, R.I. won't
discuss the FBI's assertions, but says his client's only motive was
gamesmanship. ``What Sean did involved a chess game between man and
machine, and he got a little carried away,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the Trifero case and others like it suggest that the
supposedly omnipotent young hacker is more myth than fact. Indeed,
many accused youngsters turn out to be much like
Trifero &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; nuisances to the private sector, but perhaps not
threats to national security like the teenagers portrayed in the
1983 movie ``War Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the myth resonates, in part because many of the
highest-profile cases brought by the Justice Department involve
boastful young defendants. Some even say federal officials have
overblown the threat to build support for the Justice Department's
growing computer crimes unit and a new $29
million &UR;  &LR; computer-security center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are a very convenient scapegoat,'' says John
Vranesevich, principal of AntiOnline LLP, an Internet news service
based &UR;  &LR; in Beaver, Pa. &UR;  &LR; George Smith, editor of the on-line Crypt
Newsletter in Pasadena, Calif., says the actual damages they cause
often are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're saying that these people can topple the republic, and
that's not likely to happen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To prosecutors, the criticism stings. Martha Stansell-Gamm,
deputy chief of the Justice Department's computer crimes unit &UR;  &LR; in
Washington, says officials won't ignore complaints of computer
intrusions because they can't know whether investigation will
reveal ``a surplus of testosterone, or a terrorist'' at the other
end of the wire.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in March 1997 radio equipment at the Worcester
airport was knocked out for six hours by an unauthorized tap into a
telephone-switching device, forcing air-traffic controllers to use
a shorter-range backup radio system. Investigators traced the tap
to a teenager living near the airport, who in March of this year
pleaded guilty to charges he inadvertently shut down the main
system by sending commands from a home PC. He was sentenced to two
years' probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are cases that start out looking like the crime of the
century and wind up being pretty minor,'' Stansell-Gamm says. ``But
we don't feel badly that we pursued them.''
</P>
<P>
   Trifero's case is typical of many computer-security charges
brought under federal laws passed in 1996. The new rules broadened
the definition of protected equipment to include computers involved
in interstate commerce &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; including most of the millions of
computers now connected to the Internet. Previously, hackers were
often charged with wiretapping, with limited success.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, federal prosecutors have obtained guilty
pleas from 20 defendants for the 12 months ended Sept. 30, up from
nine during the same period two years earlier. Investigations grew
to 254 from 73 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   These cases tend to involve two types of defendants, says Jeanne
Kempthorne, an assistant US attorney in Boston handling the Trifero
case. One group includes youths who mainly aim to show off on line;
the second includes adults with a grudge, usually against their
former employers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Corporate losses
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department agrees that corporate insiders cause the
most damage. A 1997 survey of 520 technology executives by the FBI
and the Computer Security Institute in San Francisco found
hacking-related losses of $136 million nationwide. The biggest
share of that, $50 million, was attributed to ``unauthorized access
by insiders'' to corporate systems, followed by thefts of
proprietary information and telecommunications fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The group didn't try to estimate the damage caused by underage
users, but in any case they rarely seem to succeed in stealing or
compromising top-secret information from government institutions.
Kempthorne says she wrestles with just how far to push cases
against youngsters who mainly seek notoriety. ``The question is,
how do you do deterrence with this group?'' she says. ``It's a huge
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Trifero's career as an on-line prankster seems to have begun in
1996, the year he turned 19.
</P>
<P>
   Through his attorney, Trifero declined to comment for this
story, citing his upcoming sentencing hearing set for January. He
faces up to 18 months in prison under the terms of his plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But court filings and interviews with people who know Trifero
paint a picture of a curious young man with a temper and perhaps
too much regard for his own expertise.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Middletown High School, Trifero began
taking computer science classes at a community college in Warwick,
but grew bored and switched to emergency medicine, family members
say.
</P>
<P>
   By January 1998 he had left school altogether and begun a job as
a telephone-help representative for clients of a staffing service,
RHI Consulting. Aside from some traffic tickets, local police say,
his only other brush with the law came when he was arrested for
illegal possession of fireworks on July 4, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Trifero's day job may not have been as exciting as his
on-line activities, for which the government alleges he often used
the screen name of ``FA-Q.''
</P>
<P>
   These activities were first brought to the attention of
authorities by John O'Donnell, owner of BBSNet Worldwide in East
Providence, R.I., an on-line service provider to which Trifero paid
$20 a month for access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
