<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE NO MORE LEADING QUESTIONS ABOUT BLEDSOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Overlooked in the chaos and excitement of
the Patriots' final drive last Sunday _ and Drew Bledsoe again
putting his name to a signature game with a broken index finger _
was what happened in the next-to-last drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great quarterbacks do what Drew did in that fourth quarter,''
said rookie receiver Tony Simmons. ``And he's the one giving us a
chance to win and he's the one coming through for us. That's why
he's The Man.''
</P>
<P>
   What the team saw in those final moments, said running back
Robert Edwards, ``is that Drew is the leader of this team. And
everybody looks up to him and expects him to make great plays.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened on the last play of the last drive, of course, is
well known. And the new attitude of the team was symbolized by
Simmons, standing on the sidelines next to Terry Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked up to Terry and said, `We're about to win,''' said
Simmons. ``I knew Drew was going to Ben (Coates) on the play and
Ben's a big-time receiver and Drew's a big-time passer.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the previous drive, there was another sign of the new
Bledsoe. With five minutes left in the game, Bledsoe had moved his
team from its own 37-yard line to a first down on Buffalo's 20. But
then his protection broke down. Bledsoe was sacked for a 9-yard
loss by Wayne Simmons on first down and then was rushed and hurried
two incomplete passes.
</P>
<P>
   He got up from the turf twice and lashed out at his offensive
line for breaking down at a crucial time. Adam Vinatieri then
missed a 47-yard field goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm free (to criticize teammates) only when I feel I'm
playing well myself,'' said Bledsoe, downplaying, as usual, any
perception that he is any different from the Bledsoe of 1997 or
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, when the Patriots took over on their 18-yard
line with 1:52 left, the pass protection was much improved. Even
though the Bills knew he was going to pass on every play (except
perhaps the last one), Bledsoe was not sacked on that final drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we had to give our quarterback time,'' said
tackle Bruce Armstrong. ``And we did. And Drew got the plays
made.''
</P>
<P>
   On the previous drive, Armstrong recalled, ``We called a couple
of protections down there at the 20-yard line and one incorporated
the tight end on the back side and I think Drew got hit on that one
and then he got pressured on the next one. The problem was that the
Bills were running a lot of stunts down there.''
</P>
<P>
   With rookie tight end Rod Rutledge in the game, and with Damon
Denson making his first start at guard, the Patriot offense was
confused by the Bills' moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a rookie tight end in and a second-year guy at guard,
and this is not to say they can't play and play well, but it just
gives you more of an opportunity to make a mistake,'' said
Armstrong. ``The Bills were coming with two-man and three-man games
and this was the first time these new guys had seen them.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Bledsoe's tongue-lashing, said Armstrong, ``We knew
we'd be better prepared as a unit the next time we saw them.''
</P>
<P>
   As you were on the last drive?
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were on the last drive,'' said Armstrong. ``Exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is crystal clear: This is Drew Bledsoe's team now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got the guy now who can make the play,'' said
fullback Tony Carter. ``It makes you feel a lot better knowing that
when you're confronted with the same kind of situation again.''
</P>
<P>
   With no running game and a leaky pass defense _ and especially
with the Denver Broncos in their conference _ these Patriots may
not be going to the Super Bowl, but the question in the back of
many minds for so long is now gone: Even if the Patriots had a
running game and a stout defense, did they have a quarterback with
that intangible Super Bowl quality?
</P>
<P>
   That question was answered twice in two weeks. And it was
answered last Sunday, not only on the final drive, but also on the
previous drive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8863 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKER-MYTH-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-02 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKER-MYTH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the Internet.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   O'Donnell says he contacted Middletown, R.I., police in the fall
of 1996 after receiving complaints from several academic
computer-system operators. One call came from Bowdoin College in
Brunswick, Maine, where a BBSNet user calling himself FA-Q had
tapped into Bowdoin's computers using a stolen password.
</P>
<P>
   A Bowdoin system administrator, Tad Macy, says FA-Q was one of
several dozen users he discovered logged onto the school's
computers without permission, apparently to access free game
software that had been secretly installed. ``It didn't hurt the
system operation, but it was a theft of resources,'' Macy said in a
recent interview. ``It was like somebody storing their couch in
your garage without your permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Another complaint came from Brad Karp, a Harvard University
graduate student. Karp says he noticed a BBSNet user &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; apparently
Trifero &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; had gained access to his network's central computer and
had run a powerful ``decryption'' program to unscramble passwords.
Karp estimates he spent about 200 hours restoring security, which
he says was particularly galling because the intruder didn't seem
to have written the decryption program himself &UR;  &LR; _ &UR;  &LR; usually a hacker
point of pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't push the envelope in any technical sense,'' Karp
says.
</P>
<P>
   Investigating the complaints, O'Donnell found the FA-Q account
was registered to the Middletown apartment where Trifero lived. He
shut down the account, though he adds, ``I'm not sure I've ever met
a teenager who doesn't go through that stage of rebelliousness.''
</P>
<P>
   But the investigation by local police lagged, and Trifero
returned to the Internet via other access providers. According to a
November 1997 affidavit filed by the FBI to obtain a warrant to
search Trifero's home, he also began to associate with a group of
hackers calling themselves the ``Virii,'' exchanging messages in
Internet chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chatroom bullies
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Computer administrators who encountered FA-Q and other members
of the Virii say they often bullied their way into others' chat
rooms without permission, dominated e-mail traffic and logged off
legitimate users who complained.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would just lock down the room and claim it for their
own,'' says Rached Blili, who once helped administer the volunteer
network known as the ``Undernet,'' which provides free chat
services. Blili, who now works for a networking company in Cedar
Falls, Iowa, says he remembers FA-Q didn't get much respect when he
first appeared in 1996, although he doesn't recall in which group
FA-Q was a member.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his friends were ragging on him because he wasn't so
good at hacking,'' recalls Blili. Although FA-Q and others bragged
about breaking into Pentagon computers, Blili says most didn't seem
to have written their own code to do so and didn't seem to have
gained access to much sensitive information. ``It was just a lot of
hot air,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the teasing may have driven Trifero to become more
aggressive. According to his plea agreement and to the FBI
affidavit, by the summer of 1997 he had begun to launch
``denial-of-service'' attacks against commercial computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   These attacks, sometimes known as ``ping-bombs,'' are software
commands that cause scores of outside computers to send brief
messages to a host computer. Unable to keep up, hosts can crash or
run sporadically.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nebraska attack
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, Trifero pleaded guilty to disrupting the
services of Navix, an Internet-access provider in Lincoln, Neb.,
owned by Alliant Communications Inc. According to the FBI's filing,
the attack caused the system to crash, knocking out service to
14,000 subscribers and 1,500 corporate users intermittently over a
36-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   Some subscribers canceled their service as a result, says
Alliant spokeswoman Lela Kelliher, although she declines to discuss
how the government arrived at a damage estimate of $29,500.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to desist, FA-Q often would respond with profanity,
system administrators say. Jason Buchanan, a chat-network volunteer
in Springfield, Mo., says FA-Q mainly wanted attention. But when he
reacted politely, Buchanan wrote in a recent e-mail, FA-Q ``would
reply back with things like `you're not supposed to like me, dude.
Why are you talking with me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Other system operators had less patience, however, and
ultimately an exchange with one in Albuquerque led to FA-Q's
undoing. The administrator, Travis Haymore, says FA-Q launched
numerous attacks on his system from August 1996 until September
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Identifying Trifero with the help of other chat-room
administrators, Haymore says he contacted Middletown, R.I., police
and learned of the ongoing local investigation stemming from
O'Donnell's complaint. Haymore says he brought it to the attention
of FBI agents in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Haymore's account and others, the FBI obtained a warrant
and searched Trifero's apartment on Nov. 4, 1997. On May 13, 1998,
federal agents returned to arrest him on computer-abuse charges,
under the 1996 computer-security laws.
</P>
<P>
   Since his arrest, Trifero has been free on $10,000 bond. He was
fired from his $2,400-a-month job at RHI, and a district court
order bans him from using the Internet while he awaits sentencing.
However, he has found a new job ``related to computers,'' says St.
Onge, his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   St. Onge says Trifero may seek a reduced sentence in return for
volunteering as a consultant to the institutions whose computers he
penetrated. But he may find few takers. O'Donnell, the service
provider, calls the proposal ``a joke'' because of the hacker's
apparent use of software written by others.
</P>
<P>
   Karp, the Harvard system operator, says he wouldn't accept the
help for similar reasons _ and suggests the government's
prosecutions may do too much to legitimize the threat from those
like Trifero.
</P>
<P>
   Says Karp, ``If I were the D.O.J., what I'd be worried about is
the notion that getting busted for computer crimes is the pathway
to a great career.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
