<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8868 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-02 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TROUBLES OVER BATHROOM BREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When factory owner Kevin Kevelson locked the door to the women's
bathroom two years ago, he unleashed a gust of angry protests.
</P>
<P>
   Workers picketed and demonstrated. Media descended on the Fall
River, Mass. plant, and the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and
Technical Employees blasted the firm for changing the conditions of
employment without negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never timed employees and we never said they couldn't use
the bathroom,'' recalled Kevelson, owner of Ideal Bias Binding
Inc., a maker of baby bibs. ``All we said was `You have to come in
the office and get the key to go.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said he locked the bathroom and put the key in the office
because he wanted to catch the culprits who were smoking in the
loo, littering the facility with cigarette butts, and violating
fire code regulations barring smoking in some sections of the
factory. But 60 textile workers didn't see it that way.
</P>
<P>
   Kevelson probably did not know it, but access to bathroom and to
rest breaks has long been a troubling problem for poultry,
agricultural, textile, and assembly workers, as well as for
druggists and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa attorney Marc Linder discovered as much while representing
migrant farm workers at a New Mexico dairy. ``These were
Mexican-Americans who could not do anything during their 12-hour
shifts,'' Linder said. ``They couldn't eat. They couldn't go to the
bathroom. They had precious few rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Stunned, Linder began researching state and federal laws
governing rest breaks. Then, he went out and talked to workers. His
findings and those of co-author Ingrid Nygaard led to ``Void Where
Prohibited: Rest Breaks and the Right to Urinate on Company Time''
(Industrial Relations Press, Cornell University, 1998), a book that
details the history of the 15-minute rest break many of us now take
for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to rest and void at work is not high on the list of
social or political causes supported by professional or executive
employees, who enjoy personal workplace liberties that millions of
factory workers can only dream about,'' wrote the authors.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports that 24 percent of all
full-time blue-collar and service workers employed by midsized and
large firms did not have rest breaks in 1993, the last year for
which data was available on the topic. Moreover, 51 percent of
part-time blue-collar and service workers and a third of clerical
and sales employees cannot take breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples culled from ``Void Where Prohibited:''
</P>
<P>
   _Female workers at Nabisco sued the Oxnard, Calif., plant three
years ago after receiving a supervisory order telling them to
urinate in their clothes while on the production line or risk
three-day suspensions for taking a bathroom break. The women solved
the immediate problem by wearing adult diapers, but several alleged
that long waits to use the restroom had led to urinary tract
infections and bladder disorders.
</P>
<P>
   _In Kansas, a poultry slaughtering worker who had been denied
permission to use the bathroom was fired after he lost control and
urinated on the factory floor.
</P>
<P>
   Denial of rest breaks is not limited to blue-collar or service
workers, though they are the most likely to be penalized for taking
them. In a study released this month, the Pharmacists Society of
the State of New York reported that nearly 70 percent of the 1,011
pharmacists it surveyed this summer ``found the lack of
opportunites for breaks for lunch, rest, and bathroom particularly
irritating.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those polled, 69 percent were male, and 44 percent were
employed by chains. Only 26 percent were independent owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some situations where the pharmacy is in a supermarket or
retail store, the bathroom break is a problem. Usually, there is
only one pharmacist and he or she cannot leave until the store
closes,'' said Craig Burridge, executive director of the
pharmacists' society. ``These are people working 12- to 16-hour
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had pharmacists call here in tears. A year out of
pharmacy school, and they cannot believe it. They feel like they've
become machines,'' said Burridge. They fill twice as many scripts,
they make half as much money, and they can't even use the
bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   With a classroom of young children needing constant attention,
some elementary school teachers have found ingenious ways to answer
nature's call. ``When we studied women teachers in Des Moines and
Iowa City, Iowa, we found that 1 in 10 had to take the entire class
with her to the bathroom,'' said Linder.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are teachers in public schools that do not have aides,''
he said. ``So, a teacher would line the children up outside the
bathroom stall because she didn't want to leave the class
unattended. Other teachers used adult diapers during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're with 23 children all day long, you really can't
run off now and then,'' acknowledged Paula Tranchita, an elementary
school teacher in Winchester. ``I know one kindergarten teacher who
took the children into the bathroom. I guess it was like having her
own in there, multiplied by 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on the third floor and there is no adult bathroom on that
floor,'' she said. ``So, I've learned not to go, or find someone to
stand near the door and watch the classroom. Even when you're
feeling a little off, you cannot just get up and go. You really
have to be creative.''
</P>
<P>
   The hue and cry over what many of us regard as a basic workplace
benefit caught the attention of the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration last year, after the United Food and Commercial
Workers union filed a health and safety complaint against the
Hudson Foods poultry plant in Noel, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The union also argued that OSHA erred when it required that
bathrooms be at worksites but did not mandate that workers must be
given the time and ability to use them.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA disciplined the firm. Then, it issued a four-page memo
clarifying its current toilet standard to mean that workers should
be allowed ``prompt access to sanitary facilities. ... Restrictions
on access must be reasonable and may not cause extended delays.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Greg Denier, a spokesman for the UFCW in Washington, ``in
almost every union organizing campaign we have these days, the
primary issue is, `Will I get the right to go to the bathroom?'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
