<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8870 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIENDLY-LAWFIRM-ART-     12-02 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDLY-LAWFIRM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADITION YIELDS TO NEED TO SURVIVE AT SOME LAW FIRMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's an in-house chef, a weekly cocktail night,
lobster bakes on the sundeck, and waterfront views. No, it's not
Club Med. It's Goulston &AMP; Storrs, a Boston law firm picked by young
associates as the best place in the country to work in a recent
poll by American Lawyer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The perks are good, and the pay is competitive with New York
firms. But such emblems of lawyerly success _ practically
necessities in the go-go '80s _ meant less to the entry-level
attorneys surveyed than something very '90s: a life.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of a midlevel associate quoted by the magazine,
Goulston &AMP; Storrs topped the other big firms &UR;  &LR;  because ``people
legitimately care if you are overworked.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a warm and fuzzy remark might have been unheard of a decade
ago, when law graduates scrapped for the biggest salaries and
planned to forsake any semblance of a life outside the law,
industry observers say. But now, more and more young lawyers
complain that big firms have become mere meat grinders that chew up
associates with long hours, dull work, and few chances for
advancement. And many now say they are unwilling to sacrifice a
life out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd die if this was it,'' says Amy Moody, a 28-year-old
Goulston &AMP; Storrs associate now in her second year at the firm,
which has 124 lawyers. ``I have friends who work until midnight
every day of the week. Being a lawyer is a big part of my life. But
it's not everything.''
</P>
<P>
   In decidedly un-lawyerly terms like ``connectivity'' and
``sharing,'' Goulston &AMP; Storrs officials say they have tried to
abolish the pain the legal profession commonly inflicts on its
newest entrants. The firm doesn't require associates to fulfill
quotas for billable hours, a departure from accepted industry
practice. Senior partners say they reprimand young associates for
working too much _ a fact that may account for a work week at least
five hours shorter than the national average. Associates and
partners alike rotate offices once every two years, an effort to
downplay class distinctions between the two groups. &UR;  &LR;  And young
lawyers are included in business discussions over lunch, held after
every meeting of the firm's leadership. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Partners are expected to mix socially with associates and even
lend a hand when a young attorney's workload becomes too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number one priority is helping people,'' says managing
partner Michael Haroz. ``We're about counseling, teaching, and
cheerleading.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``A lot of firms view associates as expendable and say only a
few are going to make it to partnership. We look at each of our
associates as prospective partners. That's a fundamental
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Goulston &AMP; Storrs isn't alone. Indeed, Boston appears to have
become a mecca for good feeling among associates. Seven of the top
20 firms named in the American Lawyer survey of the nation's 153
biggest firms are in the city. Mintz Levin Cohn Ferris Glovsky &AMP;
Popeo ranked third; Hale and Dorr, sixth; Goodwin Procter &AMP; Hoar,
11th; Testa Hurwitz &AMP; Thibeault, 13th; Ropes &AMP; Gray, 15th; Palmer &AMP;
Dodge, 16th.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, associates said they gave high marks because of
the atmosphere at their firms.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing last in Boston was Bingham Dana, which ranked near the
bottom nationally at 136. Associates ``complained of feeling
isolated and put off by the firm's cliquishness,'' &UR;  &LR; the magazine
said. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The new emphasis on treatment of associates came about because
of &UR;  &LR;  a sea change during the 1980s in the way big law firms were
managed. The number of law school graduates nationwide quadrupled
to 40,000 a year during the decade and ``changed the profession
forever,'' says Jane Sender, who runs a Boston legal placement
service.
</P>
<P>
   Before the boom, graduates could expect to live out their
careers at the firm they signed with after law school, she says.
And while the life of new associates always consisted of long hours
and occasional abuse from domineering partners, they could expect
to share in the firm's best work and count on eventually becoming
partners themselves. Young lawyers often likened the process to
joining the priesthood, a compact for life.
</P>
<P>
   But with the glut of new attorneys _ and an explosion of legal
work, much of it a result of the business boom of the decade _
firms ballooned in size. A gulf widened between rain-making
partners and the hordes of inexperienced associates who
increasingly assumed run-of-the-mill tasks, Sender says.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects for advancement became slim as a glut of new lawyers
competed for relatively few spots at the top of the totem pole,
breeding what some attorneys considered a new and poisonous kind of
politics at many firms. And when the '80s economic boom turned to
bust, firms struggled for survival. Associates increasingly were
viewed simply as cheap labor, worker bees on a treadmill that
became known as ``assembly line law.'' Few associates would ever
make partner.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of all new associates now quit their firm within six
years, according to a survey this year by the National Association
of Law Placement. One-third quit in less than three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Associates are thrown into a big maelstrom and asked to sink
or swim,'' Sender says. ``And the people at the bottom are
considered disposable.''
</P>
<P>
   The associate's plight was more or less accepted for years, she
says, but the Generation X of the legal profession has begun to
complain, forcing some firms competing for the best students to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people grew up with all those concepts of flex time and
part time, notions of fairness and this idea that there's more to
life than a job _ even a job like the law,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the praise heaped on firms like Goulston &AMP; Storrs, some
observers remain skeptical, saying feel-good policies can be little
more than a veneer to business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Firms still have to make money,'' says Mark Kwatcher, of
Kwatcher Legal Placement in Boston. ``You make money by billing
hours. Nobody has the idea that they want to grind up associates,
but it's the reality now. Those economic forces haven't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   And while most young associates are clearly happy to be at
Goulston, at least one attorney at the firm said the
feel-good &UR;  &LR; practice &UR;  &LR; doesn't always measure up to the billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make a sincere effort, and that means a lot,'' said the
associate, who asked not to be named. ``But when you get beyond
that, this isn't all that much different than a lot of firms. The
hours are still long. Some of the partners are a huge pain to work
with. And the bottom line, no matter what anybody says, is that to
really make it at the firm you've got to make money for the firm. I
don't know that any amount of policy making can get you around
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Goulston &AMP; Storrs' claim of advancing all or most of
its associates to partnership could one day evaporate for the
simple reason that entrenched partners will be ultimately unwilling
to share profits with an ever-growing group, some observers say.
Even firm officials admit it, though they point out the firm has an
unusually high ratio of 71 partners to 52 associates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everyone to be successful here,'' says Heroz, the
managing partner. ``But one of the issues is, how many partners can
you have? Is there a limit? If you cut up the pie for more and more
partners, there is. You have to be a successful law firm. To do the
kinds of things we are doing, you have to have economic
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, prosperity may lie at the heart of the matter, some
observers say. The fact that Boston firms performed so well on the
American Lawyer survey has as much to do with the local economy as
it does with firm policies, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are good right now,'' says Kwatcher. ``It's Boston's
time to shine. The firms are busy. They're doing interesting work.
But that's going to change. When times get a little worse, we'll
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Moody, the second-year associate, says she has
already worked on important cases. She has burned midnight oil, but
she also has time to travel with her boyfriend and spend summer
weekends on the Cape. She occupies an office with a harbor view,
where on one recent evening she could gaze at ferries placidly
churning toward the mist of a rust-colored sunset. ``It's probably
not nirvana,'' she says. ``But it's a very good place to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
