<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-02 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDENTIALS COULD CRAMP YOUR STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years I have developed an interest in the career of
James Fallowzzz, Big Thinker, media critic, and the recently
cashiered editor of U.S. News &AMP; World Report. Jim is now designing
word processing software for Microsoft (Great ad campaign _ ``Write
like Jim Fallowzzz!'') and, of course, I wish him the best.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who suggest that everything Jim has ever
written, from his ``small-is-beautiful'' defense theories to his
prolix valorizations of the Japanese economy, is dead wrong. But
I've always admired an excellent cover story Fallowzzz wrote for
the Atlantic Monthly in 1985, on the subject of ``credentialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he expended 12,639 words to put across his thesis,
Fallowzzz's point was a simple one: Professional mobility in
America had become wholly dependent on academic credentials, at the
expense of our professed meritocratic values. Without a degree, and
preferably an advanced degree, from a societally approved temple of
higher learning, one faced tough slogging in what was then Ronald
Reagan's America.
</P>
<P>
   But even this most convincing of Fallowzzz-izms proves to be
wrong. Events of recent weeks reveal that credentials are out, and
moxie is in. If you say you are qualified, you are qualified!
Right, Mary Bono?
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _Minnesota's Jesse ``the Governor'' Ventura, has been a
professional wrestler, a motorcyle gang _ sorry, club _ member, a
bodyguard for the Rolling Stones, a Navy SEAL, a talk-show host,
and part-time mayor of Brooklyn Park, (Minn.), population 64,000.
He doesn't have a college degree, and the two men he trounced in
last month's election must be wondering why they bothered pursuing
theirs.
</P>
<P>
   _Irene Saez, a 6-foot-1 strawberry blonde who was Miss Universe
in 1981, may or may not be elected president of Venezuela on
Sunday. In other countries, Ms. Saez might be dismissed as just
another pretty face. But in Venezuela, which has spewed forth four
Miss Universes and four Miss Worlds, her credentials are taken very
seriously indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Saez had shown surprising poll strength against
her principal rival, Hugo Chavez, a former army paratrooper who
tried to overthrow the government in 1992. Now the Associated Press
reports that Saez's campaign is losing momentum as the election
nears. ``Irene should have stayed as beauty queen and never gotten
involved in politics,'' according to some strumpet/waitress
interviewed by the AP. Who cares what she thinks, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   _Superwonderfulgreatguy Tom Hanks sees which way the wind is
blowing. If some bimbo can put up big numbers in Caracas, why not
put Forrest Gump back in the White House? Discussing his political
ambitions with The New Yorker, Hanks initially fell into the
credentialism trap, allowing that he might ``have to know about law
or economics'' to run for office.
</P>
<P>
   Then the penny dropped. He flew on ``Apollo 13.'' He has what it
takes. ``My image is a really good one. I made a nice acceptance
speech on TV a couple of times,'' Hanks told the magazine. ``The
actual ideology that anyone can glean as by my appearances on TV is
that America is good because we are all so different, and
respecting each other is not so hard a thing to do. Not a bad
platform, I suppose, to run for some office.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrific platform, Tom! Arthur the Aardvark for vice president!
</P>
<P>
   It is at this point that the discerning reader might ask: What
credentials are required to become a columnist at the Great
Metropolitan Newspaper? Who knows? A penchant for bowing and
scraping in front of editors doesn't hurt, and a casual familiarity
with the English language is encouraged, but not required. (That's
why God invented the copy desk.)
</P>
<P>
   And that's the irony, gentle reader. You could be doing my job.
But, chances are, I couldn't be doing yours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
