<HEADLINE>
AILES INSISTS FOX NEWS IS BALANCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ask Roger Ailes a question and you get an answer: fast,
colorful, blunt as a punch in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Ailes was the Republican media strategist whose no-holds-barred
use of television to fashion a ``New Nixon'' was chronicled in Joe
McGinnis's ``The Selling of the President.'' He went on perform
similar services for Presidents Reagan and Bush; it was Ailes who
created the 1988 commercial showing a helmeted Michael Dukakis in a
tank.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 58-year-old Ailes is the chairman of Fox News, which has
been accused, along with its cable rivals CNN and MSNBC, of what
critics might call the Smearing of the President. That is, of
indulging in overkill in their coverage of the Monica Lewinsky/Bill
Clinton story.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Ailes isn't buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't every day you get a president with a semen-stained
dress,'' Ailes barked Tuesday during an interview. ``It's kind of
an unusual story; you have to give a little credit to the story
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   He conceded, though, that ``there's no question that kind of
story drives ratings, and once the cable networks understand that,
they're all in the hunt.'' And Ailes admitted that the coverage
``was perhaps a little bit overboard,'' though he contended that
Fox News showed restraint at some points.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Ailes said, the network had the story of the cigar
and the dress ``several weeks'' before the competition, but chose
not to broadcast the stories because ``the sourcing had to be
exceptionally strong for that kind of story.''
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of Fox News, Ailes oversees both the Fox News
Channel on cable and the limited amount of news programming (``Fox
Files,'' ``Fox News Sunday'') on the Fox broadcast network. His
political conservatism, along with that of Fox owner Rupert
Murdoch, has prompted some critics to label Fox News as primarily a
conduit for right-wing views. Its zest in covering the White House
scandal has rekindled those suspicions.
</P>
<P>
   But Ailes insists that the aim of the network, whose slogan is
``We report. You decide,'' is to present both sides of stories.
``Between 59 and 68 percent of the American people believe the
media is biased, and most believe it's biased toward the left,'' he
said. ``We say we're not going to spin the story for you in the
middle of the newscast, and that hit a nerve with the American
people, because they know they've been getting spun.''
</P>
<P>
   The all-news cable networks have used the Lewinsky story to
dramatically boost their ratings, though their numbers are still
small compared to the broadcast networks (and Fox News Channel is
third-ranked among the 24-hour cable channels).
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, they have muscled in on territory the broadcast
networks once had to themselves, giving rise to speculation that
one of the broadcasters might eventually get out of the news
business. Ailes envisions such a scenario. ``The network news
divisions, they're struggling to justify costs to support a
half-hour program,'' he said. ``They're living off their magazine
shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which: Does Ailes worry that the current glut of
newsmagazines will jeopardize ratings for ``Fox Files,'' the
newsmagazine that kicks off a new season tomorrow at 9 p.m.?
</P>
<P>
   ``I am worried about it,'' Ailes said, no trace of worry in his
voice. ``I just hope that the rest of them cancel theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Having decided to broadcast ``Fox Files'' each week from Grand
Central Terminal in New York City _ through which nearly half a
million people pass daily _ is Ailes concerned about potential
disruptions? Au contraire. ``If it happens, we'll shoot it and air
it,'' he said blithely.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, the decision to locate ``Fox Files'' in Grand
Central was driven by his desire to ``get the show down to the
street level of real people,'' Ailes said. ``We were looking for a
way to do this without an anchor desk, because so many of these
shows are locked in studios.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosted by Catherine Crier and Jon Scott, ``Fox Files'' debuted
last summer, when it pulled a younger audience (average age: 36)
than NBC's ``Dateline'' or CBS's ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ailes reacted nonchalantly to a report Tuesday in Daily Variety
that rival MSNBC is close to signing a lucrative new deal with
nationally syndicated radio host Don Imus, despite efforts by Fox
News Channel and CNN to woo him away. The deal would more than
double the license fee that MSNBC now pays annually to simulcast
``Imus in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said to Don Imus from time to time, `If they don't treat
you well, come on over here,' but we've never had any official
negotiations with them whatsoever,'' said Ailes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told by one of their lawyers that every time they used
my name their price went up. They learned their lesson from Geraldo
Rivera; Geraldo has been able to buy a few homes thanks to
mentioning my name.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, around the time Rivera's contract was up for
renewal at CNBC, Ailes made a hefty offer to lure him to Fox News.
NBC, which owns CNBC, quickly countered with an offer for much more
money and exposure for Rivera, which kept him at the Peacock
Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people at NBC are now asking me to be their agent,''
cracked Ailes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
