<SLUG> BC-SCOUT-MANUAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S SCOUTS PREPARE FOR THE WILDERNESS _ AND THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lord Baden-Powell, who taught the original Boy Scouts how to
guide strangers out of a London fog, had no compass for the murky
wilderness of the Internet. He knew about treating snake bites,
rigging lean-tos and avoiding poisonous toadstools. He didn't know
from black-tar heroin, AIDS, or on-line predators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be prepared _ for any old thing,'' Baden-Powell urged his
scouts in 1907. These days, that means being home alone, minding
siblings, fending off sexual abuse, and dealing with weird instant
messages from strangers on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the `new things' highlighted in the latest edition of
the Boy Scout Handbook, now available across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the old things _ camping and hiking skills, first aid,
personal hygiene, citizenship _ can still be found in the
handbook's 472 pages, which have been reorganized and streamlined
for easier use and printed on recycled and biodegradable paper.
</P>
<P>
   But a new section, ``Prepared for Life,'' offers frank advice
about cyberspace, sex, alcohol, drugs, and peer pressure. ``That's
one thing that came from the scouts themselves,'' says David
Setzer, vice chairman of the Boy Scouts of America's national
committee. ``They wanted something that dealt with the tough
problems they see every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The original scout handbook, published in 1911, was all about
surviving in the outdoors, about woodcraft and campcraft. Scouts
learned how to track and signal, how to tell the deadly Amanita
phalloides from the tasty Agaricus campestris, how to stop a
runaway horse and kill a mad dog.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th edition, the first revision since 1990, still teaches
boys from 11 through 18 how to find true north, make a splint, fold
Old Glory and cook a one-pot stew over a campfire. It also includes
tips on sexual responsibility, avoiding molesters, caring for young
children, and appreciating diversity. (But it avoids mentioning
homosexuals, whom the BSA bans. On Monday the US Supreme Court
denied a gay former Scout leader's challenge to the policy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The new handbook continues the emphasis on the Scout oath and
Scout law and Scout values,'' says Setzer. ``But it does it for
21st-century kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The BSA understands that the America of Norman Rockwell (who
painted the cover for four &UR;  &LR; of the previous 10 handbook editions)
has vanished. Scouting's WASPy suburban image is evolving. A
quarter of the membership now comes from minority groups, most of
them from inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   Today's scout is likely to come home to an empty house after
school and may have to serve as surrogate parent in a fatherless
home. He doesn't need to go off into the woods to find all the
adventure he can handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scouts told us they wanted the handbook to reflect a lot
of other things,'' says Matt Milleson, a Baylor University
sophomore and Eagle Scout who helped with the revision. ``They
wanted not just a guidebook to the outdoors, but a guidebook to
life.''
</P>
<P>
   So the BSA sounded out volunteers and scouts across the country
and formed a 15-member literary review committee that spent nearly
two years reworking the handbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``This wasn't just a bunch of gray-haired guys sitting in a room
putting a book together,'' says Bob Longoria, an Albuquerque
engineering department manager and scoutmaster who worked on the
revision. ``We got a lot of input from young people.''
</P>
<P>
   The scouts said they wanted the handbook (three-quarters of a
million have been printed) to be more durable, more portable, and
decidedly more readable. So the new version has rounded edges, a
stiffer spine, and thousands fewer words.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want us to give them an encyclopedia,'' says
Setzer. ``They wanted the information brief, right at it. So we've
skinnied it down quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   They've also punched it up graphically for the Wired generation
_ bright colors, sharp graphics, pithy advice boxes that jump off
the page _ and lots of white space, just like the BSA Web site
(www.bsa.scouting.org). It's the millennial handbook for the
21st-century boy.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Baden-Powell, who honed his outdoors skills chasing Boers
across the South African veldt in the Victorian age, knew all about
boxing a compass. But he couldn't have found his way around
cyberspace &UR;  &LR; with the North Star pasted to his forehead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
EXCERPTS FROM THE NEW HANDBOOK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Be prepared,'' the age-old Scout motto, has an updated meaning
for the 21st-century boy. Excerpts from the revised Boy Scout
Handbook:  &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Sexual abuse &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one should live in fear of abuse. You do not have to let
people touch you in ways you find uncomfortable. If you are ever
asked to do something you know is wrong, you have the right to
refuse. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most sexual abuse can be prevented if young people know and
follow these three R's: recognize, resist, and report &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Using the Internet &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Don't respond to messages or Web sites that make you feel
uncomfortable or that you know are meant only for adults. If you
come across information or images that you don't understand, talk
about it with your parent or guardian.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't give out personal information, including your address,
telephone number, photograph, school name or your parents' work
address or telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   _Never agree to meet anyone who has contacted you on-line unless
your parent or guardian comes with you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Caring for younger children &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Keep children out of danger areas.
</P>
<P>
   _Lock the doors. Don't open them for anyone unless you know the
person.
</P>
<P>
   _After the children are in bed, check every half hour to be sure
they are all right.
</P>
<P>
   _Stay awake until a parent or guardian returns &QL; 
 &QL; 
--Drugs
</P>
<P>
   Drugs are chemicals that alter the body's chemistry. When you
are sick, drugs given by a doctor can help you get well.
Unfortunately, many young people use illegal drugs that don't come
from a physician. Marijuana, cocaine and crack, codeine,
depressants, LSD, heroin, inhalants, and steroids have powerful
effects on the mind as well as the body. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
