<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN SANT DRAINS `PSYCHO'; FOX'S SEVEN-YEAR BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The glossies are going quite cuckoo for the new ``Psycho,'' Gus
Van Sant's postmodern appropriation _ uh, replication _ uh,
reproduction _ uh, oh whatever of Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 horror
flick. While most directors are reimagining (read: massacre-ing)
classic movies like ``Diabolique'' or ``Sabrina,'' Van Sant sees
himself taking the Hollywood high road by staying as loyal as
possible to Joseph Stefano's original script and Hitchcock's own
setups. He says his ``Psycho,'' which opens on Friday, is not one
of those cynical remakes, the devilish breed of movie that assures
studio marketing departments of name recognition (Suit No.1: ``I
can just picture the blood-down-the-drain shot in the ads.'' Suit
No.2: ``In bloody color!!'') Van Sant's ``Psycho'' is a service to
filmmakers and audiences, he tells the Dec./Jan.  &UR; Movieline &LR; :
``It's a good thing to reestablish the importance of a work like
`Psycho' or `Citizen Kane.' Why not redo in color a brilliant,
successful film nobody's seeing because it's in black and white?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a remake is a remake is a remake, no? We're in the throes
of a tireless Re-movie Era, where sequels and remakes and now
replicas are easier to produce than riskier new visions. Rather
than revitalize cinema, re-movies erode the public value of, and
taste for, original efforts. Let's face it, Van Sant got a $25
million budget from Universal because his ``Psycho'' is a neat way
to merge Hitchcock's brand-name familiarity with the popularity of
horror-movie series like ``Scream'' and ``I Know What You Did Last
Summer.'' It's bound to be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, Van Sant has made a name for himself as one of the
more personal of American directors with stubbornly unformulaic
films like ``My Own Private Idaho'' and ``Drugstore Cowboy.'' That
he would choose to borrow an entire movie, and introduce the rough
beast of replication to a Hollywood mindset already bent on
duplication, is not a particularly encouraging move. Especially
since his Oscar-winning box-office hit, ``Good Will Hunting,''
gives Van Sant more power than ever to beat back the claws of
studio hawks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Entertainment Weekly  &LR; for Dec. 4 has a good overview of the
making of the movie, and the December  &UR; Interview  &LR; has a superficial
chat with Van Sant. But Movieline's interview is the most
interesting of the ``Psycho'' pieces, with Stephen Rebello, author
of a book on Hitchcock's ``Psycho,'' prompting Van Sant to be
honest by asking some good questions. Rebello also gets Van Sant to
disclose the names of the actors he initially eyed, including
Robert Sean Leonard, Jeremy Davies, Henry Thomas, Matt Damon, Ben
Affleck, and Leonardo DiCaprio (of course), for the Norman Bates
role that finally went to Vince Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GQ  &LR; for December has a profile of Vaughn that portrays him,
like Bates, as not just a little unusual. After marking Vaughn as
one of the new breed of leading men, along with Damon and Affleck,
writer Lucy Kaylin goes out drinking with him, an adventure that
finds Vaughn's voice becoming ``increasingly redneck'' as he
exaggerates the working-class aspects of his youth and spouts on
about America: ``I love this country; I really do. I know she can
be a harsh mistress, but she's my lady, the U.S.A., and I love her
unconditionally.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The saddest cover story of the week, though, goes to  &UR; People &LR; ,
which broke the news that Michael J. Fox has Parkinson's disease. A
TV actor for most of his career, Fox has the sort of special
intimacy with the public that comes from appearing in their homes
once a week or more. Why has Fox, whose ``Spin City'' is waging a
Wednesday night ratings war, finally come forward with the
heart-rending story of his tremors and facial stiffness after seven
years battling the disease? ``This box I had put everything into
kind of expanded to a point where it's difficult to lug around,''
Fox says. ``What's inside the box isn't inhibiting me. It's the box
itself. I think I can help people by talking. I want to help myself
and my family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
