<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TIME IS RIGHT FOR HOLYFIELD, LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don King stood behind a podium at the Parker House for
nearly two hours and did what he does best. He emoted.
</P>
<P>
   King was in Boston as part of a whirlwind trip across America
designed to kick-start the promotion of the heavyweight unification
fight between World Boxing Association-International Boxing
Federation champion Evander Holyfield and his World Boxing Council
counterpart, Lennox Lewis. The hope is that on March 13, those two
will settle once and for all who's the baddest man on the planet,
although King was content to argue that he already knows who that
is.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, he declared it is his man. Knowing King,
regardless of who wins, it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield has proven beyond a doubt he's a believe-it-or-not
Ripley,'' King said of the man he has promoted since Holyfield made
Mike Tyson null and void. ``This is going to be a giant fight
between two giants ready to do battle. It is a fight that will do
giant numbers. Giant numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is why King, Holyfield, Lewis, and their
various associates and business partners were in Boston. It is why
they were in Washington Tuesday as well and New York the day before
that, and why they'll be in Chicago and Los Angeles before the end
of the week. They are in these places to try to ensure that the big
numbers on pay-per-view and at the box office at New York's Madison
Square Garden appear on March 13, as surely as the two champions
will.
</P>
<P>
   This fight, like all prizefights, is about the money first, but
there is something more here. Holyfield agreed to risk all the
hard-earned respect he has won over the past few years for a $20
million payday and the chance to leave boxing in the
not-too-distant future as the undisputed heavyweight champion.
Lewis agreed to accept a mere $9 million for the same opportunity,
knowing that for him, the chance to define himself by such a moment
was fast slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're all done fighting, nobody remembers how much money
you fought for,'' Lewis said while reclining in a small easy chair
outside his hotel room last night. ``They remember your
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a fight like this. I don't know why Holyfield decided
to take the chance and fight me. Maybe he feels he can beat me now.
But it was important for my career to fight him. The others (Tyson,
Riddick Bowe, Michael Moorer, and George Foreman) wouldn't fight
me. If I want to be remembered in boxing, I had to fight one of
these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like I was marching up a hill and there was always an
iron gate in front of me. I've been knocking on it and beating on
it and punching at it. Now, all of a sudden, it's opened. Not
willingly, but it's opened.''
</P>
<P>
   The gate was opened for a fight the boxing public has wanted for
some time now for an assortment of reasons, many of them financial.
Once King lost control of Tyson, there was no longer a reason for
him to hold off Lewis in the knowledge that Holyfield could make
more money against Tyson with less worry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, King's position at Showtime, the cable network that
has broadcast his fights for the past eight years, grew more
tentative once he no longer promoted Tyson, so negotiating a
Holyfield-Lewis fight with Showtime's cable rival, HBO, provided
King with the kind of leverage he has made it his business to
possess through most of the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The same applied to Holyfield. With Tyson suspended and the
titles Holyfield carries having been adequately defended from the
riffraff of the sport already, he found few other obstacles worth
wasting his time on. At this stage of his career, Holyfield has one
aim: He wants to unify the heavyweight title one last time and
retire without losing another fight. To do that, he knew he must
first beat Lewis, which he is pretty well convinced is not akin to
climbing Mount Everest without bottled oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox Lewis is a good fighter,'' Holyfield said, ``but my
goal has always been to be the best, not to share that with
anybody. I appreciate the opportunity Lennox gave me to show size
don't make a difference. The question isn't, will I win? The
question is, how bad am I going to beat him? He has to make a
mistake because I'll make him make a mistake. If he's aggressive,
he'll just go faster.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Lewis, it is obvious that Holyfield is his last, best
hope at boxing immortality, and Lewis was willing to pay a price
for a shot at it, if one considers a $9 million payday paying a
price.
</P>
<P>
   He was willing to take this risk for the same reason Holyfield
is: because he sees no real risk, which is not the same as saying
he sees no danger waiting for him March 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a difficult fight,'' Lewis said. ``I expect we'll
both have some trouble at times, but I had a dream after we signed
for this. I'd won all the belts and had them in front of me. I
picked them all up and pressed them together, and they melted into
one belt. This is my chance. This is my destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, it can't be everybody's destiny to unify the
heavyweight title March 13. On that night, there can be only one
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Plus Don King, of course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
