<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACE IT, PERFECTION IS UNATTAINABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The issue is completely irresolvable, which is not to say that
things can't, and certainly shouldn't, be better.
</P>
<P>
   There will never, ever be satisfaction with professional sports
officials, in this country or any other. (Would you like to be
refereeing a big soccer game in Brazil?) That's never, as in
N-E-V-E-R. Not today. Not tomorrow. Not after the millennium. Not
on the Twelfth of Never.
</P>
<P>
   Never.
</P>
<P>
   We must start with that premise and then we must understand why
that premise will never change. It will never change because people
are fallible and because they are essentially untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, people make mistakes and people will cheat if
given a remote opportunity to do so. Put those two things together
and all the electronic help in the world will not give us perfectly
officiated games.
</P>
<P>
   Ever.
</P>
<P>
   It always amuses me when people forget that all our games are
inherently flawed to some degree. Until very recently, we as a
society silently accepted that fact, even if few of us have ever
articulated it. We accepted that mistakes would be made, that
somebody's got to win and somebody's got to lose, and that, for
better or worse, the refs would always be a part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   But that's all changed now. All of a sudden, we want perfection
from everybody.
</P>
<P>
   It's not good enough to be a good team. You must be a
championship team. It's not good enough to be a very good player.
You've just got to have that ring to validate your greatness.
(Think Charles Barkley and Karl Malone.) It's no longer good enough
for a football coach to win 10 games just about every year and have
his team in the playoffs far more often than not. You've got to win
the Super Bowl. (Think Marty Schottenheimer.)
</P>
<P>
   Officials are very important, and they have a lot to do with the
outcome of almost any game. Take basketball, for example. I have
always believed that an official has the value of a good, if not
necessarily great, player. Officials determine who will play and
how the game will be played, both highly important matters. People
who place officials in a neutral category are simply ignorant. How,
for example, can a home plate umpire not be important? (Think Eric
Gregg and Livan Hernandez, or any plate ump and Tom Glavine.)
</P>
<P>
   Officials are a significant part of the package. You might say
we can't live with 'em and can't live without 'em, with an emphasis
on the latter theory.
</P>
<P>
   Now the spotlight is on NFL officials. Are they really worse
than ever? I seriously doubt it. Colleague Ron Borges raises a very
good point when he cites expansion as having a deleterious effect
on officiating, but I think that is only a minor part of the
current controversy and I respectfully submit an alternative view.
I believe we make far more out of every officiating decision than
we did 20 years ago, not to mention 50 years ago. You think there
weren't debatable calls being made every Sunday when Sammy Baugh,
Bulldog Turner, Crazy Legs Hirsch, Chuck Bednarik, Jim Brown, Big
Daddy Lipscomb, and Bob Lilly played? Dream on.
</P>
<P>
   Society is infinitely more demanding now than it was in times
past. We are infected with an entitlement mentality in every walk
of life. None of us is immune to this thought process in everyday
life, so why should it be any different in our athletic pursuits?
Officials are now being caught in the crossfire for many reasons,
starting with the financial ramifications of so many decisions. At
the base of it all, I believe, is the growing assumption that the
man owes this call to me because, well, I'm me and we're us.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, basketball, hockey, and football _ our clear Big 4
_are all very difficult to administer. Can we all agree on this
basic point? Asking people to be precise to the quarter-inch on
balls and strikes is absurd. Deciding what's allowable contact and
what's not allowable contact under the boards in basketball is
capricious. Making a judgment on the severity of hockey's
minute-by-minute minor mayhem is laughable. Football? When isn't
there holding on a play?
</P>
<P>
   Throw in the fair/foul issue in baseball, the
who-knocked-it-out-of-bounds issue in basketball, the
was-he-in-the-crease-or-wasn't-he issue in hockey, and the one I
consider the granddaddy of all imprecise judgments _ namely,
spotting the football when there has been a 15-body pileup _ and
you've got a recipe for both confusion and error. It's inherent.
There is nothing anyone can do to make these sports easy to
officiate.
</P>
<P>
   These games would be difficult to officiate even if the
participants were scrupulously honest and completely well
intentioned. The opposite is true, as we all know. Even the sainted
Christy Mathewson was never heard to say, ``Mr. Klem, I know you
think that was a strike I just threw, but it seemed to me it was 3
inches outside, so I now ask you to make it a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Or how about this: When was the last time Rev. Reggie White
picked himself up after sacking a quarterback, walked over to the
nearest official, and demanded he be given a penalty because he was
offside?
</P>
<P>
   In the 19th century, baseball games were handled by one umpire.
Players would take advantage of his occasional preoccupation with
other matters to run from first to third straight across the
diamond, skipping the irritating necessity of going to third base
via second. Does anyone doubt they'd still be doing it today if we
had only one overworked official?
</P>
<P>
   The new cry is to make NFL officials full-time employees of the
league. In three decades of professional activity, I have never
heard a more irrelevant proposal. There is one game a week. There
is no justification imaginable to make these people spend six days
to prepare for one game. You'd think they aren't trained. They're
trained, all right. You'd also think they, like Dorothy's
Scarecrow, lacked a brain. An examination of the officiating roster
reveals 13 people with a title of CEO/president/owner/executive
director/chairman of the board and 17 who work or have worked in
academia. That doesn't count the vice presidents, managing
directors, analysts, and the like.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand why the Pete Carrolls of the world think that
since everyone else in the league is employed full-time, it would
dignify the profession if the officials were likewise under
permanent employment, but they are making more out of this than
they should. This is not the time to overreact because of a very,
very unfortunate coin flip _ explain to me how that one would have
been avoided if Phil Luckett, a computer program analyst, had been
a full-time NFL employee _ and a few other regrettable calls have
been scrutinized, rescrutinized, and ultrascrutinized, just because
we can.
</P>
<P>
   Should there be replay? Maybe. OK, probably. (Don't for one
second think replay will be a panacea for any one of these four
sports.) Should all leagues strive at all times to weed out obvious
incompetents among officials? Absolutely. That's simple common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Do anything you want as long as you recognize that all these
enterprises will forever be flawed. There is no such thing as a
perfect game and there is no such thing as a perfect person.
</P>
<P>
   I don't see why these things are so difficult to understand.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
