<HEADLINE>
HOLY CROSS HAS ITS EYE ON TOURNAMENT PRIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since Holy Cross is hosting the fourth annual ECAC women's
basketball holiday tournament this weekend, the team is trying hard
to forget Monday's loss to the University of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to press and will probably try to do on a smaller
scale what Connecticut did to us,'' said coach  &UR; Bill Gibbons  &LR; of
the 107-56 defeat that left the Crusaders 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross's opponent in the opener Saturday at 1 p.m. is Rider,
which is 2-1 in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference. Seton Hall
(2-3), which finished fifth in the Big East last year, faces Brown
(2-2) at 3 p.m. The consolation and championship games will be
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   All the games will be at Holy Cross's Hart Center. ``So it's
definitely on our agenda to win it this year,'' Gibbons said. ``We
want to win on our home turf.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross has hosted the tournament for the past two years,
finishing second both times.
</P>
<P>
   The Crusaders are led by 6-foot-1-inch forward  &UR; Amy O'Brien  &LR; of
Worcester, a hometown favorite as well as the top returning scorer
in the country (26.1 points per game) and Patriot League Player of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's our go-to player, then we have two solid guards who
always make something happen,'' said Gibbons, referring to  &UR; Anne
Kinne &LR;  and  &UR; Lara Marcsisin &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Rider features a fast-break, 3-point-oriented attack led by
guard  &UR; Iris Beistline &LR; , who connected on 66 threes last season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is led by senior guards  &UR; Vita Redding  &LR; and  &UR; Julie Amato &LR; 
and forward  &UR; Kate Veronneau &LR; , who was 1996-97 Ivy Rookie of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall is a young team with just two returning players _ 6-2
forward  &UR; Danielle Davis  &LR; and 6-1 forward  &UR; Starr Fuller &LR; , who
graduated from Jeremiah E. Burke High School in Boston. Fuller has
had two double-doubles this year and is the team's leading
rebounder with 7.8 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, priced at $6 for adults and $3 for students, and can be
purchased the day of the game or by calling 508-793-2573.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wellesley in Final Four
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley volleyball coach  &UR; Dorothy Webb  &LR; has conflicting
feelings going into the NCAA Final Four Division 3 semifinals this
weekend. She's excited, but with trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley, which cruised to a 36-0 rec-ord this season, has not
lost a match since bowing to Wisconsin in last year's NCAA
quarterfinals. The school's first opponent in the Final Four, which
begins Friday at Juniata College in Huntington, Pa., is Central
College (35-2) of Pella, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very strong,'' Webb said, ``much stronger than
any of the teams we've seen this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The average height on Wellesley's team is 5-8. Webb estimates
that the Central College women average 5-11.
</P>
<P>
   Wellesley is led by a trio of Regional All-Americans: senior
 &UR; Katy &LR;   &UR; Antypas &LR;  and juniors  &UR; Tiffany Fehr  &LR; and  &UR; Allison &LR; 
 &UR; Schnitzer &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Even though the team has been practicing, it hasn't played a
game since it beat SUNY-Cortland the weekend before last. ``So I
think we're really ready to play,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Wellesley faces Central College at 5 p.m. and Juniata
squares off against California-San Diego at 8. The championship
game is Saturday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
