<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF OFFICIAL EMPHASIZES PERSPECTIVE IN BAD CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an annual event, and one that Jerry Seeman does not look
forward to.
</P>
<P>
   Seeman is senior director of officiating in the National
Football League, and experience tells him that, for at least one
week every year, the bottom falls out with questionable calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going good until last week,'' Seeman said softly,
sounding like a guy who had just been hit by a bus. ``You just hope
it continued the way it was going, and then we hit Week 13.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point his voice trailed off, as if he were dreaming
about what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Then he added, ``Really, it's always just about three or four
plays a week, out of 2,300 plays, that turn the whole thing. But
when they are big plays, in big games, and mistakes are made, that
is ultimately my responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeman would not address directly the controversial calls in the
Patriots-Bills game or the embarrassing coin flip mistake made on
national television Thanksgiving Day in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we had problems in New England and Detroit and they
will be addressed,'' said Seeman. ``We have already changed the way
the coin flip will be done in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember here that these officials are human
beings. They are going to make mistakes. On some plays, it is just
impossible to pick up what happened because they go so fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about 15 games a week for all these weeks and you are
bound to miss some. We'd like to take back those four or five plays
each week. But we can't. We have to live with them. That's the
price you pay when you put on a striped shirt in this league. We
all have to deal with the big picture.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a cluster of controversial calls last week.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, it was the coin toss before overtime, when the
referee misunderstood the call made by Jerome Bettis and errantly
gave the ball to Detroit, which marched down the field to kick the
winning field goal.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, the Bills appeared to have a victory taken away
from them by two calls at the end of the game _ a completion to
Shawn Jefferson that appeared to be out of bounds, and a pass
interference penalty during a Hail Mary play as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   There also was outrage over questionable calls in the
Oilers-Seahawks game at Seattle, and the Cardinals-Chiefs game at
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In every instance, critical decisions went in favor of the home
team.
</P>
<P>
   This has triggered a demand for full-time NFL game officials by
many in the sports media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We visited that three or four years ago,'' said Seeman.
Tuesday ``The league set up the Shula Committee to study it. We had
Don Shula, Chuck Noll, Harry Gamble, George Young, myself, and the
commissioner all involved. The consensus was against full-time
officials. We decided that whether the officials are full-time or
not, it is not going to help them making a lightning-quick judgment
call the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our emphasis has been on training and educating, finding ways
for our officials to do the best possible job under some tough
circumstances. We have quality officials doing these jobs. They are
well-trained, and well-prepared. And they are dedicated. But it
seems like every year one of these weeks is going to happen, and it
happened last week.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bills owner Ralph Wilson was still furious over what happened to
his team in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am more upset about that game in New England than I was
about all four of our Super Bowl losses,'' said Wilson. ``I really
mean that. In the Super Bowls, we were beaten by the other team. In
New England, the officials took the game away from us. We deserved
to win that game, and we didn't get it. I don't know what to do
about it, but I am going to do something. We can't let something
like that happen again to any team. Things much change.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steelers coach Bill Cowher is putting the coin flip controversy
behind him and focusing on the Patriots, who visit Pittsburgh
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish the league would say they made a mistake, and then
get on with it,'' said Cowher. ``Then it would be all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lost a couple of games lately that we are not used to
losing. Our history is that we win the close games. Then in the
last month, we lost a couple of games that we had the lead going
into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I'm pleased with the way our team is playing. I mean
that. I told our team to just keep playing the way we are, and not
get distracted (by losing two tough ones) and we'll start to win.
Offensively, we've had our opportunities and squandered them. Like
the Patriots, we've had some injuries and lost some continuity. But
we're getting some people back and that will help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with Jerome Bettis. Some of the problem
with our running game is inconsistency in the offensive line but we
feel like we will play better. Our defense has been solid, our
kicking game good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it. Right now Denver is off in a league of their
own someplace. The rest of us are in a wild scramble to see if we
can win the division or get a wild card spot. Jacksonville, us, New
England, the Jets, the Bills, Miami, it's up for grabs. That's what
I told the team. Because we are all playing each other in these
final four games, all of us have our own destiny in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowher remembers his team winning two tough defensive games
against the Patriots at the close of last season, and he expects
the same kind of game in Three Rivers Stadium this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like their defense,'' said Cowher. ``Ty Law is having
a Pro Bowl year. Ted Johnson and Lawyer Milloy are both
exceptional. I'm really impressed by this Chad Eaton kid in the
middle of that defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, Ben Coates and Terry Glenn are both big weapons.
It seems like our games against the Patriots are always tough, and
come right down to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
