u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BOOKS-2TAKES-     12-02 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BOOKS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DELUGE OF STYLE BOOKS CATERS TO ALL TASTES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Astronauts work and live inside cramped, high-tech
space capsules packed with computers and controls. But their houses
on Earth can look like Southern plantations, Arts &AMP; Crafts
bungalows, even French chateaux.
</P>
<P>
   One might live in a converted warehouse loft and fill it with a
mix of machine-modern and flea-market finds. Another might choose a
high-rise apartment stylishly decorated with antiques and Oriental
rugs. Never in our history has interior design been so diverse, so
ready to take the best of the past, blend it with the present and
embrace the future.
</P>
<P>
   The deluge of new design books this season reflects these
wide-ranging interests. No matter what style you favor, whether you
are interested in history or decorating advice, there's probably a
book about it. To review the best of the new books, we have divided
them into five categories: decorating insight, styles, small
spaces, design history and cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Decorating insight &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do some people insist on neat, tidy rooms, while other
people tend to pile their stuff all over tables, chairs and floors?
Why do some folks crave airy rooms with curtainless windows, while
others are more comfortable in cozy quarters with cushions and
drapery all around?''
</P>
<P>
   Because, explains Judy George in her excellent new book, ``The
Domain Book of Intuitive Home Design'' (Clarkson Potter, $30), we
tend to decorate according to our personality types. George, an
interior designer who created and runs 23 Domain stores on the East
Coast, identifies four personality profiles and explains each one.
</P>
<P>
   A quiz lets the reader decide if he is a Visionary, an Artisan,
an Idealist or an Adventurer, or perhaps a blend of two. George
says that while the book offers decorating ideas, images and
inspiration, ``it also seeks to promote understanding of ourselves
and others ... ultimately, to empower readers to create home
environments that cradle their true selves.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one design book you'll want to read, discuss and share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open Your Eyes _ 1,000 Simple Ways to Bring Beauty Inside Your
Home &AMP; Life'' (William Morrow, $28) is interior designer Alexandra
Stoddard's 20th book. It tells the reader how to enhance visual
awareness and create a home reflecting individual tastes and sense
of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homestyling: Contrasts in Design'' by Mike Strohl (PBC
International Inc., $19.95) shows a wide variety of excellent
interior photographs and explains the theories and execution of the
designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feng Shui Design: The Art of Creating Harmony for Interiors,
Landscape and Architecture'' by Sarah Rossbach and Master Lin Yun
(Viking, $29.95) may be the best yet on feng shui (pronounced
``fung shway''), combining history and modern practicality with
charts, graphics and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Styles &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are drawn to the charm of country French style and the
warmth of English decorating. Two new books offer in-depth looks
and ample advice on how to create them in your own home.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Provenal Interiors: French Country Style in America''
(Gibbs Smith, $39.95), interior designer Betty Lou Phillips, a
former Houston resident, uses her seasoned expertise to explain why
she considers this style understated luxury at its finest. The
photographs demonstrate how many designers have re-created it in
American homes. The book provides an extensive resource list, with
a number of Houston firms included.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl MacLachlan takes us step-by-step through inviting English
interiors, from overstuffed chintz sofas to vibrant colors and dark
woods, in ``Bringing It Home: England'' (Clarkson Potter, $40). The
Idea Notebook ending each chapter gives simple suggestions for
decorating the English way, and history boxes provide background on
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   If neither French nor English is your look, here are more books
to tug at your style inclinations:
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco Modern: Interiors, Architecture &AMP; Design'' by
Zahid Sardar and J.D. Peterson (Chronicle Books, $40) _ a tour of
32 residences from opulent Russian Hill flats to funky studios _ is
a treat for anyone with modern taste.
</P>
<P>
   Two books that celebrate today's penchant for furnishings that
reflect another age are ``Flea Market Style: Decorating With a
Creative Edge'' by Emelie Tolley and Chris Mead (Clarkson Potter,
$30) and ``At Home With the Past: How the Love of Old Things
Creates Beautiful Interiors'' by Steve Gross and Sue Daley
(Clarkson Potter, $40). &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
