u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALCOHOL-VENDING-HNS &LR;      12-02 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOL-VENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RULES ALCOHOL VENDING MACHINES ILLEGAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE OLAFSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Beer drinkers in Texas will have to keep getting their
brews the old-fashioned way after a state attorney general's
opinion declaring that high-tech vending machines that dispense
booze are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The legal opinion, sought by the administrator of the Texas
Alcoholic Beverage Commission, means that adult beverage machines
that had been placed at private golf courses in the Dallas area
will have to be removed.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had agreed in June to allow installation of the
machines, but a state representative and an official with Mothers
Against Drunk Driving protested the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Their protest was based on the state's Alcoholic Beverage Code,
which states that coin-operated machines or ``similar devices'' may
not be used to sell alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   An Oklahoma City company had argued that its machines, which
dispense drinks when a customer enters a personal identification
number, are not covered by the statute.
</P>
<P>
   The state Alcoholic Beverage Commission sought the attorney
general's opinion after state Rep. Scott Hochberg, D-Texas, and
Vena Cronin, a Houston MADD activist, complained that the agency
was attempting to legislate liquor laws without public involvement
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office, in a Nov. 13 opinion,
agreed with Hochberg and Cronin, stating that it is ``patently
obvious'' that adult beverage machines are similar to coin-operated
machines, and thus prohibited. Hochberg and Cronin, who had feared
the machines could lead to illegal sales to minors, said they are
happy with the attorney general's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the A.G. made an obvious decision in an obvious case
that was obvious to everybody but the TABC,'' Hochberg said
Tuesday. ``It was pretty clear to me what the law said.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cronin: ``We don't need TABC legislating laws that could be
potential problems.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
