<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-BOOKS-2NDTAKE     12-02 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-BOOKS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION-BOOKS-2NDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  HOUSTON: Potter, $40). 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judith Miller's Classic Style (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35) is a
visual feast of sophisticated, sometimes surprising traditional
design in the 1990s, preceded by a smartly executed chapter on
history to set the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Those with a passion for the primitive should take a look at
``Rustic Style'' by Ralph Kylloe (Abrams, $39.95), a broad study of
rustic American design, with interiors from Maine to California,
decorating ideas and a resource list. Also ``Adirondack Style'' by
Ann Stillman O'Leary (Clarkson Potter, $37.50), a closeup look at
the rustic New York State playground of the urban elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexican Color'' by Amanda Holmes and Elena Poniatowska
(Stewart Tabori &AMP; Chang, $35) and ``Mexicolor: The Spirit of
Mexican Design'' by Melba Levick, Tony Cohan and Masako Takahasi
(Chronicle Books, $24.95) use glorious photographs to convey the
compelling architecture, textiles and decorative objects of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Small spaces &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How to live well in limited space is a perennial design topic.
Of course, for some ``limited'' means 900 square feet, and for
others 3,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Not So Big House: A Blueprint for the Way We Really
Live'' (Taunton Books, $30) architect Sarah Susanka explores
common-sense residential design. The smaller home, Susanka
explains, lets us simplify our lives and beautify our space rather
than taxing our energies with high maintenance. If you're building
or buying a new home or considering remodeling, this book offers a
lot to think about.
</P>
<P>
   Two more books devoted to compact quarters are ``Designing for
Small Homes'' by Dylan Landis (PBC International Inc., $34.95) and
``House Beautiful: Small Spaces'' (Hearst Books, $30).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Design history &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arts &AMP; Crafts design resurfaced in 1988 when Barbra Streisand
paid an astounding $363,000 at auction for a 1903 Gustav Stickley
sideboard. Interest in the furniture and architecture of the early
20th-century movement keeps growing stronger.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome new book, ``Greene &AMP; Greene Masterworks'' by Bruce
Smith and Alexander Vertikoff (Chronicle Books, $40) surveys the
greatest California houses of architects Charles and Henry Greene,
built mostly between 1903 and 1911. This closeup look at joinery,
woodwork and other details, as well as interiors and exteriors,
will thrill Arts &AMP; Crafts Movement enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Form &AMP; Decoration: Innovation in the Decorative Arts,
1470-1870'' by Peter Thornton (Abrams, $39.95) eloquently surveys
four centuries of Western design, from motifs to styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Public and Private Worlds of Elizabeth I'' by Susan
Watkins and Mark Fiennes (Thames and Hudson, $40) gives an engaging
portrait of the remarkable 16th-century English queen by studying
the Elizabethan homes, portraits, paintings, tapestries and
personal objects of the period.
</P>
<P>
   Francophiles will relish two beautiful new volumes: ``Treasures
of the French Renaissance: Architecture, Sculpture, Painting,
Drawings'' by Ivan Cloulas, Michele Bimbenet-Privat and Serge
Chirol (Abrams, $49.50) and ``Mansions of Paris'' by Olivier Blanc
and Joachim Bonnemaison (Terrail, $27.50).
</P>
<P>
   ``Williamsburg: Decorating With Style'' by Tricia Foley (Crown,
$30) translates the beauty of Colonial Williamsburg to today's
interiors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuscany Interiors'' by Paolo Rinaldi (Taschen, $39.99) gives
us an intimate tour of the picturesque Italian region and its
residences, both grand and modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Shaker Legacy: Perspectives on an Enduring Furniture
Style'' by Christian Becksvoort (Taunton Books, $40) explains how
Shaker belief inspired the simple, beautiful furniture still
influencing design today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Design in the Fifties: When Everyone Went Modern'' by George
H. Marcus (Prestel, $29.95) defines the tastes and hopes of a
country emerging from the war years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cultural history &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The study of houses and their furnishings over the centuries can
be a much more enjoyable way to learn history than memorizing dates
or the names of battles. Three books give new slants on this
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``House'' by illustrator Albert Lorenz (Abrams, $17.95) is a
visually wonderful and verbally concise overview of how people have
lived around the world. The intricate drawings, complete with
cutaway perspectives and closeup details, go from Egyptian pyramids
and Roman houses to midcentury mass housing and the Russian space
station Mir.
</P>
<P>
   Homes of the famous, such as Thomas Jefferson and Claude Monet,
are explored _ even the fictional London town house of Sherlock
Holmes. ``House'' is a delightful book for adults and a captivating
way for children to absorb cultural history.
</P>
<P>
   Lecturer and author Myrna Kaye can get so excited over a
marvelous piece of furniture, it's no wonder she finds studying
historical interiors a way to learn how people lived and who they
were. In ``There's a Bed in the Piano: The Inside Story of the
American Home'' (Bulfinch Press, $38.50), Kaye shows us how to
``read'' rooms and furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Old etchings and photographs with family and guests, in parlors
or around dining tables, visually describe their tastes and
traditions. As the title suggests, there's a photo of a circa 1870
upright piano whose front pulls down, revealing a fold-out bed _
definitely an entertaining space-saver.
</P>
<P>
   More recent design history is relished and often ripped apart in
``Your World ... and Welcome to It: A Rogue's Gallery of Interior
Design'' by Patrick Mauries with hilarious illustrations by fashion
designer Christian Lacroix (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Picking apart the fashionable trends and questionable fads, the
authors start with 1960s ``Horizontal Modern,'' work their way
through ``Disco Deco'' in the '70s and ``Be Still, My Chintz'' in
the '80s (Colefax &AMP; Fowler English country), to today's ``Junk
Junkies'' (``decoration addicts'' searching for the ``decrepit,
rickety, scratched, if not downright dubious''). Nothing is sacred.
Sometimes references are too insider for most of us, but it's
wicked, fun reading. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
