<HEADLINE>
CULINARY FINDS ARE A PHONE CALL AWAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It wouldn't be the holidays without some specialty
foods and mail-order products that have become traditions through
the years _ Mrs. Travis Hanes' Moravian cookies, pecan cakes and
fruitcakes from Mary of Puddin Hill and handmade pralines from
Evelyn LeBlanc of Abbeville, La. Alas, we received a letter from
LeBlanc recently saying she has retired from making pralines.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are some foods, including a few new items, to
brighten holiday tables and gift baskets. Here are some of the Food
editor's favorites:
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Travis Hanes' Moravian cookies are paper-thin, hand-rolled,
hand-cut and hand-packed cookies. They come in round and heart
shapes and are available in six flavors: sugar, ginger,
butterscotch, lemon, chocolate and black walnut. Mrs. Hanes' makes
about 100,000 pounds of cookies a year; that translates to about 10
million cookies.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-pound tin (100 cookies) is $15; 2-pound, $25; and set of two
8-ounce tubes, $15. Call 888-764-1402 for charge orders, or fax
888-764-4072. Hours are 6 a.m.-4 p.m. Monday-Friday and 7 a.m.-3
p.m. Saturday. Make checks or money orders payable to Mrs. Travis
F. Hanes and send to 4643 Friedberg Church Road, Clemmons, N.C.
27012-9506. Or access www.hanescookies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie Island cookies are baked fresh daily from natural
ingredients, presented in rough-cut pine boxes and shipped by FedEx
so they arrive while still moist and fresh. A favorite is Oatmeal
Raisin, but other flavors also are scrumptious _ Original Chocolate
Chip Oats, Chocolate Chip Oats with macadamias, Peanut Butter
Chocolate Chip, White Chocolate Macadamia and Chocolate Chocolate
Chip Coconut, to name a few. The 12 varieties of plump gooey
cookies are Kosher certified. Happy Holidays boxes are available
with 12, 24, 48 or 64 cookies; prices range from $22.50 to $44 plus
shipping. The Exam-Cram Box makes a welcome gift for students
facing finals and midterms.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie Island contributes a percentage of all pretax profits to
the Webb International Center for Dyslexia, a foundation to aid
learning disabled and dyslexic students. It was founded in 1990 by
Cookie Island president Billy Baldwin. Call 888-266-5434 or access
the Internet site (www.cookieisland.com).
</P>
<P>
   Cakes from Mary of Puddin Hill (celebrating its 50th
anniversary) are a holiday tradition. The Pecan Fruit Cake with
loads of pecans, cherries, dates and pineapple in a light batter is
a favorite. The recipe came from Great-Grandmother Mary Horton.
Walnut Fruit Cake and Apricot Fruit Cake are other specialties. The
1 {-pound Pecan Fruit Cake loaf and Apricot Fruit Cake are $26.50
each; walnut is $25.50. Call 800-545-8889.
</P>
<P>
   Willow River Fruitcake: These nut-filled cakes made at Willow
River Farms are gaining favor with many people who disdain the
usual fruitcake. Traditional Fruitcake is packed with red and green
cherries, pecans, dates, walnuts and coconut. The Brandied Fruit
and Nut Cake, filled with dried fruit and nuts and laced with
brandy, appeals to those who usually avoid fruitcake.
</P>
<P>
   Cakes are made by volunteers and residents at Willow River
Farms, part of the Center for the Retarded in Houston, which
receives all the proceeds. Willow River Farms is a community of
adults with developmental disabilities. The cakes can be shipped
all over the world. They also are available at Rice Epicurean
Markets.
</P>
<P>
   A 1-pound cake is $10 plus $3 shipping and handling; 2-pound,
$18 plus $5 shipping; and 3-pound, $27 plus $6 shipping. Call
713-525-8468 or 800-939-3720. Houston-area residents can fax
713-525-8465. Shoppers also can access the company's Internet site
(www.fruitcakes.org).
</P>
<P>
   Eilenberger's of Palestine's (Texas) version of the
nontraditional fruitcake is Texas Pecan Cake. The honey-sweetened
batter is filled with Texas pecans, pineapple, dates and red
cherries. A 2-pound gift box is $14.95; 3-pound, $21.95; and
4{-pound, $30.95; plus shipping. Call 800-831-2544 or fax
903-723-2915. Deadline for Christmas orders is Dec. 9. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rowena's cakes _ Coconut Pound Cake, Luscious Lemon Pound Cake
with Raspberry Curd and Almond Pound Cake with Lemon Curd _ are
classics. Island Kissed Key Lime Pound Cake with Key Lime Curd is
new. Cakes are 44 ounces; prices range from $26 to $30. From the
Rowena catalog, which features genuine Virginia hams. Call
800-980-CAKE.
</P>
<P>
   Michael's Bakery cakes _ Anne's Applesauce Holiday Cake made
with Gravenstein apples, cinnamon and nuts has no eggs, no
cholesterol and no preservatives. The moist Applesauce Holiday Cake
also is featured in this year's Neiman Marcus Savor mail-order
catalog. Michael's Bakery of Millville, Calif., makes these moist,
home-style cakes. Call 800-449-CAKE for orders and prices. Deadline
for Christmas delivery is Dec. 21. Shoppers also can access
Michael's Internet site (www.michaelsbakery.com).
</P>
<P>
   Great cheesecake is only a phone call away from Junior's of
Brooklyn. Junior's, famed for its deli sandwiches, blintzes and
skyscraper desserts since 1950, offers 10 flavors, including Apple
Crumb Cheesecake (tart apples, raisins, cinnamon, streusel crumb
topping), Cherry Crumb, Raspberry Swirl, Chocolate Malted and
Brownie Marble Swirl. Seasonal favorites range from pumpkin to
Black Forest Cheesecake loaded with Black Forest cherries, Meyer's
rum and a chocolate sponge cake base. For cheesecake without guilt,
order the Fat Free Cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   A standard 8-inch, 3-pound cake can be shipped anywhere in the
continental United States for $27.95 plus shipping and handling.
Rugelach also is available (2 pounds, $24.95). Call 800-958-6467.
</P>
<P>
   Goode Co. Barbeque Hall of Flame _ Houston knows Goode Co.'s
barbecue, jalapeno cheese bread and Grandma Goode's Brazos Bottom
Pecan Pie firsthand. But with the Goode Co. catalog, you can send
sauces, barbecue gear, pie and other goodies from the Goode Co.
Hall of Flame to outlanders and fans of Goode Co. barbecue. The
four-spice gift box includes four jars of Jim Goode's special blend
of dry spices ($14.95). D.J. Special combines three flavors of
Goode Co.'s BBQ Sauce and four bottles of dry spices ($29.95). An
8-inch pecan pie, packaged with a miniature Texas flag and two
country music cassettes, is $39.95.
</P>
<P>
   The catalog features other food items, barbecue tools, gloves
and smoker boxes, Russell Harrington knives, grills, caps, aprons
and decorative items. For mail orders, call 800-627-3502.
</P>
<P>
   For fine tea and gifts by mail, consult the Bigelow Mail Order
Catalog. Favorites include a walnut tea chest, traditional and herb
tea assortments, teapots and an Herbal Garden Tea Service with
botanical florals scattered on a white porcelain background. Prices
range from $11.95 for a 64-bag assortment to $44.95 for a stocked
Walnut Tea Chest to $110 for a Jenaer Glas loose tea teapot.
Bigelow is celebrating its 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite is the Lemon Lovers Basket with lemon cake, cookies,
lemon drops, teas, a mug, honey straws and tea bag holder. It's
$29.95 plus shipping. We also liked the Mary Engelbreit teapots and
the Tea Notes Gift Pack of notecards with 16 tea bags. The gift
pack, a cloth-covered keepsake box with teapot motif, is $21.95.
Call 888-BIGELOW or access its Internet site (www.bigelowtea.com). &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
