<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8940 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS-3TA     12-02 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS-3TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF FLAVORS: HOLIDAY COOKBOOKS RANGE FROM BASIC TO EXOTIC 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ There's a cookbook for everyone this season, whether
you can't boil water or, with a few hours' notice, can prepare a
feast fit for a king. Big and small, general and specific, lavishly
illustrated or not, homespun or sophisticated, this year's books
cover a world of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   The crop of fall books for review has been piling up in the Food
editor's office for months _ recently 22 books arrived on one day.
There are books on chitlins, chocolate, tomatoes, bread, baking,
simple soups and three-ingredient recipes, as well as cookbooks by
celebrities, including semiautobiographical books such as Sophia
Loren's ``Recipes &AMP; Memories'' (GT Publishing, $28). Others include
vegetarian recipes, salsa variations and ideas for healthful
cooking (low-fat, low-cholesterol, low-sodium, low-carbohydrate,
high-fiber).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   International &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those with a taste for international fare will find inspiration
in ``My Mexico'' by the doyenne of authentic Mexican cooking, Diana
Kennedy (Clarkson Potter, $32.50); ``Rosa Mexicano'' by Josefina
Howard (Viking, $29.95), a culinary autobiography with 60 recipes
from the owner of one of the best Mexican restaurants in New York;
``Simple Menus for the Bento Box'' by Ellen Greaves and Wayne Nish
(Morrow, $25), recipes for the Japanese lunch box (bento) that is a
hot item on the West Coast; and ``Cooking at the Kasbah'' by Kitty
Morse (Chronicle Books, $22.95), recipes from Morse's Moroccan
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``Julie Sahni's Introduction to Indian Cooking'' (Ten
Speed Press, $16.95); ``Simple Italian Food: Recipes from My Two
Villages'' by TV Food Network star Mario Batali (Clarkson Potter,
$30); and ``Dolci Toscani: The Book of Tuscan Desserts'' by Anne
Bianchi and Sandra Lotti (Ecco Press, $28.95).
</P>
<P>
   Lee Bailey, author of nine best-selling food books, including
``Country Weekends'' and ``Lee Bailey's New Orleans,'' covers
Tuscany, Gascony, the Greek Isles, St. Barth's and New York in this
revised edition of ``Cooking for Friends'' from Gramercy Books
($30). The photography is by Tom Eckerle.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For beginners &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps these are more your speed: ``The Complete Idiot's Guide
to Cooking Basics'' by Ronnie Fein (Alpha Books, $18.95); ``Cooking
For Dummies'' (IDG Books, $19.99); ``The Absolute Beginner's
Cookbook or How Long Do I Cook a 3-Minute Egg?'' by Jackie Eddy and
Eleanor Clark (Prima Publishing, $8.95); and ``How to Cook
Everything'' by Mark Bittman (Macmillan, $25). And you can't go
wrong with Betty Crocker, whose latest is ``Betty Crocker's Cooking
Basics: Learning to Cook with Confidence'' (Macmillan, $19.95).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upscale cooking &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More adept culinarians may wish to check out ``Taste'' by David
Rosengarten (Random House, $29.95); ``Saveur Cooks Authentic
American'' (Chronicle Books, $40); and ``Seductions of Rice'' by
Jeffrey Alford and Naomi Duguid (Artisan, $35). ``Saveur'' includes
the recipe for Real Texas Chili from Houstonian Carter Rochelle.
</P>
<P>
   For a new slant on Texas cooking, acclaimed chef Stephan Pyles,
a native Texan and one of the pioneers of Southwestern cuisine, has
written ``New Tastes From Texas'' (Clarkson Potter, $18.95). It
accompanies his public television series of the same name. The
recipe for Grilled Snapper with accompaniments follows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African-American cooking &QL;
</P>
<P>
   African, African-American and soul food cookbooks also were big
this year. Consider: ``Ideas for Entertaining from the
African-American Kitchen'' by Angela Shelf Medearis (Plume,
$14.95), with recipes and traditions for holidays throughout the
year; ``The Book of North African Cooking'' by Lesley Mackley (HP
Books, $12), with a color photo and preparation photos of each
recipe; and ``Soul Food'' by Joyce White, a solid book of recipes
and reflections from African-American churches (HarperCollins,
$25).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables and vegetarian &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This was the year for vegetable and vegetarian cookbooks,
including the slick ``Hot Vegetables'' by Hugh Carpenter &AMP; Teri
Sandison (Ten Speed Press, $17.95). As usual (this is the fifth in
the ``Hot'' series), Sandison's mouthwatering photographs tempt you
to try such unusual dishes as Roasted Beet Salad With Fresh
Mozzarella Cheese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mollie Katzen's Vegetable Heaven'' (Hyperion, $27.50) is the
latest book from acclaimed chef and public television cook Mollie
Katzen, author of ``Moosewood Cookbook'' and ``The Enchanted
Broccoli Forest.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Cadwallader, author of more than 10 cookbooks and a
nationally syndicated food columnist, tenders simple recipes in
``Easy Vegetarian Cooking'' (Nitty Gritty, $8.95). Tofu is balanced
with a lot of delicious dishes featuring beans, mushrooms,
eggplant, grits, polenta and rice. ``Fresh Vegetables'' by Rose
Grant (Nitty Gritty, $8.95) offers fresh ideas on seasonal
vegetable dishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Occasional Vegetarian'' by Karen Lee with Diane Porter
(Warner Books, $15.99) takes a fresh look at recipes for part-time,
as well as full-time, vegetarians. ``Great American Vegetarian'' by
Nava Atlas (Evans, $24.95) offers traditional and regional recipes,
from Virginia Peanut Soup to New England Blueberry Cake. Atlas also
has written several vegetarian cookbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fresh From a Monastery Garden'' by Brother Victor-Antoine
d'Avila-Latourrette (Doubleday, $25) is ``an A-to-Z treasury of
delectable vegetable recipes,'' from Artichoke Ragout and Broccoli
Flans to Peach-Zucchini Chutney.
</P>
<P>
   A hot new topic, phytopia or plant-centered cuisine, is explored
in ``the phytopia cookbook'' (LOWERCASE CQ) by Barbara Gollman and
Kim Pierce (Phytopia Inc., $17.98). Phytopia is a word coined from
combining phyto, the Greek word for plant, with utopia. These Texas
authors examine the importance of phytochemicals (including
antioxidants such as beta carotene and vitamin C) and list the
Phytopia Top 10, some of the most powerful or promising phyto
foods: broccoli, oranges, garlic, kale, soybeans, green tea, red
wine, onions, brussels sprouts and tomatoes. Gollman, a spokeswoman
for the American Dietetic Association, did the nutrition analysis
for each recipe.
</P>
<P>
   There are 80 ``completely meat-free'' recipes in ``Babe's
Country Cookbook'' by Dewey Gram (GT Publishing, $19.95). The
porcine star of the Academy Award-winning film gives us a Babe's
eye view of the Hoggett family kitchen. And Babe seems to have
gourmet taste, touting such upscale dishes as Apricot Coffee Cake
With Streusel Filling; Warm Linguini With Fresh Tomato, Balsamic
Vinegar and Parmigiano Reggiano; and Ferdie's Chocolate Bread
Pudding.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Specialty books &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Specialty books that deserve a spot on your cookbook shelf
include:
</P>
<P>
   ``Florence Henderson's Short-Cut Cooking''(Morrow, $19.95). Good
short-cut tips with each appealing recipe, from Favorite Beef
Stroganoff to Quick Chocolate Mousse, from former TV mom Henderson,
who played Carol Brady on ``The Brady Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Memorable Meals'' by San Antonio cooking teacher and hostess
Nancy Wood Moorman (Eakin Press, $22.95). Moorman has taught
classes in Houston at Rice Epicurean Market Cooking School and has
had several autographing sessions here. She studied in Europe, as
well as in San Francisco, with several notable chefs. Traditions of
South Texas ranch cooking and Mexican cuisine are combined with
European influences in more than 180 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Smokehouse Ham, Spoon Bread, &AMP; Scuppernong Wine''
(Cumberland House, $19.95), Joseph E. Dabney offers a look at the
people, food and customs of the Appalachian Mountains, from pioneer
days to the present. It's an intriguing glimpse into the culture
where corn likker, clabber cheese, hand-churned butter, sausage and
mush, fried apples and molasses gingerbread were common. There are
modern, kitchen-friendly recipes for Crock-Pot Brunswick Stew,
Grits Souffle and No-Mix Blackberry Cobbler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pillsbury Best Desserts'' (Clarkson Potter, $24.95). Your
favorites are sure to be found in this collection, the first
all-dessert book from Pillsbury. Polish your skills by reading the
opening chapter on dessert basics. There's a chapter on cheesecakes
and others on cakes, frosting, pies and tarts and sauces. The
chapter on BAKE-OFF (CQ) Desserts includes such favorites as Topsy
Turvy Apple Pie from 1951 and the first $1 million winner,
Macadamia Fudge Torte.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nick Malgieri, director of the baking program at Peter Kump's
New York Cooking School, was in Houston last week to teach classes
at Le Panier cooking school, owned by LaVerl Daily. He shared
recipes from his latest book, ``Chocolate: From Simple Cookies to
Extravagant Showstoppers'' (HarperCollins, $35). Chocolate lovers
will relate to the renowned baker and pastry chef, who once rushed
home to try a brownie recipe he found on an index card on the
street near his apartment. The only dilemma: which chocolate
creation to choose for a holiday party _ Chocolate Raspberry
Bavarian Cake, Buche de Noel (Christmas Log), Texas Sheet Cake,
Bittersweet Chocolate Crme Brle or Mexican Chocolate Pudding. One
solution? Choose one of each for a dessert party. The Chocolate
Basics chapter is particularly useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Chocolate'' (Chronicle, $22.95). Elaine Gonzales, a
Chicago teacher and author of several other books on chocolate,
worked with photographer Frankie Frankeny on this beautiful and
useful book of techniques. It includes recipes for cakes, desserts
and confections such as truffles. Chocolate lovers of an artistic
bent will appreciate Gonzales' creations: chocolate leaves,
flowers, cups, baskets and boxes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
