A8945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS-3RD     12-02 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS-3RDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY-COOKBOOKS-3RDTAKE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  HOUSTON: and boxes. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All About Chocolate'' by Carole Bloom (Macmillan, $17). This
lives up to its subtitle, ``The Ultimate Resource for the World's
Favorite Food,'' with the who-what-when-where-why of chocolate plus
25 recipes, from Chocolate Nut Biscotti to Chocolate Espresso Pots
de Creme. The book also includes lists of where to find the best
chocolate in the world, chocolate festivals, events and schools.
Yes, schools. According to Bloom, the best (three-star) chocolates
are found in France, Italy and Switzerland. But she gives two stars
to Fran's Chocolates of Seattle, Wash., and Harbor Sweets of Salem,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Babalu! Favorite Recipes From the World's Top Latin Chefs and
Celebrities'' by Michael Valdes and Art Torres (General Publishing,
$24.95) includes two Houstonians, Michael Cordua of Americas and
Churrascos restaurants in Houston and Robert Del Grande of Cafe
Annie restaurant in Houston, along with David Garrido (Jeffrey's of
Austin, Texas) and Matt Martinez Jr. (YO Ranch Restaurant, Rancho
Martinez and Matt's No Place of Dallas). Recipes are printed in
English and Spanish. Favorites are included from celebrities such
as Benjamin Bratt (TV's ``Law &AMP; Order''), Julio Iglesias, Oscar de
la Renta, Placido Domingo, Hector Elizondo, Rita Moreno, Chita
Rivera, Liz Torres and Geraldo Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dining With the Stars: A Taste of the Best'' compiled by Paul
Kent Dorn (Pocket Books, $22). More than 100 recipes from
celebrities such as Joan Collins (Pheasant and Leek Soup), Angela
Lansbury (Famous Power Loaf), Jay Leno (Uncle Louie's Chicken Wings
Marinara) and Elizabeth Taylor (Spicy Chicken; recipe follows). A
portion of the net proceeds will be contributed to AIDS Project Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage Pass'' by John D. Crisafulli, Sean Fisher and Teresa
Villa (Cumberland House, $18.95). Crisafulli and Villa are a
brother-and-sister team who own Behind the Scenes, a catering
company specializing in concerts, major sporting events and movies.
They offer a fascinating glimpse at celebrities' dressing room
requirements and recipes for favorite menus. Want to know Frank
Sinatra's backstage requests? They never changed over the years _ a
hot crock of Campbell's Chicken and Rice Soup, Dunhill cigars and
cherry Life Savers.
</P>
<P>
   Rock band Pearl Jam's dressing room had to be stocked with
bottled water, beer, wine, fruit juice, chips, candy and
cigarettes. Requirements for Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire included a box of
cayenne pepper, Jif peanut butter and grape jelly, a bag of organic
corn chips and Dannon yogurt. One of their menus included Korean
Chicken/Shrimp, Ginger Glazed Baby Carrots and Fruit Salad With
Orange Amaretto Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   For the Michael Bolton-Celine Dion World Tour 1994, dressing
room requests included coffee and tea services, Cherry 7Up, fruit
and deli trays, Peanut M&AMP;Ms, spring water on ice and at room
temperature, a bottle of vinegar, a small plate of watermelon and
Diet Coke. For one dinner, Behind the Scenes provided seafood
vermicelli, Saffron and Porcini Risotto, and Grilled Radicchio and
Parmesan With Balsamic Vinaigrette. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
