<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-02 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIND PARALLEL UNIVERSES IN AUSTRALIA, CALIFORNIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are many similarities between the history of wine in
Australia and that of wine in California.
</P>
<P>
   For example, both industries didn't really get under way until
the mid-1800s. That's about the time Edward Tyrrell planted his
first vines in Australia's Hunter Valley. Today Tyrrell's remains
one of the oldest family-owned wineries Down Under, export manager
Grant Bellve told me sometime back.
</P>
<P>
   And Tyrrell's proved to be innovative. ``Tyrrell's also made the
first commercial chardonnay (in 1971) in the Hunter Valley,'' he
said. ``And we were the first to put oak on our chardonnay.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyrrell's makes four ``series'' of wines, but not all are
available here. Here's a look at some, and you'll see what bargains
some of them can be.
</P>
<P>
   One of the series is called ``Long Flat,'' named in 1966 after
one of the best-known Tyrrell's vineyards. The 1996 Tyrrell's
``Long Flat'' Chardonnay/Semillon _ 3 stars _ is a classic
commercial Australian white wine blend, very ``tropical'' in style,
with loads of ripe mangoes, pineapples and vanilla. If you like
that style, you'll love the price: $6.99.
</P>
<P>
   A little leaner, and thus a better food wine, was the 1996
Tyrrell's ``Shee-Oak'' Chardonnay _ 3 { stars _ which is a
single-vineyard wine. Bellve called the Shee-Oak Chardonnay an
``instant gratification'' wine. It's also more expensive at $18.99
and is available only by special order.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 ``Old Winery'' Chardonnay _ 3 stars _ was redolent with
ripe pineapple flavors. The $9.99 price won't dent your mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the ``Private Bin'' series is the 1994 Vat 47 Chardonnay
_ 4 stars _ a classy wine, but the price is classy, too: about
$28.99.
</P>
<P>
   Then we tasted the reds. Make no mistake: The 1997 ``Long Flat
Red'' _ 4 stars _ is a simple wine and meant to be drunk slightly
chilled, but it's also simply delightful. This is a happy wine, a
blend of cabernet, shiraz and mourvedre, with lots of raspberry and
strawberry fruit flavors. For $6.99, jump on it.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 ``Old Winery'' Pinot Noir _ 3 stars _ was a decent
rendition of the red burgundy grape, but it also had a gamay-ish
quality that was a little out of character. About $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 ``Old Winery'' Cabernet/Merlot _ &UR;  &LR; 3 { stars _ is fairly
rich, ripe and well-balanced. About $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   Australia is famous for its rendition of the red Rhone grape
syrah, which is called shiraz Down Under. The 1995 ``Old Winery''
Shiraz _ 4 { stars _ had lots of raspberry and white pepper
flavors, and was well balanced, with few harsh tannins in the
aftertaste. My note read: ``Grab the lamb chops, baby!'' The $9.99
is a steal.
</P>
<P>
   Also a special order, like the Shee-Oak Chardonnay, is the
individual vineyard 1994 ``Stevens'' Shiraz _ 4 { stars _ with
excellent black fruit flavors, such as black currant, and some
pepper and vanilla undertones. It's not inexpensive at $18.99, but
it is good.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line on Tyrrell's: Some good values here, especially with
the reds.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrrell's is handled here by Glazer's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Paul Revere, ``The holidays are coming! The
holidays are coming!''
</P>
<P>
   And that means it's OK to splurge on wines for family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But here are a couple of high-ticket items I can't recommend.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, egos have gotten completely out of
control in some corners of California. Some wineries with barely a
two- or three-year track record are charging more than $100 for
their wines, usually highly extracted cabernet sauvignons.
</P>
<P>
   Those ridiculous prices mean, unfortunately for us consumers,
that a $40-$50 cabernet is no longer an unusual sight.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wines in this range are worth it, especially if the
wines have a proven track record of excellence _ and if you can
afford them.
</P>
<P>
   However: Mike Grgich has been making literally world-famous
wines in the Napa Valley since 1972. But his 1995 Grgich Hills
Cabernet Sauvignon _ 2 stars _ is an oddball. Maybe it's too young
_ and Grgich's wines can age _ but this wine has both good fruit
and an unpleasant herbal quality, and the tannins and acidity seem
out of sync with the fruit. I'd like to taste this again in a few
years, but not at $45 per bottle.
</P>
<P>
   You'd be much better off splurging on the 1995 Shafer Cabernet
Sauvignon _ 4 stars _ with its attractive Napa fruit and solid
structure. It isn't cheap _ it's $30 _ but that's a third less than
the Grgich.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of producers of high-quality alambic
(cognac-style) brandy in California. Perhaps the best-known is
Germain-Robin, which makes a range of brandies that can get pretty
expensive. How much is expensive? How about $240 a bottle for their
``Perfection''?
</P>
<P>
   Now that's expensive.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not worth it. Frankly, other Germain-Robin brandies,
far less expensive ones, have tasted better to me.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, brandies in this price category usually are aged
for decades; that's what gives them the deep layers of flavor and
complexity. The Germain-Robin ``Perfection'' _ 2 stars _ however,
is just a 14-year-old brandy. For another thing, while this brandy
is delicate, with some finesse _ and do not infer that this means
heavy, ponderous, oaky brandies are better _ it doesn't have what
aficionados would call a ``middle palate.'' That is, it's light and
pleasant up front, and the aftertaste is decent, but there's a
hollowness to the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   You want a light, delicate alambic brandy? Try the Delamain XO
Pale and Dry _ 5 stars. It's far better, it's almost twice as old _
and it's one-fourth the cost.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth _ straight, no chaser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail correspondence to: michael.lonsford (at) chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
