A8971 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-FRANCHISES-HNS     12-02 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-FRANCHISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO FIGURE THE VALUE OF A PRO TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For those of you in who have figured out the
arcane math that comprises college football's BCS ratings, here's a
brain teaser.
</P>
<P>
   Explain, in 25 words easily understood by college graduates, how
it is that the Oakland Athletics can be:
</P>
<P>
   Bought for $68 million.
</P>
<P>
   Announced as having been bought for $85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Claimed by their owners to have actually been bought for $95
million.
</P>
<P>
   Valued at $118 million by Forbes magazine.
</P>
<P>
   And put on the market for $155 million.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Forbes rankings always cause a twitter among our
nation's fattest cats, because while we think that sports is about
athletic achievement, they know better.
</P>
<P>
   They know it's about newness of stadiums, number of luxury
suites and available suckers to fill them, total amount of
government givebacks, percentage of bank loans still outstanding,
Internal Revenue Service interaction and amount of money that
doesn't have to be shared with one's partners.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Forbes list is just a way the suits keep
score.
</P>
<P>
   There are others, to be sure, and they're just as arbitrary and
fluid as this one. How else can you determine that the apparently
bankrupt Pittsburgh Penguins are actually worth $89 million? Or
that the Kansas City Royals were just sold for $75 million, or $33
million under Forbes' mythical blue book, while the New York
Yankees were nearly bought for $600 million, or $238 million more
than the Forbes number.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Forbes number has no meaning for you or me. But it
would if the Forbes people did a number for us, one that we could
apply our own standards to and adjust for circumstances we
understand.
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a team, do some arbitrary guesswork on the average
value of any team in that league (say, $250 million for an NFL
team, $150 million for an NBA team, $497.50 for an MLS team, etc.),
and apply our own variables.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   If you are about to get a new stadium, add $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you have suckers in local government footing the bill, add
another $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to go to the bank for your financing, subtract $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   For every half-percent rise in the prime rate, subtract $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   If the city ends up being your landlord, subtract $10 million
(legal fees for breaking the lease).
</P>
<P>
   If you sue the city, subtract $15 million. If the city sues you,
subtract $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you threaten to move your team, subtract $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you move your team to a smaller media market, subtract an
additional $22.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every luxury suite, add $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every unsold luxury suite, subtract $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you find an attorney who can find a way around the
inheritance tax laws, add $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you get the first draft pick, add $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the first pick signs Arn Tellem, Drew Rosenhaus, Scott Boras
or Don Meehan as his agent, subtract $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the first pick is arrested, subtract $180,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the first pick is convicted, subtract the value of the
contract plus $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a good local radio-TV package, add $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a bad local radio-TV package, add $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a competent broadcaster, add $6 million, then
subtract the salary of said broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   For every bad broadcaster, subtract $3 million for not knowing
better.
</P>
<P>
   For every championship, add $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every conference championship, add $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every last-place finish, subtract $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every big-money player who goes elsewhere because you say
you can't afford nore than a $43 million payroll, subtract half the
price of the contract that player would have received.
</P>
<P>
   For every national commercial one of your players does, add $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   For every appearance on a wrestling pay-per-view event, add $3
million for attractive demographics.
</P>
<P>
   For every illegitimate child/unmarried mother combination,
subtract $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   For every wholesome family man/woman who can't play a lick,
subtract $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   For every federal indictment, subtract $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   For every district attorney willing to plea bargain away jail
time, add $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   If the millennium bug computer catastrophe actually happens,
subtract $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't, add $500,000 and consider yourself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   If your best player chokes your coach, and you end up looking
bad and still have to pay his salary, subtract the purchase price
and get into another line of business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
