<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Dec. 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments surrounding the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment inquiry on President Clinton. By
Eric Schmitt. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-STARR (Washington) _ Documents are unsealed that reveal
more about how Kenneth Starr's people treated Monica Lewinsky at
their first encounter. By Don Van Nata. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ Even as the House Judiciary
Committee moves to expand its impeachment inquiry, a growing number
of conservatives _ from Huffington to Kristol to Bennett _ are
quietly, grudgingly giving up any hope that President Clinton will
lose his job. By Melinda Henneberger. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SPEAKERS (Washington) _ Impeachment of the president has
fallen into the vacuum between speakers. Livingston hoped Newt
would deal with it. Newt, ousted by Livingston, seems to have no
interest in solving his successor's problems. Republicans are
increasingly panicked that no one has a party plan. Democrats are
enjoying the show. By Alison Mitchell. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   DEMS (Washington) _ Sen. Leiberman, Rep. Gephardt and Vice
President Gore address the Democratic Leadership Council. Gore
tries out new slogan, ``practical idealism,'' and takes a slap at
the early Republican front-runner's slogan, saying ``compassionate
conservatism'' falls short of what is needed in America. By
Katharine Q. Seelye. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HEALTHCARE (Washington) _ While Republicans dither over
impeachment, Clinton and the Senate Democrats try to show that they
care about progress, not partisanship, by emphasizing their plan to
revive the Patients' Bill of Rights. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-PANEL (Washington) _ The bipartisan Commission on the
Future of Medicare meets and, for the first time, debates proposals
for big changes in the program. By Robert Pear. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   VINYL-TOYS (Washington) _ The Consumer Product Safety Commission
expected to advise against use of all vinyl for toys children put
in their mouths. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MANHUNT (Huntsville) _ Although authorities said
confidently that they would catch Martin Gurule, the first
death-row inmate to escape from the prison, they have been unable
to do so. Now they are adding a helicopter to the search, and the
people who prosecuted him killer have hired body guards. By Rick
Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   WARM-WEATHER (Chicago) _ It's ridiculously warm, even in
Chicago. Ski resorts are upset. It's 66 even in places like
Minneapolis. A wrapup, with some scientific explanation about all
this. Is La Nina, who was supposed to bring cold weather, not
coming? By Bill Dedman.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-SHEPPARD-MURDER (Columbus, Ohio) _ The Ohio Supreme Court
today cleared the way for a wrongful imprisonment lawsuit by the
son of Dr. Sam Sheppard to determine whether the doctor was
innocent of the 1954 murder of his wife. The state's highest court
ruled 4-3 against a request by prosecutors to stop the case. By Fox
Butterfield. (800 words)
</P>
