   And a related story:
</P>
<P>
   PALM-PILOT (Undated) _ 3Com introduces its next generation Palm
Pilot, which is the only real competition for Windows CE and which
represents a step forward in the kind of Internet-everywhere device
and gadget market that was a motivating factor in the AOL-Netscape
deal. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   KELLOGG-CUTBACK (Undated) _ Kellogg will fire 765 workers in
North America _525 salaried and 240 contracted positions at its
Battle Creek, Mich., headquarters _ as it cuts costs to pay for new
products and more advertising and promotions. The firings are the
first major cost-cutting move by the company's president and chief
operating officer, Carlos Gutierrez, who took his post in June.
Kellogg will take a quarterly charge of 11 cents a share. By Dana
Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   BMW-ROVER (London) _ BMW ousts Walter Hasselkus as chief
executive of the German company's Rover Group. Rover and BMW also
say that the agreement reached with unions last Friday to cut 2,500
jobs will save 150 million pounds, or $249 million, a year. By Alan
Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   SOCSEC-ECONSCENE (Undated) _ As the Clinton administration
prepares to opens a splashy two-day conference to explore options
for fixing Social Security, the White House and the other
participants would do well to read a lucid study by a panel of the
National Association of Social Insurance, a nonpartisan research
group. By Michael M. Weinstein.
</P>
