<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r b &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-COLUMN-     12-02 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECIPES FOR YUMMY CHICKEN AND DUMPLINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's obvious from our mail who a family's best chicken and
dumplings cook is: someone from a previous generation.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Griffis e-mailed the recipe for old-fashioned rolled
dumplings. It's from her grandmother, Pearl George of Columbia, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The second recipe is from Bessie Long of Weatherford, texas. She
says her mother-in-law made the best chicken and dumplings but
never used a recipe. A daughter-in-law watched as she made the
dumplings and wrote down each ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   GRANDMA'S ROLLED DUMPLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups unsifted flour
</P>
<P>
   Beat first 5 ingredients together with a fork. Add flour and
beat until stiff. Roll very thin on floured board, cut into
1-by-3-inch strips with pizza cutter and drop into 6 cups of
boiling broth to which boned, cut-up chicken has been added. Cook
10 minutes over medium heat. Recipe can be doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Hint for cooking chicken for dumplings: Never boil the chicken
in water alone. Always add salt, black pepper, a touch of onion, a
little garlic powder and either thyme or marjoram. Just a touch of
turmeric also adds great flavor, but don't add too much, or your
broth will be too yellow.
</P>
<P>
   ``This recipe yields the best chicken and dumplings you will
ever eat.''
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 308 calories, 16 grams fat, 34
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 55 milligrams cholesterol,
341 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER LONG'S DUMPLINGS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   3 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups broth from the cooking chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 beaten egg
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 4 ingredients, cutting in the butter.
</P>
<P>
   Add broth and beaten egg. Pour mixture onto well-floured board.
It will be thin, but work excess flour into the dough as you pat it
into a 1/2-inch sheet. Cut into strips and drop into boiling broth
with the almost-cooked chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 211 calories, 6 grams fat, 33
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 39 milligrams cholesterol,
328 milligrams sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Lagniappe: Sometimes, readers just want to share a recipe that
is always a great success, even though it hasn't been requested.
Here are two we received recently. The first is from Geraldine Hall
of De Leon, Texas, who discovered this recipe in ``Potluck on the
Pedernales.'' She made it for her husband, who doesn't like
broccoli. Not only did he eat it, he bragged on it.
</P>
<P>
   The second recipe is from Betty Craiglow of Grapevine, Texas,
who got it from Louisiana relatives.
</P>
<P>
   BROCCOLI SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches broccoli, sliced into fairly small pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 1/4-ounce can black olives, sliced
</P>
<P>
   8 slices bacon, cooked and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup salad dressing (Miracle Whip)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup Parmesan cheese (or less)
</P>
<P>
   Italian salad dressing, to thin
</P>
<P>
   Combine vegetables and bacon. Combine dressing ingredients and
pour over vegetables; stir until all ingredients are moist. Chill
for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Cauliflower may be used in place of some of the broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 324 calories, 32 grams fat, 5
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 30 milligrams cholesterol,
551 milligrams sodium, 89 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   CORN CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   15-ounce can cream-style corn
</P>
<P>
   1 stick margarine
</P>
<P>
   5-ounce-can condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced onion
</P>
<P>
   2 heaping tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Melt margarine in casserole dish. Stir in flour. Add remaining
ingredients and mix. Bake in preheated 375-degree oven for 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 331 calories, 22 grams fat, 29
grams carbohydrates, 8 grams protein, 167 milligrams cholesterol,
487 milligrams sodium, 59 percent of calories from fat. Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Beulah Gordon of Bedford, Texas, would like a recipe for a cake
frosting that is hard and can be peeled off.
</P>
<P>
   A Hurst, Texas, reader would like a recipe for deviled crab.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Rayburn of Hurst, would like a recipe for cranberries
baked in the oven. She seems to remember brandy as one of the
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   DeLaine Clifton of Kennedale, Texas, would like a recipe that
her aunt made about 50 years ago. It's a holiday cake that contains
no fruit, just nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Bundy's column appears each Wednesday. Send recipes and
requests to Beverly Bundy, ``Star-Telegram,'' Box 1870, Fort Worth,
TX 76101. Or E-mail to bbundy\Nstar-telegram.com. Include a daytime
phone number. Responses to requests will be made only through this
column.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
