<SLUG> BC-SNOBBERY-DECLINES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE STARCH OUT OF STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELLIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By CHARLES McGRATH  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    When I was in college, there was a guy famous for wrapping his
brand-new Weejuns with duct tape so that it would look as though
his soles were already flapping. He also, or so it was said, took
brand-new shirts from Brooks Brothers and painstakingly frayed the
cuffs with sandpaper.
 &HT;    This was at Yale in the late '60s, during the last wheezing gasp
_ the final catarrh _ of the patrician ethos that held that the
ultimate status, the highest social perch, belonged to those who
seemingly paid no attention to status. That poor Yalie, with his
tape and sandpaper, made the fatal mistake, of course: He cared too
much and, worse, was seen to care. But in other respects he
understood the code perfectly.
 &HT;    In those days, old was still good. Shabby was good. Instead of
renting a tuxedo, for example, or even buying a new one, it was far
cooler to borrow your great-uncle Ned's _ that hand-sewn mohair
dreadnought, now mossy with age, that he wore to the Stork Club in
the '40s while squiring tipsy debutantes.
 &HT;    What recommended this mothy garment was not just its special
flask pocket or the cigarette burn on the left lapel but that it
(quietly) advertised you as someone who came from tuxedo-wearing
stock, the sort of people who donned formal wear all the time and
not just on self-conscious occasions.
 &HT;    This particular social code owed a lot, obviously, to the old
WASP tradition, with its shunning of vulgar display and its
reverence for old (as opposed to new) anything _ houses, silver,
furniture and, especially, money. And American WASP-iness _
filtered through our Puritan heritage _ in turn owes something to
an imagined ideal of life among the landed British gentry.
 &HT;    You can see the real thing, lovingly and comically depicted, in
the novels of Nancy Mitford or, more recently, in ``The Dower
House,'' by Annabel Davis-Goff, a novel about arguably the most
puritanically class- and status-obsessed people who ever lived: the
Anglo-Irish, who by the 1960s, when this book is set, are neither
truly English nor truly Irish anymore. All they have left, their
sole badge of identity, is good breeding (among themselves and,
just as important, among their dogs and horses) and their dwindling
store of heirlooms.
 &HT;    In the novel's funniest and most painful scene, the scion of a
noble but down-at-the-heels family describes his attempt to repair
his family's fortunes by marrying a girl from London: The courtship
has to be abandoned when, in a shocking display of commonness, she
carries her handbag down to breakfast.
 &HT;    In midcentury America, you didn't have to be a WASP to
appreciate WASP values. In Irish Boston, where I grew up _ Catholic
Irish, not the other kind _ the middle and working classes
sedulously adopted the customs and preferences of their Yankee
overlords. Men took pride in how often their shoes had been reshod,
in the number of times their car odometers had ticked over.
 &HT;    When our next-door neighbor pulled up one evening in a
late-model Cadillac, eyebrows were raised for weeks _ until it was
discovered that he had inherited it from his father-in-law, who was
an undertaker.
 &HT;    For WASP and non-WASP alike, the old status indicators _ thrift,
simplicity, understatement, self-effacement _ made a virtue of the
inescapable: ignorance, insecurity, penury, not to say stinginess.
They also placed a not entirely inappropriate value on history _ on
things (and the people who owned them) that had stood the test of
time.
 &HT;    So what happened? WASP, where is thy sting? Already when I was
in college, there were hints of a new elite, of non-status-seeking
pursued with unimaginable rigor. There were people who didn't even
own Weejuns, much less tape them _ who either didn't know the code
or didn't care and militantly rejected the very idea of property
and hierarchy. (Many of them, after brief stints on the commune,
went on to lucrative careers in investment banking and commercial
real estate.)
 &HT;    And then there were the puritans and the minimalists; you see
them even now, or their descendants, down on Spring Street on
Saturday afternoons _ Mom, Dad and Baby all clad in black, eating
rice cakes and drinking designer water.
 &HT;    The WASP's, meanwhile, fell from their once-lofty ascendance,
done in by inheritance taxes, inbreeding and newly rigorous
admissions standards at the very institutions they once regarded as
their finishing schools. Uncle Ned, were he alive now, would no
longer be working at the family firm. (It was bought out by the
Japanese years ago.)
 &HT;    There's also not enough old stuff to go around anymore. (At a
Sotheby's show of ``important Americana'' recently, I spotted among
the highboys and the sideboards an item labeled ``Sheraton style
... 20th century.'' It was a 1950s coffee table.)
 &HT;    But a more fundamental trouble with the old WASP idea of status
was that it depended on a code as subtle and as complicated as
18th-century calling-card etiquette. The line between an heirloom
and a piece of junk was often hard to draw, as was that between
being ``old shoe'' and looking like a bum. As time went on, fewer
and fewer people knew the signals, until they ceased to be
recognized even by the people who were sending them.
 &HT;    When you think about it, there was probably something phony and
overearnest about America's long romance with gentility and
authenticity. We have always been vulgar _ it's our defining trait.
At the turn of the century, the really rich and really
status-conscious Americans, the people who set the tone that so
many aspired to, were not self-effacing or puritanical at all.
 &HT;    This is the great theme of Edith Wharton and Henry James, that
the Gilded Agers literally wanted entitlement. They wanted palaces
and noble lineage, and they wanted real history, so they went to
Europe and brought it all back _ instant class. Such is the miracle
of America: you can get it now in a good department store in the
Ralph Lauren boutique.
 &HT;    Lauren's genius has been to provide not only stuff that looks
new and feels old _ loafers with a patina of invisible duct tape,
so to speak _ but also a prepackaged ancestral past: cotillions,
hunts, summers at the Adirondack camp. An Uncle Ned for everyone.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles McGrath is editor of The New York Times Book Review
section.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _________ &QC;
