<HEADER>
A9020 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCE-CHARLES-PROFIL     12-02 2822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCE-CHARLES-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FRESH PRINCE ... ON THE COMEBACK TRAIL WITH PRINCE CHARLES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By WARREN HOGE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The royal train, sleek and black with pencil-thin red trimming,
is hurtling toward Newcastle, and inside one of the armored middle
cars, Charles, the prince of Wales, is taking his breakfast.
 &HT;    He's dressed down in an open-collar white-and-burgundy striped
shirt, blue cardigan and khaki trousers, and as I enter the cabin,
his look of welcome is mixed with one of concern.
 &HT;    ``I do hope you managed to get some sleep,'' he says, motioning
me to sit across from him.
 &HT;    Gales and lashing rain had rolled in from the North Sea as we
made our midnight departure from Perth, and the heir to the throne
seems to be apologizing for turbulence in the realm.
 &HT;    ``Ghastly night,'' he says.
 &HT;    Freshly done up in blond wood with little ornamentation, the
coach reflects a new reduced configuration aimed at cutting the
train's operating cost. Part of royal downsizing? I ask.
 &HT;    ``Yes,'' he nods. ``What you see is the anorexic British
monarchy.''
 &HT;    In a corner bookcase, there is a small vase of flowers and a
picture of the Queen Mother, said to be Prince Charles' favorite
member of the family. Earlier her two corgis, Dash and Rash, had
taken their morning stroll through the carpeted corridors, friskily
tugging at the leash held by her footman, Leslie Campbell.
 &HT;    The prince's face is ruddy from a blustery weekend at his home
on the Balmoral estate in Scotland, and gray is making a debonair
debut in his thinning hair. His ears are large, as advertised, but
they ride closer to his head and in happier proportion to it than
cartoonists' pens would have you believe.
 &HT;    He speaks so softly that I have to strain to hear him even in
the stillness of the cabin, with its thick, bulletproof windows
keeping out the clatter of our passage along England's northeastern
coast.
 &HT;    Smartly turned out crewmen in navy blazers, charcoal gray
trousers and black shoes shined to a military gloss place before
the prince a silver tray with small jars of preserves and honeys
and a bowl of wheat germ and cereal grains, all of which meet his
high threshold for unadulterated, healthful food.
 &HT;    He reaches for a container of honey, opens it and spoons the
golden spread directly into his mouth. I think I am observing royal
prerogative.
 &HT;    ``I actually don't eat very much at all,'' he says, confirming
the warnings I had received minutes earlier from the butlers and
security men in the mess car as they tucked into their heaping
platefuls of eggs, tomatoes, mushrooms, sausage, bacon and toast.
 &HT;    In fact the atmosphere around the prince and his once-embattled
retinue is assured and upbeat these days. Not long ago the most
reviled member of the British royal family, Charles was able on his
50th birthday in November to look back on a year in which he was
liberated from the competition with Diana, the princess of Wales,
for attention and approval.
 &HT;    He also was given credit previously denied him for being a
sensitive parent to his two sons; was celebrated by the new Labor
government of Prime Minister Tony Blair for the pioneering social
work his Prince's Trust has done; and was encouraged by
significantly growing public endorsement of him as the next
sovereign and of his mistress, Camilla Parker Bowles, as his
private life companion and possible wife.
 &HT;    He has turned the most convulsive moment in his life _ the death
in August 1997 of his former wife, Diana _ into an opportunity for
staging his own revival and for staking a strong claim on the role
of guiding the monarchy into the 21st century.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, his progress has freshened the image of the monarchy.
Mutinous feelings in Britain toward the royals have subsided, and
the major player in disarming the public has surprisingly been
Prince Charles.
 &HT;    For a long time the percussive, single-syllable words like
``twit,'' ``wimp'' and ''prat'' that Britons use to dress down
their well-born often accompanied mention of his name. The product
of an undemonstrative mother, a chastising father and the decidedly
uncozy Windsor household, Charles suffered from self-doubt and
appeared hesitant and distracted in the face of the burdensome
demands of his awesome inheritance.
 &HT;    The question he most commonly puts to people he encounters now
on his official rounds _ ``What do you do?'' _ is one he might have
best avoided years ago for fear someone might ask him back.
 &HT;    When he got around to doing something, he only made matters
worse, uttering ill-thought-out and crudely stated condemnations of
modern architecture, medicine and education. By the time Diana
began attracting favorable attention for her visits to AIDS wards
and refugee camps, Charles had marked himself as something of a
young fogy, dismissing new approaches to old problems as
``fashionable.''
 &HT;    What's more, he was conducting a personal life that became an
ongoing tabloid saga complete with confessional television
interviews and smutty tape recordings of stunningly graceless
sexual small talk.
 &HT;    Recently, however, newspaper and magazine articles and new books
assessing him in connection with his birthday have portrayed a
new-look prince and declared him an underacknowledged overachiever
whose good works went unnoticed in the press onslaught on his
shortcomings.
 &HT;    Anthony Holden, a royal biographer considered hostile by the
prince's supporters and denied all cooperation for his new book,
``Charles at Fifty,'' concluded that ``the human qualities well
known to his inner circle, for all the battering they took during
the Diana years, have come back to the fore. If not entirely at
peace with himself, he is more so with the world around him. Throw
in the shrewdest advisers he has had since his youth, extending
beyond his own office to the inner councils of government, and you
have a public figure suddenly and unexpectedly at the peak of his
powers, bloodied but unbowed by his past, with cause for unwonted
optimism about his future.''
 &HT;    The prince's schedule for this day alone calls for him to spend
seven hours opening a home for the aged, a glass museum, a
job-training center and, most improbably, an oil rig. True, there's
nothing new about the prince of Wales going off to lay cornerstones
and plant trees. In 1997, he had 513 engagements like this.
 &HT;    What is new is that he is no longer alone with his ceremonial
shovel. People are paying attention, and they are doing so because
the ideas of a man long associated with the country's past now seem
very much a part of its future.
 &HT;    Back in the staff mess car, one of Charles' aides confided that
he believed the most significant factor in the changing fortunes of
the prince was the election in May 1997 of Tony Blair and the Labor
Party: ``Suddenly his views became part of the political language
of this country.''
 &HT;    It is a breathtaking fact that many of the reforms the Labor
government is pursuing _ getting private enterprise engaged in
public service and opening up opportunities for young people,
minorities and the unemployed _ are ones that have been undertaken
for years by a member of the famously out-of-touch British
monarchy. On issues such as the environment, genetically modified
food and organic farming, the prince has even bolder prescriptions
than the government.
 &HT;    Where the queen just this year rode in her first public taxi,
walked into her first McDonald's and visited her first pub, Prince
Charles has been tramping through housing projects for two decades.
In 1976, he began a program that made loans available to young
people whom banks wouldn't go near, and the idea is credited with
having helped more than 40,000 people to start new businesses.
 &HT;    Several people who run sections of the Prince's Trust said they
know Charles was motivated to act in the 1980s by evidence that
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's economic revolution was leaving
Britain's poor unprotected and marginalized.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't that he used her name,'' said one executive close to
the prince. ``He spoke out when it was very unfashionable to have
these concerns, and he was the one who persuaded business it had to
enter areas that the government was abandoning.''
 &HT;    Financed by the consolidation of three royal trusts and by
contributions from corporations and individuals, the trust today
manages an endowment of $125 million.
 &HT;    Blair's people have praised the prince for his foresightedness,
and the prince has expressed his pleasure that Labor has found
inspiration in his good works. One gleeful Labor official said,
``He was a Blairite before Blair.''
 &HT;    In contrast, the queen is not known to have any political
viewpoints, and in her long years on the throne she has never been
caught out expressing one. She and Prince Philip are reported by
biographers to be put off by their eldest son's social activism in
general and the perception that he could be playing favorites in
Britain's public life.
 &HT;    The prince has not responded to the grumbling in the House of
Commons about his role, but he has long said the monarchy of the
future should be ``a contributing monarchy.''
 &HT;    In a letter to Tom Shebbeare, the head of the trust, five years
ago, he addressed the question, saying, ``I have no 'political'
agenda _ only a desire to see people achieve their potential.'' He
reasoned that his ability to get attention made him ``a catalyst to
help produce a better and more balanced response to various
problems.''
 &HT;    The prince has known the prime minister since 1990, when Blair
was Labor's shadow employment secretary and took an interest in the
work the Prince's Trust was doing in the area of youth employment.
Their relationship was to deepen in the immediate aftermath of the
death of Diana, as the royal family found itself tone-deaf to the
sorrow and anger of the nation and looked to the newly triumphant
Labor government for help tuning in.
 &HT;    Blair and the prince spoke by phone during the flight Charles
made to Paris to bring Diana's body back to Britain, and associates
of the prime minister played a prominent role in planning the
funeral and in encouraging the royal family to respond to the
outpouring of grief. The prince is the member of the family
credited with convincing the palace that it was too remote, and
much of his counsel came from Blair officials.
 &HT;    Today, on the prince's staff are none of the advisers who
counseled him to confess his adultery in a 1994 television
interview, a strategic decision he now regrets.
 &HT;    While the queen has kept her private secretaries for decades at
a time, Charles has had six since 1985, a measure of his
temperamental leadership. He has now settled down and reached out
to the worlds of politics and entertainment for help. By design,
his staff is no longer all male, all white, all Oxford- and
Cambridge-educated.
 &HT;    Often at odds with their more tradition-bound counterparts in
Buckingham Palace, the prince's people are busy putting forth their
man as the voice of the monarchy's future, even going so far as to
set up his own Web site _ www.princeofwales.gov.uk.
 &HT;    The prince's current honeymoon with the British press began
after a simple act of reconciliation suggested by his new aides.
For 10 years, he had not directed a personal word at any of the
reporters covering him.
 &HT;    Then, on a trip between South Africa and Swaziland last year, a
shirt-sleeved prince walked back to the economy section of the
plane where the press was riding and struck up conversations. He
captivated the surprised reporters with a few jokes on himself, and
by the same afternoon The Evening Standard was on the streets of
London with a front page saying, ``Chattering Charles Plays Royal
Tour Joker.''
 &HT;    The charm offensive was on. Public appearances increased and
Charles began to be seen at West End first nights, film openings,
Spice Girl concerts _ in short, the circles where Diana once
reigned. The usual titled guests at dinners at St. James' Palace
and at Highgrove found themselves seated next to Charles' new
friends, such as Emma Thompson and Rowan Atkinson, whose comic
creation Mr. Bean has come, like the prince, to represent the
lovable side of English awkwardness.
 &HT;    The Sun, Britain's largest-selling tabloid and long a Charles
tormentor, became the recipient of leaks from the prince's office
and made a rapid conversion to the rehabilitation cause. The prince
and his organic garden at Highgrove were lovingly chronicled in
celebrity magazines such as Hello!
 &HT;    Charles took his sons to Vancouver, where they publicly
frolicked in the caps of the Canadian Winter Olympics team. And, in
a gesture interpreted as a truce, the prince agreed to serve as
patron for a new press ball.
 &HT;    At a televised birthday gala, the prince became the star of the
show, appearing in a skit with the actors Stephen Fry and Roger
Moore. The scene was a restaurant, and look-alikes of Michael
Jackson, Tina Turner, Madonna and Humphrey Bogart appeared on stage
as Fry and Moore, the diners, tried unsuccessfully to guess who
they were.
 &HT;    Charles, an accomplished college actor at Cambridge, then walked
on, playing a waiter with a cloth napkin slung over his forearm and
a pen and pad at the ready. When the cheers died down, he
recommended the organic vegetables and cookies made from the
Highgrove granary. ``They're damn good,'' he said.
 &HT;    Moore pondered the prince's performance. ``I know who you're
supposed to be, but you are going to have work on your voice a
bit,'' he said to the laughing crowd.
 &HT;    The aides who have helped engineer the turnabout in public
opinion are encouraged about the future. ``We find doors flying
open everywhere now where we had to really struggle before,'' one
said.
 &HT;    Though the recognition of the prince's pioneering
accomplishments and the public sympathy for him as a single parent
have given him new balance, Charles can still stumble over his
bulky collection of resentments.
 &HT;    There is, first and foremost, the somewhat icy, always
complicated relationship with his parents. It is clear too that the
prince has not fully freed himself from the sense of anger he felt
a year ago at being cast as a villain who betrayed a saint, a
careless adulterer who married a virgin for dynastic reasons and
then destroyed her emotionally.
 &HT;    ``You know the prince thought that Diana was on a mission to
destroy him,'' one courtier explained. He recalled a night in which
Charles could talk of nothing else until the aide, a relative
newcomer to the staff, said: ``You can't keep going on like this.
You must get on with your future.''
 &HT;    The prince agreed that he was being ``obsessive'' but insisted
on talking on. ``Unless you hear what went on in the past,'' he
said, ``you won't understand how I am today.''
 &HT;    How he is today, friends say, is a lot more pleasant than he
used to be, and the behavior figures prominently in his
rehabilitation.
 &HT;    ``He's actually doing the same things he did before,'' said a
Prince's Trust executive, ``but he is much more relaxed and
confident that he can do things on his own. It helps not having
someone out there saying, 'I can do that better than you can.'''
 &HT;    Of course, he is still far from taming his notorious moodiness
or mastering his tantrums, but the best antidote to them, Camilla
Parker Bowles, is more frequently at hand.
 &HT;    ``He is a world-class, wall-to-wall whinger,'' one of his
closest aides said, invoking the English word for whining that
makes self-pity sound even more insufferable.
 &HT;    A woman who heads up one of his charities looked aghast at the
recollection of a moment when she lost patience with the prince and
apparently lost track of whom she was speaking to. ``He does moan
about so,'' she said. ``One day I just said to him: 'Stop
complaining. We all have problem parents.'''
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Warren Hoge, editor of The New York Times Magazine from 1991
to 1993, is chief of The Times' London bureau.) &LR;
