<P>
   CIR-FUZZY-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ Arthur and D.W. look for all the
world like simple stuffed toys based on the aardvarks from PBS's
most popular children's show, ``Arthur.'' But these two 21-inch
figures, called Actimates, are not just toys: they are furry
computer peripherals. But Arthur and D.W. are not alone. This fall
has seen the release of a menagerie of fuzzy computers, like My
Interactive Pooh ($99.99) by Mattel and two less expensive toys,
Furby ($34.99) from Tiger Electronics and Real Live Babe ($40), a
toy pig from Equity Toys based on the movie character. All these
dolls offer varying levels of interactivity and differing claims
about educational value. But the educational value of these kinds
of interactive toys is a matter of keen debate among
child-development experts. By Ian Austen.
