<HEADLINE>
NUTS ABOUT CHEF GRADY SPEARS' SPICY PECANS? READ ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``My family loves the pecans Reata serves on their salad. Does
anyone know how those are prepared?'' writes Joann Bresciani from
Crowley, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was chef Grady Spears happy to share his recipe for the
nuts served at his Fort Worth reataurant, he's also sharing many of
his recipes in ``A Cowboy in the Kitchen: Recipes From Reata and
Texas West of the Pecos'' (10 Speed Press, $29.95). The book is hot
off the press and will not be available in bookstores until
January. However, it is for sale at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY PECANS
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   4 cups pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons pasilla powder, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   Note: Make pasilla powder by removing the stem and seeds from 5
pasilla chiles. Toast peppers in skillet over medium heat for 5
minutes, turning them often until they are dry and crisp, but not
burned. Puree the peppers in a coffee grinder until they become a
fine powder.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In large bowl, toss pecans with
butter until well-coated. Toss chile powder and brown sugar with
nuts. Sift with fingers. Place on baking sheet and bake for 10-20
minutes. (The length of time may vary, depending on your oven.)
Bake until sugar begins to caramelize. The coating will not be
crunchy at this time, but coating will harden as the nuts cool.
These can be used as croutons on salads or set out for holiday
snacks. Store in airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 451 calories, 44 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 12 milligrams cholesterol, 8
milligrams sodium, 87 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   On the milder side: Fern Best of Arlington, Texas, sends the
requested recipe for a broccoli casserole with a soufflelike
texture.
</P>
<P>
   BROCCOLI RICE BAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8-10
</P>
<P>
   10-ounce package frozen broccoli, cooked and drained
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 cups torn, firm wheat bread
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cans cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce jar Cheez Whiz
</P>
<P>
   Butter, for sauteing
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Saute onions and celery in butter. Combine eggs, milk and bread
in a bowl; set aside to absorb liquid. Add drained broccoli.
Combine all ingredients and pour into a casserole. Bake for 375
degrees for 20-30 minutes until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 212 calories, 12 grams fat, 17
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 110 milligrams cholesterol,
772 milligrams sodium, 49 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet treat: Geraldine Hall of De Leon, Texas, sends the
requested recipe for date nut bars.
</P>
<P>
   EASY DATE NUT BARS
</P>
<P>
   Yields 16
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup baking mix
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped dates
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Stir together first 3 ingredients. Add egg, milk and vanilla.
Stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Add dates and pecans and blend well. Pour into 8-by-8-inch
greased pan. Bake at 375 degrees for 20-25 minutes. Sprinkle with
powdered sugar. Cut into squares.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 125 calories, 6 grams fat, 19
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 13 milligrams cholesterol, 66
milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Pink stuff everywhere: Judging by the response we got to the
request for ``pink stuff,'' everyone in the county makes some
version of this side dish/dessert. Penny Acrey sent the first
recipe. Sally Newman of Fort Worth sent in the second recipe. The
frozen version is from Cheryl Rayburn of Cleburne, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   PINK STUFF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   13-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce container cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce box strawberry gelatin
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce container nondairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans, optional
</P>
<P>
   Heat pineapple, and add gelatin. Mix until disolved. Let cool.
Mix together with other ingredients and let set overnight in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with pecans: 369 calories, 25
grams fat, 30 grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 36 milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   PINK STUFF II
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   14-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple
</P>
<P>
   21-can cherry pie filling
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce container nondairy frosting
</P>
<P>
   Combine milk and lemon juice. Mix well. Add remaining
ingredients and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 469 calories, 16 grams fat, 77
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 23 milligrams cholesterol,
110 milligrams sodium, 60 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   FROZEN CRANBERRY SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   16-ounce can whole cranberry sauce
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce can crushed pineapple, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   8-ounce carton sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and freez. Serve frozen in slices.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 260 calories, 11 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 13 milligrams cholesterol, 35
milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Star-Telegram, Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
