<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSTS SEE CHEVRON RESISTING MERGER MANIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Chevron Corp., the offshoot of the old Standard
Oil of California, is unlikely to be swept into the momentum of
consolidation in the oil industry, a company official and industry
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon Corp. announced Tuesday that it agreed to acquire Mobil
Corp. for about $80 billion in stock, raising the likelihood of
more mergers in the competitive world oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at things constantly. Selling assets and acquiring
assets is part of our business,'' said Dawn Soper, spokeswoman for
the San Francisco-based Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Soper hastened to add that the trend of huge mergers might
not be right for Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of speculation out there,'' she said, ``but the
continued speculation that you have to be bigger is not a
philosophy we subscribe to.''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts who monitor the oil industry concurred, saying
that all the big oil and gas mergers had been put in play. In
addition to the Exxon-Mobil deal, British Petroleum Co. agreed in
August to buy Amoco Corp. in a transaction valued at $48.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Eisenbarth, an analyst at Collins &AMP; Co., a San
Francisco-based brokerage firm, said one potential suitor of
Chevron is Royal Dutch/Shell in the United Kingdom. Eisenbarth said
Royal Dutch/Shell had a market value or capitalization of about
$100 billion, compared with Chevron's $53 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as market cap goes, (Chevron's) at the top of the
list,'' he said. ``It would be an expensive pill to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   A more likely scenario is that Chevron could be a potential
buyer of a smaller refiner like the Atlantic Richfield Co., or
Arco, which has a market value of about $22 billion and a
significant presence in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Another option for Chevron is not to do anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chevron would be fine for the time being,'' said Jennifer
Gordon, a Baltimore-based analyst at BT Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of reducing costs to compete with other oil giants,
Eisenbarth said Chevron already was a very lean operator. With
39,700 workers, the company has about half the employees it did a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're one of the low-cost producers right now,'' Eisenbarth
said. ``Chevron doesn't want to scale down operations too far
because it gets to the point where you jeopardize revenues. But
(cost) benchmarks could be reset once the operating structures of
the recently merged companies are hashed out.''
</P>
<P>
   The heads of Exxon and Mobil said they could better compete as
one company in a global market faced with declining prices and
stiff competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole oil industry's in a tough situation,'' Eisenbarth
said. ``Profitability is under fire right now. There's a global
glut of oil on the market. ... That's the catalyst that gets
consolidation going. But Chevron is not going to do anything to the
detriment of its shareholders. They're not going out of business,
merger or not.''
</P>
<P>
   What's most clear is that any move Chevron makes shouldn't bore
a hole in consumer pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prices at the pump are more determined by supply and demand of
gasoline,'' Eisenbarth said. ``From a consumer perspective, the
impact would be minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   Chevron, like Exxon and Mobil, is an offshoot of the Standard
Oil Co. founded by John D. Rockefeller in 1870. In a landmark
antitrust case, that oil empire was broken up in 1911, creating a
series of separate companies.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon and Mobil are the largest pieces of the old Standard Oil.
If the deal is approved by regulators and stockholders, the
combined operation, to be called Exxon Mobil, would eclipse Royal
Dutch/Shell as the world's largest oil company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
