<P>
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram plans to move the following stories
for clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Dec. 2, and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tom Uhler, Paul Wagner, Lou Hudson, Carmelita Bevill or
Jim Peipert on the Star-Telegram's National/Foreign Desk at (817)
390-7785. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   N A T I O N A L &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOSSIL-FISH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mountains of waste will soon be heaped into the
newest trash pit at Hunter Ferrell Landfill, but for now, the hole
is home to a prehistoric prize. Nestled 60 feet under the landfill
are fossilized pieces of an 8- to 12-foot-long xiphactinus, a
menacing fish with razor-sharp teeth and powerful jaws that roamed
waterways 90 million years ago. By DIANE SMITH. Story will move in
``a'' general news category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-INDEPENDENTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Exxon-Mobil deal is all about Big Oil,
and that makes it a big deal in Texas. But Little Oil is standing
by to pick up the leftovers, and that, too, is a big deal in Texas.
That's because the huge, integrated multinationals such as Exxon
and Mobil have been doing a long, slow retreat from Texas and the
U.S. midcontinent over the past two decades in favor of new plays
in the former Soviet Union, China and Southeast Asia. By DAN
PILLER. Story will move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-LEADERS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ On paper, they seem so similar. In the flesh, they
seem very different. Lee Raymond and Lucio Noto, the chief
executives of Exxon and Mobil, respectively, joined their companies
in the early 1960s within a year of each other. They spent time
working abroad and then, after displaying financial skills, climbed
through the ranks at home. Roughly 30 years after joining their
organizations, each was named chairman and chief executive _ again,
within 12 months of each other. Now, with both at age 60 and with
the oil industry in the throes of extensive consolidation, the
paths of Raymond and Noto have converged, with the agreement to
combine their companies in the biggest merger in history. By
MITCHELL SCHNURMAN. Story will move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-TEXAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ If the merger of oil giants Exxon and Mobil
is approved, North Texas will be home to the world's biggest
corporation. But the region might have to accept some job cuts
along with the distinction. For example, Mobil Corp. employs 2,300
at a production research center in Farmers Branch and at a Dallas
data center. But Exxon Corp., which is based in Irving's Las
Colinas area, also has a production research center. It's in
Houston, the site of Exxon's U.S. production headquarters and the
designated home of the merged company's world production and
chemical operations. By JIM FUQUAY and ANDREW BACKOVER. Story will
move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-STATIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's a long way from the Mobil Corp.
boardroom to Dennis Heiser's Mobil station on Loop 820 in North
Richland Hills. Heiser has run the dealership for 23 years and has
long enjoyed a companionable relationship with the owner of the
Exxon across the street. Now, after Exxon and Mobil's megamerger,
the Exxon station on the opposite corner will be a brother business
to Heiser's Mobil station. What that means for dealers and
consumers remains in question. By BILL BOWEN. Story will move in
``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERGER-EXXON COMPLEX &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It's almost as if a megamerger were in the
blueprints four years ago when Exxon built its headquarters
complex, which dominates the horizon west of Las Colinas' pink
granite towers. The 360,000-square-foot complex can accommodate
hundreds of additional workers who could be shifted as a result of
the Exxon-Mobil merger, according to real estate observers and
local chamber officials. And if they can't be squeezed into the
main office, which already houses about 300 employees, the company
also has 30 acres on which it can build nearby. By MILES MOFFEIT.
Story will move in ``f'' financial category &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F O O D A N D D I N I N G &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUDGE MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RAPEVINE, Texas _ Jan Singleton was known as The Fudge Man in
Oklahoma City. Now, he's living in Grapevine and sharing his sweet
secrets for divine confections. By CATHERINE HOPPER. Story will
move in ``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RECIPES-BUNDY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Recipes for spicy pecans, broccoli rice cakes, easy
date nut bars, pink stuff, pink stuff II and frozen cranberry
salad. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move in ``d'' food and dining
category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
