<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9110 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-T     12-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PECAN TREES SHELLED OUT A SPARSE CROP THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ At Weatherford's public market, just east
of the Parker County Courthouse, this is the time of year when
shoppers do their annual dance of the pecan.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, there are sacks and sacks of pecans, piled up like
sandbags holding back a river of pie bakers and candy-makers. The
shoppers move deftly between the sacks, grabbing a sample here,
another taste there.
</P>
<P>
   In the background, a sheller pounds out the beat.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the dance floor is far less crowded. The drought
is once again showing its effect. The pounding sheller goes silent
for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drought really hurt,'' said Michelle Dunn, who with her
husband, Jim, runs Dunn Produce at the market. ``It's not like it
has been in years past, but it can't be helped.''
</P>
<P>
   There are still mountains of bags stacked in a corner of the
market, and the Dunns have done their best to display their finest
nuts. But being people who rely heavily on the pecan harvest for
their livelihood at this time of year, they are obviously
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the irrigated farms didn't do that well,'' Michelle Dunn
said. ``We thought that would make the difference, but it didn't. I
am not an expert on growing pecans, but I think it was more than
just the lack of water; it was the high temperatures as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pawnee pecans were good, she said. They came in late
September, and they have already disappeared. Apparently, some
shoppers understood what was going on and jumped on the early crop.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only Cheyenne, Wichita and Kiowa are left. Their quality
has been damaged by the drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get a 55 percent yield on the pecans,'' she said.
``That means that out of 10 pounds of pecans, we will get 5.5
pounds of meat; the rest is shell. That is kind of our standard.
This year, we're seeing 47 percent in the Cheyennes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Choctaws _ a thin-shelled pecan with a meaty flavor _ didn't
even show up this year. The tasty Desirables were the same. Dunn
said they are hoping that some Burkets would be coming in late, but
doubt that it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the Dunns said, lots of people pick up pecans in nearby
parks and fields _ just looking for some extra spending money. But
this year, they haven't shown up either.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with the rows and rows of varieties missing, the
Dunns insist that what they do have is better than the pre-packaged
pecans in the grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   For years, pecan growers have tried to persuade grocers to put
pecans in refrigerated areas to keep them from drying out, but to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to sound too negative,'' Michelle Dunn said.
``Actually, the average person might not be able to tell too much
of a difference between this year's crop and last. The pecans we
have are good; we just don't have as many as we would like.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Wichitas have a high oil content and are good for
baking; the Cheyennes are light-colored and look very good as a
garnish.
</P>
<P>
   All of them, along with California walnuts, almonds and mixed
nuts, look good in Christmas baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a big business in fruit baskets,'' she said. ``We get a
majority of the fruit-basket business from the churches around
here. We'll have grapefruit and oranges, apples, and lots of fresh
persimmons.''
</P>
<P>
   The most common use for pecans is still pecan pie; here is one
of the most often-used recipes. It is from the folks who make Karo
syrup, the syrup commonly used in pecan pies.
</P>
<P>
   KARO PECAN PIE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 8
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs, slightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Karo syrup, light or dark
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 (9-inch) unbaked pie crust
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350. In a large bowl, stir first 5 ingredients
until well-blended. Stir in pecans. Pour into pie crust. Bake 50 to
55 minutes, or until knife inserted halfway between center and edge
comes out clean. Cool on wire rack.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 502 calories, 24 grams fat, 69
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 79 milligrams cholesterol,
233 milligrams sodium, 44 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
