<P>
   MUSEUM-SHOPS (Undated) _ Some gift shops have nice museums
attached. Giant flags wave in front of New York's Museum of Natural
History beckoning the public to Vodou, its exhibition of the sacred
arts of Haiti. Inside, cash registers are ringing up sales of
Haitian arts and crafts made of tin, glass and sequins at the Vodou
shop that's been set up for the duration of the show. At the
Philadelphia Museum of Art, a special shop has been created for its
current Delacroix show. Museums large and small have come to depend
on the profits of their shops now that so much public and private
funding of the arts has dried up. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KALMAN-DESIGN (Undated) _ Thirty years ago the designer Tibor
Kalman showed up. Kalman's brilliance has been to sustain,
throughout his career, a tirade against oppression and for
intellectual freedom. He has maintained that tirade with fearless
biting humor and a legendary, often withering grumpiness toward
those who disagree with him. Kalman's visual manifestoes rail
against technological hyperbole and other fetishes about ``the
Future.'' His work in advertising, journalism and graphic design
constitutes a eulogy for the single clear voice. That voice, a
blunt water cannon, has delighted in hosing down storm-troopers of
style and fashion around the globe. By John Hockenberry.
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Modernism can be dangerous.
Just ask Cremilda Conceicao, whose forehead and sweatpants bear the
battle scars of fourteen years of cleaning the see-through
elevator, the transparent sinks and some 17 levels of plexiglass
walkways and chrome-plated I-beams that snake bewilderingly through
the late architect Paul Rudolph's Beekman Place triplex, perhaps
the city's most unusual apartment.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SEE-THROUGH-CAMERA (Undated) _ Rarely has an urban legend been
born so quickly and openly as the tale that Sony's NightShot video
camera could see through clothes. Jay Leno joked about it: ``Hear
about this new video camera that looks through clothes? Well, Sony
has recalled it _ and raised the price.'' The titillating tale
rippled through the news media like snickers through a sophomore
science class. It had only the tiniest grain of truth: in skilled
hands, during the day, under just the right conditions, with just
the right (gauzy) fabrics, it might be possible to produce an image
of a body beneath. The camera could not, of course, see through
clothes, and there was no recall. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-DESIGN (Undated) _ The spirit of universal design _
making something that enhances everyone's life _ has filtered into
my garden plans for next spring. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   FANTASY-CAKE-DECORATOR (New York) _ The call came in from the
White House on Nov. 10. Could Colette Peters, fantasy cake
decorator to Bette Midler, Whoopi Goldberg, Al Pacino, Joan Rivers
and Rockefeller Center, make edible Christmas decorations for the
mantels in the Red Room and the Green Room and for the Grand Foyer.
And could she have them installed by Saturday night, Dec. 5? Not
too many people say no to the White House. Neither did Ms. Peters,
who gave up a career as a painter _ that thing about making a
living _ to bake and decorate cakes for the rich and famous. The
latter turned out to provide a very nice living. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   TIFFANY-WINDOWS (New York) _ When you enter the long nave of St.
James African Methodist Episcopal Church here, there is a deep,
rich glow near the altar, coming from windows that pulsate with
color and light. The dazzling interplay of emerald greens, dark
blues, ambers and rubies inspires a feeling verging on rapture.
Anyone seeing these six windows will wonder if they are by Louis
Comfort Tiffany. The answer is a definite ``maybe'' and, in fact,
the mystery may never be resolved. By Caroline Seehohm.
</P>
