<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9150 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUL-TRAIN-HNS &LR;      12-02 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUL-TRAIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUL-SINGING TRANSIT DRIVER TOLD TO TONE IT DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY DELGADO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A singing driver for the Municipal Railway has
been slapped on the wrist for disrupting the peace with his
renditions of soul classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius Perdue, known as Dr. Love to his daily passengers on
the F-line, has been warned by his supervisors not to have his
train's outside speakers on when he serenades riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just cautioned and reinstructed,'' said Perdue, 55.
``The voice continues. No problem. I can sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Perdue, who croons melodies from the likes of Marvin Gaye, Al
Green and other pop singers, faced suspension or other disciplinary
action when a resident of the city's Castro District complained
that Perdue refused to shut off his outdoor speakers when he was
asked to. The resident accused Perdue of insulting him in front of
passengers, alleging that Perdue called him a ``party pooper,'' a
statement that Perdue denied.
</P>
<P>
   Perdue said he could not shut the speaker system off during the
night of the confrontation because it was broken and he offered a
maintenance slip as proof of the defect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't rude to him,'' Perdue said. ``Everyone on that train
was mad at him. I'm the one that saved him. I closed the doors when
they wanted to get out and give him a piece of their mind. He broke
their spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Municipal Railway, or Muni, notified Perdue Tuesday that the
man's complaint was valid. Muni spokesman P.J. Johnston said he
could not comment on what disciplinary action was taken because it
was a confidential personnel matter.
</P>
<P>
   Muni supervisors have reiterated the policy that speakers on the
outside of trains are to be used only for emergencies or to give
information to waiting passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an immensely popular driver, and he's likely to accept
the consequences and we'll move on,'' Johnston said. ``Knowing this
driver, I think he'll do whatever he can not to offend those
residents again.''
</P>
<P>
   No other complaints were filed against Perdue. Several hundred
riders on the F-Line train signed a petition supporting him.
</P>
<P>
   But other residents along the line said they were pleased that
the singing has been silenced. One of them, Peter Groubert, drove a
city bus for 20 years before retiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was the only one that it disturbed until he
mentioned it,'' Groubert, 52, said in referring to the complainant.
``It's not that he's singing. It's just so darned loud. When he
turns the corner, it's like he's in the living room.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to whistle and sing so I can't put him down for it,''
Groubert said. ``But I kept it in the bus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1538EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
