<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9157 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUDGEMAN-TEX     12-02 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUDGEMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSOR FUDGE: CANDY EXPERT JAN SINGLETON SHARES HIS SWEET
SECRETS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KATHRYN HOPPER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ Making great fudge is like dancing the tango.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timing is the key,'' says Jan Singleton, a dance instructor
turned carpenter turned fudgemaker extraordinaire. ``All the parts
have to fit together at the right moment, or it doesn't really
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton is a Grapevine handyman known as Mr. Fixer, but in
Oklahoma City, he's better known as The Fudge Man. For 13 years, he
went door to door selling his fudge, which came in more than 20
flavors, from the bestselling chocolate pecan to the unusual lemon
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is teaching his craft to fellow fudge fiends through the
Grapevine Parks &AMP; Recreation Department. Singleton teaches a
one-day seminar on the basics and a longer course that explores
exotic varieties, such as Kahlua Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he demonstrated his fudgemaking prowess at the
Grapevine Recreation Center. Anyone trying to work out on
treadmills or run laps around the track was forced to smell
Singleton's handiwork as he blended his way through several
batches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all how long you cook it, how long you beat it and when
you add the dry ingredients,'' he said before delving into the
finer points of fudgemaking.
</P>
<P>
   Like any master chef, he's a bit particular when it comes to the
ingredients. For example, he only uses Imperial and C&AMP;H sugars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cheaper stuff doesn't come out nearly as good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He also insists on using real butter but says any brand will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think it would make a difference, but it doesn't,''
he says. ``A cow's a cow.''
</P>
<P>
   As for chocolate, he tells students to go with Guittard and
Baker's brands:
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the only ones that give you a rounded flavor and all
the rich nuances of the chocolate,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Once the proper ingredients are assembled, it's time to stir.
Singleton uses a long-handled, black wooden spoon to blend the
sugar, marshmallows and condensed milk in his basic fudge recipe.
His favorite spoon is worn down to a straight line on the tip after
stirring more than 1,200 batches.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton tells a bit of his life story as he stirs. The
60-year-old Oklahoma native probably wouldn't have ever gotten into
the fudge business if the oil bust hadn't hit so hard in the '80s.
When his carpentry jobs dried up, fudge got his family through the
tough times.
</P>
<P>
   He sold his fudge at craft shows and then door to door,
eventually building a clientele of more than 1,500 customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got used to seeing The Fudge Man coming around,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife moved to Grapevine about two years ago, and
people there are just now learning about his way with nuts and
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the equipment and space that I used to have, so
we're doing this on a much smaller scale,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He prepares for the key moment of fudgemaking: taking the melted
concoction off the burner at precisely the right time. Not doing
so, he warns, is the biggest mistake most people make.
</P>
<P>
   He can usually tell by sight and texture when its ready, but he
warns novices to use a candy thermometer, which should read 245
degrees Fahrenheit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't use one of those thermometers you buy at the grocery
store,'' he says. ``They're cheap and not really accurate. Get one
from a bakers' supply company or cake-decorating shop.''
</P>
<P>
   When the concoction is ready, it's time to blend it with the
chocolate in a mixer. Singleton uses two classic KitchenAid mixers
and tells students to forget their favorite hand-held ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be able to be at least 225 amps to handle it,'' he
says. ``Otherwise, it will burn out the motor as it starts to
set.''
</P>
<P>
   He mixes batches for at least 12 minutes. For a more exotic
variety, such as his Chocolate Silk, he pours in amaretto and turns
on the mixer for 30 seconds more.
</P>
<P>
   He then stirs in the remaining dry ingredients and spoons the
fudge into a greased baking pan. Singleton lets it set for at least
30 minutes, although he says that the time can vary, based on
humidity, altitude and even barometric pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to store the fudge, Singleton recommends using a
glass jar with a plastic top, which will preserve it _ in the
fridge _ for up to 6 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ages in the jar and actually gets even smoother,'' says his
wife, Marie Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, for all his work, Jan Singleton can't eat the fudge he
creates because he is diabetic. But he doesn't seem to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the challenge of creating it,'' he says. ``It's fun for
me to see what I can come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   JAN SINGLETON'S BASIC BUTTERY FUDGE
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound butter
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces semisweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces miniature marshmallows
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces of nuts, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Mix butter, vanilla and chips in a mixing bowl and set aside. In
a shallow saucepan, heat sugar, marshmallows and condensed milk on
medium heat, stirring constantly with a long-handled spoon. Bring
to a boil. Cook until 245 degrees on a candy thermometer. Pour hot
mixture into the butter mixture and beat for 12 minutes. Add 6
ounces of nuts, if desired, and mix thoroughly. Turn out on a
greased cookie sheet and let set for at least 30 minutes. Cut into
bite-size pieces and store in a glass jar in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per ounce: 95 calories, 4 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 7 milligrams cholesterol, 28
milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE SILK FUDGE
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Substitute 1/4 cup amaretto for the vanilla in the basic fudge
recipe
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per ounce: 96 calories, 4 grams fat, 16
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 7 milligrams cholesterol, 28
milligrams sodium, 38 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKY ROAD FUDGE
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 2 3/4 pounds
</P>
<P>
   6 more ounces of miniature marshmallows and 6 ounces of shelled
walnuts, plus the basic fudge recipe
</P>
<P>
   Combine the hot chocolate mixture and butter mixture, then beat
for 15 minutes. Stir additional marshmallows and walnuts into the
mix until thoroughly blended. Turn out on a greased cookie sheet
and let it set at least 30 minutes. Cut into bite-size pieces and
put in a glass jar in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per ounce: 128 calories, 6 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 7 milligrams cholesterol, 28
milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Jan Singleton's fudge classes, call
the Grapevine Parks &AMP; Recreation Department at (817) 410-3470.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9159 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TRIVIA-2TAKES-NYT     12-02 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRIVIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PURSUING THE TRIVIAL, CHOOSE YOUR PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quiz shows have been around at least since the days of radio and
were also a staple of early television programs. Even though the
shows were broadcast through a speaker, they were often interactive
for their listeners, who would play along and shout out the answers
to the trivia questions along with the on-air contestants.
</P>
<P>
   At least they did in my family, where the nightly half-hour of
``Jeopardy'' was considered educational television.
</P>
<P>
   Trivia-quiz games also proved popular at parties. The original
Trivial Pursuit was a hot seller in the early 1980s. People
gathered together for the challenge of hopping little pie pans
around the game-board wheel in search of intellectual dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Multiplayer quiz games for the personal computer seem like a
natural step. In that market niche, You Don't Know Jack, which
bills itself as ``the irreverent quiz show party game,'' has
dominated the market since its release in 1995, and for good
reason.
</P>
<P>
   The game is programmed to respond to each player's keyboard
input with a variety of jokes and insults; it truly lives up to the
billing of interactivity that CD-ROMs promise. The game pumps mass
quantities of energy, humor and attitude into the television
quiz-show format with clever questions that combine popular culture
with typical general-knowledge topics.
</P>
<P>
   (A sample question on the subject of ``baked goods and the
height-challenged'' reads: ``The Keebler elves are what? (a)
nomadic; (b) carnivorous; (c) migratory, or (d) arboreal?'') The
Quiz Kids have grown up into the MTV generation.
</P>
<P>
   Head Rush, a spinoff of You Don't Know Jack, loosely follows the
same formula but aims for slightly younger players. Jeopardy! and
Rocky &AMP; Bullwinkle's Know-It-All Quiz Show are bookends for the age
groups, with the former intended for adults and the latter meant
for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   All the games reviewed here follow similar formats. They allow
one to three players to compete at the same time under names they
choose. Each player is assigned a specific key on the computer's
keyboard with which to ``buzz'' in ahead of the other players, and
a couple of the programs allow users to select an avatar, a
graphical character to represent the player on the computer's
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps as a nod to the impact of their broadcast forebears, all
the games here use the set of a television studio as a framing
device for the action.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of television, the Keebler elves are arboreal. In their
many commercials, they are shown living in trees. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YOU DON'T KNOW JACK VOLUME 4, THE RIDE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jellyvision and Berkeley Systems; $29.99; Windows 95 and 98,
Macintosh 7.1 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back with yet another edition, You Don't Know Jack comes
screeching onto your screen with 800 new questions, all with the
same tone of hip sarcasm that made the first three versions of the
game a hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Ride begins with an on-screen elevator descent. While the
floors pass by through the elevator's windows, an unseen guide goes
over the rules of the game and guides players through the setup.
</P>
<P>
   If your mind wanders and the game senses no keyboard response
when it asks you to type in your name in preparation for play, it
speaks right up with a sneer: ``Come on, this isn't television. You
have to (italics)work.''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   True to the television-style format, the game presents a wide
range of fake commercials and sponsors of imaginary products like
E.coli Diet Shakes. The background music veers from thunderous rock
to pure game-show cheese, and most of the hosts deliver the
questions in a smart-alecky manner reminiscent of the old Dennis
Miller ``Weekend Update'' segments on ``Saturday Night Live.'' But
it all fits with the hyperactive tone of the game.
</P>
<P>
   With spinning visuals and a steady backbeat of noise, trivia
questions are hurled toward players at a frenetic pace and in
varying formats. The Ride contains several minisections devoted to
word associations, including one called Road Kill in which terms
related to a clue float on the screen, daring you to buzz in on the
correct answer as a yellow line on a dark highway speeds by in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   The You Don't Know Jack game series has been quite successful
because of its take-no-prisoners attitude, bawdy humor and dazzling
graphics, and Volume 4 continues in that vein. The program itself
is quite huge, though, and users need a computer with at least 180
megabytes of free hard-disk space to install it.
</P>
<P>
   An online version of the game can be found at www.bezerk.com.
Jack has earned its reputation as a party animal, and between gags
about bodily functions, double-entendres and bad puns, the game
even manages to impart some wisdom. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JEOPARDY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Hasbro Interactive; $29.95; Windows 95 and 98.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This ... is ... Jeopardy!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular and cerebral game shows on the air is
now on a CD-ROM, complete with the familiar big blue board of
categories and the television host, Alex Trebek, doing the
voice-over as the moderator and appearing in digitized form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeopardy,'' which ran on NBC from 1964 to 1975 and has had
fresh episodes in syndication since 1984, has a unique format in
which players have to respond to an answer by providing the right
question.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
