<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9160 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOROS-WAKE-UP-CALL-RE     12-02 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOROS-WAKE-UP-CALL-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE SOROS' SORROWS: READ IT AND WEEP  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending from Nov. 30 for those needing)   (This interesting 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald Tribune.
  
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
  
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``i'' international news and ``a'' domestic/general
news files.)  
  
 By LAWRENCE MALKIN  
 c.1998 International Herald Tribune  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Soros, the greatest speculator of the age,
admitted in a book published worldwide Sunday that putting his
funds' money into Russia was ``the worst investment of my
professional career'' and warned that the world is heading into a
depression unless international finance is reformed soon.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Crisis of Global Capitalism,'' Soros has put together
many of his observations of recent years in a book that amounts to
a wake-up call from a man who knows his subject firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   This year the value of the Soros funds dropped from about $22
billion to $18 billion _ half of the losses vanished in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   One section of the book consists of his diary of how he tried to
prevent the August financial meltdown in Moscow, an experience that
he concedes demonstrated to him the difficulty of reconciling his
role as an investor with his efforts to help make Russia a
democratic society.
</P>
<P>
   He seeks neither sympathy nor redress for his losses, only a new
and more stable order for global finance, despite the fact that
less volatility would mean fewer opportunities for speculators like
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to prevent the global capitalist system from destroying
itself,'' he writes. It is as if Joseph P. Kennedy had demanded
stock-market regulation during the Roaring Twenties _ or, if Soros
is right, just before the crash of 1929.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book is devoted to an attack on what he calls the
dogma of ``market fundamentalism'' underlying the structure of the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
   At times he overstates the obvious, most notably in a lengthy
explanation of his favorite market theory of ``reflexivity,'' which
boils down to the observation that the thoughts and statements of
market players can affect the market.
</P>
<P>
   His definition of this unsurprising theory: ``Facts can be
influenced by making statements about them.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, when enough people chant the mantra of ``the magic
of the marketplace,'' Soros warns, this helps create the mass
delusion that the market solves all problems, whereupon people like
him bet that the herd will eventually stumble and he then picks up
the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   He explains how his theories have helped make this contrarian
rich, but lest he give away Soros Fund Management's crown jewels,
he cites few examples beyond his already well-documented
billion-dollar profit on the 1992 fall of the British pound.
</P>
<P>
   In the present crisis, he argues that more information for
lenders is not sufficient because markets are inherently unstable _
and ``how much instability can society take?''
</P>
<P>
   Soros proposes a carrot-and-stick combination that would help
guarantee loans to countries that disclose their full balance
sheets and penalize banks that ignored warning signs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having the International Monetary Fund serve as the
multinational banks' debt collector from devastated borrowers in
the developing world, the banks would have to swallow some of their
losses by turning bad debts into equity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the IMF's lending capacity would be increased
by issuing Special Drawing Rights to fill the financial hole
created by a default. The Special Drawing Right, or SDR, is an
artificial IMF reserve currency that central banks can cash in for
dollars and other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   This complex plan would be institutionalized by an International
Credit Insurance Corporation with access to all information about
outstanding loans, public and private, carried by borrowers and
lenders alike.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation would then decide what proportion of a loan to
guarantee at preferential interest rates. Foreign banks and
bondholders would be at risk for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that lenders could no longer count on IMF bailouts,
Soros argues, would put a powerful tool in the hands of the IMF and
``avoid excesses in either direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's publishing history demonstrates the public lack of
urgency about the problem. Originally contracted to Random House
for an advance of $50,000, a draft of the book was delivered this
summer to the publisher, which had recently been bought by
Bertelsmann AG of Germany. Soros urged Random House to move up the
publishing date from early 1999 to the autumn of this year.
</P>
<P>
   After Random House refused, the author went to PublicAffairs, a
small, new, and aggressive house, which shipped copies to U.S.
bookstores within two months of receiving his manuscript on Sept.
22.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, PublicAffairs sold the international rights for
$900,000, splitting the money in the traditional ratio of 75-25
between author and publisher in a financial coup worthy of, well,
George Soros. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this interesting 750-word article from the
International Herald Tribune, it must be purchased from New York
Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-TRIVIA-2NDTAKE-NY     12-02 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRIVIA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: right question.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The computerized version of the game transfers the format, as
well as the look of the ``Jeopardy'' television studio, to the
desktop. Three players compete in each match, although if you're
short on players, the game will provide electronic ones.
</P>
<P>
   When buzzing in, human players type in their responses on the
keyboard (although the program will provide the ``who is ...'' or
``what is ...'' half of the question for you) while the
cybercontestants get away with answering out loud.
</P>
<P>
   Users can choose three levels of play: normal, tournament and
speed match. In the normal game, which resembles the television
version, subject categories are paraded out and attached to the big
board along with rows of monetary figures.
</P>
<P>
   To choose a category and a dollar amount, click on the
appropriate square. The clue is read, and players can buzz in as
soon as the ``lockout'' lights come on. The lockout lights prevent
the human players from excitedly buzzing in while the clue is being
presented.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeopardy'' in any form has never pandered to the intelligence
(or lack thereof) of its audience. The game's subjects range from
the choreographer Twyla Tharp to obscure geography tidbits to the
reigns of foreign dictators. ``Yessss!'' Trebek often says when a
player comes up with the proper answer.
</P>
<P>
   The interface is fairly basic. To break up the monotony of
looking at the blue squares for the whole game, different views of
the virtual studio are displayed on the screen. The game will not
amuse you with inventive animations or witty repartee being mumbled
in the background; it is designed as a serious, stately game for
intelligent trivia buffs _ without the parting gifts for
contestants. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HEAD RUSH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jellyvision and Berkeley Systems; $29.95; for Windows 95 and
98, and Macintosh 7.1 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The box copy for Head Rush says: ``This product contains
immature content, loud body noises, a smattering of mildly saucy
language and references to music, TV shows and movies that will
definitely not be suitable for most geezers. Besides, they won't
get it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Who says there isn't truth in advertising these days?
</P>
<P>
   Aimed squarely at teen-agers, Head Rush is a junior version of
the hugely popular You Don't Know Jack, but it doesn't skimp on
features.
</P>
<P>
   The game format follows that of its older sibling: players pick
an avatar and a name, and they try to beat one another at pressing
their assigned keys on the keyboard in response to questions, then
select one of four multiple-choice answers.
</P>
<P>
   Players rack up large totals of imaginary money for nailing the
right answers to questions, but a wrong answer will result in
having your avatar disintegrate before your eyes, only to bounce
back for the next round.
</P>
<P>
   With thumping background music, slick animation, quick keyboard
responses and an unseen announcer moving things along between
questions, Head Rush manages to wrangle such unusual suspects as
Arnold Schwarzenegger, the bubble-gum pop group Hanson and
television's ``X-Files'' into questions that are actually about
classical music, grammar and history.
</P>
<P>
   The game allows a maneuver called Bite Your Neighbor, complete
with chomping little teeth, in which a player can jump in with the
answer if the first player who buzzed in stalls.
</P>
<P>
   As in You Don't Know Jack, there is also a section called Dis or
Dat that asks players to decide if a term flashed on the screen
falls into one of two categories. (``Famous Artist or Foreign Car _
Audi? El Greco? Alfa Romeo?'').
</P>
<P>
   Head Rush keeps up its level of prickly personalized attention
to the player at all times. ``Not bad, you only missed one!'' the
announcer will sometimes scoff after a round.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperactive as it is, Head Rush is also infectious, as long as
you do not tend to get easily upset or disgusted in the pursuit of
knowledge. It's like the high-school quiz bowl with humor about
embarrassing body functions thrown in. The game is loud, rude and
crude _ and teen-agers will probably love it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROCKY &AMP; BULLWINKLE'S KNOW-IT-ALL QUIZ GAME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Houghton Mifflin Interactive; $19.95; Windows 95 and 98, and
Macintosh 7.1 and later.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For young trivia fans not quite old enough to handle You Don't
Know Jack or Jeopardy but who still want to play, Rocky &AMP;
Bullwinkle's Know-It-All Quiz Game might be a good choice. The
original Jay Ward cartoon television shows starring Rocket J.
Squirrel and Bullwinkle J. Moose ran from 1959 to 1973 and have
been in perpetual reruns ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The Know-It-All Quiz Game transfers much of the look, sly humor
and insider asides from the show to the CD-ROM. (``What's an
avatar?'' the moose asks as the program prepares the players for
action. ``Bullwinkle!'' the squirrel scolds. ``Didn't you pay
attention at the production meeting?'')
</P>
<P>
   The game takes its time, and several screens, setting up the
action. Players select the level of questioning (Easy or Hard),
pick avatars to represent themselves, then choose virtual teammates
from the Bullwinkle stable, including Peabody the talking dog,
Dudley Do-Right and, of course, the consummate foes Boris and
Natasha.
</P>
<P>
   Intended for players age 9 to 12, the program is designed as a
straightforward quiz show with three rounds of play. The first two
rounds consist of multiple-choice questions, and the third is a
true-false test. In the first round, players are with their
selected team members, who comment on the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we have the superior team,'' Peabody proclaims every
so often after a correct answer. Most of the questions seem on
target for the preteen-age audience the game is aimed at; they
range from stumpers about the book ``Johnny Tremain'' and basic
history and science trivia.
</P>
<P>
   The animation in the program is simple and somewhat jerky, much
like the animation in the television show, and the pace of play is
not particularly fast.
</P>
<P>
   The game does not dump hundreds of megabytes onto your hard
drive, however, and the system requirements are fairly low, so you
do not have to have the latest and greatest hardware for your kids
to see Boris and Natasha plotting (italics)beeg(end italics)
trouble for moose and squirrel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1542EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOROS-WAKE-UP-CALL-RE     12-02 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOROS-WAKE-UP-CALL-RESEND-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE SOROS' SORROWS: READ IT AND WEEP  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending from Nov. 30 for those needing)   (This interesting 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
  
