<HEADER>
A9185 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-REVISED-HISTORY     12-02 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-REVISED-HISTORY-RESEND-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHT-WINGERS REVISE JAPAN'S HISTORY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending from Nov. 30 for those needing)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS EASILY-CUT
ARTICLE STANDS IN 850 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT VERSION RUNS 975.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``i'' international news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Everywhere you go in Tokyo _ hanging from the straps on
crowded underground trains, in cafes, restaurants, and in parks _
you will come across people reading ``manga,'' the plump, pulpy
Japanese comic books.
</P>
<P>
   There are kids' manga about sci-fi robots, sentimental ``ladies'
manga'' about young women looking for romance, and graphic
gentlemen's manga, featuring a different kind of lady in various
states of undress.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's most fashionable and original comic book could
hardly be more different: it is 400 pages long, packed with dense,
polemical text and bears the solemn title of ``Sensoron: Theory
About The War.''
</P>
<P>
   Its author is Yoshinori Kobayashi, a lean, bespectacled young
intellectual, a frequent guest on television discussion programs
and the principal character of his own comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, compiled from his bi-monthly contributions to a
popular magazine, Kobayashi orchestrates historical argument,
dramatized scenes of past and present, and horrible caricatures of
his intellectual adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   It all presents a simple message: that, contrary to the view
propagated in the West, Japan's invasions of Asia during the
Pacific War were not the brutal actions of a predatory colonizer.
They were a noble and valiant undertaking, carried out with
discipline and restraint, and their effect was to liberate Asians
from the colonial dominance of Western imperialists.
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, a group of former Allied PoWs left Tokyo
bitterly disappointed after losing their claim for compensation and
apology. The pages of ``Sensoron,'' it is fair to predict, would
leave them in despair.
</P>
<P>
   A typical sequence of frames shows ugly Caucasians with fat lips
and outsized noses sticking Union Jacks, Stars and Stripes and
Tricolors into a map of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   In the next box, stern but noble Japanese soldiers surge across
the map, snapping the puny flags to the chagrin of the hideous
whiteys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white Western countries thought of colored people like us
as primitive monkeys and colonized the countries of East Asia,''
runs the text. ``It was the Japanese army which beat them. Let's
give them a round of applause.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a strain of such thinking in Japan _ in
Tokyo and most big cities, so-called ``rightists'' can be seen
every day blaring martial music from black trucks painted with
rising suns, and eulogizing the Emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the din, few Japanese regarded them as more than noisy
middle-aged eccentrics. Kobayashi, by contrast, is young,
widely-read and cool.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the success of his comic has fostered a
surprising and in some ways an alarming trend _ a revival of
right-wing revisionism about Japan's war among the youngest and
cleverest Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never used to talk to my friends about these things, but
it's all changed in the last two years,'' says Tomomi Yamada, a
26-year old magazine editor, and a fan of ``Sensoron.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're Japanese, and you start raising questions about
Japan in the war, people always used to point the finger and say,
`rightist!' Now my friends talk about it and a lot of them agree
with me. It's terrific, and Kobayashi has had a big influence.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan's right-wing revival has little in common with those of
Europe and _ with her polite English and fluffy sweater _ Ms.
Yamada could hardly be further from a drooling neo-Nazi. Once a
month she attends a meeting of the Japan Public Opinion Society, a
discussion group of like-minded people, to hear speeches by
conservative historians.
</P>
<P>
   These days as many as half the members of the audience are her
own age; when she first attended, three years ago, very few were.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the speakers were saying was so different from what we
were taught in school, that Japan fought an aggressive war,'' she
says. ``It was shocking and new, and very attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   A frequent subject of discussion is the 1937 Rape of Nanking.
According to most Western and many Japanese historians, the
imperial army embarked on an orgy of killing, looting and rape
which left at least 100,000 dead _ the Chinese reckon it could have
been as many as 300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``To kill 300,000 you would need two nuclear bombs,'' asserts
Kobayashi. ``It couldn't be done with Japanese guns.''
</P>
<P>
   His book has gone through 17 printings and some 400,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   This year's most successful Japanese film was ``Pride,'' an epic
eulogy to Hideki Tojo, the wartime prime minister hanged as a war
criminal 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over a million copies have been sold of a series of books
entitled ``The History Which The Textbooks Don't Teach,'' by a
group of revisionist historians irritated with the increasingly
liberal tenor of history teaching in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese are depicted as criminals on whose shoulders fate
has placed the burden of atoning for their sins for generations to
come,'' says one of the authors, Professor Nobukatsu Fujioka of
Tokyo University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current Japanese textbooks include the wartime propaganda of
former enemies, treating it as though it were historical fact.'' &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 850. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Unlike Western neo-Nazis, Japanese revisionists have never
turned their intellectual agenda into any kind of political action,
and the numbers of committed activists is probably small, even if
their influence is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends very much on social conditions, and whether the
economic situation gets worse or not,'' says Tesuya Miyazaki, a
writer who frequently speaks out against Kobayashi and his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the post-war period everyone in Japan thought of themselves
as middle class, but now things are changing and gaps are opening
up between the top and bottom, and between parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the confusion that Kobayashi speaks to _ it's not that
people are trying to revive the spirit of the war, just a feeling
of togetherness.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
