<HEADER>
A9190 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-FASHIONS-LADN     12-02 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-FASHIONS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOIREE SAVVY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; 'Tis the season for opulence and office parties.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is up, businesses are celebrating, and people are
excited about dressing up again, says Milinda Martin, fashion
spokeswoman for Robinsons-May stores. But after such a long dry
spell, many employees don't have a clue about what's new and
yule-cool, much less about office politics to keep your name out of
the rumor mill.
</P>
<P>
   So is it safer for women to wear basic black or go for festive
red festooned in feathers? Are sweaters better or should
corporate-climbing guys invest in vests?
</P>
<P>
   ``The office party is one of the most difficult social events to
dress for because you need to get the right mix between festive and
professional,'' says Martin. ``One of the best options is what we
call evening sportswear, items that can be interchanged to dress up
an outfit.''
</P>
<P>
   Think color. Think sparkle. Think simple but elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds easy enough, right? Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   We loaded the car with clothes and put style standards to the
test by consulting that fashionably frisky office staff on the set
of NBC's sitcom ``Working,'' and even the actors who play the
dysfunctionally funny crew couldn't settle on the same look.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Savage, who plays young college graduate Matt Peyser,
traded his trademark business suit for a cheery red pull-over
sweater with polo shirt detailing by Tommy Hilfiger. ``Nothing too
flashy ... I like to be casual,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Too flashy? There's no such phrase in Debi Mazar's world, thank
you very much. The newest addition to the ensemble cast plays Liz,
a saucy and ambitious office worker with an in-your-face 'tude, who
likes high drama in her wardrobe. With a toss of her red
fur-trimmed stole, Mazar advised, ``Always wear something you'd
never wear during office hours. You want them to talk!''
</P>
<P>
   So much for staying out of the rumor mill. At this rate, she'll
be the talk of the office the Monday after _ unless Arden Myrin
gets her way.
</P>
<P>
   Myrin, who plays perky Abby, the unofficial office cheerleader,
also goes for the glam, zeroing in on a red and leopard print
velvet number by Mica.
</P>
<P>
   As she tries on the dress, she explains, ``Abby's a little
naive, like a cruise director or a sorority girl who's just so
organized and cares so much about social events, so she'd want a
complete ensemble, like this velvet dress. And that coat with the
feathers. And the tiara.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Not only are feathers and tiaras showing up at
stores all over the country, but velvet is one of the hottest
fabrics of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Says style authority Leah Feldon, who's the author of ``Dress
Like a Million _ On Considerably Less'' and fashion consultant for
Wards stores, ``Fabrics with textures, sparkle and color are what
will make the biggest impact at the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Hytner, the ``Working'' cast's bitter and sarcastic
Delaney, was hip to the vibe on velvet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the all-black look with a turtleneck sweater is in, but
my character wouldn't wear the matching sweater,'' Hytner says as
he tosses the sweater and buttons up a white dress shirt with his
night-clubby Claiborne blazer and trousers in black velveteen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party tips? You need false sincerity (to impress the boss and
score with chicks).
</P>
<P>
   ``The best attitude after you've made a fool of yourself?
Denial!
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if they've got actual photos of you misbehaving, you'd
better have your own set of photos,'' he quips.
</P>
<P>
   Then Maurice Godin jumped into the fashion fest.
</P>
<P>
   The actor who plays the opportunistic, morally challenged
corporate boss, says, ``Ahh, the office party rules. I know ...
never get drunker than the boss. And always watch to see who the
boss is hitting on and steer clear of that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Suiting up in an elegant Hugo Boss suit and knotting his Donna
Karan tie, Godin laughs. ``Oh, you wanted real advice? I think you
should consider having it away from the office so everyone is on
the same footing, and can feel free to wear what they want,'' he
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Myrin is back in the dressing room to change into another party
dress, and confesses she's having a blast. ``When it comes to
dressing up, I tend to overdo it. I like boas, big red lips ... and
anything frivolous. And I have lots of tiaras,'' she explains.
``But I guess if I were giving advice to a new person in the
office, I'd say, `Look pretty, but not too sexy. And work the
outskirts of the party instead of being the center of attention so
you won't be talked about.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line? ``To avoid career suicide, never step out of
character,'' says Yvette Freeman, who plays Evelyn, the bossy
know-it-all office manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``My character is a hard-nosed company liner, so she wants to
show the staff she does have a fun side. But no party hat,'' she
snaps.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca McFarland, who plays the ultra-sexy secretary, refused
to wear a party hat, too. She squeezed into a slinky gown, loaded
herself down with rhinestones, and wrapped up in a big boa and
stretched out on the sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-oh. A low-cut dress isn't what most fashion mavens or
professional consultants would advise. A much safer fashion
alternative for office parties is a sweater, says Martin, because
it's festive and glam but not overly sexy.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland changes into a sweater, but she's still a tad too
saucy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in doubt, consider Martin's rule when in a
professional party setting: ``Never expose skin in more than one
place at one time. If you've got a slit up your skirt, don't have a
bare back.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
