<HEADER>
A9221 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-BOX-$ADV05-     12-02 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-BOX-$ADV05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PRIMER ON VENEZUELA
 &HT;    With VENEZUELA-ELECTION-$ADV05.
 &HT;    For Use Saturday, Dec. 5 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERE ARE FACTS AND FIGURES ABOUT VENEZUELA, THE UPCOMING
ELECTION:
</P>
<P>
   Size: 340,569 square miles, about twice the size of California.
</P>
<P>
   Population: 23 million.
</P>
<P>
   Government: Federal republic of 21 states. There are two
legislative houses; a Senate with 49 seats and a Chamber of
Deputies with 201 seats.
</P>
<P>
   Capital: Caracas; population 5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Currency: Bolivar.
</P>
<P>
   Language: Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Independence: July 5, 1811; from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Religion: Predominantly Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Illiteracy: 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Life expectancy: 73 years.
</P>
<P>
   President: Rafael Caldera, 82.
</P>
<P>
   Natural resources: Petroleum, natural gas, gold, bauxite, and
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Main political parties: Center-left Democratic Action and
center-right COPEI.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates: Former coup leader Hugo Chavez, Yale-educated
businessman Henrique Salas, and former Miss Universe Irene Saez.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runner: Hugo Chavez, an independent.
</P>
<P>
   Issues: Voters are shunning the traditional parties, blaming
them for a bloated state and patronage system, as well as
corruption, inflation, and widespread poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
