<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     12-02 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOURNING A LOSS TOO OFTEN IGNORED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the day the postman turned it over to me nearly eight
years ago, the small wooden box _ about 2 inches by 4 inches _ has
sat undisturbed on the mantel in my den.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I had the emotional strength to open it, to touch the
ashes inside, to smell them, but I don't. I had loved Snuggles _
the Samoyed my husband gave me as a wedding present _ as if she
were a child.
</P>
<P>
   Just about the time we were settled into our new home in Fort
Worth and were ready to send for Snuggles, my friend who had been
caring for her in Sacramento called to say that mu dog had died.
Rather than bury her in California, I asked that she be cremated
and her ashes forwarded. The thought of having her so far away was
too painful.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think much about losing Snuggles anymore; somehow, I
find comfort in the presence of that small wooden box. There is no
such comfort, however, when I remember the baby I miscarried.
</P>
<P>
   He was at 11 weeks gestation, and few states, if any, would even
consider him human.
</P>
<P>
   And so today, I hope someone will read my words and do for me
and other North Texas women who've lost their babies what the
Milton S. Hershey Medical Center has done for women in
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, I read a story on the news wire about a
$12,000 communal burial site for stillborn babies, miscarriages and
ectopic pregnancies had been dedicated in September and will be
maintained by the medical center through private donations.
</P>
<P>
   Graveside services will be held quarterly, and infants will be
buried in common graves, each marked by a gray stone. The first
memorial service was held Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Such burial sites are becoming increasingly common, said Fran
Rybarik, director of Bereavement Services of Gundersen Lutheran
Medical Center in La Crosse, Wis., the model for the Hershey
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do the training, we ask people to look at what's
available and fill the gap,'' Rybarik said. ``But not all programs
opt to provide the burial site.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two Fort Worth hospitals, John Peter Smith and Harris
Methodist downtown, offer services to couples who have lost a baby
through miscarriage, ectopic pregnancy, stillbirth or neonatal
death. At John Peter Smith, an annual memorial service is held for
people who have suffered those sorts of losses. A marker dedicated
to ``the memories of our babies'' stands at the hospital's west
entrance, proclaiming ``our tears for lost smiles, our grief for
lost dreams and our courage to find them.'' But although some
funeral homes provide a designated area for infants, no common
burial ground is available in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a world that sometimes seems to honor its pets more than it
does its children, it is the least we can do.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are few, if any, tangible memories of these
infants, ``many people minimize the loss,'' said Dan Baker,
coordinator of John Peter Smith's perinatal bereavement program.
</P>
<P>
   To alleviate the problem, both Fort Worth hospitals work to
create memories for parents when possible, taking pictures of the
infant, for instance, or allowing parents to hold the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people want to view the baby, even if it's just
tissue,'' Baker said. ``We don't push this on people, but if they
need to do that, it's very therapeutic.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the size of the fetus _ 20 weeks gestation or more
under Texas law _ some parents are given a birth and death
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   But if you miscarry before then, as I did 10 years ago, there
are no tangible memories. It is as if your baby never existed.
</P>
<P>
   A common burial ground could help change that.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
