<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9236 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      12-02 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN Q &AMP; A 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LESLIE LAND    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOO MUCH SMOTHERING
</P>
<P>
   Q. Three years ago, I transplanted three rhubarb plants. I
smother them with manure early in spring, during the summer and at
the end of the summer. Yet, all I get are thin stalks, although
they came from a plant that gave my friends wide stalks.
</P>
<P>
   A. It sounds as if you might be smothering them more than they
can stand. Rhubarb is a heavy feeder, it's true, and composted
manure is a fine fertilizer, especially if you are using what my
neighbors call ``hen dressing.'' But too much of a good thing is
still too much; one generous application each year should be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Heap it on in late fall, after the plants have gone fully
dormant, or in early spring, before they start active growth. Give
them a side dressing of compost in mid-spring and a small amount of
balanced commercial fertilizer _ or more composted manure _ when
you are almost done harvesting. Be sure to mulch heavily all
through the growing season. Rhubarb does best when its roots stay
cool and get plenty of moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Thin stalks may simply mean that the plants are young and not
yet well established, but they can also indicate overcrowding.
Rhubarb plants should be at least three feet apart in all
directions.
</P>
<P>
   Shade might also be the culprit. Although rhubarb will survive
low-light conditions, it must be grown in full sun to produce
thick, flavorful stalks.
</P>
<P>
   Tilden, a variety that has very broad stalks, is available from
Fedco Trees, P.O. Box 520, Waterville, Maine 04903-0520; (207)
878-7333; catalog, $2. Chipman's Canada Red, which can be a bit
sweeter and is noted for strong color that comes through cooking
well, is sold by Henry Field's Seed and Nursery, 415 North Burnett,
Shenandoah, Iowa 51602; (605) 665-4491; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   WINTERING HOSTAS
</P>
<P>
   Q. I grew hostas in pots this past summer. How do I keep them
over the winter?
</P>
<P>
   A. Tough perennials like hostas don't mind frozen ground, but
they suffer when subjected to repeated freeze-thaw cycles, and most
pots hold so little soil they make such cycles likely. Repeated
freezing and thawing is also hard on the pots themselves: plastic
becomes increasingly brittle, terra cotta tends to chip and crack,
and even cement may break if tiny fissures get filled with water
that swells into ice over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   You can store the potted hostas in an unheated garage or shed
where temperatures stay between 32 and 40 degrees Fahrenheit. Or
you can protect both plants and pots by burying them right up to
the rim. Make sure the soil around clay pots is free of rocks that
might shift and cause damage. Mulch after the ground freezes to
help it stay frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Truly huge ``estate size'' planters (think the bottom third of a
telephone booth) may be left in place; there's safety in volume.
But pots that fall in the middle _ too big to bury, too small to
trust _ should be emptied. Same goes for planters made of wood,
which is vulnerable to rot. Transfer the plants to plastic pots,
and store or bury them as above; then, turn the planters upside
down so water doesn't collect in them.
</P>
<P>
   All else failing, just group the pots together and insulate as
best you can. There's a good chance they'll come through fine.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
