<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TIFFANY-WINDOWS-ART-6     12-02 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIFFANY-WINDOWS-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CHURCH FIGHTS TO RESTORE WINDOWS WITH A TIFFANY LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: A 200-wd sidebar on an upcoming auction of Tiffany works
follows article.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CAROLINE SEEBOHM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ When you enter the long nave of St. James African
Methodist Episcopal Church here, there is a deep, rich glow near
the altar, coming from windows that pulsate with color and light.
The dazzling interplay of emerald greens, dark blues, ambers and
rubies inspires a feeling verging on rapture. Anyone seeing these
six windows will wonder if they are by Louis Comfort Tiffany. The
answer is a definite ``maybe'' and, in fact, the mystery may never
be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   St. James Church stands on a hill in a blighted area of Newark.
Originally Presbyterian, it became African Methodist Episcopal in
1945. Today, the Rev. Dr. William Watley presides over the church,
which provides free meals daily and support to its community.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting this hard-working place, one feels like the person who
goes into a grandmother's attic and discovers an Old Master
painting. The fine 1850 Gothic-style building was designed by John
Welch, with extensive additions in the 1890s by Carrere &AMP; Hastings.
In the addition there is a magnificent south-facing rose window,
six feet in diameter. Five of the six stained glass windows
surrounding the altar depict religious scenes; the other one shows
a woman looking out into a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Churches in the New York area that have Tiffany windows include,
most notably, St. Michael's Episcopal Church, at 225 W. 99th St.
and, on Long Island, St. Andrew's Dune Church in Southampton, the
Church of the Atonement in Quogue, St. John's Episcopal Church in
Cold Spring Harbor (near the site where Tiffany built his country
home, Laurelton Hall) and St. Mark's Episcopal Church in Islip.
</P>
<P>
   While Tiffany windows add a spiritual and esthetic dimension to
churches, their maintenance is a huge responsibility, particularly
if the buildings pass from affluent memberships to those struggling
to meet parishioners' needs. A congregation in Brooklyn that was
selling the All Souls Universalist church in 1997 decided to lend
its two Tiffany windows to the Brooklyn Museum. (At least the
windows were not sold; Christie's valued the pair at $120,000 to
$160,000.)
</P>
<P>
   As for the St. James windows in Newark, it is not certain they
are by Tiffany. All documents relating to the building of the
church were burned, and local newspapers contain no record of its
erection. Nor are the windows listed in the 1912 inventory of
Tiffany's work. But Arthur Femenella, one of the leading Tiffany
glass consultants in the country, points out several reasons why
the Tiffany attribution is convincing.
</P>
<P>
   ``These windows were put in at a later date than the other ones
in the church,'' he said, ``probably in the 1890s, when the Carrere
&AMP; Hastings addition was being built. Thomas Hastings had worked
with Tiffany on the Seventh Regiment Armory in Manhattan, and it
seems likely he brought the artist with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Femenella said the glass is of the highest quality. ``The
studio's full arsenal of artistic weapons has been unleashed
here,'' he said. ``The drapery glass in particular bears the mark
of Tiffany. The emphasis on landscape and foliage is typical of
Tiffany. Finally, the use of copper foil in the windows was rarely
used by glass designers other than Tiffany.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Lennox, the owner of Stained Glass Imagery Inc. of Staten
Island, is in charge of restoring the windows. ``Up to four or five
layers of glass have been used to give a three-dimensional
impression, like relief work,'' he said. ``The chunk glass around
the memorial plaques is very Tiffany. The rondels are like
handblown jewels.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany or not, the windows are in need of help. ``Lead in
stained glass windows should be replaced every 50 to 100 years,''
Lennox said. ``The protective plexiglass put up over the rose
window has actually been detrimental, creating a climate of
moisture between the covering and the window that has rotted the
wood and encouraged termites.'' The rose window is being removed,
then cleaned and releaded in Lennox's studio. It will be reset in
the church in March in restored wood frames.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The St. James congregation hired Annabelle Radcliffe-Trenner, a
preservation architect in Princeton, N.J., to examine the entire
building and give a diagnosis. The news was not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crisis management,'' Ms. Radcliffe-Trenner said. ``We are
doing emergency work simply to prevent further deterioration. Damp,
rot, removal of tar _ the list is endless. We removed 15 dead
pigeons from the roof. We should be making long-term plans, but the
cost is prohibitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Historic Trust gave St. James the largest loan it
has ever made, $450,000, toward the repair of the roof, the
building's stonework and the rose window. But Calvin Jackson, a
church trustee who is overseeing the restoration, said that even
that sum will not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime these days people crowd the dining hall for a free
meal and a prayer, to the accompaniment of the sound of hammering
on the church roof. St. James has vowed not to sell its treasures.
Instead, it continues to look after its flock under their jeweled
light.
</P>
<P>
   A HAMMER'S FALL
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Interest in Tiffany continues. Along with the Tiffany
exhibition at the Metropolitan Museum and a collection of historic
church stained glass at the American Bible Society, Christie's is
holding an auction next Thursday devoted exclusively to Tiffany
works. The prices that Christie's estimates the objects will bring
are an indication of how well Tiffany pieces have done at auction
previously.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's is offering a clematis skylight from the Harbel
mansion in Akron, Ohio, circa 1915, which it estimates will bring
$90,000 to $120,000; a brilliantly colored window showing a young
woman with auburn hair ($70,000 to $100,000), and floor and table
lamps with themes as varied as poppies, peonies and fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   A star of the auction is a magnolia leaded-glass and gilt bronze
floor lamp, circa 1913. A similar one brought a record $993,500 in
June. Also at auction is a mantel clock covered in mosaics with a
band of linked peacock ``eyes'' ($28,000 to $36,000). Viewing
begins Saturday at Christie's. The auction is scheduled for 2 p.m.
next Thursday. The catalog is $35 from (800) 395-6300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
