</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSSIL-FISH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSSIL OF 90-MILLION-YEAR-OLD FISH FOUND IN TEXAS LANDFILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mountains of waste will soon be heaped into the
newest trash pit at Hunter Ferrell Landfill, but for now, the hole
is home to a prehistoric prize.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled 60 feet under the landfill are fossilized pieces of an
8- to 12-foot-long xiphactinus, a menacing fish with razor-sharp
teeth and powerful jaws, that roamed waterways 90 million years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The fish's fin, jaw, teeth and a string of vertebrae were
discovered Monday by workers who were digging a pit at the
landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't ever expect to find interesting treasures when
we're digging the holes. It's always when we are filling it,'' said
Mary Nix, disposal manager for the Irving Department of Public
Health and Environmental Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I called `a dino-fish,' '' Nix said. ``It's
big.''
</P>
<P>
   After being excavated, portions of the fossil were taken to
Southern Methodist University in Dallas, where the fish was
identified by Louis Jacobs, a professor of geological sciences.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I heard is that because of the rain, they had moved to
another area to dig, and that's the only reason they saw it,''
Jacobs said. ``If they hadn't been digging there, it would have
never been found. It would have been forever under the trash pit.''
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the fossil were taken to the Dallas Museum of Natural
History Tuesday afternoon for further study. Museum officials said
they hope to continue the dig.
</P>
<P>
   Herminio Beltran, a 21-year-old employee with the L.D. Kemp
excavation company, unearthed the fossil while operating an
excavator.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran said that he often looks for fossils when digging and
that he wasn't surprised by the find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found the head first,'' he said. ``It was different than the
rock. It looked black.''
</P>
<P>
   Excitement about the find spread quickly among area experts in
geology and paleontology, the study of fossils.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have one that good here'' at SMU, Jacobs said. ``It's
just a beautiful specimen. The head is out, but all the pieces are
there, and it can be prepared beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Fiorillo, curator of paleontology at the Dallas museum,
said the find will complement a less-than-perfect xiphactinus on
display in the museum's Oryx Hall, which showcases Texas dinosaurs
and prehistoric turtles, fish and other animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the specimen is how much of it is there,''
Fiorillo said.
</P>
<P>
   The remains of the carnivorous fish were found in shale from the
Eagleford Formation, dating to the Cretaceous Period. At the time
this type of fish traveled the oceans, dinosaurs roamed the land.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Head, a graduate student in paleontology at SMU, said the
xiphactinus was an ancestor of the tarpon, an ocean game fish. But
this fish, which averaged 15 feet in length, had an appetite for
other creatures of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a large predatory fish,'' Head said, noting that a
xiphactinus specimen in Kansas was found with a fish in its
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   The stomach of the Irving Xiphactinus has not been found, but
experts said they hope the fish died shortly after eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they find another fish in its belly,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
