<HEADER>
A9339 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     12-02 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS, REPUBLICANS SEEK THE SAME ENDS THROUGH DIFFERENT MEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) ,
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If strangers from another planet studied the policy
declarations of Democrats and Republicans running for president in
2000, they might wonder what, if any, the differences are between
America's major political parties.
</P>
<P>
   What issues, they might ask, split the two most dramatically?
</P>
<P>
   Both parties' hopefuls speak confidently of reforming education.
They promise to save Social Security and Medicare. They talk about
cutting taxes, pledge protection of the environment, vow to fight
crime and strengthen our national defense.
</P>
<P>
   None of them so far have suggested huge federal programs of the
kind created during the presidencies of Franklin D. Roosevelt and
Lyndon B. Johnson. Few, if any, indicate a preference for the
discredited isolationist, protectionist policies of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be presidents generally agree about the areas where
action should be taken to strengthen America and move it
confidently into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   So how does Al Gore differ from George W. Bush or Dick Gephardt
from Dan Quayle or Bob Kerrey from Lamar Alexander or Bill Bradley
from Steve Forbes?
</P>
<P>
   The answer lies in the details of the initiatives they offer and
the priorities they assign to those initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Take education, for example. Both parties recognize that
schools, especially those in the central city, need improvement.
But how can improvement be achieved?
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats would channel more billions into recruiting
additional teachers, building classrooms and rejuvenating the
public school system.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also talk of constructing classrooms and adding
teachers, but they focus most on the voucher system, which provides
students from poor areas with money to enroll in upscale private
and parochial schools in affluent neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats claim that in channeling money away from public
schools and into private institutions, the government would destroy
the public school system, which is one of the treasures of our
republic.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats seriously question whether the voucher plan, which
may violate our historic devotion to the separation of church and
state, is constitutional. They also question whether the money
provided by vouchers would be adequate to support poor children in
schools with hefty tuition requirements.
</P>
<P>
   And what, they ask, would be the fate of those children left
behind in substandard public schools?
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans assert that Democratic opposition to the voucher
system is motivated by the fact that a majority of members of the
National Education Association and other teachers' unions are
staunch supporters of the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that the voucher plan provides parents with a needed
choice of where their children should be educated and makes schools
competitive with one another.
</P>
<P>
   So the issue before voters is not whether one party or the other
would try to make education better. The question is how it should
be done.
</P>
<P>
   Times and politics are changing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Democratic Party has been able to count on
strong backing from women, African Americans, Hispanics, gays and
the underprivileged. But in last month's election, Republicans
George W. Bush in Texas and Jeb Bush in Florida were elected to
governorships with sizable support from Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   A similar situation confronts the GOP. In previous elections,
they have been able to count on a tremendous turnout of members of
the religious right, who oppose abortion, want to mandate prayer in
public classrooms and favor such other things as term limits for
members of Congress and reduced federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, however, the religious right split its vote far more
than it has in recent years. That is one reason Republicans lost
seats in the House and failed to gain any in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, Democrats tend to adhere to Bill Clinton's
pledge to ``save Social Security first'' with funds from America's
first federal budget surplus in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidates do not question the need to
save Social Security and Medicare. But their priorities include
returning sizable portions of surpluses to voters in the form of
tax cuts. They also would move toward privatizing Social Security
by encouraging investment in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Accepting the GOP presidential nomination in 1960, Richard Nixon
sought to move to a new political plateau, far removed from the
bitter, red-baiting demagoguery of his past.
</P>
<P>
   He contended therefore that Democrats, who had just nominated
John F. Kennedy for president, and Republicans sought similar ends
but through different means. The means he advocated were, of
course, those of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   If Nixon returned to earth today, he would recognize that the
battle between the two parties still is less over the ends desired
by Democrats and Republicans than the means to attain those ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
