</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-MUSEUM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPANSION PLAN FOR FORT WORTH MUSEUM IS BIG-LEAGUE STEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ I've always respected the Amon Carter
Museum. Its collections are great. Its staff is sophisticated,
utterly professional and devoted to its mission. The goals are
lofty. The programs are first-class.
</P>
<P>
   But, greedy me, I've always wanted more. I want to walk into the
Amon Carter and experience the sort of thrill that comes from
simply being in the Kimbell Art Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, I've wanted to get excited about the Carter as a
place _ and that means getting excited about its architecture.
</P>
<P>
   And now I'll have my chance, thanks to Philip Johnson's new plan
for the museum. Adopted by museum trustees last week, it more than
triples the space for showing art, by far the Carter's most crucial
need. But it also has the potential to give the Carter a shot of
architectural charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson designed the original 1961 structure, with its splendid
view and its shell-stone walls, as a memorial to museum founder
Amon G. Carter Sr. Johnson also designed the two additions.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Johnson said recently, none of those structures was
designed as a museum, which may be why experiencing the Carter can
be confusing. Elation over the superb artworks turns to anxiety as
the exhibition spaces that start out so grandly in the main gallery
become jumbled and cramped in the mezzanine galleries.
</P>
<P>
   That's about to change, however. Because finally, Carter
officials have commissioned Johnson and his partner, Alan Ritchie,
to design them a museum _ one that will crystallize, in the form of
a new building, all of the Carter's keenly focused sense of
identity as a major repository of American paintings, sculpture,
photographs and other works on paper.
</P>
<P>
   For, although the Carter memorial collection comprised works by
Remington and Russell _ works that remain central to the museum's
identity _ it has grown far beyond that. The museum owns key
paintings by 19th-century artists such as Thomas Cole and Martin
Johnson Heade; paintings and sculptures by early modernists such as
Georgia O'Keeffe, Elie Nadelman, Charles Demuth and Stuart Davis;
and photographs by giants including Robert Frank and Paul
Outerbridge, as well as by gifted anonymous photographers. The
collection has grown from 400 to almost 300,000 artworks.
</P>
<P>
   What the plan calls for is radical: nothing less than
demolishing and rebuilding two-thirds of the structure. All that
would remain of the current museum is the initial memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of doing away with so much space that simply doesn't
work is exhilarating in itself. But Johnson's plan _ and no
construction timetable has been announced _ is outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's all that exhibition space: more than
27,000 square feet. The plan also calls for a 170-seat auditorium,
a paper-conservation lab, improved library and research facilities,
a larger retail space and an additional public entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the original entrance will bring visitors into a
space once again dedicated to Amon G. Carter Sr.'s collection and
other works representing the 19th-century American frontier. Apart
from introducing visitors to the museum's origins, this space will
become an entry into the larger museum via an atrium _ canopied to
admit natural light _ that will also link it to the new south
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The new structure's second floor will house galleries for the
permanent collection of paintings and sculpture, space for showing
works on paper, and 4,000 square feet devoted to the photography
collection. More than 5,000 square feet will be reserved for major
traveling shows.
</P>
<P>
   This plan catapults the Carter into a new league
architecturally: It will go from being a decent building by an
important architect to a major statement about Philip Johnson. The
plan says that Johnson is a creator of witty, memorable
architectural statements and a sober, bread-and-butter
problem-solver. And it synthesizes both identities in one building.
</P>
<P>
   His new, chunky museum building becomes a simple but obviously
fine setting for his Carter memorial _ underscoring its stylized,
classical design as a rare architectural gem representing a
significant period in his restless career. Clad in a luscious brown
Arabian granite that contrasts beautifully with the shell stone of
the '61 building, it will make us look at and consider that
original structure as much more than the showy front end for a
couple of make-do additions.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, I see this plan as a vindication of Johnson's career: It
gives both the Carter and the architect's reputation a new lease on
life.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
