<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-ARREST (Washington) _ U.S. troops on Wednesday arrested
Radislav Krstic, a Bosnian Serb general accused in the massacre of
thousands of Muslims in Srebrenica in 1995. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-REVIEW (Washington) _ World Bank issues its first
comprehensive review of world financial crisis with searing
criticism of how IMF and U.S. Treasury handled the early months.
The review offers pessimistic predictions for Russia and developing
nations. By David E. Sanger. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ARMS (Cartagena, Colombia) _ Sixteen months ago, the
Clinton administration lifted a de facto ban on sales of the most
advanced American weapons to countries in Latin America, but there
are few signs that any country in South or Central America will be
able to purchase the sorts of sophisticated weapons covered by the
ruling anytime soon. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments surrounding the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment inquiry on President Clinton. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CONSERVATIVES (Washington) _ Even as the House Judiciary
Committee moves to expand its impeachment inquiry, a growing number
of conservatives _ from Huffington to Kristol to Bennett _ are
quietly, grudgingly giving up any hope that President Clinton will
lose his job. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SPEAKERS-ASSESS (Washington) _ As the nation awaits the
verdict on impeachment, the House is caught between two speakers.
Newt Gingrich is trying to leave the scene with uncharacteristic
quietness. Robert L. Livingston, the speaker to be, wants to time
his own entrance at a moment when the incendiary issue of
impeachment has already been dealt with. Into this vacuum has
stepped Rep. Tom DeLay, the House Majority Whip from Texas. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The Federal Election Commission
is widely expected to reject the recommendation of its auditors
that the 1996 campaigns of President Clinton and former Senator Bob
Dole be required to repay the Government millions of dollars
because of violations of campaign finance rules. By David E.
Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ESPY-AQUITTAL _ Former Agriculture Secretary acquitted on all
charges.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;  (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SEATTLE (EVERETT, Wash.) _ For all the talk of Microsoft
exercising global dominance from the empire's capital here, most
residents know that the big engine for jobs remains the Boeing Co.,
so when it announced it was cutting 20 percent of its worldwide
workforce over the next two years, with many of those 48,000 cuts
in jobs targeted for the Seattle area, the news hit like a chill
winter wind. By Sam Howe Verhovek. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-SIZE (Undated) _ In each of the staggering mergers
announced this week, executives hauling their companies to the
altar said the marriages would produce the best of the breed. But
try as they might to spin these combinations as strokes of
corporate brilliance, in many cases, mergers are not so much about
what they can deliver to the customers or the shareholders, but
rather what they can deliver, directly and indirectly, to top
management. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   EXXON-MOBIL (Undated) _ Developments in wake of the Exxon-Mobil
announcement, including a Texaco analysts' meeting, a look at the
companies that might be next as the industry consolidates, and a
look at the companies that will be the most threatened by the
Exxon-Mobil deal. By Agis Salpukas. With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
