<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST PLANE MISERY: GOD-AWFUL LUCK IS MY COPILOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``So what's the weather really like in Phoenix during
the summer?'' the man across the aisle asked me as I leaned as far
over into the aisle as I could. ``I'm moving here in a couple of
months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' I said, trying to separate my leg from my fellow
passenger sitting to the right of me, ``It's not hot enough to kill
you, just hot enough to make you want to die.''
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to die right about now, too. Heading toward Los Angeles
in a 737, I wasn't very happy, but I wasn't surprised. I've never
had good luck with airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Once, while flying back from San Francisco, the pilot
nonchalantly announced as we approached Las Vegas that one of the
engines had simply dropped off the plane and was now hurling toward
the ground at a ferocious speed to become the headpiece for some
showgirl.
</P>
<P>
   On another trip to Seattle, I checked in at the gate, and
instead of getting a seat assignment, I was handed a number, like
at a deli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'll take a ham on rye, easy on the mustard,'' I replied,
but the real joke was on me when I boarded the flight.
</P>
<P>
   With every seat occupied, crammed and overflowing, I looked down
the aisle and realized I wasn't flying on a plane. I was flying on
what could only be described as a Vietnamese bus gone airborne, and
I desperately waited for some flying chickens or a couple of mean
pigs to come snorting down the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   At snack time, the flight attendant started whipping out little
bags of peanuts and throwing them at people, and if you didn't
catch one, you just didn't get to eat.
</P>
<P>
   This time, headed to L.A. to visit friends, not only was I
hungry, I was in physical agony. Still not completely recovered
from a sinus infection, my head was full of so much pressure that
the only thing keeping the eyeballs in my head was some very badly
applied mascara.
</P>
<P>
   My right leg was stuck to the woman sitting next to me, bound by
perspiration and tight quarters. I felt empathy for her, because
her needs weren't exactly being met, either. We were all squeezed
into tiny little airplane seats, but for my neighbor, a
plus-plus-size woman, they provided even more of a challenge when
her extremities started to turn white because her blood wasn't
circulating.
</P>
<P>
   To be nice, I tried to give her as much room as possible, and
moved as far over to my left as I could, which pretty much put me
in the aisle. So far, it had been a horrible trip, and I was only
seven minutes into it.
</P>
<P>
   At the metal-detector station in the terminal, the guards had
insisted on searching my bag, and started to giggle as they dug in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, you're a married lady, huh?'' one of them said with a
smirk. ``The hole in your bra matches the one in your panties. Or
is that a deflated hot-air balloon?''
</P>
<P>
   They made me feel dirty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here I was, swapping sweat with a strange woman who was
physically closer to me than I ever let my husband get, even on his
birthday. The only relief in sight was the flight attendant a
couple of rows ahead of me, nicely placing little bags of pretzels
on people's trays.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of work do you do?'' the man across the aisle asked
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an antagonist,'' I said, wiping the sweat from my
forehead, not really in the mood for conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sounds scientific,'' he said, popping a pretzel into his
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't cure cancer, I cause it,'' I said caustically, then
noticed his snack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did you get those? I didn't see any flying pretzels!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The girl came by when you were fussing with your lady friend's
leg,'' he answered, popping another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not my friend,'' I said simply, stretching my neck up,
only to see the flight attendant move farther away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my own business,'' my neighbor said, leaning closer
to me. ``And I figure it would do pretty well in Scottsdale. I'm a
distributor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' I said with a sigh. ``Cocaine or crystal meth? Cocaine,
I bet, because you'd have to live in Apache Junction for crystal
meth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm a regional manager,'' he said as I tried to flag down
the flight attendant. ``For Amway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah?'' I said in horror. ``A cult job! My mom once bought
Amway shampoo, but when she went to throw it away, it had gone
through a molecular transformation and had eaten through the bottom
of the cabinet and down to the foundation of the house. Firemen had
to come and take it away. We had to live in a hotel for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure could use somebody to show me around a new town,'' he
added, undaunted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm MARRIED,'' I said sharply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought so. Well, I don't care what people say. If you love
somebody, you should say so, no matter what the world thinks,'' he
said with a wink and a motion of his hand. ``I had already figured
you two were a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   I turned my head toward the direction of his motioning hand, but
the only thing I saw was my neighbor eating the last of her
pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   As I turned my head back around to tell him our joint sweating
was not conjugal, just unavoidable, I felt a dull thud and a sharp
pain and looked up to see the flight attendant rubbing her left
thigh. She gave me a dirty look and walked on, still rubbing the
spot where my head had hit her butt. As I rubbed my own head,
something sparkly and blue on the ground caught my eye, and as my
vision started to clear, I saw the soft halo of a beautiful little
bag of pretzels.
</P>
<P>
   With my dry hand, I reached out to get it. My fingers were
almost touching it, I almost had it in my possession, when
suddenly, the plane hit an air pocket and the pretzels shot down
the aisle to four rows ahead of me.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't even have enough time to scream in anger before we hit
another air pocket, then another and another, and the pilot
overhead instructed everyone to remain seated and to buckle up. My
knuckles clawed the arm rests, and I held on tight as the plane
embarked on a ride wilder than Mr. Toad's. My hands, I noticed,
were turning white with fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wanna hold hands?'' my neighbor to the right asked, her voice
shaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' I said, and gave her my sweaty one. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Write to her in care of the
``Rep,'' P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002 or by e-mail at
therep(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
