A9439 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-TE     12-02 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY AND WALTERS ARE KINDRED SELLOUTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky and Barbara Walters. Makes sense. Both have sold
out. Lewinsky and her dignity. Walters and her integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Walters was a scrappy journalist with everything
to prove, in an industry in which men talked on camera and women
fetched water to help the men clear their throats. Then came
celebrity and riches and a comfy niche. A TV journalist became a TV
personality.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Walters is the only interviewer who can chat with Tom Hanks
as though they're in the same line of work.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of covering show biz and news, Walters has become
show biz and news, her own entity. ``The Babs,'' or ``BW,'' as
she's affectionately referred to on the ABC morning talk show ``The
View.''
</P>
<P>
   I dismissed Walters as a serious newsperson long ago, way before
network news became as soft as a Nerf ball, long before you
couldn't figure out who was the larger celebrity, the interviewer
or interviewee. She'd taken her place in that world where charming
personalities vie for our attention, each apparently intent on
giving us not information and explanation but comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Walters does this better than anyone. Better than Oprah Winfrey,
better than Katie Couric, better than Fred Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's interview on the Walters-fronted 20/20 will most
likely fall during February, when her book hits shelves and the
networks seek to impress advertisers by scheduling over-the-top
programming for sweeps. The interview is certain to draw millions
and rank up there with her chummy chats with Gen. Colin Powell,
Christopher Reeve and Demi Moore, who, promoting a film, taught
Babs how to wiggle like a stripper.
</P>
<P>
   Walters mentioned this week on ``The View'' that she courted
Lewinsky like everyone else (reportedly Fox News and ``Hard Copy''
were ready to go to their vaults), but not by tossing large money
bags through her window. ``We don't pay for interviews,'' Walters
said.
</P>
<P>
   The cynic in me says ABC indeed slipped something under the
table, but if Lewinsky watched ``The View'' in the past year,
perhaps it was obvious that she couldn't find a more sympathetic
interviewer unless she paid for one.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, Walters talked of the ``terrible year''
Lewinsky is having, recounting the former White House intern's
``heartbreak'' that taped conversations with Linda Tripp were
surfacing and saying how ``innocent'' Lewinsky was in the whole
affair with President Clinton. Walters was on a roll, halting only
when it was obvious that this gushing was going even beyond her
standards. ``I'm certainly not her public relations person,''
Walters would say.
</P>
<P>
   A pause later, Walters was accusing the press (it's not
surprising that she talks of the media as a separate entity from
herself) of ``vilifying'' Lewinsky as a calculating, power-hungry
tart.
</P>
<P>
   Word is that Oprah Winfrey was also in the running for the
interview, but that was a no-brainer. In shows of this sort,
Winfrey's audience has been more likely to vilify the cheater and
the cheatee. (In Winfrey's world, everyone takes blame.) I can see
some audience members actually booing the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky figured Walters was just the newsperson to lob softball
questions at her, to pull back if she begins to get teary, to, who
knows, hug her when bringing up the sensitive subject of love vs.
lust for power and position.
</P>
<P>
   I can see Walters leaning over at one point, handing Lewinsky a
tissue, and whispering, ``You loved him dearly, didn't you, child?
... Oh, how painful this must be.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, MSNBC's Jodi Applegate would probably have made a more
effective interviewer. Some say Cokie Roberts. (I can't imagine the
Lewinsky camp ever considering a male interviewer, except Fred
Rogers.)
</P>
<P>
   My choice? ``The View's'' resident jokester Joy Behar, who
cracks me up. At least we'd get a laugh out of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
