<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITE-HOUSE03-COX     12-02 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-HOUSE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNDER THE WHITE HOUSE, BIG IMPROVEMENTS ARE PLANNED
 &HT;    560&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two decades into the new millennium, a moving
sidewalk will carry tourists through a tunnel to the White House.
Correspondents will question the presidential press secretary in a
high-tech underground studio. But the first family will still see
softball games on the grassy Ellipse behind their historic home.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the ``carefully crafted vision'' that National
Park Service officials sketched Wednesday in an ambitious, 20-year,
$300 million ``Comprehensive Design Plan for the White House and
President's Park.''
</P>
<P>
   The project would accomplish the biggest alteration of the White
House complex _ albeit mostly underground _ since George Washington
approved the original design in 1791.
</P>
<P>
   It will ``effectively meet the demands of the 21st century
presidency'' while protecting historic structures and preserving
familiar vistas around 1600 Pennsylvania Ave., promised Robert
Stanton, director of the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been six years in the making, but still faces
scrutiny by Congress and several oversight agencies, as well as a
90-day period of public review, before any construction is begun.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the current visitor's center, located across
15th Street southeast of the White House, will be expanded
underground. Four small theaters and interactive displays will be
added to keep tourists busy while they await their White House
tours.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than walking across 15th Street, the tourists will ride
moving sidewalks beneath it, coming up near the visitor's gate on
the sidewalk adjacent to the South Lawn. About 1.2 million tourists
visit the White House each year.
</P>
<P>
   Street-level parking would be banned from around the Ellipse
behind the South Lawn. White House staffers would instead park in a
two-level underground garage constructed beneath the park. The
Ellipse is the site of the National Christmas Tree, as well as
almost daily softball and soccer games and periodic mass protests
such as the annual ``Right to Life'' anti-abortion march.
</P>
<P>
   A second underground parking lot for senior staffers and
motorcade vehicles would be built below the section of Pennsylvania
Avenue directly in front of the White House, where traffic has been
blocked off since the Oklahoma City bombing raised security
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service did not include a plan for renovating the
street level of this stretch of pavement between the White House
and Lafayette Park. A pedestrian mall has been suggested, but would
have to be approved by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Deliveries to the White House would also be made underground,
with an entrance located near the New Executive Office Building.
located two blocks northwest of the White House. Tunnels would run
to an underground storage facility beneath Pennsylvania Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   An underground addition would be made to the present press room,
which is located between the West Wing and the main White House
building. The press briefing room would be moved into this new
facility.
</P>
<P>
   An underground recreational room for the first family would be
added just north of the existing executive mansion, and an
underground conference room would be located beneath Executive
Avenue, between the West Wing and Old Executive Office Building.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service plan had input from a dozen other agencies,
ranging from the Secret Service to the Commission on Fine Arts. It
concludes that past White House planning has been ``piecemeal'' and
resulted in an assortment of problems. There is no room to store
furniture, for instance, and no place for many White House staffers
to park their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, Americans are unaware of these problems,''
the report said. ``On the evening news or the front page of the
morning paper, the white columns still gleam, the chandeliers still
sparkle and the lawns and shrubs remain impeccably groomed.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes will ensure that the White House continues to run
efficiently, Stanton said at a press conference where the plan was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan seeks to protect the historic site while making site
operations over the next two decades smoother and more efficient,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Congress would have to appropriate most of the $300 million cost
of the renovations, but the Park Service said some would come from
private donations.
</P>
<P>
   The Park Service's report is available on the Internet
(http://www.nps.gov/planning).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
