<HEADLINE>
THE SEARCH FOR SPEED 
</HEADLINE>
   By J.D. BIERSDORFER (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What is xDSL technology and is it available in New York?
</P>
<P>
   A. The term xDSL refers to several types of digital subscriber
lines that speed up a user's connection to the Internet. While
conventional modem speeds are topping out around 56 kilobits per
second, the new technology offers significantly faster speeds.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most popular members of the xDSL family is ADSL (for
asymmetric digital subscriber line), which promises speeds of up to
8 megabits (8 million bits) per second for data coming to the user;
most users will probably see speeds of 1 to 4 megabits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Uploads can attain speeds up to 1 megabit per second. ADSL is
aimed at users who need to download a lot of information in a
hurry, like Web pages or digital video, but don't have to upload,
or send, a lot of material. ADSL is not universally available yet.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike cable modems, which offer fast connection speeds over a
shared line, ADSL uses special digital coding to get more speed out
of a single phone line. It also allows you to use a single
telephone line for both an Internet connection and for regular
phone or fax needs simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent Web site devoted to ADSL, www.adsl.com, contains a
table that shows what parts of the country have access to ADSL
service (yes, it is available in parts of New York).
</P>
<P>
   (italics)Circuits invites questions about computer-based
technology, by postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York
Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail
to QandA(AT)nytimes.com.(end italics)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
