<HEADLINE>
FOREST SERVICE SCIENTIST CRITICIZES REDWOOD PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A respected federal scientist said in a
report released Wednesday that the environmental plan designed to
protect a redwood forest in Northern California from loggers was
inadequate and would cause more mudslides and further threaten an
endangered fish.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie M. Reid, who works for the U.S. Forest Service, said that
logging of the Headwaters Forest by the Pacific Lumber Co. could
strip away vital vegetation that protects streams from erosion and
provides cool waters for the dwindling numbers of coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's report, which was requested by Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif., is being touted by environmentalists who want to scuttle
an agreement with the logging company over the fate of the
privately-owned forest and its stand of old-growth redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Reid's report, environmental groups have gathered
some allies in their fight. People who live near the forest are
worried that continued logging by Pacific Lumber will cause ruinous
mudslides and foul their drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of the Humboldt County town of Stafford have
already sued Pacific Lumber over a 1997 mudslide that destroyed 10
houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been trying to say, `Stop, already,''' said Nona
Kraus, 69, who lives near Eureka across a road from the north fork
of the Elk River. The logging ``is really doing a lot of damage to
the stream. It has absolutely destroyed the fishery in the north
fork. They have slide after slide after slide. The value of our
property is declining, along with the water quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a hard-fought deal, taxpayers will spend $480 million to
buy and permanently preserve about 10,000 acres of redwood groves
owned by Houston-based Maxxam, which owns Pacific Lumber and is
controlled by financier Charles Hurwitz.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapped up in the deal is an environmental plan covering about
180,000 acres surrounding the new Headwaters preserve. That plan is
being scrutinized by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and the
National Marine Fisheries Service. The plan is supported by
President Clinton, Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and California
Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Reid's report is highly critical of the environmental
protections the plan promises. Reid, who prepared the report for
Miller and the Environmental Protection Agency, is an expert on
logging erosion and has worked for 20 years with fisheries
biologists.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Miller, she said that the environmental plan is
not strong enough to prevent logging-related landslides,
particularly near small streams. The plan will ``decrease the
likelihood of survival of any coho salmon migrating through''
erosion-choked streams.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the plan is changed, mudslides will cause ``increasing
damage to downstream properties and infrastructure, destroying
salmon (spawning grounds) and newly hatched fry, and increasing
rates of downstream bank erosion and stream-side landsliding.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the plan protects Pacific Lumber from liability, she
said, ``American taxpayers would become fiscally responsible for
addressing'' any problems that come up after the plan is approved.
</P>
<P>
   But Pacific Lumber questioned Reid's fairness, and points to
other scientists who have praised the environmental plan. John
Campbell, president and chief executive of the company, said
Pacific Lumber had agreed to study and find ways to correct erosion
problems over the next five years and, in the meantime, will not
log within 100 feet of large streams and 30 feet of smaller
streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize Dr. Reid is a good scientist,'' Campbell said
Tuesday, ``but we're disappointed she appears to have abandoned her
scientific objectivity in this review. ... I think on this
particular review, it's important to understand that this is the
opinion of just a few scientists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups hope that by enlisting local residents they
can persuade federal authorities to reconsider the environmental
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The logging company, which has been cited by state forestry
officials for 134 violations since 1996, was cited again in
September for continually running heavy logging equipment through a
large stream, said Karen Terrill, a spokeswoman for the state
Department of Forestry, which suspended Pacific Lumber's logging
license until at least Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and environmentalists worry about additional
violations under the new Headwaters agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very real,'' said Paul Mason, president of the
Garberville-based Environmental Protection Information Center.
``The claims that logging doesn't have an impact on watershed are
hollow. People who have lived at the bases of these watersheds for
50 or 60 years have seen the shape of the stream change from being
a narrow, deep channel to being filled with silt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our domestic water supply has been ruined,'' said Nona Kraus'
husband, Ralph, 71, a former science teacher. ``Even in the winter,
it has a distinct taste of rotting vegetation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
