<HEADLINE>
DRIVING IS THE ROAD TO RUIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The learned folks who juggle statistics say that we are at a
greater risk of being injured while in an automobile than in an
airplane. That's quite believable, when you consider the thousands
of people who commute by plane every day and the fact there are
relatively few reports of major accidents in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, I pass accidents involving motor vehicles
almost every day. Some are minor fender-benders, and others require
paramedics and ambulances. Few of us will live our entire lives
without hearing the disheartening sound of crumpled metal as our
car collides with another.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the problem. I've acquired a fear of driving.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I have no fear of flying, unless the weather is bad. I'm
not afraid to eat at a truck stop where the waitress calls me
``Honey'' and wipes her hands on a dirty apron. I'm not even afraid
of those rental bowling shoes that never fit properly, but I do
have a growing fear of other drivers on the raging roads of life.
Ordinary, normally kind people get behind the wheel of a car and
lose their minds. ``Defensive driving'' has taken on a whole new
meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Think about all the wonderful new driving tips we've acquired
over the past decade. Keep your doors and windows locked at all
times, no matter how hot it is. Leave a full car length in front of
you when stopping at a red light, as an escape route in case of a
carjacking attempt. Don't ever flash your lights at another car; it
might be a gang member, and he might shoot you. Don't toot your
horn at anyone sitting at a green light; It might be an executive
who just got downsized and deleted, and he might shoot you. Never,
ever cut anyone off on the freeway, because it might be a psycho
terrorist on the run, and you know what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that so many people in large urban cities don't
even own a car? Who needs that kind of stress?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when we get those flying cars in the next millennium,
everything will get better. Until then, hop in your car and
carefully cruise over to Circle T's Truck Stop out on the
interstate. Tell Big Mabel that you want one of those giant
chicken-fried steaks with cream gravy and a side of mashed
potatoes. Forget the salad; the lettuce is always brown.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not implying that a big dinner will make your life a
bed of roses or clear traffic out of your path, but at least you
won't be hungry for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   Geez, will you look at that! I've gotta go. Those kids are
trying to steal my bicycle again!
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
