</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODOT-THEATER-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: DIDI AND GOGO IN MIDDLE AGE, UNCHANGING BUT
FRESH 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty years ago Samuel Beckett began writing
``Waiting for Godot,'' the play that was to transform his life and
alter the direction of contemporary theater. In a recent survey,
the Royal National Theater in London concluded that ``Godot'' was
the most significant English language play of the 20th century, a
point that no longer seems arguable.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, in the intervening years, the play has been seen and
appreciated by a wide theatergoing public, as demonstrated by the
current production at the Classic Stage Company in the East
Village. The times and the audience have changed, while Beckett has
remained immutable.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Godot'' opened on Broadway in April, 1956, critics held
it at a distance, as if it were a foreign body, a meteorite landing
on earth. They were so busy wondering what ``Godot'' was and what
it was doing on Broadway that they failed to recognize its
originality.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Beckett won the Nobel Prize in literature in 1969,
skepticism had faded and the world _ or at least part of it _ was
attuned to the author's message of fortitude in the face of
nothingness. The play and the playwright gathered their own
momentum. Soon Beckett was being taught on college campuses and the
paperback text of the play and his other plays went into endless
reprintings.
</P>
<P>
   Often after an artist's death, the work takes a downturn _ or
lands in limbo _ awaiting re-evaluation. With Beckett (who died in
1989), there was no waiting period. Since then, productions have
proliferated, and Beckett's audience has continually expanded.
</P>
<P>
   When Dublin's Gate Theater presented all his stage plays at the
first Lincoln Center Festival two years ago, it proved to be the
festival's highlight. The Gate will repeat the marathon next year
at the Royal Shakespeare Company.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hall, who had staged the first London production of
``Godot'' in 1955, returned to it successfully last year (with Alan
Howard and Ben Kingsley). There were school children in the
audience who had not seen the play and did not even know if Godot
would come. They greeted it as a fresh new work.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar is occurring with the Classic Stage Company
production. Directed by Andrei Belgrader, it stars Tony Shalhoub
and John Turturro, actors who had profitable theatrical careers
before making their names on television and in films. Almost all
tickets to the show's limited run have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, Estelle Parsons is performing ``Happy Days'' at
the Hartford Stage Company. Along with ``Godot'' and ``Endgame,''
that play is a cornerstone of Beckett's work.
</P>
<P>
   From performances at both theaters, it is evident that the
confusion exhibited early on by theatergoers as well as critics has
disappeared. Now they sit back and enjoy the play, which is not to
say that their minds are at rest. At a recent Sunday matinee at
Hartford, the theater was filled with people choosing to spend an
afternoon with Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   After the performance, there was a public discussion about the
play and its author. From the questions, it seemed clear that
theatergoers were unfazed by the oddity that Winnie (Ms. Parsons)
was buried up to her waist and later, to her neck, in a mound of
earth.
</P>
<P>
   One theatergoer wondered if Beckett's audience was predominantly
older, overlooking the fact that there were people of all ages at
Hartford. Another asked about Beckett's influences, Joyce and other
playwrights. The response was that Beckett certainly owed a great
debt to Joyce and Synge, among others, but that his primary
influences were Laurel and Hardy, Buster Keaton and French and
English music hall and vaudeville clowns _ one reason for his
enduring popularity. It was added that Beckett was less the
influenced than the influencer.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, since Beckett's death directors have tried to be
more freely interpretive of his work. Earlier this season, Joy
Zinoman's production of ``Godot'' at the Studio Theater in
Washington featured black actors and looked at the play through the
prism of black vaudeville.
</P>
<P>
   In the belief that the production was contrary to the
playwright's wishes, Beckett's New York agent demanded that it be
withdrawn, a ban that was later rescinded by Edward Beckett, the
playwright's nephew and literary executor.
</P>
<P>
   For Edward Beckett, as it would have been for his uncle, the
question was not that of the actors but of the approach. Black
actors have often played ``Godot.'' Seven months after the original
Broadway production closed, it reopened with Earle Hyman, Mantan
Moreland and Geoffrey Holder. In 1980, the South African version
(with John Kani and Winston Ntshona) was presented at the Long
Wharf Theater in New Haven, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett forcefully objected to any attempt at altering the
gender of a character. Often there were requests to do an all
female ``Godot'' and for an actress to perform ``Krapp's Last
Tape.'' ``It's a man voice,'' he said about ``Krapp.'' ``Were a
woman to do it, it would be like having a soprano sing a baritone
role.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly he would have objected to the idea of an all male
``Happy Days.'' The role of Winnie, as Dame Peggy Ashcroft
asserted, is ``a summit part'' for an actress, a female equivalent
of ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   On one other point the playwright was always adamant:
productions should follow his stage directions explicitly. In a new
book, ``No Author Better Served,'' a collection of 30 years of
letters between Beckett and his director Alan Schneider (published
by Harvard University Press and edited by Maurice Harmon), the
playwright offers fascinating insights about performance and
interpretation if not meaning. As Beckett described one production
of ``Happy Days'' to Schneider, ``all poised on a razor-edge and no
breather anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came to questions of exegesis, Beckett refused to be
involved. In a very important letter to Schneider, written in 1957,
he insisted ``on the extreme simplicity of dramatic situation and
issue,'' and added, ``If people want to have headaches among the
overtones, let them. And provide their own aspirin.''
</P>
<P>
   With Beckett supplying drawings indicating stage movement and
also specifying the exact intention of individual lines, there is
no doubt that at each point he knew precisely what he was doing. In
a 1955 letter he said that Vladimir was ``the spirit'' of
``Godot,'' that in performance the character was restless and
``always on the fidget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Godot'' was a sudden burst of intuition, but it is also a
carefully plotted work, as was also true of ``Happy Days,'' in
which Winnie's dialogue is interspersed with detailed descriptions
of her gestures and expressions, a minefield for any actress
attempting the role.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his reputation for pessimism, Beckett took a
philosophical position toward all questionable productions and to
the possibility of failure itself.
</P>
<P>
   In ``No Author Better Served,'' it is clear that he was calm
even in the face of hostility. His advice to Schneider as the
director was about to embark on the first American production of
``Godot'' (in Miami in 1956): ``Et courage! On les aura!'' or
``Courage, we'll win.''
</P>
<P>
   On this, as in other matters, Beckett had the last word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
