<HEADER>
A9485 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BRANDS-NYT &LR;      12-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BRANDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN RUGRATS CROSS OVER? YES AND NO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time in the 1960s _ long before fast-food chains
began to distribute superhero action figures as freely as french
fries _ when my brother Jack and I lived for the ``Batman''
television show.
</P>
<P>
   If a particular episode truly moved us, the next morning we
would be out on the backyard swings, wearing Batman and Robin capes
that looked suspiciously like our mother's aprons tied across our
shoulders. We pumped our swings as high as we could, then jumped
off, shrieking, ``Take that, Riddler!''
</P>
<P>
   We concocted elaborate plots in which we trounced Freeze or the
Penguin (both played grudgingly by our schnauzer) or zoomed off to
the Bat Cave (the garage) in the Batmobile (our Schwinn Pixies,
with training wheels).
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, I realize that this was my introduction to
cross-over branding, the phenomenon that occurs when pop-culture
icons leverage their popularity in one entertainment medium to make
the leap to another. In those days, the distance that Batman and
Robin traveled was relatively tiny _ from the fuzzy black-and-white
set in our bedroom to the backyard swing set.
</P>
<P>
   Let the marketers point smugly to the Batman Color-Forms and
plastic Batmobiles that followed. To me, the true measure of the
effort's success is the fact that my brother and I still sometimes
greet each other with ``ka-Pow, Batman!''
</P>
<P>
   Today, life seems more complicated. In a single 24-hour period
last week, my two older daughters and I participated in a
1990s-style cross-branding extravaganza called the Rugrats. For
those who don't have kids: the Rugrats are television's band of
big-eyed cartoon toddlers who were recently transformed into stars
of both the cinema and the computer desktop (not to mention the
action figures).
</P>
<P>
   Curious to see how successfully the Rugrats would cross over to
new milieus, I watched my daughters watch an episode of the
television show, then accompanied them to the theater to see ``The
Rugrats Movie,'' then installed The Rugrats Movie Activity
Challenge CD-ROM game for them on my home computer.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what I observed:
</P>
<P>
   In front of the television set, the subjects (ages 9 and 7) sat
enthralled on the sofa. (For the purposes of this study,
``enthralled'' means that they were so caught up in the on-screen
action that no one noticed that one sister had violated a treaty by
placing her arm in the demilitarized armrest zone between their
seats or that the other was eating more than her fair share of
snacks.) When the show ended, both subjects asked if they could go
see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   At the theater, the subjects sat enthralled (see above) in their
seats, snickering during a scene in which the rebellious toddlers
undercut the authority of their doddering parents by escaping from
a playpen.
</P>
<P>
   At the computer, they sat politely for 10 minutes, working their
way through the Rugrats game's series of six simplistic tasks,
which mainly called for players to click on images of various
Rugrats or their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, my daughters played Aqua Reptar, steering a
toddler-laden raft down a river by using the arrow keys on the
keyboard. Then they played a few rounds of Monkey Mayhem, in which
they used both the arrow keys and the spacebar to propel the
Rugrats into the air to grab jars of baby food away from jeering
monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   One subject said, ``Are you bored, Zoe?'' and the other
answered, ``Yeah, let's go ride bikes or something.''
</P>
<P>
   From this experiment, I concluded that although the Rugrats
brand was indeed strong enough to cross over from television, the
computer game version failed to hold the subjects' attention for a
simple reason: it did not take advantage of the possibilities of
its medium.
</P>
<P>
   All the Rugrats computer game had to do to win over my daughters
was to allow them to interact _ to identify with the slyly anarchic
toddlers in the same way that my brother and I had patterned our
play on Batman and Robin three decades earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the only portion of the game that managed to even
invoke the spirit of the Rugrats was a series of animated opening
screens (lifted almost verbatim from the movie) in which the
toddlers resembled Indiana Jones in diapers as they navigated a
dark cave to find treasure.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the game quickly deteriorated. At best, the
point-and-click scenes were vague reminders of the Rugrats. But
they had no more personality than a tattoo that ``dances'' when its
owner flexes a bicep.
</P>
<P>
   What would have worked better? For starters, building the game
around a strong narrative, the way the television episodes and the
movie are built. Then the computer game could have taken full
advantage of its interactive capabilities by giving players the
power to influence events.
</P>
<P>
   Let the players control the actions of the protagonists. Or
better yet, let them imagine themselves as the protagonists. Then
players will believe that they have a stake in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   I am reminded of my daughters' all-time favorite computer
program, Oregon Trail. Created by a group of Minnesota teachers in
the 1970s as a text-based educational exercise played on punch
cards, Oregon Trail allows players to experience firsthand the
tribulations of the westward migration of 1848.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest multimedia versions distributed by the Learning
Co., players traveling cross-country with a wagon party must make
decisions every step of the way _ about how to overcome obstacles
like swollen, rushing rivers, for instance, or how to avoid the
deadly threat of cholera.
</P>
<P>
   In my household the true measure of a successful brand (which
the Oregon Trail mastered) is whether it crosses over and succeeds
in the rigorous interactive medium known as my daughters'
imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   After Zoe and Ellie abandoned the Rugrats Movie computer game, I
heard them scuttle down to the basement, where, an hour later, I
found them wearing pioneer costumes, fashioned from old tablecloths
draped across their shoulders. Aprons would have worked just as
well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
