</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FIELDS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILDREN OF THE FIELDS': TOO BUSY WORKING TO GO TO SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: program airs at 8 p.m. Eastern time)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 11-year-old James Flores, school is a sometime, somewhere
thing. He spends much of the year on the road in his family's
breakdown-prone old van traveling thousands of miles with his
father and seven brothers and sisters in hopes of catching a few
weeks of picking at harvest time.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of '98, as chronicled in Thursday night's
``Dateline NBC,'' it was a grueling four-month trip; if the oil
pump didn't conk out, it was the transmission. Working for less
than the minimum wage, the family didn't make enough to meet
expenses and ended up dragging back home to Texas worse off than
when they started. The focus of this report by Dennis Murphy is on
James, who by law should not have been working at all, the minimum
legal age for farm workers being 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of the Fields'' is sketchy about the numbers of the
under-aged out picking, and, unlike famous past exposes, it doesn't
dwell on the conditions in which migrant workers exist these days,
except to note that electricity and clean water can be in short
supply. Murphy concentrates instead on a collusion between migrant
families and farmers to skirt the law.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers need the low-paid seasonal workers to bring in their
crops for a profit; the families need the muscle power of every
member, even an 11-year-old, to earn enough to keep the van running
and everybody eating. ``I have to help my dad,'' says James. When
the blueberry crop fails in Michigan, the wage goes down to $2.35
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   As for the big food processors like Heinz, which buys the
cucumbers that the Flores clan picks in Ohio, they declare their
abidance to the law against employing minors (``We just won't
tolerate it'') but don't seem to go to excessive exertions to
enforce it. The report suggests that the prevailing rule in
American agriculture is, ``Don't ask, don't tell.''
</P>
<P>
   One farmer, who runs into trouble when James is discovered
working his pickle farm is shamefaced about his reliance on workers
whom he can't afford to pay a decent wage. But another makes the
vehement case that James is better off working the fields along
with his close-knit family than in a broken home. A sorry choice,
yet the evidence of family unity adds a softening touch to their
harsh odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, James manages to get some schooling, but next
season he'll be 12 and so permitted to work legally. The hour is a
painful look at the migrant-worker condition and at an engaging,
dutiful, plucky boy who seems on his way to giving up what chance
he may have to get through high school in an effort to help his
family get through a hard life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
