<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: BRITONS GET DESIGN PRIZE; NOT A REMBRANDT; BRASSAI
IN HOUSTON;   LAGGING LEXICOGRAPHERS; BARDS OF MONTCLAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Texas, N.J., Great Britain, Netherlands)  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ceremonies Wednesday in Cambridge, Mass., the English
architect and urban designer Sir Norman Foster and his London-based
firm, Foster &AMP; Partners, received the fifth Veronica Rudge Green
Prize in Urban Design from the Harvard Design School. Foster &AMP;
Partners was chosen for two projects: the subway system in Bilbao,
Spain, and the development of the Carre d'Art Plaza in Nimes,
France.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Try
</P>
<P>
   The 15-by-11-inch painting looked like a Rembrandt. It was
labeled a Rembrandt. Its subject was Rembrandt himself. But on
Wednesday the unsigned oil, ``Self-Portrait With Gorget,'' which
has hung for years in the Mauritshuis museum in The Hague,
Netherlands, was judged by experts to be a copy. A signed version
hangs in Germany. Researchers using infrared technology and X-rays
discovered outlines of the portrait under the Mauritshuis painting,
and because Rembrandt never made outlines, experts agreed it was
probably a copy by one of his students.
</P>
<P>
   Viewpoint
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating the 100th anniversary of the birth of Gyula Halasz,
the photographer known as Brassai, the Museum of Fine Arts in
Houston will open what is billed as the first major American
retrospective of his work in three decades. The show, ``Brassai:
The Eye of Paris,'' from Sunday through Feb. 28, will feature about
140 works by Brassai (1899-1984), who focused primarily on scenes
of everyday Paris life and the leading artists, writers and
intellectuals who were his friends.
</P>
<P>
   Page Turner
</P>
<P>
   After 147 years of work, a 40-volume, 45,000-page dictionary
compiled by Dutch and Flemish lexicographers has finally been
completed. The work, the Dictionary of the Dutch Language, is, of
course, already out of date, lacking words like Internet and yuppie
because its millions of entries stop with the language of 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Words, Music, Etc.
</P>
<P>
   As world premieres go, the one scheduled for 8 p.m. on Saturday
at Mount Hebron Auditorium in Montclair, N.J., is one with a few
differences. Titled ``Broken in Parts,'' it is a multimedia work by
the saxophonist and composer Oliver Lake that draws on more than
200 poems submitted by more than 90 people of all ages and
backgrounds living in and around Montclair. In addition, the piece
by Lake, a founder of the World Saxophone Quartet, features a poet,
three actors, a dancer, a string quartet, a steel drum, bass and
electric bass, a trumpet and drums. ``Broken in Parts'' will be
repeated at 3 p.m. on Sunday. Information: (973) 744-6770.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1736EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
