<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KALMAN-DESIGN-2TAKES-     12-02 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KALMAN-DESIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPLENDID RAGE OF TIBOR KALMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN HOCKENBERRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Choice and free will have lost some of their
philosophical luster in our day. Updated and retooled through the
decibels of corporate advertising, free will is today expressed as
the fashionable condition of being edgy or in your face. In
America, corporate symbols, the young, the famous, all aspire to
this sublime state. The same blank look of disaffected angst sells
everything from stockbrokers to Buicks to white cotton briefs. Free
will in the classical sense implies that you actually do something.
Being edgy requires only that we show up, late of course, and that
we buy something.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, the designer Tibor Kalman did much more than
show up. Kalman's brilliance has been to sustain, throughout his
career, a tirade against oppression and for intellectual freedom.
He has maintained that tirade with fearless biting humor and a
legendary, often withering grumpiness toward those who disagree
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman's visual manifestoes rail against hyperbole about our
technological future. His work in advertising, journalism and
graphic design constitutes a eulogy for the single clear voice.
That voice, a blunt water cannon, has delighted in hosing down
storm troopers of style and fashion around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman (called Tibor even by those who do not know him) may be
an obscure, egghead personality, but his work is everywhere. In the
1970s, he designed distinctive medieval-looking shopping bags for
Barnes &AMP; Noble that became the signature for a global retail
empire. He produced the memorable East-meets-West logo _ a coat of
arms with chopsticks _ for the midtown Manhattan power room China
Grill, and hilarious menus and advertising for the downtown
after-hours mecca Florent.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman designed perhaps the '80s' greatest album artwork, for
Talking Heads, matching the impenetrable nerdiness of lead singer
David Byrne with a collage of color, primitive typography and
techno-images. And he was behind Colors, Benetton's radical and
mysterious magazine. His memorable images invariably evoke the
response: ``He did that? I love that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a body of work breathtaking to behold all at once, which
is the best thing about ``Tibor Kalman: Perverse Optimist''
(Princeton Architectural Press, $60), a handsomely produced volume
published last month that is an archive of and homage to the
designer.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also an oddly appealing scrapbook of Kalman's
passions, which include his family and his hard-to-nail-down
politics. It is a playful greatest hits compilation of his most
important work with M&AMP;Co, the groundbreaking design firm he founded
with his wife and collaborator, the artist and children's book
author Maira Kalman.
</P>
<P>
   In the fine print is his own story, entertainingly told by
various contributors, including Kalman himself. He is interviewed
by writer Kurt Andersen. We learn how the child political refugee
from Eastern Europe fell in love with America even as he was
repulsed by its capitalist excesses in the 1950s and '60s. At New
York University, he joined SDS and in 1970 he made an illicit trip
to Castro's Cuba to learn farming, which could have earned him a
deportation hearing.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped out of NYU, and as a ``paste and prop boy'' making
window displays for a college bookstore, he started his career. The
store's owner, Leonard Riggio, was then cobbling together a retail
business that would become Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman's education as a designer never got much beyond cutting
sugar cane; yet, he directed Barnes &AMP; Noble's national advertising,
a job that landed him a position as director of visual
merchandising at the E.J. Korvettes chain. Using M&AMP;Co as his
mysterious cover, he went on to design watches, calendars and
stationery items (a genre Kalman calls Yuppie Pornography), and to
produce the logo and type for the fashion designer Issac Mizrahi,
his neighbor in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   M&AMP;Co's forte was a kind of anti-corporate voice and feel that
attracted well-heeled clients like Knoll Furniture, the Limited,
the 42nd Street Development Project, ABC News, Lifetime Television
and a number of museums and movie studios thrashing about in the
1980s and '90s for some succinct statement of purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman supplied it. But it was his reputation as a salesman and
irrepressible charmer that brought the greatest legend and
financial success to M&AMP;Co. The book is at its most interesting as a
deconstruction of an influential designer's interior interplay of
craft, inspiration, personality and pure ego.
</P>
<P>
   As his stature grew in the design community, Kalman became
famous for his shocking, iconoclastic presentations at stodgy
professional meetings of designers and architects. Most designers,
he claimed, were prissy sycophants; successful designers were
fronts for the evils of the system. For Kalman, design award
ceremonies became an irresistible opportunity to expose
exploitative corporate business practices. Fashion companies were
bluntly excoriated for their inhuman wages in Third World
countries. Manufacturers were showcased as rapists of the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   In his public appearances, Kalman demanded that designers make
themselves relevant by focusing on the concrete needs of a
prosperous industrialized society plagued with poverty and
inequality. A great story line in this book shows how the more
Kalman railed against corporate hypocrisy and waste, the more
successful he became and the bigger clients he attracted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Olivieri Toscani, creative director at Benetton, hired
Kalman to start up Colors, a global magazine envisioned as the
perfect union between corporate sponsor (Benetton) and editorial
content (Kalman). In visual style, Colors was seductive and
shocking; yet, it was as journalistically aggressive as more
conventional publications. There were single-concept issues on
Heaven and AIDS. A poverty issue contained a global map of where
the people live versus where the money is. Radical for its time,
the editorial style has since been imitated by publications like
The New Yorker and U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Colors had no interest in celebrities and took few
advertisements, a radical concept. But because it was devoid of
explicit advertising and had a design that deliberately blurred the
conventions of commercial and editorial copy, each image had the
effect of wordlessly evoking Benetton as a benevolent godfather.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, this drew considerable criticism. Yet, the
early issues of Colors were Kalman's troubled, brilliant
masterpiece. Each offered a slice of his passions, outrages and
visual experiments. For an issue on race, for instance, he depicted
Queen Elizabeth and Arnold Schwarzenegger with black skin, and
Spike Lee as a white guy with a goatee and blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   With Colors, Kalman became a storm trooper of style. His
vocabulary of biting visual contrasts begat the more timid generic
edge of the moment. As a social reformer, Kalman has a less secure
legacy, a condition that is also a commentary on the profession of
design. Designers are along for the ride in corporate America. They
do not get to drive. Yet, Kalman can at least claim to have
demanded the keys.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Colors under Kalman was too lavish a production and
too challenging visually to sustain itself. This is one of Kalman's
great talents: finding the fabulous big-budgeted project and
through it pushing his personal vision to the limit until the
project either implodes from excess or the client's money runs out.
Here he is Michelangelo _ a subversive virus infecting his clients
and making them do very entertaining things. His annual report for
the Limited during one of its worst years reads like a contrite
public humiliation ritual from a Maoist re-education camp. It did
not reassure stockholders. M&AMP;Co was not asked back.
</P>
<P>
   It should be said that Tibor Kalman is also one of the great
acid-tongued monsters of his or any other profession. People on the
receiving end of his frostiness are featured in the book: Elisabeth
Sussman, a museum curator; the restaurateur Florent Morellet, and
Mizrahi. Ingrid Sichy had a stormy collaboration with Kalman at Art
Forum and Interview magazines. She named him Creative Troublemaker
on Interview's masthead. In an affectionate and candid testimonial,
she compares Kalman with the upper-crust fashion iconoclast Diana
Vreeland, whom Kalman might have targeted for a pie in the face had
he met her at a party.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, when I was a correspondent for ABC News, I
had a brief encounter with Kalman. Tom Yellin, the executive
producer at ABC News, had hired M&AMP;Co to design the logo for a new
prime-time news magazine and to come up with a title for it. Kalman
suggested ``Naked Eye,'' a not so subtle slam at the competition,
CBS, and its eye logo, and a prophetic commentary on what would
become the whole mission of television journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Although Yellin loved it, ``Naked Eye'' was trashed by network
management in favor of the more conventional ``Day One.'' ``Good
clients are smarter than you,'' Kalman says in the book. ``Bad
clients are dumber than you.''
</P>
<P>
   On balance, this book, like his work, is oddly touching for all
its bluster. Unstated but poignant on every page is the hint of
Kalman's struggle with cancer, which has taken a toll on his
outward vitality and gives this whole volume the somber feel of a
retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   His free will intact, Tibor Kalman lives on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
