<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9510 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILD-ESCAPES-HNS &LR;      12-02 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-ESCAPES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPES FROM DEATH ROW ARE RARE, BUT HAVE HAPPENED BEFORE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike Texas death row inmate Martin Gurule, who had to scale a
razor wire-topped fence amid gunfire from the guard tower,
condemned inmate Robert Lewis simply walked unchallenged through
the gate of a Florida prison in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how it happens, an escape by a dangerous inmate is
a nightmare for anyone in the prison business.
</P>
<P>
   Prison administrators around the country are following the news
of Gurule's escape from Texas' death row with keen interest and,
occasionally, real empathy. Although death row breakouts are rare,
they have happened before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine percent of all escape plots, we stop them,'' said
Harry Singletary Jr., Florida Secretary of Corrections. ``But it's
the fear of every correction administrator ... where the next high
profile escape will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people who escape, all you do is wait out at
their Mama's house,'' Singletary said. ``But it's a scarey thing
and my heart goes out to the folks in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've probably got citizens out there who are armed _ it just
escalates, and a lot of bad things can go wrong, including the
inmate hurting somebody. I've been praying for them, and I hope
they'll be able to recover the inmate. I know what it's like to
have 500 people out there looking for dangerous folks,'' Singletary
said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Correctional Association reports there were 9,482
escapes nationwide in 1997 out of a total prison population of
slightly more than a million. But spokesman Jim Turpin cautions
that different states report escapes differently _ for example,
Texas reported 20 escapes and 19 returns that year, while Illinois
reported 1,000 escapes with 962 returns. Turpin said that Illinois
may be including such things as bail jumpers and parole violations
as ``escapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida had its own escape from death row in 1978, when Lewis
simply walked out of the prison unaccosted, wearing a guard's
uniform which had been smuggled in by a visitor under his own
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Department spokeswoman Debbie Buchannan said the
visitor went to the visiting area bathroom, shed the uniform, and
returned to the visiting area. ``Bobby Lewis went into the bathroom
and changed into it and for lack of a better term, simply walked
out,'' said Buchannan.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates and visitors are no longer allowed to use the same
bathrooms, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually got to the back gate where only cars are allowed
in and out, and told the officer in the tower his wife had been in
an auto accident and he had to go home,'' Buchannan said. ``They
opened the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis remained at large for about 10 days before he was
apprehended in South Carolina and his death sentence was later
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   States like Florida and Texas have some of the largest prison
populations in the country, with hundreds of people waiting for
execution. But Virginia gets the nod for the biggest death row
escape on the books.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, 1984, six condemned men took 13 prison employees
hostage, stripped them of their clothing, tied them up and locked
them in a cell. They managed to convince prison officials they had
a bomb, which turned out to be a hoax.
</P>
<P>
   The six had one of the hostages call in the ``bomb'', they
masqueraded as guards in prison riot gear and, after pretending to
neutralize the bogus bomb with fire extinguishers, drove out of the
Mecklenberg Correctional Center in a prison van.
</P>
<P>
   One of the escapees was arrested in Vermont about a week after
the breakout. The rest were captured within three weeks. Lem Davis
Tuggle Jr., the last surviving member of the escape team, was
executed in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the highest risk inmates we have. They have
nothing to lose insofar as they're looking at death in prison,''
said Nic Howell, spokesman for the Illinois Department of
Corrections. ``So we expect them to be high escape risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far as I can recall, we've never had an escape... even an
escape attempt in death row,'' Howell said. But Illinois has had
its share of other escapes, including one which occurred during the
filming of a prison movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nick Nolte was filming the movie `Weed' and this one guy got
out by hiding in one of the trucks they used to bring in stuff for
the movie,'' Howell said. ``He was caught three days later in
either South or North Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   But many prison officials point to the 1920s and 1930s as the
wild years for prison breakouts, before sophisticated prison
security made things more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were inmates at Stateville who killed an assistant
warden, commandeered a truck, put a ladder on it, went up the
ladder to go over the wall,'' Howell said. ``Statesville's walls
are 33 feet high.
</P>
<P>
   ``An armed tower officer saw what was going on and fired on
them,'' Howell continued. ``They had taken a hostage and the
hostage was killed in the fusillade. One of the inmates was killed
and the rest subdued.''
</P>
<P>
   But a half a century later, two prisoners went over the wall at
Statesville again, this time on New Year's Eve, and this time they
made it, Howell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We chased those two guys for a period of time,'' Howell said.
``In fact we caught one of them in Dallas or Houston a month or a
month and a half later. He was going to bartender school. The other
guy we found in the Carolinas.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola, the natural
barricade presented by the adjacent Mississippi River has always
made escape more dangerous, and inmates have drowned in the swift
waters. But at Angola, they remember Charlie Frazier's escape in
1933 as the prison's most daring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and 10 other inmates escaped from Angola,'' said prison
museum curator Nadine Tanner. ``One of the inmates had gotten his
common-law wife to smuggle a small-caliber gun in during visiting
hours. It was a Sunday afternoon, there was a baseball game going
on and everyone was involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   One inmate was shot during the escape, she said, as well as the
captain of the prison guard. The inmates got to the Mississippi
River at a time when it was low, hopped on a log and floated
downriver to a sandbar, and eventually made it to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The group split up at that point, Tanner said, and Frazier sent
some of the escapees on to a point where he knew they'd be caught,
creating a diversion for his own escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then he and several of the other inmates made it all the way
to Northern Louisiana,'' Tanner said. ``They robbed banks in North
Louisiana, Texas and Arkansas. They went on a spree, but he was
caught in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was returned to Angola, he was welded into his cell,
Tanner said, where legend has it he remained for eight years.
Frazier died in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day in every (prison) system in the country there are
inmates hatching escape plots,'' Florida's Singletary said.
``That's part of what people held against their will do. The more
secure your place becomes, because of fences, razor wire and armed
patrols _ the more elaborate the escape plots will become and the
more they try to compromise staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to always have to worry about looking within _ that
inmates would try to escape from within,'' Singletary said. ``But
now people from the outside may come and help them escape by
blowing up a tower or your fence or taking out your patrols on the
perimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our last murder of a staff member was Officer Fred Griffith.
He was on an escort taking an inmate to a medical appointment and
two ex-inmates tried to break him out,'' Singletary said. ``They
ended up killing our officer. Both of them are on death row in
Florida now. These things are getting more exotic.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
