<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS lets us all groove on Darin's cool moves
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone with half a grasp of the history of popular song knows
that Bobby Darin could sing. His treatments of ``Beyond the Sea''
and ``Mack the Knife'' (the latter the swingingest treatment ever
of a serial killer) are part of the pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   But it's nice to be reminded, or to see for the first time, how
the dude could move.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of clips from old TV shows, ``Bobby Darin: Beyond
the Song'' (9:30 E.S.T. tonight on WGTV) gives us a cocky young guy
who glides around a stage with a beguiling fluidity; in body
movement (though not in musical taste), he could be the father of
Beck.
</P>
<P>
   This new PBS special (part of a PBS pledge drive, so be prepared
for interruptions) is packed with golden clips.
</P>
<P>
   On Darin's first TV appearance in 1956, he doesn't have cue
cards, so he writes the lyrics to ``Rock Island Line'' on his hand
and keeps surreptitiously glancing down. Jimmy Durante, on some
uncredited variety show, does an extended goof with Darin, with
each imitating the other. In a 1970 concert, he does ``Mack the
Knife'' in its entirety (thank you, PBS, for not cutting away).
</P>
<P>
   But Darin's personal life was as bizarre as his onstage act was
finger-poppin'. Born Walden Robert Cassotto, he had a congenital
heart defect, and he said he never expected to live past 30. He
made it to 37, when his heart gave out during an operation in 1973.
A few years before his death, he had learned that the woman he
thought was an older sister was his biological mother, and his
``mother'' was really his grandmother. In a spooky clip from a 1959
``This Is Your Life,'' he's reunited with his ``sister'' at a time
when he didn't know she was his mother. Imagine what Jerry Springer
would have done with all this, and be thankful for the gentility of
an earlier time.
</P>
<P>
   Darin was first known as a rock 'n' roller with hits such as
``Splish Splash.'' Dick Clark, one of many who reminisce about
Darin, recalls that when the singer said he wanted to make an album
of standards (one that included ``Mack''), Clark told him: ``Are
you out of your mind? That's the kind of stuff you'd hear a lounge
lizard do. You're a rock 'n' roll singer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Splish Splash'' now sounds like a novelty record, while ``Mack
the Knife'' will forever be identified with the deepest shade of
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Haworth leaving CNN
</P>
<P>
   CNN is losing a valued player at the end of the year with the
departure of Steve Haworth, the company's chief spokesman for a
decade. As vice president of public relations, Haworth has
frequently been called upon to issue official comment on
CNN-related stories ranging from ratings during the Persian Gulf
War to this summer's Operation Tailwind debacle. He's also been one
of CNN's key executives in planning corporate strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Network spokesman is a high-turnover, high-burnout job (sort of
the TV equivalent of White House press secretary) that Haworth
handled with grace, aplomb, honesty and extremely hard work during
his years at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Haworth is leaving CNN and his longtime home in Atlanta to
become vice president of communications for RealNetworks Inc., a
Seattle-based Internet company that markets streaming video and
audio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
