<HEADLINE>
CHECK ALL THAT APPLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday Dec. 4)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Friends:
</P>
<P>
   Santa Claus would like to thank you for your belief and
patronage. In order to update his files and better serve your needs
in the future, he asks that you take a few moments and answer the
following questions:
</P>
<P>
   1) How did you find out about Santa Claus?
</P>
<P>
   a. Book
</P>
<P>
   b. Newspaper
</P>
<P>
   c. Tabloid
</P>
<P>
   d. Howard Stern
</P>
<P>
   e. TV commercial, toy (i.e. Furby, Game Boy, Bouncing Tigger,
etc.)
</P>
<P>
   f. TV commercial, non-toy (i.e. Budweiser, Norelco, Snake Light,
etc.)
</P>
<P>
   g. Strange man wandering around living room late Christmas Eve
</P>
<P>
   h. Reindeer poop on roof
</P>
<P>
   i. Parents
</P>
<P>
   j. Word of mouth
</P>
<P>
   k. Other (specify):-----
</P>
<P>
   2) In your mind, Santa Claus represents:
</P>
<P>
   a. The spirit of giving
</P>
<P>
   b. The spirit of getting
</P>
<P>
   c. A mountain of toys and gifts
</P>
<P>
   d. A mountain of debt
</P>
<P>
   e. The commercialization of Christmas
</P>
<P>
   f. The Christmasization of commercials
</P>
<P>
   g. The innocence of childhood
</P>
<P>
   h. The innocence of bankruptcy
</P>
<P>
   3) On a scale of 1 to 10, what aspects of Santa's appearance
and/or personality do you find most/least appealing (1 is most
appealing; 10 is least appealing):
</P>
<P>
   a. Jolly demeanor ---
</P>
<P>
   b. Giving spirit ---
</P>
<P>
   c. Scratchy whiskers -----
</P>
<P>
   d. Heavy, red, perspiration-absorbing suit ----
</P>
<P>
   e. Cuffs and collar made from real animal fur ----
</P>
<P>
   f. Startling, unprovoked ho-ho-hos ----
</P>
<P>
   g. Sickly-sweet breath that suggests candy-cane addiction or
nascent diabetic condition ----
</P>
<P>
   h. Utter lack of muscle tone ----
</P>
<P>
   i. The way he yawns whenever you mention the elves' sweatshop
working conditions ----
</P>
<P>
   j. Loud cursing when fat butt gets stuck in chimney ----
</P>
<P>
   k. The way he refuses, year after year, to bring you that
assault rifle you've always wanted ----
</P>
<P>
   l. That discriminatory ``naughty/nice'' business ---
</P>
<P>
   4) What aspect of the Santa Claus story do you find most/least
believable? (1 for most believable; 10 for least believable.):
</P>
<P>
   a. Delivers presents to millions of children all around the
world in only one night ---
</P>
<P>
   b. Flying reindeer ---
</P>
<P>
   c. No labor union for elves ----
</P>
<P>
   d. Lifestyle makes Michael Jackson's look normal, yet no scandal
stories in National Enquirer ---
</P>
<P>
   e. An old, fat man, traveling alone, who conspicuously carries
lots of valuable loot through bad neighborhoods after dark yet
never gets mugged ---
</P>
<P>
   f. Can break into homes without setting off the security alarm
or getting bitten on butt by angry Rotweiller ---
</P>
<P>
   g. If he's so clever, why does he live year-'round at the North
Pole? ---
</P>
<P>
   5) List the best/worst ways that Santa could modernize his image
(1 is best; 10 is worst):
</P>
<P>
   a. Lose the gut ---
</P>
<P>
   b. Have him confess sex addiction on Jerry Springer show ---
</P>
<P>
   c. Have him run for governor of Minnesota as Santa ``The Booty''
Claus ---
</P>
<P>
   d. Ditch sleigh; replace with sports utility vehicle ---
</P>
<P>
   e. Do infomercial for Thigh Master ---
</P>
<P>
   f. Have affair with one of the Spice Girls ---
</P>
<P>
   g. Sign sportswear contract with Nike ---
</P>
<P>
   h. Shave beard; go with three-day stubble look ---
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Sarasota (Fla.)
Herald-Tribune.)
</P>
</TEXT>
