<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Dec. 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures soared to 77 degrees at Pierre, S.D., on Tuesday, a
reading indicative of the unusual weather pattern holding across
the contiguous states. Thursday, unseasonable warmth will persist
across much of the eastern half of the nation as fast jet stream
winds from the west-southwest over the northern-tier states
continue to impede the advance of colder air from Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Wet weather will again beset parts of the Pacific Northwest as
an important southward dip in the jet stream marks an active trough
of low pressure over the eastern Pacific Ocean. Moderate to heavy
rains are possible later Thursday or Thursday night in northern
California as a potent Pacific disturbance associated with the
trough moves inland. Isolated thunderstorms may accent the rain in
some areas. Prior to the arrival of the disturbance, moist onshore
winds will promote broken areas of lighter rains from western
Washington to northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a renegade low pressure system in the southern branch
of the jet stream will generate showers and thunderstorms across
the southern Plains. The heaviest rains will fall across parts of
north-central and northeast Texas, Oklahoma, southeast Kansas and
western Arkansas, where moisture streaming northward from the Gulf
of Mexico is lifted by the disturbance. A few thunderstorms could
approach severe levels, but low clouds will limit heating by the
sun and thereby limit the potential for severe storms.
</P>
<P>
   Precipitation over the northern Plains will be spotty and light
because moisture will be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Skip Winter
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Minnesotans skipped winter. The mercury rose to 68
degrees at the capital on Tuesday, setting a new all-time record
for December. The previous record for the month at Minneapolis was
63 degrees, set most recently in 1982. Many other locations in
central and southern Minnesota set daily and monthly records as
readings rose into the 60s. These values are typical for the first
day of autumn, rather than the last few weeks of this season when
afternoon readings should be near freezing. The warmth will persist
until the weekend when a large storm will bring back seasonal
chill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1753EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
