<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARING FOOD MAY BE A GENDER THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday Dec. 8)  
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I may be wandering into sensitive territory here, but I think
that women are more adept at sharing their food than men.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about collective dining,
eating-off-another-person's-plate kind of sharing.
</P>
<P>
   Simple observation proves it. At a restaurant you're more apt to
see a tableful of women passing their plates back and forth than a
tableful of men.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the men are serious foodies or have a professional
interest in sampling a menu, women seem to be more comfortable at
round-table eating where you are welcome to stick your fork into
another's plate without getting stabbed.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it works. You and, for example, five friends agree
to order six different items which you all have some interest in
tasting.
</P>
<P>
   You may be the one to lobby for the ravioli but it will not
become your personal ravioli. You may not even get to have the
first bite of it or the last. However, if the ravioli is a big
success you could get credit for making a stunning choice.
Likewise, because there's general consensus before ordering, if the
ravioli's a flop it's not your fault. Or your loss, since there are
five other dishes to eat from.
</P>
<P>
   Many women assume they'll be doing collective dining when they
go out together. It's as if every restaurant is Chinese style.
We'll just order a bunch of food and pass it around.
</P>
<P>
   But I suspect that when men go out with their men friends that
doesn't naturally happen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course I also suspect that when men go out with men they
order big steaks dripping with blood and fat and other retro food
like baked potatoes with butter and sour cream which they wash down
with brown liquor and top off with cigars. If you ask them later
what they had to eat they say pizza.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not fair to stereotype. If they did that with women
they'd have us all sipping wine spritzers and ordering dainty
salads _ dressing on the side _ arguing over the check and leaving
paltry tips.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't true with the gangs I graze with.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a good sized group you can end up experiencing a
large part of the menu. You don't have to decide on the honeyed
lamb, the calamari or the marinated duck. You can have it all. At
least guaranteed bites.
</P>
<P>
   It's like being at your own personal food tasting, minus the
sorbet in between to cleanse your palate.
</P>
<P>
   You want to choose a restaurant that understands collective
dining, one that doesn't mind that you order six appetizers, three
salads and four desserts, sometimes no entrees at all and need
extra plates.
</P>
<P>
   You can only do this with friends who also look at eating as an
adventure, who aren't worried about germs, who are flexible and
don't get upset when strange and unlike foods touch each other.
</P>
<P>
   Some people, not necessarily just men, don't like foreign
elements next to their chicken. They order chicken, they're
thinking about chicken, and chicken is all they want to taste. They
do not welcome non-chicken elements being spooned onto their plate.
These people seldom offer chicken bites and when asked will give up
the tiniest amount, grudgingly. Perhaps they grew up with a brother
or sister sitting next to them like some giant seagull, ready to
grab their last drumstick when they weren't paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   In the collective dining style you can't horde.
</P>
<P>
   You also want to make certain that no one in the group is on a
diet or has grave food prejudices and could act out if the pasta
comes with chipotle sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally you do see men and women sharing their food in
public. They sit side by side and feed each other off their forks.
But this is probably something else, a prelude to greater
intimacies. They don't count in this discussion.
</P>
<P>
   I used to think that a willingness of women to eat from
another's plate was a natural result of the mothering experience,
seeing how mothers can eat anything at anytime, no matter who's
touched it. But maybe we're just more daring in our eating habits,
more eager to challenge tradition. Or could be we're just not sure
when we'll get out to eat again so we better try it all.
</P>
<P>
   Collective dining becomes the evening's entertainment.
Participants tend to sigh and moan a lot and discuss each offering.
You also tend to eat slowly, at the same pace, respecting
everyone's butternut squash moment.
</P>
<P>
   The group effort means that eventually just about everything on
the table disappears. Waiters learn not to clear prematurely just
because there's a pause in the action.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly someone can eat this last sliver of hazelnut torte.
Here, let's cut it into sixths.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. Her e-mail address is sfswartz(at)pressdemo.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1754EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
