<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9535 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COOKIES03a-COX     12-02 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COOKIES03a-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life long search for the perfect Christmas confection owes its
start to parade of ants
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My search for the perfect Christmas cookie began behind a column
of ants in an Alabama kitchen 41 years ago, before I was tall
enough to reach the countertop.
</P>
<P>
   I have no memory of it, but the domestic legend is retold
whenever several of us get together with homemade cookies on the
table. With three children under 6, my mother had time to herself
only when we slept. Projects that took more than one nap time were
considered very big deals indeed, especially if they involved
cooking _ not her favorite pastime. And so on a quiet afternoon in
December 1958, she worked quickly, cutting out and baking a whole
season's worth of sugar cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The next afternoon she dressed her Santa Clauses in
white-trimmed red suits and chocolate boots. She iced the bells
with blue, the stars with yellow and Christmas trees with green,
and topped them with sprinkles, cinnamon red hots and those silver
dragees so hard to find today.
</P>
<P>
   When I got up from my nap, she lifted me up to see them laid out
to dry on the countertop. Then she went to the bedroom to get my
sister out of her crib.
</P>
<P>
   That's when, as the story goes, I spied the ants and picked up
the pump-action ant sprayer.
</P>
<P>
   When she heard the familiar ``psst, psst, psst,'' Mama ran down
the hall crying, ``No, Marcia, no.'' She asked if I had sprayed the
cookies, but in the end she couldn't take any chances.
</P>
<P>
   She gathered up all her work, took it outside and threw it in
the trash.
</P>
<P>
   Mama doesn't know if she made more cookies that year, but
starting the next year, she let me help. All I know is I've been
baking and decorating and clipping recipes ever since, trying to
find cookies as perfect as those red-suited Santas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9536 &Cx1f; tad-z
