<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COOKIES-RECIPES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Closing in on confection perfection
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years I've been on the trail of the perfect cookie.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind, it has just a few ingredients, ones that are easy to
find and aren't too difficult either to mix or to bake. It might be
crunchy, but it isn't necessarily chocolate. And most of all, it is
more delicious than any other.
</P>
<P>
   In my husband's mind, it's a Mallomar.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it's a Viennese Crescent _ a sublime and proportionally
superior combination of vanilla sugar, freshly mashed walnuts,
unsalted butter and flour that meets all my expectations when it's
cookie baking time.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie cutters seem to stamp out copies of themselves in my
kitchen, where every year I wonder how the stuff multiplies. There
are three cookie presses, decorating bags, cookie stamps, cutters
shaped like letters and numbers, airplanes, trucks and dogs.
Santas, angels, stars, wise men and sprucelike trees are there,
too, although one nontraditional year we decorated palm trees and
had Santa truck in the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   This year, while looking for cookies that don't contain butter _
because the price of a pound hovered around $4 _ I found a new
keeper in the gingersnaps in Elinor Klivans' new book, ``125
Cookies to Bake, Nibble and Savor'' (Broadway, $25). Klivans also
offers great tips on freezing cookies wrapped by twos in plastic
wrap and storing in metal or plastic freezer containers.
</P>
<P>
   Other cookie-baking tips:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Turn cookie sheets halfway through baking, even if you're
baking only one sheet. Ovens have hot spots, and cookies will bake
more evenly if turned.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Line cookie sheets with parchment paper, available in the
baking supplies section of most large grocery stores and at kitchen
specialty shops.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Most professionals recommend shiny, heavy-duty cookie sheets,
though I've had good results with insulated sheets. Whatever your
preference, let them cool between uses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unless the recipe says otherwise, chill dough before baking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If a recipe doesn't specify how to cool the cookies, cool on
the sheets for a minute or two, then transfer to wire racks to cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Viennese Crescents
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 dozen crescents Preparation time: 45 minutes Cooking
time: 15-18 minutes for each sheet Standing time: overnight for
vanilla sugar
</P>
<P>
   Introductory remarks on this seemingly simple recipe caught my
eye: ``When this recipe was first published in The (New York)
Times, one food authority wrote that it was, in her opinion, the
greatest cookie recipe ever devised.'' How could I resist? Because
there are so few ingredients, use the best. Crack and chop fresh
walnuts, use a good-quality vanilla bean and the best butter you
can find.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 vanilla bean
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped walnut meats
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Chop the piece of vanilla bean. Pound it in a mortar or
pulverize it in an electric blender with about 1 tablespoon of the
sugar. Mix with the remaining confectioners' sugar. Cover and let
stand, preferably overnight. Cut the walnuts with a sharp knife
into very small pieces. Pound the nuts to a paste, using a mortar
and pestle.
</P>
<P>
   When you are ready to make the cookies, preheat oven to 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   With a wooden spoon or your fingers, mix the walnuts, butter,
granulated sugar and flour to a smooth dough. Shape the dough,
about a teaspoon at a time, into small crescents about 1 1/2 inches
in diameter. Place an inch apart on ungreased cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 15-18 minutes, until lightly browned at edges. Put vanilla
confectioners' sugar in a shallow dish. Cool the cookies one minute
on the sheet, then, while they are still warm, roll them in the
vanilla sugar. Store in airtight containers for 3 days, or freeze.
_ From ``The New York Times Cook Book,'' by Craig Claiborne (Harper
&AMP; Row, 1961)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 62 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 51), 7 grams carbohydrates, 7 milligrams
cholesterol, less than 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate-Tipped Butter Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 dozen cookies Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time:
10-12 minutes for each sheet
</P>
<P>
   This has been my sister-in-law's favorite since it was published
by Scripps Howard News Service in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 (6-ounce) package semisweet chocolate morsels
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon hydrogenated vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. With electric mixer, cream butter
and confectioners' sugar until fluffy. Add vanilla. Gradually add
flour, mixing well with a wooden spoon or the hands. Dough will be
dry. Shape dough into sticks about 2 1/2 inches long, 1/2 inch wide
and 1/2 inch deep (thick). Place on ungreased cookie sheets about
an inch apart. Flatten 3/4 of each cookie lengthwise with fork to
1/4 inch thickness, leaving the patterns of the fork tines in the
dough.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 10-12 minutes, or until set but not brown. Remove to wire
racks to cool.
</P>
<P>
   Combine chocolate morsels and shortening in microwaveable dish;
microwave on high (100 percent power) 45 to 60 seconds, or until
melted. Or melt in top of double boiler or in a heavy-bottom pan.
</P>
<P>
   Put melted chocolate in a small, deep glass. Dip the thick,
plain end of each cooled cookie in chocolate mixture and let excess
drip back into the glass. Place cookies on wax paper until
chocolate is firm. Store in airtight containers between layers of
wax paper for 3 days or freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 77 calories, 1 gram protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 63), 7 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Toasted Hazelnut Shortbread Shapes Dipped in Milk Chocolate
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 dozen Preparation time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 1 hour
Cooking time: 20 minutes each sheet
</P>
<P>
   A shortbread variation, this one is sweetened with toasted
hazelnuts and dipped in milk chocolate. Rolling the dough 1/4 inch
thick ensures the delicate cookies won't crumble when you dip them.
If you don't have heavyweight cookie sheets, reduce the baking time
and watch them closely.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup peeled hazelnuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound plus 4 tablespoons (2 1/2 sticks) soft unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup superfine granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Parchment paper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable shortening
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces milk chocolate, chopped (preferably Callebaut or Dove
Bar)
</P>
<P>
   Put the cornstarch and hazelnuts in the work bowl of a food
processor fitted with the steel blade and process with a few short
bursts to combine. Process the mixture about 2 minutes, until the
hazelnuts are finely ground. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour, baking powder and salt together. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put the butter in a large bowl and beat with an electric mixer
on low speed for 15 seconds. Add the sugar slowly and beat on
medium speed for 2 minutes, until the mixture lightens slightly in
color and looks smooth. Stop the mixer and scrape the sides of the
bowl once during the mixing. Blend in the vanilla. Decrease the
speed to low and mix in the nuts. Add the flour mixture and beat
just until a soft dough forms. Stop the mixer and scrape the bowl
and the beaters during the mixing. Form the dough into two 6-inch
discs and wrap in plastic wrap. Refrigerate until the dough is cold
and just firm enough to roll, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Position 2 oven racks in the lower middle and upper third of the
oven. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Line 2 heavyweight baking sheets
with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Remove 1 disk of dough from the refrigerator. Lightly flour the
rolling surface and rolling pin and roll the dough 1/4-inch thick.
Use a 2-inch metal cutter to cut out shapes. With a metal spatula,
transfer the cookies to the prepared baking sheets, placing them 1
inch apart. Remove the second disc from the refrigerator and
repeat. Gather the scraps together and repeat until all the dough
is used.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the cookies for up to 20 minutes, or until they are golden,
reversing the baking sheets after 10 minutes front to back and top
to bottom to ensure even baking. Cool the cookies on the baking
sheets for 5 minutes, then use a wide metal spatula to transfer
them to wire racks to cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Put the vegetable shortening and milk chocolate in a heatproof
container and place it over, but not touching, a saucepan of barely
simmering water. Stir over the hot water until the chocolate is
melted and the mixture is smooth. Put the melted chocolate mixture
in a small, shallow bowl. Dip one side of the top of each cookie in
the chocolate and place it on the wire rack until the chocolate is
firm. Use a sweeping motion to pull one side of the cookie through
the chocolate. _ From ``125 Cookies to Bake, Nibble and Savor'' by
Elinor Klivans (Broadway, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 69 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 6 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 78), 4 grams carbohydrates, 10
milligrams cholesterol, 16 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Ribbon Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 54 cookies Preparation time: 25 minutes Cooking time: 10
minutes for each sheet
</P>
<P>
   Method is what makes this cookie a standout. Half the dough is
flavored with chocolate and half with rum, then they are layered
and cut to form striped cookies. If you don't have a taste for rum,
flavor with almond or vanilla extract.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup semisweet chocolate morsels, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup miniature semisweet chocolate pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon rum flavoring, or 1/2 teaspoon almond or vanilla
extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a mixing bowl, beat butter and
shortening with an electric mixer on medium to high speed for 30
seconds. Add sugar, baking soda and salt; beat until combined. Beat
in the egg, milk and vanilla. Beat in as much of the flour as you
can with the mixer and stir in remaining flour.
</P>
<P>
   Divide dough in half. Knead the melted chocolate and nuts into
half of the dough. Knead the miniature chocolate pieces and rum or
other flavoring into the other half of the dough. Divide each of
these portions of dough in half.
</P>
<P>
   To shape dough, line the bottom and sides of a 9-by-5-by-3-inch
loaf pan with wax paper or clear plastic wrap. Press half the
chocolate dough evenly in pan. Top with half the vanilla dough,
then the remaining chocolate dough, then the remaining vanilla
dough, pressing each layer firmly and evenly over the last layer.
</P>
<P>
   Invert pan to remove dough. Peel off wax paper or plastic wrap.
Cut dough crosswise into thirds. Then turn each third and slice
crosswise into 1/4-inch-thick slices. Place cookies 2 inches apart
on an ungreased cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake cookies about 10 minutes or until edges are firm and
bottoms are lightly browned. Transfer the cookies to a wire rack to
cool. _ From ``Better Homes and Gardens Cookie Classics''
(Meredith, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 93 calories, 1 gram protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 10 grams carbohydrates, 11 milligrams
cholesterol, 16 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 dozen 2 1/2-inch cookies Preparation time: 25 minutes
Chilling time: 1 hour or more Cooking time: 8-10 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   Cutout cookies decorated with colored sugars or tinted frosting
are required at our house, and this year we'll use this version
calling for shortening instead of butter.
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughly cream shortening, sugar and vanilla. Add egg and
milk; beat till light and fluffy. Sift together dry ingredients;
blend into creamed mixture. Divide dough in quarters. Cover with
plastic wrap and chill at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. On lightly floured surface, roll
one quarter of the dough to 1/8 inch thickness. Chill other
portions until ready to roll them. Cut in desired shapes with
cutters. Transfer to ungreased cookie sheets and bake 8 to 10
minutes. Cool slightly; remove to wire racks to cool. _ Adapted
from ``Better Homes and Gardens New Cook Book'' (Bantam, 1976)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 45 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 46), 6 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 28 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Gingersnaps
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 50, 2 1/2-inch cookies Preparation time:15-20
minutes Cooking time: 8-10 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   A snap to bake, these snaps fill the house with a holiday scent
that beats a candle. The dough is very sticky but easier to handle
once it's rolled in sugar.
</P>
<P>
   2 1/3 cups unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup canola oil or corn oil (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1 cup packed dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Use either heavy-duty cookie sheets
or insulated sheets; line sheets with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Sift the flour, baking soda, salt, cinnamon, cloves, ginger and
nutmeg together and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, put oil, molasses, brown sugar and egg. Beat
with electric mixer until smooth, about 30 seconds. Add flour
mixture and mix at low speed until incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Put the granulated sugar in a small bowl. Drop dough (which will
be sticky) by heaping teaspoonfuls into bowl of sugar and, with
your fingertips, roll it around until it is completely covered with
sugar. Place balls on cookie sheets about 2 inches apart. Bake in
center of oven for about 8-10 minutes, turning sheet around halfway
through baking. Cookies are done when they flatten and tops crack.
Cool on baking sheet 2 minutes, then transfer to wire racks to cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Measure oil in a measuring cup, then, without wiping out
cup, use it to measure molasses and the molasses won't stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 80 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 40), 12 grams carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 49 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Master Dough
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough dough for two varieties of cookies Preparation
time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Glover Pendleton, former food editor of Gourmet magazine,
bases her new book on this master dough and how it can be used to
make 50 different cookies. If you don't have an 11-cup food
processor or an electric stand mixer, you'll get a workout mixing
this dough.
</P>
<P>
   1 pound (4 sticks) unsalted butter, softened slightly
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt (use 3/4 teaspoon if using salted butter)
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg yolks (save the whites for use later)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   4 3/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   If using a heavy-duty electric mixer with paddle attachment: In
a large bowl, cream together the butter, sugar and salt. Add the
egg yolks and vanilla and beat until smooth. Add the flour
gradually, beating on low speed until incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   If using a food processor with a steel blade and with a bowl
capacity of 11 cups or more: In the food processor, blend the
flour, sugar, butter (cut into small pieces) and salt until the
mixture is crumbly. Add the yolks and vanilla, and blend the
mixture, scraping the bowl occasionally, until it forms a dough.
</P>
<P>
   If mixing by hand: In a large mixing bowl, cream together the
butter, sugar and salt, stirring with a wooden spoon. Stir in egg
yolks and vanilla. Gradually add flour and stir with spoon or mix
with hands.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Classic Spritz Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 7 dozen Preparation time: 15 minutes Cooking time: 12 to
14 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   You can freeze the Master Dough for use later for most of the
book's 50 varieties _ except this Spritz cookie. Because dough
consistency is tricky when using a cookie press, make these right
away.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Master Dough (recipe at right)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup egg whites, lightly beaten with 2 teaspoons water
</P>
<P>
   Decorations: colored sugars or sprinkles, chopped nuts or
glaceed fruits
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Fit the canister of a cookie press with the desired cutting
disc. Then fill it with some of the dough. Press out the cookies 1
inch apart on cool, clean, ungreased baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Brush the cookies lightly with the egg white mixture and
decorate as desired.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until the edges are pale golden, 12-14 minutes. Let the
cookies cool on the sheets for 1 minute, then transfer to wire
racks to cool completely. Do not let the cookies cool too long on
the sheets or the egg whites and sugar may cause them to stick. _
From ``One Dough Fifty Cookies,'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton
(William Morrow, $13)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 40 calories, 1 gram protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 54), 4 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 16 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mocha Butter Balls
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 dozen Preparation time: 15 -20 minutes Cooking time:
15-20 minutes per sheet
</P>
<P>
   Instant espresso powder really perks up the nutty chocolate of
these sugar-coated bites. While it can be hard to find (we found
some at Harry's Farmers Market in Alpharetta) you can grind enough
instant espresso or instant coffee to equal 2 teaspoons powder.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 recipe Master Dough (recipe at right)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsweetened cocoa
</P>
<P>
   powder
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons instant espresso powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped walnuts or pecans
</P>
<P>
   About 2 cups confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the dough, cocoa powder, espresso
powder and nuts until thoroughly combined, using either an electric
mixer on medium speed or using your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Roll the dough into 1-inch balls and arrange them 3/4 inch apart
on ungreased baking sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake until they are just firm and beginning to brown, 15 to 20
minutes. Let the cookies cool for 5 minutes on the sheets.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, whisk the confectioners' sugar (sift if sugar
is very lumpy). While the cookies are still warm, working with a
few at a time, coat them with the sugar by swirling them around in
the bowl. Transfer to sheets of wax paper to cool completely. _
From ``One Dough Fifty Cookies'' by Leslie Glover Pendleton
(William Morrow, $13)
</P>
<P>
   Per cookie: 70 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 50), 9 grams carbohydrates, 14 milligrams
cholesterol, 17 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
