<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 COX &HT;    A custardy version of pecan pie
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Though Georgia home cooks probably have about as many
pecan pie recipes as cooks anywhere, not too many came through when
Shirley Chapman of Atlanta requested a version with a custard
filling.
</P>
<P>
   Among the handful that have trickled in since the summer request
is this one from Betty Crosson of Carrollton, GA. It includes
vanilla pudding mix and may not be exactly what Chapman had in
mind, but it is a nice change from the usual syrupy pies.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Creamy Pecan Pie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 4 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 3-ounce package
</P>
<P>
   cook-and-serve
</P>
<P>
   vanilla pudding mix
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup evaporated
</P>
<P>
   low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 9-inch unbaked pie shell
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In medium bowl, blend pudding mix
with corn syrup. Add milk and egg, then stir in pecans. Place pie
shell on cookie sheet on oven rack. Pull out oven rack and fill pie
shell with pecan mixture (this avoids spills). Bake 40 minutes or
until top is cracked and a thin knife inserted in center comes out
clean. Cool on wire rack 1 1/2 hours, then refrigerate 3 hours
until chilled. Refrigerate leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 384 calories, 4 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 55 grams carbohydrates, 27
milligrams cholesterol, 270 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Leslie Booth of Fayetteville, GA. is looking for a wing sauce
recipe with more ingredients than Tabasco sauce and butter, similar
to those at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sheila Richardson of Dahlonega seeks a corn bread salad recipe
such as one served at Ancheaux's restaurant in Clemson, S.C. It
includes moist corn bread, cucumbers, tomatoes, bell peppers, corn
and other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone
number. E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
