<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SAVEUR03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine celebrates real food, real cooks _ and circulation
soars
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From peasant fare to prix fixe feasts, the world of food is
often divided between the everyday and the gourmet. But for the
folks at upstart Saveur magazine, such a distinction is off the
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply think `good food' and `bad food,' '' explains editor
and co-founder Colman Andrews, as he savors his first taste of
cracklin' bread at Harold's Barbecue in south Atlanta. It quickly
takes a place in his ``good food'' category.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, who lived in Atlanta briefly in 1964, banging out
free-lance stories on a typewriter borrowed from famed Atlanta
Constitution Editor Ralph McGill, was back in town recently to
promote his magazine's new cookbook, ``Saveur Cooks Authentic
American'' (Chronicle Books, $40). It's a lush look at what we eat
in our homes and favorite restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``French fries done right are better than foie gras _ from a can
with a dent in it _ that tastes like shoe polish,'' he goes on
between the Brunswick stew and chopped pork.
</P>
<P>
   Food done right is what Saveur magazine, and now the cookbook,
is all about. And doing it right can just as often mean honoring a
tradition as perfecting a technique, with the expert as likely to
be your next-door neighbor as a celebrity chef.
</P>
<P>
   There, on Page 108 of the cookbook, renowned American chef
Jonathan Waxman shows how to stuff a whole striped bass with blood
oranges and fresh tarragon and bake it in a salt crust. Turn the
page and there's South Carolina game warden Ben Moise giving the
lowdown on a Lowcountry oyster roast, complete with the sauce that
starts with plain old ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Both are illustrated with compelling on-location photos _ a
trademark of the magazine. There are more than 400 stunning
photographs throughout the cookbook, illustrating 175 recipes and
numerous short stories about the people, places and rituals behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes Saveur equally at home on the coffee table and
the kitchen counter. As book or magazine, it's as engaging to
browse and read as it is to cook with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to operate on the common wisdom that said you
have to have 100 recipes per issue, and 25 percent needed to be low
fat, and you have to review restaurants, and you have to address
health concerns,'' Andrews says.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he and co-founders Dorothy Kalins and Christopher
Hirsheimer _ all friends, foodies and journalists _ wanted a
magazine that ``reflected the way we feel'' about food, he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   One look at the publication and you know that that ``feeling''
is for food as culture, as history, as geography, as soul and
sensation. And then back again to being simply good food.
</P>
<P>
   Capturing all that means going to the rivers of Minnesota to see
the wild rice being harvested; squeezing a ``dead man's recipe''
for fried chicken out of Gus Vanderbilt, who runs a joint near
Memphis; and discerning that the burritos at H&AMP;H Coffee Shop in El
Paso, Texas, transcend all ``wrap'' trends.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are authentic, the photographs almost always
naturally lit and presented. No glossy spreads of beautiful people
with fake laughs drinking cocktails here _ even in the book's
section on cocktails. Instead, we see real bars and real
bartenders.
</P>
<P>
   And trends? ``Oh, they say basil is out this year,'' Andrews
says. ``Well, it's been around for 3,000 years. Trends in food are
invented by people who don't want to do one thing well for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see balsamic barbecue turkey wraps at Harold's,''
Andrews points out. ``You might at a lesser place.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that attitude and its reflection in Saveur _ pronounced
``sa-VUR'' and meaning flavor or taste _ that has shaken up the
food magazine business. In just three years, Saveur has won six
James Beard Awards, two National Magazine Awards and Advertising
Age's Magazine of the Year Award. Subscriptions have far surpassed
the original target of 100,000 and are now around 375,000, Andrews
says.
</P>
<P>
   That means Monte's secret is out.
</P>
<P>
   Monte Mathews is an advertising copywriter in New York who
believes the trick to entertaining a crowd is a cheap ham,
hopefully not costing more than 99 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   In the cookbook (and here), he shares his recipe for spiking a
smoked, bone-in ham with whole cloves, slathering it with orange
marmalade, Dijon mustard and brown sugar, then roasting it to a
crusty brown to serve to 20 or so of your favorite people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's food done right.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
