<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE MOCKS BUSH SLOGAN OF 'COMPASSIONATE CONSERVATISM'
 &HT;    Eds: Will be updated after 9 p.m. EST with Clinton remarks.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, rehearsing his campaign for
the presidency, tweaked Texas Gov. George W. Bush and the
Republican Party's newly discovered ``compassionate conservatism''
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the centrist Democratic Leadership Council (DLC),
Gore said such talk reminded him of Theodoric of York, the Middle
Ages barber portrayed by comedian Steve Martin on TV's ``Saturday
Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After indulging in the most grotesque and primitive practices
in medicine or the law _ applying leeches or dunking witches in
vats of oil _ Theodoric would pause for a sudden blinding insight
and question whether we need a new enlightened approach _ whether
due process of law, or the scientific method, or the rule of
reason,'' Gore said. ``And after musing poetically about the
possibilities of the future, he'd admit: 'Naaah.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Bush by name, Gore gleefully noted the
similarities in the themes the Texas governor sounded in his hugely
successful re-election campaign this fall and those of President
Clinton in his 1992 campaign for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some (Republicans) now say that what we need is 'compassionate
conservatism.' They call for opportunity combined with
responsibility,'' said Gore. ``Hmmm. ...I wonder where they got
that. It sounds familiar.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``We welcome the apparent suggestion by some
Republicans that they want to move their party to the center _ that
they want to fashion their own new centrist philosophy. But we know
that there is a long road between rhetoric and results.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing differences between Democrats and Republicans on
education spending, Social Security, taxes, the environment and
crime, Gore said, ``compassion is more than a pretty word: it is
the highest of all disciplines.''
</P>
<P>
   Testing the broad themes of his campaign for the presidency in
2000, the vice president said the nation ``needs something more
than compassionate conservatism.'' He instead called for a ``new
practical idealism'' that recognizes ``our mutuality'' and moves
the country beyond ``the old polarities'' that have characterized
American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton was scheduled to address the DLC on Wednesday
evening, Gore's speech was the most anticipated event of the DLC's
one-day conference because of his front-runner status for the
party's presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was one of the founders of the DLC, which was created after
Walter Mondale's disastrous 1984 presidential campaign. The
organization, once dismissed as a refuge for disaffected white
Southern male Democrats, is widely credited with helping to move
the Democratic Party to the political center and electing Clinton
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, another DLC
founder and its first chairman, also addressed the gathering
Wednesday, but sounded less like a presidential aspirant than a
would-be speaker of the House. In fact, the DLC president, Al From,
introduced Gephardt with the prediction that a new Democratic House
majority would make him speaker in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said the Democratic Party narrowed the GOP majority in
the House this fall because of ``in-touch ideas'' of ``fairness,
opportunity and responsibility'' that are relevant to people's
lives.
</P>
<P>
   The DLC also heard from Democratic Sens. John Kerry of
Massachusetts and Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, both of whom are eyeing a
White House campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry chastised both parties for not doing more to improve
public education. ``Democrats are viewed as defending the
indefensible, while Republicans refuse to be a part of what they
believe is indefensible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Kerrey, who lost the Democratic nomination to Clinton in
1992, warned that there is ``no easy way out'' in trying to reform
Social Security. Any plan to assure long-term financing of the
federal retirement program will be a ``tough vote'' for
politicians, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
