<P>
   RUSSELL-HQ _ ATANTA _ Russell Athletic, which is moving part of
its headquarters to Atlanta, picks Cobb County, creating 400 to 500
jobs initially and twice that eventually. Plans call for a
250,000-sq-ft building on Cumberland Blvd. west of 41.(Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPS-PALMPILOT _ ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service and the maker of
the Palm Pilot personal organizer have reached a deal to have UPS
shipping and tracking technology built into the devices. UPS sees
it as a way to become the shipper of first choice among users of
the hand-held organizers. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/UPS-ARGENTINA _ ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service said it is
buying the assets of an Argentinian package delivery company and
setting up UPS de Argentina to boost its presence in the South
American country. UPS has operated in Argentina through contractors
until now. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-PALMPILOT _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth has some connections
to the new version of the 3Com Palm Pilot that can wirelessly surf
the Web. An announcement is expected. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/BELLSOUTH-CARDS _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth, still forbidden from
offering long-distance service to customers, is apparently sneaking
into long-distance by selling pre-paid long-distance cards.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATL-INVESTMENT _ Atlanta falls to fifth place in a survey that
measures foreign investment in U.S. real estate. It ranked first in
1994, 1995 and 1996, then fell to fourth in 1997. (Slater, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WESTERNCABLE _ ANAHEIM, Calif. _ We cover the opening panel of
the Western Cable show, which features industry heavyweights such
as USA's Diller, media investor Gordon Crawford, NBC President Bob
Wright and Leo Hindry, chief executive of TCI. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/WESTERNCABLE-COLOR _ ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The look and feel of
the convention and what's hot here among the attendees. (Haddad,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TEX-TELEPHONE-CHARGES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ State regulators have
approved a new surcharge that will begin appearing on all telephone
bills next month, but officials said it will replace several
charges that customers already pay and should not result in a
higher total bill. All telephone companies _ local, long-distance
and wireless, including pagers _ must pay the new fee, about eight
tenths of 1 percent of each monthly bill. They are not required to
pass on the new surcharge to customers but are expected to do so.
(Hight, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIZMAGS _ A rundown of the week's financial press. (Walker,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
