<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-FOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIBURN FOUNDATION TO STAGE AMATEUR PIANO COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
 AMATEURS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The people who just sit in the audience and
dream, but keep practicing the piano anyway, will have a chance to
shine in Fort Worth next summer: The Cliburn Foundation, presenter
of the world's most significant international piano competition for
professsionals, will sponsor an International Piano Competition for
Outstanding Amateurs, to be held June 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   John Giordano, music director of the Fort Worth Symphony and
chairman of the jury of the Van Cliburn International Piano
Competition, will head the jury. The jury will include Gerard
Bekerman, a professor of economics at the University of Paris who
is also the founder and president of the ``Concours des Grands
Amateurs de Piano,'' an international competition for amateur
pianists held annually in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rodzinski, executive director of the Cliburn Foundation,
became interested in the concept because of Aniela Rubinstein, the
widow of Artur Rubinstein and a longtime friend of Rodzinski's. A
frequent member of the jury in Paris, she spoke enthusiastically to
Rodzinski of the atmosphere of the French competition.
</P>
<P>
   Rodzinski served on the jury in Paris this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful idea,'' he says. ``Its real value is that it
encourages the making of music, not just on the stage, but at home.
In Paris, it brought together a number of people who share a common
interest. Everyone played well, but winning was not the main
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The quadrennial Cliburn competition has long served as the model
for other competitions around the world, but this new amateur
competition is frankly modeled on the Parisian competition.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1989 and financially supported by Radio France and
the cultural ministry of the government of France, the French
amateur competition draws about 100 competitors every year from
around the world. The first prize is approximately $2,000, and
every five years, the first-prize winners appear in a joint concert
of concertos with orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of the competition in Fort Worth will depend on
the success of next summer's contest. Rodzinski expects that the
funds from application fees and ticket sales will cover the cost of
the event.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants for the amateur competition in Fort Worth must be
older than 30 as of June 1, 1999, and may not earn a living as a
professional musician or music teacher. Approximately 100 pianists
will be accepted in the event, which will open with a three-day
preliminary round June 9-11 at Ed Landreth Auditorium at Texas
Christian University. Each competitor in the preliminary round will
play a 10-minute program.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 18 semifinalists will perform 20-minute programs on
June 12; six finalists will perform programs of 30 minutes on June
13. The first-prize winner will receive a cash prize of $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are no restrictions on repertory, and complete rules are
available from the Cliburn Foundation at (817) 738-6536.
Applications, including pertinent materials and an application fee
of $50, are due March 1, 1999, and accepted applicants will be
notified by April 15.
</P>
<P>
   The TCU/Cliburn Piano Institute, which annually hosts an
amateurs' program along with its programs for teachers and aspiring
professionals, will hold its amateurs' division on the TCU campus
June 1-9 and June 14-22, including selective auditions for a chance
to perform a concerto movement with the Fort Worth Chamber
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
