<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS NOTES ON COMPUTERS AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (af) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clio, a handheld computer that arrives in stores this month,
falls somewhere between standard laptops, and the smaller Windows
CE devices. The 9.4-inch screen and nearly full-sized keyboard are
akin to a laptop, but the brains _ no hard drive, 16 megabytes of
RAM, and a MIPS processor _ are not much more than a CE would
muster.
</P>
<P>
   The $999 Clio, made by Vadem, based in San Jose, Calif., offers
one added twist, literally. Its screen is attached to the keyboard
by two aluminum arms, on which the screen can rotate top to bottom.
</P>
<P>
   This ``swing-top design,'' as Vadem calls it, allows the screen
to be put in three positions: upright in a standard computer setup;
folded atop the keyboard for use as a digital tablet (it comes with
stylus and hand-recognition software), or folded outward _ opposite
the keyboard _ so that it can be used to display presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Epel, Vadem's vice president for marketing, calls the device
a ``mobile information appliance,'' leaving open the question of
whether mobile refers to the person carrying the device, or to its
screen. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At last, a compelling reason to buy high-definition television.
</P>
<P>
   Future games of the New York Rangers hockey team, the world
champion New York Yankees, the New York Mets, and the New York
Knicks _ if professional basketball ever resumes _ are going to be
delivered to cable television subscribers in high definition next
year, according to an announcement Wednesday by the MSG Network, a
division of Cablevision Systems.
</P>
<P>
   True, the current HDTV sets are atrociously expensive, costing
many thousands of dollars. Only a relative handful of people in New
York City have bought them and only a few HDTV programs have been
broadcast. But at 1,080 lines of resolution, HDTV promises to allow
cable subscribers to see each drop of sweat as clearly as if the
viewer had court-side season tickets costing many thousands of
dollars. And cable seats are easier to get.
</P>
<P>
   The MSG Network, which began HDTV broadcasts of a few Rangers
games in late October, just purchased a pair of Lucent MPEG-2
Digital Video System encoders for its Madison Square Garden digital
cable production facility, signaling that it is serious about
regular high-definition transmissions for sports and special
events.
</P>
<P>
   But one big question remains: Is HDTV a curse on New York teams?
The Rangers have lost every HDTV game so far, and the Knicks are on
strike. Does HDTV spell doom for the Yankees next season?
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter H. Lewis &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To avoid viruses in this day and age, it is advisable to be
careful when swapping floppy disks, and, perhaps before long, Web
pages too. Some companies that make virus protection software _ and
thus have a commercial interest in telling us these things _ report
they have seen a new, though rare, strain of virus notable because
it can be embedded in hypertext markup language, or HTML pages, the
documents that make up Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this virus, like most others, is not widespread and
poses no widespread danger. But the potential impact could be
significant since in theory a hard drive could get the virus simply
when a user opens an infected Web page or e-mail, said Igor
Grebert, who is a senior virus researcher at Trend Micro, a Silicon
Valley company that makes virus protection software.
</P>
<P>
   The viruses started appearing in early November, and some 20
variations have emerged, Trend Micro officials said. Many of the
viruses are not malicious, but one of them is designed to replace
``text'' files _ documents that end with ``.txt'' _ with a picture
of a naked man making a lewd gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Grebert said the viruses were not particularly worrisome
at this point for several reasons, one of which was that they were
only circulating among researchers and hackers, not ``in the
wild.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance is that this is proof of the concept that
such a virus can live in HTML,'' he said. A further reason not to
worry is that Windows, the operating system that would be
susceptible to the viruses, has some protection built in: Before
the virus can become active, Windows will provide a prompt asking a
user whether it should execute a visual basic script, the language
in which the viruses are written. This, at least, can warn users of
a pending problem.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Cooper, the moderator of the NTbugtraq mailing list, a
discussion group of security issues affecting the Windows NT
operating system, agreed that, for now at least, the viruses are no
big deal. Although he added that the concept had the potential to
``make people wary of everything on the Net.'' ``For now,'' Cooper
said, ``I'd be more worried that people will see pornography while
surfing than that they will get a virus.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have theorized that the proposed buyout by America
Online of Netscape could put a crimp in the Justice Department's
efforts to categorize the Microsoft Corp. as the Internet's
reigning monolith. A new survey seems to back that argument.
</P>
<P>
   If the buyout goes through, Web sites owned by AOL will become
by far the most dominant gateways to cyberspace, according to the
survey by Cyber Dialogue, a New York-based Internet research firm.
</P>
<P>
   The company's report says that after an AOL-Netscape alliance,
one in every three American adults would start each Web experience
from an AOL-owned site. These sites would include AOL's proprietary
service, used by 14 million people worldwide, AOL's home page on
the Web and the Netcenter portal, which is Netscape's home page.
</P>
<P>
   That dominance won't be without challenges, however, said Thomas
E. Miller, vice president of Cyber Dialogue. In particular, he
said, AOL would have to fuse two vastly different cultures _ the
newbies and neophytes of AOL with the relatively more sophisticated
surfers who regularly log onto Netcenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitudes of the two audiences are really quite
different,'' Miller said. ``The challenge is going to be how to
blend them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
