<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY'S BOOK DEAL SMACKS OF DESPERATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of this, we may be certain: Monica Lewinsky's book deal smacks
of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Press will publish ``Monica's Story'' in February.
Lewinsky's co-author, a snappier title than ``ghost writer,'' will
be Andrew Morton, best-known for writing the bestselling ``Diana:
Her True Story'' with considerable input from the princess. For
baring her soul to the world about baring the rest of herself to
Bill Clinton, Monica picks up a reported $600,000 plus ``bonuses
for bestseller rankings.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute that Lewinsky is unconditionally
thrilled. From who is publishing the book to who is helping
Lewinsky write it to the money she's being paid, the literary tea
leaves are impossible to misinterpret.
</P>
<P>
   Start with St. Martin's Press, Monica's American publisher. Yes,
the deal was supposedly put together by Britain's O'Mara Books,
which will publish ``Monica's Story'' in the rest of the world, but
by all reports the rest of the world is unconcerned with
presidential peccadilloes. For ``Monica's Story,'' financial
success hinges on U.S. sales.
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's is known for churning out quickie titles. From
David Koresh to O.J. Simpson, if there's a sensational murder or
spicy scandal, St. Martin's will probably be the first to weigh in,
usually with a superficial quick hit designed to grab a few bucks
before the fickle public turns its attention to something else.
Signing with St. Martin's is a flat-out admission by Monica and/or
her advisers that her book needs to hit stores ASAP.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it's increasingly obvious that most Americans are
sick of the whole Lewinsky business and that impeachment
proceedings against Clinton are unlikely to be the drawn-out affair
(pun intended) they seemed certain to be just a few months ago.
Back then, Monica &AMP; Co. wanted a lot more than $600,000 to spill
her guts in print. But the recent national elections shot down more
than Newt Gingrich; any publishing company's belief that countless
outraged Americans would snap up Monica's book vanished, too.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Monica's Story'' comes out in December 1999 instead of
February, it might just as well be stuck straight in the $1 bargain
bins. So St. Martin's became the perfect publisher; in this
situation, speed counts more than quality.
</P>
<P>
   Morton's involvement is further proof of sales desperation.
Among the many celebrity flavors-of-the-month over the past silly
decade or so, Princess Diana is one of the few who retained
long-term icon status. St. Martin's has to hope _ pray _ that
enough people still link Morton's name with the Diana book to buy
anything else he writes about a poor lost girl suffering through no
fault of her own.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the money. Just weeks ago, solid
publishing-industry scuttlebutt had Monica close to signing a $2.2
million deal with a much more prestigious publisher. Six hundred
thousand may seem like plenty to the rest of us, but as a
celebrity's book advance, it's less than tip money. Don't be too
impressed by the add-on bestseller bonus. ``Monica's Story'' will
undoubtedly be a bestseller for two, maybe three weeks, until the
easily titillated have bought their copies. ``Rankings'' is the key
word in the money end of the agreement. It could easily mean that
``Monica's Story'' would have to end up among 1999's top 10 sellers
to earn her an extra penny. It won't.
</P>
<P>
   If it's any consolation to Lewinsky, her scaled-down deal will
still eclipse anything Linda Tripp will get. And even if ``Monica's
Story'' sells better than expected, its success will still pale
against the numbers racked up by the Clinton book that everyone
will want to read no matter when it is published _ the White House
memoirs of Hillary Rodham Clinton. .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
