<P>
   GA-LOTTO-FELON _ ATLANTA _ The winner of the state's biggest
Lotto drawing _ a prize that could have totaled $31 million if paid
out over time _ is on parole and has a lengthy criminal history in
Georgia and at least three other states, according to records.
According to state records, new millionaire Kenny Dukes, who also
went by the name David Lee McKenzie, has been in Georgia prisons
four times since the late 1970s and will be on parole until July
2001 for burglary. Records show he also has been charged in
Georgia, Florida, South Carolina and Nevada with felonies such as
aggravated assault, theft, robbery, drunken driving, fraud,
domestic violence, simple battery, trespassing and obstruction of a
police officer. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CARE _ ATLANTA _ Fifty years ago, the relief organization CARE
delivered boxes of food and supplies to grateful Europeans
struggling to recover from the ravages of World War II. But CARE
could never get away today with doing what they did then. Those
boxes contained peanut butter, which was alien to the native
population. They contained candy, which is not nutritious. And they
contained cigarettes, which damage health. Today, aid workers
realize that aid can hurt the people it is intended to help. It can
foster dependency. It can help fuel a war, as in Sudan. Camps that
save refugees can also harbor killers, as in Rwanda. So as CARE
begins work in Honduras and Nicaragua, it is working hard to
deliver aid in an effective and non-harmful way. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EARHART-BONES _ A newly rediscovered record of bones found in
1940 on an island in the South Pacific give ``very strong
evidence'' that the remains might have been those of Amelia
Earhart. Nobody knows whether the bones still exist; if they do,
the scientists who conducted the DNA study on Count Casmir Pulaski
plan to run DNA tests on them to see if they're a match. They're
presenting a paper on this later this week to the American
Anthropology Association. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-ROADS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The new millennium will mean a
massive reconstruction of area highways fueled largely by growth in
the Dayton-Cincinnati area, ambitious plans unveiled earlier this
week by state highway officials show. (Bennish, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PIG-MUSIC _ STUART, Fla. _ The music two pig farmers say
they play for their swine's health and enjoyment fell within
allowable levels of Martin County's new noise ordinance last month.
``I'm just thankful the truth is in black and white,'' pig farmer
Paul Thompson said of the sheriff's report, released Tuesday.
``This isn't about music. It's about pigs, and it's about smell,''
said Thompson, who has raised pigs at his home for more than three
decades. (Moore, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
