A9650 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-LAMAFIA-HNS     12-02 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-LAMAFIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING UP IS HARD TO DO FOR LA MAFIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: `norteno' in 21st paragraph has a tilde over the second
`n' 
 
By JOEY GUERRA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Houston-based Tejano supergroup La Mafia has decided
to call it quits after nearly two decades of music, international
success, two Grammy awards and a slew of multiplatinum albums.
</P>
<P>
   But not before one more tour.
</P>
<P>
   The band's latest album, ``Euforia,'' was released in September
on Sony Discos. The first single, ``Pido,'' was a top 20 hit on
Billboard's Hot Latin Tracks chart. La Mafia will hold a press
conference Thursday addressing the break-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been thinking about it. It's hard because I've been
doing this since I was 12 with La Mafia,'' lead singer Oscar de la
Rosa said Wednesday at Houston Sound Studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knew that this was going to happen. I didn't even know
it was going to happen. It's just something that I decided a few
months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Located just off Interstate 45 North, Houston Sound Studio has
served as La Mafia's headquarters and recording studio. Every wall
is adorned with posters, platinum albums and snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, the fortress was quiet, and the mood
somber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm just getting tired of doing the same thing,'' de
la Rosa said. ``All the touring, always away from home. You start
doing things because you have to, not because you want to. I want
to enjoy myself when I'm performing, and it's gotten to a point to
where it's like work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say that I didn't enjoy it, because I love
when the fans get into what you're doing. It just started getting
to a point to where it was work, and it wasn't music anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   La Mafia established itself as the premiere Tejano group in
Texas and around the world. After nearly two dozen albums on small
and local labels, the group signed with Sony Discos and released
``Estas Tocando Fuego'' in 1991. It sold more than 1 million copies
worldwide, a then-unheard-of number for the primarily regional
Tejano market.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent albums were also successful, thanks to La Mafia's
lilting blend of Tejano rhythms and pop sensibilities. The band
earned Grammys in 1997 for ``Un Millon de Rosas'' and in 1998 for
``En Tus Manos,'' both in the Mexican/Tejano category. Album sales
to date are well over the 5-million mark.
</P>
<P>
   Those past accomplishments are still important for de la Rosa,
as is the sense of family that developed within the band _ members
Leonard Gonzales, David de la Garza, Tim Ruiz, Michael Aguilar and
Mando Lichtenberger Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys have been wonderful. It's been great while it
lasted, but it's time to move on and try something else, do
something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The break-up comes after much discussion, de la Rosa said.
Ultimately, he wanted to end things on good terms, instead of
waiting for the wear of hectic schedules and constant promotion to
develop into disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rosa downplayed rumors of fighting and money problems, but
pointed to problems with Sony Discos as a factor in the group's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, the past few years, I've been really, really
disappointed with the label. They haven't been doing their job.
They haven't been doing the work they should have been doing for
the band,'' he said, referring to the group's disappointing
promotional tour of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there for a whole month, and we were promoting the
album (`Euforia'), visiting radio, doing TV shows,'' he said. ``We
were told (by the label) that the album was out, and we have people
that go out and check all the stores to make sure the product is
out. We find there is no product out in the stores, and so we
started asking questions. We had to cancel our tour in Mexico for
that reason. The band was totally upset with the record company
because we didn't get the respect we should've gotten.''
</P>
<P>
   La Mafia has canceled its scheduled appearances for December and
January, but the group will play 20-40 dates in the United States
and Mexico in 1999, de la Rosa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about opening the tour here in Houston or closing
the tour here in Houston, because Houston is our home base. Houston
is where the group was born,'' de la Rosa said. ``Once we go to one
city, it means we won't go back as La Mafia. It's going to be a
one-time thing, a last-time thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has one album remaining on its Sony contract. De la
Rosa said the group's final album will be similar stylistically to
``Euforia.'' An anthology of '80s hits is another possibility.
</P>
<P>
   La Mafia is selling most of its equipment, including lighting
rigs and tour buses. A bus recently purchased for the ``Euforia''
tour was sold to ``norteno'' group Los Palominos, and another truck
was sold to a musical group out of California. Houston Sound Studio
will remain. Lichtenberger, who served as La Mafia's keyboardist
and producer, will continue to work on projects with other artists.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rosa wants to get away from Houston for a few years, he
said, ``just try to start my new life ... maybe go to Miami, get
myself a condo in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, I'm happy it's over, then in a way I'm sad, because
... I'm still wondering what am I going to do. It's not going to be
the same. Come Christmas, New Year's Eve, you're always around your
friends. You're always together, and I know that this time around
we're not going to be together. Everybody's going to go their own
way. After 20 years of the same thing, it bothers you.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joey Guerra is a free-lance writer based in Houston. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9651 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANSON-SERIES-TEX     12-02 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANSON-SERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BECKER' IS THE POSTER BOY FOR STRIDENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look who's back: Ted Danson, that wild misfire called ``Ink''
safely behind him, returns to series television, and not a moment
too soon. He's gone psycho.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Becker,'' he's John Becker, doctor with an attitude. A bad
one.
</P>
<P>
   Let's assess the damage, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   On society: ``You know what's killing this country? Talk shows.
I watched one last night. I should have just stuck a fork in my
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   On talk show hosts: ``White trash is the only natural resource
this country will never run out of.''
</P>
<P>
   To an overweight patient: ``Your blood pressure's too high, your
cholesterol is through the roof, and your legs are killing you.
Then why wouldn't they be? Look what they're trying to hold up.''
</P>
<P>
   To his ditzy nurse's aide: ``If you shut your mouth, it keeps
the words from falling out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   To the homeless guy asking for spare change: ``You mean extra
change? Money that, if you weren't here, I would just throw away?''
</P>
<P>
   Becker rants and raves like this throughout the pilot, whether
eating or lounging or smoking (yeah, he puffs, on camera!) at his
favorite diner. There, he goes toe-to-toe with Reggie (Terry
Farrell), the cute female owner and certain love interest, and Jake
(Alex Desert), the blind newsstand proprietor armed with a few
snappy one-liners of his own.
</P>
<P>
   At his small clinic, Becker's head nurse (Hattie Winston)
catches his fury. At his apartment, which is supposed to be a guy's
sanctuary, Becker yells frantically out the window when a
neighbor's loud music bugs him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, foreigner,'' he screams. ``Turn that off or I'll call
immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   Creator and executive producer Dave Hackel, who produced
``Wings,'' says Becker is designed as the anti-sitcom, a half-hour
of equal-opportunity offending. He likens ``Becker'' to Archie
Bunker of ``All in the Family,'' who spoke his mind on bigotry and
politics, making us laugh at the absurdity of his views. These
days, ``You can't write about anything without offending someone,''
Hackel moans. ``It's a little silly.''
</P>
<P>
   So Becker is Archie without the narrow bigotry and with a brain,
zeroing in on the irritating aspects of contemporary American life.
The question, of course, is whether we'll laugh at his deranged
overreactions and if we'll simply tire of him going postal every
week.
</P>
<P>
   Hackel is betting that we'll not only laugh, but identify with
his tantrums, indulging our secret desires to see a loud,
music-playing foreigner get his.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's reading too much into ``Becker,'' but it reminds me
of the Michael Douglas film ``Falling Down,'' that kind of
manipulative revenge fantasy that shot its credibility by going
after such broad, easy targets.
</P>
<P>
   Same here. Everyone Becker meets should get it: The fat guy who
won't diet, the car saleswoman who cries on Becker's shoulder
(''Can I talk to a man salesman, please?''), the homeless guy
looking for change.
</P>
<P>
   He goes after TV talk shows, but Becker's own tone reminds me of
those glib, self-righteous jerks populating talk radio. Instead of
offering a coherent point of view, Becker merely gripes, hoping for
a reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, deep down, Becker isn't anti-sitcom at all.
Tonight, for instance, he shows compassion for an HIV-positive
7-year-old, even paying for the kid's treatment. And remember the
fat guy to whom he gave a tongue-lashing? Before leaving the
examination room, he tells him, softly, ``Hey, you can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike, say, ``All in the Family,'' where Archie's views matured
and his heart softened, somewhat, over several years, ``Becker''
already has a heart. It's hidden from his colleagues but
conveniently exposed to viewers.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially a cop-out, because Becker's under-the-table
good deeds are designed to take the sting out of the ranting that
lures us in the first place. We're asked to believe that Becker
isn't the true aggressor at all. He's merely the poor defender,
striking back at a lousy world.
</P>
<P>
   To me, he's merely an angry guy who needs to take a chill pill.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins covers television for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
