<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS     12-02 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOCIDE-MINISTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGES ORDERS CLERGYMAN RELEASED TO WAR CRIMES TRIBUNAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ A federal judge ordered that an elderly former
pastor be handed over to a United Nations war crimes tribunal to
face charges of genocide in his native Rwanda, the man's lawyer
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge John Rainey issued the order Monday but gave
the defense lawyer 30 days to appeal the decision, effectively
delaying extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey Clark, the former U.S. attorney general who is
representing Elizaphan Ntakirutimana, said he would appeal the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Rainey ruled that there was sufficient evidence to warrant
Ntakirutimana's arrest and that it was legal to hand him over to
the tribunal. If that happens, it would mark the first time a
person arrested on U.S. soil would face a war crimes tribunal,
officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal, based in Tanzania, has accused the 74-year-old
Ntakirutimana of leading attackers armed with machetes, grenades
and guns in a murderous April 1994 rampage that killed dozens of
people who were hiding in the church.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Rwanda was in the throes of a bloody feud between
the country's dominant ethnic groups, the Hutus and Tutsis, strife
that killed an estimated 500,000 and sent 2 million refugees
fleeing to neighboring nations. Most of those killed, including
those in Ntakirutimana's church, were Tutsis. Ntakirutimana is a
member of the dominant Hutu ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana, the former head of the Seventh-day Adventist
Church in Rwanda, is being held at the Webb County Jail in Laredo.
He has spent almost 20 months in the lockup.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a lifetime of religious service, he's met a tragedy of
biblical proportions, to his people, his ministry and himself,''
Clark said by telephone from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clark contends it would be illegal to send Ntakirutimana to
stand trial before the tribunal because it would amount to the U.S.
government honoring a treaty that was made without the approval of
the Senate or the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he would appeal to the Supreme Court, if necessary.
``It's certainly Supreme Court material,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the United Nations and the Justice Department,
which supports the extradition of the minister, could not be
reached for comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses, whose identities are being kept secret, have said
Ntakirutimana drove soldiers to the church compound in his pick-up
truck and carried a pistol.
</P>
<P>
   A witness, who survived the slaughter by hiding among the
bodies, quoted Ntakirutimana as saying: ``You are all condemned to
die. It is all over for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ntakirutimana, who has battled severe health problems, had been
living with one of his sons, who is Laredo physician.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling is the latest twist in a case that has twice
sent Ntakirutimana to the Webb County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a U.S. magistrate judge found the charges against
Ntakirutimana to be unconstitutional and ordered him freed after 15
months behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors refiled the case before Rainey, who then
ordered that Ntakirutimana be returned to jail. He has spent the
last five months behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Clark contends Ntakirutimana is being unjustly accused as a
result of ethnic hatred and a government that despised
Ntakirutimana's power as the head of the 265,000-member church.
</P>
<P>
   He faces up to life in prison, a sentence the tribunal has
already handed to two former Rwandan government officials who were
convicted of genocide.
</P>
</TEXT>
