<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9671 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-TORIES-BOS &LR;      12-02 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-TORIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORY LEADER OUSTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In the first casualty of an increasingly divisive
battle between liberals and traditionalists, Lord Cranborne was
dumped Wednesday as the Conservative Party leader in the House of
Lords after Prime Minister Tony Blair said he had a deal with
Cranborne to reform the upper house of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party leader William Hague appeared caught off
guard when Blair rose in the House of Commons and said he had cut a
deal with Lord Cranborne to steer through reform of the House of
Lords, the centerpiece of which is the abolition of the voting and
speaking rights of the so-called hereditary peers who inherit their
seats in the unelected, 1,164-member upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Conservative Party's traditional links to the
aristocracy, Tory peers account for the vast majority of the 759
hereditary peers, which gives the Tories a perpetual advantage in
the upper house, and Hague has made defending the hereditary peers
a key plank in his opposition party's platform.
</P>
<P>
   After the dramatic confrontation on the House of Commons floor
with Blair, who called Hague's opposition to Lords reform
``absurd'' given the deal struck between Cranborne and the
government, Hague called an emergency meeting with Tory peers.
Hague asked Cranborne to repudiate the deal claimed by Blair. When
Cranborne refused, Hague sacked him.
</P>
<P>
   Some parliamentarian observers said they could not recall a
similar situation in which a House of Commons leader had sacked the
party's Lords leader in a policy dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic war of words on the Commons floor between Blair and
Hague, and its apparently unprecedented aftermath, underscore how
the fate of the hereditary peers has become a battle of epic
proportions between Britain's two biggest political parties, a
defining moment in Blair's attempt to modernize British democracy
and traditionalists' desire to maintain the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's governing Labor party, which enjoys the biggest
parliamentary majority in nearly two centuries, sees the House of
Lords in general and its hereditary members in particular as relics
of Britain's aristocratic past. As part of his drive to make
Britain's democracy more similar to those in the rest of Europe,
Blair wants to drastically reform the unelected upper house and at
the very least make it more democratically accountable.
</P>
<P>
   Hague, whose party has struggled since Blair's election in May
1997 to find a cohesive opposition policy after leading the British
government for 18 years, says the government should not try to fix
something that is not broken. Hague and the Conservatives say the
Lords function perfectly well, and say Blair's claim that he wants
to democratize the upper house is a ruse to eliminate one of the
few checks on government power. They also say Blair wants to expand
his patronage patch, eliminating the hereditary peers, some of
whose titles go back to the Norman invasion, so he can appoint his
own handpicked peers.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has said he would forfeit his right to appoint so-called
life peers in exchange for reform, but the government's lack of a
precise model to replace the current upper house has led many
critics to say Blair is exploiting class divisions here to get rid
of a check on his power.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Lord Cranborne was until recently one of those who
accused Blair of megalomaniac excess in targeting the hereditary
peers for extinction. But the picture that emerged on the Commons
floor Wednesday was of someone who had accepted that, under law,
the Lords can delay a government's legislative intent for up to a
year but cannot unilaterally block it.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Cranborne's supporters describe him as a man of principle
who accepted the constitutional limits placed on the upper house,
and that he was wary of being used as a pawn in what is shaping up
as an unseemly partisan battle. They said he had agreed to a
compromise in which the government would leave 10 percent of the
hereditary peers in place until there was a consensus on how to
reform the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, however, Tory leaders denounced him as
duplicitous and disrespectful of Hague and putting the party leader
in an embarrassing position on the Commons floor.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the truth, Lord Cranborne is hardly the last casualty
in this latest battle of Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
