A9675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADIA-EXECUTION-HNS     12-02 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIA-EXECUTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE RULES TEXAS PAROLE BOARD VIOLATES LAW IN DECIDING CLEMENCY
PLEAS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ For the second time this year a district judge in
Austin has ruled that the State Board of Pardons and Parole
violates the constitution and state laws in the way it decides
clemency pleas from condemned convicts.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling Tuesday in a class-action lawsuit filed on Oct. 9 by
death row inmates, state District Judge Paul Davis said the parole
board's practice of reviewing cases in secrecy ``violates the Texas
constitution and the Texas Open Meetings Act.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the two named plaintiff's is Joseph Stanley Faulder, the
Canadian national whose pending execution has drawn protests from
the Canadian government and a plea for a stay of execution from
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Faulder was arrested
and convicted of murdering a prominent East Texas woman without
being informed of his rights to contact his government _ a
violation of the 1969 Vienna Convention on Consular Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Davis issued a temporary restraining order requiring the board
to comply with the constitution by ``keeping a record of its
actions and stating the reasons for its actions'' and to comply
with the open meetings act by ``deliberating and voting in
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hold meetings, the 18 members of the board review
inmate files individually and cast their vote by fax or telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, state District Judge Mary Pearl Williams made a
similar ruling in a suit brought by Lesley Lee Gosch, who was about
to be executed for the 1985 murder of a San Antonio woman during a
botched extortion attempt.
</P>
<P>
   She ordered that the board hold a public meeting to decide
Gosch's case, but the Court of Criminal Appeals overturned the
order because it would have delayed the execution _ a power that
Williams did not have.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Davis' order was issued Tuesday, Attorney General
Dan Morales, who has argued that the parole board is exempt from
the open meetings law, asked the appellate court to again overrule
the lower court.
</P>
<P>
   Austin attorney Kurt Sauer, who filed the class action suit on
behalf of Faulder, Andre Lewis and ``all other living persons who
are or will be on death row in Texas or who were on death row in
Texas after 1988,'' said there is a difference in the restraining
orders issued by the two judges: Davis' would not delay an
execution.
</P>
<P>
   It specifically states that ``because this court has no
authority to stay or interfere with an execution, if the (parole
board) fails to comply with this order by three o'clock p.m. on the
day of an execution, then this order shall expire as to that
individual plaintiff.''
</P>
<P>
   The order would remain in effect for other inmates seeking
clemency until a higher court vacates it.
</P>
<P>
   Parole Board Chairman Victor Rodriguez could not be reached
Wednesday for comment on the judge's order, but after the Gosch
case last spring he said that the board might reconsider its
procedures and hold public meetings to decide the clemency cases.
It continued to deliberate and vote in private, however.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer said he will file a response on Friday to the attorney
general's motion asking the Court of Criminal Appeals to overturn
Davis' order. He plans to continue attacking the argument that the
parole board is exempt from the open meetings law.
</P>
<P>
   He said legislation passed in 1993 states that the board ``does
not have to meet as a body,'' but claims that does not give it a
blanket exemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legislative history is clear,'' he said. ``The House
wanted to exempt everything (concerning the parole board) and the
Senate wouldn't go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dusek, a spokesman for the attorney general, said the
language of the statute is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are not required to meet as a body, there is no public
meeting issue,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
