<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0322 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9676 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-12-03-COX     12-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-12-03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT: SUN'S JAVA SEEKS NEW COMPUTER MONOPOLY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    575 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    EDS: 13th and 15th grafs contain language that may be offensive
to readers
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Microsoft Corp. portrayed itself Wednesday as the
victim of a monopoly plot in claiming that arch-rival Sun
Microsystems Inc. hatched plans in 1995 to seize control of both
the software and hardware that powers personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   By inserting a sheaf of previously secret Sun documents into the
landmark antitrust trial, the company claimed it was the intended
target of Sun's new Java technology. To further its own
monopolistic goals, Microsoft said, Sun seeks to displace Windows
on users' desktops and the Intel Corp. chips mated to Microsoft's
operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft lawyer Tom Burt contended that under a September 1995
business plan, Sun, in the company's words, wanted to ``turn Java
into a complete architecture and product franchise for computing''
while establishing ``a high-volume, low-margin hardware product
line based on Java and breakthrough graphics performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But James Gosling, a Sun vice president and Java's chief
creator, said, ``Taking a Java virtual machine and putting it on a
piece of silicon would be a nutty thing to do, to use a technical
term.''
</P>
<P>
   From the witness chair, Gosling largely dismissed the internal
documents and e-mails from Bill Joy, one of Sun's chief strategists
and a co-founder of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill invents 10 products a day with the names he attaches to
them,'' Gosling said.
</P>
<P>
   When Burt persisted in asserting that Microsoft was the wronged
party, allegedly fertile prey to Sun's planned ``all-encompassing
complete computing platform,'' Gosling shot back: ``You make it
sound as if we tried to take control of 100 percent of the computer
universe. We would have been happy with two orders of magnitude
below that.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, as Burt stood by helplessly, Gosling, a direct man
with shoulder-length hair that flows below a bald crown, engaged in
a seven-minute tutorial with U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson on the subtler points of the Java technology he invented in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   But Gosling conceded under cross-examination that Java may not
yet be ready for prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly tasks to which Java is not appropriate.
That's why there are multiple languages in the world,'' Sun's chief
scientist said.
</P>
<P>
   Gosling claims Microsoft has used its deep financial pockets and
its clout with software developers in a bid to scuttle
cross-platform Java.
</P>
<P>
   His views were echoed on the federal courthouse plaza by David
Boies, the government's top litigator, who said: ``This is a case
on whether consumers should have a choice between Windows and
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Gosling's testimony, Boies showed another videotape of
Microsoft chairman Bill Gates. The highlight from the August
deposition came when Boies asked Gates about a May 1997 e-mail
message in which one of his lieutenants, Ben Slivka, said, ``We're
going to be pissing on (a new version of Java) at every
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy and often comical exchange with Boies, Gates said:
``He might mean that we're going to be clear that we're not
involved with it, that we think there's a better approach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... Would it be fair for me to assume that 'pissing on' is not
some code word that means saying nice things about you, that has
the usual meaning that it would in the vernacular?'' Boies asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gates replied: ``... Believe me, it's not a term that's commonly
used. ... In this case I think it means what you've suggested.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
