<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAIN-GRANT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$25 MILLION GRANT TO ESTABLISH CENTER FOR BRAIN AND BEHAVIOR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A five-year, $25 million grant from the Houston-based
Brown Foundation will enable Baylor College of Medicine to
establish the Center for Brain and Behavior to integrate basic
research and treatment of mental illness, school officials
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brain is the answer,'' said Dr. James Patrick, vice
president and dean of research at the medical college. ``This
institute will provide special care for specific brain-related
ailments and will really be an excellent setting for clinical basic
research into the genetic basis of mental illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mental illness has been poorly served by research funding in
the past,'' said Patrick, who is also chairman of Baylor's
Department of Neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the biologic and genetic bases of mental illnesses
will contribute to the creation of better treatments, Patrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stuart Yudofsky, chairman of psychiatry, said there's an
enormous stigma associated with psychiatric disorders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stigma clouds the fact that these are highly common,
serious illnesses,'' Yudofsky said. ``When they occur, it is
devastating not only for the patient but also for their families
and the community at large.''
</P>
<P>
   The center will concentrate on four areas of study and
treatment: affective disorders, neuropsychiatric disorders of
learning and memory, psychotic disorders and addictive behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   Affective disorders include depression and major bipolar
disorders as well as associated anxiety disorders. Public health
officials estimate that one in five women and one in 10 men will
suffer from a depressive illness at one point.
</P>
<P>
   The learning and memory portion will focus on diseases of the
central nervous system that affect learning and memory of children
and adults.
</P>
<P>
   The study of psychotic disorders will focus on understanding
schizophrenia at all levels with the goal of developing better
drugs and treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In the addictive behaviors section, alcoholism and the abuse of
legal and illegal substances will be studied to determine how the
brain is changed by these mind-altering compounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just hit the point where we have the tools in science
to understand the biological bases for these conditions,'' Yudofsky
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new center will look at the biological, social,
psychological and spiritual approaches to treatment of mental
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been quoted in the past that it is very dangerous to
leave out the biologic or brain components in mental health,'' he
said. ``I call it `brainless psychiatry.' However, I don't want to
have a mindless approach to it either. It is important to be
comprehensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brown Foundation was established in 1951 by Alice Pratt
Brown, George R. Brown, Herman Brown and Margaret Root Brown.
George and Herman Brown founded Brown and Root Inc., a construction
company with holdings in oil, real estate, paper mills and mining.
All of its philanthropy has been in the state of Texas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
