A9734 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHELL-EXPANSION-HNS &LR;      12-02 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHELL-EXPANSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SPECULATE THAT OIL GIANT ROYAL DUTCH/SHELL GROUP WILL
ACQUIRE MAJOR U.S. COMPANY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL DAVIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the dust has cleared on the merger of Exxon and Mobil,
speculation has shifted to whether Royal Dutch/Shell Group will
also gobble up a major U.S. oil company,
</P>
<P>
   If the oil giant makes that move _ and there is no indication
that the company is even talking to potential merger partners _
many expect Texaco to be the likely candidate, largely because of
existing ties the two companies have in their U.S. refining and
marketing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron Corp. and Atlantic Richfield Co. are also considered
prime merger candidates, but it is Texaco that analysts say may be
pushed into the arms of Shell by the Exxon-Mobil merger and British
Petroleum's deal to buy Amoco.
</P>
<P>
   The Texaco-Shell speculation shifted into high gear earlier this
week when the two companies called off talks for an alliance in
their European refining and retail operations. Many viewed it as a
sign that a bigger deal was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to squelch the rumors, Texaco's chairman and chief
executive said Wednesday the company is shopping for acquisitions
and alliances but has no plans to rush into a merger to remain
competitive with the new breed of ``super majors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not rush into anything. I do not feel the urge to
merge,'' Peter Bijur said at the company's annual meeting with Wall
Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies have ties that keep the takeover talk alive.
</P>
<P>
   Texaco and Shell already have a joint venture of their refining
operations in the United States, a chief factor contributing to
speculation that they might merge completely.
</P>
<P>
   Shell has not given any public indication that it is looking for
a merger with Texaco or any other major oil company, said Stacy
Hutchinson, a spokeswoman for Shell Oil Co., Royal Dutch/Shell's
U.S. oil and gas exploration unit based in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Following Bijur's remarks, Texaco's stock lost 2 to close at 54
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a wider base of opportunities,'' Bijur said.
``That's why we continue to look for acquisitions,'' he said. As
for being taken over, he said, ``I never say `never' to anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts' opinions vary on the potential benefits of a
Texaco-Shell union, with some saying it would make sense while
others feel Shell already has enough problems managing all of its
assets. All, however, agree that more big deals are coming as long
as oil prices remain depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speculation is running wild because Exxon has proven that size
is going to matter,'' said Lysle Brinker, senior vice president at
John S. Herold Inc. ``And Shell has kind of floundered in the last
couple of years; they have seen their earnings decline more sharply
then other majors such as Exxon as oil prices have dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   Texaco would be a more likely candidate to pair off with Shell
than Chevron, Brinker said, because buying Chevron would give the
combined company so much of the U.S. refining and marketing market
that such a deal would probably not pass regulatory approval.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch/Shell saw its earnings drop 56 percent in the third
quarter compared to the same time last year, the result of low oil
prices and the Asian economic crisis. Exxon, by contrast, only had
a 23 percent decline in third quarter profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you could say that Shell has got its work cut out for
it rationalizing its existing asset base,'' said Adam Sieminski,
oil analyst with BT Alex. Brown in Baltimore. ``They don't need the
headache of a merger. They have had two very bad quarters and have
admitted to analysts that they have failed to deliver on their
promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe Exxon is not finished and may target another
major for acquisition after it completes its deal to buy Mobil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not sure that Exxon is done,'' said Paul Korus, oil
analyst with Petrie Parkman &AMP; Co. in Denver. ``I don't think we
should be surprised by any further consolidation that involves
Texaco, Chevron or Arco.''
</P>
<P>
   A report in the San Francisco Examiner on Wednesday quoted a
Chevron spokeswoman as saying the trend of huge mergers might not
be right for Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of speculation out there,'' said Dawn Soper with
Chevron in San Francisco, ``but the continued speculation that you
have to be bigger is not a philosophy we subscribe to.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
