</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLOGG-CUTBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLOGG ANNOUNCES JOB CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a widely expected move intended to help revive its ailing
cereal business, Kellogg Co. said Wednesday that it would dismiss
525 salaried employees from its North American operations and would
eliminate 240 of about 600 contracted positions.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg, the maker of Rice Krispies and Frosted Flakes, said it
would take a one-time charge against fourth-quarter profits of $45
million, or 11 cents a share, to pay for the job cuts, which the
company expects will reduce annual expenses by about $105 million.
Those savings would help offset increased spending on product
development and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg said most of the job cuts, which will affect 21 percent
of its salaried work force, would come from operations at its
headquarters in Battle Creek, Mich., but that about 25 percent
would come from sales division and plants elsewhere in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is centered on increasing growth in our
ready-to-eat cereal business, accelerating the expansion of our
convenience foods and continu/usly improving the cost efficiency of
our operations worldwide,'' said Arnold Langbo, chairman and chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were not impressed. Shares of Kellogg fell 93.75
cents, to $36.375.
</P>
<P>
   The market reaction, analysts and fund managers said, was a
signal to the company that management would have to take more
decisive action to improve the company's long-term prospects. ``We
consider this to be the first step in what is likely to be a long
journey to turn the company around,'' said Eric Katzman, an analyst
at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the analysts and fund managers said, management has
offered few details about how it plans to compete more effectively
as bagel makers and manufacturers of cheaper, private-label cereals
continue to erode Kellogg's sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company's revenue and profits have plummeted. Last month,
Kellogg reported a 32 percent drop in third-quarter profits, to
$141.9 million, or 35 cents a share, and warned that earnings for
the full year would be disappointing, possibly falling as much as
20 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 1908EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
