u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-TIM-PA     12-02 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-TIM-PA </SLUG>

 &HT;        TIMONEY RIPS PHILLY POLICE DEPARTMENT AT LIVABLE CITIES
CONFERENCE   By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, December 2 -- During Philadelphia Police
Commissioner John Timoney's first nine months heading up the city's
department, he encountered problems he had never seen before, he
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over the department of 7,000 officers, his first
challenge was that he could only find 6,500 of them, Timoney said
in a speech at the Heritage Foundation's Livable Cities Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney, who is credited with restructuring New York City's
police force as first deputy commissioner of the department, and
helping to lower the city's crime rate in his tenure, proceeded to
pepper his speech with jokes that ripped apart the Philadelphia
department.
</P>
<P>
   He said when he got to Philly, he found an inefficient
department organization, a lack of higher education in the upper
ranks, federal court decrees that tied officers' hands, and ``one
union'' that ``fits all.''
</P>
<P>
   But before you can turn a department around, he said, you have
to know where everyone is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sort of a game,'' Timoney said. ``Let's find the
missing officers who are on the payroll, but who are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he located the officers, some of whom were on loan to
other localities, while others were on special task forces that
were never dissolved after their stated mission expired.
</P>
<P>
   Under his watch, every task force must have an expiration date
when its mission will be reviewed, Timoney said. If an officer is
loaned to another locality, he must have a specific return date.
</P>
<P>
   He said federal court decrees keep officers from doing their
jobs, citing one that essentially required officers to read crime
witnesses Miranda rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell a witness they have the right to remain silent ...
that's insane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Philadelphia's gun-related crime rate was ``out of
control.'' Of the 410 homicides reported in 1997 in the City of
Brotherly Love, 327 were committed by handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can get a gun in this city unless you have a
criminal record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said there is a ``woeful lack of higher education'' in
the upper ranks.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of Philadelphia's officers with a rank of
captain or above have college degrees, while in cities like New
York, nearly all officers in the higher ranks are expected to have
degrees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He extended the police academy training from 25 to 32 weeks.
Also, he started a program in September with six universities that
allows police officers to continue their education.
</P>
<P>
   Timoney said he had never seen a department where ``one union
fits all.'' The same union that represents the commissioner also
serves his lower-ranked colleagues. He said it defied logic that if
the chief decided to sue him it would be through a union lawyer
paid for by both of their dues.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best methods for turning a department around is by
being honest to community members, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may not like what I have to say,'' Timoney said. ``But
by the end after I tell them what the problems are and how I plan
to fix them, I usually win them over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
