<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-COUNTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA MAKES FINAL PREPARATIONS FOR ENDEAVOUR LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ Buoyed by an improved weather forecast,
NASA made final preparations late Wednesday for a pre-dawn launch
of the shuttle Endeavour, with six astronauts and the second
component of the new international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's launch window from the Kennedy Space Center was
limited to a 10-minute period to enable the shuttle and its 25,000
pound station payload to reach the orbiting station component
launched by the Russians on Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   As night fell Wednesday, mission managers directed ground teams
to fill the shuttle's fuel tanks with explosive propellants. Rain
showers posed a small threat to the liftoff, but forecasters said
conditions had improved overall.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters closely watched cloudy conditions at the shuttle's
three emergency runways in Europe and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Loaded in the shuttle's payload bay is the station's Unity
module, a 33-foot long cylinder with a half-dozen docking ports
that will connect a future U.S. laboratory module, airlock and
power generating gear to the new outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-built Zarya module, a much larger spacecraft
designed to provide propulsion, electrical power, guidance and
ground communications, awaited the shuttle crew's arrival in an
orbit just over 240 miles high. The $240 million, U.S.-financed
Zarya was launched by the Russians from Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Endeavour crew plans to rendezvous with Zarya then, using
the shuttle's robot arm and at least three long spacewalks, join
the two components. Forty-five launches are envisioned over the
next six years to fully assemble an orbital complex that will
sprawl to the size of two football fields placed side by side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crew is ready and very excited about their upcoming
mission,'' said Frank Culbertson, NASA's director of space station
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-day flight will require Endeavour's crew to embrace a
day-for-night work regime.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour commander Bob Cabana, pilot Rick Sturckow, flight
engineer Nancy Currie, spacewalkers Jerry Ross and Jim Newman and
Russian cosmonaut Sergei Krikalev awakened Wednesday afternoon and
prepared for the early morning trip to the launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Stowed aboard the shuttle during its countdown were a pair of
Russian electronic devices and cabling that Krikalev may be asked
to install aboard Zarya. The electronic controller on one of six
power storage batteries aboard the module that discharges
electricity is not working properly.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the balky battery's charging and discharging is being
handled by ground control teams. A repair would re-automate the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is basically risk versus risk,'' said Culbertson.
``Do you want to take the risk of leaving it as is, hoping for no
further failures, or do you want to take the risk of changing it
out, making a mistake or making it worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates from many of the 16 nations involved in the massive
project assembled at Kennedy to witness the Endeavour launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new era of space exploration that will contribute to
the well being of mankind,'' said Alain Dubeau, who manages the
development of the large robotic arm the Canadian Space Agency will
contribute to the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a starting point, everyone's dream come true,'' said
Hideo Takamatsu, who leads the Japanese Space Agency's development
of a research module and other scientific equipment. ``We will face
many challenges, but I believe we will get through them.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the obstacles are differences of culture, language and
economic means.
</P>
<P>
   ``Truly, we are not testing just hardware as part of this
program,'' said Mikhail Sinelschikov, chief of the Russian Space
Agency's financially handicapped human space program. ``We are
testing our relationship very much, and our mutual trust and our
confidence in each other.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
