<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9787 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CURRENCY-HEDGING-LATI     12-02 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURRENCY-HEDGING-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE YOUR BETS
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE, with SERGIO R. BUSTOS in Miami 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Four years ago, Brazilian airline Varig was flying low.
 &HT;    The country's leading airline had been leasing aircraft using
Japanese financing since 1980. But it hadn't done anything to
protect itself from currency fluctuations. When the Brazilian
economy took a nose dive in early 1994, leading to a sinking
cruzado and runaway inflation, Varig couldn't pay the US$400
million due on 14 aircraft leases. If not for a massive
restructuring plan, the patience of its creditors (who became
shareholders) and some backup lease support from McDonnell Douglas
and General Electric, the airline would have gone under.
 &HT;    ``They could have easily insured themselves,'' says Marcelo
Martinelli, a consultant with Eurolatin, a Sao Paulo-based airline
consulting firm, ``but they didn't.''
 &HT;    It's hard for even the world's best economists to predict the
rise and fall of currencies around the world, especially in a
topsy-turvy region like Latin America. Mexico's 1994 peso
devaluation, for example, caught most economists, business
executives and citizens by surprise, creating a domino effect
across the region.
 &HT;    Now, after a couple of years of stability, Latin America's
currencies are again under attack, mostly due to the economic
fallout in Asia, political instability in Russia and nervousness in
the U.S. markets. On Sept. 2, less than one month after incoming
President Andres Pastrana assumed power, Colombia devalued its
currency, the peso, by 5 percent. Less than two weeks later,
Ecuador followed suit, allowing the sucre to fall by 10 percent,
the second time this year that the central bank devalued the
currency. Shortly thereafter, Peru started buying U.S. dollars to
protect its currency, the new sol. Many think Brazil, Venezuela and
Mexico may be next to devalue, despite assurances from their
respective leaders.
 &HT;    ``Brazil could make an adjustment to its currency by early
January,'' says Miguel A. Valdes, director of Ernst &AMP; Young LLP's
Latin American Business Center.
 &HT;    No matter what occurs, there are several actions companies can
take to protect themselves against currency fluctuations and
devaluations. Here are five:
 &HT;    HEDGING PROGRAMS: Hedging is a commonly used tool to offset
future currency fluctuations and protect the value of a company's
goods or services. The master of the hedge is Cemex, Mexico's
largest cement maker. With operations all over the world, from
South America to Spain to the Philippines, the Monterrey-based
company is extremely active in the capital markets. ``With [its]
debt so large and in so many different denominations, Cemex is the
most aggressive in terms of hedging,'' says Eduardo Cabrera, Latin
America equity strategist at U.S. investment house Merrill Lynch.
 &HT;    Argentine oil and industrial conglomerate Perez Companc has also
had some success using hedging techniques. This year the company
hedged 100 percent of its oil sales at $18 to $20 a barrel, a
pretty smart bet given soft oil prices and even softer currencies
across the region. ``That way, they can protect their cash flow in
case of a devaluation,'' says Frank McGann, Latin America oil and
gas analyst at Merrill Lynch in Buenos Aires.
 &HT;    But betting the wrong way can be very expensive. Argentine oil
giant YPF found that out a few years ago, when it wagered that oil
prices would remain at $20. They ended up shooting up to $24.72.
The bet cost the company $40 million.
 &HT;    ``We did a study on the long-term effects of hedging and found
out that half the time people were right and half the time people
were wrong,'' says Eduardo Dutrey, an investor relations manager at
YPF. ``So we decided the best hedge was to be as efficient as we
can be.''
 &HT;    Small to mid-sized companies should beware of hedging programs.
These techniques are expensive, with premiums ranging from 12
percent to 20 percent on the risk. Bill Zink, an international tax
partner at U.S.-based accounting firm Grant Thornton, recommends
hedging programs only for large, well-capitalized, multinational
companies. One of his clients, which makes machine tool parts in
Brazil, tried to join a hedging program at three different banks.
But the premiums, which were averaging in the teens, would have
killed them. ``Hedges aren't an easy answer,'' he says.
 &HT;    STICK WITH DOLLAR-BASED DEBT: After Mexico's devaluation,
companies that had peso-denominated debt got hammered, having to
pay ballooning interest rates. Those with dollar-based debt had to
generate more pesos to pay off their notes, but over the long term
they paid less because of a lower interest rate. ``Dollar debt is
so much cheaper long term and so much more reliable,'' says
Christopher Taylor, a Latin America fixed-income analyst at BT.
Alex Brown, a U.S.-based investment firm. ``If it's long-term debt,
you have a natural hedge because inflation always catches up with
devaluation. Any company that still has local-currency debt has a
foolish capital structure.''
 &HT;    For an extra level of comfort, many Latin American companies
hedge their dollar-based debt by swapping dollar contracts for
local currency contracts. That's what pan-regional bottler Panamco
and Mexican juice company Jugos del Valle did before the Mexican
peso devaluation and, as a result, their net earnings weren't as
impacted. Other Mexican beverage companies that didn't hedge, such
as Gemex, Femsa and Coca-Cola Femsa, saw their net earnings turn
into huge net losses. It took them years to catch up. Despite what
happened, Gemex and Femsa were still not hedged as of the end of
the second quarter.
 &HT;    Taking a page from Panamco's book, Brazilian brewer Brahma is
hedging its short-term, mostly dollar-based debt by swapping dollar
contracts for local currency contracts, paying the cost up front.
And Chilean bottler Andina is hedging its dollar-based notes by
investing in U.S. money-market instruments. ``While Andina has been
carrying a 200 negative-basis point spread, this has mitigated its
currency risk,'' says Laura D. Meizler, a Latin America food and
beverage analyst at New York investment firm Salomon Smith Barney.
 &HT;    RAISE PRICES: Often, the best way to prepare for a devaluation
is to simply raise prices. Panamco recently did that in Venezuela,
where it bought the soft drink operations from the Cisneros Group
and converted them from Pepsi to Coca-Cola. The only risk is that
your competitor might cut prices, stealing customers. Luckily for
Panamco, Pepsi has followed its competitor's pricing policies.
 &HT;    NEGOTIATE ALL YOUR CONTRACTS IN DOLLARS: That's not a problem
for domestic or foreign manufacturers supplying many of the larger
U.S. players in Latin America, such as the big auto makers. But
many of the larger companies in the region have become
multinational players themselves and may agree to sign deals in
something other than their local currency. ``Many U.S. companies
are afraid to ask their customers to agree to this,'' Grant
Thornton's Zink says, ``but it pays to try. They're often much more
willing to agree than you might expect.''
 &HT;    EXPORT WHEN POSSIBLE AND IN DOLLARS: For example, U.S.-based
diaper company Drypers has to buy much of its wood pulp from U.S.
suppliers for its manufacturing operations in Mexico. To counteract
its dollar-based raw materials costs with its peso-based sales,
Drypers is exporting as much excess production as possible to
Andean countries such as Venezuela, which have been willing to pay
in dollars. ``It's a natural hedge and it's cost free,'' says Wally
Klemp, chairman of Drypers.
 &HT;    Unfortunately, the company hasn't been able to do the same in
Brazil, where demand is brisk and supplies are tight. ``It's not
always possible,'' Klemp says. ``But where we can, we try to get as
much receivables as payables in dollars.''
 &HT;    One thing Drypers does do: The company estimates the next year's
currency devaluation and accrues the difference over the year.
``The real risk is if there's more of a devaluation than world
economists think,'' Klemp says.
 &HT;    If you're a foreign company considering setting up operations in
the region, Grant Thornton's Zink recommends you either link up or
sign a licensing agreement with a local company. That way, you can
give them the capital and/or technology they need and they will
take on all the currency risk. ``In Brazil, the ones that are
getting clobbered are not partnering,'' he says.
 &HT;    Companies already operating in Latin America should consider
scaling back. One of Zink's clients, a manufacturer of industrial
parts, recently pulled its Brazilian operations and is now
licensing its process to a local company. Contract manufacturing in
dollars would have been another way to go.
 &HT;    In Varig's case, the Brazilian airline could have avoided its
problems four years ago with the use of such financial tools as
overnight accounts, whose rates are adjusted daily to hedge against
inflation. It could also have developed a faster revenue-collection
system. Or it could have avoided the problem entirely by not
leasing the planes in a currency from a country located halfway
around the world.
 &HT;    The airline has learned its lesson. It just signed a new leasing
agreement for 39 jets, none of which were financed in yen. ``We
don't do that anymore,'' Varig spokesman Marcelo Lima says. ``That
was in the past.'' In these uncertain times, that was probably a
smart move.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
