<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 3. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   ESPY-ACQUIT (Washington) _ After only two days of deliberation,
a federal jury acquits Mike Espy, the former agriculture secretary,
of all charges, ending an independent prosecutor's four-year effort
to prove he was corrupt in accepting sports tickets and other
favors from companies he was supposed to regulate. By Neil A.
Lewis. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-REVIEW (Washington) _ The decision by the
International Monetary Fund and the United States Treasury last
year to push Asian nations to send their interest rates soaring was
a crucial blunder that worsened the world financial crisis, the
World Bank concluds in its first history of how the trouble
started. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.) With graphic. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead: 3-column photo reefer to WARM-WEATHER story, inside.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   ADMIRAL-CHARGED (Washington) _ A one-star Navy admiral accepts a
finding of guilt on charges that he improperly steered military
contracts to his mistress and agreed to early retirement at a
substantially reduced pension and penalties, Navy officials say. By
Frank Bruni. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA-ARREST (Washington) _ U.S. and allied forces in Bosnia
arrest a Bosnian Serb general recently charged with genocide by the
Yugoslav war crimes tribunal in a secret indictment. By Steven
Erlanger. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ Developments surrounding the House
Judiciary Committee's impeachment inquiry on President Clinton. In
a series of conference calls, House Republicans overwhelmingly tell
their leadership that they want the impeachment issue brought to a
quick vote in the House this month, and they want the House
Judiciary Committee to end its impeachment investigation into
President Clinton this year. By Alison Mitchell and Lizette
Alvarez. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   reefer: EXXON-TEXACO (Undated) _ With Exxon and Mobil deciding
to join hands, the pressure on other major oil companies to find a
partner intensified Wednesday _ something that was acknowledged by
Peter Bijur, the chairman and chief executive of Texaco Inc. By
Agis Salpukas. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIAN-ART-AUCTION (New York) _ The twice-a-year sale of
American Indian art at Sotheby's didn't go as planned. Nineteen of
the objects, including six that a number of Indian tribes had asked
to be withdrawn from the auction block, were withdrawn by the
auction house or the consignors for legal reasons. Three other
objects _ a Plains ceremonial club, a Yurok ceremonial dance apron
and a 16th or 17th century Aleut wood mask _ that Indians had also
asked to be withdrawn from the sale were bought by three determined
individuals who wanted to see the items returned to the Indians.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-SEATTLE (Everett, Wash.) _ For all the talk of Microsoft
exercising global dominance from the empire's capital here, most
residents know that the big engine for jobs remains Boeing Co., so
when it announced it was cutting 20 percent of its worldwide
workforce over the next two years, with many of those 48,000 cuts
in jobs targeted for the Seattle area, the news hit like a chill
winter wind. By Sam Howe Verhovek. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m.
ET in ``a'' news file.) With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLLARD (Washington) _ More details emerge about the
debate withing the Clinton administration over Israel's presssure
on the United States to grant amnesty to the spy Jonathan Pollard.
By James Risen. (We plan to move the story at 9 p.m. in the ``i''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ARMS (Cartagena, Colombia) _ Sixteen months ago, the
Clinton administration lifted a de facto ban on sales of the most
advanced American weapons to countries in Latin America, but there
are few signs that any country in South or Central America will be
able to purchase the sorts of sophisticated weapons covered by the
ruling anytime soon. By Steven Lee Myers. (The story has moved in
``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CELL-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In unusually emphatic and
optimistic terms, scientists tell a Senate hearing that research
with human embryonic cells is likely to yield important medical
benefits and should be supported by the federal government. By
Nicholas Wade. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
