<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-MISSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE CREW EMBARKS ON DANGEROUS, MOMENTOUS MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The space shuttle Endeavour is poised for a liftoff before dawn
Thursday morning on a mission expected to be among the most
difficult and complex since shuttles began flying in 1981 _ and a
mission that is to usher in a whole new era for humans in space.
</P>
<P>
   If the mission goes as planned, the first two sections of the
planned $60 billion International Space Station will be placed in
orbit and joined, and briefly occupied by astronauts connecting
their power and data cables. It will be the beginning of the
assembly of by far the largest structure ever built in space, and
the first one to involve so much international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   When completed _ in 2004, under the current schedule _ the space
station will extend over an area almost as large as three football
fields, and its laboratory and living modules will have as much
room as two Boeing 747 jumbojets. That's a big leap from the Apollo
days of the late '60s, when astronauts worked in a capsule about
the size of a Volkswagen beetle.
</P>
<P>
   Already postponed for a year because of Russia's delays in
completing its key modules, the planned 3:56 a.m. launch may be
delayed again for a more typical reason: bad weather expected at
Cape Canaveral and at emergency landing sites in Spain and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force meteorologist Ed Priselac said there was only a 40
percent chance the weather would cooperate for the predawn launch;
the odds are equally bad for Friday morning. That means getting the
shuttle off the ground ``is going to be a crapshoot'' either day,
Priselac said. There is a 60 percent chance of acceptable weather
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   And because this mission requires a pinpoint rendezvous in orbit
with a Russian station module called Zarya (sunrise), launched two
weeks ago, the launch window is an unusually brief 10 minutes. But
because of the unusual orbit required, the shuttle should be
visible from most of the East Coast as it climbs into orbit powered
by three hydrogen-burning main engines. Its brighter-burning solid
rocket boosters, which only last for about two minutes, will have
been jettisoned before it comes into view here.
</P>
<P>
   Once in orbit, the shuttle will spend three days chasing the
Zarya module in a delicately choreographed series of moves,
eventually closing to within just 600 feet. Then, astronaut Nancy
Currie will use the shuttle's robot arm to lift a US-made
connecting module called Unity out of the shuttle's cargo bay and
connect it to an airlock attached to the crew cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Then, shuttle commander Robert Cabana will begin a slow, careful
maneuver to line up the 18-foot-long, 15-foot-diameter Unity module
with Zarya, nudging it slowly close enough for the two crafts'
docking rings to connect.
</P>
<P>
   When this difficult space ballet is completed, the combined
space station modules will be 63 feet long and carry an array of
solar panels 78 feet across. Then, astronauts Jerry Ross and James
Newman will make three 6-hour spacewalks in the following days to
finish connecting and testing the combined pieces _ the ``first
element'' of the International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   It will take 45 flights by the US space shuttle and Russian
rockets to put together all 100 components of the station. But in
just over a year, in January 2000, it will be able to support a
crew of astronauts. Three astronauts will be sent up that month on
a Russian Soyuz module to begin a five-month stay in the station.
They will return by shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The whole assembly process will involve more spacewalks in orbit
than have been carried out so far by all US and Russian astronauts
since the dawn of the human space program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This flight will clearly demonstrate the unique capabilities
of the space shuttle and of astronauts and cosmonauts to assemble
large structures in space,'' said George Abbey, director of the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration's Johnson Space
Center.
</P>
<P>
   And with 16 nations involved in building and operating parts of
the space station _ including all 11 members of the European Space
Agency, as well as Russia, Japan, and Canada _ this will be by far
the largest international collaboration ever attempted in space. It
will be a very different era after decades of intense international
competition.
</P>
<P>
   As NASA administrator Daniel Goldin put it, the station will
usher in ``a multinational permanent human presence in space. In
doing so, we will truly open up the space frontier, replete with
its tremendous challenge for the human spirit and its promise of
intellectual and material riches. The ISS will be a world community
living and working together in space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
