<HEADLINE>
GORE ATTACKS GOV. BUSH OVER CONSERVATIVE STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore moved closer to presidential
campaign mode Wednesday with a centrist call for ``practical
idealism'' and a pre-emptive attack on the man who might be his
Republican rival, Texas Governor George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning Bush by name, Gore, addressing members of the
Democratic Leadership Council, ridiculed the Texan's recent
declaration that he can adhere to a ``conservative philosophy and
implement policies that are compassionate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some now say that we need a `compassionate conservatism.' I
wonder where they got that from?'' Gore said in a mocking tone.
``Let us be clear. We welcome all who truly want to join us in this
vital center. But there is a difference between using the rhetoric
of the center, and actually governing from the center.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the governor was surprised at
Gore's remarks. ``He said what? Where?'' Bush said, according to
Hughes. She called Gore's statement ``rather odd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It must indicate that the vice president is nervous or is at
least thinking a lot about an election that is two years away,''
Hughes said in a phone interview. ``It is unusual for the vice
president to clearly engage in an attack against a very popular
governor of Texas who has not even decided whether he will make a
national race.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech before the Council, a moderate force within the
party, was described by aides as an effort to underscore that he is
in the political mainstream as he prepares to run for president in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he attempted to portray his possible chief
rival as only a pretender to moderation. It was an effort that
echoed the way then-Governor Bill Clinton, with Gore as his running
mate, ran against Bush's father, President George Bush, in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's event before the leadership council, which had the
earmarks of a cattle call for possible Democratic presidential
candidates, underscored that the party's hopes for retaining
control of the White House may be in the hands of the moderates.
Three other Democratic prospects who appeared Wednesday _ Senator
John F. Kerry, Senator Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt _ tailored their speeches to the center.
Kerry reiterated his call for education reform, Kerrey proposed
revamping Social Security, and Gephardt declared that Democrats
represent ``practicality and pragmatism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's history with the DLC goes back a dozen years, and his
status as front-runner made him the star attraction, even though he
was vague about how he would implement ``practical idealism.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech filled with empathy for suburban angst and
references to pop culture, Gore bemoaned a ``Beavis and Butthead
world'' where children are assaulted over the airwaves with
violence. He also cited the plight of two-income families with
little time for their children, and mourned an American landscape
blighted by sprawl and shopping malls. Gore did not, however, offer
any new initiatives to solve such problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's attack on Bush included a mocking comparison of a
compassionate conservative to a character from a ``Saturday Night
Live'' skit named Theodoric of York. ``After indulging in the most
grotesque and primitive practices in medicine or law, applying
leeches to heal the sick, or dunking witches in vats of oil,
Theodoric would pause for a sudden blinding insight, and question
whether we need a new, enlightened approach ... and after musing
poetically about the possibilities of the future, he'd admit,
Naaah!''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who helped create the Democratic Leadership Council a
dozen years ago and won election with President Clinton by running
on its centrist philosophy, Wednesday sought to redefine the DLC's
vision of a ``third way'' in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president defined his practical idealism slogan with
the following statement: ``By strengthening the bond between
progressive goals and responsible government, by leading boldly
from this new and dynamic center, we can strengthen the bonds
between us all, and we can affirm our proudest potential: jobs and
opportunity, safe streets and strong communities, and a clean
environment; equal opportunity and fundamental fairness, global
strength and security.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
