<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-GIFTBOOKS-1     12-02 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-GIFTBOOKS-1700(2ndTake)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 
FROM MARK McGWIRE TO MARC CHAGALL, THE YEAR'S BEST COFFEE-TABLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: all quite exciting &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JEFF GUINN'S TOP TEN (listed alphabetically by title)
</P>
<P>
   ``Celebrating 70: Mark McGwire's Historic Season'' by Bernie
Miklasz, Ron Smith, Mike Eisenbath and Dave Kindred (Sporting News,
$29.95). If anyone wonders whether baseball is back, just count the
oversized books on the sport that cram stores shelves this holiday
season. The best is this team effort by staffers at The Sporting
News, which captures the excitement of the 1998 season and a sense
of the player who dominated the diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Country Life: A Handbook for Realists and Dreamers,'' by Paul
Heiney (DK Publishing, $24.95). Believe it or not, here is a
coffee-table book that teaches readers how to milk cows and shear
sheep. Even if you have no plans to go out and live off the land,
you'll have lots of fun learning how to build a proper manure pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Icons of the 20th Century: 200 Men and Women Who Have Made a
Difference,'' by Barbara Cady (Overlook, $75). This is a truly
stunning collection of essays about the great leaders, thinkers and
performers of modern times. Photo editor Jean-Jacques Naudet
provides equally impressive art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leading the West: One Hundred Contemporary Painters and
Sculptors,'' by Donald J. Hagerty (Northland, $60). The American
West has been described as ``the landscape of the American
psyche.'' It is impossible not to be drawn to at least some of the
art and sculpture reproduced here, and Hagerty's accompanying notes
are highly informative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music From the Heart: The Fifty-Year Chronicle of His Life in
Music,'' by Rod Kennedy (Eakin Press, $39.95). Although he is
best-known as producer of the legendary Kerrville Folk Festival,
Rod Kennedy's career mirrors the history of Texas music since the
1960s. This is fun to read and a primer on the music industry, and
it represents a significant achievement on the part of Austin-based
Eakin Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt: A New Vision in Animation,'' by Charles
Solomon (Abrams, $45). Film animation has come a long way since the
primitive contortions of ``Steamboat Willie.'' DreamWorks SGK has
spared no expense creating ``The Prince of Egypt,'' its touted
holiday '98 release, and this eponymously titled book lets us in on
all the secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rolling Stones: A Life on the Road,'' by Jools Holland and
Dora Loewenstein (Penguin Studio, $50). In a coffee-table book
publishing cycle when it is obviously ``in'' to chronicle rock
stars and bands (Phish, Springsteen, the Grateful Dead), this
insider's view of the Stones on the road proves to be the best.
There are lots of reasonably insightful interviews with Keith,
Mick, Charlie and Ronnie. Ex-bassist Bill Wyman gets a chance to
reminisce. Too bad Brian Jones can't add his tuppence worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superman: The Complete History,'' by Les Daniels (Chronicle
Books, $29.95). Some oversized books are meant to be informative,
others to awe readers with sheer gorgeousness. A special few, like
this one, are meant to be both, plus fun to read. Daniels shares a
wealth of knowledge; devotees of the Man of Steel have to have this
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testament: At the Creation of the State of Israel,'' by Aaron
Levin (Artisan, $35). The photographs are all in black and white,
but none is somber. Each depicts an older Israeli and complements
his or her recollections of the founding of Israel after World War
II. These first-person accounts are staggeringly honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Warhol Look,'' edited by Mark Francis and Margery King
(Bullfinch Press, $75. Depending on your opinion, Andy Warhol was
either a modern-art pioneer or an overhyped hack. Either way, this
eclectic package of photos, essays, reproduced newspaper articles
and other assorted bits and pieces pretty well captures the man's
quirky work and interests. .MDBU/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
