<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-GIFTBOOKS-1700(2 </SLUG>
 Takes)-TEX 
From Mark McGwire to Marc Chagall, the year's best coffee-table
books 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL AND JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From ``Dressing Diana'' to ``Ultimate Beer,'' from ``Texas Sky''
to ``Tuscany Interiors,'' the season yields coffee-table books
about everything but the kitchen sink. Of course, maybe that will
come next year.
</P>
<P>
   In midyear they trickled in, and with autumn they became a
landslide: a few hundred gift books to bewilder us once more. No
way to cover them all, so Star-Telegram book editors have
endeavored to identify their favorites from the lavish inventory.
</P>
<P>
   LARRY SWINDELL'S TOP TEN
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Heritage History of the United States,'' by
Douglas Brinkley (Viking, $50). This is not a textbook; instead, it
is what textbooks eternally should be. It's a spirited narrative
account of the birth, life and ascent of our nation. The work is
not overpowered by the visual quotient, although paintings,
drawings and photographs are abundant, and all well-chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chagall,'' by Jacob Baal-Teshuva (Taschen, $50). The season
offers fancy-volume salutes to individual artists famous and less
so. This sumptuous tribute to Marc Chagall eclipses the field for
three primary reasons: the stature of the artist; the value of the
substantial critical text; and the fidelity of color reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder: The Photography of James L. Stanfield,''
(National Geographic, $40). Here the color photography is
captivating not in a spectacular way, but for the human drama it
consistently defines. Stanfield's camera has been all over the
world. Extended captions and random text inserts decode the skill
and imagination of Stanfield's 30-year picture-taking odyssey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Illustrated Longitude,'' by Dava Sobel and William J.H.
Andrews (Walker, $32.95). Sobel's ``Longitude'' was critically
acclaimed three years ago. This republication in oversized format
is richly illustrated under Andrews' supervision. It's for science
buffs, being the ``true story of a lone genius (John Harrison) who
solved the greatest scientific problem of his time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One Digital Day: How the Microchip Is Changing Our World,''
created by Rick Smolan and Jennifer Erwitt, and designed by Tom
Walker (Times Books/Random House, $40). From the creators of the
popular ``Day in the Life'' series of books in coffee-table format,
here's an exploration of the microchip's omnipresence. ``In one
generation, microchips have changed the world so profoundly that
daily life without them has become unimaginable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Painted Sketch: American Impressions From Nature,
1830-1880,'' by Eleanor Jones Harvey (Dallas Museum of Art/Abrams,
$49.50). Some art books are merely to look at. This one's
educational, a fascinating crash course in the tradition of
American landscape painting. The pioneering heroes of this serene
volume are Thomas Cole, Albert Bierstadt, Frederic Church and
Sanford Robinson Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   The Simon &AMP; Schuster Encyclopedia of Animals, Dr. Philip
Whitfield, general consultant ($50). It's what it says it is: ``A
visual who's who of the world's creatures.'' It may not be as much
fun as a trip to the zoo, but it's more informative, and here
you'll find more animals than any zoo could accommodate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sports Art of Bart Forbes,'' (Beckett, $39.95). The
enterprising, Dallas-based specialist in commemorative sports books
has outdone itself with this assembly of oils and watercolors by
one of the sports world's premier artists. Forbes doesn't miss,
whether it's baseball, football, basketball, boxing, tennis, auto
racing, or outdoor sports; but the impression given here is that
golf is the activity closest to the artist's heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Opera,'' by Richard Somerset-Ward (Abrams,
$49.50). For anyone who cares about opera, this is the gift book of
the year. People who don't go for grand opera may change their tune
if they absorb this book, which is to be read. It's a vivid history
of the hybrid theatrical form that is opera, from the very
beginning to now. Sample chapter headings: ``From Gluck to
Mozart''; ``The Golden Age of Italian Opera''; ``German Romantic
Opera''; ``Popular Musical Theater''; and ``On the Twentieth
Century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tributes: Celebrating 50 Years of New York City Ballet,''
conceived and edited by Christopher Ramsey (Morrow, $50). There's
enough to see and enough to read, although the preface by Peter
Martins and foreword by Mikhail Baryshnikov are superfluous. A
potpourri of essays on different aspects of the art adds up not to
a book about ballet, but a book about a ballet company, and it's
all quite exciting. MORE &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
