<HEADLINE>
JOHN HANCOCK SIGNS DEAL TO SELL ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co. signed a $7.5
million deal Wednesday to market through websites on Microsoft's
MSN online service, joining a growing number of companies signing
big Internet advertising contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Microsoft will help construct interactive
banner advertisements that will appear for two years at sites
including MSNBC, MSN HomeAdvisor, MSN MoneyCentral and the online
magazine Slate.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is one of many hammered out this year by Internet
services like America Online and Microsoft, which has recently put
together agreements with financial institutions like First USA and
Unilever, the consumer products giant that makes everything from
Lipton tea to Calvin Klein perfumes, industry observers said. But
Hancock is the first insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one deal in many that is making a trend,'' said Jill
Frankle, an analyst at Framingham-based International Data Corp.
``This one is set apart because it's insurance. But what it's
telling us is that a much broader spectrum of companies are seeing
the Internet as a place to advertise.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads will have electronic links that hook up consumers with
Hancock's homepage and allow them to fill out applications and
purchase insurance on-line, said Kathy Graveline, a Hancock senior
vice president in charge of Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   Internet insurance sales are expected to soar in coming years.
Dozens of companies now offer products online. And Forrester
Research in Cambridge says it expects sales over the Internet to
approach $155 million this year and to climb to $4 billion within
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's Graveline said since the company developed its
homepage two years ago, on-line sale of life insurance has jumped
to almost 20 percent of the company's total life insurance sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surprised everyone,'' she said. ``We want to be the
player on the Internet. We want to be there when those sales
figures get big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
