<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD DIPS INTO ENDOWMENT, UPS FUNDING 20 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard University, responding to an embarrassment of
riches in its investments and fund-raising, Wednesday announced
that it will tap its endowment for an extra $95 million beginning
next year to reduce class sizes, expand financial aid, hire more
professors, and make other educational improvements.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 percent increase will bring the endowment's payment into
Harvard's annual operating budget _ which currently stands at $1.7
billion _ to $500 million starting in fiscal 2000. Officials said
the contribution would subsequently grow by 4 percent to 5 percent
a year, and by more if investments continue to soar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very major move,'' Neil Rudenstine, Harvard's
president, said in a telephone interview last night. ``It's rare
that you have the chance to undergird so many parts of the
institution that need the help. . . . Historically, I don't
remember when it happened last, it's that unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's action has significant implications, both for its own
future and for other top-tier educational institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In an academic world in which national competition for students
and faculty is rapidly intensifying, the additional money
presumably will help Harvard maintain or even expand its prestige
and appeal. At the same time, Harvard's decision to dip more deeply
into its endowment seems certain to induce other schools to follow
suit _ especially since they also have enjoyed investment returns
hovering around 20 percent during the stock market boom of the last
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including some major donors, have urged many American
colleges and universities to channel more of their windfalls to
offset tuition increases and other rising costs. Harvard has
received the most attention, however, because its endowment of
nearly $13 billion far exceeds that of any other institution of
higher education in the world.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston Globe series earlier this year raised questions about
whether Harvard was growing more concerned about accumulating funds
than spending them. It reported that the university, while reaping
huge returns on its investments and exceeding goals in a $2.1
billion fund-raising campaign, spent less than 4 percent of its
endowment for educational purposes at a time when tuition costs
were rising, junior faculties salaries were lagging, and many
students sought more financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials acknowledged Wednesday that they were aware of
the criticism surrounding their endowment, and had been prodded by
some contributors, as they considered whether to move more money
into the operating budget. But they insisted they had not acted in
response to any pressure; rather, they said they had waited until
they felt certain about the stability of their financial gains,
then started discussions last summer on how large a shift to
execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was clearly an awareness . . . that people perceive us
as being extremely fortunate,'' said Elizabeth C. Huidekoper, the
university's vice president for finance. ``We already knew we were
fortunate, though, and we felt an obligation to use our good
fortune wisely to invest in high-priority progams.''
</P>
<P>
   While they would not acknowledge it for the record, the Harvard
officials clearly knew months ago that some big infusion of funds
would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   In September, they announced the most sweeping restructuring of
the school's undergraduate financial-aid program in three decades.
The 20 percent overall boost in assistance included an additional
$2,000 per student annually beginning this year, along with an
easing of work requirements.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no one discussed exactly where the money would come
from to pay for the ambitious program, which Harvard touted as an
attempt to ease the burden of its $31,132 yearly pricetag.
Wednesday, though, the source of the funding became clear: the
extra endowment contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Several administrators said specific decisions had not yet been
made on where else the $95 million will go, but they agreed that
much of the money will be channeled to areas that don't tend to
receive targeted donations. They said, for example, that graduate
and professional-school students are likely to get more financial
aid and that attempts will be made to hold down tuition rises _
which have been criticized in recent years because they exceeded
the rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine said a significant chunk of the money will be used
for capital investment, particularly in the sciences and new
technologies. Those fields increasingly require larger expenditures
for buying and updating equipment, since the state of the art
advances so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to stay strong in science, you know now that you
have to spend the money,'' said Rudenstine. ``It's very
competitive; it's just a fact of life. . . . You simply need the
systems that allow people to do the kind of work they expect to do
at a place like Harvard.''
</P>
<P>
   Other officials, noting this same competitive climate, said the
university plans to recruit new faculty in several areas with its
additional funding, including some to expand its offerings in the
sciences and new technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The breadth of Harvard's plans for the endowment money
illustrates just how ambitious it plans to be _ and how much money
is involved. The university also intends to help pay for extensive
new computer systems for research and teaching; for the
preservation of voluminous library materials; for promoting more
cross-disciplinary study; and for cutting the size of some classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinarily welcome step that will allow some
very significant improvements in education,'' said Jeremy Knowles,
the dean of the faculty of arts and sciences. He estimated that his
school's annual budget of $550 million would now grow by $20
million to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   His smile almost audible over the telephone, Knowles added:
``You are talking to a very happy dean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
