<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-BOS &LR;      12-02 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL CHALLENGES ARAFAT ON INDEPENDENT STATE CLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government said Wednesday that it would
cede no more West Bank land until Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
reversed his often stated intention to declare the creation of an
independent Palestinian state next May.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimatum by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu casts an
ominous cloud over the rekindled peace process and the pending
visit by President Clinton on Dec. 14 to Gaza, seat of Arafat's
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The United States reacted quickly Wednesday, rejecting the new
conditions. Officials in Washington said envoy Dennis Ross would
head to the region this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe it is appropriate to add new conditions to
the implementation of this agreement,'' State Department spokesman
James Rubin said, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
   This latest war of words climaxed a long day of violence and
bloodshed that left an Israeli soldier injured and a Palestinian
civilian dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis, under a new interim peace agreement hammered out
in October at the Wye River Plantation in Maryland, are to withdraw
from an additional 5 percent of the West Bank in mid-December and
turn the land over to Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Israel agreed in the accord to hand over another 13 percent of
the West Bank in three stages. It has already carried out the first
stage.
</P>
<P>
   This next step forward in the peace process was to coincide with
Clinton's visit, which a White House spokesman vowed Wednesday will
take place as planned despite the new tension created by the
Israeli demand.
</P>
<P>
   The statement from the Netanyahu government said, ``Israel will
carry out the next stage of the withdrawal only if . . . the
Palestinian Authority explicitly announces the abandonment of its
intention to unilaterally declare a Palestinian state.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement listed two other conditions: Palestinian agreement
to Israel's terms for the release of Palestinian political
prisoners from Israeli jails, and punitive measures against
Palestinians who took part in Wednesday's violence.
</P>
<P>
   The new Israeli ultimatum set the two sides on a collision
course in which Arafat would have to abandon a deeply emotional
promise to his people to declare the creation of an independent
state on May 4, 1999, or face the possibility of a new deadlock in
the much-delayed peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, both sides charged that the other had violated the
Wye Memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Palestinian peace negotiator Saeb Erekat called the
ultimatum a ``grave threat to the process'' and a ``complete
violation of the Wye agreement signed at the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not carry out the release of political prisoners.
They have continued expansion of settlements. And now they have set
a new condition,'' Erekat added. ``Why should we believe that they
are honoring this agreement? This is a total violation.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu senior advisor David Bar-Illan responded by asking,
``What are we giving them land for if they are going to scuttle the
process by unilaterally declaring a state?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinians have violated the Wye agreement by inciting
the violence we saw this afternoon and the constant pronoucnements
that they would declare an independent state,'' Bar-Illan added.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis last night watched chilling television images of a
group of Palestinian student demonstrators surrounding an Israeli
car in the West Bank town of Ramallah and brutally beating an
Israeli civilian and a soldier in the car.
</P>
<P>
   With TV cameras running, the Palestinians dragged the soldier
out of the car, pummelled him with rocks and stole his weapon
before he fled for his life toward an Israeli checkpoint. The
student protesters had gathered to demand that Israel live up to an
agreement to release Palestinian political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   But the morning began with Palestinian blood being shed.
</P>
<P>
   A 41-year-old Palestinian father of six was stabbed to death by
what police believe was an Israeli ``ultra-nationalist'' intent on
avenging the killings of Jews by Palestinians in Jerusalem.
Jerusalem Police commander Yair Yitzhaki said detectives were
investigating to determine if the murder was linked to the
stabbings late last year of six other Palestinians, one of which
was fatal, in Mea Sharim, the heart of the Jewish ultra-Orthodox
community in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral of the man, Osama Natshe, took place Wednesday in
the usually peaceful Arab-Jewish Jerusalem neighborhood of Abu Tor
where he lived and died. It touched off more violence as
Palestinian youths threw rocks and clashed with Israeli troops in
nearby East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israel did carry out the release of some 150 Palestinian
prisoners last month, but Palestinian leaders say half of them were
common criminals and not the political prisoners they had expected
to be released.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Bar-Illan last night said the Israeli ultimatum was a
reaction to the beating of the Israeli soldier by the Palestinian
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see that? Did you watch those images? This is a mob
instigated by the Palestinian Authority.'' Palestinian Legislative
Council Chairman ``Abu Allah called on them to use `their stones,
their bodies' to attack settlers. What do you expect?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the ultimatum) is not just an emotional reaction to a near
lynching. It is the anger created when you know that this was
instigated and encouraged by the Palestinian government,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   David Makovsky, the diplomatic correspondent for the leading
Israeli newspaper, Ha'aretz, said, ``This is a dramatic
development. There have been fits and starts before. But this is
the first time the linkage is directly to a delcaration that Arafat
not declare a state on May 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Makovsky, who follows the peace process, said Arafat may have
brought this new crisis upon himself by repeatedly declaring his
intention to declare a state on May 4, a date which marks the end
of the five-year period set for Israelis and Palestinians to reach
a final agreement as outlined in the historic 1993 Oslo accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``These statements (by Arafat) were a miscalculation, and in a
way Arafat has played right into Netanyahu's hands. . . . It will
cast a shadow over the presidents visit if what was to be a
celebration of peace turns into a breakdown in the process,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
