<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EUROPE-ARMS-MAKERS-AR     12-02 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ARMS-MAKERS-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE MOVES TO CREATE SINGLE ARMS AND AVIATION COMPANY
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic depicting military exports from Britain, France
and Germany is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Even as global pressures drive Europe to a
tighter single market and a new single currency, similar pressures
are forcing a consolidation of the weapons and aviation industries.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders recognize that with the fall of Communism,
their military needs are radically different. And the emergence of
U.S. giants like Boeing, Raytheon and Lockheed Martin creates a new
competitive landscape. So these leaders envision the arms and
aircraft industries from each nation uniting in a single, highly
efficient, all-purpose conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Progress toward this goal has been glacial, but it is still
creating tremendous strains, especially in France. Aerospatiale,
France's aerospace and arms group, is about to be transformed from
a state-owned company to a private one for the sole purpose of
qualifying to join this Continent-wide behemoth, but Yves Michot,
its chairman and chief executive, is not entirely happy with how
the process is unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to merge together, we need to have each other's
full confidence,'' he said. But Michot has not found that comfort
level. Like many in France, he objected to the way foreign business
leaders, notably those at British Aerospace and DaimlerChrysler
Aerospace, a unit of the German industrial giant DaimlerChrysler,
had threatened to snub the French if they did not cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Europe pulls off the creation of the conglomerate,
tentatively known as the European Aerospace and Defense Co., some
experts, fearing a monopoly that would stifle competition, wonder
whether they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not like a world in which you have three large United
States integrated contractors _ Boeing, Raytheon and Lockheed _ and
one in Europe,'' said John Deutsch, a former U.S. Undersecretary of
Defense. A single European military contractor, he argued, would
``essentially not be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from fighting off antitrust regulators, though, Europe's
military industries are actually getting encouragement from their
governments. Competition is assured, the companies argue, given the
huge American presence in the European arms and aviation market.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies have always done a booming military business in
Europe. During the Cold War, many European countries, particularly
smaller nations like the Netherlands and Belgium, almost
exclusively bought U.S. fighter aircraft and weapons systems.
European industry leaders, including the French, deny they want
anything like a Fortress Europe now.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. arms companies, of course, went through a similar, though
less extreme, consolidation. European executives like to talk about
the ``Last Supper,'' a 1993 gathering at which Les Aspin, then U.S.
defense secretary, sketched out for industry leaders the Pentagon's
view of the future, one in which a few military contractors would
divide a greatly curtailed Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in Europe, the process has been reversed, with executives at
British Aerospace and DaimlerChrysler pushing their agenda on often
reluctant governments.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere has that reluctance been more evident than in France.
The prospect of marring the prestige of a French national industry,
not to mention losing jobs, is creating a fierce conflict that pits
French traditions against the harsh realities of a globalizing
world.
</P>
<P>
   But the process has most definitely begun. In November, Dassault
Aviation Group announced that it would transfer the government's
stake, 46 percent, to Aerospatiale. The plan involving Dassault, a
maker of Mirage and Rafale military jets and Falcon business jets,
was announced in July, but it took months to secure the approval of
Serge Dassault, the company's feisty 73-year-old chief executive
and controlling shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   This follows a decision in July by the government of Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, after months of debate, to push the
government's stake in Aerospatiale below 50 percent and bring in
the big weapons and publishing group Lagardere as the leading
private shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   By this week, after separate consultation with the German and
British governments about recasting the military industry, Paris
appeared to have dropped its fundamental insistence on a
simultaneous three-way merger, clearing the path for a gradual
two-by-two process, including some form of union between British
Aerospace and DaimlerChrysler, to be followed by a link with
Aerospatiale and Lagardere's Matra military business.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale has excellent products and advanced technology, but
past government largess produced a company rich in technology but
inefficient and unaccustomed to the notion of shareholder value.
``Ten years ago, the government told Aerospatiale not to make
profits but to make products,'' said Philippe Gossard, of Credit
Lyonnais Securities in Paris. And the numbers show that
productivity has indeed sagged. Last year, each of Aerospatiale's
37,000 employees generated $297,000 of revenues, against $326,000
for British Aerospace's 46,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   For France's partners at British Aerospace and DaimlerChrysler,
both owned by shareholders, getting government out of the business
is an essential first step.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our demand is that future shareholders be of the same sort and
share the same goals,'' said Wolfgang Piller, a strategy chief at
DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard Evans, chairman of British Aerospace, agrees. The
group should feature a highly fragmented shareholder base, he said
recently, adding that for the Germans and the British, there should
be zero government ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders are also urging European governments to end
centuries of fragmentation and form common military and security
policies, including weapons procurement. ``Combine your purchasing
power,'' Piller said, ``and you will have all the influence
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Michot readily acknowledges that the changes at Aerospatiale
must go forward. ``It's not a problem of whether big is beautiful
or small is beautiful,'' he said in an interview, ``but projects
are more and more sophisticated, and bigger and bigger companies
are needed.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What he acknowledges less readily is that Aerospatiale needs
reorganizing. It is, after all, no slouch. It has a 37.9 percent
stake in Airbus Industrie, the efficient, profitable consortium
that, despite bitter competition from Boeing, grabbed half the
worldwide orders this year for commercial jets. The Ariane rocket
program, a joint European undertaking in which Aerospatiale is
primary contractor, controls 50 percent of the market for satellite
launchings, a business expected to be worth $60 billion over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some activities, like missiles, lose money, while others,
like a stake in ATR, a maker of turboprop aircraft, face an
uncertain future. And Ariane itself may prove to be a white
elephant, as smaller and cheaper satellite launching devices enter
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts even question whether Michot, 57, an aeronautical
engineer with decades of experience as a government adviser on
weapons programs, is the man to do the reorganizing. Indeed, part
of the reason for bringing in Lagardere was to tap the group's
thick-skinned managers, like Philippe Camus, its 50-year-old chief
executive. The challenges facing the merger appear not to have
escaped Lagardere's investors, about 40 percent of whom are
American and British investment funds: After the July announcement,
the shares lost nearly half their value, though they have since
recovered much of that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the French willingness to accept private solutions by
bringing in Lagardere and Dassault shows their flexibility. And
Michot says it can go further. Jospin's government, he said, which
originally insisted on a permanent government minority stake in
Aerospatiale, and hence in the new European arms company, is now
pragmatic. ``If I go back with a good idea, the consequence of
which is a new decrease in the government stake,'' he said, ``they
are ready to examine it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such French pragmatism, experts say, illustrates how even rigid
political positions are gradually yielding to the realities of
international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, discussion of a common European security policy is
reviving, and the process is expected to be accelerated when the
euro, the European single-currency, begins in January. Finance
ministers from the 11 countries that will adopt the euro now meet
regularly to formulate common economic policies, and this month the
15 military ministers of the European Union began similar meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have common grounds for our prosperity,'' said Holger H.
Mey, director of the Institute for Strategic Analyses in Bonn,
``then shouldn't we have a common security policy?''
</P>
<P>
   But if that is the long-term goal, what drives the current
change is the onslaught of the U.S. giants _ Boeing, Raytheon and
Lockheed Martin. In 1987, the United States had 22 percent of the
$85 billion world arms market; by this year, the market had shrunk
to $40 billion, but the U.S. share had climbed to 55 percent,
though in dollar terms it had risen only from $19 billion, to $22
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, governments in France, Britain and Germany
endorsed the idea for a unified company; the plan has since been
supported by Spain, Italy and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some experts caution that seeking to merge the industries of
three or even six countries at once will be almost impossible. Nor
has the global economic slowdown made the task easier. This week,
Boeing said the downturn in Asia would force it to trim production
of commercial jets beginning next year and to cut as many as 20,000
more jobs the next two years than it had earlier indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking recently to British industrialists, Sir Richard of
British Aerospace checked off just some of the thornier choices
facing such a company, including where production sites should be
and where to put groupwide units, like finance and central
management.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as industries are merged, jobs will disappear.
Deciding who remains will be particularly difficult, since Europe's
unemployment rate remains at least double that of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where there are two partners, it is difficult, but just
achievable,'' said John Dowdy, of McKinsey &AMP; Co.'s military
industry group in London. He described the American industry
consolidation, with its two-by-two mergers, as the ``Noah's Ark
formation.'' But ``when you add three or four or more, it becomes
exponentially more difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Weston, British Aerospace's chief executive, said the
Pentagon's decision earlier this year to block Lockheed Martin's
bid for Northrop Grumman might have signaled the start of an
American search for trans-Atlantic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Michot agreed, adding that Europe must be prepared for such
alliances. Europe's goal, he said, is not to circle the wagons but
``to create conditions in which we are on a level field with the
United States.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
