<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-PALMPILOT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PalmPilot to feature Internet access
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The faddishly popular PalmPilot will soon come with
Internet access, a wireless feature that will be carried over
BellSouth's burgeoning network.
</P>
<P>
   The makers of the PalmPilot, 3Com Corp., announced Wednesday
that the Net-friendly version of the handheld organizer, available
early next year, will have the ability to ``clip'' data from
various Net sites while the user is on the move _ as long as the
right kind of BellSouth transmission tower is in range.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot, which came to 3Com with its purchase of U.S.
Robotics, now apparently holds the majority share of the market for
handheld computing but that dominance is being challenged by
technology from Microsoft. The souped-up PalmPilot is meant to
exploit both the passion for mobile organizers and the trend toward
wireless communications.
</P>
<P>
   Signals from the PalmPilot to the Net and back will be
transmitted through base stations installed by BellSouth throughout
the country. Neither company would disclose details of the
arrangement, except to say 3Com will pay for the use of the
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will bill their customers and we will bill them,'' said
William Lenahan, president of BellSouth Wireless Data.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth already has coverage in the southeast and has the
equipment in 16 other metropolitan areas, with plans for many more,
he said. ``It is very ambitious, but this particular poject is only
one piece of why we are building this out.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is still rooted in the southeast where it reaps about
$15 billion in revenue from a near-monopoly in local phone service.
However, of late, the $22 billion-a-year company has been branching
out. BellSouth has poured money into Latin America _ mostly to
build wireless phone systems _ while also investing in wireless
phone companies in Houston and Los Angeles. BellSouth recently
launched a national two-way paging service.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot will work over the same network used for
interactive paging, a system designed for data, not voice, Lenahan
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new PalmPilots will be sold by 3Com. BellSouth has talked
about marketing the devices. ``There's no reason why it shouldn't
happen,'' Lenahan said.
</P>
<P>
   Joining in the 3Com announcement were a number of companies
whose technology will mesh with the PalmPilot, including
Atlanta-based UPS, which promised customers the power to check on
the status of deliveries via the device.
</P>
<P>
   The company now permits users to track packages on the Internet.
Dale Hayes, UPS vice president, said it will be the first time such
data will be available to customers through a wireless device.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
