<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Editions double up to make forecasts
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If it's December, it must be forecast time for the
nation's business press.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune, in a special year-end double edition, looks at the
future from the viewpoint of investors, asking why they are so
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, the great bull market of the 1990s has
entered a new phase. Suddenly we find ourselves in a world where we
are as concerned about deflation as inflation. Where Internet
stocks flash (and sometimes flame out) ... and each morning we fret
over the latest bulletins from Indonesia and Brazil,'' Fortune
says. ``It's all rather humbling, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Humbling, maybe, but the magazine offers a package of articles
on how to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Worth (December/January), also in a double edition, is just as
somber about the outlook, declaring ``the game has changed. The
world is again a scary place. Genuine risk has returned to
investing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We would probably be better off today if the Federal Reserve
Chairman (Alan Greenspan) had forestalled some of the speculative
excess as the Dow (Jones industrial average) topped 9,300 this
summer. ... Dow 10,000 now seems no more likely to come next than
Dow 7,000 (or below),'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Money offers its year-end advice in a special financial guide in
addition to its regular magazine. In it, the personal finance
publication advises readers to take care of 1998 details before
moving on to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine lists 25 ``moves to make now'' that will lower
taxes and save money, and eight ``use it or lose it'' benefits that
expire at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Money assembled a panel of six analysts who agree
growth will be slower in 1999 but disagree widely about everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   Take that, chauvinist
</P>
<P>
   Business Week cover story on chief executive officer vacancies,
illustrated by an empty pair of men's wing-tip shoes, was too much
for the editors of Working Woman.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to use a pair of men's shoes instead of an empty
desk or chair conveyed the idea that only men are qualified for
such positions, said Bernadette Grey, editor-in-chief of Working
Woman.
</P>
<P>
   In its December/January issue, Working Woman illustrates its
profile of 30 senior women executives with a cover photo of an
empty pair of ladies' business shoes.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a good-natured jab at the folks at Business Week,''
says Grey.
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Worth mentioning ...
</P>
<P>
   _ Business Week (Dec. 7) says the combination of America Online,
Sun Microsystems and Netscape Communications could become ``the
crossroads of online business in the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ticker (December) says mutual funds that invest in
European-based stocks ``are seeing strong growth.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta-based Business to Business (December/January) profiles
Theragenics' chief executive officer, Christine Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
