<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's appeal slipping among foreign real estate investing
group
 &HT;    By Sallye Salter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metro Atlanta's real estate market took another hit
Wednesday when a survey of foreign investors showed the city, which
was top-ranked in the mid-1990s, has declined to fifth among U.S.
cities in investment potential.
</P>
<P>
   The gap was wide between top-ranked Washington, D.C., which
scored 44, and Atlanta, which scored 4, in the annual poll by the
Washington-based Association of Foreign Investors in Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the group's 145 members, mostly Europeans,
responded to the survey asking them to rank the top five U.S.
cities for foreign investment potential.
</P>
<P>
   New York scored second-highest; San Francisco, third; and
Boston, fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta, which was fourth a year ago, was ranked No. 1 in
the survey in 1994, 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The poll results were the latest in a string of reports over the
past year that reflect investors' concerns about the area's excess
construction, as well as constraints on growth caused by
infrastructure problems.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the foreign investors' plans for investment in
U.S. real estate in general are more cautious than a year ago.
Forty-two percent of the respondents said they would increase their
U.S. investment in the year ahead, down from 67 percent in last
year's survey.
</P>
<P>
   While domestic turmoil among both real estate investment trusts
and capital markets has created opportunities for these investors,
``the optimism of foreign investors has been tempered by continuing
concerns about a global recession,'' said David Golden, chairman of
the investors' association.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
