<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russell to move key operations to Cobb County, Ga.
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Russell Corp., maker of sportswear and Major League
Baseball uniforms, has picked Cobb County's booming
Cumberland-Galleria district over several sites in north Fulton for
the relocation of several key divisions from its headquarters in
Alexander City, Ala. Russell said Atlanta will be its
``co-headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, the nation's largest athletic clothing manufacturer
with $1.23 billion in revenue, announced in July it would establish
co-headquarters in Atlanta. The company will transfer 100 to 150
high-level corporate employees, including division presidents and
the chief financial officer. Russell Chairman and Chief Executive
Jack Ward will have offices in both Alexander City and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Initial plans call for the construction of a 250,000-square-foot
building on Cumberland Boulevard west of South Cobb Parkway.
Russell said it plans to execute a formal lease and joint venture
agreement on the building by Jan. 15. The property, which is under
contract by Pope and Land Enterprises, will go before the Cobb
County Board of Commissioners Dec. 15 for rezoning.
</P>
<P>
   The company will soon sign a letter of intent on the site,
according to a recent letter from Ward to broker and developer Pope
&AMP; Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Cumberland) was selected from an extensive list of
alternatives, primarily located in north Fulton County,'' Ward's
letter said. The letter said the commitment was contingent on
rezoning. Ward could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Russell hopes to move into its new headquarters by mid-2000,
said Russell spokeswoman Nancy Young. Construction will take 12 to
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the meantime, we're looking for temporary sites to begin
moving employees early next year,'' Young said. One potential
temporary site includes the nearby Atlanta Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   The relocation is part of a major restructuring by Russell,
which is in the midst of cutting more than 20 percent of its work
force and moving most of its sewing operations to Mexico and
Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The new Atlanta headquarters is part of the company's increased
focus on marketing and advertising its brands, which include
Russell Athletic team uniforms, Jerzees sweatshirts and sweatpants
and Cross Creek golf wear. Young said the move from Alexander City,
a rural community of 15,000 about 50 miles northwest of Montgomery,
will make it easier to recruit top-notch marketing talent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
