<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS expands in its 'last frontier,' Latin America
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service is moving to enlarge its Latin
America toehold by buying a small shipping company in Argentina, a
key market.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandy Springs, Ga.-based delivery company said it is
acquiring the assets of Union Pak S.A. for an undisclosed price and
will use them to establish its own operations under the banner UPS
de Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has used Union Pak as a contractor to test the Argentine
market.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina becomes the third South American nation, along with
Brazil and Chile, in which UPS has operations. It uses contractors
to serve other countries but remains well behind rivals DHL
Worldwide and Federal Express in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Scherck, president of Marietta, Ga.-based consulting firm
Colography Group, said the buyout alone will not significantly
boost UPS' position in South America.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``It may very well be the first signs of an
emerging strategy similar to what what UPS did in Europe.'' UPS in
the late 1980s began buying local firms in Europe, absorbing huge
losses before seeing profits in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Heraclio Rojas, UPS' Latin American marketing manager, said the
company now has only a ``single digit'' market share of
international air shipments in Argentina but believes it can
quickly add to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plans are to attain a 25 percent market share on exports
and imports,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows a recent UPS deal to use air rights held by
cargo carrier Challenge Air to fly between the United States and
Brazil five times a week. Contract carriers will feed cargo from
Argentina and other nations to the UPS flights.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas said Union Pak has 62 employees and UPS expects to add
more. He called South America UPS' ``last frontier'' and said the
company is not discouraged by a cooling Latin economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as an opportunity because customers will be looking
for alternatives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS has had a Latin America and Caribbean regional headquarters
near Miami since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
