<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cable, broadcast industries find much in common
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When a cable TV operator bashes broadcasters
today, it's not unlike hitting a brother on the head.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and broadcasting have become that entwined. Nowhere was
that more evident than at the opening of the cable industry trade
convention called the Western Show, being held here Wednesday
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Seated side-by-side on stage were Bob Wright, NBC chief
executive, and Leo J. Hindery Jr., president of giant cable
operator Tele-Communications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Wright and Hindery weren't exactly making kissy-face. But they
did agree more than disagree as part of a panel on the future of
the cable TV industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for us is not just getting bigger,'' said Wright,
whose company owns cable channels MSNBC and CNBC. ``The issue is
are we in businesses that are getting bigger because opportunity is
growing quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Hindery, whose company is being bought by AT&AMP;T, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years from now 50 percent of our revenue will come from
new businesses,'' he added, referring to the fact cable lines are
increasingly being used to deliver telephone service and high-speed
access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Wright and Hindery discussed the industry in front of several
thousand cable industry executives. Other panelists were Barry
Diller, chairman of USA Networks and the force behind an attempt to
create a hybrid cable-broadcast network, and Gordon Crawford, the
industry's leading investor.
</P>
<P>
   All saw tremendous opportunity as operators continue to lay
digital wires, capable of delivering everything from
high-definition television to telephone service to CD-quality music
to Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   But all saw great danger, too. Crawford, for one, scolded the
audience for not taking digital satellite operators such as DirecTV
more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Satellite will add 2.5 million new subscribers this year,
while cable will add only 1 million,'' said Crawford, who runs Los
Angeles-based investment fund Capital Research and Management Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means satellite will capture 60 percent of the growth in
new subscribers.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford urged operators to speed introduction of new digital
services to stay competitive, but Hindery said that was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one should underestimate the difficulty of delivering these
new services,'' said Hindery.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2025EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
