<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARE03-COX     12-02 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CARE changes with times
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Fifty years ago, the new international relief
organization called CARE delivered boxes of food and supplies to
Europeans struggling to recover from the ravages of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   And many Europeans were profoundly grateful.
</P>
<P>
   But CARE officials know they could never get away today with
doing what they did then. Those boxes _ the original CARE packages
_ would be completely unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   They contained peanut butter, which was alien to the native
population. They contained candy, which is not nutritious. And they
contained cigarettes, which damage health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is in a different place today,'' said Peter Bell,
CARE's president. ``Today, I think the world expects more.''
</P>
<P>
   The growing realization that aid can sometimes do as much harm
as good _ that it can foster dependence and even fuel wars _ has
prompted relief organizations like CARE, which since 1993 has been
headquartered in Atlanta, to change the way they deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   CARE, Bell said, pays greater attention now to the cultural and
economic context in which its aid is delivered. And, in some areas
torn by war, CARE has not only delivered food but lobbied for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics say that is not enough. They contend that the whole
idea of aid is wrong, that what is needed is investment rather than
charity, and that aid too often harms the people it is intended to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the current system needs to be dismantled,'' said
Michael Maren, an author and former aid worker whose book, ``The
Road to Hell,'' offers sharp criticism of international aid
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But Bell said the delivery of aid needs to be improved, not
scrapped. When people are dying, he said, the only ethical choice
is to save lives.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, humanitarian aid seems easy to understand and to
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   When Hurricane Mitch leaves people in Honduras and Nicaragua
with no food, shelter or clean water, those necessities must be
provided. When people in Sudan are starving, they need food. When
people flee mass murder in Rwanda, they need a safe haven, a place
to stay, something to eat.
</P>
<P>
   Few people dispute those basic assertions.
</P>
<P>
   But even aid officials agree, however, that delivering aid,
however badly it is needed, can also cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   Sheltering and feeding people in Central America can foster
dependence. Airlifting food into Sudan can draw people off their
land and help sustain that country's 15-year civil war.
</P>
<P>
   And running camps for refugees from Rwanda, in addition to
saving lives, probably provided a safe haven to genocidal killers.
</P>
<P>
   Mary B. Anderson, of the Local Capacities for Peace Project in
Cambridge, Mass., has studied the challenges of delivering aid.
Though she believes assistance can be rendered effectively, she
suggests that aid workers, like physicians, should take the
Hippocratic oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding that the best-intentioned humanitarian or
development assistance can inadvertently also do harm,'' she wrote
in 1996, ``they should also declare that they will `First do no
harm.'''
</P>
<P>
   CARE delivers aid in a much different way today than it did 10
years ago, Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   As it engages in a major effort to help people in Nicaragua and
Honduras, two countries devastated in October by Hurricane Mitch,
CARE is trying to meet victims's immediate needs without fostering
long-term dependency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as little as five years ago, we would talk about a
relief-to-recovery-to-development continuum,'' Bell said. ``And we
have become acutely aware that this is not so much a continuum, and
that we need to be thinking about all of these elements _ relief,
recovery and development _ all the time that we are working with
people in extreme poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking only about victims' immediate needs, critical as they
are, could foster not only dependency but despondency, he said.
Over time, gratitude could become mixed with resentment.
</P>
<P>
   So, while sheltering and feeding people, CARE is working
simultaneously on development programs _ planning to have people
work in exchange for food, perhaps cleaning their communities, and
ordering seeds and tools to distribute so people can again become
self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said it will be six to nine months before any semblance of
normalcy returns to Nicaragua and Honduras, but the planning must
begin now.
</P>
<P>
   ``CARE's whole reason for being is to help people help
themselves,'' he said. ``And it's important for the self-respect
and the well-being of the people with whom we're working that they
be able to, insofar as possible, support themselves, to earn a
living on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Honduras is a one-time emergency from which a
recovery can envisioned. But Sudan, where a civil war has been
fought for 15 years, poses more difficult challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Maren, the author who is critical of international aid agencies,
said that some portion of the food aid is siphoned off by the rival
armies; that food, he said, has helped fuel this long-running
conflict, with disastrous consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible that this war would not still be going on if it
had not been for all this aid going in over the years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he noted the damage to the society of southern Sudanese
people caused by feeding stations _ damage acknowledged by many aid
workers in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The famine camp is a logistical necessity for aid groups, but
it is a cultural disaster,'' Maren said. ``You have an entire
generation of kids who have grown up in the camps. They don't have
the survival skills that their parents have. You have a breakdown
of traditional authority. The kids who grow up in these camps are
great fodder for the rebel armies.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE does not dismiss that analysis out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly trying to sort through issues just like
those,'' Bell said. ``And we are responding differently today than
the way we might have responded 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, other issues demand consideration, too, he said, such as
all the people who will die if no food is provided.
</P>
<P>
   This summer CARE set up feeding stations in the southern
Sudanese city of Wau. Tens of thousands of people walked five days
or even 10 to reach the food. Hundreds probably died along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was our choice?'' Bell asked. ``Food was the difference
between life and death. And we responded by feeding those people.
Ethically, there was absolutely no choice.''
</P>
<P>
   But recognizing that the war had greatly exacerbated the famine,
CARE abandoned its traditional apolitical stance and ``felt it
important to crank up a full advocacy strategy with regard to
Sudan,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   CARE lobbied both sides to extend a cease-fire that was set to
expire this fall. And CARE took the lead role in organizing four of
the world's largest relief agencies _ CARE, Oxfam, Medecins Sans
Frontieres (Doctors Without Borders) and Save the Children Fund _
to jointly urge the U.N. Security Council to take an active role in
ending the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The genocide in Rwanda posed its own excruciating ethical
dilemmas. In 1994, about 500,000 Rwandans were killed in ethnic
fighting. More than a million people fled the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   But refugee camps set up just outside Rwanda's borders offered a
safe haven not only to desperate women and children, but to people
who had organized, and who continued to perpetrate, massive ethnic
murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember myself visiting the camps at Ngara in Tanzania,''
Bell said, ``and staying up much of the night talking with CARE
staff _ you know, should we remain, should we go? Under what
circumstances should we remain? And in the end they felt strongly
that we had to remain because of all the innocent children, that we
just couldn't turn our backs on them.''
</P>
<P>
   CARE tried to discriminate, insisting, for example, on
distributing food only to women rather than to men who might use it
for paramilitary purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But CARE did not control the camps, it had no security forces,
and in the end the choice was either to stay or to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not clear-cut choices,'' Bell said. ``Maybe the world
has become more complex. But certainly we have become more
sensitive to the broader context in which we are working.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
