<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9878 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOTTO-DUKES03-COX     12-02 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOTTO-DUKES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery winner breaks losing streak
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ Kenny Dukes, whose lengthy criminal record
surfaced after he picked up $10.65 million in lottery winnings this
week, said he felt so ashamed of stealing from his mother three
years ago that he decided to turn his life around or kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''While I was sitting in jail, I felt so low, all I wanted to do
was end my life. All I wanted was to see my parents one more time
and let them know I was sorry,'' Dukes, 40, said in an interview
here Wednesday at his attorneys' office.
</P>
<P>
   After his 1995 arrest for burglarizing a Brunswick business and
homes, including his mother's, he planned to ''do a plunge'' off of
a second-tier balcony onto the concrete floor at the Glynn County
jail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Dukes said, a dream convinced him he could become
''someone my parents could be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything has changed since I'm not drinking and drugging
anymore,'' Dukes said. ''That Kenny Dukes is not the person sitting
here before you today.''
</P>
<P>
   Released from prison to a Savannah halfway house in 1996, Dukes
was hired by a Savannah architectural concrete company, quickly
working his way up from an hourly wage position to plant
superintendent. He swore off alcohol and drugs, he said. A former
acolyte in the Lutheran church, he became a regular churchgoer,
Dukes said.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, he bought a small cottage on the marsh near
Midway and redeveloped a good relationship with his parents. He
also began planning a construction business with his brother, Eric,
in Brunswick. That's still his plan; though a new multimillionaire,
he is required to work while he remains on parole until 2001. He
must also meet a curfew and pass periodic drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Topetzes, state director of parole, said he hopes Dukes
will succeed in turning around his life, but the agency will treat
Dukes the same as any other parolee. ``If he violates parole, he's
going to be the wealthiest inmate in the Georgia prison system,''
said Topetzes.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes said he felt successful and good about himself, even
before he learned he'd won the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The Sept. 19 jackpot of $31 million was the largest in its
history. Dukes waited about two and a half months to claim his
prize, opting for an after-tax cash payout that amounted to about a
third of the total jackpot that would have been paid over a 30-year
period. Asked why he made that choice, he said, ''I'm not ignorant.
I knew I could do a lot more with it in 30 years than (lottery)
officials could.''
</P>
<P>
   He withheld the big news from most his family until Thanksgiving
dinner. After he announced his good fortune, his 16-year-old niece
asked if this meant she could afford to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Dukes blamed alcohol and drug abuse for a lengthy list of
felonies he committed in Georgia and at least three other states.
</P>
<P>
   According to state records, Dukes, who sometimes had used the
alias David Lee McKenzie, was in Georgia prisons three times and in
a South Carolina prison once since the late 1970s. Records show he
had been charged with a variety of felonies, including aggravated
assault, theft, robbery, drunken driving, fraud, domestic violence,
simple battery, tresspassing and obstruction of a police officer.
At age 18, he said, he was dishonorably discharged from the Navy _
which he joined at 17 _ for using alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''At age 14, I discovered drugs, rock and roll and women,''
Dukes said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has not touched alcohol or marijuana since being
arrested in 1995 for stealing jewelry worth $1,400 from his
mother's trailer and $80 in change from her truck. He also broke
into a Brunswick doughnut shop and house owned by Gary and Jeannine
Share, who had befriended Dukes and his former wife, Sherri.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Share, who now owns a music store, said Dukes wrote to him,
apologizing, while he was in jail and has called since getting out
to ask if they could meet face-to-face.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he called, I told him I didn't really want to have
anything to do with him,'' Share said. ''I felt the friendship had
been violated. But afterwards, I felt I'd spoken too hastily.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Share said, he would hesitate to meet with Dukes, ''because
it would seem I was meeting with him because he's suddenly rich,''
he said. ''I'm not interested in that.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not, however, rule out the possibility of seeing Dukes
''without anybody knowing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Share, most coastal residents seemed willing to forgive and
forget.
</P>
<P>
   In Darien, where Dukes bought his winning lottery ticket, folks
sat around the popular ''family table'' at Archie's Restaurant,
discussing the big winner and his checkered past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the premise of the lottery, I'm not sure it makes sense
to deny a winner because he's a felon,'' said Fred Stregles, the
restaurant's new owner. ''Besides, if I had a winning ticket and I
was a felon, you better believe I could get someone to go pick up
my money for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Darien resident Earl Duncan, who owns storage units in town,
joked about McIntosh County's shady history as a landing place for
shrimpboats loaded with bales of marijuana. At the moment,
residents are fuming over an audit that showed about $100,000
missing from the tax commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dukes seems like he'd fit right in here,'' Duncan said.
</P>
<P>
   George Wallace, a commercial crabber from Cox, said, ''Are you
sure he's not from McIntosh County?
</P>
<P>
   Even the retired clerk of superior court, Adam ''Junior''
Poppell, was inclined to be forgiving of Dukes' past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe if he's been in that much trouble, maybe he needed (the
winnings) worse than anybody else,'' Poppell said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
