<HEADLINE>
AFTER ACQUITTAL, ESPY CRITICIZES INDEPENDENT COUNSEL
</HEADLINE>
  (With ESPY-ACQUIT)  
(sw) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After four years of harrowing investigation and two
months of sitting mute through his trial, Mike Espy broke his
silence on Wednesday, alternating bursts of exultation at his
acquittal with condemnation of the independent counsel's failed
$17-million dragnet effort to put him in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each and every day I read the 27th Psalm,'' said Espy, the
former secretary of agriculture, beaming gratefully outside the
courthouse in having prevailed against corruption charges. ``And it
basically says that the Lord is my light and my salvation. Whom
shall I fear? Certainly not Donald Smaltz.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz, the independent counsel, was among the special
prosecutors who have been conducting seven separate investigations
of Clinton administration officials over the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cost a lot,'' said Espy, eying nearby his brother, Henry,
who was indicted then acquitted in the independent counsel's
multiple prosecutions, but too late for last election day when he
lost his job as mayor of Clarksdale, Miss. ``It's been tough,''
said Mike Espy.
</P>
<P>
   At his side, one of his lawyers, Ted Wells, celebrated the
verdict as a double victory _ for Espy personally and for critics
who feel the hefty investigatory and budget powers of the
independent counsel law must be reined in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, the United States Congress will look at this
victory and decide to change the independent counsel statute and
put both Donald Smaltz and Kenneth Starr out of business,'' said
Wells, referring to the best known independent counsel, Starr, who
has recommended the impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With public opinion remaining strong behind the president in his
own investigatory travails, the fairness of the independent counsel
law itself has come under increasing doubt as it faces renewal by
Congress next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision is probably another nail in the coffin for the
independent counsel statute, which was in a lot of trouble to begin
with,'' said Irv Nathan, a former Justice Department prosecutor who
has studied the law on behalf of the American Bar Association. ``It
will be perceived as another example of excessive exuberance by an
independent counsel and of poor judgment,'' he said of the Espy
prosecution, stressing that the public's perception of fairness is
crucial if the independent counsel statute is to be workable.
</P>
<P>
   Espy described how he returned home to Yazoo City, Miss., for
sustenance over the past four years. ``The people there took me
in,'' he said, ``They knew that none of this was true.''
</P>
<P>
   Hometown friends helped him raise legal defense funds at
$25-a-bowl soup pot rallies. ``This is good news for Yazoo City,''
said Joseph Thomas, vice president of Guaranty National Bank, who
thought the president may owe Espy an apology for jettisoning him
so quickly. ``They pounced on him pretty hard,'' Thomas said, but
Espy kept the faith with his supporters back home, whom he
previously served in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Espy, ``They didn't believe the cynicism and the
levels of acrimony thrown at you, such as have been thrown here in
Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   In his joy, Espy sparked laughter as he described how his own
troubles provided an almost total distraction from the president's
troubles. ``You may not believe it, but I barely know who Monica
Lewinsky is,'' he said, smiling. ``So I really have not paid much
attention to it, and I just wish him well.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the indepedent counsel law have argued that it lacks
safeguards against politically biased and zealous prosecutors
ranging across the land in a veritable ``parade of horribles,'' to
use the phrase of Walter Dellinger, a former Justice Department
official in the Clinton administration who opposes renewal of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the cure is even worse than the disease,'' said
Dellinger. ``The law may lead to a kind of all-or-nothing strategy
once $17 million has been spent,'' he said. The high stakes leave
no leeway, he said, for the sort of plea bargaining to misdemeanor
counts as might happen in standard criminal procedures for some of
the activities that independent counsels delve into.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his ordeal had soured him on public service, Espy
cryptically told of how, as he was forced from the administration,
he met ``man to man, person to person'' with President Clinton to
profess his absolute innocence. ``He looked me in the eye and we
talked and he made a promise to me,'' said Espy, declining to spell
it out. ``I'm hopeful that he'll keep that promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy described the ordeal of withstanding a full-scale
independent counsel investigation as a test of physical as much as
spiritual courage. ``He's not unlike any other schoolyard bully,''
he said of Smaltz. ``You've got to stand up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the independent counsel's charges, Espy stood
outside the court and looked back 11 years to the Reagan
administration and the independent counsel prosecution of Labor
Secretary Raymond Donovan. Donovan was acquitted of fraud charges
after a lengthy, costly struggle. Donovan's parting comment, still
widely remembered by politicians here, was, ``Where do I go to get
back my reputation?''
</P>
<P>
   As he prepared to leave the court a free man, Espy commented,
``I won't repeat that because I don't believe that I ever lost my
good name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
