<HEADLINE>
PALMEIRO DESERVES THE CREDIT FOR ENGINEERING THIS REUNION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
I was beginning to wonder. Was it us? Was the drawl too slow, was
it our thing about chicken-frying a steak, were there too many
pickups barreling down our roads, was it the crispy-fried summer
heat?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The word got out that Randy Johnson's wife didn't care to move
here. And Todd Stottlemyre's wife didn't care to stay here.
Personally, I didn't care enough to ask why.
</P>
<P>
   Both free-agent pitchers ended up in Arizona, which if nothing
else blows the summer heat theory.
</P>
<P>
   But while unloved by others, at least Rafael Palmeiro has given
back our dignity. And while not exactly giving the Rangers what
they need _ a rotation ace _ the surprising return of Rafael gives
the Rangers what they claim they want in a high-dollar star player
_ loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Go far beyond the numbers, financial and on the field. This took
a major reconstruction for Palmeiro to return, and Rafael did most
of the work himself.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the bridge he crossed leaving town wasn't merely
burned. The damage went far beyond that. This bridge was nuked.
With Arlington in his rearview mirror, all that remained of
Palmeiro's ties with the Rangers was a pile of rubble that glowed.
</P>
<P>
   Ugliness prevailed. At his most angry moment, Rafael accused the
Rangers of an anti-Latin player bias, which was silly, and he knew
it. But as Palmeiro, in his bitterness, constantly lashed out at
Tom Schieffer and that era of Rangers' ownership, one thing became
clear.
</P>
<P>
   The departure from Arlington devastated Palmeiro. The more he
squawked, the more we knew he hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Blame Schieffer, blame Rafael, blame Rafael's agent for what
happened. But as much, if not more, than any player who has passed
through here, Palmeiro came to represent the Rangers' stated goal
of suiting up good citizens who want to play here, stay here and
produce on the field here.
</P>
<P>
   For five long seasons, Palmeiro fulfilled the good-citizen and
staying-here requirements _ his permanent home remained in
Colleyville. Unfortunately, the playing and producing huge numbers
were done in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly but surely, however, the bridge back to Arlington began
to take shape. Palmeiro never gave up on the idea of coming home,
and constantly hinted at such in conversations with news media
members during his Baltimore days.
</P>
<P>
   But for that bridge to actually rise again _ and certainly
Schieffer had to turn the other cheek for it to happen _ don't rule
out a re-welcome mat here for Kevin Brown, Jimmy Johnson, Jason
Kidd, Yvonne Gonzalez, Pat Sullivan, etc. Palmeiro's return tells
us that anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Melvin inadvertently had the most telling comment about
Rafael's return. Talking about the private meeting Tuesday that
Palmeiro requested, the general manager said, ``I heard a
\Rfinancial\S number from Rafael that I hadn't heard from his
agent.'' That number would work for Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Follow along here:
</P>
<P>
   What Rafael told Pudge, Kenny told Rafael. What Rafael told
Kenny, Rafael didn't tell himself five years ago, and Kenny also
ignored two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Believe me, all of the above makes perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers pitcher Kenny Rogers, in a conversation with
Palmeiro on Tuesday morning, had advised him, ``If you want to make
it possible in Texas, you can make it possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, with the Rangers and Pudge Rodriguez at a
negotiating impasse, Palmeiro had called from Baltimore with the
same advice for Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Without his agent, Pudge asked Schieffer for a face-to-face
meeting. The deal was done. The same thing happened Tuesday for
Palmeiro, sans agent.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, again while in Baltimore, had given Rogers that advice
when the pitcher was about to leave the Rangers via free agency.
But Rogers never followed through, and departed. Palmeiro had
learned through experience. When he left five years ago, it was in
a swirl of confusion about whether his agent had overplayed the
hand. But the main deal-breaker was that Palmeiro did not become
personally involved in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Every player needs an agent _ absolutely. But at some point, if
that player wants to ``make it happen'' with a certain team, he has
to take charge. Most, however, don't.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro did this time, and he's better off in Arlington because
he obviously loves the place. The Rangers are better off with
Palmeiro because of what he means in the batting order and
defensively at first base.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made an all-out effort to improve their pitching by
signing Johnson. When Johnson's wife balked, at least the team
improved somewhere else, while the search for pitching goes on.
</P>
<P>
   One bridge, so to speak, was crossed. A bridge that Palmeiro
personally rebuilt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
