<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RUGBY-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA GAINS IN COURT BATTLE OVER RUGBY INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Awarding a round to President
Nelson Mandela in his battle with South Africa's former rugby
hierarchy, the country's highest court unanimously agreed Wednesday
to hear his appeal of a lower court ruling against him.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, the court, which was created by the 1994
constitution, demonstrated again that it does not intend to sit
back while lower courts dominated by apartheid-era judges take up
important issues. Instead, the court, called the Constitutional
Court, seems to be pursuing potential landmark cases to rule on
them quickly.
</P>
<P>
   In April, a Pretoria judge ruled that Mandela had acted
unconstitutionally in appointing a commission to look into charges
that the administration of rugby was corrupt and nepotistic.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, Judge William de Villiers ordered Mandela to
take the witness stand, where he was cross-examined for two days
about whether he had ``applied his mind'' before appointing the
Browde Commission of Inquiry, or whether he had simply
rubber-stamped a recommendation of his minister of sport.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a South African president had been called
to testify in court. The case raises constitutional issues about a
judge's powers to compel presidential testimony, and about how
deeply the courts can inquire into decision-making in the executive
branch.
</P>
<P>
   After ordering that the inquiry commission not meet, de Villiers
astonished many lawyers and other justice officials by waiting
months before issuing an 1,159-page explanation of his ruling.
Among other things, it questioned Mandela's credibility and
behavior on the stand.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying case is about the control of rugby, one of the
three sports _ along with soccer and cricket _ that South Africans
care passionately about. Rugby is still popular largely with
whites, especially with Afrikaners.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the South African Rugby Football Union, which
influences every level of the game from high school up to the
Springbok national team, had failed to bring black players along
and was dominated by Louis Luyt, who controlled important teams and
stadiums. A committee of the rugby union said accusations of racism
were ``defamatory, inflammatory and devoid of all substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, at the urging of his sports minister, Steve Tshwete,
appointed a commission headed by Jules Browde, a prominent human
rights lawyer, to investigate. Luyt sued to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of Mandela by Luyt's legal team infuriated many
South Africans. The National Sports Council called for a world
boycott of South African rugby and trade unions threatened to
disrupt games. Luyt was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Luyt, a former fertilizer and brewery magnate who acted as a
front man for apartheid government efforts to bankrupt the liberal
English-language press 20 years ago, has become something of a hero
to Afrikaner nationalists. He recently formed his own political
party for the 1999 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the Constitutional Court, its president, Judge
Arthur Chaskalson, rejected the contention by Luyt's lawyers that
the appeal was more about facts than constitutional law and that it
should be heard by the former high court, the Supreme Court of
Appeals in Bloemfontein. The Constitutional Court will hear the
appeal beginning March 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
