<HEADER>
A9890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT &LR;      12-02 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: STUDY CUTS THROUGH BLATHER ON SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Clinton administration begins a two-day conference next
week at the White House on fixing Social Security, the most radical
option on the table, and the darling of Republicans, will be the
one that would allow individuals to deposit part of their payroll
taxes into private retirement accounts rather than into the
existing government fund.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, supporters say, is to give individuals more control
over their financial futures and to reap the large returns that are
possible once they can invest in stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The issues are complex, but conference participants might cut
through the usual blather if they first read a lucid study,
released last week, by an expert panel of the National Academy of
Social Insurance, a nonpartisan research group. Its chairman is
Professor Peter Diamond of the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, about evenly divided between supporters and critics,
was assigned the task of clarifying the pros and cons of
privatization, not choosing sides. And clarify it did. The report
resolves most of the financial issues and exposes the political
issues that cannot be settled by technical analysis. Indeed, it was
largely disagreement over the treatment of the political trade-offs
that prompted three panel members to resign before the final draft
was written.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis suggests one sweeping generality: there is no
financial goal that private accounts can achieve that cannot be
achieved at lower administrative costs by a government system that
can invest in private stocks and bonds. There are plausible
arguments for private accounts, but they are political. If the
report does nothing more than prove this point _ that privatization
is a political, not a financial, fix _ then it will move the debate
away from the posturing that advertises privatization as a
financial cure for a bankrupt system.
</P>
<P>
   The panel did not concern itself with plugging the gap between
Social Security's revenue and outlays that will widen early in the
next century. The plausible solutions _ a combination of modest tax
increases and benefit cuts _ are well known. Some supporters of
private accounts contend they can help balance Social Security's
books by investing in stocks and bonds. Private accounts should
generate returns of, say, 5 percent a year above inflation. By
contrast, the return on money deposited into the government fund
hovers below 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel cites a paper by three of its members proving that
the high return on private accounts is an optical illusion. The
government ran up trillions of dollars of debt by paying benefits
to earlier retirees far beyond what they paid into the system. If
private accounts were taxed to bear a fair share of this debt
burden, their gaudy return would, as a matter of arithmetic, fall
to the level of the government fund.
</P>
<P>
   The panel walks the reader through three crucial issues.
</P>
<P>
   Should taxpayers be forced to save more for retirement? Yes, the
panel says, because the personal savings rate is puny and the best
way to generate income in the future is to save and invest more
today.
</P>
<P>
   Should Social Security payroll taxes be invested in stocks?
Again, the panel says yes. The current government fund invests only
in Treasury bonds. Wealthy Americans need not care, because they
can mitigate this bonds-only strategy by investing private savings
in stocks. But most families have virtually no savings. The only
way for them to tap the high returns on stock is for Social
Security to invest for them.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the panel asks, should stock investments be made by a
government fund on behalf of everyone or by individuals on their
own behalf. Here the panel was split.
</P>
<P>
   A government fund _ identical to today's system, though
partially invested in stocks _ would earn higher returns but at a
fraction of the cost of setting up 150 million separate accounts.
It would also preserve the collective security of today's system,
where retirement checks are tied to an individual's lifelong record
of earnings rather than the vagaries of stock and bond prices.
</P>
<P>
   The danger is political. The government would indirectly own
huge parts of U.S. companies, with the potential of political
manipulation. Would Congress allow a government fund to buy, say,
shares of tobacco companies or of companies that are unfriendly to
unions?
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of private accounts, supporters say, is that they
give people autonomy to tailor their investments and the assurance
that comes with ownership. Also, workers who own retirement
accounts might be more willing to add to them by saving more.
Another virtue, again political, is that Congress might be loath to
tamper.
</P>
<P>
   But critics point to their high administrative cost _ perhaps 20
percent or more of the accumulated value _ and the numbing
complexity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides financial risk, there are also political risks. Would
Congress let ill or otherwise desperate workers invade their
accounts early, exposing spouses to financial harm? Would Congress
ride to the rescue of retirees who make lousy investment decisions,
thereby encouraging everyone else to gamble? And would a system
that relies on accumulating savings from lifelong earnings
victimize widows, orphans and the disabled?
</P>
<P>
   The report sweeps away the financial underbrush to the debate
and highlights political trade-offs. Congress might decide that
autonomy trumps collective security. But idle chatter about
financial emergency should not be allowed to camouflage naked
politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
