<HEADER>
A9895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLUNDERED-ART-BOS &LR;      12-02 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUNDERED-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH GROUP ACCUSES FRENCH OF HIDING STOLEN-ART RECORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing an apprehensive audience, the World Jewish
Congress startled a private session of a 44-nation international
conference on Holocaust assets by saying it has already identified
1,700 artworks in 225 museums worldwide that it suspects may have
been looted by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Lauder, the chairman of the Congress' Committee on Art
Recovery, also accused the French government at the Tuesday session
of hiding records that would reveal the identities of Jews whose
looted artworks French museums now display. Lauder's charges were
disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday, on the second day of the three-day conference,
British Lord Greville Janner raised an issue that the US hosts had
deliberately kept off the agenda because of its controversial
nature: slave labor.
</P>
<P>
   Janner, the chairman of Britain's Holocaust Education Trust,
cited 11 major companies, including Ford Motor Co.'s European
subsidiaries, and Daimler Benz, which just merged with Chrysler, as
having used slave labor from Nazi concentration camps during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Ori Z. Soltes, chairman of the Holocaust Art Restitution Project
and a panelist Wednesday, scolded the conference organizers for
talking about the rights of art claimants, but refusing to invite
victims of looting or listen to their concerns, according to an
account provided to the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   The hopes of the US hosts, that the conference would be
relatively free of rancor, appear to have been dashed, leaving in
doubt whether the State Department can win consensus on a fairly
mild, non-binding agreement for the 44 countries to open their
archives and seek to match claimants with artworks that have been
missing for more than a half century.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal does not even call for the return of looted art,
only that ``steps be taken immediately to achieve a just and fair
solution.''
</P>
<P>
   When Secretary of State Madeleine Albright formally opened the
international conference on Holocaust assets on Tuesday, she urged
the delegates to ``work together constructively in an atmosphere
free from threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Dubrow, a State Department spokesman, said last night
that ``the discussions could certainly be described as frank. But
that shouldn't be a surprise, given that these are such important
and long-festering issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubrow, who said there was no expectation that the conferees
would gather ``just to pat one another on the back,'' said he
believes there is positive forward movement on the US proposal on
looted art, though he said there is not yet consensus.
</P>
<P>
   Though Albright said in her welcoming remarks that the
conference ``requires that painful memories be revisited, easy
evasions confronted, and inconvenient questions asked and
answered,'' The US hosts had given every other indication possible
that they wanted to avoid confrontation of any sort.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, art investigator Willi Korte said the Americans
miscalculated how divisive such issues are in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is not pursuing any substantial claims
against other countries, nor are there any claims against the
United States,'' Korte said in an interview. ``They do not realize
how difficult, controversial and complex these issues are in
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   To insure comity, some critics have charged that the State
Department pruned from the list of speakers some experts they
thought would be controversial, though State Department officials
have denied doing so.
</P>
<P>
   One expert who was told she would be included as a panelist,
only to have her name dropped, was Patricia Kennedy Grimsted, an
associate at the Ukrainian Research Institute at Harvard and one of
the world's leading experts on the restitution of historical and
government records.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole subject is controversial,'' she said, Russia's
refusal to return to European countries the important archival
records that Soviet troops took home from Germany after World War
II. Germany had looted the archives from Occupied Europe during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   When she was in Amsterdam last week, Grimsted discovered she had
not only been dropped from the panel on archival restitution, but
that she could not even get a pass to attend the conference. She
will give a seminar on her research this Friday at the National
Archives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a complicated story and a complicated issue,''
Grimsted said of the archives in Russian possession. ``Yet the
people in Washington want to make it all very simple. They want
everything settled by the year 2000, and that's very unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Washington conference, while expressing
gratitude for Grimsted's role at planning sessions for the
conference, said she was deemed ``too subject specific'' in her
expertise, since the US hosts chose not to focus attention on any
specfic country.
</P>
<P>
   Lauder, who is overseeing a World Jewish Congress art
restitution effort that was begun several months ago, said his
researchers have already been through catalogues of the holdings of
225 museums, looking at ownership information that might raise
suspicions that the works were plundered by the Nazis and not
restituted after the war.
</P>
<P>
   Lauder did not identify the museums or the countries, but art
specialists said Wednesday that they expect that not many of the
artworks are in US museums.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Janner, who angered the US hosts on Tuesday when he
suggested in a luncheon speech to the conference that a follow-up
session he held a year from now, held a news conference Wednesday
to raise the slave labor issue.
</P>
<P>
   Janner said the issue has implications even for the United
States, and that substantial compensation may be required. He said
the Holocaust Education Trust, which he heads, recently completed a
report showing that about one million of the six million Jews
killed in the Holocaust died from slave labor. An additional 7.7
million non-Jews were employed as slave laborers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Ford was sued as part of a class action suit
seeking compensation for its subsidiaries' use of slave labor.
Janner said that in addition to Ford and Daimler-Benz, other major
companies that used slave labor include BMW, Volkswagen, Krupp,
Siemens and Knorr.
</P>
<P>
   So sensitive was the State Department to the slave labor issue
that they had even dissuaded the National Archives from holding a
seminar on how to research slave labor records. And the substantive
discussions on how to deal with thorny issues of restitution have
all been held in private.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
