A9901 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUS-PRISON-ESCAPE-COX     12-02 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUS-PRISON-ESCAPE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Death row escape a black eye for Texas prisonsBy Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After six days, the dog teams, high-tech helicopters and scores
of officers still haven't found escaped killer Martin Gurule, and
prison officials are leaning on their in-house fugitive hunters to
pick up his scent if he managed to slip out of their 17,000-acre
search area.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the bustling search area, where the dogs and choppers
repeatedly crisscross the same woods and marshes, the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice's internal affairs unit has been
beating the bushes for signs that Gurule has popped up elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That police activity out there is not visible ... and we're
not going to talk about what they're doing,'' prison spokesman Glen
Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   But he made it clear that the information they're receiving from
the 150-member unit has bolstered their ongoing belief that Gurule,
29, is still somewhere inside the seven-mile perimeter they have
established around the Ellis Unit north of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury said the internal affairs unit is the reason the
prison system has been able to re-capture virtually every escaped
prisoner in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them have been working to find Gurule since early
Friday, when he led six other prisoners in a dash for the prison
fences after cutting through a recreation yard fence and hiding on
the prison roof for three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The other six inmates surrendered when guards opened fire.
Gurule, who shot two men to death during a 1992 restaurant robbery
in Corpus Christi, disappeared into the nearby woods.
</P>
<P>
   Still smarting from the black eye that Gurule gave them by
becoming the first inmate to escape death row in 54 years, prison
officials are trying to underscore their overall record on escapes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Criminal Justice Institute, a Connecticut-based
group that keeps statistics on escapes nationwide, Texas reported
21 escapes from its prisons in 1996, the last year for which
statistics are available. Texas, which had more than 130,000
inmates that year, reported that all 21 were captured.
</P>
<P>
   California, with roughly 140,000 inmates in 1996, reported 56
escapes and 43 captures. New York, with about 69,000 inmates,
reported five escapes and five captures, while Florida, with about
65,000 inmates, reported 32 escapes and 25 captures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prison system is secure,'' Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas prison system has re-captured all but one prisoner who
escaped in the past decade, he added, with 90 percent of the
escapees caught while still on prison grounds and the other 10
percent tracked down by internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The one that got away has been living in Mexico for the past two
years, he said. ``We can't get him, but we watch him all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Internal affairs reports to the prison board and investigates
escapes as well as possible crimes by prison employees,
inmate-on-inmate crimes and parolees who disappear.
</P>
<P>
   When they have time, Castlebury said, the officers dig through
cold cases, sometimes with dramatic results: Last year, they worked
with other Texas agencies and Mexican officials to re-capture
Ernesto Lopez, who was convicted of murdering a 12-year-old Dallas
girl in 1956 and had escaped from the Harlem State Prison Farm near
Richmond in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any more old cases,'' Castlebury said. ``These
guys cleaned them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
