<HEADLINE>
GROSSMAN TO QUIT TOP DEMOCRATIC POST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Steve Grossman, a Massachusetts businessman who as
chairman of the Democratic National Committee helped lead the
party's resurgence and elbowed Boston into the top rank of
contenders for the party's national convention in 2000, announced
Wednesday he is resigning from his post.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily arranged news conference at the Democratic
headquarters, Grossman said he is resigning to spend more time with
his family, particularly his 79-year-old father, who is suffering
from the debilitating effects of Parkinson's disease and is his
business partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can afford to have an occasional tin ear in politics, but
we can't afford to have a tin ear when it comes to our nearest and
dearest,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, a Democratic activist for nearly 30 years who was
tapped as national party chairman in January 1997, said his leaving
will not hamper Boston's chances of hosting the quadrennial
convention, a comment echoed by the party's general chairman,
Colorado Governor Roy Romer.
</P>
<P>
   Boston is among three cities, including Los Angeles and Denver,
competing to host the convention. By stepping down, ``I can be a
little more aggressive on behalf of Boston,'' Grossman said in an
interview, after describing himself as an ``objective
cheerleader.''
</P>
<P>
   Romer said, ``I'll guarantee you, as a colleague of Steve's, I
would not allow, would not allow, his departure to prejudice that
decision. That's just not the way we do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, 52, a prodigious fund-raiser and one of the party's
most generous contributors, will leave as soon as President Clinton
picks a successor. That choice must be approved by the 400-plus
members of the DNC, which is not scheduled to hold a full meeting
until March. However, both Grossman and Romer indicated the process
may be accelerated so the leadership issue is settled by
mid-February before the Democrats select a convention site and the
presidential campaign begins to take off.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman's resignation stunned even Romer, who said it ``came as
a surprise to me . . . when Steve gave me a call.'' Volunteering
that he will stay on as general chairman, Romer added, ``I just
want to say, it has been an interesting 22 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman, who was the Massachusetts Democratic Party chairman in
1991-92 and runs Massachusetts Envelope Co. based in Somerville,
Mass., a Boston suburb, has been commuting between Newton, Mass.
and Washington, where he runs the party's day-to-day operation.
</P>
<P>
   He helped mastermind the Democrats' wins in last month's
elections. That effort involved raising millions of dollars in
unregulated campaign contributions, known as soft money, and
spending the funds on get-out-the-vote efforts in selected states
with tight races. The Democratic Party defied historical trends,
becoming the first party since 1822 to pick up seats _ five of them
_ in the sixth year of an incumbent president's term.
</P>
<P>
   But Grossman's signature contribution may be helping the
Democratic Party overcome the taint of fund-raising abuses in the
1996 presidential campaign that triggered judicial and
congressional investigations and ran up a massive legal debt for
the party. He has winnowed the party's roughly $18 million debt in
1996 down to about $8 million today.
</P>
<P>
   At a DNC fund-raiser Tuesday night featuring several new
Democratic members of Congress, Clinton heaped praised on Grossman,
just minutes before the party chairman took him aside and told the
president of his plans to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't be here if he hadn't put in all the long hours and
long days and long weeks and long months,'' Clinton said at the
fund-raiser. ``He never got tired,'' the president went on. ``I do
get tired. I plead guility, I get tired. Steve Grossman never got
tired. And I think we ought to tell him that we know that and we
thank him so much.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton made those remarks, Grossman ``figured, since it
doesn't get any better than this, I'd better let him know right
now,'' he recalled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first words out of Clinton's mouth, Grossman recalled in
Wednesday's interview, were, ``We are going to miss you a lot. But
you're doing the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released by the White House, Clinton said:
``While it is good news for his family, the resignation of the DNC
National Chairman Steve Grossman is a loss for the Democratic
Party. Steve has been a leader, a party builder, a prolific
fund-raiser, and a wonderful friend to Hillary and me.''
</P>
<P>
   While he had wanted to leave sooner, Grossman said the November
elections made it more difficult but also allowed him to leave on a
high note.
</P>
<P>
   He said the health of his father, Edgar Grossman, had
deterioriated to the point that he felt a personal responsibility
to be there for him and other family members. He also said he
couldn't bear his 9-year-old son Joshua giving up soccer and
baseball, because in Josh's words: ``When you stopped coming to my
games, it took all the fun out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
