<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT RESIDENTS PROTEST COST OF FOOTBALL STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Connecticut taxpayers concerned about financing details of the
proposed stadium for the New England Patriots flooded House
Democrats with phone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And Representative Moira Lyons, a Stamford Democrat who stood
behind team owner Robert Kraft to show her support the day he
signed the publicly-financed stadium deal earlier this month, cast
a more critical eye on the plan, under which a new report shows the
state would barely break even.
</P>
<P>
   But in stark contrast to the political climate in Massachusetts,
Connecticut politicians _ from US Senator Christopher Dodd to the
rank and file Democrats who toil under Republican Governor John
Rowland _ renewed their support for completing a deal to solve the
team's need for a new facility.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders met with Rowland for two hours at the state
Capitol Wednesday morning, discussing such things as logistics for
the Dec. 19 special session when the agreement is scheduled to be
voted on, along with the perceived negativity of the Boston press.
</P>
<P>
   However, the bipartisan group said they did not change any
aspect of the Memorandum of Understanding that would bring the
Patriots to a site along the Connecticut River by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   And, following the meeting, lawmakers said they felt the KPMG
Peat Marwick study released Tuesday answered most of the tricky
questions members of the House and Senate had been asking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Peat Marwick report helped us tremendously,'' said House
Speaker Thomas Rittercq, who spent the weekend talking to lawmakers
and gauging what he characterized as strong support.``What we want
to do is make sure this is revenue neutral to the state. That's our
objective here.''
</P>
<P>
   The report showed that, over 30 years, the state would reap $3.2
million in direct stadium revenue after paying off $374 million in
principle and interest for the facility and surrounding
infrastructure. The state would lose money in the first 14 years
but would start to see net revenue generating after that.
</P>
<P>
   But KPMG is working on another study to determine what effect
paying as much as $100 million in cash out of Connecticut's
projected budget surplus would have on the bottom line of the
project. The report, expected to be completed before the Dec. 15
vote, could determine how to substantially shorten the term of the
debt, now estimated at $25 million a year for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming they put more cash on the table as opposed to
bonding, that would lower the debt service and shorten the
timeframe,'' said Roy Occhiogrossocq, a spokesman for Senate
President pro tem Kevin Sullivancq. ``It's an option.''
</P>
<P>
   The length of deal is important for another reason.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators, led by Lyons -- who will replace Ritter as Speaker
in January -- wants to know how the state will be protected if
Kraft leaves the state before the 30-year timeframe outlined in the
memorandum of understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the guarantee by which the Patriots would be kept in
Connecticut for the 30-year period,'' Lyons asked. ``I believe
they're attempting to work that out as I speak.''
</P>
<P>
   Ritter would not say whether anyone is trying to tighten the
language of the agreement to assuage such concerns that Kraft could
pull out, leaving the state with a 68,000-seat, open-air facility
that just the University of Connecticut football team would play
in, along with some concerts in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was (a change) I wouldn't tell you,'' Ritter said.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic caucus, the first to address the stadium plan, is
scheduled for the morning of Dec. 9, when a public hearing on the
subject will be held at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average legislator has probably gotten about 10 (negative)
phone calls. For something this monumental, I would think you'd get
more phone calls than that,'' Ritter said. ``There is the overall
support of the public. Only those who are opposed are calling.''
</P>
<P>
   While the initial KPMG study answered many questions, there are
some still dangling.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to an exit clause, Lyons said questions persist
about the state's $17.5 million annual guarantee of luxury seating
sales and who will pay for any project costs over the $350 million,
which could rise to $374 million once inflation is factored in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, is that the absolute number?'' Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the luxury seat component of the agreement, Dean Pagani,
a spokesman for Rowland, said ``there would be no changes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So far it seems the votes are there. No one has an exact
count.'' Pagani added. ``Everyone wants to be for this, they just
want to spend the next two weeks asking questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Joe Santangelocq, a spokesman for House Minority Leader
Robert Ward, a Northford Republican: ``Our caucus is in general
support and we expect it's going to pass.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
