<HEADLINE>
THE SITES OF FRANCE IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A bucolic image of the French countryside is featured in a new
magazine and billboard ad campaign inviting visitors to the tasting
room of Fetzer Vineyards, which is in Mendocino County. The copy in
Sunset magazine and on two billboards along Highway 101: ``Tour the
Wine Country: Without the Tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   Fetzer is owned by Brown-Forman Corp., a conglomerate
headquartered in Louisville, Ky.  &UR; Phil Lynch &LR; , that company's
public relations man, acknowledged that the photo was bought from
stock. ``We selected the photograph because it was representative
of the tree-lined lane leading to the winery,'' he said. The trunks
of the elm trees leading to the actual winery are painted white,
and ``we decided we didn't like the look,'' Lynch said. The
decision to use the French photo was made by Fetzer people in
California, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertising, after all, is about representing an experience a
consumer may enjoy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The $50,000 campaign was created by Gardner Geary Coll &AMP; Young
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The fall issue of ``Off Mike,'' a KGO radio promotional
magazine, features an interview with Dr. &UR; Laura Schlessinger &LR; , in
which the advice-giver credits her success in radio to mentor
 &UR; Bill Ballance &LR; , an L.A. radio personality. This is the same
Ballance, notes  &UR; Al Guthertz &LR; , whose nude photos of Dr. Laura have
been all over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco Supervisor  &UR; Tom Ammiano  &LR; got a call this week
from the makers of an HBO movie being shot in Toronto about the
killings of &UR; George Moscone  &LR; and  &UR; Harvey Milk &LR;  (who's being played
by  &UR; Peter Coyote &LR; ). Ammiano, president-elect of the Supervisors,
was asked if he wanted to play some small role in the production;
he says he's not sure what it is, ``but I don't think it's  &UR; Dianne &LR; 
 &UR; Feinstein &LR; ,'' who had the job then.
</P>
<P>
   _ TopFive.com is a Web site in which selected contributors
supply daily suggestions as answers to comic queries. A recent list
included the names of American movies and made-up translations for
the titles of same, as they purportedly show in Asia. Turned out
that the totally imaginary TopFive list wound up _ reported as
truth _ in a New York Times story about this real phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; John Glenn  &LR; is owning up to the truth: He was throwing up as
the shuttle Discovery came in for a landing. ``I preloaded with too
much fluid coming down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GUIDE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ From the catalog of the Japan Woodworker in Alameda, Calif.: a
Sword Quality Woodworking Knife, &LR;  made by 71-year-old
 &UR; Masao Miyamoto &LR; , who is a knife-making celebrity in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   This $339 tool ``is painted with a special mixture of clay and
ash and then heated and quench-cooled. ... This is done during
certain full moons, when Mr. Miyamoto feels his ability to judge
color is most acute.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Anatomical Products Premier Gift Catalog, forwarded by
 &UR; Kate Rassbach &LR; , is brimming with holiday suggestions. Among them,
the $3.95 Urine Specimen Bottle (``Impressive as a serving cruet
for your fresh-squeezed orange juice or finest balsamic
vinaigrette''); &LR;  and One- and Five-Pound Fat Replicas ($12 and
$75), the mere sight of which leaves ``a profound memorable
effect.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
