<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-CONFIDENT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M EXPECTS TO MARCH AGAINST KANSAS STATE DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Perspective can be a unique thing.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M players, who struggled to produce 173 yards against a
Texas defense ranked ninth in the Big 12 in their most recent
outing, said they expect to move the ball with authority against
the league's stingiest unit in Saturday's Big 12 title game.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   The 10-2 Aggies, ranked 10th in The Associated Press poll, have
been encouraged by videotape reviews of recent efforts by No. 2
Kansas State (11-0), which will bring the league's top-rated
defense to St. Louis for the 3:30 p.m. game Saturday at the Trans
World Dome. The Wildcats have surrendered a combined 791 yards and
55 points in their past two outings, which were high-scoring
victories against Nebraska (40-30) and Missouri (31-25).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to give away the game plan, but they've got some
holes out there. They're beatable. They're not 1997 Nebraska,''
said wide receiver Chris Cole, comparing the Wildcats to the
Cornhuskers' squad that hammered A&AMP;M, 54-15, in last year's title
game. ``They're a team that can be beat, I promise. If we execute
our offense, we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M players and coaches offered a litany of reasons why the
Aggies could not produce more than 173 yards, including minus-7
yards on the ground, in last week's 26-24 loss to Texas. Among
them: slippery turf, overthrown receivers, underthrown receivers,
dropped passes and blown assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Those mistakes, said A&AMP;M players, should not resurface against
the Wildcats. In their minds, the Texas game represents a
statistical aberration rather than a reason to panic for an offense
that ranks 95th among 112 teams in Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M players also were quick to discount any residual effects
from last year's 35-17 loss in Manhattan, Kan. During that contest,
Kansas State limited A&AMP;M to four first downs and 90 yards total
offense, including minus 35 on the ground. It remains A&AMP;M's most
futile offensive effort in 10 seasons under coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were undefeated when we went up there and I
don't think we were ready for them,'' tight end Dan Campbell said.
``Nebraska had already stomped them \R56-26\S and we felt like they
were just another team. Now, we know how good they are. We know
what we're getting into.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the Wildcats offer the nation's second-ranked
defense, allowing 251.6 yards and 11.3 points per game. But the
Aggies, who have gained 232 yards or less on five occasions this
season, insist they see chinks in the Wildcats' defensive armor
they can exploit.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska, after all, rushed for 212 yards. Missouri, which ranks
11th among Big 12 teams in passing offense (two spots below A&AMP;M),
threw for 249 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we minimize our mistakes, we ought to be able to compete
with their defense,'' quarterback Randy McCown said. ``We just
can't afford to waste our scoring chances. When we get them, we've
got to cash in.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the passing game, said McCown, who identified
the secondary as ``the soft spot'' of the Kansas State defense.
Cole praised the Wildcats' defenders but said they are not in the
same class as Florida State, which defeated A&AMP;M, 23-14, on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most athletic team I've seen in my life,'' Cole
said of the Seminoles. ``They had guys on the defensive line that
could play in the secondary. You don't see many teams like that.
Kansas State can play, but not like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we're going in looking to make some big plays in
the air. If we have to throw 1,000 times to win this game, we'll do
it. We've got to redeem ourselves ... and get to a big-time bowl.
They're just a little obstacle in our way.''
</P>
<P>
   A stagnant offense, of course, could be a major encumbrance in
clearing such an obstacle. But when they look in the mirror, the
Aggies don't see one, despite recent evidence to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one game out of 12. You're going to have days like
that,'' said tailback Dante Hall, who gained 8 yards on 10 carries
against Texas. ``We need to find a way not to let that happen
again. But I don't know how we're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said: ``You look at how football works from one week to
the next, it may be a totally different situation in St. Louis.
Yes, their defense, over the course of the season, has been better
than Texas. But it comes down to that one day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
