<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPEE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH ROW ESCAPEE `COULD BE ANYWHERE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Martin Gurule, the Death Row inmate who
pulled off a daring escape from one of Texas' most heavily guarded
prisons, remains on the lam with authorities reluctantly
acknowledging Wednesday that he ``could be anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Department of Criminal Justice officials said the most
likely scenario is that the killer of a Corpus Christi restaurant
owner remains holed up in the swampy, snake-infested woods
surrounding the Ellis Prison Unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no hard information that he is not in this area,''
said Glen Castlebury, a prison system spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an intensive search with law officers and packs of
tracking dogs combing the woods, officials tried for the second day
Wednesday to lull the 29-year-old fugitive into a false sense of
security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him to relax,'' Castlebury said ``But when he makes a
move, he's a goner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in this Southeast Texas community of 35,000 said they
.MDNM/suspect that Gurule made a clean getaway Thanksgiving night,
when he and six other Death Row inmates bolted from a prison chapel
rooftop and scrambled toward a fence topped with razor-wire.
</P>
<P>
   All but Gurule surrendered inside the fence after prison guards
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess, he's gone,'' said Ben Wade, a convenience store
clerk who works a few miles from the Ellis Unit. ``He's probably in
Mexico by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade said some motorists who stopped at his store off Interstate
45 told him they feared getting out of their automobiles because
Gurule was on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   Huntsville residents are generally taking the escape in stride,
said Robert Barley, another store clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people here either work for TDCJ or used to work
for TDCJ,'' said Barley, a former correctional officer. ``And most
of us carry guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prison mug shots of Gurule, Death Row inmate 999063,
are being distributed along the Texas-Mexico border in case the
inmate slipped.MDNM/ through the army of law officers that
converged on Huntsville, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he could have caught a ride somewhere out here and
gotten past our checkpoints,'' said Larry Fitzgerald, another
prison system spokesman. ``There's nothing to suggest he has.
There's been no reports of stolen cars or stolen clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if he did get past us, he could be anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that although the activity around the prison unit
has attracted the most attention, law officers across Texas are
aiding in the manhunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of this looks like a one-dimensional effort focused
around the prison,'' Castlebury said. ``But, in fact, there is a
police intelligence network that has been put to bear across this
state almost as soon as the inmate went over the fence.''
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury sidestepped questions about whether law officers had
contacted friends and relatives of the inmates captured in the
prison break attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not confirm anything on police intelligence efforts,''
Castlebury said. ``You can use your own common sense based on what
you know about law enforcement's fugitive-apprehension
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the escape, law officers and about 70 dogs have tramped
through the 11,000 acres of heavy woods a few miles south of the
Trinity River in remote Walker County. Helicopters on loan from the
National Guard, the Immigration and Naturalization Service and the
Coast Guard crisscrossed the area outfitted, searching with
infrared heat-sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday the scene appeared more sedate. The farm road leading
to the Ellis Unit was dotted with gray-uniformed correctional
officers _ some standing, others watching while sitting on patio
chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Most officers built small, open-pit campfires fueled by deadwood
collected from the piney woods that surround the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Helicopters buzzed the woods only sporadically, and the dog
teams rested. Officials said the dogs will.MDNM/ be used randomly
or if there is cause to believe that Gurule is on the move.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Safety troopers and correctional officers
continued to stop and search all vehicles on roads leading from the
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Polunsky, chairman of the Texas Board of Criminal Justice,
has appointed a committee to investigate all aspects of the state's
first successful Death Row escape since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be looking at how the doors are locked. To how the
inmates are taken to work areas, to anything else involved in
inmate security,'' Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
