<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX MAY SEEK SERVICES OF WILL CLARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone for a cheap Thrill?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question they're asking on Yawkey Way, where the Red
Sox are pondering a pursuit of Will ``The Thrill'' Clark, the
newest potential replacement part for Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette was there the day Clark, playing
for the US Olympic team in 1984, hit three home runs in Fenway
Park. He hasn't homered in Fenway since, but his .438 average (35
for 80) there is his personal best in any ballpark. Only six of his
hits at Fenway were for extra bases (five doubles and a triple).
</P>
<P>
   Clark, a 13-year veteran who turns 35 March 13, had hoped to
return to the Texas Rangers, where he finished out a five-year
contract with his best season in a Ranger uniform, batting .305
with 23 home runs, 98 runs, and 102 RBIs. More important, he
appeared in 149 games, his most since 1990, when he was with the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, apparently reluctant to give Clark a multiyear
extension because of his injury history with the club, instead
lured Rafael Palmeiro back to Texas with a five-year, $45 million
deal. Clark, who had held back from shopping his services around
until Texas made its move, became the best available free agent
first baseman left and should come a good deal cheaper than either
Vaughn (six years, $80 million) or Palmeiro. The Red Sox might be
able to get away with signing him to a two- or three-year deal,
though as of early Wednesday evening, they had not made an offer.
</P>
<P>
   According to agent Jeff Moorad, Clark would love to come here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My position is clear,'' said Moorad, who along with Leigh
Steinberg represents Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe. ``If Boston
is interested in Will Clark, Will Clark is interested in the Red
Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have enough interest in Clark that on Monday,
Duquette asked manager Jimy Williams to place a call to the New
Orleans native, who is known for his feisty and aggressive approach
to the game.
</P>
<P>
   For most of last season, Clark hit fifth in the Texas order
behind Juan Gonzalez, who saw enough good pitches to hit .318 with
45 home runs and 157 RBIs, numbers that helped him win the American
League's Most Valuable Player Award. But for much of his career,
Clark has been a No. 3 hitter and could fill that role for the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   There are trade avenues the Red Sox could explore for a first
baseman. Seattle, which has to move outfielder Jay Buhner to first
because of his shoulder surgery, would be willing to trade David
Segui. Expansion Tampa Bay has two veteran first basemen, Fred
McGriff and Paul Sorrento, who have a year left on their contracts.
The Brewers could move injury-prone John Jaha, and the Marlins
might listen to offers for Cliff Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   But Clark, a six-time All-Star (last appearance, 1994) who hit a
home run in his first big league at-bat off Nolan Ryan and 10
seasons ago was runner-up to Giants teammate Kevin Mitchell in the
National League's MVP voting, is arguably the best of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   Voted the nation's top college player at Mississippi State in
1985, Clark had just one month last season in which he hit under
.300, and with runners in scoring position, he batted .318. The
lefthanded batter hit better against lefties (.327) than righties
(.297), but in two playoff series for the Rangers, both against the
Yankees, he hit just .111 (3 for 27).
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, he slipped last season, making 13 errors after
committing just four in each of the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But he was healthy until he fractured his right big toe when hit
by a pitch by Tampa Bay's Julio Santana Sept. 12. He missed two
games before returning to the lineup as DH.
</P>
<P>
   Before last season, he had a series of injuries with Texas. At
various times, he went on the disabled list with a pulled left
quadriceps, badly bruised rib cage, strained right calf muscle,
sprained left wrist and fractured finger, and torn fascia tissue in
his right heel.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of track record would scare a few teams away. But
Clark is at a point in his career that he's not looking for a
long-term commitment. He's looking to play for a contender, and
with his track record, he won't be intimidated about being the man
who replaces Vaughn.
</P>
</TEXT>
