<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-QUOTAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON EXPECTED TO APPEAL RULING ON SCHOOL QUOTA SCHEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a decision that could affect public school
desegregation plans nationwide, the Boston School Committee is
expected to appeal to the US Supreme Court the recent federal court
ruling declaring Boston Latin School's admissions policy
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the School Department announced Wednesday that all
students invited to the city's three exam schools for next
September will be admitted strictly on merit, without considering
race.
</P>
<P>
   If the Supreme Court decides to hear the Latin case _ which
could happen as early as the spring _ it would be the first
public-school affirmative action appeal heard by the high court. In
recent years, the Supreme Court and other federal courts have
increasingly overturned racial quotas in cases involving government
employment and college admission, but not in cases involving public
school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is so important that we must seek the final judgment
of the highest court to give us clear direction,'' Boston School
Superintendent Thomas W. Payzant said Wednesday before an evening
executive session of the School Committee that was called to vote
on the issue. ``This is a threshold case with respect to
affirmative action and public and secondary schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the First Circuit Court of Appeals said the
Boston School Committee improperly defined diversity strictly in
terms of race in its admissions policy for the prestigious Latin
School.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered the white plaintiff, Dorchester 10th-grader
Sarah Wessmann, to immediately be admitted to Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Under the admissions policy the court threw out, half of
students were admitted based strictly on scores, and half based on
race and scores. Wessmann had been passed over despite scoring
better than 10 minorities admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Next year will be the first time in 25 years that race is not
used as a factor in admissions to Latin, and the number of
minorities admitted is expected to drop, although not dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   This year, if race had not been used in admitting students to
Latin, 13 percent of seventh-graders would be black or Hispanic,
compared to the current class that is 20 percent black and
Hispanic. Systemwide, blacks and Hispanics make up 75 percent of
Boston's 64,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its affect on admissions to Boston's exam schools, the
court case has the potential for large national repercussions. If
the Supreme Court upholds the Appeals Court in disallowing race as
a factor in admissions at Latin, the ruling may set a precedent for
lawsuits against any race-based student assignment policy in any
school district. Boston currently assigns students to schools based
on choice and race.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, federal courts are lifting school desegregation
orders in cities such as Denver and Oklahoma City, saying that past
discrimination has been remedied and there is no longer need for
federal oversight. If the Supreme Court takes the Latin case,
school officials nationally may use its decision as a guide in
designing student assignment policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt the case is going to be important,'' said
Wendy Parmet, a Northeastern law professor.
</P>
<P>
   Parmet said the highest court, if they take the case, can look
at the Latin appeal in one of two broad ways: as a general
race-based policy in education, or more narrowly as a ruling on
race-based admissions criteria in a city with a history of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court does not speak often on race base remedies
and every time they do, it is important, widely read and
observed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is just the latest twist in a three-year battle at
Boston Latin School that involved two admission policies and two
white students, each claiming she was unfairly denied entrance
because she is white.
</P>
<P>
   Julia McLaughlin, the first plaintiff, successfully challenged
an admission policy that automatically set aside 35 percent of all
seats for blacks and Hispanics. Wessmann, now a student at Boston
Latin Academy and expected to start at Latin in January,
successfully challenged the revised admissions plan created by the
school committee after the McLaughlin case. Wessmann's lawyer is
Michael McLaughlin, Julia's father.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, McLaughlin said ``If the School Committee decides to
go to the Supreme Court, that is its prerogative. The question I
would have is whether they can point to any significant
inconsistencies with the first decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven-member School Committee had three options before it
Wednesday night: not to appeal; to appeal the decision back to a
federal court of appeals, or appeal it to the Supreme Court. The
deadline for filing to the appeals court was Wednesday. The Supreme
Court deadline is in three months.
</P>
<P>
   While he did not have a figure on how much an appeal would cost,
Payzant said Wednesday night filing an appeal would not be
expensive because the Supreme Court will review the appeal court
decision and not hold a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Payzant said no white parents have ``officially'' approached him
demanding to have their child admitted to an exam school because
they scored higher than minorities who were admitted, since the
appeal court decision.
</P>
<P>
   And while Payzant said he was concerned by the Supreme Court's
recent rulings against affirmative action policies, he said it was
still important to have the case decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a different standard that should be used for
public elementary and secondary schools than would be applied in
higher education institutions,'' he said. The supreme court's
position ``doesn't deter me from believing we need to give it our
best argument.''
</P>
<P>
   The school department is expected to use before the Supreme
Court the same main two arguments it used before the the First
Circuit Court of Appeals in defending using race as a factor in
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   They were that diversity has a genuine educational value, and
that past racial discrimination is enough reason to use race today
when admitting students. Both arguments were rejected by the First
Circuit of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts have said that one way the U.S. Supreme Court
could allow a race-based Latin admissions policy, even after having
ruled against affirmative action in other cases, would be by ruling
that diversity has more importance in public education than in
either the private sector or universities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
