u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESPY-ACQUITTED-HNS &LR;      12-02 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPY-ACQUITTED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPY ACQUITTED OF ALL COUNTS OF ACCEPTING ILLEGAL GIFTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A jury acquitted former Agriculture Secretary Mike
Espy on all 30 counts of accepting illegal gifts from corporations,
delivering a decisive blow to a lengthy independent counsel
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing 70 prosecution witnesses called by Independent
Counsel Donald Smaltz, the jury deliberated for nine hours before
finding Espy innocent of accepting free tickets to sporting events
and gifts for his girlfriend from farm companies under his agency's
regulatory arm in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cost a lot. It's been tough. But I knew from day one that
I would stand here today before you completely exonerated,'' said
Espy, 45, who was forced to resign in 1994 because of the
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, facing his own independent counsel, said he
was ``pleased by the jury's verdict.'' He said the former
Mississippi congressman ``worked hard and successfully to create a
department that now better serves the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz, the first of several independent counsels appointed to
investigate members of Clinton's Cabinet, spent four years and $17
million on the investigation. His probe has netted 15 previous
convictions of lobbyists and executives.
</P>
<P>
   But his wide-ranging investigation drew complaints of excess
even before critics directed their wrath at Kenneth Starr, who is
investigating several aspects of Clinton's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met our obligation and the jury has spoken,'' Smaltz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our investigation and prosecutions dissuade corporations
from giving gifts to their regulators, and the regulators from
accepting gifts from those who are regulated, I believe that the
costs we have occurred are worth the price,'' Smaltz said.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, joined outside the courthouse by his brother Henry who
also was indicted by Smaltz and acquitted in a separate trial,
criticized independent counsels as ``someone with all the money,
all the power, very little supervision, no timetable, to unleash
powerful hoards of prosecutors (on) you and your family.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy said that he hopes he is the first witness before Congress
next year when members decided whether to renew the expiring law
that authorizes the appointment of independent counsels against
high-ranking executive branch officials.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the independent counsel law, Smaltz said, ``That's a
matter for Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz angered many Clinton supporters when he tried to extend
his investigation into the relationship between the president and
Arkansas-based Tyson Foods. His creation of his own web site on the
Internet also drew criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Espy and Clinton, independent counsels also are
investigating accusations against Labor Secretary Alexis Herman and
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   Former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros, the former San Antonio
mayor, faces trial in February on charges stemming from an
independent counsel investigation surrounding his payments to a
former mistress. An independent counsel investigation of Commerce
Secretary Ron Brown ended with Brown's death in a 1996 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz charged Espy with violating federal law by accepting
$33,000 in free gifts and tickets to sporting events as well as
cash and air fare for his girlfriend from Sun-Diamond Growers
Cooperative, Tyson Foods Inc., Quaker Oats and Oglethorpe
Power/Smith Barney/EOP Group Inc. Espy's lawyers maintained that no
one received favorable treatment in exchange for the gifts and that
they fell under an exception for receiving gifts from friends.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on gratuities applied only to executive branch
officials. Members of Congress routinely received such gratuities
until a recent law change.
</P>
<P>
   Smatlz did not accuse Espy of accepting bribes and argued that
prosecutors need not prove that the corporations received any
favors in return for their gifts. In closing arguments, Smaltz also
told the jury, ``This case must be decided on the facts. It cannot
be decided on sympathy or politics or race.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy, like the majority of the jury, is black.
</P>
<P>
   But Espy's lawyer, Ted Wells, labeled the charges ``a bunch of
garbage'' and suggested prosecutors ``haven't even gotten close''
to proving their case. ``It has been a joke every day,'' Wells
charged. Defense attorneys called no witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some of the 70 prosecution witnesses testified over the
seven-week trial that Espy neither offered nor gave any special
treatment in return for gifts. Several testified they gave Espy
gifts out of long-standing friendships, not because of the
expectation of favors.
</P>
<P>
   Sun-Diamond lobbyist Richard Douglas testified that Espy sought
his advise on issues and they discussed in general issues affecting
Sun-Diamond. He testified that Espy did ask him to lie to the FBI
as the investigation began in 1994, but he said Espy never granted
favoritism to the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas also said he felt badgered by Smaltz who threatened him
with 60 years in prison until he finally pleaded guilty to a
related case and became a ``puppet'' for the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 conviction against Sun-Diamond recently was overturned by
an appeals court but Smaltz has taken the issue to the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, now practicing law in Jackson, Miss., was the first
Cabinet official to face trial since Labor Secretary Raymond
Donovan. Donovan, who served under President Reagan, was acquitted
in 1987 on charges stemming from business deals.
</P>
<P>
   Once a rising star within the Democratic Party, Espy was an
early supporter of Clinton's during the 1992 presidential campaign.
He was rewarded with the agriculture post, becoming the first
African American to hold that position.
</P>
<P>
   Espy also made vague suggestions that Clinton had made
additional promises to him should he be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him then and there that I was not guilty of any of
these accusations. And I told him to his face and he made a promise
to me. He looked me in the eye and we talked and he made a promise
to me, and I would not reveal what he said. That was man to man,
person to person. So I'm hopeful that he'll keep that promise,''
Espy said of the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
