<HEADLINE>
SNYDER KILLED WILDCATS' FIESTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Sunday, you're likely to hear Kansas State coach Bill Snyder
being interviewed about how the Wildcats were jilted by the Fiesta
Bowl because they finished third in the final BCS poll.
</P>
<P>
   Listen closely to see if Snyder blames anyone. He should be able
to find an easy scapegoat: himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Snyder will surely find any other option preferable than
actually looking into a mirror. That would require humility.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats are 11-0, and probably the best overall team in the
country, in terms of balancing an explosive offense with a powerful
defense.
</P>
<P>
   That probably won't be enough to send the Wildcats to the Fiesta
Bowl, however, if Tennessee and UCLA win their season finales on
Saturday. Even a Wildcats victory over 10th-ranked Texas A&AMP;M
probably won't vault them from No. 3 to No. 2 in the BCS standings.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where Snyder fits in. His nonconference schedule of
Indiana State, Northern Illinois and Northeast Louisiana has
kneecapped Kansas State in the strength-of-schedule department.
</P>
<P>
   If Snyder had just played Indiana instead of Indiana State. Or
Illinois instead of Illinois State. Or Louisiana State instead of
Northeast Louisiana. Kansas State would have beaten all those
teams, and its strength-of-schedule ranking would be a lot higher
than 62nd.
</P>
<P>
   Outscoring those three nonleague patsies 201-14 made fans happy
in September but proved damaging in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Snyder is playing it close to the vest this week,
concentrating on the Big 12 championship game against Texas A&AMP;M.
And don't even ask if the Wildcats need a four-touchdown victory to
vault past the Bruins or Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``You probably create some problems for yourself if you think
that,'' Snyder said. ``A&AMP;M's too good to think winning by a
particular margin would help us. We want to do the things we do
well. Anything beyond that puts us in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual in college football, for an honest reaction, you go to
a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played what they've scheduled us to play,'' linebacker
Jeff Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, sounds like Snyder's the culprit on that one, which won't
make missing the Fiesta Bowl any easier to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've worked hard all year to get to where we are,'' return
specialist David Allen said. ``We finished 11-0. Not to make the
national-championship game would be a big disappointment to us. . .
. All we can do is win out. If we do, something good might happen
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In case you were wondering, Texas A&AMP;M is well aware the Wildcats
need a big margin of victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Kansas State) will be caught up in the BCS, and I
imagine they'll look to beat us pretty good,'' A&AMP;M quarterback
Randy McCown said. ``But we're a pretty good team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rising star: It didn't take long for Oregon State coach Mike
Riley to start getting courted by other schools. Riley was in talks
with Mississippi this week for the head job that eventually went to
Tennessee offensive coordinator David Cutliffe.
</P>
<P>
   __ Prediction: Everyone knows USC linebacker Chris Claiborne
will turn pro after the season. But the more surprising occurrence
will be when wide receiver R. Jay Soward follows his teammate to
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   __ What injury?: Dave Plati, Colorado's director of athletic
media relations, acknowledged that quarterback Mike Moschetti
played in the Buffaloes' last two games despite suffering broken
ribs on Nov. 7 at Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Plati said Colorado didn't release news of Moschetti's second
rib injury _ he suffered separated rib cartilage earlier in the
season _ to the media because the player did not want it disclosed.
If the school acted otherwise, Plati contended, it would be in
violation of the privacy act that covers all students.
</P>
<P>
   He also said reporting the most recent injury ``would have put
more of a bull's eye'' on Moschetti, who suffered 38 of this
season's 47 sacks. Moschetti, a junior college transfer from Mount
San Antonio College, started every game but did not finish four.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Moschetti's injury first appeared on the
Internet, prompting Colorado's denials.
</P>
<P>
   __ Worried Wildcats: Sixth-ranked Arizona is concerned that it
will be bypassed by the Rose Bowl if UCLA is selected for the
Fiesta Bowl. Especially when it hears comments from Rose Bowl
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arizona would be a great representative. We would be
excited to have them,'' committee member Ron Okum said. ``But there
are no guarantees.'' &QL; 
TOP 10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Tennessee (11-0): Beat Vandy by 41 points, watched lead
shrink in BCS poll. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Kansas State (11-0): Better rout Texas A&AMP;M by four touchdowns
or no Fiesta for Wildcats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. UCLA (10-0): Miami called Monday to see if game could be
rescheduled for 2001. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Florida State (11-1): Wide receiver Peter Warrick deserves
some Heisman votes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Ohio State (10-1): Buckeyes sore that BCS bowls are ignoring
them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. Florida (9-2): Gators will be staying home for holidays _ in
Citrus or Outback Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   7. Arizona (11-1): Shouldn't there be an asterisk if Pac-10
runner-up makes Rose Bowl? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   8. Tulane (11-0): The magic ended with Tommy Bowden's
departure. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   9. Nebraska (9-3): Huskers get privilege of bullying Oregon in
Holiday Bowl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10. Virginia (9-2): It's turned out to be a Peach of a season
for Cavs. &QL; 
__ Five more to watch: 11. Wisconsin (10-1); 12. Michigan (9-3);
13. Texas A&AMP;M (10-2); 14. Arkansas (9-2); 15. Air Force (10-1). &QL; 
__ Say What?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those games that has no explanation.'' &QL; 
