<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESPY-CHARGES-BOS &LR;      12-02 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPY-CHARGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER AGRICULTURE CHIEF ESPY FOUND NOT GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a four-year investigation by an independent
counsel that cost taxpayers $17 million, the corruption trial of
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy drew to a dramatic close
Wednesday with a string of 30 not-guilty verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   The federal jury's verdict, following nine hours of
deliberation, cleared Espy of charges that he illegally accepted
$33,000 worth of trips, tickets to sporting events and other gifts
from companies regulated by his department.
</P>
<P>
   News of the ruling ripped through Washington's political
establishment, which for more than a year has been riveted by
scandal, the prerogatives of special prosecutors and the power of
money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, moreover, delivered a blow to the
independent-counsel statute, which is at the heart of the
impeachment struggle on Capitol Hill, even as it alarmed
self-proclaimed citizen watchdog groups who vowed to redouble their
fight to restrict the flow of special interest money into the
pockets of government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Legal observers across the political spectrum agreed that the
case for the first time legalizes gift-giving to Cabinet executives
as long as a quid pro quo cannot be proven, setting a new _ and
some say dangerous _ precedent making it more difficult to prove
official corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, 45, an African-American and former member of Congress from
Mississippi, was appointed in 1993 to the Cabinet and was widely
considered a rising star in the Clinton administration until he was
forced to resign in 1994 amid concerns that he was under a legal
cloud of suspicion for frequent socializing with farm company
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the Lord for this tremendous, absolute and
total victory,'' said Espy, outside the courthouse. ``It's cost a
lot, it's been tough but I knew from day one that I would stand
here before you completely exonerated.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton issued a statement saying he was pleased with
the verdict. ``After what have been challenging times for Mr. Espy,
both personally and professionally, I am heartened that he has, as
he said, emerged from this ordeal stronger. I hope that as he moves
forward he will continue his notable record of service to the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy wasted no time denouncing Independent Counsel Donald
Smaltz, who was appointed to investigate allegations that Espy took
football tickets, travel and other gifts from Tyson Food Inc.
Smaltz eventually widened the investigation to include other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   After accusing Smaltz of lying about the gifts he was alleged to
have received when he was secretary, Espy characterized the
independent counsel as one who has ``all the money, all the power,
very little supervision, and no timetable to unleash powerful
hordes of prosecutors upon you and your family'' _ echoing
criticism aimed at Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel statute, Starr also has spent four
years on his investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This helps doom the independent counsel statute . . .,'' said
Frank Mankiewicz, vice chairman of the public relations firm Hill &AMP;
Knowlton, and a Democratic activist who was once Robert F.
Kennedy's press secretary. ``Smaltz made Ken Starr look like a
legal genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz, who has in the past charged that the Justice Department
was stonewalling his efforts, said, ``We met our obligation and the
jury has spoken.''
</P>
<P>
   Espy admitted to ``ethical lapses in judgment'' in comments
following the verdict, and his lawyers never explicitly denied that
their client accepted some of the gifts. They did, however,
conclude that the government's case was so weak they would not have
to put Espy on the stand or offer any witnesses in his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the prosecution's witnesses actually strengthened Espy's
case, legal observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prosecution's witnesses were abysmal,'' said William B.
Canfield, who, as a partner at the law firm of Williams and Jensen
has represented many members of the House and Senate charged with
ethics violations. ``They tended to side with Espy and say the
gifts were made in friendship and that he did nothing on their
behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution tried to show that Espy sought out or accepted
gifts from lobbyists including tickets to the 1994 Super Bowl, a
Chicago Bulls playoff game and a US Tennis Open match, as well as
free airline tickets for a woman friend.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law prohibits excessive gift giving, except from
friends. Espy's lawyers claimed many of the gifts were allowable
under the exception.
</P>
<P>
   The key to understanding the verdict, Canfield said, is to see
that the jurors made a distinction between an ethical lapse and
bribery, or a violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
   The law up to now has been understood as prohibiting officials
from receiving gifts as long as the gifts are given because of the
official's status and duties. Under this interpretation of the law,
it would have been enough for Smaltz to prove simply that Espy
received gifts from individuals whose businesses he regulated.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the judge interpreted the law narrowly, telling the
jury Smaltz had to prove there was a quid pro quo for the gifts. In
other words, Smaltz had to show that Espy, as a result of receiving
gifts from companies he regulated, made policy decisions or took
actions on behalf of these companies whose representatives had
bought him tickets, vacations and other gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Such a narrow interpretation, said lawyers and citizen's groups,
means that it will be harder to make corruption cases against
officials in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It deals a blow to the independent counsel statute and to the
theory that you can impose strict liability on Cabinet officials
for accepting gifts under the gratuity statute,'' said Stanley
Brand, who frequently defends public officials in court as a lawyer
with the Washington law firm Brand, Lowell, and Ryan. ``Clearly
more has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   What it does, said Gary Ruskin, director of the Congressional
Accountability Project, is legitimize the ``graft culture'' of
political Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, reject the entire premise of the case and point
to the verdict as evidence that the man who was unfairly targeted
has finally been vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing was crazy,'' said Mankiewicz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
