<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI CABINET SUSPENDS LAND TRANSFERS, DEMANDS PALESTINIANS DROP
PLANS TO DECLARE STATEHOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Casting doubt on the latest Middle East peace
agreement, Israel's Cabinet Wednesday suspended further West Bank
land transfers to the Palestinians until they concede to a list of
demands, including the makeup of prisoner releases and plans to
declare statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis insist that under the terms of the October Wye
accords, they are allowed to release criminal as well as political
prisoners. The Palestinians say the agreement refers to political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet also asked for a renewed pledge from Palestinian
leaders to refrain from encouraging violence against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, speaking
to supporters in Washington, reiterated his intention to establish
an independent state in the West Bank and Gaza in May 1999, the
date interim peace agreements are set to expire.
</P>
<P>
   The Cabinet action also followed a day of violence in the West
Bank, when an angry mob of Palestinians protesting Israel's refusal
to release political prisoners beat an Israeli soldier, and in
Jerusalem, when a Palestinian man was stabbed to death by an
extremist Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel demands that the Palestinian Authority announce clearly
that it is abandoning its intention to declare a Palestinian state
and announce its commitment to continuous negotiations until a
final arrangement is achieved,'' said a statement released by the
prime minister's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel demands that the Palestinian Authority stop violent and
inciteful acts and punishes rioters,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is committed under the terms of an agreement signed in
October to turn over 13 percent of West Bank territory to
Palestinians by the end of January. Last month, Israeli troops
withdrew from the first 2 percent of that total.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that there will be no further withdrawals
unless the Palestinian Authority lives up to all its commitments,''
Netanyahu's spokesman, David Bar-Illan told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the Clinton administration was sharply critical
of the new Israeli conditions and said the accord ``should be
implemented as signed.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest blowup comes less than two weeks before President
Bill Clinton is due to visit Palestinian-ruled Gaza to attend a
session of the Palestine National Council. At that time the ruling
body is supposed to reiterate its commitment to annul parts of its
charter Israel considers offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians reacted angrily to the Cabinet decision and accused
Israel of looking for excuses to postpone the transfer of West Bank
land to Palestinian control and to disrupt Clinton's trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is absolutely unacceptable,'' said top Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat. ``We have an agreement. We should respect
it, honor it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this decision doesn't affect Clinton's trip here
and I hope it is not directed against that trip, to disrupt it,''
Erekat said. ``We really urge the Israelis to refrain from such
policies and such steps.''
</P>
<P>
   For several days, Palestinians have protested, sometimes
violently, to Israel's inclusion of 150 common criminals when it
freed 250 prisoners last month. Under the terms of the agreement
negotiated in October at the Wye River conference center, Israel is
to free 750 prisoners over three months.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians say all of those released should be political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says some of them can be common criminals and that it
will not release prisoners belonging to Hamas, a militant
organization opposed to peacemaking, or those with ``blood on their
hands''
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement should be implemented in accordance with the
criteria specified in the annex,'' said Erekat. ``The annex said
Israel should release political prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   Protests outside the West Bank town of Ramallah turned violent
when a car carrying an Israeli soldier and civilian passed by. A
mob attacked the car, bashed the soldier's head repeatedly with
rocks, and yelled ``Yehudi, Yehudi'' _-Arabic for ``Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   After the soldier and the civilian fled, the mob set the car on
fire. Soldiers who arrived on the scene used tear gas and rubber
bullets to quell the rioters.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier, Assaf Miara, was hospitalized with head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The attack, captured on film, caused an uproar in Israel. The
Cabinet blamed the Palestinian government for failing to curb the
unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's violent incident near Ramallah reflects a grave
deterioration in security for which Israel holds the Palestinian
Authority responsible,'' the Cabinet said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident overshadowed the morning murder of a Palestinian
worker, Osama Natshe, 41 and a father of six, who was stabbed to
death while walking to work in the mixed Jerusalem neighborhood of
Abu Tor.
</P>
<P>
   Natshe's murder is the second fatal attack in a series of
assaults on Arabs in Jerusalem, which police believe were carried
out by a Jew for nationalist reasons. At the scene of Wednesday's
attack, police found evidence that they said showed that the
attacker was Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   During the funeral procession in east Jerusalem, Palestinians
threw stones at Israeli soldiers, who responded by shooting tear
gas canisters and rubber-coated metal bullets at the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's violence follows a candlelight vigil held on Tuesday
by the children of Palestinian prisoners. During a speech at the
event, Palestinian leaders vowed to keep up pressure on Israel to
release political detainees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership that threw stones is ready to return and use
stones to free the people,'' said Ahmed Qurie, the Palestinian
speaker of the legislative council, or parliament, better known as
Abu Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd responded with the chant, ``Stones will turn into
Kalashnikovs, '' meaning rifles.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Israel's Cabinet called on Palestinians to stop
what it said were threats to achieve their goals by force.
</P>
<P>
   ``All acts of violence, threats of violence and Abu Ala's
threats of violence must cease,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan is a free-lance journalist based in Jerusalem. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
