A9958 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-PONCE-LADN     12-02 0303
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-PONCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONCIANO NAMED COACH OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As a first-year head coach, Ron Ponciano admits he
made mistakes. Too many, he confesses, to begin counting them or
naming them. What he rarely mentions is what went right, which
happened to be plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Big Sky Conference coaches selected Ponciano as
the league's Coach of the Year. The award was announced Wednesday,
and Ponciano is the first CSUN coach to claim the honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty cool,'' Ponciano said. ``It's a great feeling. The
assistant coaches and the players did it. I didn't do a thing. But
it's a phenomenal feeling. It gives you an extra boost going into
the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano led the Matadors to a 7-4 mark, a second-place finish
in the Big Sky and within one win of the Division I-AA playoffs for
the first time. And he did it with a team decimated by injuries to
the offensive and defensive lines, a team projected to finish
seventh in the nine-team league.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way CSUN came within one victory of tying a school
record for wins in a season and registered its first win against
perennial power Montana.
</P>
<P>
   When CSUN pounded No. 13 Northern Arizona in the second game of
the season, it represented the highest-ranked team a CSUN squad has
defeated. Later in the season the Matadors beat No. 18 Montana and
No. 23 Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always question yourself of what you can do better,''
Ponciano said. ``I made a lot of mistakes during the year. We all
did. There's better coaches than me in the conference. I know that.
But this is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said he voted for Montana State coach Cliff Hysell, who
guided the Bobcats to an identical 7-4 (5-3 Big Sky) mark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
