u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CLEMSON03-COX     12-02 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLEMSON03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson lands a Bowden
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A couple of weeks ago, the state of South Carolina was
collectively lamenting the sorry state of its two major college
football programs. Clemson and South Carolina were a combined 3-17
when they met on Nov. 21. And the future did not look very bright.
</P>
<P>
   That could change starting today when Tommy Bowden, a member of
college football's famous family, is introduced as Clemson's new
head football coach. In Bowden, 44, Clemson will finally have what
its fans have wanted for so long _ an offensive-minded coach who
will bring excitement back to Memorial Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden is one of the hottest young coaches in the country after
leading Tulane, a perennial doormat, to an 11-0 season, its best
since 1931. Bowden's arrival will send waves of excitement around
the state, some of them reaching all the way to Columbia, where
South Carolina is will try to trump Clemson's hiring of a good
young coach by bringing in one of the best old coaches in the game.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina athletics director Mike McGee, knowing that his
school must do something bold to get the football program out of
its perpetual state of mediocrity, has offered former Notre Dame
coach Lou Holtz $1 million a year to take over the Gamecocks.
Holtz, who now lives in Orlando, is reportedly mulling over the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   If South Carolina lands Holtz, and presently there doesn't seem
to be another candidate, a state that was in the football doldrums
in November will bristle with excitement in December.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden replaces Tommy West, who was fired after a 3-8 record
this season. He reportedly will receive a contract that will pay
him just under $800,000 per year. But Clemson will not get Bowden
without paying a price beyond his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden, in just his second season at Tulane, has a $750,000
buyout clause that the school has decided to invoke. Clemson has
agreed to pay half of that buyout, with Bowden left to handle the
rest.
</P>
<P>
   It could turn out to be a wise investment for Clemson. Since
Danny Ford was forced out as coach in 1989, Clemson has needed an
offensive approach that was sophisticated enough to beat Florida
State, which has won or shared every ACC title since it joined the
conference in 1992. Clemson has lost seven consecutive games to
FSU. What better way to beat the Seminoles of Bobby Bowden than to
hire his son, who learned the family business from the ground up?
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden, 69, said he has no qualms about coaching against
one of his sons. In fact, he was already set to do it in the 1999
opener, when Florida State is scheduled to host Auburn. But Terry
Bowden resigned his post at Auburn in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind coaching against one of my boys, unless they beat
me, of course,'' said Bowden. ``I think that's a good situation
over at Clemson with great tradition. I didn't want them to fire
Tommy West, but it is a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clemson's 3-8 season was its worst since 1975, the program
is in much better shape than South Carolina's. That's why McGee
must do something dramatic like hiring Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina went 1-10 last season and showed absolutely no
signs of progress in the five years of Brad Scott, who was an
assistant to Florida State's Bowden for 11 seasons. In five years,
the Gamecocks were 1-14 against Florida, Tennessee, and Georgia,
the powers in the SEC East.
</P>
<P>
   McGee has learned what has been painfully evident to the rest of
the league for some time. Because of the dearth of high school
talent in South Carolina _ not quality, but quantity _ and because
the Gamecocks must fight Clemson for that limited pool of
prospects, the school will never compete in the SEC until it can
recruit nationally.
</P>
<P>
   It will never be able to recruit nationally unless it has a
coach who can walk into any living room in America with instant
credibility. There are only a handful of men like that in college
football _ Bobby Bowden, Steve Spurrier, Joe Paterno and Lou Holtz
are on the short list.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, 61, was in Columbia, S.C., this week and met with McGee,
who offered him the job. McGee has asked Georgia Tech for
permission to talk to George O'Leary if Holtz rejects the offer,
but O'Leary is about to put the finishing touches to a new contract
at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
