<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Unknown' Madkin is Miss. State quick study
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STARKVILLE, Miss. _ Tennessee defensive lineman Darwin Walker
may have done Mississippi State a favor earlier this week when he
said he didn't know much about the quarterback he will be staring
down in Saturday's SEC championship game. Wayne Madkin isn't
exactly a household name in college football, but the perceived
snub has served to rally a close-knit football team that seems to
revel in being discounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne Who?'' doesn't want to get drawn into a feud between the
top-ranked and undefeated Volunteers and his unheralded teammates
who will try to foil their national championship aspirations. But
the rangy redshirt freshman thrown into the starting lineup in
midseason has been gaining more notice as the Bulldogs have notched
three straight SEC wins to claim their place in the league's title
contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand it, but I don't have anything bad to say about
the guy,'' Madkin said, referring to Walker. ``After the game we'll
probably shake hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Madkin played the best game of his career Nov. 21 in a 22-21 win
over Arkansas that set the Bulldogs on course to win the SEC West.
This for a player who didn't enter the lineup until State's back
was against the wall early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   After a resounding 42-23 September loss at Oklahoma State,
Madkin started in place of ineffective senior Matt Wyatt. The
Bulldogs continued to struggle _ Madkin was the starter in
back-to-back losses to LSU and Kentucky _ but coaches noticed he
was gaining confidence.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, Madkin has completed 86 of 177 passing attempts
for 1,448 yards and 11 touchdowns, with just four interceptions.
``He's a lot tougher inside than he was earlier in the season,''
State coach Jackie Sherrill said. ``He's able to make adjustments
when he's out there. He's grown up an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Madkin learned to adapt quickly while playing in a demanding
program at Johnson High in Huntsville, Ala., where he passed for
5,500 yards and 53 touchdowns in his career.
</P>
<P>
   He describes having butterflies, and admits they're flaring up a
little already this week. ``Of course I'll have them, it's the SEC
championship game,'' he said, excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   Madkin is normally low-key, and rarely is heard above a whisper.
But he isn't shy about pointing to the reasons for his rapid
progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because of my maturity,'' he said. ``They can
draw it up on the board, but it's different when they snap the
ball. Once I got comfortable with being able to do that on the
field, I handled it all right. But if I had started the first game
of the season, I wouldn't have been ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   His 6-foot-4 height and strong arm are his main features, and
like Tennessee's Tee Martin, he can be dangerous when flushed out
of the pocket. In offensive coordinator Lynn Amedee's conservative
game plan, however, he's being encouraged not to think option too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really picked it up the last three or four games,''
center Eric Allen said. ``If something doesn't go right, he doesn't
dwell on it. He moves on and tries to make a better play the next
time. I'd hate to think where we would be without him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
