<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The big `Cheese'
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The banquet, an impromptu tailbacks
thanksgiving of sorts, is set for tonight. When Jamal Lewis and
Travis Henry say thanks to all the not-so-little people who made it
all possible, they'll probably do so in an atmosphere an offensive
lineman can appreciate and also pig out. Besides, Mr. Gatti's Pizza
dovetails nicely with Henry's nickname. Say, ``Cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice way to appreciate what they've done this year,''
said Henry. Actually, this pizza paean to a Tennessee offensive
line that head coach Phillip Fulmer calls ``as good a group as
we've had here'' was Lewis' idea. But then, the line was his, too,
until that awful afternoon in Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Lewis was the leading freshman rusher in the nation.
Although he never started until the fourth game, the tailback from
Atlanta's Douglass High finished with 1,364 yards rushing. This
season, the fourth game was again pivotal for Lewis. Planting to
make a cutback at Auburn, Lewis tore a knee ligament. He and his
497 yards were done for the year. So, some thought, were
Tennessee's hopes of repeating as SEC champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a situation we had to manage well,'' said Fulmer. ``I
felt really bad for Jamal. He looked like he was going to have a
phenomenal year. But it was all very professional and businesslike:
What do we need to do next? Who's our next-best player? We were
just going to have to lean on Tee (Martin, the quarterback) more
and (wideout) Peerless Price more.''
</P>
<P>
   And find another tailback. ``We had a lot of confidence in the
two Travises,'' Fulmer said of Henry, the rock-solid, 5-foot-11,
212-pounder from Frostproof, Fla.; and little Travis Stephens, the
fast train from Clarksville, Tenn. ``My only concern was how well
they'd hold on to the football. They're both just sophomores, but
we wouldn't be where we are without them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't be 11-0, top-ranked and back in the Georgia Dome
Saturday night, where the Vols play Mississippi State for the SEC
title and a shot at the Fiesta Bowl and a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ballgame is do-or-die,'' said Henry. ``If we win, we go
to the national. If we lose, they say we go to the Outback or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   If they win, the Vols will do so thanks, in large part, to
Henry. Once Lewis was lost, Stephens started the next week at
Georgia and gained 107 yards in UT's 22-3 win. ``Since then,'' said
Fulmer, ``Travis Henry has emerged.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Henry has had four 100-yard games in UT's last six
victories. After rushing for 113 yards and two touchdowns against
Alabama, he was dominant in the win over Arkansas (32 carries for
197 yards and a TD). Saturday at Vanderbilt, Henry bulled his way
for 136 yards in a typically Cheesy way. There are two explanations
for his nickname: That Henry looks and runs like a block of cheese,
or that he's hard to cut, like government cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the derivation, he's become a big Cheese who's helped
UT become the top rushing team in the SEC. The Vols average 216.8
yards rushing per game. They have rushed for at least 150 yards in
every game and topped 200 yards seven times.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jamal went down, it was a sad thing,'' said Henry. ``But
me and the other Travis knew we had to step up. We went out to
practice with a different attitude, worked hard. It was our
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Both capitalized. Henry's rushed 150 times for 850 yards
(averaging 5.7 yards per carry) and seven touchdowns. He needs 150
yards for the 10th 1,000-yard season in UT history. Stephens has
run for 427 yards and three TDs. Now they face the blitzing defense
orchestrated by Mississippi State defensive coordinator Joe Lee
Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the offensive line blocks the way I know they can block,''
said Henry, ``and we run the way I know we can run, we can pretty
much run on any defense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
