<SLUG> BC-FBN-CHANDLER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler anticipates he will play
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler practiced
Wednesday for the first time since spraining his right ankle on
Nov. 22, and the team is optimistic that he will play Sunday
against the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler worked out with the ankle heavily taped under his sock
and over his shoe, but other than stepping gingerly a few times on
rollouts, he looked stable. He improved dramatically from Monday,
when coach Dan Reeves said he'd have to make a lot of progress to
play. Chandler also worked out on Tuesday, the team's normal off
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell for sure,'' Chandler said. ``I had a
good practice today, and if it's not too sore ... I anticipate it
should continue improving. Barring anything strange happening the
next few days, it should be good enough to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (10-2) are 14-4 when Chandler starts and finishes
games, 3-7 otherwise, including 3-1 this season.
</P>
<P>
   He is sixth in the NFL with a passer rating of 93.2. He has
completed 137 of 249 passes (55 percent) for 2,248 yards, 17
touchdowns and nine interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was discouraged on Monday about the way Chandler had
performed during pregame warm-ups in St. Louis, where the Falcons
defeated the Rams 21-10. Backups Tony Graziani and Steve DeBerg
shared quarterback duties.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said after practice on Wednesday that the decision on
Chandler's playing status will be left largely to the player.
</P>
<P>
   ``There didn't seem to be too much problem, but we weren't
hitting and moving,'' Reeves said. ``I was pleased. I didn't think
he was going to look as good as he did. If it feels good, and he
feels he can move around and get away from people, then certainly
it will be his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler has a ``high ankle sprain,'' which team doctor Andrew
Bishop explained is more painful than a typical ankle sprain. The
sprain involves a ligament high on the outside of the ankle,
connecting the tibia and fibula, the two major bones in the lower
leg.
</P>
<P>
   Every time someone with a sprain like this takes a step, and
especially when he or she pushes hard to the side, those two bones
separate slightly, stressing the inflamed ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler suffered a similar sprain to the same ankle last year
against Denver, but did not miss a game because the Falcons had a
bye the next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the same way it felt after the bye week last
year,'' said Chandler, who in his first game after last year's
sprain completed 10 of 22 passes for 117 yards and a touchdown in
23-17 victory at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason it looked so bad (Sunday) was it was probably
the hardest tape job I've ever had. I had no blood circulation and
my foot was asleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
