<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX     12-02 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kick coverage out of step
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tim Dwight's game is based largely on speed, but he
and a few players on the Falcons' kickoff coverage team were a
little too fast Sunday when St. Louis rookie Tony Horne returned a
kickoff 102 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   When rookies Dwight, Keith Brooking and Elijah Williams _ the
second, third and fourth Falcons from the left sideline _ pursued
too hard to the right, Horne cut back hard to his own right behind
them and tied the record for the longest kickoff return against the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, Horne had a 66-yard return to the other side.
A week earlier, Chicago's Glyn Milburn had a 61-yard kickoff return
to set up a field goal. That return was nearly identical to Horne's
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Falcons have dropped to 20th in the NFL in
kickoff coverage, allowing an average return of 23.6 yards. The
coverage teams have come under greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta works on kickoff coverage on Fridays, but film review
began Wednesday and special-teams coach Joe DeCamillis spent five
minutes after practice working on the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had learned our lesson the week before,'' coach
Dan Reeves said. ``We got suckered in on something that should have
been clear as crystal.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dwight's first game back after missing five in a row with a
knee injury, he took rookie running back Ken Oxendine's spot. He
and Williams beat blocks about halfway down the field _ although
Williams was slowed up significantly _ and Brooking was blocked.
</P>
<P>
   They were too far inside _ out of their ``lanes.'' Their first
mistake was not recognizing something was up when they were blocked
so soon in the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (opponents) are trying to wall you inside (like St. Louis
did), they're going to try to come your way. That's the only reason
they block you early (rather than retreat toward the ball
carrier),'' DeCamillis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to ... keep the ball on your inside shoulder and
maintain position. On the second one (against St. Louis), guys were
just afraid to make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of like, `Why's he blocking me early?' The next
thing you know, the guy is running past me,'' Dwight said. ``Now I
know to keep it wide.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two other failures on Horne's touchdown return.
</P>
<P>
   If the middle coverage men had busted the Rams' wedge, they
could have forced Horne to take a wider angle to the sideline,
allowing other defenders to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   Left safety Michael Booker, who lined up closest to the
sideline, missed his assignment. When the safety sees a hole open
up, he's supposed to fill it immediately rather than wait for the
ball carrier.
</P>
<P>
   By reacting too slowly, Booker gave a Rams blocker time to knock
him out of the play. ``We've got a lot of young guys on the
coverage team,'' DeCamillis said. ``The mistakes are correctable,
but we shouldn't be having to correct them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
