<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New faces right ones for Braves
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Excuse me for what I'm about to say. I've been feeling
a little giddy lately. After all, this is the first time since
those who run the Atlanta Braves traded David Justice and Marquis
Grissom two years ago that I've seen them justify their genius tags
during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan? Otis Nixon? Don Baylor? Next thing you know, the
Braves will do something else as enlightened by trading Ryan Klesko
for a veteran bench guy and prospects as they prepare for George
Lombard's arrival in left field to begin the next century.
</P>
<P>
   I've got no complaints about the Braves' current direction.
Well, sort of. You don't acquire Bret Boone to play second base
when Fernando Vina is out there with nearly the same skills
defensively and with about half as many strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Since October is the only month that matters for the Braves
during this decade, we're talking about this team needing contact
hitters more than power hitters to conquer the epidemic of dandy
pitching and cozy games they often see during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Vina has speed to Boone's none. Just as the Cincinnati Reds were
willing to part with Boone, the Milwaukee Brewers were prepared to
do the same with Vina when the Braves were still looking.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there isn't a need to be picky when the Braves
suddenly are doing just about everything else right.
</P>
<P>
   There was Jordan's acquisition, for instance. Just like that,
when the Braves signed this strong safety disguised as a right
fielder, they got a couple of things they've lacked since unloading
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   First, they acquired one of the game's hidden clutch hitters. In
1996, Jordan tied the major-league record for most hits with the
bases loaded during a regular season, and then he showed his clutch
ability in October. In fact, he did so against the Braves, with a
homer in the eighth inning of Game 4 of the National League
Championship Series to give his St. Louis Cardinals a 3-1 lead at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also will add some tutti-frutti to the Braves' vanilla
clubhouse, and so will Baylor, the new batting coach. While Baylor
will somewhat resemble his predecessor, Clarence Jones, as a
quietly effective worker on a staff that likes to operate in the
shadows, Baylor also will liven things more as a former star player
noted for inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   As for the second coming of Nixon, it gives the Braves a leadoff
hitter, much-needed speed and better defense than Klesko. Nixon is
nearly 40 years old, but only on his birth certificate. Nixon
should start, and will, just as soon as the Braves continue to do
the right thing by shipping Klesko away.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the New York Yankees have shown their peers
that you can't get enough depth and experience in reserve. That's
why the Yankees have done at least what the Braves should have done
during the past three years by winning the World Series twice.
</P>
<P>
   Without Klesko, the Braves become more of a right-handed team in
their batting order. But Klesko is losing power each season, Nixon
is back, and Lombard is in the minors on the verge of becoming the
Braves' next great something.
</P>
<P>
   Good.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
