A9966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD03-COX     12-02 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trainer's departure surprises Holyfield
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Evander Holyfield said he was surprised when assistant
trainer Tommy Brooks left his corner recently to accept the
mentally exhausting position as Mike Tyson's trainer. Holyfield
understood the lure of more money but is perplexed by the manner in
which Brooks broke the news to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy called me and said, `Well, I've got this offer for a new
job in Phoenix,' '' Holyfield said Monday in New York after the
announcement of his March 13 bout against Lennox Lewis. ``I said,
`Well, Tommy, if that's what it takes to make you happy, you should
go for it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said it dawned on him a few minutes later that Brooks
had not mentioned what the job was. So he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Well, I'm gonna be training Mike Tyson (in
Phoenix),' '' Holyfield said. ``I was like, `Well, OK.' There was
no reason to turn it into a negative situation, if that's what
makes him happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Turner, Holyfield's lead trainer, said he hasn't spoken to
Brooks since the Holyfield-Vaughn Bean fight at the Georgia Dome in
September. But he denied any friction between the two, and Brooks
maintained, ``Don and I will always be friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks will make between $750,000 and $1 million per fight as
Tyson's trainer, which approximately triples what he made as
second-in-command to Turner.
</P>
<P>
   Turner said that if he had been in the same position as Brooks,
``I wouldn't have done it. But that's me. Tommy should do what he
wants. I just wouldn't leave a champion to go with a guy who's
erratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks acknowledged that he was angered when Tyson bit Holyfield
twice in their rematch, but he said, ``After I thought about it, I
realized the guy had his back against the wall and he felt there
was nothing else for him to do. Fatigue will make a coward out of
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   King-speak
</P>
<P>
   Promoter Don King is assured of at least $2.5 million from
foreign sales for the Holyfield-Lewis fight, but he will be more
active than usual in this promotion because other potential profits
for him will come from pay-per-view sales of more than 740,000
``buys.'' The record pay-per-view event is 1.9 million buys for
Holyfield-Tyson II. King's belief that Holyfield-Lewis can hit 2
million is overly optimistic. Sales in the 1 million to 1.2 million
range are more realistic. The bout probably will sell for $49.95.
</P>
<P>
   Money matters
</P>
<P>
   A bigger surprise than Holyfield and Lewis finally signing was
seeing Time Warner/HBO executive Seth Abraham and King, a longtime
bitter rival, sitting together on the dais at Monday's news
conference. The two have a 40-page contract, and word was they even
feuded about the placement of an apostrophe in the fight's
promotional billing, ``Kings' Crowning Glory.'' The promoter wanted
it to read, ``King's,'' of course. Abraham wanted the reference to
the two heavyweight ``Kings.'' Abraham won. ``Negotiating a big
contract with Don King again is like dating your ex-wife,'' Abraham
said. ``You think it's the best thing, but only time will tell. If
the fist fight is anything like the negotiations were, it will be
like Ali-Frazier.''
</P>
<P>
   Sideshow
</P>
<P>
   The Garden wanted to make Monday's news conference a spectacle,
using video clips of Holyfield and Lewis, old footage from Garden
fights, fireworks, a ring and a luncheon on the arena floor to kick
off the news conference. But mostly, the news conference was just
plain long. It lasted nearly two hours, but Lewis spoke for only
four minutes and Holyfield for one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
