A9968 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH03-COX     12-02 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investigators examine secret memos about alleged fund-raising
abuses
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Judiciary Committee investigators examined
secret memos about the president's alleged involvement in campaign
fund-raising abuses Wednesday, and White House lawyers demanded to
see the same documents and other material so they can mount a
``vigorous defense'' of the president next week.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing an earlier decision, U.S. District Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson allowed one staffer from each side of the
committee to examine memos written by FBI Director Louis Freeh and
former Justice Department official Charles LaBella as well as two
supporting documents.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans suspect the memos contain evidence of the
president's involvement in questionable fund raising during the
1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   In accepting an invitation to appear before the panel, White
House attorneys say they needed access to the memos in order to
prepare a proper defense for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain that the scope of the defense must equal the scope
of the inquiry,'' wrote White House lawyers Gregory B. Craig and
Charles F.C. Ruff. ``Once we have reviewed the material, we will be
prepared to present a vigorous defense of the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig and Ruff said they may want to call their own witnesses as
well during their appearance before the committee, which is
tentatively scheduled for next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Freeh and LaBella memos, the White House
would like to examine thousands of pages of evidence turned over to
the committee by independent counsel Kenneth Starr related to the
president's affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
and Kathleen Willey, a former White House volunteer who alleges
that the president made an unwanted sexual advance on her.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McNulty, the press secretary to the Judiciary Committee,
responded to the White House lawyers' letter by suggesting that
``they should take that up with Attorney General Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee will continue to be fair to the president,'' he
said. ``We are certainly willing to notify the White House prior to
its presentation next week of the issues it may wish to defend,
although the president knows the truth better than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's decision to grant Republicans access to the memos was
a victory for Republican members of the committee, particularly
Georgia's Republican Rep. Bob Barr, who sits on both the
impeachment panel and the main House committee investigating
campaign fund-raising misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be more difficult for the Democrats to continue with
their defensive tactics if there is credible evidence in these
memos,'' Barr said. ``If in fact, it shows with some degree of
clarity that the president may have violated federal criminal laws,
that is very significant because it would be impeachable. It's
difficult to say that bringing foreign money in is irrelevant,
personal or just about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Democrats remained confident that the memos do not
contain the smoking gun that Republicans hope for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democratic counsel has thoroughly examined the memoranda in
question and has advised me that nothing in these documents is in
any way relevant to this committee's consideration of possible
impeachable offenses by the president,'' said Michigan Democratic
Rep. John Conyers, the ranking member of the committee. ``The
majority's sudden lurch into the subject of campaign finance is
ill-advised and simply a last-ditch attempt to resuscitate a dying
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In granting limited access to the documents, Johnson said it was
in the ``the public interest that this limited disclosure be
made.'' But she placed several restrictions: the documents can not
be copied or removed from the Department of Justice; no notes can
be taken and the contents of the documents must not be disclosed to
anyone other than the chairman and ranking minority member of the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   David Schippers, chief counsel for the Republican side, and
Kevin Simpson, deputy counsel for the Democrats, spent the
afternoon reviewing the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Following the closed-door hearing to grant access to the memos,
Arkansas Republican Rep. Asa Hutchinson said ``it is a step in the
right direction.'' Considered a bridge builder on the ideologically
split panel, Hutchinson said the release of the memos would have
little impact on the committee's agenda next week.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh and LaBella could appear for questioning by the end of the
week. Next week a legal representative from the White House could
appear before the committee for questions followed by closing
statements of the case by Schippers and Abbe Lowell, chief
democratic counsel. Debate on articles of impeachment to start as
early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If any articles are approved, the matter could go to the House
floor the week of Dec. 14. Lawmakers then could vote to send
Clinton to trial in the Senate, censure him or do nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But if explosive evidence of criminal wrongdoing surfaces in the
memos, it could mean that the committee extends its deadline. ``We
will just have to wait and see what is in the memos,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's ruling gave investigators access to four internal
memos from the fund-raising inquiry:
</P>
<P>
   _ Freeh's memo to Reno on Nov. 24, 1997. Freeh has acknowledged
the memo recommended a special prosecutor to investigate Clinton's
fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   _ A July 16, 1998 interim report on campaign fund-raising abuses
and an Aug. 12, 1998, addendum from LaBella and James DeSarno, the
FBI agent who oversaw the campaign fund-raising task force.
LaBella, too, urged appointment of a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   _ An Aug. 5 , 1998 memo from Lee Radek, chief of the Justice
Department's public integrity unit, to James Robinson, assistant
attorney general. Radek reviewed and assessed the LaBella and
DeSarno interim report.
</P>
<P>
   _ An Aug. 25, 1998 memo by Robinson analyzing the
LaBella-DeSarno report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
