<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      12-02 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEGAL TEAM SEEKS SECRET MEMOS TO PREPARE `VIGOROUS
DEFENSE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House impeachment investigators Wednesday examined
secret memos outlining fund-raising irregularities in President
Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal team then asked for access to the same
sensitive information as they prepared to mount a ``vigorous
defense'' before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of receiving a briefing on the internal Justice
Department documents, the Judiciary Committee's top-ranking
Democrat declared they were not ``in any way relevant'' to the
panel's impeachment investigation of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust that this closes a short and unproductive chapter in
the history of this very strange proceeding,'' said Rep. John
Conyers, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., has no immediate plans to
discuss what turned up in the documents, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson agreed
to allow limited access to the documents, which fueled Republican
hopes of expanding their inquiry beyond Clinton's effort to conceal
his affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   If the memos provide information the Republican-controlled
committee considers worth pursuing, the panel is unlikely to meet
its self-imposed deadline for wrapping up the inquiry and approving
articles of impeachment by next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, White House lawyers formally agreed to appear before
the committee on Tuesday to defend the president and suggest who
should be called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter delivered to Hyde's office late Wednesday, the
president's lawyers asked for any information the committee is
considering as it prepares articles of impeachment, including
anything its investigators gleaned from the Justice Department
memos.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain that the scope of the defense must equal the scope
of the inquiry,'' said White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and
special counsel Gregory Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Hyde can comply with the request regarding the Justice
Department memos is uncertain under the order issued by Johnson.
The judge, who previously denied the committee access to the
internal Justice Department documents, reversed course and ruled
that they could be examined by only two committee investigators _
one named by the Republicans and one by the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Neither notes nor copies could be made, according to Johnson's
order, which also limits the investigators to discussing the
contents of the documents with each other and with Hyde and
Conyers. Republican counsel David Schippers and Democratic
investigator Kevin Simpson spent about three hours examining the
documents Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled committee voted along party lines Tuesday to
subpoena the memos, which are in the possession of the Justice
Department. The documents have been kept confidential by Attorney
General Janet Reno, who has said their release could compromise the
agency's two-year investigation of campaign fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans had hoped to get unredacted copies of the
memos, but they considered Johnson's ruling a positive move. ``That
is a step in the right direction,'' said Rep. Charles Canady, a
Florida Republican on the Judiciary Committee. ``I don't believe
the restrictions are necessary, but that is the ruling.''
</P>
<P>
   The memos, written by FBI Director Louis Freeh and the federal
prosecutor who once headed the task force probing campaign finance,
Charles LaBella, include confidential information from grand juries
under Johnson's jurisdiction. When congressional leaders were
allowed to examine the documents earlier this year as part of their
investigation of campaign finance abuses in 1996, more than half of
the text had been redacted, or rendered unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   The memos contain summaries of the campaign-finance
investigation and conclusions drawn by Freeh and LaBella as they
recommended appointment of an independent counsel to take over the
inquiry because it touches on fund-raising activities by Clinton.
So far, Reno has declined to name a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson decided to allow limited access to the Justice
Department memos, Reno issued a statement saying the agency has
``sought to appropriately balance the (House Judiciary) committee's
constitutional responsibilities with the needs of law
enforcement.'' The attorney general said Johnson's order ``has
achieved a just balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, a tentative scheduled for committee hearings was
announced beginning Tuesday, which had been set aside for Clinton
or his lawyers to present his case against impeachment. Also on
Tuesday, and running through Wednesday, committee investigators _
Republican Schippers and Democrat Abbe Lowell _ will summarize
their findings for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Thursday, Dec. 10, the committee is tentatively
scheduled to begin debating and voting on articles of impeachment
against Clinton, who was accused in a report by independent counsel
Kenneth Starr of 11 counts of perjury, obstruction of justice,
witness tampering and abuse of his presidential authority. The
tentative schedule includes committee meetings through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, in a memo outlining the schedule, Hyde said,
``Meanwhile, the committee will continue with its expeditious
investigation of other matters relevant to the inquiry, including
the taking of depositions'' from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The White House complained Wednesday that House Speaker Newt
Gingrich and speaker-designate Bob Livingston have been strangely
absent as the panel prepares for a final round of hearings and
votes next week on articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously an odd situation where you have the Congress
undertaking the most grave responsibility they have short of
declaring war and the leadership saying that they don't want
anything to do with it,'' Lockhart said. ``They need to step up and
figure out a way to get this thing resolved expeditiously because
everybody wants to get this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who is resigning from the House despite winning
re-election Nov. 3, visited his Capitol office briefly Wednesday to
say goodbye to his staff but declined to wade into the impeachment
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston, who takes over in January, has said he wants the
issue resolved by the end of the year, but is leaving the course of
the inquiry up to Hyde, the committee chairman. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
