<SLUG> BC-CURRIE-SHUTTLE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weather may make Endeavour launch a `crapshoot'
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla._ The Space Shuttle Endeavour was
poised for an early-morning launch today to start assembly of the
International Space Station, but weather experts said the odds were
against it.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for the best, the launch team started filling the
shuttle's orange external fuel tank with liquid hydrogen and liquid
oxygen Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's six-member crew includes former Troy resident Nancy
Currie, an Army lieutenant colonel with two shuttle flights under
her belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had been launching today, we'd have been good to go,''
NASA's shuttle weather officer Ed Priselac said Wednesday morning
as bright sunlight glinted off the ocean. But with winds blowing
offshore clouds and showers toward the launch site, he said, ``We
expect the weather's going to (make today's launch) a crapshoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some emergency landing sites under the shuttle's global flight
path were also expected to have marginal or unacceptable weather,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the precise timing required for this mission, today's
launch window would last 10 minutes, from 3:54 to 4:04 a.m. NASA
had set the launch time in the middle of the window at 3:59 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The next launch window is another 10-minute slot starting at
3:31 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is important: Endeavour must chase down Zarya, the 22-ton
control module Russia put in orbit last month. Mission commander
Robert Cabana and pilot Frederick Sturckow will perform maneuvers
over two days to position the shuttle within a few feet of Zarya.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Currie will use Endeavour's 50-foot-long robotic arm
to lift the second piece of the space station, the Unity connecting
node, out of its berth in the back of the shuttle's payload bay and
mount it vertically atop the shuttle docking system in the front of
the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Once Endeavour is near Zarya, Currie will use the arm again to
position the Russian unit within inches of Unity's top end. Then
Caban and Sturckow will fire the shuttle's maneuvering jets to
shove the two units together.
</P>
<P>
   This will mark the first assembly of space station elements in
orbit, but the crew's work will be far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Currie will use the arm like a high-flying cherry picker to move
two astronauts, Jerry Ross and James Newman, on three spacewalks to
hook up cables and install equipment on the units.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-three more shuttle flights and nine Russian rocket
launches will be needed to finish the station, assembling more than
100 major elements in orbit. The first crew to occupy the station,
two Russians and an American, is scheduled to be launched in
January 2000. The station is to be finished sometime in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the first assembly flight for the station might also
become its first repair call.
</P>
<P>
   Zarya's electrical system includes solar panels and rechargeable
batteries, but one battery has not been charging and discharging
automatically as intended, NASA managers say. The battery can be
charged and discharged from the ground, but NASA is considering
having Endeavour's crew replace its control unit in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   Two replacement control units and connecting cables were stowed
in Endeavour's lockers, and the crew could carry them into Zarya,
remove a floor panel and replace the unit, mission payload manager
Steve Ernest said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew is looking at the operations,'' Ernest said. ``We're
working closely with the Russians, obviously. Once a procedure is
established and the crew feels comfortable. . .we'll give a
go-ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of repair job cosmonauts have done countless times
to Russia's 12-year-old Mir space station. In fact, Endeavour crew
member Sergei Krikalev, a veteran Russian cosmonaut, made similar
repairs on Mir, space station operations manager Frank Culbertson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Krikalev, who is intimately familiar with Russian space hardware
after living aboard Mir for more than a year on two missions, will
help check out Zarya once the two station units are hooked up.
</P>
<P>
   This mission will also give Krikalev a sneak preview of his
future home: He is one of the two Russian cosmonauts assigned to
occupy the partially built station in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
