<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATESDOLL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Catching Bill Gates With His Pants Down  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Here's your chance to dress up _ and consequently dress down _ the
nation's richest person.
</P>
<P>
   ``BillGates99: A Paper Doll Book'' is a low-tech treasure that
offers everyone _ from the high-tech cognoscenti to the common Joe
_ a chance to outfit a paper version of the CEO that America loves
to hate.
</P>
<P>
   See the Microsoft CEO dolled up as a certain U.S. attorney
general; be amazed at the sight of the high-tech land baron in
George Washington garb; picture an angelic Bill as ``Pearly
Gates.'' OK, that last image may be a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The colorful, snappy read costs $9.99 and ``requires absolutely
no RAM,'' according to its author, Seattle humorist Chris Alpine.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the 36-page construction book (St. Martin's Griffin)
takes only good-natured pokes at Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Alpine admits to being a fan of his subject. ``The guy is a
complete genius, and he loves comedy,'' says Alpine, 43, who has
performed stand-up acts onstage with Gates at several Microsoft
functions. ``He's a pretty decent guy away from business although
I'm sure I wouldn't want to cross swords with him on any deals.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Alpine's creation lampoons the digital king's
inexorable march to eviscerate archrivals Netscape, Sun
Microsystems, IBM, Apple, Oracle and countless others.
</P>
<P>
   There are references to Gates' status as linchpin of the nerd
empire, cutting remarks about Microsoft's innovative ways (``simply
rewrite the stolen software his way ... and get it on the market'')
and a few jabs at the software titan's legal tussles with the U.S.
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   One particularly galling _ and insightful _ illustration shows
Gates wearing briefs with a worm-infested Apple Computer logo
strategically positioned.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the book includes more than a dozen outfits and
accessories for the four Gates paper dolls.
</P>
<P>
   It is also littered with Gatespeak. For example, when Bill says,
``It is preposterous to think that any one company could ever
control access to the Internet,'' what he really means is ``Give us
two more years,'' Alpine writes.
</P>
<P>
   Or when Gates says, ``Microsoft's future is very uncertain,''
the true translation is ``We're uncertain if we're going to own the
world, or just lease it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alpine said he was contacted by Becker and Mayer(was &LR; 
lowercase) &LR;  Books in Microsoft's back yard of Kirkland, Wash.,
about the parody. The publishers already had produced similar books
savaging President Clinton, Newt Gingrich and Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The book, Alpine's first, is available at major online and
retail book stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big fan of Bill's. I'm sure a lot of the antitrust case
is jealousy,'' says Alpine, who has appeared on HBO, MTV and Comedy
Central. ``Besides, I own a chunk of Microsoft stock.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Alpine is set to perform during a Microsoft holiday
party F &LR; riday  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that Gates &AMP; Co. find the book as humorous as his
publisher does.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't,'' Alpine jokes, ``it could be a long night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
