<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNFB-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN FISHING FOR LINEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Defensive and offensive linemen are Cal State
Northridge's dire needs. Linebackers, a few receivers and a couple
of tight ends would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the field. The real battles are under way. It's time to
recruit at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff needs to parlay its surprising 7-4 season _
despite the 32-29 season-ending loss to Idaho State _ into
recruiting coups if it wants to remain in contention for the Big
Sky title. Coaches began visiting schools Tuesday, the first
official day of the recruiting season.
</P>
<P>
   And CSUN's Ron Ponciano, named Big Sky Coach of the Year on
Wednesday, has set the guidelines. If all goes well the Matadors
will sign 25 players to national letters of intent in February, and
Ponciano said 15 would be either Division I or junior college
transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some bulldogs here when it comes to recruiting, but we
need everyone to be a bulldog,'' Ponciano said. ``The kids all read
papers. They know how we've done, who we've beat and when we
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears CSUN is already addressing the defensive-line need.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a handful of Division I players are expected to make
their way to CSUN. And perhaps they'll be there as early as spring
practice.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week or so, some Division I players made unofficial
visits to CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA rules prohibit coaches from talking about potential
recruits.However, University of Washington tight end Kevin Cooper,
a 6-foot-6, 260-pound sophomore, and Washington State defensive
back Jermaine Hunsaker, a 5-9 sophomore, were spotted on CSUN's
campus recently, and both expressed interest in transferring.
Cooper is from Brethren Christian High in Cypress. Hunsaker is a
graduate of Ganesha High in Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Oregon State defensive lineman Jason Mageo, brother
of Matadors defensive lineman Jacob Mageo, said he planned on
transferring to CSUN for his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   And former Washington State defensive tackle Taeao Salausa and
ex-Fresno State wide receiver Terrance Jones, a speed specialist,
are already enrolled at CSUN and are expected to be eligible next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're going to take some of the transfers but not
all of them,'' said Ponciano, speaking in general about his
transfer beliefs and not about anyone directly. ``We want to see
what kind of character they have and that really comes from talking
to the kid. Then you talk to their coaches and they're pretty
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   In just the few days in which coaches can visit with recruits,
CSUN's coaching contingent has noticed a favorable reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past it's kind of been, `Northridge? You guys are in
what conference, and who do you play?' '' offensive coordinator Rob
Phenicie said. ``This year the reaction was so much different. At
one school, one of the coaches walked over to me with a grin and
said, `Hey, way to (mess) that Idaho State game up.' ``But that's
good. It shows they were watching and they knew what it meant for
us. In the past, no one really knew who we would be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano said the key to CSUN's recruiting class could come down
to the school's administration. CSUN is supposed to increase the
number of scholarships from 50 to 55 for next season, but Ponciano
is hopeful he can get two of those scholarships immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
