<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIOSITES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 MP3 Web Sites a Mixed Bag   By Neva Chonin 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Locating those darn copyright-infringing, illegal MP3 Web sites on
the Net can be like looking for multiple needles in a haystack:
Every time you're about to give up, another one pricks your typing
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the range of interesting material in the legal MP3
universe is about as exciting as cyber-Muzak. Overground MP3 sites
such as the Audio Forge ( &LR; www.audioforge.net &LR; ) offer a few
sanctioned tracks by major artists, live bootlegs and a slew of
recordings by unknown bands for whom MP3 technology offers new
horizons of distribution.
</P>
<P>
   But these also offer links to other sites _ which in turn offer
links to still other sites, and so on _ that dabble in the racier
stuff, including free downloads of multiplatinum,
mega-million-dollar-selling albums such as Lauryn Hill's
chart-topping ``The Miseducation of Lauryn Hill,'' Green Day's
``Nimrod,'' Metallica's ``And Justice for All,'' ``Queen's Greatest
Hits'' and the soundtracks to ``The Sound of Music,'' ``Spawn'' and
``Love Story.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, such sites often vanish as quickly as they
arrive, only to resurface under new names. Yesterday's MP3 source
is today's failed connection. And the search goes on as the trail
of links breaks off into new branches.
</P>
<P>
   Some groups have jumped on the bandwagon with their own MP3 Web
sites. The Beastie Boys led the charge with a wealth of concert
material from their 1999 tour at  &LR; www.beastieboys.com. &LR;  At
 &LR; www.public-enemy.com &LR; /, populist rap outfit Public Enemy has
released a few MP3s from their new album, ``Bring the Noise 2000.''
And at &LR;  www.lessthanjake.com/, &LR;  ska-punk band Less Than Jake offers
a free download, in full, of its most recent CD.
</P>
<P>
   Is online music the final blow to an ailing record industry? Are
the MP3 pirates proletarian heroes or base thieves? It depends on
whom you ask and who wins the escalating copyright war.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome, though, those who stand to gain are
computer-savvy fans, and those who suffer most will likely be the
independent record stores who once supplied those fans with
low-tech, hard-copy CDs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
