<SLUG> BC-RIOSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Everything You Need to Know To Use MP3  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Here's a quick glance at what the MP3 format is and how it works.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 compresses digital audio signals by removing parts of the
sound spectrum not ordinarily heard by the human ear. The MP3
coding can compress an audio signal down by a ratio of as much as
12 to 1. According to the Fraunhofer Institute for Integrated
Circuits, a German audio research lab that played a major role in
developing the MP3 standard, the format's sound matches or nearly
matches a CD and is better than what's available on FM radio.
</P>
<P>
   To play an MP3 file, you need to download a software player.
There are about 70 different players available on the Web designed
for different operating systems, including Windows, Macintosh, Unix
and Linux.
</P>
<P>
   To copy songs from a CD into MP3, a process called ``ripping,''
you need to download a ``ripper'' program from the Web. There are
about two dozen freeware or shareware programs.
</P>
<P>
   Is it legal? U.S. copyright codes allow you to copy songs from
your own CDs for your own use, so in that sense, making MP3s is
similar to dubbing a cassette tape. But it's illegal to copy songs
into MP3s, trade them to others or otherwise make them widely
available without permission of the copyright holders of the song.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 stands for Moving Pictures Experts Group 1, Audio Layer 3.
MPEG is a group that works with the International Standards
Organization and the International Electro-Technical Commission to
approve standards used for the coding of moving pictures and audio.
</P>
<P>
   More information can be found at Web sites like &LR;  www.mp3.com, &LR; 
 &LR; www.musicglobalnetwork.com &LR;  or
 &LR; www.village21.com/tom(UNDERSCORE)50/default.htm. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
