A9998 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIO-SFCHRON &LR;      12-02 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Fun Device for High-Tech Music Fans   By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
OK, I confess, I admit my guilt. Call the cops, call the D.A.
</P>
<P>
   Call the Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   My crime? I'm listening to an MP3 version of Madonna's ``Ray of
Light'' that I downloaded from a pirate Web site into one of
Diamond Multimedia's new $199 Rio PMP300 players.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, while in the mood to clear my conscience, I
should admit that I've also loaded pirate copies of Celine Dion's
``My Heart Will Go On'' and an oldie but goodie ``Low Rider'' by
War into the little Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I know I've broken the Audio Home Recording Act, but it's
so easy to do. Blame it on the Rio, Diamond Multimedia's portable
MP3 player that hit the stores shelves last week.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Rio _ which comes with a cable for connecting to your PC
to download tunes and earphones for listening to them _ is an
interesting newfangled toy that's great for MP3 music fans even
though it still has a few limitations.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is a format for compressing audio files found on the
Internet or copied off CDs. Previously, those files could only be
played using a computer with speakers. The Rio cuts that tether.
</P>
<P>
   The basic Rio stores MP3s on an eraseable 32-megabyte flash card
that comes with the unit. That's supposed to be enough for 60
minutes of what Diamond calls ``continuous digital quality
playback'' and eight hours of ``voice quality audio.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet I was only able to cram about nine songs in the Rio _ almost
enough for the 40-minute BART trip into work. You can buy an
additional 32MB flash card for $99, or a 16MB card for $49 _ pretty
steep compared to the cost of a blank cassette tape.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth Sound
</P>
<P>
   The Rio's main advantage is that there are no moving parts,
unlike a portable CD player, which spins a disk read by a laser
beam. One bump and the music skips. With the Rio, you can pound
through Market Street with a jackhammer and it wouldn't miss a
beat.
</P>
<P>
   The other advantage is its size. The Rio is about the size and
weight of a tin of Altoids mints, and more portable than the
smallest Walkman cassette player.
</P>
<P>
   MP3s work by compressing audio files, removing sound waves the
human ear doesn't normally hear. That still leaves a rich, clear
stereo sound that Diamond says is ``near CD quality.'' The quality
of the sound produced by the Rio compared to a CD was good enough
for my average ears and anyone short of a picky audiophile should
be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The device has an equalizer switch to tailor the audio to jazz,
rock or classical music.
</P>
<P>
   I also ``ripped'' (MP3 language for ``copied,'' not ``ripped
off'') two songs from a CD, and the MP3 was just as crisp as the
original and far better than songs copied on a cassette.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, I'm not copping to yet another crime: Under the
aforementioned home recording act, U.S. copyright protection code
that was written with vinyl records and cassette tape in mind, it's
legal to copy songs from your own CDs for your own use, as long as
you don't distribute the copies to others.
</P>
<P>
   Moving From CD to MP3
</P>
<P>
   The Rio comes with software called MusicMatch that converts CDs
to MP3s in your computer.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up and using the Rio is easy. It comes with an adapter
that plugs into a standard computer parallel port.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to transfer music into the device.
</P>
<P>
   If you want music from the Internet, go to an MP3 Web site and
download a song to your PC, which is best done on a high-speed
Internet access line. One song that took 20 to 30 minutes to
download using my 56Kbps modem at home took less than 30 seconds
using a high-speed line at work.
</P>
<P>
   Then you plug the Rio's adapter into your PC's parallel port and
transfer the song into the Rio, which takes less than 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, if you want to transfer music from your own CD,
you put the CD in your computer and use the MusicMatch software to
convert the songs into MP3 format on your hard drive. This is a
slow process; ripping a four-minute Tower of Power song took seven
minutes with MusicMatch. Another type of ripper program took an
hour for a four-minute song.
</P>
<P>
   Both methods are more cumbersome than the easy cassette copying
we're used to.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking Down Music
</P>
<P>
   Finding songs, whether they are legal or illegal, on the
Internet can be time-consuming, navigating past broken links and
pornographic sites that have piggy-backed onto MP3 sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Rio drains the one AA battery it uses quickly because it
remains in a ``low-power'' mode even when turned off. On the
demonstration model Diamond sent for a test drive, the battery lost
two-thirds of its power in four days even though the Rio was turned
off much of the time. Diamond advises taking out the battery when
the Rio is not in use for a while. There is no AC adapter.
</P>
<P>
   Serious MP3 fans and early adopters will love the Rio, and
analyst Mark Hardie of Forrester Research believes Diamond will
quickly reach six figures in unit sales, even at the $200 price
tag. ``I would buy one for $400,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He might have the chance soon. Saehan Information Systems of
South Korea has also just introduced its own MPMan player to the
United States. The first MPMan, already selling in Japan and
Europe, is also $199, has 32MB of flash memory expandable to 64MB.
But at the recent Comdex technology trade show in Las Vegas, Saehan
displayed future models that may hit stores by the end of 1999 that
cost as much as $500, but have hard drives or a removable 40MB
Iomega Clik disk for storage.
</P>
<P>
   Saehan is also developing a vending machine that would let you
plug in your MPMan and buy MP3 songs for about $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may want to wait for competition, falling flash memory
to drop the price of the Rio and similar MP3 players. That should
happen if sales are strong, Hardie said.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, $200 seems a little to steep a price to pay for an
hour's worth of portable MP3s. Then again, Sony Walkmans also
started out selling for about $200 each and turned out to be
best-sellers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
