<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXXON-GAS-STATIONS-NY     12-02 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXXON-GAS-STATIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVICE STATION OPERATORS JITTERY ABOUT WHAT MERGER WILL BRING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (See also EXXON-TEXACO, EXXON-OPEC, EXXON-ROCKEFELLER) 
 (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROSLYN HEIGHTS, N.Y. _ Art Barbuto's credit-card printer spat
out a terse message Wednesday morning: ``Dear Mobil dealers,'' it
said, ``A letter has been sent to you today with information on the
Exxon Mobil merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other gasoline dealers across the country with
Mobil franchises, Barbuto now must wait for answers to the
questions that keep popping into his head like the pangs of an
oncoming migraine.
</P>
<P>
   Will he have to pay more in rent for his filling station? Will
the combined entity of Exxon Mobil eliminate the rebates that
provide half of his profits? Will he still be able to send his son
to college in two years?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Barbuto, 42, is in a particularly precarious position.
His station, along the eastbound side of the Long Island
Expressway, is in direct competition with an Exxon station on the
westbound side. Will one of the two stations be shuttered or sold _
either by corporate strategists or by order of the government's
antitrust lawyers?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of I-don't-knows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon's $80 billion acquisition of Mobil is expected to result
in a loss of at least 9,000 jobs for refinery workers and
white-collar employees. Consumers could be unaffected, some
industry analysts said, if the combined company can bolster profits
by cutting costs rather than by raising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle, though _ facing neither the certainty of a
swift demise nor the slightest reassurance about the future _ are
gasoline dealers like Barbuto, who leases his shop from Mobil and
buys Mobil's gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   There are 8,500 Exxon stations in the country, and 7,400 Mobil
stations, according to National Petroleum News, an industry
publication. Self-employed dealers account for most of those
stations, industry analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   These dealers, who have struggled with shrinking profit margins,
are left wondering how many will survive the industry's
consolidation and at what price.
</P>
<P>
   The recent combination of the refining and retail operations of
Shell and Texaco, which took effect Aug. 1, suggests the dealers
may not escape unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Madani, a former Exxon dealer in Redondo Beach, Calif.,
said the combined Shell and Texaco quickly raised wholesale prices
and eliminated the cash rebates they had paid to dealers based on
the amount of gasoline they sold _ rebates that frequently meant
the difference between profit and loss.
</P>
<P>
   At Madani's station, now under the Texaco flag, monthly
operating profits have fallen sharply. He said he competes with a
nearby Mobil, where the operator pays $2,440 a month in rent, and a
Shell, where the rent has been raised to $6,000. Since August, he
said, the Shell station's pump prices have risen and its sales
volume has declined.
</P>
<P>
   Financially distressed Shell and Texaco station operators in 12
states are considering lawsuits over what they consider contract
violations resulting from the merger, said Jim Daskal, a lawyer who
represents several groups of gasoline dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McKinney, a spokesman for the Shell-Texaco joint venture,
said he could not immediately respond to complaints raised by
unhappy dealers.
</P>
<P>
   With profits on gasoline shrinking nationwide, service stations
have broadened their businesses wherever possible. They have moved
from tiny retail counters with cigarettes and candy to ever-larger
convenience stores, with drive-up windows for sandwiches and
walk-in beer refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   On this stretch of Long Island's prosperous North Shore, Barbuto
wonders what will become of his hopes to raze his old cinder-block
garage, with its three rarely used car lifts, and build a bigger
convenience store. ``The repair business is dead today, with the
advent of leased cars and five-year warranties,'' he said. ``All we
get is an oil change here and there, maybe a brake job or a
tune-up. I only have one mechanic now. I used to have four.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbuto clearly does not relish the idea of big change. Since he
bought the 35-year-old Mobil station from his father in 1983, Mobil
has overhauled its fee structure three times, he said. In one
instance about six years ago, Mobil charged Barbuto 20 percent of
gross profits _ including sales of gasoline and proceeds from auto
repairs. Then, he said, it started charging its costs on the
property, plus a markup. Overnight, Barbuto said, his costs jumped
from $3,000 to $8,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   These days, his Mobil has been locked in fairly stiff
competition with the Exxon across the expressway. The cheapest
grade of gas at each station was priced at $1.09 Wednesday, only 3
cents above what Barbuto said was his cost. His station sells about
250,000 gallons of gasoline a month from its three pumps, and he
believes he has the better location, since his is one of the first
service stations for drivers leaving New York City, where fuel
costs more. But Barbuto said he still fears what will happen if the
merged companies end up selling or closing some stations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law gives gasoline dealers the right of first refusal to
buy their stations when oil companies decide to pull out of a given
area, according to C. Fred Weil, the general counsel for the Long
Island Gasoline Retailers Association. If an oil company instead
sells a group of those franchised stations to an independent
company, the new owner is required to offer dealers a chance to
stay on. ``I don't think any dealer is going to find himself out on
the street,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbuto remains uneasy. While representatives of Exxon and
Mobil did not return calls Tuesday about their pricing structure
for dealers, Barbuto said all he had heard about Exxon was that it
charges gasoline dealers more in rent than Mobil does.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what gets me nervous about the merger,'' he said.
``With Exxon, if they raised my rent another $8,000, I could be
facing a $100,000 cost differential. That goes right to my bottom
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
