r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HMO-SFCHRON &LR;      12-02 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HMOs Propose Outside Reviews  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
California's leading health maintenance organizations are promising
that by the end of next year, 18 million consumers will be able to
ask an outside medical authority to rule on expensive and
experimental medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed plan, HMO patients, who are denied care by
their insurer, will be allowed to ask an outside expert to force
insurers to pick up the tab on these costly cases.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only a few plans afford such an outside review. This
proposal would greatly broaden the review option, but still stops
short of mandatory reviews that 16 other states have already
established.
</P>
<P>
   Critics immediately denounced the external review program that
was unveiled yesterday in San Francisco by the president of an HMO
trade association. They say it doesn't go far enough to protect
patient's rights, since HMOs will still hire _ and possibly bias _
the reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as Assemblywoman Carole Migden, D-San Francisco,
praised the HMO industry for creating this self-review process, she
said she still intends to introduce legislation Monday to set up an
outside review process in which the state, not HMOs, selects
medical referees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the reviewers are independent,'' said
Migden, who saw a similar bill stall last year.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy surrounding yesterday's announcement by Walter
Zelman, president of the California Association of Health Plans,
underscores a thorny issue in the health care debate: who gets to
make the final call on whether or not an HMO pays for a
controversial medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zelman's proposal, California's 16 largest HMOs, which
cover about 18 million people, have agreed to create outside review
programs. Patients denied treatment because their HMO deemed a
procedure unnecessary or experimental, would be able to ask the
outside reviewer to force the HMO to pay for the treatment. The
participating plans say they will abide by these outside decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Each HMO is free to create slightly different review processes
and even ask consumers to pay for part of the cost of the outside
medical review.
</P>
<P>
   At least two large HMOs, HealthNet and PacifiCare, already offer
such outside reviews. The others have set varying timetables to
deliver on the promises Zelman made yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will touch all of the consumers by the end of 1999, and
most of the consumers will have this in place before that,'' said
Bruce Bodaken, president of Blue Shield of California and chairman
of Zelman's lobby group.
</P>
<P>
   But Betsy Imholz, health care lobbyist for Consumer's Union in
San Francisco, characterized the voluntary plan as little more than
a public relations ploy to influence the Legislature, which nearly
passed a mandatory review bill last session and seems even more
likely to act once Gray Davis becomes governor.
</P>
<P>
   Imholz said other states, including Florida and Texas, already
have mandated medical review programs that are stronger than the
California HMO industry's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Imholz said HMOs probably wouldn't care if the state chose
outside reviewers, as Midgen's bill would mandate. But the same
issue that paralyzed lawmakers last year hasn't gone away. That is,
what happens if the outside reviewer also rejects a certain course
of coverage? Should the Legislature then let consumers take their
HMO to court _ which is extremely difficult to do now _ to ask a
judge to decide the matter?
</P>
<P>
   Zelman said the issue of outside review should be dealt with
before the state decides whether consumers should be able to take
haul their HMOs to court. He also insisted his plan was more than a
sop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask my critics this: Would consumers be better off if we
didn't impose this on ourselves?'' said Zelman, 54, who had a long
history as a consumer advocate himself before he shocked his former
colleagues by taking over as president of the HMO lobby in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Zelman said HMOs aren't terribly worried that consumers might be
allowed to sue them for denying care, especially if an outside
reviewer made the final call.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But he said lawyers are trying to go even further and make
HMOs liable for all sorts of malpractice suits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``If plans were to give an inch on liability, the lawyers
would take five miles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Karin Caves, a spokeswoman for the Consumer Attorneys of
California, called Zelman's comments ``hogwash.'' She said her
lobby simply wants HMOs to be held legally accountable for denying
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider external review a sham if consumers don't have the
right to sue HMOs for denial of coverage,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Migden, who has become a legislative leader on health care
issues, said Democrats will probably give consumers some form of
right to sue HMOs as part of any HMO bills. She said the only
question would be how broad that right should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were an HMO exec,'' she said, ``I'd be figuring out what
I can live with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
