<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES IS HIS FAMILIAR SELF IN NEW YORK APPEARANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
(mk) 
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Bill Gates who has appeared on video screens in a
Washington courtroom is halting, forgetful, slumped in his chair.
As government lawyers in the antitrust trial that began in October
have repeatedly shown excerpts of an August deposition of Gates,
observers of Microsoft have speculated that the company's
long-running confrontation with the Justice Department has left the
company's chairman in a depressed funk.
</P>
<P>
   But the more familiar Bill Gates of computer industry lore _
sharp, self-confident and combative _ showed up in New York
Wednesday, serving up equal measures of playful scorn for his
prosecutors and his rivals at a luncheon sponsored by the Manhattan
Institute, a bastion of libertarian conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Rivals who hoped the suit would curb Microsoft's fierce
competitive drive found no comfort in Gates' remarks. After
extolling the virtues of technology, Gates was asked by a member of
the audience whether Microsoft's extraordinary prosperity was
threatened by companies like Sun Microsystems Inc., which believes
that computing power should reside in networks rather than on
desktop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Gates dismissed the Sun concept as nothing more than a ``sales
slogan'' and went on to assert that the ``PC model'' with hardware
and software made by separate companies was a superior business
model.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the PC model has defeated every other model,''
Gates said. ``There's no going back.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``next battleground,'' he said, was to demonstrate that the
personal computer could handle the industrial-strength chores now
handled by large ``server'' computers running Unix operating
systems and even by mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't proved that yet, but we will,'' he said. ``The PC
model will take over the rest of the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates again proclaimed that America Online's planned purchase of
Netscape Communications Corp. for $4.2 billion, announced last
week, was proof that the Internet software business was a healthy,
vibrant industry, best left alone by the government. The fact that
America Online was willing to pay so much for Netscape, he said,
even after competition with Microsoft forced it to give its browser
away, is a ``very resounding answer'' to the government's
contention that Microsoft engaged in predatory pricing.
</P>
<P>
   When he described the antitrust suit as ``something that no one
should have to go through,'' the crowd applauded enthusiastically.
</P>
<P>
   Still, life has not been too painful for Gates since the trial
started. Microsoft's stock price has risen 26 percent. And the
Gates family is expected to grow as well. A Microsoft spokeswoman
confirmed that Gates and his wife, Melinda, are expecting their
second child in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2142EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0462 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0004 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MP3-SFCHRON &LR;      12-02 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Download That Tune, It's Web Music   By Benny Evangelista  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
``We're the music pirates,
</P>
<P>
   We sail the IR seas.
</P>
<P>
   We rip our favorite albums,
</P>
<P>
   We share our MP3s.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lyrics from ``Pirate This Song,'' by God Ate My Homework.
</P>
<P>
   Homer, Hobbes and Earl Grey T are hardly household names.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to a file-squishing technology called MP3 that has
become a grassroots movement on the Internet, their band, God Ate
My Homework, is known by thousands of people. The group says
100,000 Web surfers have visited their site to download tunes like
``Pirate This Song'' and play them on a personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for three University of California at Berkeley students
who lack a recording contract and whose ``studio'' is small dorm
room and a desktop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of MP3s has provided an instant Internet
audience for weekend musicians like God At My Homework, a new
promotional tool for known artists like Dionne Warwick and the
Beastie Boys, and a major headache for the recording industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone in high school or college or any young adult who has
Internet access has probably downloaded an MP3,'' said Earl Grey T,
who is studying molecular genetics. ``The concept itself is
universally appealing _ the idea of getting free music.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is so appealing that copying, trading by e-mail and
posting songs in the MP3 format is one of the fastest-growing
phenomena on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a techno-underground-punk kinda thing anymore,''
said Michael Robertson, founder of a popular Web portal called
MP3.Com.
</P>
<P>
   Until two weeks ago, the only way to listen to MP3 songs was on
a PC. But just before Thanksgiving, electronics stores began
selling a $199 portable MP3 player, the Diamond Rio PMP300, which
can record MP3-compressed songs from the Internet or a CD and play
them in high-quality stereo.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the hand-held player could have the same runaway
success as the early Sony Walkman, spreading the MP3 phenomenon to
mainstream consumers just in time for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to sell like hotcakes,'' said Mark Hardie,
senior analyst at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. ``It
doesn't skip, the sound is perfect no matter what you're doing. You
could be doing jumping jacks or someone could be punching you in
the head.''
</P>
<P>
   One measure of MP3s' popularity is WinAmp, the leading MP3
software player. According to WinAmp's creator, a bored University
of Utah dropout named Justin ``Badino Tarantino'' Frankel, copies
are being downloaded at a rate of 60,000 per day, and more than 5
million have been downloaded since mid-1997. And analysts say MP3s
have become one of the most-requested topics, besides sex, on major
Internet search engines.
</P>
<P>
   MP3s' wildfire popularity has the recording industry nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Recording Industry Association of America, which
represents major recording labels like Sony, Atlantic and Warner
Bros., failed to persuade a federal judge to halt shipment of
Diamond's Rio MP3 player. The association said the player, as well
as MP3 itself, encourages illegal pirating of songs and thus cheats
artists of their royalties.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, San Jose's Diamond Multimedia filed a countersuit
against the industry association, claiming the major record labels
violated antitrust laws by conspiring to ``stifle'' the Rio and
similar devices to protect their own control over music
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot at stake. According to Jupiter Communications, in
New York City, online music sales this year will total $88 million,
just a fraction of overall revenues. But by 2002, online sales will
hit nearly $1.4 billion or nearly 8 percent of the overall market.
And there is no counting how many legitimate music sales are lost
when fans copy songs from pirate MP3 sites.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 is setting the standard for an emerging new era in the music
industry _ digital distribution of songs and albums directly to
consumers via the Internet, bypassing traditional distribution
channels like record stores.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Web pages have sprung up offering MP3 songs. Many
of the MP3 tunes online are legal copies of songs or by unknown
artists like God Ate My Homework, who find the Internet a cheap and
effective way to promote themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There are titles from such better-known acts as Taylor Dane,
Peter Cetera and the Beastie Boys. And Dionne Warwick's oldie
classic ``Say a Little Prayer'' had 29,000 downloads during a
special MP3 promotion from her record company.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also countless pirate Web sites that feature
illegally copied songs from artists ranging from the Beatles to
Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   A team of record industry association Net surfers breaks links
to pirate MP3 sites as soon as it can find them, and it is
``finding thousands of them every day,'' said Hillary Rosen, the
association's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen insisted her association is not trying to stamp out the
MP3 format entirely.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, she said, is for the recording industry to agree
on an encrypted digital music standard that will keep songs from
being illegally copied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker the record companies move to put legitimate music
online, the less incentive there is for people to search for
illegitimate files,'' Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   But the major recording companies, which control about 80
percent of the world's copyrighted music, have been sluggish in
picking which technology to use, analysts said. That has allowed
MP3s to proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   If the music industry does not act soon, it may have no choice
but to join the MP3 wave, said Forrester's Hardie.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen at the recording industry association said it is
``difficult to quantify'' the revenue lost to illegal MP3s.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 promoters believe the music industry is using piracy as a
means to stall MP3s' momentum until it can set a proprietary
digital standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piracy is not a threat, it's a smoke screen,'' said Steve
Grady, vice president for corporate communications with GoodNoise
Corp., a Palo Alto startup that is trying to become the first
record label to distribute music on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   One 29-year-old San Francisco man said he has downloaded one
gigabyte worth of MP3s from pirate sites and his own CD collection
into his home computer, which is hooked up to a stereo system. He
has created long playlists of songs that he listens to at work
without having to change CDs.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, ``it may be illegal, but, hey, it's free,'' said the man,
who did not want his name printed for fear of getting a nasty
letter from the industry association.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 fan Kevin Fox, a 29-year-old Web site designer from
Berkeley, said he does not download pirated songs but still has
built an MP3 library of more than 600 songs that he copied off his
own CD collection and ``encoded'' into MP3s. That is legal as long
as he does not sell or distribute the songs.
</P>
<P>
   He has friends who ``each night pop in a CD to encode,'' Fox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, whenever he wants to hear techno groups like Nine Inch
Nails, or an old Beatles tune, or even the soundtrack from ``The
Little Mermaid,'' he has them just a click away.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain defiant attitude among MP3 users that the
recording industry cannot take away their freedom of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to defend the right to have this new method of
encoding music,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   And not all record labels see the MP3 as a threat. Independent
label Platinum Entertainment Inc. is allowing free downloads of MP3
songs from Dionne Warwick and The Band with Eric Clapton.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Officer Steve Devick said he believes MP3s can
be as important a promotional tool for the music industry as radio
was in the early days of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly what the consumer wants to do,'' Devick said.
``If the public is given a choice, I don't think they want to
violate the law or rip-off artists. But you create piracy when you
don't give people enough alternatives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
