<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEARS-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEAK SALES SEND SEARS SHARES DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. fell as much as 7 percent
Wednesday, after the nation's largest department store retailer
said weak apparel sales hurt revenues in November, and could result
in lower-than-expected earnings for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts cautioned that the slump in
clothing sales _ especially outerwear, due to recent warm
temperatures _ could hurt other major department store retailers as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pain that Sears is feeling will be inflicted on other
competitors,'' said Richard Church, an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Sears said total domestic store revenue declined 4.5 percent in
November, to $2.61 billion, compared with revenues a year ago of
$2.73 billion. Same-store sales slid 3.6 percent, compared with a
0.6 percent decrease last year.
</P>
<P>
   Total revenues for the four-week period ending last Saturday
were $3.49 billion, down 3.2 percent compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
   The news, delivered by the chairman and chief executive, Arthur
Martinez, at an analysts conference sponsored by Lehman Brothers in
Boca Raton, Fla., came one day before most retailers are scheduled
to report November sales. Analysts quickly lowered earnings
estimates for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts of fourth-quarter earnings declined 8 percent, to an
average of $1.48 a share; earnings for the year fell 3 percent, to
an average of $3.33, according to First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said the company now expected earnings to increase at a
low single-digit percentage rate in 1998, compared with an earlier
forecast of a mid-single-digit increase. Earnings last year were
$3.27 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Sears stock closed at $43, down $1.5625. The stock had lost
about 33 percent of its value this year. Shares of other major
department stores also fell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
