<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-GORE-2000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TRIES A 2000 THEME: `PRACTICAL IDEALISM' 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday offered up his
vision of the Democratic Party of the future, saying it should aim
for a ``practical idealism'' that leans neither left nor right but
moves forward and upward.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, testing a theme for his all-but-declared
presidential candidacy, contrasted it with the ``compassionate
conservatism'' coined by Gov. George W. Bush, the Texas Republican
who is a potential rival for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke here at a meeting of the Democratic Leadership
Council, a 13-year-old organization devoted to appealing to
moderate voters in the vast middle of American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton's address to the same group in 1991 unofficially
opened his presidential candidacy, a bit of history that converted
Wednesday's meeting into a staging ground for a handful of Gore's
potential Democratic rivals, all of whom are courting the moderate
middle.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's ``practical idealism,'' a slogan he set forth Wednesday
for the first time, is based on his notion of navigating between
the political poles of the past _ labor vs. management, for
instance _ and rejecting ``false choices'' like that between
protecting the environment and fostering development.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, it is not much different from the ``third way''
that Clinton has advocated for the last six years. The difference
is in emphasis: Gore's platform relies heavily on technology as a
tool for education, helping people take care of their elderly
parents, protecting consumer privacy, containing suburban sprawl
and reducing the traffic jams that induce road rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six years ago,'' Gore said of the onset of the Clinton
administration, ``we moved politics forward, beyond right and left.
Today let us move politics not only farther forward but also
upward, to a higher place, to a place far beyond the false
divisions and dichotomies of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   With virtually no philosophical differences separating him from
the president, Gore seemed intent Wednesday on contrasting himself
with the Texas governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between using the rhetoric of the center
and actually governing from the center,'' Gore said. He said that
being compassionate meant saving Social Security before cutting
taxes, opposing school vouchers, rejecting the agenda of the gun
lobby and allowing women to decide for themselves whether to have
an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   With the vice president given the prime speaking role at the
meeting, other potential candidates were left to counter his
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the House Democratic leader,
staked out a kind of reality-based position in contrast to Gore's
somewhat abstract discussion. Gephardt called the Democrats the
party of ``kitchen-table, everyday issues,'' fairness and
opportunity, and called for an overhaul of the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   Getting wind of Gore's ``practical idealism,'' Sen. Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska said, ``Practicality is where America just begins to
dream, not where we wake up and say, `That's the best we can do.'
''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, who has signaled that he
would make education the centerpiece of any presidential campaign,
faulted both parties for failing to improve the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was held against a backdrop of word that the party
would be looking for a new national chairman. Steve Grossman
resigned from the post Wednesday, citing personal reasons. He said
his father was ill and needed him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
