<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      12-02 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS TO FACE HOUSE REPUBLICANS AT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-CONSERVATIVE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to call attention to what they consider
Republican bungling, White House lawyers said on Wednesday that
they would defend President Clinton before the House Judiciary
Committee next week. But they demanded a raft of information in
advance to cope with what they called a ``dramatically expanded''
impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that they needed a little more time and a lot
more information to prepare their defense, even as Republicans
signaled on Wednesday night that they might limit the investigation
after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain that the scope of the defense must equal the scope
of the inquiry,'' the lawyers wrote in a letter on Wednesday
evening to Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, who as chairman of the
Judiciary Committee is leading the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides have argued that Republican efforts to broaden
the inquiry into possible campaign finance abuses and other matters
will make it appear scatter-shot and partisan. On Wednesday night,
the White House appeared to be going a step further and seizing on
the proposed expansion as a lever to pry out information
potentially damaging to the Republicans' case and to Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They bring things out of nowhere and put them on the table,
we're prepared to engage with them,'' said one senior White House
official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The demands came as the public tone of the White House toward
the inquiry softened somewhat, from the outright derision unleashed
Tuesday to a sort of baffled condescension.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are politics at play here,'' Joe Lockhart, the White
House press secretary, said of the committee's doings, ``but we're
not smart enough to figure out what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the lawyers wrote that their defense ``may
include calling witnesses with respect to any or all of the matters
being considered by the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House continued on Wednesday to insist that it wants
the impeachment inquiry resolved as soon as possible, and exhausted
officials are clearly eager to get it over with.
</P>
<P>
   But no one in the White House wants to risk losing an
impeachment vote, and aides acknowledged that they may have a
better chance of prevailing in the next Congress, when the
Republican majority will be slimmer.
</P>
<P>
   One senior White House aide said that delay could also be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has changed so quickly and so unpredictably who
knows what happens next year,'' this adviser said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``I'm not able to articulate an advantage
beyond pure numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the lawyers demanded to review information
in three areas: Evidence relating to Starr's impeachment referral
to Congress; evidence relating to Kathleen Willey, a former White
House volunteer who has accused Clinton of making a sexual advance
toward her; and evidence related to campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   Among other specific items, they requested any decisions by a
federal judge about whether prosecutors denied Monica Lewinsky
access to a lawyer when they first surprised her with accusations
of an affair with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said that they would need only 48 hours to review
the information, which, they said, the committee already possessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we have reviewed this material, we will be prepared to
present a vigorous defense of the president,'' the lawyers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which was approved by Clinton before its release,
was signed by Charles F.C. Ruff, the White House counsel, and
Gregory Craig, the special White House counsel who is coordinating
Clinton's defense.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also requested their first meeting with Hyde, ``to
discuss how best to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton continued to present himself on Wednesday as removed
from the wrangling over his political fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you know, I have a group of lawyers handling that,'' he
said in response to a reporter's question. ``But the Congress in
the end has to make its own decisions about what it will do and how
it will conduct itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking while seated in the Oval Office beside the Pakistani
prime minister, Nawaz Sharif, Clinton added, ``It's important for
me to get on with the work of the country and that's what I'm doing
here here and that's what I intend to continue to do.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
