12-02 -- Jeannie Ralston, at her home in the Texas Hill Country,
reads to her son, Gus. Ralston's satellite service was cut off
because her provider was adhearing to a law passed by Congress in
1988 stipulating that a house was not allowed to receive network
programs through a satellite dish unless it was ``unserved,'' which
means that it is not able to get an acceptable picture from local
affiliates via antenna. (Mathew Sturtevant/New York Times Photo)
</P>
