Dimitri Philemonof, president and chief executive officer of the
Aleut Tribal Group, is given a prehistoric wooden mask by Anne
Bleecker Corcos that she purchased to return to the Aleut on
Wednesday. The twice-a-year sale of American Indian art at
Sotheby's didn't go as planned as 19 of the objects being auctioned
were withdrawn by the auction house or the consignors for legal
reasons. Other items were purchased by buyers who returned the
artifacts to representatives of the respective tribes. (Ozier
Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) TOUL DANGKOR, Cambodia -- Dec. 2, 1998 --
CAMBODIA-POVERTY, 12-02 -- Women break rocks in Toul Dangkor, some
50 miles north of the Cambodian capital of Phnom Penh, where the
economy is based entirely on chipping rocks to sell. The more
skilled use a chisel to fashion grinding stones for rice flour.
Others, particularly the children and the elderly, hammer small
stones into smaller ones to be sold as paving material. (Seth
Mydans/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
