<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Dec. 2, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 12-02
-- Today most bathroom sinks have pop-up stoppers instead of the
old-fashioned rubber plugs. Generally pop-up stoppers work well,
but over time they may become clogged with hair or other debris and
fall out of alignment. Then they may not open or close properly.
Fortunately, these stoppers are easy to repair. The tools required
are simple ones, usually only a screwdriver and a pair of pliers.
(Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) *LITE
</P>
