A0025 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS &LR;      12-02 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-ESCAPE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY OPPONENTS PROTEST CONDITIONS FORCED UPON PRISONERS
AFTER INMATE'S ESCAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC BERGER 
and ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As escaped death row inmate Martin Gurule evaded authorities for
a sixth day, death-penalty opponents and other activists gathered
to protest conditions forced upon the prisoners remaining at the
Ellis Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters said prison officials have refused to allow
inmates to meet with anyone since the breakout, and raised the
possibility that guards are exacting retribution on the remaining
prisoners for Gurule's successful breakout.
</P>
<P>
   Gurule, of Corpus Christi, was among seven condemned killers who
tried to break out of the prison late Thanksgiving night. The other
six, under fire from guards, surrendered before reaching the
prison's fences.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's protest, the sister of one of the six, Eric
Dewayne Cathey, said she was glad Gurule escaped and wished that
her brother had gotten away also.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell the truth I feel bad, really, that Eric didn't get
away,'' said Shelicia Baker. ``If it was me I would have done the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker and her mother, Willie Cathey, said they were also
concerned because they do not know if Cathey was shot during the
escape attempt or otherwise injured.
</P>
<P>
   That no one from outside the prison has seen the inmates, say
death penalty opponents, raises the question of whether they have
been mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of such a major escape _ it has been more than six
decades since a Texas death row inmate last escaped _ members of
the Texas Coalition to Abolish the Death Penalty said prison
guards, flustered over their inability to capture Gurule, were
probably ``interrogating'' the prisoners left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of whether these six men are being
brutalized, it's a question of how much,'' said Dan Wirt, a Houston
physician who called for doctors not employed by the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice to be allowed to examine the
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Rubac, a coalition member, said all inmates at the Ellis
prison _ not just the six escapees and about 440 other death-row
inmates _ have been under ``lockdown'' conditions since Gurule's
escape.
</P>
<P>
   According to a memo allegedly passed out by prison officials
after the escape _ and mailed to the activists by an inmate _
prisoners will not be allowed visitors or any recreation time out
of their cells until at least next week.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials, who could not be reached for comment after
Wednesday evening's protest, have said little about the inmates
remaining at Ellis other than that they are being closely watched.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities continued searching for Gurule near
Huntsville on Wednesday, employing ``low-pressure'' techniques they
hope will make him overconfident and blunder into being captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of applying constant pressure, we'll be applying
random pressure. We want to confuse the inmate,'' said prison
spokesman Glen Castlebury. ``Where we once ran the dogs almost
constantly, we'll now use them on a random basis. Now he doesn't
know when they'll be running.''
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the change of strategy earlier this week, Wayne
Scott, Texas Department of Criminal Justice executive director,
reiterated his agency's belief that the 29-year-old escapee likely
remains in the 17,000 acres of prison property that surround death
row near Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Scott spoke of Gurule's ``resolve'' to remain motionless and
avoid officers and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   While as many as 500 officers are still engaged in the search,
and more state personnel are being requested, prison authorities
now believe their best chance of finding Gurule a Texas National
Guard helicopter equipped with sensitive heat-detecting equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft's forward-facing, thermal-imaging unit can
distinguish between humans, livestock and other animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can even detect a dead body,'' prison spokesman Larry Todd
said, ``provided that decomposition has reached a stage that some
heat is generated.''
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter took to the air Tuesday, but was grounded later
by dense fog. Another prison spokesman, Larry Fitzgerald, said
Wednesday that a similarly equipped U.S. Coast Guard helicopter
also will join the search.
</P>
<P>
   Castlebury noted that the agency's belief that Gurule remains in
the Huntsville area is based on police intelligence gathered from
around the state. Castlebury declined to comment on specifics of
the larger investigation, but police have grilled Gurule's family,
friends and acquaintances for leads concerning his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Prison authorities routinely try to capture fugitives within
three hours of their escape and within three miles of the prison,
Castlebury said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we don't consider this situation frustrating. It's just
our job,'' he said. ``I wish this were a six-day job, or a
seven-day job. But even if it takes two months, we will get the job
done.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2152EST &QL; 
