A0026 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-PHARMACEUTICAL     12-02 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-PHARMACEUTICALS-MERGE-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH DRUG MAKERS TO COMBINE IN $10.4 BILLION STOCK DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two French drug makers, Sanofi SA and Synthelabo SA, agreed
Wednesday to merge in a deal valued at $10.4 billion, the second
alliance between two European pharmaceutical companies announced
this week.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, Sanofi-Synthelabo, will have $6.3 billion in
annual sales _ about one-fourth those of Merck &AMP; Co., the world's
largest drug maker _ and will have considerable product strength in
the industry. While analysts were largely unimpressed by the
partial merger between Rhone-Poulenc SA and Hoechst AG that was
announced on Tuesday, the union of Sanofi and Synthelabo won
considerable praise.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that a big difference between the deals was the
sales potential of the companies' products. Aventis, the company
created by Hoechst and Rhone-Poulenc, will be largely saddled with
old drugs, while Sanofi-Synthelabo will have two cardiovascular
drugs _ Plavix and Avapro _ that could each produce $1 billion in
annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two drugs should be big sellers for Sanofi-Synthelabo,''
said Tom Brakel, an analyst with Mehta Partners, a
biopharmaceutical investment research concern in New York.
``Neither company has a lot of history with cost cutting. There is
a lot of duplication in some areas they are in, so there could be
some substantial savings here.''
</P>
<P>
   As with Aventis, investors fled both stocks involved in the
deal. Analysts thought most investors merely wanted to take profits
after merger speculation had lifted both stocks about 18 percent in
the last two months. Sanofi fell 7 percent, and Synthelabo dropped
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will be a stock swap, with Sanofi offering 13 of its
shares for every 10 Synthelabo shares. The oil giant Elf Aquitaine,
which has a controlling interest in Sanofi, and the cosmetics maker
L'Oreal, which controls Synthelabo, will retain big holdings in
Sanofi-Synthelabo. Elf Aquitaine will control 35.1 percent of the
shares and 45 percent of the voting rights, while L'Oreal will have
a 19.4 percent stake and 25 percent voting control.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding at least one possible pitfall, the chief executives
have agreed to different roles in the new company. Jean-Francois
Dehecq, Sanofi's chief executive, will become chairman of the
combined company, while Herve Guerin, Synthelabo's chief executive,
will be vice chairman. Three megamergers announced in the drug
industry failed this year when the chairmen refused to yield power
to their counterparts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Analysts have been impressed with Dehecq's ability to focus
Sanofi, which also has holdings in perfume and beauty and
diagnostic kits, more on pharmaceuticals, especially on high-profit
cardiovascular drugs. While companies more than twice Sanofi's size
were struggling to develop top-selling compounds, Dehecq and his
staff engineered two potential big sellers, a feat crucial to
keeping pace with the industry's 16 percent annual earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   The merged entity should be able to squeeze more profit from
pharmaceuticals, analysts said. Both companies are regarded by
analysts as having shrewd research staffs, and the combined revenue
of both companies will allow Sanofi-Synthelabo to spend more on
research and development. Sanofi spent only $577 million last year
on pharmaceutical research, about half of what most large drug
companies spend.
</P>
<P>
   Dehecq has already signaled that Sanofi-Synthelabo will be more
dedicated to the pharmaceutical market than Sanofi has been in the
past. Sanofi announced Wednesday that it would sell its beauty
division, which includes Yves Saint Laurent and Oscar de la Renta
scents. The company did not disclose a timetable or price.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Sanofi-Synthelabo should have several top-selling
drugs, the company will have its share of troubles, including a
weak presence in the United States. Synthelabo has just one small
joint venture here, and though Dehecq has expanded Sanofi's U.S.
presence in recent years with acquisitions and joint ventures, the
company is still small compared with giants such as Merck and
Pfizer Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
