<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-NEEDS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URBAN AGENDA EMPHASIZES SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GROMER JEFFERS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Black civic leaders at a national summit
Tuesday in Kansas City stressed the need for better urban schools
and better opportunities for minority-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The summit, sponsored by the National Black Caucus of Local
Elected Officials, took place in conjunction with this week's
National League of Cities annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus intends to develop an ``urban platform'' by the end
of the week to present to national leaders. And education is
expected to be a key issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get people to move to your city if you don't have a
good education system,'' said John Saunders, executive director of
the National Forum for Black Public Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said that with good urban schools, minorities could be
trained to operate their own businesses in their own communities. A
well-educated, self-reliant urban community would ease some of the
disadvantages of central-city life, such as poverty and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to bring it (entrepreneurship) back to our own
communities,'' Saunders said.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Williams, president of the Joint Center for Political and
Economic Studies, said cities needed more federal empowerment zones
to spur economic development. Williams also suggested that black
businesses receive more assistance from local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Bell, president of the National Association of Black County
Officials, said urban areas had high rates of juvenile
incarceration. She called for more family-based programs to combat
substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Bell said that substance-abuse prevention programs like as DARE
(Drug Abuse Resistance Education) don't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pay attention to what works, not what sells,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar Eason Jr., president of Blacks in Government, said that
political attacks on affirmative-action laws in Washington, D.C.,
and California were making it difficult for minorities to get
better educations and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick in certain areas now is to maintain diversity
without using race-based recruitment,'' Eason said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But how can employers and contracting officials grant minority
job applicants and contractors documented opportunities without
being able to specify who is to be assisted?...To affirmatively
recruit minorities in Washington and California is to violate the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   William Spriggs, director of research and policy for the
National Urban League, said an economic policy that benefited
minorities was needed, although blacks were faring better today
than during the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have a proper economic policy in place,'' Spriggs
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
