<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      12-02 1160
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIARY COMMITTEEC PULLS BACK FROM PLAN TO WIDEN INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee, under fire on many
fronts for abruptly expanding the impeachment inquiry, quickly
began to pull back Wednesday night after the panel gained limited
access to secret FBI and Justice Department documents that detail
alleged fund-raising abuses in President Clinton's 1996 reelection
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours after impeachment, investigators reviewed the
documents, the Judiciary Committee staff alerted members that it is
unlikely to serve subpoenas that the panel had approved the day
before to compel testimony from the FBI director, Louis J. Freeh,
and a former top Justice Department official.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the committee's Republican majority informed members
that all other depositions of potential witnesses are on hold and
likely to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   That could remove the final obstacles to the committee debating
and voting next week on GOP proposals for as many as three or more
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In another sign that the committee is prepared to wrap up the
expanded inquiry, the panel last night tentatively scheduled final
presentations by Clinton's lawyers and committee investigators next
Tuesday and Wednesday, with debate and votes to follow Thursday
through Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Committee sources said the moves indicate investigators who
reviewed the Justice Department documents Wednesday uncovered no
substantial evidence of impeachable offenses that would warrant a
protracted investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The subpoenas for Freeh and Charles G. LaBella, the former chief
of the Justice Department's campaign finance task force, directly
related to the fund-raising inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry J. Hyde, had no
immediate comment on the contents of the documents, which included
recommendations from Freeh and LaBella that Attorney General Janet
Reno seek an independent counsel to investigate Clinton's 1996
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel's highest ranking Democrat, Representative John
Conyers Jr. of Michigan, said, ``Democratic counsel has thoroughly
examined the memoranda in question and has advised me that nothing
in these documents is in any way relevant to this committee's
consideration of possible impeachable offenses by the president. We
trust that this closes a short and unproductive chapter in the
history of this very strange proceeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's likely withdrawal of the committee's other subpoenas
_ for Clinton's lawyer, Robert S. Bennett, and close adviser, Bruce
R. Lindsey _ also indicates the panel sees no merit in further
pursuing an allegation by former White House volunteer Kathleen
Willey that Clinton groped her near the Oval Office in 1993,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment case, by most accounts, is expected to end where
it began, with the committee focusing on allegations by the
independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   He charged that Clinton may have committed perjury, witness
tampering, obstruction of justice, and abuse of his office in
trying to conceal his sexual relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Representative W. Asa Hutchinson, an Arkansas Republican who
serves on the Judiciary Committee, defended the panel's search for
evidence of fund-raising crimes, saying it would be irresponsible
not to pursue a lead that investigators had received on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it most likely won't go anywhere,'' Hutchinson said.
``What we should concentrate on is the referral we received, and
the allegations of perjury and obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The day before, Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, had blasted
the Judiciary Committee as being ``hijacked by extremists.'' But
the White House last night informed the panel that Clinton's
lawyers ``will of course accept your invitation to appear before
the committee and to present a defense on behalf of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde had set Wednesday as a deadline for Clinton's legal defense
team to request an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton lawyers issued several conditional requests for
their appearance, including gaining access to all the material the
committee has received or reviewed since expanding the inquiry
beyond the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is plain that the scope of the defense must equal the scope
of the inquiry,'' wrote White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff and
special counsel Gregory B. Craig. ``Once we have reviewed the
material, we will be prepared to present a vigorous defense of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   The moves to apparently rein in the burgeoning inquiry came
after US District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson struck a compromise
between the Judiciary Committee, which had subpoenaed the
confidential Justice Department documents, and Reno, who said the
material included secret grand jury information that would be
illegal to unseal.
</P>
<P>
   But the developments also followed increasing attacks on the
committee, even from within Republican ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Among those blasting the panel's GOP lawmakers for expanding the
inquiry was Representative Christopher Shays of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let this out of the box, but we don't know how to get it
back in, and it has blown up in our face,'' Shays said in an
interview. ``The republic is suffering, not just the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the FBI and Justice Department documents, Johnson
permitted two Judiciary Committee investigators _ one each for
Republicans and Democrats _ to read them and report their findings
to Hyde and Conyers. The investigators were not allowed to copy the
documents or take notes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a potentially key player in the impeachment saga, the
House Rules Committee chairman, Gerald B. Solomon of New York, said
through a spokesman, Mike Powers, that the outgoing speaker, Newt
Gingrich, has told him he does not plan to play a leadership role
in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is ``interested, but he's not engaged,'' Solomon said
through Powers. ``He's left it to the incoming leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   The speaker-designate, Robert L. Livingston of Louisiana, has
said he plans to steer clear of the impeachment fray until the
Judiciary Committee completes its business.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon also left open the possibility that the Rules Committee
would permit the full House to vote on a censure, even if the
Judiciary Committee blocks such a move, as Hyde has said he is
likely to do.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Newton Democrat, said Solomon's
possible willingness to approve a censure resolution indicated that
some GOP leaders may be maneuvering for an alternative because
polls show that the public opposes Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense may be somewhat reasserting itself,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Powers, Solomon's spokesman, said the possible willingness to
consider a censure proposal ``is in no way a Solomon prescription''
to resolve the impeachment issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
