<HEADER>
A0064 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMICS-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      12-02 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMICS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PROBLEM? PEOPLE, NOT CAPITALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   The proliferation of global economic
problems is fueling a misguided backlash of blame directed toward
free markets and free enterprise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When liberal economists and media analysts assess the woe
betiding Asia, Russia and Latin America and ponder the reckless
blunders of high-octane hedge funds, they seem eager to conclude
that all this trouble is evidence of market failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Research Center's MediaNomics report recently cited as
an example of the phenomenon a Time magazine article calling ``an
unfettered global market a dangerous gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with such perspectives, MediaNomics said, is that
viewing the global market as ``unfettered'' is a misperception.
Most, if not all, of the worst problems besetting troubled
economies is that they have been messed up more by political
manipulation than by adherence to market principles.
</P>
<P>
   Nobel laureate economist Milton Friedman made the same point in
The New York Times recently when challenged by a columnist to
explain the apparent widespread failure of market economics.
Friedman said most problems were not due to market failure but
rather the result of bad government policy and bad advice from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always a tendency when things go wrong to blame the
private market,'' said this generation's staunchest advocate of
free enterprise. ``Given that we've had these difficulties, there's
no doubt we'll have some backsliding'' on the road to what's an
inexorable movement toward greater individual freedom and less
government influence on economies.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert A. Sirico, president of the Action Institute for
the Study of Religion and Liberty, characterized editorial
criticism of markets as ``flawed economic analysis (with) a
generous dollop of redistributionist ethics'' in an essay for The
Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   What is happening, he said, ``is not institutional failure, but
human failure.'' What's needed, Sirico asserted, is more market
discipline from the system known as ``profit and loss.'' Much of
the world's woe, he said, is the result of audacious gambles taken
by those expecting friends in high places to bail them out if
investments go sour.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing wrong with the market economy that an
enhancement of market signaling cannot correct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most interesting aspect of the left-liberal's
resurgent criticism of market economics is the absence of
alternative proposals. If free enterprise capitalism is inadequate
to meet human economic needs, what's the answer? Communism?
Socialism? Fascism? Syndicalism? Corporatism?
</P>
<P>
   All have been tried and found not only inadequate but, at their
worst, destructive. Why? People usually act in their self-interest,
whether they're crafting government policy or seeking their fortune
in the marketplace. When self-interested officials gain power to
impose their will on others, this power corrupts them _ sometimes
to the point of homicidal megalomania.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, Friedman said, is that the champions of
individual liberty are winning. Their greatest weapon in the fight
to shrink government power, he predicts, will be the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it harder to collect taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
