<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU SAY GRINCH IN SPANISH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They left from Parker, Ariz., in three vans on a trip to buy
Christmas presents for the kids in the Colorado River Indian Tribes
Head Start program.
</P>
<P>
   It was the day after Thanksgiving and the Wal-Mart in Calexico,
on the California-Mexico border, was having a big sale.
</P>
<P>
   Their plan was to buy the Christmas presents, then cross into
Mexicali to pick up some fabric and costumes for children in a Head
Start dance group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all went pretty much the way we figured,'' said Head Start
volunteer Lola Westfall. ``At least until we crossed the border,''
when their Christmas fairy tale turned into a horror story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true,'' said Caroline Constabile, the Head Start
program's director. ``Our volunteers ran into the Grinch down
there. A whole bunch of them.''
</P>
<P>
   They appeared in the form of Mexican border guards, and before
the day was out, the Head Start toys had been confiscated and the
volunteers were stuck with a very un-Seuss-like fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a painful thing to go through,'' Lola said.
</P>
<P>
   She had never been to Mexico before. She volunteers at Head
Start almost every day, and has been a foster parent for nearly 20
years. In that time, she's cared for 18 children, most of them on a
long-term basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most wonderful life you could imagine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The group traveled caravan-style. Lola was third in line. After
several hours in the Wal-Mart, they'd piled her van high with
everything from dolls and action figures to bicycles. The other two
vehicles were driven by women with relatives in Mexico. They'd
crossed the border dozens of times over the years. Lola followed
them, hauling $700 worth of toys.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us had any idea we were breaking the law,'' Lola said.
</P>
<P>
   But, they were.
</P>
<P>
   In border towns, Mexican law sets a limit of $50 per person, per
day on merchandise you can take into the country. Anything above
that carries a stiff tax.
</P>
<P>
   The van Lola was driving was picked by guards for a random
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see any signs or anything like that,'' Lola said.
``The guards pulled me over and said, `You're breaking the law.' I
said, `I'm sorry. I didn't know. I'll just go back across.' But
they said no.''
</P>
<P>
   Lola's group had used a traffic lane reserved for those claiming
to have nothing of value to declare. As far as Mexican border
agents were concerned, the Head Start ladies were smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men knew our people weren't trying to do anything
illegal,'' said Constabile, the Head Start program director. ``They
could have been understanding. They could have let them go.''
</P>
<P>
   They didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the Mexican officers I didn't want to leave that
vehicle,'' Lola said. ``So, I went from office to office while they
did `paperwork.' I ended up there about 13 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Lola was told the van would be returned to her if
she paid a $650 fine. She and her friends maxed out their ATM cards
and got the vehicle back.
</P>
<P>
   Empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last person we talked to was a lawyer,'' Lola said. `'He
told us the law said the goods would be confiscated. So, they kept
our toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Constabile told me she's spoken with representatives of the
American consulate, the Mexican consulate, the Border Patrol and
even members of Mexican-American chambers of commerce. With no
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Francie Noyes, press secretary for Gov. Jane Hull, said, ``We
are a border state, and people are comfortable going back and
forth. But you are crossing the border into a foreign country and
their rules are very different.''
</P>
<P>
   An assistant to the Mexican Consul-General in Phoenix told me
essentially the same thing. She said the $650 fine most likely was
sent to ``fiscal officials'' in Mexico. She did say she'd look into
trying to get the toys back, but she wasn't overly optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers at Head Start had collected the money for the toys
during a Halloween carnival. No tax dollars were involved. The
federally-subsidized program serves 183 low-income children around
Parker, both tribal members and others. They'd planned a Christmas
party for Dec. 16, the day before the children's classes end for
the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa was supposed to come and give out the presents,'' said
Constabile, whose organization is scrambling to try to replace a
little of what they lost. ``It breaks my heart that something like
this has happened. I guess some border guards down there will be
having a nice Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday I called the library to ask if there was a Spanish
translation for Grinch. A researcher there told me what the women
from Head Start had learned that day in Mexicali.
</P>
<P>
   A Grinch is a Grinch in any language.
</P>
<P>
   E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at
ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
