<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO FRENCH DRUG MAKERS IN $10.4 BILLION MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Two French drug makers, Sanofi and Synthelabo, agreed to merge
for $10.4 billion, the second alliance between two European
pharmaceutical companies announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, Sanofi-Synthelabo, will have $6.3 billion in
annual sales _about one-fourth the size of Merck _ but will have
considerable product strength in the industry. While analysts
largely dismissed the partial merger between Rhone-Poulenc and
Hoechst on Tuesday, the union of Sanofi and Synthelabo won
considerable praise.
</P>
<P>
   GATES PROFESSES JAVA IGNORANCE
</P>
<P>
   In excerpts from a videotaped deposition played in federal
court, Bill Gates, chairman of Microsoft, professed general
ignorance of his company's legal battles with Sun Microsystems over
the Java computer language.
</P>
<P>
   Gates appeared at a luncheon in New York, serving up equal
measures of playful scorn for his prosecutors and rivals.
</P>
<P>
   3Com announced an $800 wireless version of its popular Palm
Pilot that offers limited Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   HEAD OF BMW'S ROVER UNIT RESIGNS
</P>
<P>
   Walter Haselkuss, chairman of Rover Group, a subsidiary of
Germany's BMW, stepped down, saying he felt ``quite strongly that
somebody has to be prepared to stand up and be counted'' for the
company's failure to make a profit. The British automaker also
disclosed proposals for job cuts, flexible working hours,
government aid and new investment intended to propel the company
into profitability.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING, SEARS LEAD STOCKS LOWER
</P>
<P>
   Stocks weakened after Boeing and Sears, Roebuck warned of lower
1999 profits, but the main gauges rebounded during the afternoon
and finished with losses of less than 1 percent. The Dow Jones
industrial average fell 69 points, to 9,064.54. The S&AMP;P 500 fell
4.03 points, to 1,171.25, and Nasdaq fell 8.54 points, to 1,995.21.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Sears, Roebuck fell as much as 7 percent after the
nation's largest department store retailer said weak apparel sales
hurt revenue in November and could result in lower-than-expected
earnings for the year. Several Wall Street analysts cautioned that
the slump in clothing sales could hurt other major department store
retailers as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission approved rules to give
small investors access to the best available stock quotes on
electronic trading networks.
</P>
<P>
   SALES OF NEW HOMES REMAIN SOLID
</P>
<P>
   Americans snapped up new homes rapidly in October, keeping sales
on course for a very strong year and highlighting the resilience of
the U.S. economy. Sales of single-family homes rose eight-tenths of
a percent, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 851,000 units,
the Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   REQUIRED SOCIAL SECURITY READING
</P>
<P>
   When the Clinton administration begins a two-day conference next
week at the White House on fixing Social Security, the most radical
option on the table will be the one that would allow individuals to
deposit part of their payroll taxes into private retirement
accounts. The issues are complex, but conference participants might
do well if they first read a lucid study by an expert panel of the
National Academy of Social Insurance, a nonpartisan research group.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP MORRIS TO BATTLE SMOKING
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to be the most elaborate and costly effort of
its kind by a tobacco company, Philip Morris USA, the nation's
largest cigarette maker, plans to spend at least $100 million a
year to discourage children and teen-agers from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   CATHAY PACIFIC PULLS OUT OF TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Cathay Pacific Airways has pulled out of talks to buy a stake in
the ailing Philippine Airlines, making the uncertain future at
Philippine Airlines even cloudier.
</P>
</TEXT>
