<HEADLINE>
JOHN WAYNE'S LAST RANCH IS FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL SOWERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thirty years ago, John Wayne, America's hero, climbed atop a
rise overlooking the handsome Santa Cruz Valley in Arizona near the
Mexican border and envisioned building a huge compound for his
family there.
</P>
<P>
   The 4,200-foot rise, known as Duke's Hill, is the highest point
of Wayne's 670-acre spread of Sonoran Desert, just six miles from
Nogales, Sonora, one of the actor's favorite haunts.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne died in 1979 before he could start building on his
100-acre hill. His partner and longtime friend, Ralph Wingfield,
89, said the scenic land was never developed because ``John got
sick and I got too damned old.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the spread, adjacent to the Nogales International Airport,
is for sale for $2.3 million, put on the market in October by the
actor's sons, Michael and Ethan.
</P>
<P>
   When the ranch sells, it will be the last of the Wayne land
legacy in Arizona, which served as the landscape for some of the
actor's he-man movies.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne's ranch near Springerville is now owned by the Hopi Tribe.
Another of his spreads near Casa Grande is in a trust, and once was
the proposed site of a war museum.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Perna, a Scottsdale Realtor specializing in luxury
properties, is handling the latest sale, which has prompted stories
in the ``Wall Street Journal'' and a two-page spread in the
``duPont Registry,'' a national real estate publication featuring
upscale properties.
</P>
<P>
   Development at neighboring Kino Springs golf community _ once a
working ranch belonging to Wayne friends, actors Stewart Granger
and Jean Simmons _ prompted the Wayne brothers to sell the
property, Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Wayne died, the impetus to build the compound was
lost,'' Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   A prospective buyer from Denver is coming this month, and if
he's amenable, Perna will take him through the property on
horseback, and let him climb up Duke's Hill for a glimpse of the
cottonwoods lining the Santa Cruz River on the southern edge of the
property.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by $5 million working ranches, the Wayne land could
morph into a development of single-family homes, or a resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see lots of opportunities,'' Perna said.
</P>
<P>
   So did Wayne, said longtime friend Wingfield, a Tubac rancher,
who often talked with the actor about building a home for his
family in the high desert near Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wingfield supplied the cattle for Wayne's 1948 movie, ``Red
River,'' and later for his 1962 movie, ``McLintock,''filmed near
Nogales.
</P>
<P>
   Wingfield recalled a fishing trip to the Mediterranean with
Wayne, and said the actor frequently stayed at his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became good friends,'' Wingfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wayne, a movie producer, told the ``duPont Registry''
that his father was fascinated by southern Arizona and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The actor thought ``it was great down there,'' Michael told the
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, he said his father flew his jet to the Nogales
airport from the family home in Newport Beach, Calif., and talked
about building a hangar on the property so he could taxi to the
compound.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Mexico, Michael said, his father drank a special kind of
tequila, savored the Mexican food, and ``loved the Latin ladies.'' &QL; 
Carol Sowers can be reached at 444-7482 or at
carol.sowers(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
