<HEADER>
A0082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      12-02 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Germany: Change Urged for E.U.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said new members should be
admitted to the European Union only if Germany's financial
contributions to the 15-nation group were reduced. Germany, the
largest net contributor, has long lobbied for reform of the EU's
finances.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland: Blair Returns to Belfast
</P>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Prime Minister Tony Blair of Britain flew to Belfast
for the second time in a week to meet with political leaders in an
effort to break the deadlock in the peace effort. Catholic and
Protestant parties are feuding over the makeup of the new
legislature's executive office and the responsibilities to be given
new cross-border councils with the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia: Protesters March on Palace
</P>
<P>
   JAKARTA _ Ignoring an appeal by President B.J. Habibie to stay
off the streets, about 1,000 students marched on the Presidential
Palace to present a petition demanding democratic reforms. Student
protesters have kept an almost daily vigil in central Jakarta since
November 13, when soldiers fired on students, triggering
confrontations that left 16 dead.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   Libya: Annan to Press for Trial
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan will go to Libya this weekend
to discuss with Moammar Gadhafi the impasse over a trial for two
Libyans suspected of bombing Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in December 1988. Without an assurance of success, the
trip could be politically risky for Annan, since Libya is under
U.N. sanctions for refusing to hand over the suspects for trial in
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Minimum Wage Increased
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A government panel boosted Mexico's three-tiered
minimum wage by 14 percent. The increase, which raises the daily
minimum wage to as high as $3.50, was supported by representatives
of President Ernesto Zedillo and the business sector. But because
the increase is below the 16 percent inflation rate, labor's
representative voted against it.
</P>
</TEXT>
