<HEADLINE>
NBA AND PLAYERS TO MEET THURSDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the season continues to slip away, National
Basketball Association players and owners will meet Thursday in
Manhattan for the first time in 13 days to try to end the
five-month-old lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're beyond the part of being frustrated,'' said
Michael Curry, a member of the union's negotiating committee.
</P>
<P>
   Having set an unofficial mid-December deadline for striking a
deal and having tested the union's resolve for the past month _ a
period in which more than 200 players did not receive two paychecks
_ the owners may have a renewed urgency in talking.
</P>
<P>
   The union is feeling the pressure, too. The union's executive
director, Billy Hunter, has had his work questioned by Isiah
Thomas, a former union leader. Phil Jackson said Wednesday he had
reservations about the players' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about the representation on the players
side,'' Jackson said from his home in Chicago. ``I've talked to
some players who are not your $10 million and $20 million players _
that do not feel like they have enough power to speak out because
they don't have the clout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
