<HEADLINE>
COUPLES WILL BE BACK FOR MORE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; Fred Couples will defend his title at the Bob Hope Chrysler
Classic when the Southern California swing of the 1999 PGA Tour
gets under way next month in Palm Desert.
</P>
<P>
   The five-round competition, which runs Jan. 20-24, will be
played this year at Bermuda Dunes Country Club, Indian Wells CC,
Tamarisk CC and the Arnold Palmer Private Course at PGA West. The
Palmer course hosts the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Couples, the PGA Player of the Year in 1991 and '92, has had to
deal with the loss of both parents to cancer in recent years but
rebounded this year to set a personal record for earnings with
$1,650,389.
</P>
<P>
   He edged Bruce Lietzke in a playoff for the Hope title in
January, won the Memorial in May and led the Masters until the
final holes before finishing second to eventual Player of the Year
Mark O'Meara.
</P>
<P>
   As usual in the popular Hope format, pros will be paired with
celebrities for the first four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour arrives in Los Angeles the following month, when
Riviera Country Club resumes its role as host of the Feb. 15-21
Nissan Open _ hosted by Valencia Country Club last year when
Riviera hosted the U.S. Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Mayfair, who defeated Tiger Woods in a playoff to win at
Valencia, will return to defend his title in the Nissan, which has
boosted its purse to $2.8 million _ $504,000 for first place.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, managed by the Los Angeles Junior Chamber of
Commerce for a 73rd year, is the oldest civic-sponsored event on
the PGA Tour. Nissan has been affiliated since 1986 and been title
sponsor since '89.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; We are the champions: Forty-eight area golfers have earned
the right _ as club or affiliate champs _ to compete Monday in the
Southern California Golf Association's tournament of champions.
</P>
<P>
   The annual December competition will include 344 players this
year, divided by handicap into three flights for play at Yorba
Linda Country Club, Los Coyotes CC and Rolling Hills CC.
</P>
<P>
   This year's field includes Chatsworth's Tim Hogarth, a longtime
successful amateur player who won the U.S. Public Links title in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Other area players in this year's championship flight include
longtime Braemar CC champ Don Baker and Woodland Hills CC champ
Michael Turner, the former Cal State Northridge star who two years
ago became the fourth ex-Matador to win the 1997 L.A. City
championship.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Nissan Open discounts: The Nissan Open returns to Riviera
with a discount opportunity for early ticket-buyers and a chance to
help area charities. With a charity ticket package, the entire
amount of the ticket purchase goes to participating charities.
</P>
<P>
   A $300 charity package, which benefits the Boys and Girls Club
of the Santa Clarita Valley, includes two season tickets for all
practice and tournament rounds, 20 daily tickets valid any day and
one weekly parking pass. The price increases to $400 after Feb. 1.
Other packages are available for $500 (four season passes, 35 daily
tickets) and $700 (six season, 50 daily), those prices rising to
$675 and $900 after Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (800) 752-6736 or (213) 480-3232.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; More skins, please: The Senior Skins Game will be played
Jan. 30-31 at Mauna Lani, Hawaii, where notable participants Jack
Nicklaus, Arnold Palmer and Hale Irwin will try again to hold off
Raymond Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   History suggests it won't be easy. Floyd comes into this Super
Bowl Weekend, made-for-television event (ABC will cover) having won
the last five times.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd, the first player to win tournaments on the PGA Tour and
Senior PGA Tour in the same year, will be playing in his seventh
Senior Skins Game, having already won $1,820,000 in that
competition. Two or three more skins next month, and he will
surpass Palmer's career earnings ($1,861,857) on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his skinning prowess, this one might be tougher for
Floyd. No one in golf _ on any tour _ is hotter than Irwin, who
earned a all-tour record $2,861,945 this year while winning seven
times.
</P>
<P>
   In his past two senior seasons, Irwin has won 16 tournaments and
more than $5.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Names in the game: Aren Burd, Kirk Jensen, John Van Leeuwen
and Stuart von Wolffradt are the latest golfers to post aces on
hole-in-one heaven Scholl Canyon, which has had nearly a dozen in
the past few months. &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   J.T. Kohut, the Westlake High senior expected to be one of the
top prep golfers in the area next spring, advanced to the
semifinals of the American Junior Golf Association Polo Golf Junior
Classic in Florida last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
