<SLUG> BC-HUFFY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Huffy employers, community excited by talk of plant buy
 &HT;    By Scott Elliott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ While Huffy Corp. officials said the sale of its
closed Celina plant is not imminent, talk Wednesday of a possible
buyer generated optimism. Mercer County residents hope new jobs
could be on the way for 1,000 former Huffy workers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the plant closed in July, Mercer County's unemployment
rate tripled to almost 10 percent, Ohio's worst.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Huffy confirmed four suitors have expressed serious
interest in buying the Celina plant. Even so, officials cautioned
that a deal is not near.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not that close,'' said Paul Fisher, Huffy's assistant
treasurer. ``A number of interested parties have toured the
facility. We're going to be getting proposals from the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   The vacant 850,000-square-foot plant has an advertised asking
price of $8 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher would not identify the interested companies, but Crown
Equipment Corp., a New Bremen lift truck manufacturer, told
employees this week it had inquired about the Celina plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking with Huffy,'' said Rod Hinders, associate
general counsel for Crown. ``We put a bulletin out to our employees
to quell rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Stelzer, community development director for Mercer County,
said Huffy might have announced a deal this week with a
Philadelphia investment company that planned to rent portions of
the plant to several industrial users, but backed off when Crown
expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   Stelzer would not name the investment company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been a good deal, too,'' Stelzer said of the
Philadelphia group's offer. ``Everybody, Huffy included, is
interested in what is the best fit for the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinders said he did not know how Crown might use the Huffy plant
if it was purchased. Crown operates plants in Dayton, New
Knoxville, Greencastle, Ind., and Kinston, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Arnold, community development director for the city of
Celina, said a manufacturer would be ideal for the Huffy plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best case scenario would be to sell that facility to a
large industrial user,'' Arnold said. ``The use of the facility is
paramount.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials are cautiously optimistic that sale of the plant
could mean a significant job opportunities for former Huffy
workers, Arnold said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that makes us attractive is our available
workforce,'' she said. ``Skilled labor is hard to come by. With
Crown, we're hoping their intention is to create a new division or
make a new line here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
