A0253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-INSTITUTE03-COX     12-02 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-INSTITUTE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Glenn announces launch of Ohio State public service institute at
event
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The party for Sen. John Glenn's return to
Washington drew Vice President Al Gore and about 400 other guests
Wednesday night, and pulled Ohio State University into a bit of the
beltway glitz.
</P>
<P>
   Black-tied servers toted hors d'oeuvres and guests sipped
cocktails amid the spectacular and ingenious furnishings of the
main hall of the National Air and Space Museum.
</P>
<P>
   At center stage was, of course, the Friendship 7 Mercury capsule
that Glenn flew into history as the first American to orbit the
Earth in 1962. Suspended above it, the 1903 Wright Flyer.
</P>
<P>
   Off center stage, but not too far from it, was a wall of
photographs taken during Glenn's latest foray into space, the
November flight of the space shuttle Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand was Air Force Lt. Col. Steve Lindsey, who was the
pilot on Glenn's flight, and Dr. Scott Parazynski, another crew
member.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's gala was Glenn's first public appearance in
Washington since he became the oldest man in space at age 77.
</P>
<P>
   But space was only a backdrop. The evening's purpose was to
announce the launch of Glenn's ``next mission,'' creation of the
John Glenn Institute for Public Service and Public Policy at Ohio
State.
</P>
<P>
   OSU announced the creation of the Glenn Institute in September,
with excitement and fanfare at a Buckeye football weekend. Glenn
and his wife, Annie, were introduced to an adoring stadium crowd at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's gala was aimed at more than adulation. The
Glenn Institute, which will open in January with $20 million in
start-up cash already budgeted, needs national visibility to
attract corporate sponsors for the long term. The school hopes one
day to rival the John Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University, but with a greater emphasis on developing
civic-mindedness and a greater interest in working with younger
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased, obviously, by the turnout,'' Glenn said,
``and I think I'm thrilled to see this kind of support for
something that I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU President William Kirwan said the gala was important to get
the new Glenn school the kind of attention needed to draw policy
leaders and program sponsors to help build the school's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a wonderful turnout,'' said Herb Asher, a
political science professor at OSU who postponed retirement to
direct the Glenn Institute until a permanent replacement is found
next year. ``And to get the Vice President's ringing
endorsement...we're just thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore appeared in a private reception before the main event,
which included an IMAX theater movie on Glenn's life and latest
space mission.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Glenn Institute will be housed in OSU's Bricker
Hall, but eventually could get its own building. It is one of a
handful of high-priority capital projects being touted as part of
the university's $1 billion fund-raising campaign called Affirm Thy
Friendship.
</P>
<P>
   The gala was Glenn's first public appearance in Washington since
he became the oldest man in space. His nine-day space shuttle ride
aboard Discovery ended Nov. 7, more than 36 years after Glenn
became the first American in orbit aboard a tiny Mercury capsule.
</P>
<P>
   The Glenns returned to Washington last Saturday, after driving
up from Houston, where Glenn underwent weeks of postflight medical
tests at the Johnson Space Center. The car trip was a private
adventure, their first in ages, in which Annie Glenn had said she
looked forward to being simply ``Mr. and Mrs. Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Glenn celebrated Thanksgiving on the road _ at the
Shoney's buffet in Hattiesburg, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
