<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0527 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0268 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-STRONGIN-NYT     12-02 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-STRONGIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEODORE STRONGIN, 79, CRITIC WHO CHAMPIONED CONTEMPORARY MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.C., Conn., N.Y., Tenn.)  (bl) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore Strongin, a music critic for The New York Times in the
1960s, died Nov. 24 at St. Joseph's Hospital in Asheville, N.C. He
was 79 and lived in Englewood, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was leukemia, said his daughter, Debby Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   Strongin began writing about music for The Times in 1963, and
within his first few months at the paper he produced an extensive
report about the acoustical deficiencies of Philharmonic (now Avery
Fisher) Hall, with material from a secret architects' report
showing that the hall's interior had to be rebuilt, and quotations
from musicians and conductors who were critical of the hall's sound
a year after it opened.
</P>
<P>
   As a reviewer, Strongin was particularly interested in
contemporary music. He had been a composer himself, and in the
1950s several of his works, including a Suite for Unaccompanied
Cello and an Oboe Quintet, were performed in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Strongin was born in New York in 1918 and grew up in Darien,
Conn. He attended Harvard University and Bard College, where he
studied music and biology. His specialty was entomology, the study
of insects, and he identified several rare species of beetles for
the American Museum of Natural History. After military service,
between 1942 and 1946, he attended the Juilliard School and
Columbia Graduate School, where he studied flute and composition.
</P>
<P>
   He began his newspaper career as a reviewer for The New York
Herald Tribune in the early 1950s but gave up reviewing briefly to
teach composition at Bennington College and Dartmouth. He returned
to writing in 1957, when he became the arts editor and music critic
for The Chattanooga Times. He held the same positions at The
Knickerbocker News, in Albany, N.Y., from 1961 until he joined The
Times in 1963. He remained at The Times until 1970, when he
retired, moved to East Hampton, N.Y., and occasionally contributed
reviews to The East Hampton Star.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, of Manhattan, he is survived by a
son, Daniel of Richmond, Calif.; a grandson, John Randolph of
Manhattan; two stepdaughters, Alice Friedman of Fern Park, Fla.,
and Judith Rosenberg of Austin, Texas, and his companion, Leah
Lasbury.
</P>
</TEXT>
