<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-TENURE-265&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. LEGISLATURE MOVES TO END TENURE FOR PRINCIPALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York state Senate passed a bill Wednesday night that
would abolish tenure for principals, amid signs that the New York
City Board of Education and the principals' union were moving
closer to a compromise plan that would make it easier for New York
City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew to get rid of principals who are
failing.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill, passed in a last-minute flurry of negotiations,
would replace tenure with three-year renewable contracts.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the chancellor and local school
superintendents would evaluate principals annually and could
dismiss them after two bad evaluations. Principals would have the
right to appeal through an accelerated hearing process under the
jurisdiction of the Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Also, New York City's chancellor would have final authority to
dismiss a principal. In the rest of the state, the local
superintendents would have that power.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill passed as momentum built around a second,
slightly more moderate proposal to expand the school system's
ability to get rid of incompetent principals while still preserving
their rights to lesser jobs within the school system. City and
state officials indicated last night that this proposal could
become the basis for an eventual compromise, though not in the
current legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Crew have pushed for a
tough bill on principal tenure, calling for its abolition and
replacement by contracts _ a proposal similar to the bill passed by
the Senate. Their approval would be essential to any compromise.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials familiar with the negotiations said that while the
Board of Education was interested in making a deal, the mayor was
holding out for the complete abolition of tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Roche, a spokeswoman for Giuliani, said Wednesday that
the Senate bill ``certainly doesn't go as far as the mayor believes
we should go, but it's a step in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight over tenure has led to a stalemate in contract talks
among the Board of Education and Giuliani administration and the
principal's union, the Council of Supervisors and Administrators.
The union has been working without a contract for nearly two years.
Talks reached an impasse in September, when the principals refused
a raise of more than 30 percent in exchange for giving up tenure
and working a 12-month year and longer days.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in the Democratic-led State Assembly said that the
Assembly would oppose any change in the tenure system for New York
City principals that had not first been negotiated in contract
talks with the principals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared to put in a bill right now that guts the
collective bargaining talks which are ongoing,'' said Steven
Sanders, chairman of the Assembly Education Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Sanders said, ``There are issues that both sides agree with
that deal with accountability and an expedited review process, and
I believe if the negotiators were allowed to proceed under those
parameters, without the Damocles sword of having to excise from the
law the word tenure, it is a very reasonable expectation that they
could come to an agreement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
