r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GARDNER-LADN-(SLA     12-02 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GARDNER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGING OF THE GUARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Don't bother Jelani Gardner with any axioms
about how life imitates art. In his case, life has imitated hoop.
</P>
<P>
   Really. Spend a few minutes with this Pepperdine point guard,
discuss his messy exit from Cal nearly three years ago, and it's
undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a bad guy. I was a bad person,'' Gardner said of his
recent past. ``I was really arrogant and cocky, thinking the world
revolved around me.''
</P>
<P>
   With the ball, or off the court without it, this was one selfish
person. Gardner freely admits it. In fact, that word popped up
frequently as he discussed those heady days when he left St. John
Bosco High in Bellflower as one of the most hotly recruited guards
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Get him talking about his current state of affairs at
Pepperdine, however, and an antonym works its way into his speech:
selfless. Gardner, in his final year of college eligibility, said
he is finally learning the value of deferring to teammates on the
court. And conducting himself humbly away from it.
</P>
<P>
   The painstaking process will continue Saturday as Gardner leads
the 5-1 Waves against seventh-ranked Kansas at the Wooden Classic
in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken a lot of patience on our part, because he's done it
his way for 20 years,'' said Pepperdine coach Lorenzo Romar, who is
also one of Gardner's closest friends. ``It's like removing bricks
from a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner's way worked pretty well for a long time. He was a
McDonald's All-Star and atop the wish lists of such programs as
UCLA and Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   He selected Cal, he said today with a blush, ``for a selfish
reason, because as a freshman I would be able to start, whereas on
the other teams they had great players on returning teams and I
would have had to wait my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking about my future and going to the NBA early,''
he went on. ``Even in high school, as a junior, I was thinking
three years in college and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner wanted to be the center of attention. He certainly got
his wish at Cal. Friction with then-coach Todd Bozeman during
Gardner's sophomore season led to a lost starting job and increased
time on the bench, which flustered Jelani and incensed his dad, Tom
Gardner, who wasn't exactly living down his reputation as a
meddlesome stage father.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani Gardner ultimately asked for a release from his
scholarship and transferred to Pepperdine to play for Romar, who,
as an assistant coach at UCLA, had been central to the Bruins'
recruitment of him.
</P>
<P>
   Then matters really got sordid. Tom Gardner, admitting at the
time that he wanted to see Bozeman fired, blew the whistle on the
coach with the NCAA. The allegation held that Bozeman, working in
conjunction with former agent James Casey and former NBA player
Butch Carter, had funneled $30,000 over two years to . . .the
Gardners.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff had been agreed to when Jelani was in high school,
and was contingent upon his attending Cal. Tom maintained that
Jelani knew nothing of the scheme and insisted that his son was
never pressured by the family to attend Cal.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bizarre tale, but a Cal investigation resulted in
Bozeman's ouster, and the NCAA's subsequent probe resulted in a
three-year probation for the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani Gardner carries the taint around with him to this day,
whether he likes it or not. ``I had nothing to do with it,'' he
said this week while reclined in the bleachers after practice at
Firestone Fieldhouse. ``I guess a lot of people didn't believe
that. Maybe it's hard to believe, but I really didn't know anything
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   From the family home in West Covina, Tom Gardner approached the
subject as he would an appointment to get his gums scraped. After
rebuffing at least three queries on the subject, he finally said,
``I've gone through this kind of conversation a million times, and
I think I've expressed my regret enough. This is behind us. . . .
I've talked about Cal more than enough. No question about it, it
impacted us, it impacted J, it impacted a lot of people. It's very
regrettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Jelani Gardner can't look back on the entire Cal experience
without reaching, however briefly, the same conclusion. He had to
sit out a year after transferring, and now he's playing far from
the bright lights and packed arenas of the Pacific-10.
</P>
<P>
   The next Jason Kidd? A future lottery pick? Now he's just
laboring to be considered for a job at the next level. But Gardner
hastens to add an important caveat: The experiences, he said,
humbled him and had a refining effect.
</P>
<P>
   Over a period of a few weeks in 1996, Gardner feuded with his
coach, saw his playing time shrivel, struggled with his health,
executed a transfer to another school and left an explosive scandal
in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   At a particularly low point, he said, he became a Christian, and
with that came a much different perspective on life. ``If all that
stuff wouldn't have happened to me, I wouldn't be where I am now,''
Gardner said, ``and I would be a totally different person, a person
that most people wouldn't want to have contact with.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, overall, I'm thankful that all that stuff happened. It
changed me tremendously, not only in basketball but more as a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Jelani Gardner wasn't difficult to spot. The persona was
especially evident on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overdribbling the ball,'' Romar said with a roll of his eyes.
``Overhandling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner recalls the preoccupation with making spectacular
passes, with having little game plan beyond popping from the top of
the key or driving into the paint and kicking to a teammate.
</P>
<P>
   The source of his on-court troubles at Cal? Gardner smiled
sheepishly and said, ``The coach was basically trying to get me to
do the same thing that I'm doing now. I just didn't understand. But
I don't think he taught me the way coach Romar did. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to think helping my team was always making something
happen, whereas sometimes you can run your team by letting the
offense run _ hit the guy coming off a screen, set a screen, do the
little things to help your team.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this young season, Gardner has employed this formula to
lead the Waves in assists (6.5) and minutes (35) per game, while
scoring a modest 12.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   His anemic shooting percentage _ 37.9 percent _ is attributed to
the attention he is attracting from defenses, while perhaps half of
his 22 turnovers, a Pepperdine official said, would have resulted
in points had the recipient of his passes shared Gardner's
considerable athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   But Gardner's approach has been altered, his attitude is
different. And he considers those the greater achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like when you're selfless and worry about your
team,'' he said, ``the more things happen for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the same way it is in life. If you worry about treating
others well, then you'll be treated well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
