<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT QUESTION FOR MR. MICROSOFT 
SOROS GOES SILENT 
TOWN AND COUNTRY 
KIDS WITH FOUR LEGS
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH JOHN TIERNEY, MARCELLE S. FISCHLER AND COREY
KILGANNON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was a friendly crowd and a friendly question, but
Bill Gates resisted the temptation to speak too frankly.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, chairman of Microsoft and star witness at the
government's antitrust trial, was addressing a luncheon Wednesday
at the Roosevelt Hotel organized by the Manhattan Institute, a
public-policy group more sympathetic to entrepreneurs than
government attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, one person in the audience raised a question about
the antitrust case: Was it based on a genuine misunderstanding of
the law and the marketplace, or was it class warfare inspired by
jealousy of Gates?
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Gates could give an answer that would fill a nice long
e-mail. But not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't delve into their mental processes,'' he said, smiling.
``There are many paths to making a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   No Hard Feelings
</P>
<P>
   The financier George Soros is not an unqualified admirer of the
International Monetary Fund, and said so at the New York Public
Library on Tuesday night. ``The IMF system of raising interest
rates in a crisis is rather counterproductive,'' he declared.
</P>
<P>
   At which point his microphone died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF just turned it off,'' quipped the economist Jeffrey
Madrick, who was moderating the session.
</P>
<P>
   The 550 or so tip-hunting listeners did not find out where Soros
thinks the stock markets will go, but once the public-address
system was revived, he was asked about his famous bet on the
British pound, the one that netted him $1 billion in a single week
in 1992. He called it morally defensible.
</P>
<P>
   The financier Leon Levy went further.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that the British had to devalue the pound and lower
interest rates, Levy said: ``George should be honored. They should
make him Lord Soros.''
</P>
<P>
   Reverse Commute
</P>
<P>
   It was camp-reunion time for the Hamptons crowd on Tuesday
night. Artists, filmmakers and writers who seem to have been
spending at least as much time on eastern Long Island as in
Manhattan were sipping cocktails at the Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know all these people had places to live in the
city,'' said the actor Alan Alda, looking over the black-tie crowd
at the Guild Hall Academy of the Arts awards dinner, an annual
event for the theater-and-museum complex in East Hampton. Alda _
like at least two other guests, Peter Stone and Barry Sonnenfeld _
lives in the Hamptons year round and ventures into Manhattan only
when he has to.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the crowd come and go, but often spend much of the
workweek wishing they could stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being outside New York City tends to leaven people somewhat,''
said the ABC News anchor Peter Jennings, who is himself a Hamptons
homeowner. ``I was talking to Julian Schnabel, who under normal
circumstances is a giant, but under Hamptons circumstances is a
neighbor. It makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A Pet Project
</P>
<P>
   Eartha Kitt arrived with her two miniature poodles, Abba and
Mutzi. They are dogs-about-town: She takes them along when she
performs at the Carlyle Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But this was a lunch for the Harmony Institute, a nonprofit
group that studies the relationships between people and animals and
was unveiling plans for a ``luxury pet residence'' in Orlando, Fla.
It will have concierges for pets and outdoor doggie showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have two-legged kids, I have four-legged kids,''
Martha Lentz, the Harmony Institute's chairwoman, said as she
reached for a cigarette after the lunch. ``I try to smoke around my
pets as little as possible, but I'm sure they have the same amount
of lung disease as I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
