<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-POWELL-NYT &LR;      12-02 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-POWELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST CRAWL, THEN RUN: POWELL A NATIONAL CROSS-COUNTRY FAVORITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Ill.)  (bl) 
 By MARC BLOOM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, Andy Powell of North Easton, Mass., the best young
middle-distance runner in the United States, was brought to his
knees by an identity crisis in the longest race of his life.
</P>
<P>
   It happened on the cross-country trails of Van Cortlandt Park in
the Bronx. Powell, then a junior at Oliver Ames High School, was
already an accomplished miler with a national sophomore indoor
record of 4 minutes 9.82 seconds to his credit. But when he
competed in the Foot Locker Northeast high school regional, Powell
was unproven at the cross-country distance of 5,000 meters. He had
not trained much the previous summer and did not yet have the
stamina to match his speed.
</P>
<P>
   But Powell ran to the limit to try to make the top eight and
qualify for the national championship. Ten meters from the finish,
he held sixth place. But suddenly, Powell fell to his knees and
collapsed. Spectators implored him to get up. Two runners whizzed
by him; two more runners, sensing opportunity, sprinted for the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blacked out,'' Powell said. ``Running with the leaders
killed me. My body just stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, with the persistence that would make him one of this
season's national favorites, Powell crawled to the finish and dived
across to nail the eighth and last qualifying spot by inches. The
onrushing runners, unable to avoid the fallen Powell, grazed his
head.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say to me: `Wow, that was awesome. I can't believe you
did that,''' said Powell, now an 18-year-old senior. ``But for me,
it was more embarrassing than anything else. That's not how I want
to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 28, Powell replaced that image with one of power and
grace when, undefeated this fall, he returned to Van Cortlandt and
won the Northeast regional by 125 yards in 15:23.2. His victory,
dominating a field of state champions, made him a contender for the
20th annual Foot Locker national meet, Dec. 12, in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to prove I was a cross-country runner,'' Powell said.
``The incident made me train harder. Last summer, I began training
in July and by October was running 70 miles a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof was uncontestable. Leading up to the regional, Powell,
bound for Stanford, shattered the 5,000-meter course record at
Franklin Park in Boston. His time was 14:52. The previous record,
15:09, was held by Abdirizak Mohamud, the 1996 and 1997 Foot Locker
national champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Foot Locker event, with fields of 32 boys and 32 girls, is
considered the premier showcase of future American talent. Its
roster of winners includes Olympians like U.S. 5,000-meter
record-holder Bob Kennedy and marathoner Cathy O'Brien. College
coaches swarm over the Orlando race course to follow prize
recruits.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast also has a strong girls contingent, led by
regional winner Jillian Mastroianni, a junior at Sayville High on
Long Island, and defending national champion Erin Sullivan of Mount
Mansfield, Vt., who was off form at the regional and placed sixth.
They will be challenged by California state champion Sara Bei, a
sophomore who ran 10th last year.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, who finished 20th in the 1997 nationals, is so intent on
the race that he stunned his coach, Paul Carr, last month when he
didn't take advantage of a good excuse to miss practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Saturdays, we run to a hill three miles from school, then
do several repetitions of the hill,'' Carr said. ``Andy had an
early flight that day for a college recruiting visit. He asked me
to hold the practice at 6:30, while it was still dark, so he could
run and still catch his plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's running prowess was first noticed when he played youth
soccer. Then, in eighth grade, he entered a junior high mile
because the finishers were given donuts. He won in 5:31 but still
preferred playing soccer as well as basketball. His father, a
minister, urged him to concentrate on one pursuit like his older
sister, a music prodigy who played piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do the mile,'' his father repeated. ``The mile.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Carr who persuaded Powell to run. But while Powell said
he quickly ``fell in love'' with the mile for its speed and
glamour, he maintains a reckless streak that belies his maturity.
He still plays pickup basketball. He goes water skiing. He does
flips on a backyard trampoline. Last summer, he hurt his hip
bouncing around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's dumb, but I like that kind of thing,'' said
Powell, who is 5 feet 10 inches and 137 pounds. ``Someone once told
me, if you just run, you'll drive yourself crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell's link to basketball has given him a connection to his
leading opposition in the nationals _ Jorge and Ed Torres, twins
from Wheeling High in the Chicago area. Jorge, the midwest regional
winner and the only boy to make the nationals all four years,
placed second in Orlando last year. Ed placed sixth and has also
qualified again.
</P>
<P>
   Powell previously lived in the Chicago suburb of Lake Zurich,
where, in seventh grade, he played in a basketball league against a
team featuring the Torres brothers. All three youngsters were point
guards who were matched against one another on the court.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in Orlando, the boys reminisced and since then Powell
has called the Torres twins on occasion just to say hello. Jorge is
considered a strong hill runner, but since the nationals' terrain
is flat, Powell's speed is a potent weapon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a miler's course,'' said Powell, who has run the 400
meters in 50.9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Last track season, without his recently acquired endurance,
Powell ran the fastest high school 1,500 meters in the country,
3:47.37, which equates to a 4:05 mile. He won the national indoor
mile in 4:07.34, a junior class record, as well as the two-mile
event. His best two-mile race, an 8:59.19 indoors, was also the
fastest in the country in 1998. This spring he hopes to become the
first high school runner in 32 years to run under 4 minutes in the
mile.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, a newcomer, Franklyn Sanchez of nearby Lynn Tech in
Massachusetts, rose to challenge him. But instead of digging in his
heels, Powell nurtured Sanchez, a senior but still 16 and unsure of
his talent. They ran together in their state meet as Powell
triumphed with precision by one second, leading Ames to the
Division II team title.
</P>
<P>
   And, at Powell's suggestion, they ran together at the regional
until Powell surged ahead near the finish. Sanchez, originally from
the Dominican Republic, where he lived on his grandmother's farm
and milked cows before school, placed second. ``Andy tells me,
`Let's work together,''' Sanchez said. ``He's helped me get to the
nationals.''
</P>
<P>
   Their friendship began last summer when the two boys trained
together at Walden Pond, running as far as 15 miles, and Sanchez
took Powell out for a Dominican meal of chicken and rice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still owe him,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a payback meal, Sanchez would like to have Powell at
his side in the nationals. ``That's my goal,'' Sanchez said. ``To
hang with Andy.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be every runner's goal, but now that the miler has
become a distance runner, too, there may be no catching Powell. As
long as he can stay off the trampoline.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
