<SLUG> BC-BKC-GREAT-EIGHT-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM GUIDES RHODE ISLAND TO AN UPSET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ He took the long way to Rhode Island from Christ the
King High School in Queens. There were stops at Connecticut and
upstate New York at prep schools in his senior year, followed by a
summer in Las Vegas, where he was presumably going to join the
Runnin' Rebels. Lamar Odom is probably the most well-traveled
freshman in college basketball, and the road has always been bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   He was implicated in a college entrance exam cheating scandal
that prompted Nevada-Las Vegas to rescind its scholarship offer. He
apparently passed a full load at Rhode Island last year as a
full-time student, but he was entered in last spring's National
Basketball Association draft until the National Collegiate Athletic
Association cleared him to play this season.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he is the antithesis of Utah's point guard,
Andre Miller, who was academically ineligible to play at the start
of his Ute career, but hit the books hard enough to graduate with a
sociology/criminology major last spring and decided to pass up the
NBA to take graduate courses as well as to take advantage of his
fourth year of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what was apparent as the two dueled Wednesday night in
the Great Eight at the United Center is that both are splendid
players no matter what their personal histories. It was Odom and a
balanced Rhode Island attack, however, that prevailed, 70-63, over
No. 21 Utah in the first game of a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   The grace with which Odom loped downcourt and sliced leading
bounce passes to his teammates belied his 6-foot-10-inch, 220-pound
frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's incredibly fluid,'' Miller said of Odom. ``I didn't know
much about him coming in, but he's as good as I've seen. He's going
to get a lot better, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Miller won the duel of statistics with 28 points, 4 assists
and 6 steals.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how circuitous his travels, Odom demonstrated that he
is most at home on the basketball court running a team. He finished
with 15 points, but that didn't begin to measure how he controlled
a contest that pitted Rhode Island's raw athleticism against Utah's
cerebral passing game.
</P>
<P>
   His six assists kept his teammates slashing to the basket and
looking for the ball as four Rams scored in double figures _ led by
Antonio Reynolds-Dean with 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming in that they may be double-teaming Lamar,''
said Reynolds-Dean, a muscular 6-7 forward. ``I knew that would
mean more chances for me. I hit two shots early, and that's all I
needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom hit a three-pointer with a little more than 10 minutes left
in the game to put the Rams up by 50-46. That sparked Rhode
Island's 14-6 run to grab control of the game. Rhode Island shot 52
percent to become the first team this season to fire better than 40
percent against the defense-minded Utes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a a very good win for us and one we needed badly,''
said Rhode Island Coach Jim Harrick, whose team improved to 4-3
after tough losses to Providence, Cincinnati and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   For Utah, the 6-2 Miller never gave up. His hands whirled as
quickly as his feet scooted from baseline to baseline with the ball
in perpetual motion as he tried to keep Utah close. Only one other
player, Hanno Mottola, finished in double figures (13 points) as
Utah shot just 38.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking to be aggressive enough,'' said Utah Coach
Rick Majerus, whose team is now 3-3. ``I've got them uptight on
offense.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If Rhode Island, which lost its backcourt of Cuttino Mobley and
Tyson Wheeler to the NBA, is to return to the NCAA tournament's
Round of 8 or beyond, it is up to Odom.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he matures more physically and mentally, we'll run our
offense through him like Utah does Miller,'' Harrick said. ``He's
the guy who can take us there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Odom knows he has more to prove off the court. He is bright,
perceptive and finally humbled. ``I made some bad choices,'' he
said of his nearly two years of basketball travels. ``I admit them.
Now it's time to persevere. I'm glad I made my mistakes now instead
of when I'm older with more to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading to their locker rooms, Miller and Odom crossed paths and
hugged. The newcomer thanked the player of the year candidate for a
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You showed me a lot of things I could use,'' Odom told Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Miller smiled and said, ``It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Utah guard walked away, Odom said he didn't know Miller
well. ``But you can tell by his smile and the way he handles
himself he's a good person,'' Odom said. ``I want people to say
that about me someday. I've got a long way to go. But I'm trying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
