<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 GIULIANI GARBAGE PLAN MARRED BY POLITICAL GAFFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also NY-WASTE-JERSEY) 
(mk) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN and DAN BARRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani triumphantly unveiled a
proposal Wednesday to ship most of the city's residential garbage
to transfer stations in New Jersey, but the administration's glee
was quickly muted by an embarrassing lapse in political tact: It
did not tell New Jersey of the plan until Wednesday morning, and
then only in sketchy detail.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that Giuliani was proudly discussing how his
administration had possibly resolved one of the city's most vexing
problems _ the future disposal of its millions of tons of trash _
New Jersey's governor, Christie Whitman, was issuing a news release
that included the headline ``Whitman to New York's Garbage Plan:
Drop Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal being promoted by the City of New York is a
direct assault on the beaches of New Jersey and a very real threat
to our quality of life, especially to the residents of Hudson,
Union, Essex and Middlesex Counties,'' Whitman said. She added that
she would do everything in her power to block any plan that might
harm the state's environment.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high for New York City, which must find an
alternative to dumping its trash at the largest landfill in the
world, Fresh Kills in Staten Island. But Fresh Kills is scheduled
to close by the end of 2001, and Giuliani expressed fears that
federal environmental authorities could shut it down at any time,
creating an immediate crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city's plan, it would send nearly 5,900 tons of
Manhattan and Queens garbage to transfer stations to be built by
private contractors in Newark and Carteret, N.J. In addition, a
transfer station would be built at the Port of Red Hook in Brooklyn
to handle that borough's 3,900 tons of daily trash. Then, after
being compacted in air-tight containers at these transfer stations,
the garbage would be shipped to privately owned landfills in
Virginia, Pennsylvania and other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``This plan is a very fair one and a very equitable one,'' the
mayor said. But by Wednesday night, other New Jersey officials had
joined the ``drop dead'' chorus, placing Giuliani's deputy mayor
for operations, Joseph Lhota, in the delicate position of defending
the plan as environmentally sound but apologizing for its delivery.
Lhota had informed an aide to Mrs. Whitman of the city's plans just
hours before the mayor's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our fault, and not Gov. Whitman's, that she did not
understand New York City's environmentally sound plan for long-term
solid waste management,'' Lhota said in a statement. ``The Governor
and her staff were not adequately briefed in a complete manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview Wednesday night, Lhota said his statement
was one of contrition. ``No one likes to be surprised, and in this
case, the governor was surprised,'' he said. ``It's my job to make
the governor fully apprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The sensitivity of the matter goes beyond the traditional
rivalry between New York and New Jersey. Although they are both
moderate Republicans, Giuliani and Whitman have quarreled in the
past over several issues, from the rights to Ellis Island to the
management of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. And
recent history made the city's plan sting all the more: The
complaints of Mrs. Whitman in early 1997 forced Giuliani and New
York Gov. George Pataki to postpone a city plan to dump 560 million
gallons of raw sewage into New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Giuliani and his aides had engaged in a
little New Jersey humor while detailing where the city's garbage
would go. ``Does any go to the Meadowlands?'' the mayor joked. When
told no, he said: ``Too bad. Well, we ought to get even, right? I
mean for the Giants and the Jets.'' The two professional football
teams left New York to play in the Meadowlands in New Jersey years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the New Jersey jokes had ended by evening as state, county
and local officials in New Jersey criticized the plan. ``We will
not be the dumping ground for any entity,'' Mayor Sharpe James of
Newark said, ``especially since their plans call for bringing this
solid waste to a site that is near an area that is undergoing
extensive revitalization.''
</P>
<P>
   Governor Whitman and her aides said their principal worry was
that garbage might spill from the city barges on the way to the
transfer stations in New Jersey, causing pollution of her state's
beaches. She characterized the garbage shipping as ``an
environmental disaster waiting to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
