<SLUG> BC-NY-WASTE-JERSEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION SEEN FOR GIULIANI PLAN TO SEND GARBAGE TO N.J. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With NY-WASTE) (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's proposal
to ship tons of New York City's garbage through New Jersey each day
could not be implemented without county and state approval and
faces stiff opposition at both levels, officials in Trenton and in
Essex and Middlesex Counties said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement in New York that the city intended send nearly
5,900 tons of garbage to transfer stations to be built in Newark,
which is in Essex County, and Carteret, which is in Middlesex,
elicited a range of reactions from tepid skepticism to eruptions of
fury Wednesday in New Jersey. Giuliani did not tell officials here
of his plan until Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman, in a statement issued Wednesday
afternoon, said, ``The sites in Middlesex and Essex Counties would
require amendments to the solid waste plans for both counties,
which must also be approved by the county boards of freeholders and
ultimately by the state.'' The statement added, ``All of these
processes require public hearings and input from members of the
affected communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Under state law, each of New Jersey's 21 counties has a solid
waste advisory council, which is responsible for developing a
county solid waste management plan. The plans include specific
criteria for how trash is transported and disposed of throughout a
county, including the traffic routes that garbage trucks can use
and limits on the amount of trash that can be burned by an
incinerator or dumped in a landfill. Changes must be approved by
the county's freeholders and the state, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Middlesex County, where Giuliani's plan calls for the
construction in Carteret of a transfer station where barges would
unload nearly 4,000 tons of garbage a day from Queens and
Manhattan, the director of the board of freeholders, David Crabiel,
reacted venomously and pledged to fight it. ``It's the most
ludicrous proposal I have ever heard,'' Crabiel said. ``It will
never happen in Middlesex County.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabiel noted that Middlesex had fought successfully in the
1980s to stop other counties from dumping their garbage there. ``We
are not going to let in any out-of-state or any out-of-county
garbage,'' he said. Of Giuliani, he said, ``Let him barge it up the
Hudson and take his garbage to Albany.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabiel predicted that the county's solid waste advisory
committee and the other freeholders would agree. ``I am sure both
groups would vote unanimously no,'' Crabiel said.
</P>
<P>
   William Abele, executive director of the Essex County Utility
Authority, said Giuliani's plan would need county and state
approval because it involved constructing the transfer station.
``The county and the state have approval powers over the
development of any transfer station, regardless of the source of
the trash that it handles,'' he said. ``I can't imagine any
circumstances where this authority would approve a new transfer
station if that would cause any environmental or economic harm to
Essex County.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
