u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-BENJAMIN-NYT &LR;      12-02 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BENJAMIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY BENJAMIN, 93, DEALER IN DOCUMENTS OF THE FAMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT McG. THOMAS Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Benjamin, an autograph dealer with such an authoritative
eye for authenticity and such a sure sense of value that for
decades she virtually dictated prices American collectors paid for
the writings of presidents, poets and other prominent people, died
Nov. 30 at her home in Hunter, N.Y. She was 93 and had been so
widely recognized as the nation's leading document authority that
she regularly received mail addressed simply to ``The Autograph
Lady.''
</P>
<P>
   As a daughter of Walter R. Benjamin, a onetime New York Sun
reporter who founded what is now the nation's oldest autograph
dealership in Manhattan in 1887, Miss Benjamin, a native of
Yonkers, N.Y., who graduated from Barnard, did not so much inherit
her expertise as absorb it by osmosis during a 13-year
apprenticeship at her father's elbow.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she took over Walter R. Benjamin Autographs in 1940,
Miss Benjamin had become so familiar with the handwritings of
presidents, cabinet secretaries, signers of the Declaration of
Independence, Civil War generals and American and European
composers, literary figures and the like that she could often tell
at a glance not only if a document was authentic but which master
forger had produced it if it was not.
</P>
<P>
   Her expertise was so respected that once, when an auctioneer at
a leading Manhattan gallery announced to the assembled bidders that
the next item would be a George Washington letter, an audible snort
of derision from Miss Benjamin was enough to cause the auctioneer
to withdraw from the sale on the spot. As her snort had indicated,
she had gotten a quick look at the letter moments earlier and
recognized it as a forgery.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when there were only a handful of dealers who handled
autographs _ a term, meaning ``self-writing,'' that applies to
anything, not simply the signature, written in a person's own hand
_ Miss Benjamin's standing tended to overshadow her role as the
only woman in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her reputation, experienced collectors and those with
trunks full of old papers tended to seek her out, but Miss Benjamin
was never satisfied with walk-in trade.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to tracking down valuable documents, she was very
much the daughter of the man who catapulted himself into the first
ranks of his field in 1907. Learning that the Customs Service had
sold 140 tons of old documents to a junk dealer, he persuaded the
man to let him go through the refuse and ended up paying 25 cents
each for thousands of documents signed by Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when Miss Benjamin learned that the publishers of
``The Dictionary of American Biography'' had cleaned out its files
of questionnaires filled out by 25,000 prominent Americans over two
decades, she tracked down the junk dealer in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., who
had picked them up and ended up acquiring hundreds of them,
including three separate intimate questionnaires that had been
filled out by President Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a photographic memory that allowed her to recognize a
handwriting she had not seen in years and to rattle off obscure
biographic details of more than 10,000 notable figures of the
previous 500 years, Miss Benjamin, who bought and sold between
5,000 and 10,000 documents a year and maintained an inventory of
some 50,000 documents in her office vaults, had an uncanny sense of
their value in the market of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   A woman whose passions could be inflamed by a surprise
discovery, Miss Benjamin, a crack bridge player, once likened the
thrill of opening a trunk of old letters to the feeling of
anticipation she felt at picking up a hand at the bridge table.
</P>
<P>
   In her 40s when she married Harold G. Henderson, a Columbia
professor of Japanese art who had served on General Douglas
MacArthur's staff and composed Emperor Hirohito's renunciation of
divinity, Miss Benjamin soon drew her husband into her scholarly
detective work. On weekends the couple, wearing kimonos, would sit
in the backyard of their Manhattan town house reading old
manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   They also became famous for dinner parties whose regular guests
included the likes of Georgia O'Keeffe.
</P>
<P>
   A boom in autograph collecting in the 1960s brought her more
competition, but Miss Benjamin, whose oft-revised 1946 book,
``Autographs: A Key to Collecting,'' has been regarded as a
standard in the field, remained a figure to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   After her husband's death, she moved her business to Hunter,
about 40 miles southeast of Albany, in 1974 and continued to be
active until 1995. It is now operated by her nephew Christopher
Jaeckel, who became her assistant in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Jaeckel, Miss Benjamin is survived by a sister,
Yolanda Jaeckel of Cranbury, N.J.; another nephew, Theodore Jaeckel
of Princeton Junction, N.J., and a niece, Pamela Oppen of Hunter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981202.0538 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-02 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIANTS-STADIUM-NYT &LR;      12-02 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIANTS-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOW THE MOWER: GIANTS STADIUM GRASS FIELD DELAYED 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Officials for the Giants, the Jets, the MetroStars and the New
Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority decided Wednesday to
postpone the installation of a permanent grass field at Giants
Stadium until 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Giants and MetroStars officials came to the meeting prepared to
support a grass field for the 1999 season, while Jets officials
were more skeptical. Jets coach Bill Parcells on Monday had
criticized the temporary grass field installed last summer for
being a little soft and said, ``I don't want to be involved in any
experiment here.''
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the issue was never taken because Scott Clark, the
president of Clark Cos., which would install the field using trays
of grass, indicated that the best solution might be to wait another
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott Clark said he could give us an acceptable field that
would work,'' said John Mara, the Giants' vice president and senior
counsel. ``But he recommended waiting so more things could be
studied.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point on, everybody knew we had to wait, but I
wanted to be sure we weren't postponing this every year. We want
the grass in 2000, and we were told the best technology would be
ready by then.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said Parcells' comments Monday did not directly influence
his presentation at the meeting. ``I didn't think what he said was
way out in left field,'' he said. ``This is a prominent place in
American sports, and we can't have one ounce of failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel, who has supported the installation of a
grass field, said he was not disappointed by the decision to delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the reasoning,'' Fassel said. ``My understanding is
that Scott Clark said if you wait a year, this field will be really
special. But this year might have been pushing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Financing the grass field, which could cost as much as $4
million was not discussed at Wednesday's two-hour meeting. It would
probably be split up among the parties involved. New Jersey and the
teams will begin financing the installation and testing of a
permanent grass field at the facility, which is the only stadium
that is home to two National Football League teams.
</P>
<P>
   Work will begin early next year on the modular warning-track
system, made of a red rubber compound, that will surround the more
than 6,400 grass trays that will make up the field. The track will
extend to the bench areas and allow vehicles to move inside the
stadium without driving on the grass.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the design and engineering of the environment control
system that will cool and humidify the grass field, and for
example, melt snow that settles on it, will be completed and
tested.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps most important, a system called GrassMaster will be
tested as a way to strengthen the durability of Clark's tray field.
GrassMaster is a European system that implants polypropylene fibers
seven inches deep into a grass field. There would be 12 fibers per
foot of field; they are meant to substantially extend the playable
hours of a natural grass field.
</P>
<P>
   Even Though it has been used at European athletic sites, the
first GrassMaster system field in the United States is being
installed by Clark Cos. in Binghamton, N.Y., for use by the Mets'
minor league affiliate there.
</P>
<P>
   GrassMaster, however, has not been tried on a tray field. Clark
said his plastic trays would have to be placed on a conveyor that
passed beneath a fiber stitching machine.
</P>
<P>
   Giants Stadium will have a temporary grass-tray field again next
summer, with the MetroStars playing most of their games on it. The
Giants and Jets will play all their preseason games on the grass;
the Kickoff Classic will be played on the turf, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The grass trays will then be removed for the Giants and Jets
1999 regular seasons. In early 2000, the plan calls for work to
begin to lay down a permanent grass field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aiming at the best grass field we can,'' said Jets
President Steve Gutman, who attended Wednesday's meeting. ``Our
objective is by 2,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Most pleased by Wednesday's developments seemed to be Charlie
Stillitano, general manager of the MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, everyone walked out believing that grass
is the future at Giants Stadium,'' he said. ``It's a real,
unequivocal commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides playing host to 20 Giants and Jets preseason and regular
season games, Giants Stadium also is the site for about six other
college and high school football games a year and 45 other events
ranging from rock concerts to marching band competitions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
