<HEADLINE>
3 ACCUSED OF CHEATING INVESTORS IN FLORIDA RECYCLING COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)  (bl) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three people who were promoting the stock of a
Florida company that recycled toxic waste were indicted Wednesday
on charges that they cheated 200 investors, including more than 50
New York state court officers and their friends and families, out
of more than $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the investors' money, which has not yet been recovered,
went directly into the private bank accounts of the three suspects,
instead of for the purchase of stock, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The three suspects, Edward Halloran, Michele Caridi and Richard
Furman, and the company, Inorganic Recycling Corp. of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., were indicted by a grand jury on 24 counts,
including 11 counts of grand larceny, said Manhattan District
Attorney Robert Morgenthau.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran, 57, and Ms. Caridi, 37, are married, and Morgenthau
said they misled investors by failing to disclose that Halloran,
and not Ms. Caridi, was the largest shareholder in Inorganic
Recycling, and by failing to disclose that Halloran had been
convicted of racketeering in federal court in 1996 and a fraud
scheme in a New York state court in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Halloran is a fugitive from justice, Morgenthau said, and Ms.
Caridi has been released on her own recognizance, pending the
posting of a $1 million bond.
</P>
<P>
   The investors included many state court employees and their
relatives and were recruited by Furman, Morgenthau said. Furman, a
court sergeant who supervises officers in charge of security for
the New York state Supreme Court, is also free on his own
recognizance. He is charged with encouraging other court employees
to invest in Inorganic Recycling, although it is not listed on
public stock exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Carolyn Pelling said the promoters
of Inorganic Recycling promised potential investors returns of 3 to
12 times their initial investments in just a few months. Many of
the investors, including the state court employees, had moderate
annual incomes of $30,000 to $50,000. The largest individual sum
lost was $60,000 belonging to Richard Grimm, a friend of Furman and
a fellow court security officer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Furman, 48, must have known Halloran's record and the fraudulent
nature of the Inorganic Recycling investment scheme, the
authorities said, because as a court sergeant he attended
Halloran's fraud trial in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Reached Wednesday night at his home in Flushing, Queens, Furman
declined to comment. To remain free, the district attorney's office
said, he must surrender his ability to collect his state court
pension, totaling hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Halloran, Ms. Caridi and other investors took control
of 51 percent of the stock of Inorganic Recycling, a company that
was on the verge of a bankruptcy but had a promising patented
process for converting poisonous steel waste into nontoxic
byproducts, Ms. Pelling said. But they did nothing to find working
capital for the struggling company; instead, the money went for a
lush Florida life style, Ms. Pelling said, and the company filed
for bankruptcy in Broward County earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Edward W. Hayes, 51, Ms. Caridi's lawyer, said, ``She's got
terrible taste in husbands and that's all of her problem right
there.'' He added: ``She never sold anybody to anything. She never
met any of these people,'' referring to the Inorganic Recycling
investors.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said his client first met Halloran as a teen-ager, when
she was a baby sitter for his family, and later married him. They
are now separated and in divorce proceedings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So first she's a baby sitter, then she's a wife, and the next
thing she knows she's indicted,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
