<SLUG> BC-CA-HMOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY BEN SULLIVAN 
</HEADLINE>
 
HMOs TO GRANT OUTSIDE REVIEWS 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California's biggest HMOs said Wednesday that they
will voluntarily give their customers access to an independent,
third-party review if they are denied treatment by the health plan.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows the adoption of similar programs at a handful
of HMOs around the country and at plans in 18 states where some
form of external review is mandated by law.
</P>
<P>
   Currently in California, most health plans must provide outside
review only when a member is treated through a federal program such
as Medicare, when the dispute is over an experimental treatment or
when a person's life is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidelines proposed by the California Association of
Health Plans and agreed to by its 16 biggest members, patients who
are denied treatment can appeal to an independent health care
professional or body that is selected by the HMO. A patient would
have to exhaust the HMO's internal appeals process first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients should not have to fear that they might be denied
care they need,'' said Walter Zelman, CAHP's president. ``Their
health comes first.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16 CAHP member plans that have signed on to the proposal
account for about 90 percent of the state's managed care enrollees,
and the organization said it expects smaller members to follow
suit. But because bills mandating independent review are likely to
find their way to the state Legislature this year, most plans are
expected to wait until the end of 1999 to implement the service.
</P>
<P>
   While the CAHP initiative was generally well met Wednesday,
consumer advocates said it is only one step in the right direction.
A better solution, they argue, is to define and mandate external
review through law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state Legislature is a better way to go,'' said Geraldine
Dallek, a researcher at the Georgetown Institute of Healthcare
Research and Policy. ``One, it's mandatory. Two, it's clearly
binding. And three, you know it really is external.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallek said it's also cheaper: A Georgetown study found that the
average cost to health plans ranged from roughly a half-cent to
4cents per patient per month in states where external review is
required.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates also say that when implemented on a voluntary
basis, the outside reviewers hired by a health plan might be prone
to rule in the HMO's favor. Peter Lee, an attorney with the Los
Angeles-based Center for Healthcare Rights, described the CAHP
proposal as ``a nice baby step,'' but said state legislation would
ensure standardization.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, participating health plans say that while they
have previously sponsored external review legislation, a market
approach can be effective and consistent. ``I don't believe you'll
actually see 16 different systems,'' said Ron Williams, president
of Blue Cross of California. ``Health plans all do have today
external review processes in place for life threatening (issues)
and will likely just build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   And nationally there is no rush among managed care companies to
create federal external review legislation. Susan Pisano, a
spokeswoman for the American Association of Health Plans, said such
laws might one day be appropriate but not now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a great deal of care exercised in how this
is done. There should be discussions about it ... but private
sector initiatives are better at addressing most questions,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
