<HEADER>
A0303 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-JOBS-SPI &LR;      12-02 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-JOBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL TASK FORCE WORKING TO AID LAID-OFF BOEING WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON and BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Boeing confirmed Wednesday that the deepening job
cuts it unveiled Tuesday would hit Puget Sound hardest.
</P>
<P>
   And President Clinton, saying he was ``very concerned,''
promised to send money and ``rapid response teams'' to coordinate
benefits and retraining for laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit, addressing for the first time the
labor impacts of production cuts his company announced Tuesday,
said in a press conference that 80 to 90 percent of the jobs would
be cut from Boeing Commercial Airplanes, the division of the
company that makes passenger jets at Everett, Renton and Wichita,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will fall most heavily on Puget Sound,'' he said. Cuts will
come across the board, including the design staff, which has no new
airplane to work on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're downsizing the whole production system,'' said Alan
Mulally, president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street, which often responds positively when a company
trims its workforce, instead hammered the aerospace company's stock
down 17 percent, pulverizing about $7 billion in investor net
worth. The stock fell $6.69, closing at $33.69 _ not far from its
12-month low of $29.50, and miles from its high of $56.25. Boeing
led the stock market down, 69 points on the Dow Industrials.
Trading more than 36.7 million shares, about 12 times the norm, it
was the most active stock in the markets.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts, who had lined up as six ``strong buys,'' six
``buys'' and five ``holds'' on Boeing stock before the company's
projections Tuesday, nervously reshuffled their chairs, and ended
the day with one ``strong buy,'' 12 ``holds'' and one ``sell.''
``Analysts have thrown in the towel on this one,'' said Chuck Hill,
director of research at Boston-based First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, however, were the wider concern in western Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's employment peaked in June at 238,000. The company said
Tuesday that by the end of 1999 it expects to cut as many as 38,000
jobs from that peak, and by the end of 2000, to cut 10,000 more.
Some 5,400 of the cuts have already been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Labor has already begun work with Boeing ...
and we will continue to work closely with them,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said during Wednesday's news briefing.
``Basically, the rapid response teams work with company and state
officials and affected employees to coordinate immediate job
placement assistance and financial assistance to workers. And I'm
told that that process is already under way, even before the
announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department has faced similar situations. An official
here who asked not to be identified said her agency had developed
rapid response teams and sent them to begin working with
Washington, Kansas and California several months ago when the
prospect of layoffs became likely at Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working with the company to get information to workers
about job placement, job retraining, financial assistance _
whatever we have within our disposal _ and there's a team of
people, some from the federal government, working closely with the
company and the unions to make this real,'' the official said.
``There will also be special funds made available to the states to
be used for retraining and job placement assistance and
counselors.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters that the Boeing layoffs demonstrate the
importance of U.S. efforts to end the Asian financial crisis. He
noted that Asian nations could not buy U.S. airplanes if their
economies were in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's why I have given such a high priority for the
better part of a year now ... to trying to stabilize the situation
there, limit the spread of the financial contagion, and then
reverse conditions in Asia and restore economic growth there.''
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, he said, ``they'll start buying the airplanes
again, production lines will start up again, and they'll call the
workers back.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing officials, while not saying anything to contradict this,
painted a somber picture of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation in Asia has worsened dramatically,'' said
Condit. ``It is much deeper and more prolonged than first
estimated.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing President Harry Stonecipher, who recently returned from a
trip to Asia, was asked how long the Asian recession would last.
``Almost every time you ask them, it's `one to two years.' Next
year it'll probably still be, `one to two years.' We think it's
three to five; we hope it's three.''
</P>
<P>
   Stonecipher said the Asian crisis had also affected the prospect
of AWACS and F-18 military sales to South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives fielded questions that suggested that they
had underestimated the Asian crisis and now were overreacting to
it.
</P>
<P>
   Condit admitted underestimating it. ``This is a business that
changes with economic conditions,'' he said. ``If you could predict
economic conditions perfectly, you could make a lot of money in a
lot of places. We're trying to follow our market.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the charge of overreacting, Stonecipher said, ``We're not
going to do anything stupid about this. We're going to go about it
in a very methodical way, a very careful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit stressed that the company's new forecast for 2000, which
was so gloomy, could be wrong. ``If things get better, there is
still some upside potential. This is our best estimate based on all
the data we have right now,'' he said. And if economies worsened in
North America and Europe, he said, cuts could be greater, and
center on programs other than the 747.
</P>
<P>
   Only 84 of the 620 airplanes slated to be built next year are
for Asian carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Stonecipher said the layoffs also reflect several years of
unmanaged hiring, in which ``things got out of control.'' He said
the company, despite its success in getting back on schedule, is
spending 20 to 30 percent more hours to assemble an airplane than
it did in 1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said they are not convinced this is a rational
exercise in productivity enhancement. Said Charles Bofferding,
president of the Seattle Professional Engineering Employees
Association, ``Is this really a reaction to the work to be done, or
is it an attempt to appease Wall Street and reduce short-term
costs?''
</P>
<P>
   Bofferding said he thought part of it relates to last year's
merger of Boeing and McDonnell Douglas. ``We get a little sloppy in
our thinking when we say this is production stuff,'' he said. ``A
lot of it is merger stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But as for the cuts, said Bofferding, ``If the company really
wants to reduce the numbers, we can't stop them, so we're doing
everything possible to mitigate the impact.''
</P>
<P>
   He said SPEEA is focusing efforts on setting up a job fair next
year to introduce members to other employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a pretty tight labor market for high-tech
employees,'' he said. ``Our goal is to let the people who go out
the door be people who choose to go out the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The other, larger union of Boeing employees, the Aerospace
Machinists, was less accepting, and angrier.
</P>
<P>
   Condit said that all the unions had been notified of Tuesday's
announcement, but Aerospace Machinist Local 751 President Bill
Johnson said he had learned about it when called by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   And he was fit to be tied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked with every union leader who would be affected by
this announcement, and no one, not one person, had been told of
this announcement in advance,'' he said in a prepared statement
released Wednesday night. ``We cannot sit by while Boeing callously
chooses what information it shares with us and when, and then lies
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson made the statement after what the union called ``a
heated three-hour meeting'' with management. The union said he was
willing for the Boeing/Machinists Working Group to meet again,
``but with a clear understanding that whatever happens will
directly impact upcoming negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   One place of agreement was the federal help. State officials,
the unions and Boeing all welcomed it.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gallwas, assistant commissioner of the state Department of
Employment Security, said the federal government played a role in
helping the state cope with the last round of Boeing layoffs, in
the early '90s, and that federal money might be needed to help pay
for tuition, books, and other support for workers in retraining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government has been extremely helpful, very
responsive, and I expect that support to continue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and its major union agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use all the assistance that we can to get our people
situated so that they can be gainfully employed and have good
jobs,'' said Boeing spokesman Larry McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   And Machinists spokeswoman Karen Waters said ``anything to help
in this situation is welcomed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-02-98 2356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
